<HEADLINE>
MENNINGER CLINIC WEIGHS SHUTTING DOWN ITS TOPEKA CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world-renowned Menninger Clinic is considering closing its
spacious Topeka, Kan., campus as it struggles to reverse financial
losses, President and Chief Executive Officer W. Walter Menninger
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger, a psychiatrist and the third generation in his family
to lead the mental-health facility, said the clinic was ``looking
at every potential option. We know that the campus is expensive for
us to operate when we maintain the full scope.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants from Ernst &AMP; Young are conducting a study, expected
to be completed this summer, on how to turn around the fortunes of
the clinic that gained fame treating the mental illnesses of
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger emphasized that no final decision had been made on the
future of the Topeka campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to imagine that there won't be some presence
(by Menninger on the campus), but I feel obligated, in terms of the
institution going forward, to be totally open-minded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Menninger Clinic reported a deficit of $2.9 million in
fiscal year 1999. In the first half of fiscal year 2000, from July
through December of 1999, the deficit totaled $1.2 million,
Menninger said, adding that the losses would have been worse
without financial help from the Menninger Foundation and other
sources of support.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic cut about 140 positions, more than half by attrition,
and demolished several older buildings on the campus last year.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic's financial problems are occurring as mental health
facilities around the country are suffering from shorter inpatient
stays, partly due to tighter reimbursements from managed-care
companies and government health programs. An inpatient is someone
who stays in a hospital or clinic for at least 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, modern medications have lessened the need for long
inpatient stays in psychiatric facilities. The result is that
psychiatric hospitals have been closing in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger said it was too early to speculate on the possibility
of layoffs in connection with the evaluation. The Menninger Clinic
has 1,054 full- and part-time employees in Topeka, more than 800 of
whom work on the main campus. It has 338 employees, both full- and
part-time, in the Kansas City area. It also has subsidiary
operations in the Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is painful,'' Menninger said. ``We're having to change
how we practice. We're having to do things differently. If there
are programs that don't make sense, we will have to visit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Health-care consultant Gail Shafton, president of Cue Resources
Inc. in Overland Park, Kan., said the uncertainty facing the
Menninger clinic came as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inpatient care is just not the norm anymore for anything in
medicine, and mental health has not been any different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And although efforts are under way to give mental health
benefits equal status with other health benefits, those efforts
will not reverse the trend toward shorter stays for those receiving
mental health care. Even wealthy people who can afford long stays
for psychiatric care are seeking other alternatives, Shafton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's especially true of baby boomers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A decision to vacate the campus would signify a radical change
for the Menninger Clinic, which was founded by C.F. Menninger and
two of his sons, Will and Karl, in a nearby farmhouse in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Together they set out to treat mental illness with
missionary-like zeal. The world's top psychiatrists flocked there
to work and learn. Movie stars such as actress Gene Tierney fled
Hollywood's glitter to find refuge there.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, celebrities such as Green Bay Packers
quarterback Brett Favre have gone to the Menninger Clinic for help
in solving substance abuse and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic has been consistently ranked as one of the nation's
top two psychiatric care providers in surveys of America's best
hospitals by U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger's main campus consists of 242 acres that unfold along
a quiet hilltop in northwest Topeka. The administration building,
with its imposing clock tower, was modeled after Philadelphia's
Independence Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic also owns 233 acres nearby to the west. It is selling
60 acres on the south end of the campus to the Security Benefit
Group of Companies. A separate 50-acre parcel is being developed
into an office park.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of patients. Menninger said the clinic had
2,238 admissions to its main hospital on the Topeka campus in 1999,
up from 740 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But over that same period, the average length of stay for each
patient declined from 74.3 days to 20.4 days, Menninger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to look at everything in terms of revenue and
expense, and how we can best fulfill our mission, which has had a
traditional commitment to patient care, professional education,
research and prevention,'' Menninger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Menninger Clinic has been branching out from the Topeka
campus in recent years, in response to changes in patient needs and
health-care reimbursements. In the Kansas City area it operates
inpatient psychiatric facilities at four hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Menninger operates a substance-abuse center in Overland Park. It
is a partner in New Directions Behavioral Health, which provides
employee assistance services and managed behavioral health care,
with Health Midwest and Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   As for how the ongoing evaluation might affect Kansas City area
operations, Menninger said: ``We're looking at everything. We're
looking at wherever we are to see how that fits into the
equation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
