<HEADLINE>
INDIANA COMPANY MOVES OPERATION, WORKERS TO MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Products and Services, which acquired Guy's Foods last
month, announced Monday that it would close its Fort Wayne, Ind.,
snack food factory and consolidate the operation with the Guy's
plant in Liberty, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The move is expected to add 50 to 60 jobs at the Liberty plant,
which once employed 1,000 workers and now employs about 600.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will mean more jobs and about 40 percent more
production,'' said Ron Hirasawa, chairman and chief executive
officer of General Products. ``It will probably mean savings of $5
million a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The closing of the Fort Wayne plant will throw 110 hourly and
salaried employees out of work. Hirasawa said key management
personnel would be offered jobs in Liberty after the plant's
scheduled closing on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Wayne plant was built in 1964 and occupies 145,000
square feet. The sprawling Liberty complex was built in different
phases beginning in 1970 and takes up 325,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an efficiency and cost standpoint, it didn't make sense
to have two manufacturing plants,'' said Gary Crutcher, director of
human resources at Guy's. ``The one in Liberty is larger, has more
capacity and can handle the volume better than the plant in Fort
Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy's and General Products both make salty snack foods,
including potato chips, corn chips, tortilla chips, pretzels,
cheese twists and popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Family Snacks Inc., which operates Guy's, filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection Feb. 14 after losing $5.75 million over the
previous 16 months. The filing gave Guy's a respite from creditors
as it sought a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   General Products received bankruptcy court approval last month
to acquire the assets of Guy's Foods after outbidding several other
businesses. The Indiana company agreed to assume $14 million in
Guy's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Guy's Acquisition Co. LLC, which was set up by General Products
to buy the assets, will be merged with General Products at the end
of the month. The merged company will be known as General Products
&AMP; Services LLC.
</P>
<P>
   The Guy's brand name, as well as the Seyfert's and Ultima Foods
names of General Products, will be retained, Crutcher said. General
Products also will continue making private-label products.
</P>
<P>
   Guy's is thought to have generated $125 million in sales in
1999. General Products, also a closely held company, is thought to
have generated about $40 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   General Products resulted from the merger last year of
66-year-old Seyfert's Foods of Fort Wayne and Ultima Foods of
Chicago. Like Guy's, Seyfert's at one time was owned by dairy giant
Borden Inc., which shed its snack food units in the mid-1990s to
concentrate on its core business.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Guy's executives purchased Guy's from Borden in 1994
for an undisclosed price. The group was led by Victor R. Sabatino,
who was dismissed as president and chief executive officer of Guy's
last month after the sale to General Products.
</P>
</TEXT>
