<HEADLINE>
PATAKIS REPORT BIG GAIN IN INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and his wife, Libby, reported
earning a record family income of $400,266 in 1999, a 62 percent
increase from the year before, according to a copy of their tax
return made public on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's salary remained the same at $177,984, and his income
from outside speaking engagements dropped to $48,000 for three
speeches. In 1998, he got $50,000 for three speeches and $24,000
for his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Pataki's income rose to $190,000 last year from two
consulting jobs. She made a total of $100,000 from her consulting
job with Ronald Lauder, the cosmetics heir and champion of
conservative causes, a 25 percent raise over 1998. Michael McKeon,
a spokesman for the governor, said Mrs. Pataki was advising Lauder
on the expansion of his television broadcasting business in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   She made $90,000 from her second consulting job, with Premier
Heart, a medical products company based in Port Washington, N.Y.,
that she joined at the end of 1998. McKeon said Mrs. Pataki spoke
to groups outside New York to promote the company's products.
McKeon said he did not know how many hours she worked at either
job.
</P>
<P>
   The Patakis' total income was the highest that they have
reported, and it puts them in the same income range as two other
first couples. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City and his
wife, Donna Hanover, a television journalist, reported $413,155
last year, and President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
reported making $416,039.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Mary O. Donohue was paid $143,985, which was her main
source of income, according to a copy of her tax return that was
also released on Tuesday. She filed as head of household, and a
spokesman confirmed that she was divorced last year. She also
received $10,990 in rent from a condominium in Mashpee, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Patakis and their four children live in a 24-room Victorian
mansion in Garrison, N.Y., and received rental payments last year
from two properties: $12,850 from the governor's childhood home in
Peekskill, N.Y., and $1,000 from a working farm in Salem, N.Y.
After mortgages, taxes and other costs were factored in, both
rental properties were reported as losses againsttaxable income.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and his wife still owed $29,324 in federal income tax _
primarily because of the jump in income _ for a total of $110,908
last year. They were assessed $20,905 in state income tax and
overpaid by $2,897, which will be applied as a credit to next
year's tax. They paid $31,605 in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Their tax return also shows that they spent $3,671 for a
part-time housekeeper last year and donated $4,238 to charities.
</P>
</TEXT>
