<SLUG> BC-NY-CABBIE-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLINGS OF LIVERY DRIVERS RISE, BUT NOT ROBBERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Obscured by the public outcry over the killings of
livery-cab drivers, and by the city's actions to protect them, lies
a curious fact. While the pace of driver homicides has been rising,
the larger crime pattern, which shows the number of reported
robberies in livery cabs, has not changed, according to police
data.
</P>
<P>
   Seven livery-cab drivers have been killed so far this year, and
five of the slayings bear striking similarities, involving drivers
riding in the darkness with passengers and being shot from behind.
Eleven drivers were killed in all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the police and Fernando A. Mateo, president of the New York
State Federation of Cab Drivers, said on Tuesday that the spike in
killings was puzzling because the homicides appeared to have
resulted primarily from robberies spinning out of control, leaving
drivers dead, yet the rate of robberies was not rising on a
statistically significant scale.
</P>
<P>
   Livery-cab drivers reported 269 robberies, including those
committed during the killings, through April 10 of this year, while
261 were reported during the same period in 1999. For the last
three years, the number of livery-cab robberies has been almost
constant, wedged in a narrow band between 966 and 978.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo attributed the increase in homicides to emboldened
criminals, whom he said can sense that street officers have become
restrained, even hesitant, in the aftermath of the widely
publicized police killings of unarmed black men, from Amadou Diallo
last year to Patrick M. Dorismond last month. ! He also said the
numbers compiled by the police might not accurately reflect the
degree of violence, because many drivers do not report hold-ups in
their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Livery drivers stopped reporting the robberies because they
find that it is a waste od their time,'' he said. ``They ent up
sitting in a precinct or a courtroom, but almost never are the
cases cracked. When they get robbed, they go home and sob a bit and
go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said they could not readily explain the rise in
killings. None appear to have been committed by the same person,
said Sgt. Brian Burke, a police spokesman, or tied to any other
criminal activity, like a gang initiation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the police and the drivers are at a loss to explain the
increase in slayings, they agree on one thing: the killings have
given the livery-cab drivers, who are primarily Hispanic, political
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has pushed the Taxi and Limousine
Commission to require livery-cab drivers to install security
cameras or bulletproof partitions in their cars, and the Police
Department has rolled out initiatives, involving more than 300
officers and scores of detectives, to deter the criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the drivers' list of 26 demands to improve safety has
been circulated among the city's news media, and some of the steps,
including joint news conferences to deter criminals and pledges to
increase officer training, have become elements of the city's
safety program.
</P>
<P>
   But while the police and the drivers are cooperating on many
measures, one Police Department recommendation remains contentious.
The police have asked the drivers to comply with Taxi and Limousine
Commission regulations that forbid them to pick up customers from
the street.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said 82 percent of the
livery-cab robberies this year, and six of the seven homicides,
occurred after drivers had picked up street hails.
</P>
<P>
   But Mateo said that even with the current concerns, the drivers
would be unlikely to comply with the rules. ``These drivers are
trying to put food on the table for their families,'' he said.
``When they see a fare with $5, they're going to stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
