<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Ho hum: Yankees beat Rangers 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Pitchers usually need to be at their best to
beat Orlando Hernandez and the New York Yankees. Kenny Rogers was
hardly that last night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rogers said bluntly, ``I was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers would seem to back up that assessment. Rogers
allowed six runs in the first four innings, and that was more than
enough for Hernandez, who pitched the Yankees to a 6-3 victory
before 43,644 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who once again started slowly and finished strong,
pitched a complete game to give the Yankees their fourth
consecutive victory over the Rangers this season. Including regular
season and playoffs, the Rangers have lost 35 of their past 46
meetings against New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to deal with, because we're always being asked about
it, but we've got nobody to blame but ourselves,'' first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro said. ``The only way the questions will stop is for
us to play baseball, play well and start beating these guys. I
think they're the best team in baseball, but they can be beat. We
can do it. We just have to figure out a way to do it, and we
haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Said left fielder Chad Curtis, ``I've got the solution. We've
got to score more runs than the other team. That's the solution ...
the process I'm not so sure about.''
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis, who spent the past two years with the Yankees, said
what they're doing is no secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good baseball players playing the game the way it was
meant to be,'' Curtis said. ``It's not complicated. It's very
simple. I'm not saying everybody can do it. But it's a simple game.
They don't beat themselves. The run they've had the past four years
is good evidence it's the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are on a pretty good run, too, having won three
division titles in the past four years. That's substantial evidence
they know how to play the game right.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, when they face the Yankees, everything changes.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers tried to pitch with a stiff back and couldn't do it,
falling behind 3-0 in the first inning. Derek Jeter, the Yankees'
second hitter, gave them a 1-0 lead with a home run to center
field, a blast that was followed quickly by doubles from Paul
O'Neill and Tino Martinez, and Jorge Posada's single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had bad stuff,'' said Rogers, whose fastball rarely
topped 84 mph. ``I wasn't finishing pitches the way I should.
That's the way it goes. You toe the rubber, you go with what you
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler hit a two-run homer off Hernandez in the second
inning, but, after the Rangers blew a big chance in the third, the
Yankees added three more against Rogers in the fourth. Posada's
two-run homer hurt the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my pitches were up,'' Rogers said. ``That was the
key, especially in the first inning. A few pitches were low but
nothing consistent. With New York, you're going to have to win a
game 2-1. It's not that we've played poorly; we just haven't done
the things we need to do to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Like hammer Hernandez when he's struggling. Curtis and Ivan
Rodriguez started the Rangers' third with singles, putting runners
on first and second. But, after four pitches, Hernandez was out of
the inning. Palmeiro was thrown out on a little roller in front of
the plate, moving runners to second and third, David Segui popped
out to left and Ruben Mateo bounced back to the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   That was it. After the Yankees scored three in the fourth, the
Rangers managed just three hits over the final six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what ... it's only April,'' Curtis said. ``I'm hoping
we get another shot at those guys down the road. But we've got to
take care of business before then because you know they're going to
be there.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
