<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINSTRIPE FLU STILL HAS STRANGLEHOLD ON RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For the home team, we offer the following
unsolicited advice:
</P>
<P>
   It's a line from the movie The Natural, uttered with memorable
good intentions by a psychoanalyst that the downtrodden New York
Knights have hired to shake their doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Before the real-life New Yorkers, the Yankees, mercifully depart
the premises today, the Rangers would be wise to follow the
rent-a-shrink's advice and detach themselves from the humbling
reality.
</P>
<P>
   With last night's relatively mundane 6-3 victory, the Yanks have
beaten the Rangers seven in a row, dating back, I think, to the
Truman administration. The Rangers have won only 11 of their past
37 regular-season meetings with New York.
</P>
<P>
   That's not domination. That's almost paranormal.
</P>
<P>
   If Monday night's Satanic ending didn't substantiate it, nothing
will. The foul ball off Luis Alicea's foot, which transformed into
a most opportune New York double play, wasn't on the last Penn and
Teller HBO special, but stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Call it black magic. Call it the Pinstripe Flu. Call the
equipment man and tell him that straitjackets are the Rangers' new
alternate uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' dizzying wizardry has gotten into the Rangers'
heads so much, manager Johnny Oates made the observation, ``As
eventful as last night was, it just seemed that tonight was one of
those methodical nights where you just played a game of baseball
without anything exciting happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody spontaneously burst into flames or changed into a cow, in
other words. In the Monday night game, even home-plate umpire Jeff
Kellogg was sucked into the Yankee vortex _ rendered momentarily
stupid during the 11th inning.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling here is that Oates didn't help his team's ongoing
malaise by sitting oddly silent during the inning's confusion. Most
baseball managers _ and some men of the cloth, even _ would have
screamed bloody murder to the point of ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Would it have changed the call? No.
</P>
<P>
   But the deeper observation is that when they play the Yankees,
the Rangers have learned to numbly accept their fate. Somebody in a
``NY'' cap is going to slap a timely single, snatch away a would-be
Rangers hit, or turn water into pinstriped wine, whenever the two
teams meet.
</P>
<P>
   The theory here is that, without the customary demonic
intervention, manager Joe Torre's Yankees would still be dominating
the series. They are the best team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But with the added psychological trimmings, the would-be close
games also are going to the Yankees, who scrap, don't quit, and
possess a telling self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers? They are Yankee wannabes, no more than the rest of
the American League pack.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said from the start, from the early days after the Juan
Gonzalez trade, that this would be a Rangers team that would come
along slowly. There are too many new and young faces, plugged into
too many vital and scattered places, to have expected the Rangers
to hit the April ground running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said from the beginning that there were going to be nights
when we'd struggle,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   His kids will get better, Oates seems to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that you grow much faster through
failure,'' the manager noted. ``Someone once told me that if you
have sunshine every day, sooner or later you'll have a desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will survive. They'll get better. They will learn the
league and learn not to give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they swallow hard. Even with his home run last night,
newcomer Gabe Kapler's average still roosts at .229. Rookie Ruben
Mateo went 0-for-4 to drop to .241.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to be all right,'' Mateo said. ``I just don't
know when.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be, let me suggest, until the Yankees leave town. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
