<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS END SKID AGAINST LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Mavericks wrapped a nice bow around Don Nelson's
final home game as an NBA coach.
</P>
<P>
   They beat LA.
</P>
<P>
   On a night that had a festive, playoff-type atmosphere, the
Mavericks closed out their home schedule with a 112-102 triumph
over the Los Angeles Lakers. The win increased the Mavericks'
record to 39-42 as they snapped a 19-game losing streak against the
Lakers that dated to April 5, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great feeling about this game,'' Nelson said. ``We are
playing so well, and I looked forward to this game more than any
game this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a great game, and we won. They are just
playing not only good basketball, but exciting basketball. This is
the way we pictured it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks close their season tonight at 7 in Minnesota
against the Timberwolves (50-31) in what Nelson has said is his
final game as an NBA coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have built a lot of teams, but I don't know that I have been
more proud of a team than this one, because of our start,'' Nelson
said of the 9-23 start. ``Our start was tough, and we got behind
the eight ball, and these guys haven't given up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers entered last night's game with the NBA's best record,
and were the only Western Conference team that the Mavericks had
not defeated this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks treated this game as if it were their playoff
outing. They hustled, dove for loose balls, even tossed souvenir
basketballs into the stands before and after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bradley even delivered a hard foul that sent Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal sprawling to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with 38 points and 20 rebounds, and he was
disturbed that Nelson used some of his players to intentionally
foul him during key moments of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know every team is going to be after us, and we just have
to be ready for it,'' O'Neal said. ``We just have to cut down on
our own mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley led Dallas with 25 points, Steve Nash had 23
points and eight assists, and Cedric Ceballos scored 21 and grabbed
six rebounds. Also for the Mavericks, Bradley had 12 points and six
rebounds, and Dirk Nowitzki and Hubert Davis scored 10 points
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot 58 percent in the first half, but led only
59-57. With the sellout crowd of 18,190 shouting ``Beat LA, Beat
LA,'' the Mavericks stormed back to take an 80-75 lead going into
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks used key free throws and crucial shots by Finley
to put away the Lakers in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan was sensational, and these guys carried it out
again with no preparation and no practice,'' Nelson said. ``We just
met before the game and went over our strategies.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
