<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1069 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX     04-19 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBONNEAU SCORES WINNER AS STARS BEAT OILERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Somebody forgot to tell Guy Carbonneau he
isn't an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   He's 40 for crying out loud. There aren't any other
40-somethings playing in the NHL, much less having an impact in the
Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So when Stars coach Ken Hitchcock challenged his impact players
before Game 4, he didn't really mean Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest player in the NHL listened anyway, doing what he has
done all season. Doing exactly what nobody expects. Tuesday night,
it was score the winning goal in the Stars' 4-3 victory against the
Edmonton Oilers at Skyreach Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone has to be accountable,'' said Carbonneau, who
had a cut by his left eye from being inadvertantly hit by a stick
from his own bench. ``I didn't real think I played well in the
first game here. For whatever reason, the emotion wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   No big deal really. All it did was give the Stars a chance to
close out the Oilers in Game 5 on Friday at Reunion Arena. All it
did was salvage a game the Stars should've won easily had it not
been for the heroics of Oilers winger Bill Guerin. All it did was
send the Stars back to the Dallas with the split they so
desperately craved and a 3-1 lead in the best-of-seven, first-round
series.
</P>
<P>
   When Carbonneau skated across the blue line with slightly more
than 15 minutes remaining in the third period, the score was tied
3-3. Two Stars had already wasted two leads. The Oilers were
beginning to get confident. You could almost see them thinking
``Hey, we can hang with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Then with a flick of his wrist, Carbonneau sent a shot flying
toward Oilers goalie Tommy Salo. The shot found a way to sneak
between past Salo on the glove side at 5:01 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carbonneau and Keane felt very accountable for the way we
played (in Game 3),'' Hitchcock said. ``They wanted to be big
factors, and they were.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Hitchcock didn't really mean Carbonneau when he said his
impact players had been outplayed by the Oilers' impact players in
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Carbo probably thought he did,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``That was a big goal by him, and we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was thinking more along of the lines of Mike Modano,
Brett Hull, Nieuwendyk, Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to do better, he said, if the Stars were going to
win the series.
</P>
<P>
   They responded. The Stars got goals from Modano, Hull and
Matvichuk. Nieuwendyk was flying all night and hit a post on a
breakaway attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good effort from Hull, and Nieuwendyk stepped up,''
Hitchcock said. ``Nieuwendyk made a difference tonight. We came
with a good one-two punch. Getting four goals on the road is pretty
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, part of the resurgence was Hitchcock's doing. He
switched lines in the second period Tuesday night, giving them a
retro look. Modano and Hull were reunited for the first time in a
month, and Nieuwendyk played with Jamie Langenbrunner. These were
the lines the Stars used to win a Stanley Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
   They worked pretty well Tuesday night, too, helping the Stars
overcome a shaky start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good change,'' Modano said. ``Jamie and Joe really
mesh together.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Game 3, the Oilers had a five-on-three power play early.
Hatcher went to the box 50 seconds into the game for slashing.
Matvichuk joined him 1:40 later. Carbonneau, one of the Stars' best
penalty killers, was assessed a 10-minute misconduct on the play
for arguing with the referee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a stupid misconduct. When I came back on the bench, I
watned to try to help the team as much as possible. In 20 years,
what's 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars killed off the 20 seconds of five-on-three and the
remainder of Matvichuk's penalty. They didn't allow a shot. The
penalties obviously didn't sit well because the Stars came back
angry, scoring two goals in 48 seconds not long after.
</P>
<P>
   Hull scored at 5:02 of the first period, chipping in a rebound
of a Scott Thornton shot. The play began when Nieuwendyk pressured
the defenseman trying to get the puck out of the Oilers' end.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 48 seconds later, Matvichuk made it 2-0 with a single
swing of his stick. He took a pass from rookie center Aaron Gavey
and one-timed it past Salo.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the raucous crowd of 17,100 didn't sound so raucous.
You couldn't hear them.
</P>
<P>
   Not a word, not a peep until 9:19 of the period when Guerin
scored the first of his three goals.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive game, an Oilers player had a hat
trick against the Stars. In Game 3, it was Doug Weight. Tuesday
night, it was Guerin.
</P>
<P>
   He scored two goals two minutes and 24 seconds apart in the
first period to erase a 2-0 Stars lead. He added another at 18:06
of the second period to erase what had become a 3-2 Stars lead.
</P>
<P>
   Only two minutes and 51 seconds before, Nieuwendyk had a chance
to extend the Stars lead to 4-2. His shot on a breakaway hit the
post, trickled behind Salo but didn't cross the line.
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Ed Belfour stopped Oilers winger Ryan Smyth on a
shorthanded breakaway attempt at 7:26 of the second period. Belfour
finished with 21 saves, and Salo had 14.
</P>
<P>
   Salo probably should've made a save on the Carbonneau shot, too.
It doesn't have the velocity it once did. Carbonneau isn't an
impact player like he once was.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not if you equate impact with goals. He doesn't score as
many of those any more.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he kills penalties, gets in Oilers tough guy Georges
Laraque's face, plays on the shut-down line, grinds on the ice in
the final seconds when the Oilers pull the goalies and plays an
all-around solid game.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and every once in a while, he scores a game-winning
goal. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
