<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' VICTORY WAS NO IMPOSSIBLE MISSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ The Dallas Stars' objective when they left
Dallas for this remote outpost in the Canadian northwest was hardly
deemed worthy of calling in the ``Mission Impossible'' crew.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the defending Stanley Cup champs arrived here from
Texas on Friday with a swagger and a comfortable 2-0 lead in this
best-of-seven opening round playoff series and the disheartened
Edmonton Oilers were in complete and total disarray.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, summing
up the situation before Game 3. ``I see us having to win ``a'' game
here. Doesn't matter if it's Game 3 or Game 4. Winning one allows
us to control our own destiny at home, without this coming down to
a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can win one of these two games, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we exhale now?
</P>
<P>
   Stars' general manager Bob Gainey was heading for the phone to
make the call to Tom Cruise and the M.I. gang _ and his team was
looking at the unpleasant prospect of having to leave their bags
packed for the long return trip to Edmonton _ when playoff-tested
Guy Carbonneau, the oldest player on the ice, re-introduced himself
to the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau's quick and deadly wrist shot early in the third
period not only caught Oilers' defender Igor Ulanov and goalie
Tommy Salo by surprise, it sucked the air out of an entire city and
lifted the Stars to a had-to-have it 4-3 victory Tuesday night at a
Skyreach Centre so charged with emotion, it seemed as if the old
arena might actually explode at times.
</P>
<P>
   This series is far from locked up, but the Stars have regained
their two-game advantage with a 3-games-to-1 lead and can end it
with a victory Friday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Praise God and pass the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   That's the essence of the big picture, but there's more, much
more to consider.
</P>
<P>
   After the first two games the Stars looked untouchable. They had
done what they had said they could do, flipping the switch back to
``on'' after ending the regular season on a lifeless five-game
winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oilers, benefiting enormously from the extra day off
between Games 3 and 4, not only regrouped, they seized the momentum
in front of their riotous home crowd by routing the Stars 5-2 in
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Stars won Tuesday night, they did it despite
blowing 2-0 and 3-2 leads, something this team is not supposed to
do. Gone is the once-almost sacred perception that the Stars are an
impregnable defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   It had been over eight years since the Oilers had registered a
playoff hat trick, but they got a pair back-to-back in these two
games, from Doug Weight Sunday and Bill Guerin Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars return to Dallas with their 3-1 lead, but also with
the myth exposed. If they play the way they did in these two games
in Edmonton, They can be had, if not by the Oilers, than down the
playoff road by someone better.
</P>
<P>
   Put that away to ruminate on for another day, because there were
also many positives to be drawn from Tuesday night's shaky victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had challenged the Stars to play ``desperate'' hockey
and to match the intensity level the Oilers had played with in Game
3. In particular the silver-haired coach had appealed to his
prime-time players _ Mike Modano, Brett Hull, Joe Nieuwendyk and
Derian Hatcher _ to lead the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' stars responded with impressive tenacity and
determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got a good effort from Hull, and I thought
Nieuwendyk stepped up,'' Hitchcock said. ``I thought Brett did what
he had to do tonight. He was ready to load it up on every shift but
the real difference was Nieuwendyk. He was a threat all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that had something to do with a blast from the past.
Hitchcock pulled a page out of last year's year's Stanley Cup
manual and put Hull back on a line with Modano and paired Jamie
Langenbrunner with Nieuwendyk, two of his favorite pairs in '99.
The strategy seemed to provide a much-needed spark.
</P>
<P>
   The game wasn't five minutes old when Hull swatted a rebound off
a Scott Thornton shot past Salo for a 1-0 Stars lead. Thirty-eight
seconds later Richard Matvichuk whistled a blast from the left
point that nicked an Oilers' defenseman, skipped once and hit the
back of the net.
</P>
<P>
   For just a moment, you could actually hear yourself think in the
frenzied arena. But only a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We led 2-0,'' Hitchcock said, ``but the game was still going a
thousand miles an hour and we were kind of reeling there. I thought
what settled us down was the third goal. After that we started
playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars had a healthy Sergei Zubov and Jere Lehtinen they
would have a reasonable shot at defending the Cup. How far they can
go is certainly a matter of pure conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, they're simply happy to be going home with their
two-game advantage once again safely tucked in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Cancel the phone call to Mr. Phelps ... for now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
