<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-STRIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE SET FOR FIRST BIG ENTERTAINMENT STRIKE IN DOZEN YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The western contingent of the country's two
largest actors' unions set the stage for what could be the first
major entertainment industry strike in 12 years, voting unanimously
Tuesday to authorize a walkout if a contract is not reached by May.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint National Board of Directors of the Screen Actors Guild
and American Federation of Television and Radio Artists objects to
a proposal by the television and radio advertising industry to give
actors a flat fee for their work in commercials on cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   Actors want to extend the current pay system of compensating
them each time a commercial appears on network television.
</P>
<P>
   They also demand a compensation provision be established for ads
appearing on the Internet and want airings of commercials to be
monitored to ensure an accurate count.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, said SAG spokesman Greg Krizman, advertisers count
how many times a commercial runs and compensate actors appearing in
them using an honor system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to end that honor system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike could still be averted if the advertisers return with
a better offer between now and May 1, Krizman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have to exhibit some real good faith bargaining,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Section of the SAG/AFTRA board of directors voted to
authorize the strike Sunday, after rejecting a final offer from the
American Association of Advertising Agencies and the Association of
National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote of their West Coast counterparts was needed to give
final authorization to the strike, which is scheduled to start May
1.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople representing the negotiators of the two New
York-based advertising organizations could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the AAAA website calls the ``pay-per-use'' compensation the
unions want extend to cable ads ``outdated'' in an April 6 update.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain hopeful that if both sides can accept that the
pay-per-use method is conceptually flawed in today's market, the
economic gulf separating the parties can be bridged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-19 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, MARINERS VICTIMS OF BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It won't be too much longer before those keeping score
at Mariners games put in for hazard pay.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle found itself involved in yet another score-a-thon
Tuesday night. Only this time, the Mariners were not the
perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Seattle's offense looked unstoppable in
Toronto, churning out runs like a mint churns out pennies. The M's
scored almost at will, totaling 47 runs in three games against
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But in Chicago, the script played differently. As did the
Mariners themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Mariners found themselves bound, gagged and tied
on the railroad tracks, helpless as the iron-and-steel locomotive
crewed by the White Sox churned furiously closer, Dudley Do-Right
nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did manage to extricate themselves from the
predicament, but only barely, escaping
cool-but-not-completely-frigid Comiskey Park without victory,
without warmth, without even much dignity in the wake of an 18-11
thrashing by the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played good baseball this year,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said. ``Today was really the only time that we were out of
a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this time, we were out of it in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of all this was an 11-run, nine-hit fourth
inning that was every bit as bad for the M's pitching staff as the
weekend in Toronto had been good for the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele entered the inning with a 6-2 lead. He could do
nothing with the White Sox, a fate that also swept up relievers
Jose Paniagua and Paul Abbott. By the time Mark Johnson's second
hit of the inning, a three-run homer, brought the scoring to a
close, the Seattle pitching staff had been folded, spindled and
mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a short night on the field,'' Sele said. ``But it's
going to be a long night at the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 runs was the most allowed in an inning by the Mariners
since 1984. It was the most scored by the White Sox since 1987. And
there weren't any rainbows at the end in a game in which the
Mariners pitched ugly _ almost too ugly for words.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle came into the game having given up the fewest runs in
the American League, but it's safe to say the Mariners' status as
league earned-run average kings is on shaky turf this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele had looked vulnerable in the first three innings, but
nothing he'd done in the early going _ three singles, three walks _
prepared the Comiskey Park crowd for what was coming. Sele knew he
wasn't sharp, but even he wasn't prepared for what followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gotten a double play in the third to get me out of
trouble,'' Sele said. ``But I was scuffling all night, trying to
find an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sele, who pitched a masterful, three-hit shutout in his
previous start, there were only questions.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Singleton doubled to start the fourth, scoring on a Carlos
Lee single. Greg Norton homered.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, right? Wrong. Seattle still held a 6-5 lead, but it
was obvious that Sele's time on the mound was dwindling at a
furious pace. Singles by Johnson, Ray Durham and Jose Valentin
loaded the bases and forced Sele's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brutal out there,'' Sele said, his lips pursed in the
manner of a perplexed man. ``I didn't give my team a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   While true, no one else pitching for the M's did, either.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua took over, got one out on a warning-track sacrifice fly
by Frank Thomas, then intentionally walked Magglio Ordonez and hit
Paul Konerko, forcing in a run. That also forced in Abbott,
although the force was not with the right-hander, just as it was
not with any of the not-quite-Jedi-Knight Mariner pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was stung for three more hits before the inning was over,
the finale being Johnson's first homer of the season, a blast that
buried the Mariners under the rubble it left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a game like this, you have to remind yourself to live in
the present, to pitch in the present,'' Abbott said. ``The bottom
line is this is just one game, and it wouldn't be any different if
we'd lost 2-0. Thinking like that is the only thing that keeps me
sane.''
</P>
<P>
   And what, exactly, drives Abbott insane?
</P>
<P>
   ``Struggling with my main pitch, the changeup, like I have been
the last two or three times out,'' Abbott said with a wan,
weight-of-the-world smile. ``You have a definite mindset when you
have all your pitches, and when you don't have one that you're used
to relying on, then it's like, `Now what do I do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Mariners, come back Wednesday and hope that
Gil Meche, the starting pitcher, wasn't absorbing anything that
happened Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
