<SLUG> BC-LA-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE LOOMS OVER MAYOR'S NEW BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Several Los Angeles City Council members recoiled
Tuesday at parts of Mayor Richard Riordan's proposed budget _
including resurrecting a plan to use tobacco settlement dollars for
Rampart corruption payouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be pretty contentious in a few places,'' said
Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, a member of the committee reviewing
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor delivered his $4.4 billion budget plan, for the fiscal
year that begins July 1, to the council Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget will improve the quality of life for Angelenos and
make this city a much better place for children to pass on to their
children,'' Riordan told the council.
</P>
<P>
   Already at issue was a plan the mayor knew would draw fire:
Raising money to pay the city's anticipated liability from the
Rampart Division police scandal by selling bonds that would be
repaid using roughly $300 million in revenue the county will get
over the next 25 years from the national tobacco litigation
settlement. About $91 million would be raised immediately on the
promise of that long-term income.
</P>
<P>
   The council rejected a similar Riordan initiative earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Hal Bernson objected to plan, saying the tobacco
dollars should be directed to anti-smoking education and health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco settlement should be used for what it was
earmarked for,'' Bernson said. ``I don't think that should be
sidetracked for anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Joel Wachs said he thinks it is too early to dedicate
millions for Rampart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've heard yet enough public input on paying
the costs of Rampart. That's the public's money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Councilman Michael Feuer, chairman of the city's ad hoc
committee on the budget, said the mayor's plan is easier to swallow
because it also includes $30 million in cash next year to pay
Rampart claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different strategy and, I think, a much more productive
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget committee will hold 10 days of hearings starting
April 26 to review the budget, which then will be subject to the
approval of the full council.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, council members praised the budget's emphasis on
children and public safety. The budget continues a program to
reduce and cut fees for children participating in recreation
programs, and adds a new police station in Mission Hills and two
new fire stations in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes money for several items proposed this
year by council members, Feuer said, including increased emergency
medical services and more money for sidewalk repairs and
playgrounds accessible to disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Some council members balked at the mayor's proposal to scrap the
L.A. Bridges gang-prevention program. A recent audit by City
Controller Rick Tuttle stated that the program, launched in 1997,
hasn't proved effective and should be closed down.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor wants to use the Bridges' $12 million allotment for
other gang prevention efforts designed to replace the failed
Bridges program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you throw out L.A. Bridges wholesale and start over from
scratch, in a year and a half or two, we'll be in the same place
again,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
