<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-MANNERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY ON CELL-PHONE MANNERS FIND USERS ANSWER THE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE CARNEY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The chirpy ring of the cellular phone echoes off
the bathroom walls, presenting a dilemma _ do you answer the phone,
or nature's call?
</P>
<P>
   Two out of five people do both, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of cell-phone etiquette released Tuesday, 39 percent
of people said they take incoming telephone calls in the bathroom,
though only 31 percent said they would do so while dining in a
restaurant, and 11 percent in a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people take affront at people talking on a phone while
eating dinner,'' said Jeffrey Nelson, communications director for
the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association. ``I can't be
the arbiter of good manners, but I can certainly encourage people
to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Delly Tamer, president of LetsTalk.com, an online cell-phone
retailer that commissioned the survey, said his company wanted to
discern Americans' feelings about where the devices are used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's becoming a product everybody can afford,'' Tamer
said. ``So the use in cars, in restaurants, in movie theaters is
much more prevalent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, fewer than half of the 557 cell-phone owners
surveyed nationwide said they would take calls in movies or
restaurants. But 76 percent said they would still take calls in the
car, even though a 1997 report in the New England Journal of
Medicine found that talking on a cell phone while driving
quadruples the chances of a crash _ about the same risk as driving
drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurants and other public places have banned the use of
cell phones, but Nelson said that's an extreme response to
something people should do on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude people are rude,'' he said. ``Putting a new piece of
technology in their hands isn't going to make them any more or less
rude.''
</P>
<P>
   At the landmark Sportsmen's Lodge in suburban Studio City, the
clientele of business people and entertainment executives make cell
phones as commonplace as silverware.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much accepted now,'' said Vesna Saric, who has
been tending bar at the restaurant for a year. ``Everybody's got
them, everybody's connected. One cell phone will ring and everybody
in the bar reaches for their phones. It's pretty funny.''
</P>
<P>
   After being interrupted by a call during a coffee break with a
friend at Starbucks, entertainment attorney Ron Tropp of Woodland
Hills said he only got his phone because he has ``certain clients
who want to reach me anytime, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep it to a minimum,'' he said. ``It's intrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Composer, musician and producer Ramin Zamani, also of Woodland
Hills, said he needs his phone for his business, though he ``would
be very disturbed'' if he heard one go off while performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I did it twice myself, so it can happen,'' he said,
recalling a couple of instances when he forgot to shut off his
phone in concert halls. He quickly jabbed it off each time.
</P>
<P>
   Ringing phones haven't been a problem at the Los Angeles Museum
of Contemporary Art, said visitor services coordinator Valerie
Partridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had one or two complaints in the past, where someone
was on the cell phone in the gallery and they were loud,'' she
said, so guards asked them to take the conversations outside.
</P>
<P>
   Phone improvements such as greater clarity and sensitivity,
which eliminate the need to shout into the mouthpiece, or silent,
vibrating ringers have erased some of the offenses. But that might
be outweighed by the devices' increasing popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Tamer said industry analysts believe 40 percent of American
households have a cellular phone _ a number they say will jump to
70 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
   With that rise might come an increase in the two out of five
cell-phone owners who consider the bathroom part of their coverage
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think about that,'' Tamer said. ``If you
take a call in the bathroom, you'll take a call anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
