<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-STADIUM-AZR &LR;      04-19 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS TO DECIDE STADIUM'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY NENA BAKER AND TESSIE BORDEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Talk about dramatic finishes.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Cardinals scored in the waning hours of the
legislative session Tuesday, April 18, finessing out of the House a
stadium-financing plan that had been voted down just a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for building a $331 million home for the
Cardinals, using largely money that will be raised through tax
hikes on hotel rooms and rental cars.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County voters likely will get the ultimate say this
fall. Gov. Jane Hull is expected to sign Senate Bill 1220 and put
it on the Nov. 7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals backers sent an all-out blitz - former Gov. Fife
Symington was pressed into play - and changed the minds of half a
dozen lawmakers to pass the bill out of the House with the minimum
required 31 votes. The team now must win the hearts of voters, who
may be more reluctant to embrace the plan.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona Republic poll of 600 state residents in late December
showed 85 percent opposed to spending tax money for a new stadium
for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And the team's last attempt at a publicly funded facility, the
Rio Salado Crossing Project, failed by a 2-to-1 margin at the
ballot box in Mesa last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are excited that the people of Maricopa County
get the opportunity to vote on this in November,'' said Mike
Bidwill, the Cardinals' vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful that voters will pass the plan. We have five
months to get a campaign going for them to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money for the plan would be raised by a 1 percent
bed tax surcharge and a 3.25 percent rental car tax in Maricopa
County. At the same time, money generated at the new 73,000-seat
stadium _ including state income taxes from National Football
League activities (a ``jock tax''), as well as sales and
construction taxes - would flow to the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals must contribute $85 million of the estimated $331
million price tag, excluding the costs for land, parking and other
infrastructure. The Fiesta Bowl is committed to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows the Cardinals to retain all NFL revenues as well
as stadium naming rights worth millions. At the same time, the
public authority that will own the facility will pay maintenance
and operation costs, including the Cardinals' game-day expenses.
Those costs are estimated at $420 million over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wheeler, the Fiesta Bowl chairman, said the funding also
may include a ticket surcharge similar to the surcharge now in
place with Arizona State University's Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a stadium, the plan includes new money for state
tourism promotion, Cactus League baseball-stadium enhancements and
youth sports activities _ goodies that worked to entice some
lawmakers who were not inclined to support a stadium bill on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, Wheeler and Bank One Chairman Michael Welborn, who
headed up a task force charged by Gov. Hull to develop plans for a
new stadium, were reluctant to talk about what might happen if
voters reject the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Wellborn said voter approval for the funding package is Plan B
for the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally very worried about what might happen if the
voters don't approve it,'' he said. ``Our sports financing group in
Chicago knows a lot of cities that would love to have NFL football.
Cities that have lost these assets have spent in excess of $1
billion trying to bring them back. I can tell you that people in LA
are terribly interested in what's going on with this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles last fall lost its bid to acquire the NFL's 32nd
franchise to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill described the Cardinals' latest plan as a better deal
than Rio Salado Crossing, which called for a general sales tax,
because hotel and rental-car taxes have less impact on Arizona
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bidwill and a brigade of stadium lobbyists had
some tense moments watching the vote unfold.
</P>
<P>
   As the House tally board held steady at 30 yes votes, one vote
shy of passage, Rep. Dan Schottel, R-Tucson, rose and said he was
changing his vote from no to yes.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Schottel told reporters he flip-flopped after
Symington gave him a call to encourage a yes vote, and then called
back to thank him.
</P>
<P>
   Schottel said he'd heard ``from a real governor,'' a clear shot
at Hull, whom conservatives have long thought to be too moderate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't believe it's a good bill,'' said Schottel. ``But
if it brings revenues to Arizona then I can support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford, too, contacted lawmakers
from the minority party who opposed the bill in an attempt to win
yes votes. But no Democrats switched their votes in spite of the
lobbying juggernaut that included an e-mail campaign by stadium
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to mention any names, but all of a sudden
lobbyists had a revelation that there was a Sally Gonzales in the
Legislature,'' said Rep. Sally Ann Gonzales, D-Tucson. ``I'm amazed
at how many people were working this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Schottel, five other representatives switched
their votes from no to yes: Rep. Wes Marsh, R-Scottsdale; Rep. Tom
Gordon, R-Peach Springs; Rep. Syliva Laughter R-Kayenta; Rep. Jim
Weiers, R-north Phoenix and House Majority Leader Lori Daniels,
R-Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of letting the public decide the issue outweighed
the concerns that some lawmakers had about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did get a flurry of phone calls and letters from people
asking for the right to vote on this,'' Weiers said. ``I don't
think it's going to pass at the ballot, but this way we'll never
have to ask ourselves, `What if?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he changed his vote after hearing from Navajo Nation
tourism representatives who said the statewide tourism promotion
could benefit the reservation, where unemployment is over 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, if the people of Maricopa County want to tax
themselves and their visitors, then let them,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the plan called the bill's passage a sad day for the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such a huge group of stellar lobbyists working
this one issue,'' said Rep. Kathi Foster, D-west Phoenix. ``You'd
think we were curing cancer or stopping world hunger. Something is
seriously wrong when we spend days on a football stadium and I have
to hold off . . . making my schools safe for children.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reporters Chris Moeser, Robbie Sherwood and Lee Shappell
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Nena.Baker(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8256.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
