<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE HOME FINALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The plump, low-flying buzzards circling the
Clippers have been served the final home course in this season's
14-67 feast.
</P>
<P>
   They were waved in Tuesday night by the Portland Trail Blazers,
who administered a 116-100 beating before a sellout throng of
18,964 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   As fan depreciation nights go, bowing out against the mighty
Blazers seems as chronologically warped as giving hostages the
bamboo treatment while the treaty is being signed.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith scored 24 points to pace Portland (59-22), which is
poised to open its post-season skirmish vs. Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who will receive this season's benediction tonight
at Seattle, pushed their losing streak to 17 and backed out of L.A.
behind 15 points from rookie Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent contender Maurice Taylor succumbed to a sore ankle
and didn't suit up, missing his final moment with the Clipper
faithful. Derek Anderson, the Clips' other anticipated free-agent
goner, tied Tyrone Nesby for team-high scoring honors by producing
20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for a capsule summation of knowledge acquired during his
single season as a Clipper, Anderson said, ``I learned to respect
the game. I always have. But now I realize that some people
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also said that despite what appeared to be a high level
of training-camp optimism, the team's record through 81 games is no
surprise to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because half the people at training camp expected it to
be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's only momentum swing occurred before the game, when
Anderson said he would not completely rule out the possibility of
signing with the Clippers this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers Notes: Clipper Keith Closs confirmed the widespread
radio rumors of his involvement in a Sunday night fight outside a
Southland nightclub. The 7-foot-3, 215-pound Closs, who - according
to team sources - was thumped by as many as 20 people or as few as
four, was not exactly declared the fight's victor. ESPN acquired a
videotape that was purported to be evidence of a one-sided fight,
but the network couldn't tell if the exceedingly tall and skinny
man being beaten was - beyond a shadow of a doubt -- Closs. ...One
of the VIP seats flanking Mr. and Mrs. Donald T. (`T' for The
owner) Sterling was occupied by USC coach Henry Bibby. Job
interview? Don't call your bookie. ... Brian Skinner (high sprain,
left ankle) now has missed 48 games. Eric Murdock (sore left ankle)
was in street clothes for the 41st game. ... Odom's punishment for
skipping Monday's practice was not starting vs. Portland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
