r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     04-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MISSTEP FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS - In another day or so, the Lakers' full focus will be on
the playoffs, and their level of play will no doubt match the
occasion. But for one night Tuesday, they instead replayed snippets
of nearly every glitch in their game, the kind of kinks they had
long since expunged.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal shot-putted free throws off the iron.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant flung passes into traffic.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA's top defense allowed drive after uncontested drive
into the paint.
</P>
<P>
   This looked a lot like the Lakers of late January as they
stumbled through a 112-102 loss to the newly awakened Dallas
Mavericks before 18,190 at Reunion Arena. For the Mavericks, who
snapped a 19-game losing streak to the Lakers, this !ital!was!off!
a playoff game, with the fevered pitch and postgame celebration to
match.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Lakers (67-14), this was an irritating, if
meaningless, loss as they try to maintain momentum for the playoffs
that begin this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to lose any ballgames, you know what I mean?''
Bryant said. ``But there's nothing you can do about it. It's not
going to be destructive, it's not going to destroy us, anything
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be because this loss ultimately means nothing, of
course. For the first time since the Lakers clinched the NBA's best
record two weeks ago, they played like a team that had nothing left
to gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a dangerous situation to be in,'' Rick Fox
acknowledged, ``especially in this league, when you play on an
opponent's home court, where they've played so well the last two
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is 15-5 over its last 20 games, the second hottest team
in the league behind these Lakers. But the Lakers' loss was the
product of some uncharacteristic blemishes.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was 7 for 20 from the field for 16 points and coughed up
six of the Lakers' season-high-tying 24 turnovers as the Lakers got
sloppy in a high-tempo game.
</P>
<P>
   And the running, gunning Mavericks outscored the Lakers in the
paint 50-36 behind 25 points from Michael Finley, 23 from Steve
Nash and 21 from former Laker Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   And though O'Neal had 38 points and 20 rebounds, he wilted at
the foul line as Mavericks coach Don Nelson again resorted to
intentional fouling, aka, ``hack-a-Shaq.'' It was Nelson who
started O'Neal's year with such harassment back in November. But
O'Neal had since gained a shooting touch at the line.
</P>
<P>
   It disappeared when Nelson ordered intentional fouls three times
in the closing minute of the third quarter. O'Neal missed all six
free throws, and the Lakers went from a one-point lead to a
five-point deficit and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``That
spelled the game right there.... That made the difference in the
quarter. That kind of energy and the energy you lose from missing
free throws really took us down in the fourth quarter, and it took
us a while to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who made 7 of 10 foul shots in the fourth, finished 8
for 19 from the line, and again lashed out at Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concentrating. Like I said, it's hard to get up for
B.S. coaches and B.S. players. He won today. Quote me on that,''
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were not at full strength. Ron Harper rested his sore
tailbone, joining Derek Fisher on the bench and forcing Jackson to
use rookie John Celestand for 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a group of guys that are banged up right now,'' Fox
said. ``You look around, you say we've got some time to get
healthy. But it wasn't anything else other than them playing a
better game than us today.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers' regular season is down to one game, tonight in
San Antonio, giving them a chance to regain a little lost rhythm
and perhaps a win at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game is going to be important regardless,'' Glen Rice
said. ``We do want to end the regular season on a winning note, and
I think that's going to be a positive thing for us. And we have to
put this one behind us. There's nothing we can do about it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
