<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1090 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     04-19 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY'S 8 RBI SPARK ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO -- It took only one swing of the bat, but Adam Kennedy's
trip to the plate in the top of the fourth inning of Tuesday
night's Angels-Toronto Blue Jays game ignited a flurry of hits,
runs and emotion that finally ended in a 16-10 Angels victory
before 13,825 at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's fourth-inning grand slam was only the beginning for
the second baseman, who finished the game with eight RBI, tying an
Angels record accomplished three times previously, the last time
done by Don Baylor in 1979, also in Toronto. Leon Wagner and Lee
Thomas both did it in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also had a bases-loaded triple in the fifth inning --
just five-feet short of another grand slam -- and an RBI-single in
the ninth. The ninth also featured a bench- and bullpen-clearing
melee, sparked when Blue Jays pitcher John Frascatore hit Scott
Spiezio with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus had doubled in a run to give the Angels a 15-4 lead,
which was followed by a trip to the mound by Blue Jays pitching
coach Rick Langford. On the very next pitch after the meeting on
the mound, Frascatore hit Spiezio on the right leg. Spiezio didn't
charge the mound, but exchanged words with Frascatore as he moved
toward first.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams then gathered along the first-base line for some
obligatory pushing and shoving before order was restored.
Frascatore was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bull-(expletive),'' said Angels first baseman Mo
Vaughn, who was in the center of the action. ``We didn't do that to
them when they dropped seven runs on us (Monday). ... We're not the
type of club that takes that stuff lightly. Somebody could get
hurt. You've got to take your beatings like a man. If you can't get
the ball across the plate, find someone else to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Blue Jays clubhouse after the game, Frascatore denied it
was intentional, but Spiezio had trouble believing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew he was going to do it,'' Spiezio said. ``I could
see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Vaughn, manager Mike Scioscia and left fielder Darin
Erstad were the most active when things were heated. Frascatore's
shirt was torn open when he escaped the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all I could do to keep Mo and Erstad back,'' Scioscia
said, adding he thought the pitch by Frascatore was intentional.
``You always like to give people the benefit of the doubt. I sure
hope he wasn't throwing at him. We weren't doing anything to show
anybody up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd never do that. They scored seven runs (Monday) night and
came back with 10 tonight. We wouldn't take that approach. But it
looked pretty obvious to me (that it was intentional).''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who was criticized last season for not joining his
teammates in a fight in Cleveland, noticed that Scioscia was right
along side him during the scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all out there together,'' Vaughn said. ``I'm sure he's
been in a lot of 'em. That's what a team is. That was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays scored six runs in the bottom of the ninth, and it
included former-Dodger Raul Mondesi having to be restrained after
being thrown out of the game by homeplate umpire Al Clark. Mondesi
had flied out, but was upset over a strike call that appeared out
of the strikezone during his at-bat. After being thrown out, tried
to get to Clark. When he finally went to the bench, Mondesi tossed
a cooler and equipment onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   None of the fireworks would have happened if it wasn't for the
career night of Kennedy, who had four of the Angels' season-high 19
hits. He came to the plate in the second inning with the bases
loaded and struck out, which gave him that much more motivation
when he batted in the fourth with the bases full again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, definitely, especially in a 1-0 game,'' said Kennedy,
who raised his average to .367. ``I was really trying to have a
good at-bat, and something good happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one inning later, he batted again with the bases full, and
he hit the first pitch he saw off the right-center field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine something like that happening,'' Kennedy said
of batting three times with the bases loaded. ``People have to get
on base in front of you. They had some good at-bats all night
long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
