<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SALMON STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO -- Tim Salmon started the 2000 season with a home run in
his first at-bat off the Yankees' Orlando Hernandez, but since then
Salmon has not driven in another run. He's hitting .178 overall and
just .050 (1 for 20) with runners in scoring position. Tuesday, he
went 0 for 6 with four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon is doing everything he can to snap out of his slump,
including watching videotape. He has looked at tape of himself from
the 1997 season -- the last time he was healthy for a full season
-- when he hit .296 with 33 homers and 129 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else just to reinforce I can hit the ball,'' Salmon
said. ``I'm not breaking anything down or looking at mechanics.
It's just something that when you're in a slump you want to see you
can get a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his problem has to do with how pitchers are pitching
him. Salmon has 13 walks, which, going into Tuesday's game, was
tied for most in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere through the middle of our lineup, other managers are
going to pick one guy and say 'We don't want to see him beat us,'
'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``For some it's Mo (Vaughn), for
some it's Timmy, for some it's G.A. (Garret Anderson). Timmy and Mo
are getting their walks, and G.A.'s getting RBIs. Although (Salmon)
is not as productive as he will be, I don't see any gross
negligence. Timmy's been disciplined. They're trying to expand the
strikezone on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has six RBIs this season; Anderson has 13.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jason Dickson (2-0) enjoyed the run support in
Tuesday's 16-10 win, but couldn't get out of the sixth inning. He
threw five scoreless innings before getting the ball up in the
sixth, when he gave up consecutive homers to Craig Grebeck, Raul
Mondesi and Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson allowed four runs and nine hits in 5 1/3 innings,
striking out five and walking none. He had retired 14 of 16 batters
entering the sixth, when all of a sudden he lost his release point,
and consequently his pitches were up in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get into a groove as quickly as you fall out of it,''
Dickson said. ``I was typical of that tonight. I cruised into the
sixth inning, made some mistakes and they took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson has allowed only one walk in 18 1/3 innings this season,
and leads the American League with an average of 0.5 walks per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been making use of their bench in recent days,
with injuries to Gary DiSarcina, Darin Erstad and Garret Anderson.
DiSarcina's on the disabled list with a bruised left thumb, but the
injuries to Erstad (shoulder) and Anderson (ankle) caused them to
miss only one game each.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine games he has started at shortstop in DiSarcina's
place, Benji Gil is hitting .300 (9 for 30) with three RBIs and two
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro and Edgard Clemente started in the outfield
Monday night and both made nice running catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game's not easy,'' said Palmeiro, who is hitting .444 (4
for 9). ``You prepare the best you can. You hit early, study tapes
and try to stay on top of it. These guys (starters) stay sharp
because they played yesterday. I don't have that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   The SkyDome roof has been closed the past two nights because of
cold and damp weather. Temperature inside the SkyDome the past two
nights -- 68 degrees. Temperature outside the SkyDome Monday -- 39
degrees; Tuesday -- 43 degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
