<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' HUNDLEY FINDS POWER SWITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley has seen enough of these sub-.200
starts. Gone through enough struggle. Heard enough doubters.
</P>
<P>
   What Hundley wanted more than anything was a fresh start, and
then there was his early .167 average staring back at him.
</P>
<P>
   But on a cool Tuesday night at Dodger Stadium, Hundley made like
a man intent on a new beginning, drilling a two-run home run to
propel the Dodgers to a 5-3 victory over the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of just 26,298 saw the Dodgers hit three home runs,
Darren Dreifort pitch six strong innings to even his record at 1-1
and Jeff Shaw close it in the ninth for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs were the way of the night, and they had the lead
bouncing around through the middle innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell and his modified goatee gave Houston a 3-2 lead in
the top of the sixth, when he hit his fourth home run of the season
halfway up the left-field pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   But leads came and went quickly Tuesday, and the Dodgers
regained the advantage in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Dotel, the prized Mets prospect acquired in the trade
for Mike Hampton, was either overpowering hitters all night or
watching them hit rockets.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, there were rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros drilled a ground-rule double on a bounce into the
left- field stands to bring up Hundley, who promptly belted a drive
to deep center.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was sure it was out, and stood at the plate a long time
watching the ball's flight. Then he noticed Roger Cedeno running
back like he had a play. The ball just did clear his glove at the
wall for Hundley's second home run of the season and a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel (0-2) left for a pinch-hitter after six innings. He gave
up the four runs on seven hits, but struck out 10 to match his
career-high. That would have come last year in his only other
appearance against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White pushed the Dodgers' lead to 5-3 with a solo home run
off reliever Doug Henry, the one-time closer for the Brewers, to
open the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort started for the Dodgers, and aside from a brief bout of
wildness in the second, pitched well.
</P>
<P>
   In his six innings, Dreifort allowed three runs on three hits.
He walked two and struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre hit the first home run on the night, his second of
the season in the fourth to tie the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had taken a 2-1 lead with two semi-gift runs in the
fourth, when Dreifort suddenly struggled with his control.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort walked Cedeno to open the inning and then hit Bagwell
on the arm with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti grounded out to second to advance the runners, and
Richard Hidalgo looped a little broken-bat, two-run single to
center.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo missed half of last season after undergoing knee
surgery, but his 12 RBI are second on the Astros to Bagwell and he
has the look of arising star.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers opened the scoring with a run in the second. Karros
walked and was singled to third by Hundley. Beltre's fly to center
was just deep enough to sacrifice the less-than-fleet Karros in for
the first run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
