<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-PHOTOGRAPHERS (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ Twenty-five years after
the Vietnam War ended, a new visual record is emerging from
thousands of photos, little known outside Vietnam, taken from the
communist perspective. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-HEROIN (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Pakistan, which does not
lead the world in much, is most likely number one when it comes to
heroin addicts. Reliable country-by-country numbers have not been
compiled, with social science a low priority in the Third World and
addicts hard to poll anyway. But the United Nations estimates there
are 1.5 million heroin addicts in this nation of 150 million, the
unfortunate result of geography, geopolitics, corruption and
poverty. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA-BOMBING (Oklahoma City) _ The bombing of the federal
building here five years ago Wednesday helped create an identity
for a state that had little outside its own borders. From the ruins
and shattered lives emerged a picture of the Heartland, of
neighbors pulling together to help each other. Some people, like a
local businessman and National Guardsman who now runs an institute
on terrorism, have a new focus. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-ACTIVIST (Miami) _ As other Cuban-American leaders
have dealt with the press and the politicians, Ramon Saul Sanchez
has been a leader of the protesters in front of Lazaro Gonzalez's
house. Once a hard-line opponent of Castro, he has adopted a more
peaceful approach and has pressed for civil disobedience. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRACKDATA-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Among the many evangelists
for online investing who have appeared in recent years, few have
been as ubiquitous as Baruch Israel Hertz. His New York company
promises to make investing a cinch even for novices, providing
stock quotes, market information and easy access to electronic
trading. ``You don't have to be a pro to trade like one,'' he says
on the Web site of his stock-trading system, MyTrack. But when
stocks plunged on Friday, many investors who had borrowed heavily
to play the market suddenly faced demands from their lenders that
they put up more money to cover their losses. And one of the
biggest losers was Hertz. Market Place column by Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERAGE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ There is a new trend in
advertising for brokerage firms. Reacting to a recent shift in the
investment climate _ not to mention the gut-wrenching plunge in
stocks on Friday _ marketers of financial products and services are
moderating their pitches, playing down irrational exuberance in
favor of counseling balance. ``Financial advertising has gotten
less silly,'' said Marten Hoekstra, executive vice president and
marketing director at PaineWebber in New York. The result has been
to cool down considerably an advertising category that had been
positively giddy in its ebulliently optimistic assertions about how
easy it is to make money by buying stocks and mutual funds. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-EMPLOYEE-OPTIONS (Undated) _ In the last three years,
Internet companies, with their promise of stock options, have had a
huge advantage in attracting and keeping employees. The sharp
swings in technology stocks have caused these companies to
reassess. Some are looking at stock grants and repricing, all the
while mindful of new accounting rules that will force them to take
a hit. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS (Undated) _ Ordinarily the antiquarian trade
is the dusty, genteel corner of the book market that attracts
fiercely independent booksellers who savor the musty fragrance of
brown-spotted rag paper and the Eureka moment of spotting a rare
first edition dumped in a garage sale heap. But now the dust motes
are flying in the rare and used book market with the flashy
emergence of Alibris, a virtual used bookseller with Wall Street
ambitions and Silicon Valley money. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-BOSS (Undated) _ Workplace profile of Homayoon Hariri,
the chairman of System Group Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-BLIND-CONSULTANT (Undated) _ Blind people can't easily
tell if a job candidate is white or black, thin or obese, plain or
pretty. So if they should happen to assess an applicant's
professional qualifications, they might well focus on a more
mundane matter: Is she actually suited for the job? That is, in
essence, the question that Herbert Greenberg, 70 years old and
blind since he was 10, has been helping managers answer for the
past 39 years. By Geoffrey Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STOOGES-TV (Undated) _ Three Stooges yuk it up in ABC-TV film
produced by Mel Gibson. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT-SCULPTURE (Undated) _ Arts in America: Huge heads of
U.S. presidents, created by Houston sculptor, await their fate. By
Kate Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   BIRD-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Green Bird,'' opening at
the Cort Theater, is reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Two reminiscences of the
horrors in Cambodia under the Khmer Rouge _ ``First They Killed My
Father,'' by Loung Ung and ``When Broken Glass Floats,'' by
Chanrithy Him, are reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
