   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd criticizes Attorney
General Janet Reno's failure to act in the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Paul Krugman assesses criticism of
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BLIND-RUNNER (Eugene, Ore.) _ Marla Runyan suffers from a
degenerative condition of the retina called Stargardt's disease,
which has left her with a hole in the center of her vision. She has
20-300 vision in one eye, 20-400 in the other. Despite her
impairment, Runyan has an encouraging chance at the U.S. Olympic
track and field trials in July to become the first legally-blind
athlete to make an American team for the Winter or Summer Games.
Her career is remarkable for many reasons beyond her visual
impairment, and she is restless for the day when someone will write
about her as an athlete, not a legally blind athlete. By Jere
Longman.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the controversy
surrounding Bobby Valentine, manager of the Mets. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAMB-FARM (Latrobe, Pa.) _ Among golfers, this town of 10,000
about an hour's drive east of Pittsburgh is known for Arnold
Palmer, who was born here. Among beer drinkers, it is known for
Rolling Rock, the malty lager in the long-neck green bottles, which
is brewed here. Among serious sundae scholars, all three of them,
it is known as the birthplace of the banana split. But among
committed cooks, it is known for Jamison Farm, between Latrobe and
Crabtree, which produces some of the nation's best lamb _ firm yet
tender, younger, paler and tastier than supermarket lamb; with
recipes. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LINGERING-DINERS (New York) _ Now that ``No Smoking'' and
``No Cell Phones'' icons have become standard signage at New York
restaurants, it may be time for one more admonishment. No
Lingering! The stock market arrows may be pointing down, but
there's still plenty of hungry money out there: demanding diners
and restaurants eager to turn as many tables as possible in a
night. The occasional bum's rush from a white-tablecloth
establishment is not a brand-new phenomenon. But an informal survey
suggests that skirmishes on the contentious border between service
and civility are on the rise.The go-go '00s are no decade for
lingering, especially over dinner. Fortunes are made and lost in
the time it takes to sip a second cappuccino. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FETTISDAGSBULLAR (Undated) _ Spring rolls, Swedish style: The
sweet almond- and cream-filled buns called fettisdagsbullar are
uniquely Scandinavian treats that were traditionally served every
Tuesday from Shrove Tuesday in February until Easter. Their closest
Anglo-Saxon equivalent is the much more modest hot cross bun, which
the English, with their usual reserve, manage to put off eating
until Good Friday. The distinctive essence of fettisdagsbullar,
literally Fat Tuesday buns, derives from cardamom, almond paste,
sugar and whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   FRESH-HAM (Undated) _ `Fresh ham' is hind leg of pork uncured
and unsmoked. To distinguish it from the cured version, it has come
to be called ``fresh ham,'' and it is a truly wonderful pork roast.
Anyone looking for a new centerpiece for the holiday table ought to
give it a chance; with recipe; with recipe. By John Willoughby and
Chris Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   TEA-ONLINE (Undated) _ Tea soothes, as everyone knows, but it
also may be good for you. A report on where to find it online. by
Shelly Belzer.
</P>
<P>
