A1095 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN     04-19 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS' L.A. MEMORIES LINGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS - Del Harris is 14 months removed from his dismissal as
head coach of the Lakers, but his emotions _ both negative and
positive _ were still evident Tuesday as he watched his former team
from the other side of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is one of nine assistant coaches under his friend and
Dallas Mavericks coach Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent four years with the (Lakers), so naturally anytime you
coach a player and have a good experience with the player, there's
something special about him to you as a coach,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won 61 games under Harris two years ago, but he was
fired after just 12 games last season and replaced by Kurt Rambis.
In a remarkable turnaround, they're now the odds-on favorites to
win the championship under coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was with the team 19 days, so what happened last year with
the people they had really is not part of my memory bank,'' Harris
said, ``because that was Kurt's year and (Dennis) Rodman's year and
(owner) Jerry Buss' year. And I don't feel I should be any part of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, the best years I had were there. I think
obviously I would have continued to win games, if that's what
you're asking.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Lakers' quick ascension, Harris said: ``Well, of course,
they're maturing. Not to take away anything from what the coaching
staff has done there, but I think they did find out it's a little
harder to win a game when Shaq doesn't play the other night. Try
that 53 times _ that's how many games Shaq missed for me (over two
seasons). ... And Kobe was 18 and 19 years old. And one of those
years Robert Horry played only 13 games.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal's MVP play is not a surprise to Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a huge fan of Shaq and had done the best that
I could to promote him as an MVP sort of a player, because I know
he was for us,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been nice to watch, particularly the evolvement of
Kobe,'' he said. ``He's just turned into a magnificent player. And
he was a magnificent 18- and 19-year-old, but he was 18 and 19.
Now, he's 21 and playing like 27. He's just an incredible player.
They both are.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Ron Harper was held out of Tuesday night's game to
rest the bruised tailbone he suffered Sunday against Minnesota. His
status for tonight's game is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed rest,'' Jackson said. ``He's under some pain. It's
something I don't think is serious. ... We'll see how he feels
(tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   Spurred to win: The Lakers have lost two of three to the Spurs
and might meet them in the second round of the playoffs, but
Jackson said he wasn't placing much significance on tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have everybody available and they don't more than
likely, because (Tim) Duncan's not available, and so what does that
send a message to whom?'' Jackson said. ``There's nothing to be
gained by it. But then there's the value of the game itself. You
play games, you play hard. ... We want to win in the Alamodome,
there's no doubt about it. But to the extent of damaging our
physical capabilities or anything else for a (playoff) series which
may start on Saturday doesn't seem to make any sense when you only
have a day of practice or two days off in between.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
