<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1096 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f bc-LADN-SMART.F     04-19 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDLY-BANKRUPTCY-MERGER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER FIRM FILES TO PROTECT ITS ASSETS
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-SMART.F (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Record sales and strong profits were not enough to
keep computer equipment maker Smart and Friendly Inc. out of
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   High Technology Distributing Co., the parent of Smart and
Friendly Inc., has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection after
some of the privately held company's creditors moved to take
control of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Solomon, Smart and Friendly's president, said he expects
the company to quickly emerge from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of compact disc recorders and other computer
peripheral devices has been experiencing record sales this year,
Solomon said. Losses last year are the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The filing was, in fact, precipitated by our bank syndicate
having declared a technical default under a trade finance
agreement. This entire situation has caught us by surprise,''
Solomon said. ``We are a leader in our industry and are confident
that we have the support of our key technical partners and our key
customers, as required, to hopefully emerge from this in an
expeditious manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, just prior to Thursday's filing, the company was
forced to suspend its business.
</P>
<P>
   Its building, equipment and inventory were seized by a group of
banks led by Sanwa Bank, which issued a written statement regarding
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Sanwa said it and two other lenders made loans to Smart and
Friendly that were secured by the company's assets, and the bank
moved to seize them after other efforts to collect were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said the company has regained possession of its assets
and expects to being shipping products immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's 50 employees have been laid off during the
slowdown, Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, key employees are running the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``As operations ramp up, we certainly will be working to staff
up to appropriate levels,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy Court documents show the company owes $5.2 million to
20 unsecured creditors. The company claims between $10 million and
$50 million in assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-19 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM DESERVES ROOKIE AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The L.A. Kings would be in a very different
position today if their power play had worked as well this year as
Steve Francis'. The Houston guard is poised to run away with NBA
Rookie of the Year honors after turning his back on the Vancouver
Grizzlies, who earned his enmity by selecting him with the second
overall pick of the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Francis forced the Grizzlies' hand and they turned him over to
Houston, where he has averaged 18.0 points and 6.6 assists for a
veteran Rockets team that has fizzled this year, falling short of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots for the NBA's regular-season awards are due today and if
we had one, Lamar Odom would be our choice for Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard all the arguments for why Odom is not as deserving
as Francis or Chicago's Elton Brand. We don't dispute that the
6-foot-10 forward is averaging fewer points (16.4) than Francis or
Brand (19.9) and fewer rebounds (7.8) than Brand's rookie-leading
10.0.
</P>
<P>
   We're fully aware Odom hasn't been able to strap his team to his
back and carry it past the Bulls or the Rockets in the won-loss
column.
</P>
<P>
   But to focus on the numbers is to forget the most numbing fact
of all, the card that trumps all others as far as we're concerned:
Odom plays for the most cheerless, the most clueless, the most
wretched franchise in the league.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the NBA's version of Cuba, delivered by fate to a place
where players plot and pray to escape one man's economic tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, no other rookie knows the hardships Odom has seen.
</P>
<P>
   How could they? Among the league's leading rookies, only Odom is
a Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old had no idea what an albatross that affiliation
would be until he started wearing it across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he had heard all the horror stories: How owner Donald
Sterling watches every penny, and we don't mean Hardaway; how the
franchise collects lottery picks like lint and eventually gives
them all the brush-off; and how the only thing shakier than the
ground L.A. residents stand on is the turf on which the Clippers
head coach treads.
</P>
<P>
   The trepidation Odom ought to have felt from the outset didn't
hit him until the Clippers lost 23 of 24 games in a January slide
that spilled into February and the head coach, Chris Ford, was
fired and the team's two veteran leaders, Maurice Taylor and Derek
Anderson, commenced using the past tense instead of the future
perfect when talking about their days as Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew in training camp the way things are,'' Odom said
Tuesday, ``but it was a little shocking to actually see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows Odom is no stranger to adversity. He bounced
around colleges before landing at Rhode Island and was dogged right
up until the draft by questions concerning his college test scores
and the company he kept.
</P>
<P>
   So it's saying something when Odom calls this season, ``the
toughest stress I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   All the losses and all the punchlines to the L.A. sports scene's
longest running joke take a toll on a player, even as one as
preternaturally positive as Odom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes its toll on you mentally,'' he said before the
Clippers' final regular-season home game, a 116-100 loss to
Portland. ``You're able to block everything out for moments at a
stretch. But of course it gets tome.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an atmosphere like this, your enthusiasm for the game is
going to get tested. But I haven't lost mine. I'm really looking
forward to being a team leader next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers could use a loyal lead dog. Imagine competing in
the Iditarod with Huskies that run off in different directions,
scattering like a broken dream, and you've got a general idea how
Ford, and interim coach Jim Todd felt this year.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was the captain but he got too bogged down in his own
contract morass to be a proper pacesetter. Eventually _ inevitably
_ the atmosphere in Clipperland would grow so unhealthy, it's a
wonder all the players didn't come down with something similar to
San Joaquin Valley Fever.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Plaza Delirium anyone?
</P>
<P>
   If Odom had any symptoms Tuesday, he sure didn't show it. He
appeared in fine fettle before the 81st game of this endless
winter, playfully wrestling with teammate Tyrone Nesby and smiling
as though it was a game he was preparing for and not some awful
grind.
</P>
<P>
   He was happy that somebody in this utterly forgettable season
wanted to remember him as Rookie of the Year. ``I'm not going to
disagree with you,'' Odom said. ``But I think Steve and Elton
deserve it more. I've been a little bit inconsistent. All the
losing started to wear on me and I carried it on the court with me.
I wasn't mentally strong enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course. No one is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
