<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ MIGHT BE ODD MAN OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rainouts, snowouts, and now again it could be,
Carlos Perez is out.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's rainout not only means the Dodgers are skipping his
next regular turn in the rotation, but with Eric Gagne's good
outing and Kevin Brown expected back Monday, Perez could find
himself pushed out of the rotation again.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he doesn't know when Perez
will start, and with Brown's return from a broken right pinkie
still uncertain, would rather not speculate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just wait and see. I don't want to spread all this
conjecture and speculation,'' Johnson said. ``The guy had a pretty
good outing and is in a pretty good frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``So let's not get too far down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was scheduled to pitch Tuesday. But with Monday's rainout,
they moved Darren Dreifort back to Tuesday, skipped Perez and
scheduled Orel Hershiser to start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed with Perez's first outing, the Dodgers sent him to
Triple-A Albuquerque, but he stayed with the team when Brown broke
his finger. When the Dodgers wavered over whether to activate him,
Perez grew angry and said he wanted out if they did not want him to
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Perez did start and went six effective innings against the
Giants, but the Dodgers are not so convinced he has found himself
after last year's 2-10 season that they would start him over a
41-year-old Hershiser with a sore groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a little bit of a groin,'' Johnson said. ``Ideally, it
would have been to push him back until Friday, but I'm going to go
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown cleared: Dr. Robert Zemel has cleared Brown to throw off
the mound. Brown said he would need only one bullpen outing,
probably Friday or Saturday, before returning to the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I'll need only one outing in the 'pen to be
ready,'' Brown said. ``I was on the DL with cracked ribs in '93,
and that's all it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Tidbits: Team vice president Tommy Lasorda remains a favorite to
be named manager of the U.S. Olympic baseball team. The decision
could come Friday, but Lasorda said he's unaware of the team's
plans: ``I haven't heard anything. I have no idea what's happening.
They know I'm interested.'' ... Monday's makeup game in New York
has been rescheduled to a 1 p.m. start EDT. It was previously
scheduled to start at 7 p.m., but the Dodgers play Sunday in
Cincinnati and Tuesday in Atlanta. Fox Sports Net 2 will televise
the game Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f bc-LADN-RALPHS.F     04-19 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RALPHS-UPSCALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALPHS MAKING NEW FORAY INTO GOURMET FIELD
</HEADLINE>
bc-LADN-RALPHS.F (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMARILLO, Calif. _ Ralphs Grocery Co. is staking its future on
Southern California's growing desire for smaller, more friendly
markets that feature organic foods and other upscale items such as
prime beef and fine wine.
</P>
<P>
   To meet that demand, the company is opening it's 10th Ralphs
Fresh Fare supermarket today at 674 Las Posas Road in Camarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the region's affluent communities, the chain's new
stores are 40,000 square feet, smaller than a regular Ralphs, and
positioned to compete against Gelson's and Whole Foods Markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it offers the best of everything customers are
looking for in a supermarket,'' said Ralphs spokesman Terry O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   The stores were designed to resemble a Whole Foods by using
earthtones and having a natural look. The stores also feature many
of the same organic and vegetarian items as its competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Whole Foods and other upscale stores in
originally planning the chain, but put a Ralphs twist to it,''
O'Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   Other upscale and niche markets welcomed the competition, but
don't expect the Compton-based Ralphs to cut into their slice of
the natural foods pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an industry that is expanding,'' said Elizabeth
Carovillano, director of marketing for Whole Foods in Sherman Oaks.
``Of course they are going to replicate us. It's the greatest form
of flattery.''
</P>
<P>
   John Correnti, the assistant manager at Trader Joe's across the
street from a Fresh Fare store in La Canada Flintridge, agreed the
new chain hasn't hurt business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a brand name,'' Correnti said. ``Customers will
continue to shop here for certain products before going to Ralphs
to buy toilet paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its competitors, however, the Ralphs Fresh Fare markets
are open 24 hours a day, seven days a week, O'Neil said. The
Camarillo store also features a pharmacy and an indoor/outdoor
dining area.
</P>
<P>
   Ralphs, a division of Cinncinati-based Kroger Co., opened its
first Fresh Fare store in West Los Angeles in October 1998. Since
then stores have opened in Mission Viejo, Villa Park, La Canada
Flintridge, Rolling Hills, Pacific Palisades, Palos Verdes, West
Hollywood and Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a smaller store, we try and cater to the customer's
needs,'' said Raissa Huravsky, assistant manager at Ralphs Fresh
Fare in La Canada Flintridge. ``We also lean toward the specialty
and gourmet item.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a typical Ralphs store, Fresh Fare carries organic fruits
and vegetables, prime cuts of meat and seafood and a bakery. The
store also operates a pre-cooked deli section that offers the
customer everything from grilled salmon sandwiches to chicken Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an upscale supermarket that features new items as well as
all the traditional offerings,'' O'Neil said. ``The prices are the
same for milk and apples as a conventional store.''
</P>
<P>
   Huravsky said the response to the new Ralphs has been
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of customers commuting from Glendale and
Pasadena to do their shopping here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Anderson, of Alhambra who stopped by to buy a frozen
dinner and bottled water to take with her to work, said she shops
at Ralphs Fresh Fare because it's convenient and reasonably priced.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``The ready-to-go food is a little too
expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
