</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-19 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
PHOENIX _ On second thought, that was never a way for it to end,
with Charles Barkley limping off the court instead of strutting
across it, propped up by crutches rather than standing on his own
two feet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight he'll do it his way, playing a few minutes at the Laptop
in the Rockets' season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a psychological thing, a bonus,'' Barkley said Tuesday
morning at America West Arena. ``I just didn't want my last memory
on the basketball floor to be being carried out. My fantasy is to
walk away on my own. Maybe some people won't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   There would, of course, be nothing new about that, because most
of the world never could understand the simple truth about Charles
Wade Barkley: It's always been about fun.
</P>
<P>
   We can analyze and compartmentalize, put him under the
microscope or break down his DNA to try to determine the tiniest
parts of what makes him so unique.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, it's the whole package. The athlete and the
actor, the competitor and the clown, the unorthodox body and the
unstoppable mouth, the profanity and the profundity, the friend and
the fighter, the brother and the brawler, the celebrity and the
conscience, the quote and the questioner, the little kid inside the
grown man's body who never for a moment forgot that he had been
given a life of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night I pray and say, `I don't know why you chose me,
but thanks,''' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 123 days since he came down in that horrible, awkward
fall in Philadelphia that wrecked his left leg and abruptly ended a
brilliant career, he has had time to relax and reflect on what he
would change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   You take the on-court shenanigans with the off-the-floor
embarrassments, and what you get is a portrait of a human being
with flaws. In other words, except for his basketball ability, not
so different than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Jordan, his contemporary and close friend, there
was always the sense of a photographer's airbrush being used to
cover up the slightest blemish to a preconceived, pre-packaged,
perfect Madison Avenue image.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is who he is, warts and all. The guy next door who wins
the lottery and doesn't take on airs, doesn't change his
personality, just takes full advantage of the opportunity that has
been dropped in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has had a better life than me; I believe that,'' he
said. ``Basketball owes me nothing. I owe basketball everything.
The game has given me everything. When I came into the league, my
goal was to make a million dollars a year, play for 10 years and
take care of my mother and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm 37 years old, rich beyond my wildest dreams and have
been all over the world. I've met presidents and kings.''
</P>
<P>
   And along the way he became Prince Charles, part superstar, part
celebrity royalty as the NBA went on a meteoric rise in popularity.
Magic Johnson and Larry Bird fueled the takeoff and Air Jordan
eventually lifted the game in terms of marketing and promotion
throughout the '80s and '90s. But it was Barkley _ Sir Charles, the
Chuckster _ who was the trail of fire and billowing smoke off the
launching pad, providing the down-to-earth thrust. In his two
appearances on the U.S. Olympic team in 1992 and 1996, it was
Barkley _ not Jordan, not Magic, not any of the others _ who was
the most popular Dream Teamer with the crowds in Barcelona and
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley never set out to be the unofficial voice of the NBA
players through his career. But he figured early on that if he had
to deal with the media, he would do it on his own terms. There was
never a topic or an issue that he would duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me a question, and I'll give you an answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you didn't like it. Even if it made you flinch.
</P>
<P>
   You get all of him, including the contradictions. The player who
was always most apt to break a play called from the bench spent so
much time trying to be a part-time coach. The player who was among
the least likely on the floor to make a 3-point shot was the one
who loved _ to the exasperation of his coaches _ to let one fly.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rockets' shootaround Tuesday morning, after four months
of missing practice, he grabbed the ball, took up a spot down in
the low post and started pointing and telling teammates what to do.
</P>
<P>
   After flirting with the idea of making a swan-song appearance in
Phoenix, he sat on the bench Tuesday night, wearing a brown suit
and the look of a man trying to hold on to fleeting memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would like to go out like Michael, making the last
shot to win a game, a championship,'' he said. ``But that's not
possible, and all I want to do is go out there for a few minutes
and try to do something. I'd like to just make a basket.''
</P>
<P>
   A slam dunk would be possible if maybe a half dozen teammates
hoisted him up to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything,'' he said. ``I just want to be out there one more
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He has played in All-Star Games and the NBA Finals, the Olympics
and in countries all over the world, and now it is a brief
appearance on a farewell night in Houston that is most special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my mother and my grandmother and about 20 friends from
around the country coming in, and that means a lot,'' he said. ``I
have loved the way the people in Houston have treated me. I wasn't
sure what the reaction would be after we went to war with the
Rockets in two playoff series when I was in Phoenix. But it's been
nothing but great. I wish I could have played my whole career in
either Phoenix or Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   A career that is down to one final night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's sad when anybody comes to retirement, whether you
work in an office or whatever. But I think for an athlete it's even
harder. I've talked to Dan Marino and Wayne Gretzky and John Elway
and, of course, Michael, and they all told me: `Retirement
(stinks).'
</P>
<P>
   ``After this game, I won't ever play basketball again. I don't
think I'll be going to the YMCA to play, though maybe I'll join a
church league and beat up guys to stroke my ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I brought to the game was toughness and charisma and
emotion. You always knew when I was happy, sad, mad or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   That bald head, that round face was like an exposed nerve
ending, acting, reacting, never showing anything except his
feelings, his raw passion. For life, for games, for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   He leaned back in his seat, made a wide sweep with his right
arm, looked out onto the court and up into the seats where the
crowds once cheered his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' said the athlete, the actor, the warrior, the
clown, ``this is just fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Always was with Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
