<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS &LR;      04-19 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ It would seem there was nothing else for which to play.
So the Rockets guards played H-O-R-S-E.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Francis on an alley-oop. Shandon Anderson on a flip in
traffic. Cuttino Mobley from 25 feet with a man in his face.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye on the weekend, the Phoenix Suns played to hold off
the San Antonio Spurs for the home-court advantage in their
first-round playoff series. The Rockets played for giggles. They
drove and bombed and sent a message to another playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   With their guards never looking back, the Rockets blew past the
Suns in the closing minutes 107-98 on Tuesday night at America West
Arena, their sixth win in seven games, including four against
playoff teams. And they had a grand time doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked like junior-high guys,'' Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ``There's no pressure on us. Our guys really feel
they can beat anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really got it rolling. We had some great, great
performances. Shandon is getting so comfortable in our system and
with the double teams. He's not only making 3s; he's driving the
seams and taking the ball to the basket. Steve played a tremendous,
solid game. He took the shots that were there and moved the ball
around. And Cuttino gave us a big lift off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   With their carefree attitude allowing them to stroke easily from
all corners of the court, and Charles Barkley back on the bench in
a suit, Anderson, Francis and Mobley combined to score 86 points.
</P>
<P>
   They made a combined 29 of 47 shots. The rest of the Rockets
were 5-of-23 for 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said before the game to be aggressive and came out and got
some shots up,'' Anderson said. ``They had to have this game.
There's no pressure on us. We just go out and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the Rockets with 35 points, making 12 of 20 shots.
Francis had 27, making 10 of 12 shots, with eight assists and seven
rebounds. Mobley had 24 points with five assists and five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were led by Penny Hardaway, who had his third career
triple double _ and first in six years _ with 20 points, 12 assists
and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns never could slow the Rockets' gunners or match
their swagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took everybody one-on-one, went right to the hole,'' Suns
coach Scott Skiles said. ``We tried to double, but they passed the
ball around and made shots. When we came out of the double teams
and tried to challenge, they shot-faked it. We'd jump by them, and
they would run to the hole again.''
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 81, the Rockets suddenly recovered,
outscoring the Suns 12-2 in the next three minutes, Anderson's
fifth 3-pointer giving the Rockets a 93-83 lead with 5:42 left.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough, even with that much time left, for the Rockets
to spread the floor and work the clock, knowing there would be no
way for the Suns to defend the guards one-on-one in the shot
clock's final ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Suns slipped back to within 96-90 with 2:10 left,
the Rockets did what they had all night. Mobley beat Hardaway to
slip inside for a layup. And with 1:12 to play and two seconds
remaining on the shot clock, Anderson rose from 25 feet to nail his
career-high sixth 3-pointer, matching his career-best scoring night
and giving the Rockets a 101-92 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like if we penetrated, we could kick the ball out and
get some easy shots, and we did just that,'' Anderson said. ``We're
playing for next year. Our core guys are healthy and will be back,
and we're playing for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But a last chance to prove something to themselves against a
playoff team seemed to be slipping away like the 17-point lead that
had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   But until that late run, it seemed certain that eventually the
Rockets would need some scoring help from someone other than
Francis, Anderson and Mobley. During a 7-2 late-third-quarter run
that cut the lead to nine, Mobley even got stuck waiting for a dead
ball to allow him back into range.
</P>
<P>
   Francis hit a jumper to push the lead back to 11. But with two
minutes left before the fourth quarter, the Rockets' guards had
combined to make 22 of 32 shots while the rest of the team had made
just four of 22.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost inevitable that unless someone did something to
help the cause offensively, the Rockets' guards would slip just
long enough for one of the Suns to catch fire and for Phoenix to
make the run.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Robinson found his shot, and the Suns' 9-1 run brought
them to within 74-71 heading into the fourth quarter. After
Francis' jumper with 2:24 left in the quarter, the Rockets had two
turnovers and missed two shots while Robinson poured in seven
points.
</P>
<P>
   After controlling almost the entire game, the only play the
Rockets executed was a pass from Barkley to the Gorilla mascot for
a dunk set up to give the Phoenix crowd an opening to salute him.
But just 75 seconds later, the rest of a Rockets lead that had
reached 17 was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had been sparring evenly with the Suns, trading the
lead as they always seem to at America West when Mobley stepped out
to nail the first 3 he had tossed up. Anderson was already gunning
from the 3-point line to help the Rockets keep pace. But once
Mobley added his trigger finger, the Rockets almost shot the Suns
out of the game in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
