<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-DODGERS-HN     04-19 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DODGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ Let the search begin for another scapegoat. Enron
Field appears to have been exonerated.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As much as they might like to blame their pitching woes on the
ballpark that welcomes home runs the way the Statue of Liberty
welcomes immigrants, the Astros are going to have to come up with
another way to defend their home-runs-allowed total, which is among
the highest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Three home runs accounted for all but one of the Los Angeles
Dodgers' runs in a 5-3 victory over the Astros on Tuesday night at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Enron Field,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``We keep getting hurt by the long ball, and we have to stop doing
that. We can't keep making that many mistakes and still expect to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who have allowed 22 home runs this season, including
seven in the first four games of this road trip, lost their third
game in a row and their eighth out of 13 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The club has not won a series since taking two of three in the
season-opening series at Pittsburgh and is off to its worst start
in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is keep battling,'' Astros second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``If we start panicking now, we're going to be in some
serious trouble. We just haven't been able to get into a groove,
and we still haven't had everyone out there together for any period
of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Singling out the pitching as the cause for the poor start would
be erroneous, considering the Astros have the lowest team batting
average (.225) in the NL. They were held to five hits Tuesday by a
trio of Dodgers, including starter Darren Dreifort, who worked six
strong innings for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Jeff Shaw survived a ninth-inning threat _ the
Astros brought the tying run to the plate three times _ to notch
his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case in each of his outings this season, Octavio
Dotel pitched well at times but not well enough to win. He tied a
career high with 10 strikeouts but surrendered the lead twice in a
span of two innings before exiting the game after the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a terrific game,'' Astros catcher Tony Eusebio said
of Dotel, who surrendered two homers. ``He just made a couple of
mistakes here and there. If he keeps pitching the way he's
pitching, he's going to win a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel matched up well with Dreifort, but the Astros righthander
wasn't quite as mistake-free as his mound opponent, who allowed
three runs on just three hits. No surprise there; Dreifort's
above-average fastball and power sinker/slider combination is a
pretty good recipe for success _ particularly for a righthanded
pitcher _ against the Astros' lineup, which is predominantly
righthanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort is tough,'' Dierker said. ``The only thing that
really keeps him from going to the top of the field is control. He
has a great arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel looked dominant in the first inning, striking out the side
around a single by second baseman Mark Grudzielanek. But a leadoff
walk to Eric Karros proved costly in the second when Adrian Beltre
drove him home with a sacrifice fly to give the Dodgers a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, whose offense consisted of a Jeff Bagwell single
through the first three innings, showed an opportunistic side of
their own in taking the lead in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodger Roger Cedeno drew a leadoff walk and moved to
second on Dreifort's errant pickoff throw. Bagwell was hit by a
pitch, and Richard Hidalgo drove both runners home with a single to
center. Cedeno has scored at least one run in seven of his last 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who is often guilty of trying to pull every pitch, did
a commendable job of taking Dreifort's offering on the outside
corner of the plate and poking it through the middle of the
diamond.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied the score on Beltre's second homer of the
season, a solo shot into the left-center-field bleachers, but the
Astros reclaimed a one-run lead when Bagwell rocketed an 0-1 pitch
from Dreifort over the left-field wall in the sixth inning. It was
Bagwell's fourth home run.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Biggio, who singled in the eighth inning, extended
their hitting streaks to 10 games apiece. Dodgers left fielder Gary
Sheffield, who was 0-for-3, saw his hitting streak snapped at 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' 3-2 lead didn't last long. Todd Hundley put the
Dodgers on top with a two-run homer in the bottom of the sixth.
Dotel has allowed five home runs this season, tying Chris Holt and
Jose Lima for the team lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the mistake that killed me,'' Dotel said of Hundley's
home run. ``We just need to start getting a little more luck. When
we get some, maybe we'll start winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers center fielder Devon White added an insurance run with a
seventh-inning solo homer off Doug Henry, who has allowed a home
run in four of his seven appearances this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not playing well, you usually seem unlucky,''
Dierker said. ``We played pretty well (Tuesday). We just have to
keep playing well until we start winning some games.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
