r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     04-19 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY FINDS POWER SWITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley has seen enough of these sub-.200
starts. Gone through enough struggle. Heard enough doubters.
</P>
<P>
   What Hundley wanted more than anything was a fresh start, and
then came a sore knee and an early .167 average staring back at
him.
</P>
<P>
   But on a cool Tuesday night at Dodger Stadium, Hundley made like
a man intent on a new beginning, drilling a two-run home run to
propel the Dodgers to a 5-3 victory over the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of just 26,298 saw the Dodgers hit three home runs,
Darren Dreifort pitch six strong innings to even his record at 1-1
and Jeff Shaw close it in the ninth for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice all-around game for the Dodgers, but the most
encouraging aspect was the bat of Hundley. This from a catcher
coming off a disappointing first season with the Dodgers that saw
him struggle to throw out runners and bat just .207.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember last year,'' Hundley said. ``It's gone. I
hear about last year. It's buried in a box. See ya, bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers offense had been fueled largely by the bats of Gary
Sheffield and Shawn Green. But on a night that saw Sheffield's
12-game hitting streak snapped and Green not reach base for the
first time this season, others got into the act.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Dotel, who struck out a career-high 10 in his only other
start against the Dodgers, was at it again Tuesday. Dotel struck
out 10 more, but when he wasn't overpowering, he was getting
rocked.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre drove in the first run with a sacrifice fly and
then hit his second home run, a solo shot to tie it at 2-2 in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was in command for most of the night, but a brief bout
of wildness in the fourth led to a pair of Houston runs. He walked
ex-Dodger Roger Cedeno and then hit Jeff Bagwell with a pitch to
open the inning. Richard Hidalgo's broken-bat single scored both
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's fourth home run in the sixth gave Houston a brief 3-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt real good, real comfortable,'' Dreifort said. ``I just
had that little bit of wildness in the fourth. I was pressing too
hard to get the leadoff hitters out and I was all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   In his six innings, Dreifort allowed three runs on three hits
and two walks. He struck out eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort threw the ball exceptionally well,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the sixth saw Eric Karros hit a ground-rule double
and Hundley's home run to almost dead center.
</P>
<P>
   A slow start for Hundley was starting to appear in his rearview
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurt my knee in (the first series) in Montreal, tried to
make adjustments to my swing, and it was just a downward spiral
from there,'' Hundley said. ``Then you start to press.''
</P>
<P>
   Devon White hit a solo home run off reliever Doug Henry in the
seventh to push the Dodgers' lead to 5-3, and another solid effort
by the bullpen this time from Terry Adams, Mike Fetters and Shaw -
helped end the club's brief two-game losing streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
