<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-SONICSKINGS-LADN     04-19 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICSKINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS WIN, AVOID LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - The Sacramento Kings and Seattle Sonics played a
game of hot potato Tuesday, and the Lakers were the potato.
</P>
<P>
   Neither wants any part of the NBA's best team in the first round
of the playoffs, but the Sonics want to avoid them most. Their
119-112 victory in overtime sends them to Utah to face the
second-seeded Jazz, handing the Kings to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Lakers look forward to playing the Kings. Despite
winning the season series against Sacramento 3-1, few teams played
L.A. tougher. The Lakers had to rally for each win, including
Friday's 121-114 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (44-37) present a number of problems with their speed
and shooting ability, and no one on the Lakers is a good fit
against Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Kings don't have anyone to stand up against
Shaquille O'Neal, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the first game we have no wins, they have no wins, we
have no losses, they have no losses so it's a new ball game,'' the
Kings' Nick Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you have to contain the big fella, and Kobe's
playing well. You know they're going to get their share of shots.
But we have to limit everybody else and not let other guys beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (45-36) outscored the Kings 12-5 in the extra period,
getting eight points from Gary Payton, including a crucial jumper
with 55 seconds left to put Seattle ahead 115-109.
</P>
<P>
   Payton finished with 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the last baskets, we won and we're fine,'' Payton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Lewis added 22 points and 13 rebounds and Vin Baker, who
has battled personal problems recently, had 23 points and nine
rebounds off the bench. Baker was removed from the starting lineup
last week after the Sonics had lost nine of 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious we're going to have to pick it up against the
Lakers,'' said Kings guard Jason Williams. ``But we're ready for
them and we can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber finished with 23 points, 10 rebounds and 13 assists but
made just 8 of 26 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had 23 points on seven 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   How badly did the Sonics want to avoid L.A.? Seattle coach Paul
Westphal stopped just short of calling the Lakers the best team
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. has really put up one of the best records in history, and
you can make an argument that it's the best record because of the
competition,'' Westphal said. ``The Western Conference this year
has been unbelievable from top to bottom, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their achievement, you can't just act like it's nothing. They
put the numbers up. I think the Kings and the Sonics both feel if
we can avoid playing the Lakers as long as possible, that's
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
