r a BC-DISCOVER-BOREDOM-ART-     04-19 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOVER-BOREDOM-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEAUTY OF BOREDOM  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ERIC HASELTINE  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Kids tire of their toys, college students weary of cafeteria
food, and sooner or later most of us lose interest in our favorite
TV shows. The bottom line is that humans are easily bored.
</P>
<P>
   Why? What prevents us from sustaining high levels of enthusiasm
for macaroni and cheese night after night? Why do long-winded
sermons seem so long-winded?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies buried deep in our nerve cells, which
automatically damp down their initial excited response to stimuli
every subsequent time a stimulus occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Those neurons also enhance responses to things that change _
especially that which changes quickly.
</P>
<P>
   We probably evolved this way because our ancestors got more
survival value, for example, from attending to what moved in a tree
(such as a panther) than to the tree itself.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom, as a reaction to a static environment, turns down the
level of neural excitation so that a new stimulus (such as that
panther) stands out more. It's the neural equivalent of
extinguishing a porch light to see the fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   Sensory boredom has many uses. Ever notice how a foul-smelling
room loses its bite after a half-hour or so, even if you haven't
opened a window? That's because the excitation levels of olfactory
neurons, or smell receptors, decrease with each repeated
stimulation, so you notice the offensive odor less and less.
</P>
<P>
   Prove it to yourself with the following three experiments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXPERIMENT 1: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slice a fresh onion in half, and hold it under your nose. The
first whiff will be pretty intense, but sniffs two, three, four and
five should become progressively milder, even though the onion
remains as potent from the first inhale to the last. (Keep tissue
handy for onion tears.)
</P>
<P>
   Continue long enough, and you might stop noticing the offending
vegetable altogether as your brain gets used to the odor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXPERIMENT 2: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperature effects can also produce some amazing phenomena.
Grab a thermometer and three large bowls. Fill the first bowl with
cold water and ice, the second with water at room temperature
(roughly 70 degrees Fahrenheit), and the third with water hot
enough to be uncomfortable but not scalding (110 degrees Fahrenheit
will do the trick).
</P>
<P>
   Place your left hand in the cold bowl and your right hand in the
hot one. Leave both hands in the bowls for about 30 seconds. Then
place both hands in the room-temperature water. After about 30
seconds, the hand from the cold bowl will begin to feel warmer than
the other hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions of hot and cold don't derive directly from
temperature but from the difference between the temperature your
thermal receptors have gotten used to and the warmth or coolness of
objects stimulating them. Since your right hand had adapted to the
hot water, the room-temperature water seemed cool by comparison,
while the reverse was true for your left hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXPERIMENT 3: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary behavioral responses can also exhibit neurological
boredom. Sneak up on a friend and yell octopus in her ear, and
you'll get a startled reaction. But octopus your friend a few
minutes later, and you'll see much less of a jump (although some
other type of behavior may emerge).
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon, called habituation, takes place in the brain
but doesn't require a specific change in the behavior of sensory
nerves. Your friend hears the word octopus but doesn't jump,
because she's habituated.
</P>
<P>
   Startle yourself out of ennui with more novel information on
sameness and the brain at www.discover.com/brainworks.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Haseltine is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
