A1201 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN20-COX     04-19 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When Dow's a bull, investors get unbearable
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's a good thing when the stock market plummets
like it did Friday because it shuts up some of these
self-proclaimed market experts for a couple of days. I get tired of
all these Dullionaires yapping about their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   If both Dow and Jones have to move into the Salvation Army,
that's OK with me as long as it stops the stockaholics around town
from running their gums about their earnings. Pick another subject.
Tell me about your dog. Tell me about your sex life. Share a chili
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick of all these people talking about how to play the stock
market. Everywhere you go these days, people are giving financial
tips and yapping about how well off they are.
</P>
<P>
   In this Hawaiian shirt, do I look like I care?
</P>
<P>
   Why, just the other day at the gym downtown, a college-age gal
wearing a ``Theta'' shirt was explaining how the market works. It's
pretty simple, by her estimation. You buy stocks at $4, and they go
up to $8. That's it. ``I buy stocks at $4, and they go up to $8.''
That's what she was telling the gal riding the stair-stepping
machine next to her.
</P>
<P>
   No mention of ever buying stocks at $4 and them going down to
$2. You can hear me cheering when they drop to $2, because maybe
it'll thin out traffic on the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   One good thing about Smart Growth? It encourages developers to
build up, not out. That way, when the market goes completely into
the dumper, these people will have enough tall buildings to jump
out of. If you leap out of a two-story building after your 401(k)
turns up worthless, all it'll do is screw up your knees. So close
the window and sit down and find another subject to bore us with
besides your net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Dullionaire I was talking to at the gym over
the weekend. I mean, this guy was still blowing and going about his
market prowess after the Nasdaq had dropped nearly 10 percent the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever gotten in a conversation with a guy who crows
about how well off he is and you want to see him have to take in
ironing? This was one of those guys. He said he bought a bunch of
Dell stock, and it went up so much that he bought his house with
cash. He said the real estate people were real happy about that
because they didn't have to fill out any paperwork. He was sure to
emphasize that he drives a Porsche. This guy said he was doing so
well that he eats every meal out.
</P>
<P>
   That's great, I said, but my wife is a wonderful cook. ``Yeah,
well, my old lady's French,'' the Dullionaire shot back. Whatever
the heck that's supposed to mean.
</P>
<P>
   I hate people trying to impress me with their bank statements.
When I hear it, I want to say, ``OK, suit boy, if you're so well
off, write me a check for $10,000. Or at least take me to Ray's
Steak House for an appetizer.''
</P>
<P>
   You know those little numbers they run across the bottom of the
TV screen that show how much your stock is worth? I'm the kind of
guy who cheers when they get real small. I love it when Alan
Greenspan makes a speech. Go, Alan, go. Every time Alan shows up
running his mouth, a passel of annoying yuppies lose their shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get any better than that.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column for the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
