</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hop into our advice for the best-tasting chocolate bunny
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If you're hopping down the grocery trail looking
for the best-tasting chocolate Easter bunny, hippoty-hoppity, help
is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   To separate the standard-issue chocolate bunnies from those
truly worthy of a place in your Easter basket, we conducted a blind
taste test of 10 chocolate Easter bunnies. A panel of 15 chocolate
lovers carefully tasted each bunny to find the yummiest.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the bunnies were chocolate; one was a mixture of peanut
butter and chocolate. The taste-testers first compared the nine
chocolate bunnies. Once they had selected their winner, they
decided if they preferred their favorite chocolate bunny to the
peanut-butter version.
</P>
<P>
   The Reese's peanut-butter bunny won, with 10 of the tasters
choosing it over their favorite chocolate bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine purely chocolate bunnies, Dove chocolate stood above
the rest, receiving eight of the 15 votes. Palmer and Brach's tied
for second place, each garnering three votes, and Russell Stover
came in third.
</P>
<P>
   Though our taste-testers did not know what brands of chocolate
they were trying, a majority of them immediately recognized the
taste of the Hershey's bunny and the Reese's bunny.
</P>
<P>
   One thing we learned, though, is that one man's favorite
chocolate is another man's chocolate-bunny roadkill. Every bunny
had its supporters and detractors.
</P>
<P>
   So, to help you make an informed decision when you traverse the
grocery aisles lined with hundreds of chocolate bunnies, here are
comments from our taste-testers.
