<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-CRAWFISH20-COX     04-19 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAWFISH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's boil up them crawfish
 &HT;    By Jana Collier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's only one way to eat a crawfish _ at a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Though they do have more legs than something you'd normally try
to eat, crawfish are easy to cook and make a great focus for any
outdoor party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whole fun of the thing _ the atmosphere and
everything,'' said Mike Mayfield, who owns the seafood division of
Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Broadfoot of Houston, a veteran crawfish boiler, agrees.
``You have to have a party for crawfish,'' he said. ``It's just so
much fun that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark and my brother-in-law, Chip Saegert, recently held a big
crawfish boil at Chip's Houston home. They boiled 160 pounds of
crawfish, along with corn, potatoes and mushrooms, for about 50 of
their friends and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of having a crawfish boil at your house,
here's a guide from Mark and Chip and the folks at Waco Custom
Meats &AMP; Seafood.
</P>
<P>
   THE CRAWFISH
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish season runs from January to June, but the prime time
for the crustaceans is April and May. That's when the supply is
greatest and the crawfish are biggest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the crawfish supply is significantly down nationwide,
primarily due to a poor yield in Louisiana. However, Waco Custom
Meats gets most of its crawfish from Texas farms, and those farms
are currently producing well, Mike said. How long those farms
continue to produce will depend on the heat and rain, he said,
noting that the price is up this year because of the low supply.
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish must be cooked live, so storing them properly is
crucial to a successful boil.
</P>
<P>
   At Waco Custom Meats &AMP; Seafood, which supplies crawfish to many
Central Texas restaurants, a special cooler was built just for
crawfish. The mudbugs should be kept at a temperature of 38 to 40
degrees _ cold enough to stay fresh, but not cold enough to freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Chip bought their crawfish at a Houston grocery store a
few hours before their boil and stored them in ice chests until
time for cooking.
</P>
<P>
   To tell if a crawfish is alive or dead, pick it up before it's
cooked and look at the tail: If its tail droops when handled, it's
dead; if the tail curls under its body, its still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Some crawfish must be ``purged'' or cleaned before cooking, but
it isn't always necessary. Mike said most Texas farmers clean their
crawfish in aerated, fresh water tanks before shipping, so they do
not need to be purged. Crawfish that have not been cleaned, though,
will need to be purged to remove mud sediment, fish bait and other
impurities.
</P>
<P>
   To purge the crawfish, Mark said he rinses them first with clean
water and then sprinkles salt over them while still in the ice
chest.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING UP THE HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Most people boil their crawfish in propane-fired pots, which can
be bought at stores such as Lowe's and Home Depot. For smaller
amounts of crawfish, you can use a large stockpot on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the pot, fill it about a half to three-fourths full
of water and add plenty of spices. At Waco Custom Meats, they use
Chef Geoffrey Michael's Cajun Red seasoning and the ultra-hot Swamp
Fire seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said he uses a large bottle of Zatarain's liquid shrimp and
crab boil and half of a large bottle of powdered shrimp and crab
boil for each pot he boils. He also adds one to two sticks of
butter, which he says makes the crawfish easier to peel, and about
5 lemons, halved.
</P>
<P>
   Many people cook corn and potatoes with their crawfish. Mark
also adds mushrooms, and Sondra Waits of Waco Custom Meats &AMP;
Seafood said she's seen people add whole garlic cloves. Some people
also add onions.
</P>
<P>
   Sausage and shrimp can be cooked with the crawfish, which is
nice for those who don't care for crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said he puts his vegetables in a mesh lingerie bag. This
keeps the vegetables from floating up to the top where they can
sometimes get too spicy. Depending on the size of the potato
pieces, you might want to add those first to give them a little
extra time to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Once the water in the pot is boiling and the spices are added,
throw in the crawfish and vegetables. The crawfish should cook
about 15 minutes. After they've cooked, Mark turns off the heat to
let them soak for another 15 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLACE
</P>
<P>
   Crawfish should be eaten outdoors _ they're way too messy for
inside.
</P>
<P>
   My brother-in-law Chip actually built two large tables to set up
on his deck. He made them taller than most tables, so people could
stand and eat their crawfish as they were poured out on a
tablecloth of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The eating area should be well-stocked with paper towels and
napkins and extra seasonings for those who like their crawfish very
spicy.
</P>
<P>
   Having tables set up outside makes cleanup easy. Once the
party's over, just remove the leftover food and newspapers and hose
down the tables and ground.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUNCHIES
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes crawfish, and, in particular, children are
often turned off by the idea of eating something that looks like
the star of last night's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   My 7-year-old Claire and 4-year-old Rachel finally tasted some
crawfish tails, but they certainly didn't eat enough to constitute
a meal.
</P>
<P>
   That's why many people add sausage or shrimp to the crawfish
pots. Chip and Mark also fried a turkey, which was a nice addition
to the party.
</P>
<P>
   My sister, Shannon Saegert, assembled a large table of crackers,
vegetable trays and dips, along with praline bars and
crawfish-shaped cutout cookies, iced with red icing and decorated
with silver dragees for eyes. In addition, Shannon's friend, Betty
Broadfoot (Mark's wife), baked a batch of crawfish bread that
turned out to be the biggest hit of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
