<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-BEER-NUTRITION20-COX     04-19 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUTRITION20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Experts debate benefits of beer
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Red wine is the alcohol source most famous for its
apparent ability to ward off certain types of heart disease. But
some researchers are suggesting that a cold beer every once in a
while has some health benefits of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The health effects of beer consumption may not seem like the
biggest issue facing America, but there's plenty of drinking going
on, according to the beer industry. After soft drinks, coffee and
milk, beer is the most popular beverage in America. In 1998 alone,
Americans spent $60 billion on 196 million barrels of brew. The
average per capita consumption that year was 22.2 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Morris Chafetz, president of the Health Education Foundation
in Washington, D.C., says the health consequences of drinking beer
are no different than those of any other food product. There's the
potential for good and the potential for bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any substance, including water and oxygen,
that would be good for you if abused,'' Chafetz said. ``I've been
in the field 40 years. I've studied all over the world. I'm telling
you that moderate usage has many health benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate about the health benefits of beer was jump-started
this spring when People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals
launched an anti-milk campaign using the slogan ``Got Beer?'' The
campaign, which has since been pulled from college campuses after
protests from Mothers Against Drunk Driving, touts beer as
nutritionally superior to milk.
</P>
<P>
   PETA officials admit their real aim was to highlight what they
perceive as the cruel treatment of cows bred for commercial milk
production. To make their point, though, PETA officials sited
medical studies that suggest beer is not the bad beverage some
would have you think.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people in the medical profession don't buy PETA's
analysis, but Chafetz isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't suggest anyone go home tonight and pound a 12 pack,
but he says people who drink alcohol moderately _ including beer _
have fewer heart attacks and fewer debilitating strokes. There's
also the social aspect of moderate alcohol consumption, especially
for older adults, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if it's the use of alcohol or the fact that they
can socialize better (because of the alcohol),'' Chafetz said.
``They're less depressed in many cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have believed for a number of years that the
antioxidants in red wine, called flavonoids, help counteract plaque
buildup in heart arteries. But some in the medical profession are
now saying that any type of alcohol is beneficial, not just red
wine.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Harvard Medical School, led by Dr. J. Michael
Gaziano, found that a drink or two a day can cut a person's risk of
having a heart attack in half. In the study, it did not matter what
type of alcohol people drank. Wine, beer and liquor were equally
effective.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gaziano, alcohol raises the body's level of HDL
(high-density lipoprotein cholesterol), the good cholesterol that
helps keep arteries free of dangerous buildups.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors surmise that people who drink red wine may see more
health benefits than beer drinkers because of their drinking
habits. People who drink red wine tend to have a glass or two in
the evening and don't binge, according to the study. Beer drinkers,
on the other hand, may average a drink a day, but that's only
because they're more likely to slam a six-pack Friday night after
drinking little to none during the week, Chafetz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard study concluded that heart patients should not go
out of their way to drink for health reasons, but it's not
medically necessary for them to give up alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Cortes, a nutritionist with Providence Healthcare
Network, said there are some vitamins in beer and some studies
point to other benefits. But before indulging, people should think
about the negatives consequences as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's a personal choice,'' Cortes said. ``In
moderation, it probably won't harm their health, but they need to
consider that it could lead to addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Because beer is made from fermented grains, it provides B
vitamins. A 12-ounce can has about 9 percent of the recommended
daily dosage of vitamin B-6 and 9 percent of niacin. Cortes said
beer also contains trace minerals chromium and phosphorous, which
can help a person keep a healthy, stable metabolism. Niacin aides
in maintaining healthy nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these benefits, however, the alcohol in beer also
interferes with the body's ability to utilize some B vitamins,
vitamin C, zinc and magnesium.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, a person who drinks beer on a regular basis or
abuses it tends to develop nutrient deficiencies that can lead to
nerve damage or other problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Janelle Walter, a professor of family and consumer science
at Baylor University, said there are plenty of food products that
can provide what little nutritional value comes in a 12-ounce can
of beer. The alcohol is not digested in the stomach, so the liver
is left to process what is treated as a toxin by the body. Heavy
alcohol use can lead to cirrhosis of the liver, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's really anything medically redeeming
about beer,'' Walter said. ``It has very little in it other than
alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's mainly water, but as Walter points out, the
alcohol is treated as a toxin by the body. To flush the toxins, the
body uses water. Drinking too much beer, then, can cause
dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Beer, which is 11 percent alcohol by weight, also comes with a
lot of calories, about 150 per can. Alcohol has seven calories per
gram, compared to carbohydrates, which have four calories per gram.
Fat has nine calories per gram.
</P>
<P>
   That means if you cut back on the cold beer, you might also cut
down your waist size, Walter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Americans, one problem we don't have is getting enough
calories in our diets,'' she said. ``Drinking beer is going to give
you weight problems.''
</P>
<P>
   PETA's campaign points out that beer has no fat or cholesterol.
Milk is ``loaded'' with fat and has 20 mg of cholesterol in every
8-ounce serving, according to PETA's studies. A can of beer also
has a half gram of fiber, 12 milligrams of sodium and three grams
of complex carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
   Chafetz said he does not condone the abuse of beer or any other
substance. Drinking and driving is bad, he said. Someone who
consumes so much alcohol that they lose control of their faculties
is drinking irresponsibly.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term effects of consumption are anything but bad,
he said. His studies, for example, show that only 10 percent of
chronic alcoholics have cirrhosis of the liver, meaning there is
little connection between alcohol and liver damage. He added that
while alcohol can impair judgment immediately after a person
drinks, there are no proven long-term negative effects on the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Whether people like it or not, he said, the reality is that beer
actually makes many people feel better, kind of like Prozac or
aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to people becoming addicted to beer or other
forms of alcohol, it's the person, not the substance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy jumps off a building and kills himself, we don't say,
'Why did we build the building?''' Chafetz said. ``We question why
the person was self-destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
