<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-pt2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: The NCAA men's South regional basketball finals will be held
at the Georgia Dome next year. Is there a number I can call, or
address to write or send e-mail, to get information or first notice
of ticket sales?
</P>
<P>
   A: The number: 404-222-6222. Information also can be found
online at www.ramblinwreck.com.
</P>
<P>
   But don't delay. Ticket requests must be received by April 28
for the random ticket selection. The games will be played March 23
and 25, 2001. Tickets are $80 and $90 for both the Friday and
Sunday sessions. Ticket requests received after April 28 will be
filled on a first-come, first-served basis depending on
availability.
</P>
<P>
   The tickets will be mailed Nov. 1 to those whose requests were
selected.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently vacationed in Myrtle Beach, S.C., and saw many
restaurants advertising ``Calabash seafood buffet.'' What do they
mean by ``Calabash''? How is that different from any other seafood?
</P>
<P>
   A: Calabash is a fishing village just across the North Carolina
line, about 25 miles from Myrtle Beach. As Stephen Greene of the
Myrtle Beach Area Chamber of Commerce explains, restaurants in
Calabash started a tradition of deep-frying locally caught fish,
crabs, shrimp and oysters in a lightly seasoned cornmeal batter and
serving them _ along with home-style vegetables, hot breads, pies
and cobblers _ in an all-you-can-eat buffet. The concept was so
popular thatrestaurants in Myrtle Beach began to copy it, bringing
it to both sides of the state line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Washington Post had an article April 5 about an
adventurer who planned to fly a World War II-era open cockpit plane
to the North Pole. The plane was to depart that day from
Gaithersburg, Md. Can you update me on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The project started on schedule when the pilot, Gustavus
McLeod, took off from Gaithersburg in his own plane, a 1939 Boeing
PT-17 Stearman. If successful, he will be the first person to pilot
an open-cockpit plane to the Pole.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod's 3,500-mile itinerary, which originally was to take 12
days: Hamilton, Elliot Lake, Jerraldton Lake and Pickle Lake, in
Ontario; Church Hill, in Manitoba; Rankin Inlet, Taloyuak, Resolute
and Weather Station Eureka, in Nunavut; 86 degrees north latitude
(ice caps); 90 degrees latitude (geographic North Pole).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rosenberg, McLeod's spokesman in Alexandria, Va., told Q&AMP;A
April 12 that the pilot had encountered a problem ``with a $1.50
gasket throwing the flight off for another day or so.'' The trouble
occurred when the temperature suddenly dropped from 9 degrees below
zero to 26 below on the leg between Pickle Lake and Churchill. The
gasket broke, with oil leaking from the engine.
</P>
<P>
   As of that afternoon, McLeod was awaiting a new gasket to be
delivered from Oklahoma City. If it worked, and a short test flight
was successful, Rosenberg said, McLeod's quest would be resumed.
</P>
<P>
   News releases are posted online at www.northpole2000.com.
National Geographic is filming the project for a future TV special,
Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the U.S. government footing the bills for flights, lodging
and meals incurred in connection with Elian Gonzales' father and
the rest of the Cuban entourage being in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. A State Department representative said all costs involved
are being paid by the Cuban government. The only role played by the
United States was to facilitate arrangements, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A TV show said Easter began as a pagan holiday in orchards or
groves and consisted of fertility rituals. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: We don't know about the orchards and groves, but it did have
pagan beginnings associated with fertility. While the origin of the
English name Easter is uncertain, some scholars trace it to Eastre,
the Anglo-Saxon goddess who presided over the vernal equinox.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient spring festivals had a resurrection theme _ new life
afer the winter _ and fertility obviously played a part, which
explains how eggs came to be included as symbols. Another symbol
that evolved was the hare, symbol of fertility in ancient Egypt,
which in North America was replaced by the Easter bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I plan to be in California in July. Do you know the date and
site of this year's U.S. Open?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you hope to be a spectator, you'll need to move your trip
up a bit. The tournament will be June 15-18 at Pebble Beach Golf
Links in Pebble Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The test dummies used in automobile crash testing could weigh
as little as 10-15 pounds. But to be realistic, shouldn't they be
much heavier, say in the 180-pound range?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dummies with the weight you mention are intended to simulate
children. But in fact the dummies cover a much wider range. Those
manufactured by Applied Safety Technologies Corp., for instance,
range from a newborn infant to what's termed a 95th percentile
male. Sample weights: Hybrid II 6-year-old child, 33.3 pounds;
Hybrid II 50th percentile male, 164 pounds; Hybrid III 5th
percentile female, 106-110 pounds; and Hybrid III 95th percentile
male, 223.4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The dummies simulate what happens to a human inside a vehicle
when a crash occurs, and have evolved into quite realistic
``people.'' One of the newest is the Hybrid III 5th percentile
female, made of vinyl and stainless steel and dressed in
fashion-forward Capri-length pants with a form-fitting cotton knit
top and military-issue size 8W shoes. She is stuffed with
instruments so researchers can determine what might happen in a
crash involving a typical small female. Her cost is an estimated
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The dummies' specifications are mandated by the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration. They are intended to gauge head,
neck, chest, spine, leg and other injuries both from impact and
from air bag deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Detailed information on Applied Safety Technologies' ``human
surrogates'' can be found online at www.astc.net. Other companies
also make crash test dummies, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: While watching the Masters on TV, I noticed that several
golfers were violating what I consider one of golf's oldest
customs, which is the wearing of a collared golf shirt. David
Duval, specifically, could be seen wearing a crew neck. Is that now
permissible at Augusta National Golf Club?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no policy requiring collared shirts, said Augusta
National's Glenn Greenspan. The only dress code requirement of the
PGA Tour is long pants on players, he added, and that's the
guideline used at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who invented the VCR, and how did it develop?
</P>
<P>
   A: The concept was the brainchild of independent American
inventor Jerome H. Lemelson (1923-97), who amassed more than 500
patents, including essential parts of the camcorder, cordless
telephone, fax machine, data- and word-processing systems, and
industrial robots.
</P>
<P>
   While the development of videotape recorders began in the 1940s,
the first such device capable of recording a television picture of
broadcasting quality on magnetic tape didn't come along until 1956.
That recorder, developed by Charles P. Ginsberg, Charles E.
Anderson and Ray Dolby, and manufactured by the Ampex Corp. of
Redwood City, Calif., was demonstrated simultaneously in Redwood
City and Chicago on April 14, 1956. The first tape, 2 inches wide,
moved at a speed of 15 inches per second; a single 14-inch reel
accommodated a 65-minute recording.
</P>
<P>
   VCRs as we know them today evolved soon afterward. Japan's Sony
Corp. marketed the first open-reel videotape recorder for home use,
the TCV-2010, in 1966. It required a separate camera, set up on a
tripod, and a separate microphone to record sound. The Betamax,
which was sold in the United States by Sony, followed in 1975. It
was built into a console that also contained a Sony color TV set.
The tape was contained in a plastic cassette to make it easy to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   NRA video: Q&AMP;A recently reported on the National Rifle
Association's online video about gun control laws in Australia,
saying it apparently had been removed from the NRA's Web site
(www.nra.org). But the video still can be viewed online at
NRA-Live, a subset of the Web site that requires Shockwave
software. The Shockwave requirement can be bypassed, however, by
using this address:
http://nraila.org/research/20000329-BanningGuns-001.shtml. It
contains a link to the Australia video and other videos and should
work for most Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
