<HEADER>
A1212 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CARL-REINER20-COX     04-19 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARL-REINER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reiner proud of accomplishments
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Carl Reiner is proud of many things, and he'll
gladly talk about all of them. But ask him about his son, Rob, and
he won't shut up. Ask him about World War II, and you'll be there
forever. Not that you'd mind.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Reiner, 78, sat for a while to talk about his
54-year career, Mel Brooks, comedy today, his role in ``Gidget Goes
Hawaiian'' _ as well as son Rob and WWII.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote (the `The Dick Van Dyke Show') for myself,'' he said.
``I was in the role Dick Van Dyke eventually played. Nobody would
buy it. And that's the best thing that ever happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was recast a year later with Van Dyke in the lead and
Reiner as head writer, making cameo appearances as Alan Brady, Van
Dyke's tyrannical, egomaniacal boss. The show became a huge hit,
running from 1961 to 1966 and providing Reiner with seven of his 12
Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That show hasn't been off the air since it first started,''
Reiner said, with Nick at Night and TVLand picking up where
syndication left off. It's the achievement Reiner says he's most
proud of, ``mainly because without that show I wouldn't be here
today, and I got enough money to buy a house. It's on Rodeo Drive,
and I still live in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He muses about the 2,000-Year-Old Man, a comedy classic that
Reiner and Mel Brooks _ a friend and fellow writer for ``Your Show
of Shows'' _ ``did for fun, at parties. We never dreamed of putting
in on a record,'' Reiner recalled. ``We'd been doing it for years.
I'd be the interviewer, and he never knew where I'd put him. I'd
make him a submarine captain, an artist ... I always tried to put
him to the wall, but the more panicked he got, the funnier he
became.''
</P>
<P>
   A party attended by Hollywood's elite finally got the routine on
the road to a recording: ``George Burns said if we didn't record
it, he'd steal it,'' Reiner laughed. ``Edward G. Robinson wanted to
take it to Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   An update of the schtick, ``The 2,000-Year-Old Man in the Year
2,000,'' won a Grammy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As for today's comedy, Reiner sees comics as simply doing their
job: ``Comedy changes as the world changes,'' he said. ``Society
changes and comedians notice it, and they're the ones pointing it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name one project he wishes he'd avoided, Reiner rubs
his face and begins to weave the tale of ``Gidget Goes Hawaiian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They offered me this thing, and I said, `No! It's a horrible
script.' They offered me more money and I still wouldn't do it.
Then they said they were doing it in Hawaii ... I hadn't been there
since the war. Television wasn't doing much with movies those days,
and I figured nobody I knew would ever see it. So I went. I played
Gidget's father. It's a terrible picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I keep getting letters from people who catch that thing
on television.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Hawaii gave Reiner a chance to revisit his old war
haunts. He was an Air Force radio operator and a teletype operator
in the Signal Corps before being assigned to Maurice Evans' Special
Services Entertainment Unit, touring the South Pacific in a G.I.
revue.
</P>
<P>
   World War II was an amazing time to be alive, Reiner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew we had to be a part of that war. Somehow we all
knew there was something terrible going on, even if people didn't
know the subtleties of what would happen if we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner was given relatively safe assignments: His brother, he
said, ``was assigned to all the places that would kill him. Omaha
Beach, Sicily, North Africa ... He was in 11 major battles and came
out alive. In war, the best thing to be is lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his oldest son, Rob, Reiner pays perfunctory homage to
the show-biz achievements _ acting (``All in the Family'') and
directing (``The Princess Bride,'' ``Spinal Tap'') _ before
launching into a passionate discourse on Proposition 10, a
California law that taxes cigarettes and uses the funds for health,
nutrition and child care for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened the New York Times yesterday and there's a picture of
my son,'' Reiner said. ``It was a story about using celebrities to
further causes. Usually the causes are already in place: Rob's is
the only example of someone who took his own idea and built on it
... He took two years of his life to research and work for that. He
says going back to making movies will be like playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner gets together with friends from the early days of his
career, including Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get together once or twice a week, watch movies and ball
games,'' he smiled. ``We're just like anybody else. At our age, we
like to talk about our health and our grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
