<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1213 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-pt1-     04-19 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-pt1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the discussion about Confederate flags and symbols in
South Carolina, Georgia and Mississippi, I haven't seen anything
about the flag situation in Arkansas, President Clinton's home
state. Is the Confederate flag flown over the Capitol in Little
Rock? Does the state flag include any Confederate symbol?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Confederate flag isn't flown over the Capitol, said Renie
Rule of the Arkansas secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   The state flag does incorporate a symbol that nods at Arkansas'
Confederate history, but it's not conspicuous. The flag has a
diamond-shaped design bordered by a wide blue band. Within the band
are 25 stars signifying that Arkansas was the 25th state to enter
the Union. The word ARKANSAS is in the center of the flag, with one
star above it and three below. The book ``State Names, Seals, Flags
and Symbols: A Historical Guide'' cites a 1913 act of the Arkansas
Legislature, amended in 1923, stating that the star above the
letter ``R'' represents the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   As the act notes, from May 1, 1861, to May 23, 1865, Arkansas
was ``part of and under dominion of the Confederate States of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've had the opportunity to see Elton John in several
concerts over the past few years. While performing, he drinks from
a can of Diet Coke. But I've also noticed that on occasion the
label has been blanked out so the name doesn't show. What's up with
that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Diet Coke remains his drink of choice, insiders say. Even on
the occasions when the label isn't visible, it's still Diet Coke,
we're told. A fan who has attended all of Sir Elton's Atlanta
performances said he could recall the can being masked on only one
occasion: a private concert when the singer was hired by webMD to
perform for its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the name Ku Klux Klan? It's an odd
combination of words and their spellings.
</P>
<P>
   A: It apparently comes from the Greek word kyklos, from which
comes the English word ``circle,'' plus Klan (clan), spelled with a
K for the sake of alliteration. The KKK was formed as a social club
by a group of Confederate Army veterans in Pulaski, Tenn., in the
1860s. Although it was disbanded in 1869, local branches remained
active for another few years. It has revived and declined several
times since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do other countries conduct census surveys on a regular basis?
What's the history of the census?
</P>
<P>
   A: The United States is by no means the only country counting
its residents. In fact the United Nations, which encourages all
nations to conduct complete, periodic censuses, publishes manuals
of recommended census procedures and works to establishes standards
so it can collect accurate world statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Early censuses date to ancient Rome. In 1086, 20 years after
William the Conqueror defeated England, his officials enumerated
the country's land, people and property in the Domesday Book.
</P>
<P>
   The first modern census _ one that was complete, direct and
periodic _ was conducted by the United States in 1790. Britain has
conducted a modern census every year since 1801, except in 1941,
during World War II. France took its first modern census in 1836.
Others following included Belgium, 1846; Italy, 1861; Germany,
1871; India, 1871-72; Russia and Egypt, 1897; and Japan, 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of John Hinckley, the man who shot President
Ronald Reagan? Is he still in jail?
</P>
<P>
   A: John W. Hinckley Jr. isn't in jail. Since he was found by a
jury to be not guilty by reason of insanity in the shootings of
Reagan and three others in 1981, he has been locked up at St.
Elizabeths Hospital in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There's a recent development in the case, however, that is
continuing to evolve. Hospital officials are recommending that
Hinckley, 44, be granted ``conditional release'' for unsupervised
visits with his parents on one weekend day each week. The parents
live within the 50-mile radius of the hospital, required as one
element of the conditional release. Over the past six months,
Hinckley has visited several Washington-area shopping malls,
restaurants and bookstores under the supervision of hospital staff.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office, which opposes the hospital
officials' plans, has asked Senior U.S. District Judge June Green
for a hearing. Green has expressed skepticism over the years about
claims that Hinckley is making progress.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent essay in Time, Patti Davis vigorously opposed the
proposed brief releases of the man who shot her father. She asks:
``Is Hinckley less insane now? Is he no longer violent?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura offered any public opinion
on the South Carolina flag controversy?
</P>
<P>
   A: The subject came up in February on NBC's ``Meet the Press''
when three govenors _ Ventura, an independent; Roy Barnes of
Georgia, a Democrat; and Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, a Republican _
were asked if they favored removing the emblem.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura declined to comment. Following his lead, Barnes said,
``I think it's wrong for all of us who are outside to go in and
give advice.'' Ridge endorsed removing the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A small creek runs behind our home. With the possibility of
water restrictions looming again this summer, I'm wondering: Is
there any danger in using this creek water, which probably includes
runoff from yards and subdivision storm drains, to irrigate our
family vegetable garden?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the stream is fast-flowing, it probably will be safe to
use it for that purpose. But if it's sluggish, like it would be
during a drought, anything coming from runoff would be concentrated
and shouldn't be used. If you decide that the creek is flowing fast
enough for the water to be acceptable, it is recommended that you
irrigate from it in the middle of the week, because people tend to
put out pesticides on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Another tip: Don't use the creek water as an irrigation source
right after a rain, when the runoff is greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: While we were touring the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, we
were told that the Vehicle Assembly Building is one of the largest
in the world in cubic feet. What's larger?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Kennedy Space Center says the building encloses 129.4
million cubic feet of space. The Boeing Co.'s factory building in
Everett, Wash., is considerably larger, with a volume of 472
million cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, consider the Pentagon, which is often called the
largest office building in the world: It has a volume of 77 million
cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.) some years ago
said she celebrated her birthday with several cakes, one of which
was decorated with a ``black flag.'' What is a black flag?
</P>
<P>
   A: A red, black and green flag symbolizing African nationhood
was adopted in 1920 by the Universal Negro Improvement Association
and African Communities League. Many African nations chose those
same colors later for their national flags, but the 1920 version _
credited to Marcus Mosiah Garvey and the UNIA-ACL _ is said to be
the first.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey followers said red was chosen to represent ``the blood
which men must shed for their redemption and liberty,'' green ``for
the luxuriant vegetation of our Motherland,'' and black for ``the
color of the noble and distinguished race to which we belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about the flag can be found online at
http://unia-acl.org/history/flagstore.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long has the U.S. government been counting heads for a
census?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first U.S. census began on Aug. 2, 1790, and lasted about
18 months. Enumerators on horseback had to ride through the
countryside to count most of the population. Many people refused to
cooperate, because they didn't know why the government needed
information about them (some things haven't changed, have they?).
</P>
<P>
   When the tally was complete, it showed the nation had a
population of 3,893,874.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported that a barrel of crude oil contains 42
gallons. How many gallons of gasoline would be refined from that
same barrel of oil?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because of the reduction in density of many crude components
during processing, that 42 gallons yields 44 gallons of
``finished'' refinery products, of which gasoline amounts to 19 1/2
gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder (in gallons): distillate fuel oil, 8.61; jet fuel,
4.20; residual fuel oil, 2.77; petroleum coke, 1.60 gallons;
asphalt and road oils, 1.39; liquified gases, 1.43; petrochemical
feedstocks, 1.22; miscellaneous, 2.98; finished aviation gasoline,
0.08; and kerosene, 0.25.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent Q&AMP;A item about salary and perks of members of
Congress cited the National Taxpayers Union as the source of
information. I'm very interested, because I think what Congress
members get is outrageous. I never heard of the Taxpayers Union
before. What does it do, and how can I get more information about
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's an advocacy group that calls itself ``the (nation's)
largest grass-roots taxpayer organization, with more than 300,000
members across all 50 states.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1969, the organization says it works for
constitutional amendments to curtail deficit spending and restrict
tax increases; lower taxes for all people; ensure taxpayer rights;
eliminate wasteful and inefficient government spending; reduce
spending, bureaucracy and regulation at all levels of government;
and require accountability from elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Information: National Taxpayers Union, 108 N. Alfred St.,
Alexandria, VA 22314 (703-683-5700), or online at www.ntu.org.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
