<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: Finally, a WCW pay-per-view that clicks
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first pay-per-view of the WCW's Vince Russo-Eric Bischoff
era, ``Spring Stampede,'' was a hit by most accounts. The show had
good action, but better than that, the story lines actually came
off as planned and carried over into Monday's show _ momentum that
WCW pay-per-views haven't been able to achieve lately.
</P>
<P>
   The premise was that all titles were up for grabs. Jeff Jarrett
beat Diamond Dallas Page for the world title, Scott Steiner beat
Sting for the U.S. title, Terry Funk won the hardcore title, Chris
Candido won the cruiserweight title and Shane Douglas and Buff
Bagwell won the tournament for the tag team title.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great show considering Russo and Bischoff had only one
week to change the lineup and build some heat into the matches.
Sting's story line carried into Monday's ``Nitro,'' which was
another solid effort and could continue to pull viewers away from
WWF's ``Raw is War.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of viewers, Russo is talking about moving ``Nitro''
back to the 9-11 p.m. slot on Monday nights to compete head-to-head
with ``Raw.'' It's much too premature for that. ``Nitro'' needs to
get its ratings back in the 4.5 range. Last week ``Raw'' had a
6.2-to-3.1 advantage, down from the previous week's 6.9-2.5.
</P>
<P>
   _ When it comes to ratings, the WWF is reporting 875,000 buys
for its ``Wrestlemania 2000'' pay-per-view. That's approximately 15
times as many buys as the WCW ``Uncensored'' pay-per-view. Despite
this, wwf.com has a survey for viewers to fill out because, ``The
World Wrestling Federation is always trying to improve the quality
of its Pay-Per-Views. You can help us achieve that goal by taking a
few moments to complete this brief survey.'' The survey wants to
know which show you ordered, if you had any problems ordering and
if you were satisfied with the show. But it also asks for your
name, address and e-mail. Is this for consumer relations or just to
sell your information to telemarketers?
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of misleading, wcw.com had a link on their site
titled ``April 17th - Madden: Goldberg Returns!'' Goldberg was not
at Spring Stampede or Nitro and on Monday the link said ``...Sorry,
Goldberg Didn't Arrive!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lot of talk this week about two WCW wrestlers seemingly headed
in different directions: the troubled Scott Hall and the in-demand
Mike Awesome. A handful of wrestlers are rumored to have talked to
Eric Bischoff about firing Hall. Although Bischoff has on-air
control, Brad Siegel has the power over WCW contracts at the
moment, so don't expect anything to happen soon. Meanwhile, Mike
Awesome's move from ECW has been full of intrigue. Last Monday at
his debut, Bischoff ordered Awesome to renounce his ECW world title
and trash the ECW before destroying Kevin Nash. After a
conversation with former ECW stars Shane Douglas and Bam Bam
Bigelow, he did neither, which did not endear him to his new boss.
In the midst of all this, there was Awesome back in an ECW ring on
Thursday to lose his title to none other than the wrestler who gave
him his title when he left the ECW, current WWF wrestler Tazz. Why
two former ECW wrestlers were there to settle the ECW's issue is
beyond me. Before an overflow crowd in Indianapolis, Tazz beat
Awesome for the belt thanks to help from Tommy Dreamer. Expect Tazz
to give the belt to Dreamer soon.
</P>
<P>
   _ One person who will not miss Awesome is Spike Dudley. Here's
what Dudley had to say via his web site, spikedudley.net: ``Without
getting into too much detail let me say this. I busted my (butt)
for three months, literally busted my leg and will sit out close to
a year in order to get a guy that signed a three-year deal with my
company over. That person walked out without any warning or without
thought towards the people that put him into a position to leave. I
wish I could say it didn't bother me, but it does. Call me
narrow-minded for putting my morals in front of my checkbook. All I
can do is speak for myself and say that after what Paul E. and ECW
has done for me I couldn't imagine walking out on them with such
little class or dignity. On the other hand, I never thought
(Awesome) was that good and his departure will not 'hurt' ECW in
any way (trust me, I know).''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bret Hart's new book, ``The best there is, The best there was,
The best there ever will be,'' was released last week. Initial
reports are the book sold more copies in its first week than than
DDP's.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Macho Man'' Randy Savage was sighted backstage at a recent
WCW house show. Rumor is he was trying to get a spot on the
``Spring Stampede'' card, but he did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rumors of Mick Foley getting in the ring for the WWF anytime
soon is just that ... rumors. Foley may have some time on TV in the
near future, but expect him to be in an official role like a
commissioner of the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sick bay for the WWF is almost full. While ``Stone Cold''
Steve Austin appears on his way back at the ``Backlash''
pay-per-view (but not in the ring), the Undertaker is expected to
remain sidelined with a torn chest muscle until June. The British
Bulldog has no timetable for his return. Grand Master Sexay is
making a speedy recovery from minor knee surgery. Kane should be
back from his broken hand injury this weekend. But the news is not
so good for Billy Gunn. His rotator cuff surgery was completed, but
WWF announcer Jim Ross says Gunn is ``in considerable pain'' and
four to six months away from returning to the ring. The injuries
have caused a problem of a different sort, mainly where do Austin
and Undertaker fit in when they return. The Rock is the top face
and Triple H is the top heel, positions they have taken from Austin
and Undertaker. Many expect Austin to become a heel and turn on The
Rock at ``Backlash,'' but that would form a very odd pairing of
Vince McMahon and Austin, who feuded for nearly two years. WWF fans
may not accept it.
</P>
<P>
   _ One new face for the WWF is a former WCW heel, Scott Vick,
a.k.a. Sickboy. He may form a tag team with Val Venis, although his
gimmick is still in the works. Also Mideon has been spending all of
his time in the gym working to reshape his body (cut the gut and
bulk up his legs). He could work his way to a big role if he makes
it back.
</P>
<P>
   _ WWF might be able to add another WCW star to its roster soon,
Juventud Guererra. His contract is up this year and WWF along with
ECW are expected to make a big push for the underused WCW
high-flier.
</P>
<P>
   John Allen covers professional wrestling for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
