<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1216 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-COLUMBINE-OHIO20-COX     04-19 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-OHIO20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio students still fearful in wake of Columbine tragedy
anniversary
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When two troubled young men opened fire on their
classmates and teachers a year ago in Littleton, Colo., they knew
nothing about students Kelly Tipton or Elizabeth Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of miles away and a year after the tragedy at
Columbine High School, Tipton, Gannon and other students in the
Dayton area still are fearful and suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Gannon, a junior at Wayne High School, said a power
outage last fall caused the lights to go out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were passing around homecoming pictures, and it suddenly
got dark,'' Gannon said. ``My first thought was that something was
about to happen. I was scared and didn't know what to do so I
followed my first instinct, which was to dive under a table.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Tipton, a senior at Fairborn High School, said before a
year ago she never paid much attention to strangers passing through
the halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one day about two weeks ago I looked out of a classroom
and saw this strange-looking adult in the hallway in a long black
trench coat,'' she said. ``It kind of freaked me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Life has basically returned to normal at local high schools a
year after the Columbine shootings, but the tragedy deeply shook
students at Wayne and Fairborn, and doubtless it shook other
schools in the Dayton area as well.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 11 students interviewed by the Dayton Daily News is
convinced that the shootings that happened at Columbine High School
could just as easily have happened at their school.
</P>
<P>
   All of them have gone back to high school kids' traditional
spring month focus of proms and graduations and senior outings and
spring breaks and who's going out with whom.
</P>
<P>
   But televised images of carnage and panic, and the details of
how Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 12 classmates and a
teacher before killing themselves is a dark spectre lurking at the
backs of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some schools have even held shooting drills,''
Gannon said. ``We've got fire drills and tornado drills and now we
have to have somebody's-coming-to-shoot-up-your-school drills. You
have to figure out how to do the commando crawl out to the woods to
save your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to say to yourself, 'Wow! How did society get to
this point?'''
</P>
<P>
   PARALLELS EASY TO FIND HERE
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, 1999, Harris and Klebold attacked their fellow
students at Columbine High School in the Denver suburb of
Littleton. Littleton and Columbine have a lot in common with towns
and high schools in the Dayton area. Eric Harris actually lived in
Huber Heights as a toddler and went to elementary school for a
while in Beavercreek.
</P>
<P>
   The correlations were too close for comfort for some local
school districts. Officials at Beavercreek High School, probably
the closest local match to Columbine, declined to be interviewed or
to allow students to be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Clements, principal at Fairborn High School, went to
Colorado on vacation last summer and spent some time at Columbine
High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood on the hill overlooking Columbine in the area where
people had erected memorials,'' Clements said. ``I was struck by
the fact that just the physical appearance of the school is a lot
like my school.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine was a massive school with nearly 2,000 students in a
campus separated into several buildings on a broad campus.
Fairborn, which has about 1,800 students, has a similar layout.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayne campus in Huber Heights also is divided into several
buildings, and the school is one of the largest in Ohio with about
2,300 students, Principal Diane Ivory said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think it's too big,'' Ivory said. ``Most of the
research out there supports the idea that smaller schools are
better for the students. When students feel there are no people who
really know them, there are problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we just have to do the best we can doing things to make
kids feel like they're in a smaller school since we can't really
break the school up.''
</P>
<P>
   THE NEED TO BE RESPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Like Columbine, Fairborn and Wayne have a mix of ethnic groups
and races within the student body. The student's said that was
another thing that brought the Littleton tragedy home for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they were targeting people was what upset me,''
said Jessie Dysinger, a senior at Fairborn. ``They targeted the
athletes or they targeted the black students or they targeted the
people who looked a certain way. If you look around here, you see
all the same groups they were targeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and principals at both schools said a significant
percentage of their communities are Wright-Patterson Air Force Base
employees, and the base draws a broad racial mix of people who are
used to relocating and fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   Sonal Singhal, a sophomore at Wayne, said learning to get along
with people who seem different is just a part of growing up in
Huber Heights. ``There's always going to be something about you
that is different, and you're always going to run into people who
don't understand you,'' Singhal said. ``You just have to deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the motivation for Harris and Klebold seemed to be that
they classified themselves as outsiders. They and other of their
friends separated themselves from the mainstream at Columbine by
dressing in trench coats and calling themselves the Trench Coat
Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Though the students and principals said no such drastic cliques
developed at their schools, there are students at Wayne and
Fairborn who don't always fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Hunt, a junior at Wayne, said he's more aware now of the
need to treat people with respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always see people getting picked on, and it makes you want
to say, 'Hey, you'd better chill on that.' People are always going
to tease and pick on people, but you can't let it go too far,''
Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   NO GUARANTEES OF TOTAL SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   Clements said Fairborn hired extra guards for the hallways
immediately after the Columbine shootings, mostly to reassure
students and parents that the school was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got calls from parents wanting me to guarantee them their
children would be 100 percent safe here at school,'' Clements said.
``I had to tell them that was impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivory said Wayne always has been proactive about security, and
that Columbine didn't change things much. Students are required to
wear identification cards on lanyards around their necks this year
to get on campus, but that change was in the works before Columbine
and students don't always wear them.
</P>
<P>
   Students and administrators agree that tightened security is not
the answer, however. They say the best way to prevent future
Columbines is through improved parenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harris and Klebold planned what they were going to do for a
long time and nobody did anything to stop them,'' said Courtney
Johnson, a junior at Wayne. ``Were their parents in a stupor
somewhere that they didn't know their kids were making bombs in the
garage?''
</P>
