<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-NEWSCASTER _ LONDON _ Ananova, the world's first virtual
newscaster, debuted on the Internet Wednesday and her British
creators say the computer-generated figure will revolutionize the
way we get our news. The glamorous cyberanchor _ with her green
hair, big eyes and jerky movements _ delivers news bulletins at the
click of a mouse. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) international and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (EDS: Moving on l (Lifestyle) and a
(General News) categories.)
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER NEWS
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ LAMPSHADES _ There's nothing like a new lampshade
to shed new light on things when you are kick -starting the
revamping of your home decor. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
hard-to-fnd items. This week: Old English Scratch Cover for light
woods, Jaffa Cakes and Cope's canned corn. (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS .
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-DESTINATION _ A weekly feature about fun places to shop
in the Southeast. This week: Museum gift shops and antique
emporiums in Anniston, Ala. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   KEYLIME-PIE _ FLORIDA CITY, Fla. _ On the edge of the sawgrass
wilderness, where the road to the Everglades National Park takes a
hard left turn, there's an overgrown produce stand with the odd
name ``Robert Is Here'' painted across the roof like a Rock City
barn. Robert is Robert Moehling, the thicket-bearded proprietor,
whose easy smile and roomy midsection suggest that he enjoys his
work. Among the bins of oranges and kumquats, he offers passing
tourists almost anything that can be made with Key limes: honey,
syrup, curd, cookies, fudge, milkshakes, marinade, marmalade, dip,
salsa, salad dressing, mustard, hot sauce, barbecue sauce,
moisturizing cream _ not to mention the people's choice, Key lime
pie. Of all the products under the big shed, the most exotic may be
Key limes themselves. Robert's were actually grown within an hour's
drive of the Keys. You can't say that about many Key limes these
days; almost all of the sour little suckers are imported from
Mexico and the Caribbean. (Aucmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
36. WITH ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KEYLIME-RECIPES _ FLORIDA CITY, Fla. _ A recipe for Key lime
pie. (Aucmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE-BUNNY _ WACO, Texas _ If you're hopping down the
grocery trail looking for the best-tasting chocolate Easter bunny,
hippoty-hoppity, help is on the way. To separate the standard-issue
chocolate bunnies from those truly worthy of a place in your Easter
basket, we conducted a blind taste test of 10 chocolate Easter
bunnies. (Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH _WACO, Texas _ There's only one way to eat a crawfish _
at a party. Though they do have more legs than something you'd
normally try to eat, crawfish are easy to cook and make a great
focus for any outdoor party. (Collier, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CRAWFISH-RECIPES _ Tasty recipes for a crawfish bowl. With box
telling how to eat a crawfish. (Collier, Waco-Tribune Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COCONUT _ Food centerpiece package on coconut cakes with
side recipes and sidebar on preparing and comparing fresh, dried,
frozen fresh and packaged coconut. (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COCONUT-SIDE _ Sidebar with Food centerpiece on coconut cakes
explaining fresh and dried coconut, how to drain, crack, grate and
differences in packaged and canned product. (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COCONUT-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Coconut story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Easter Egg Ring. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TALK _ Yumiko Baron of Boulder, Colo. soaked the country
ham and baked it exactly as the direction said. Then she picked up
the phone and called south. ``It's very salty and kind of tough,''
she said with puzzlement. ``Yes,'' I exclaimed. ``You've done it
right. You've got country ham.'' A nervous pause. ``So what do I DO
with it,'' Baron asked. I guess country ham is an aquired taste
like the sushi of Baron's homeland. But here in the South, we
celebrate it, especially in the spring, when fall hams have put on
their six months or so of flavor. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
