<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNE-KLEIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANNE KLEIN IS MAKING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Anne Klein's youthful design team, Ken Kaufman
and Isaac Franco, have survived a change in ownership and three
years of effort to get the line back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Before the pair were hired, the once quite chic company, which
was always mentioned in the same breath as Ralph Lauren and Donna
Karan, not only lost its star designer, Louis dell'Olio (who was
unceremoniously fired by the previous owners), but its focus too,
as Patrick Robinson and then Richard Tyler managed to alienate the
Anne Klein customer.
</P>
<P>
   Franco and Kaufman have every respect in the world for
dell'Olio's ability to dress the American woman with a kind of
timeless classicism that, in hindsight, looks fresh and new. What
the two have managed to do with the Anne Klein line is to keep that
classicism and make it modern and sexy at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The pair recently brought their spring/summer collection to Saks
Fifth Avenue for a style show celebrating the Susan B. Komen
Foundation's Race for the Cure. The clothes we saw were
representative of the direction the pair are taking the company _
staying within the parentheses of American sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy on suitings _ these done in soft shades of lavender,
wheat, banana, pink and celadon silks, linens and sheer, stretchy
wools _ the line also featured beading, lingerie lace and Indian
sari trims. The latter, featured on a group of charcoal-gray
separates including an ankle-length wrap skirt, virtually ``blew
out the door,'' laughs Franco, 35. ``We have nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   Each collection features a real zotz of color. For spring, a
chili-red the pair call Flame, is worked up in linen and in shiny
Napa leather on a shirtlike jacket with hook-and-eye closures. The
sexiest piece in the show, a one-shoulder siren dress of sequins,
was in this fabulous shade.
</P>
<P>
   Ken and Isaac (they have been working together so long, they
finish each other's thoughts) met shortly after Kaufman, 36, began
working for knitwear firm Waranco, designing knitwear for Geoffrey
Beene and Pringle of Scotland Cashmere. Fresh out of New York's
Fashion Institute of Technology, he hired an assistant _ Franco,
who had just graduated from Parsons School of Design.
</P>
<P>
   The two went together to Bob Mackie for two years and then off
to Italy to work with Valentino and then Anne Klein. Their
collaboration works as if it were on mental ball bearings,
effortlessly, with the two designing not only Anne Klein's five
separate clothings lines (Anne Klein, AK Initials, Anne Klein 2,
A-Line and Anne Klein Suits which will launch in the fall) but also
directing the designs for shoes, swimwear and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   What Kaufman and Franco are concerned with, besides creating
well-priced clothes, is to return a ``voice'' to Anne Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our voice is a youthful spirit,'' says Kaufman. ``Our customer
is not a demographic, a size or an occupation. She has a sense of
style and a taste level.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``taste level'' is in line with the original creative
spirit, which came directly from Anne Klein herself. ``When we
first joined the company,'' explains Franco, ``we went back into
the archives to see Anne's original sketches from the late '60s and
early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not about `career sportswear.' It was about
collectible clothes, things which you could carry over for years
instead of looking in your closet and saying, `What was I
thinking?' She wasn't about costumes. Neither are we.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
