<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-NY-BREW-PUBS-HNS &LR;      04-19 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BREW-PUBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE TOAST OF NEW YORK BREWPUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTER, N.Y. _ _ For the first time in three years, an
Albany-area brewpub is not the toast of upstate New York
microbreweries.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock Brewing Co., based in Kingston, was awarded the
Matthew Vassar Cup at the third annual Hudson Valley Microbrew &AMP;
Fine Food Festival. In addition to winning the coveted cup,
Woodstock head brewer Nat Collins also won a gold medal for his
Braveheart Scotch Ale.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Pub &AMP; Brewery captured the cup at the inaugural competition
in 1998, while Big House Brewing Co. in Albany won the award last
year. The prizes were awarded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This year's competition held here at a ski resort was markedly
different from the first two, which were held at the Culinary
Institute of America in Hyde Park.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one breweries, each bringing three beers that were
savored and rated by a panel of certified beer judges, entered.
Thirteen breweries took part in 1998; 14 last year.
</P>
<P>
   High Point Wheat Beer Co., from High Point, N.J., was the only
non-New York state brewery at the event. High Point brewer Greg
Zaccardi claimed runner-up honors with Ramstein Blonde, a
traditional hefeweizen. High Point is the first exclusive wheat
beer brewery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze medal went to Brewery Ommegang in Cooperstown for its
Rare Vos. Ommegang is the only brewery in the country that produces
only Belgian-style beers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Woodring, founder of the Hudson Valley Home Brewers Club,
one of the largest such groups in the nation, organized the
festival. Matthew Vassar, for whom the best brewery cup is named,
founded Vassar College more than a century ago with capital he
acquired in the brewing industry.
</P>
<P>
   This year's gold-medal beer, the Braveheart Scotch Ale, was
awarded a bronze medal at the first competition. It has a deep
copper color and a relatively high alcohol content, approximately 9
percent. In the tradition of Scotch-style ales, Braveheart is
sweetly malty and full-bodied. It is also exceptionally clean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SYBASE-HNS &LR;      04-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYBASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SYBASE REBOUNDS FROM TOUGH TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     by ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two years after laying off 1,000 workers and
restructuring its core business, Sybase Inc. is reaping the
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for the first quarter of 2000, excluding accounting
adjustments for last year's purchase of Home Financial Network
Inc., rose to $19.5 million (22 cents a share) from $8.5 million
(10 cents) a year ago. That beat per-share expectations of 13
cents, the average estimate of four analysts polled by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Including the accounting adjustments, earnings rose to $6.7
million (8 cents) from $5.9 million (7 cents). Revenue rose 9.1
percent to $227 million from $208 million.
</P>
<P>
   To top things off, the company reported cash reserves of $363
million.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a company many had left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been reengineering this company for over two years,''
said John Chen, chairman, president and CEO of Sybase. ``It hasn't
been easy. What with the whole dot-com environment growing around
us, keeping our core team upbeat and intact hasn't been a walk in
the park. It's been more like a walk through Central Park . . .
after dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen has reason for optimism these days, having captained one of
the most dramatic turnarounds in recent software history.
</P>
<P>
   Once a database powerhouse, Emeryville, Calif.-based Sybase fell
on some hard times in the mid-1990s. An ill-fated licensing
agreement with Microsoft, a poorly received software upgrade and
continual pressure from Oracle Corp. led to a string of annual
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing came to a head in 1998 when then-CEO Mitchell
Kertzman left after a short tenure to take a job with a division of
arch-rival Oracle. It seemed that Sybase had seen its finest days.
</P>
<P>
   Enter John Chen, a respected former executive for Siemens
Nixdorf AG, in Munich, where he served as president and CEO of
Siemens Nixdorf's $3 billion Open Enterprise Computing Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began to study our history and sales model, I realized
the space we were in was saturated and our customers were looking
for a new level of services,`` said Chen in an interview with The
Examiner. ``At that time, I realized we were not category winners,
but we had a strong in-store base.''
</P>
<P>
   So he rolled up the sleeves and started to clean house. First to
go were about 1,000 workers. Next came a reorganization of
operations into embedded applications and other technology-based
divisions that took their core business beyond database software.
It was a classic diversification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized we had to really change,'' said Chen, ``which
included identifying a high-growth market and cleaning up the
balance sheets. Unfortunately, all those things all happened at the
same time. We didn't have the luxury of taking things sequentially.
But it's all been rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   In financial terms, the rewards have become sizable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the highest-ever operating-income first quarter in the
history of the company, going back 15 years ago,'' said Chen, whose
company now boasts 4,214 workers worldwide. ``I would also venture
to say this is the highest cash balance we've ever had. And this is
also the first quarter in a very long time that we have appreciated
revenue growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen said the company plans to use its cash reserves for
acquisitions and expansions, continuing to grow its business plan
beyond the world of databases.
</P>
<P>
   Sybase agreed last December to acquire closely held Home
Financial Network, of Reston, Va., for $130 million and combine it
into a new company to target the online financial-services market.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of Chen's plan to make consulting, technical
support and other services represent more than half of the
company's sales, shielding it from the fickle swings of the
software business.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting large corporate customers, the company has had a good
amount of success in Asian markets over the past two years, where
corporate restructuring following the region's financial crisis has
fueled a need for databases and services.
</P>
<P>
   Internet banking, as well as the wireless database market, will
be two focal points for the company as it moves forward, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Sybase shares closed up $3.31 at $21.88 before the company
announced earnings. In after-hours trading, the stock gained
another $2.13 to hit $24. The company's shares have now more than
tripled since hitting a 52-week low of $7.13 in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing pretty good,'' said Chen, who was happy to see
some sanity return to the markets in recent days. ``I think the
market correction was a good thing. It reminds people that cash is
king and real revenue rules. Let's go back to being a market ruled
by the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Sybase said that it settled two lawsuits brought
against the company, its officers and directors over the company's
restatement of its 1997 financial results. Both settlements are
subject to court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Sybase didn't disclose the terms of the settlements. The
settlements won't hurt the company financially, Sybase said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-TEEN-ENTREPRENEURS-HN     04-19 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-ENTREPRENEURS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIGH SCHOOL GEEKS TALK ABOUT STOCK OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At first glance, Aaron Stone's resume reads like
a blueprint for Silicon Valley success.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years as a freelance consultant. A partnership with
friends. A dot-com start-up. It's all there.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, a major obstacle looms on the horizon: high school
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Stone, and his partner, Phil Polanski, are 18
years old, and they go to Palo Alto High School, right smack in the
heart of Silicon Valley. They're also the co-founders of
Impressitron.com, a Web site consultancy that is ``a solution for
start-ups that are having trouble getting their Web sites up and
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the duo's story is a common one at the school
affectionately known as Paly High, where stock options and
start-ups are as common as readin' and 'rithmetic. Stone, among
others, is featured in the documentary ``Paly High: Between
Classes.'' While much of the teenage, cliquey angst is instantly
recognizable to anyone who did time at an American high school, the
business savvy of the student body is pure valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely more aware of money and making money than
when I was in school,`` said Jona Frank, the San Francisco
filmmaker who produced ``Paly High'' for KQED's ``Bay Window''
series. ``It's very much a game to them, about playing with the
Internet and the stock market. It's fun to them. It's just the way
they amuse themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Stone's estimates, there are probably a couple of
hundred students at the school who intern or work at tech-related
companies in Silicon Valley. On top of that, a number of other
students have started companies of their own at Paly High, all
hoping to catch the tech wave of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Pang, a 17-year-old senior, got his feet wet in the Web
world working summers at Alteon Websystems in San Jose. Like many
of his valley colleagues, stock options were part of his pay
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really lucky to work for a company that believed in
distributing the wealth among everyone, not just the top brass,''
said Pang, sounding twice his age.
</P>
<P>
   While Frank's documentary touches on the business exploits of
Paly High's students, it delves deeper into the social interactions
among the school's various social groups. Shooting in black and
white, Frank lets the students narrate their own realities,
discussing the cliques, music and clothes they and their peers use
to define themselves at the 1,400-student school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is about what happens in between the structured time
of school,'' said Frank. ``Different students pointed out to me
that a skater might be partnered with a jock in science class, but
they would not eat lunch together. Lunch time, after-school time,
social time is when people form their own cliques. This is the time
that most interests me because it is the in-between time that
reflects people's personalities and their search for identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Paly High's tech set spends its in-between time in the
``robotics team'' lab. Sequestered on one side of the campus, the
self-proclaimed geeks work together to build a 130-pound robot
that's entered in a nationwide competition held in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Stone and Polanski met. And that's where the
techies spend most of their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the time of the competition, a six-week period
beginning in January, I would say we spend upwards of 50 hours a
week here,'' said Stone. ``There are times when we'll spend entire
days or more here.''
</P>
<P>
   During that time together, a number of the robotics team members
realized they were all doing Web work on the side. That's when the
entrepreneurial bug took a bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just noticed that, as a group, we were more effective at
selling our talents,'' said Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Polanski credits the high school with much of his technology
talent, comparing it unfavorably with his former school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did go to San Mateo High School my freshman year,'' said
Polanski, who will join Stone at Cal Poly San Luis Obispo this
fall. ``Technology there was really behind. They only had six
computers that were really slow and were crashing all the time.
Then I came here, and we have 25 Pentium III 500 (MHz) machines
hooked up to the district's T1 line.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank sees the proximity to Silicon Valley as the primary reason
some students are so involved with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so present in their lives. Most of their parents are
involved in technology,`` said Frank. ``I think if there's a
downside, it's just about having to think about money while being
young.''
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, it's not so bad being a techie anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The status of what it means to be a geek has changed,'' said
Frank. ``Their
</P>
<P>
   self-confidence is better and there's more of them. They feel
more supported.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still looked upon as the techy, nerdy types. But
because of the success of people like Bill Gates and Steve Jobs,
they're also looked upon as people whose skill will pay off for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pang, who will attend UC-Irvine in the fall, says he's missed
out on the partying but isn't too worried about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have missed out on a lot of social events to pursue my
career,'' he said, pointing out that he'd try to make up for lost
time on a trip to Europe this summer. ``During all my vacation
times, I spent them at the company instead of getting drunk down in
Santa Cruz or something. ``But as they say on `Buffy': `Geeks are
in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who runs a San Francisco production company called Camp
Pokomoke, has built a career around the social environments of
young people. For the past two years, she has been working on a
photo book on adolescent social groups, called ``High School.''
She's also shot and produced a short film called ``Catholic
School,'' which won acclaim at the Sundance Film Festival in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
