   FRANCE-LOUISXVII (Paris) _ Scientists said Wednesday that DNA
tests ``support very strongly'' the assertion that a child who died
in prison in 1795 was the uncrowned King Louis XVII, undercutting
two centuries of speculation that the young royal had been replaced
by someone else in jail and whisked to exile. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-POLITICS (Rome) _ Premier Massimo D'Alema resigned
Wednesday after setbacks in regional elections. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Last week, President-elect Vladimir
Putin pushed a long overdue arms control treaty through a compliant
parliament. Wednesday, he scored a victory with Russia's regional
bosses in parliament's upper chamber, winning an easy vote to get
rid of a meddlesome prosecutor who had been the scourge of former
President Boris Yeltsin's Kremlin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 3 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PRISONERS (Jerusalem) _ Israel on Wednesday released 13
Lebanese prisoners who had been held as ``bargaining chips'' for
more than a decade. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-PIPELINE (Edmonton) _ A verdict is due Wednesday in the
trial of an anti-globalization crusader who sabotaged an oil
pipeline. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _  &UR; General &LR;
