</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MARIJUANA (Santa Cruz, Calif.) _ Santa Cruz voters
approved the medical use of marijuana without the supervision of a
physician, effective Wednesday. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-EXECUTION (Nashville) _ With 100 people holding vigil,
Tennessee executed child killer Robert Glen Coe by injection
Wednesday morning. He was the first person to be put to death in
the state in 40 years. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIBER-CANCER (Undated) _ Two large and rigorous studies
involving thousands of people have failed to confirm one of the
most widely held beliefs about diet and health _ that eating low
fat, high fiber foods can protect against colon cancer. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-WAX-MUSEUM (New York) _ Forget the Royal Family or Jack the
Ripper. When Madame Toussaud's Wax Museum opens in New York, the
headliners will include Donald Trump, television personality Al
Roker and talk show host Larry King. By Glenn Collins.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BRITAIN-NUCLEAR (Sellafield, England) _ British Nuclear Fuels, the
government-owned company that operates the Sellafield nuclear
complex, has been under fire since it was disclosed that documents
involving fuel rods being shipped to Japan had been falsified. The
crisis has sparked a debate about just what business the company
should be in _ reprocessing spent fuel for use in power plants or
simply disposing of nuclear waste and cleaning up nuclear sites.
The debate has spread across Europe to the industry of selling
mixed oxide fuels. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   HACKER-ARREST (Undated) _ The Royal Canadian Mounted Police
announced an arrest made in connection with the February attacks
against Web sites. The suspect is believed to be a teen-ager known
as Mafiaboy. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move by 3 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-CHRYSLER (Frankfurt) _ DaimlerChrysler reported a 3
percent dip in operating profits Wednesday as mounting competition
in North America eroded earnings at Chrysler. By Edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ART-THEFTS (Beijing) _ An anonymous letter tipped off
Chinese archaeologists to what they believe is a rampant global
problem: the theft of cultural relics that are given a phony
provenance and sold to private collectors and museums, at prices
ranging into the millions. Such thefts occur on the largest scale
in China, which is filled with unexplored tombs and other
archaeological remains as well as poorly guarded temples and
museums. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-IRELAND-FILM (London) _ While still in her late 20s,
Deborah Warner made her name as something of a wunderkind of the
British stage through innovative interpretations of classics at the
Royal Shakespeare Company and the Royal National Theater. She has
now turned to her first film, ``The Last September,'' a screen
adaptation of a much loved novel about Ireland by Elizabeth Bowen.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY (Undated) _ New developments in questions
surrounding the business practices of the Marlborough Gallery, the
international art gallery heavily fined in 1975 for defrauding the
Mark Rothko estate and accused in court last month of cheating the
Francis Bacon estate. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTO-RICO-ARCHITECTS (San Juan) _ Many young Puerto Rican-born
architects who study and work on the U.S. mainland or outside the
country are giving up jobs with prestigious firms to work on a tiny
Caribbean island of 3.5 million people. For some, moving back means
an opportunity to build on the island's strong Modernist tradition;
for others, it is a chance to address polemical issues of
nationalism and identity in design. By Raul A. Barreneche.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY-DESIGN (Milan, Italy) _ At the 2-million square
foot Salone, the world's largest trade exhibition for contemporary
design, as well as two large tandem events and 320 gallery shows
simultaneously hosted in the city, designers ignored the future,
embraced the future or, in the case of a concept chair by a Dutch
team, took a sledgehammer to the present. In the latter case, they
used frustration as a tool for change. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move in `l' category)
</P>
