r s BC-FBC-CAL-HNS &LR;      04-19 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAC-10 PROBES CAL FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ A Pac-10 investigation into allegations of
academic fraud against two former Cal football players was
apparently prompted by complaints from their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year wide receivers Michael Ainsworth and Ronnie
Davenport are the subject of the probe to determine whether they
received credit for a class they only attended the last few weeks
of the 1999 spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   The conference has confirmed that an investigation is under way,
without divulging any findings.
</P>
<P>
   Football coach Tom Holmoe said a thorough in-house investigation
last spring failed to find any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Ainsworth and Davenport have since flunked out of Cal and are
enrolled in junior colleges in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Holmoe said the in-house probe followed ``rumors'' from older
players on the team regarding Ainsworth's and Davenport's academic
performance. He acknowledged that some players resented the lack of
work ethic shown by the two wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Pac-10 investigation _ as well as the in-house
Cal probe _ involved allegations that both players got credit for
an ethnic studies course called ``Crossroads: California and the
World'' even though they didn't actually enroll in the course until
two weeks before the end of the semester.
</P>
<P>
   The course's teacher, Alex Saragoza, has told university
officials that the two were in the class even though they may not
have officially signed on until late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Cal officials say it's fairly common for students to add courses
late in the semester, for reasons including paperwork foul-ups or
waiting list problems for popular classes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lester, Cal's faculty athletics representative and a
professor of chemistry, said the school's investigation found
nothing out of the ordinary in the Ainsworth-Davenport case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows what was done was the appropriate addition of
classes,'' he said. ``These guys followed protocol. They had been
in the class. They just added it. They were not registered for
whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester said that professors often ``frowned'' on the late adds,
but said they were acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Holmoe cited the example of another player who recently was
notified he was getting an F in a class. In this case, the player
had inadvertently enrolled in the wrong class and has been
attending another class even though he wasn't officially enrolled.
Now, with just a few weeks left in the semester, he is adding the
class he's actually been attending and dropping the course he never
intended to enroll in.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Muldoon, Pac-10 spokesman, would only confirm that the
investigation was under way. He did note that such probes were
fairly common, with the conference following up on academic
compliance issues on a ``constant basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The case offers a rare glimpse into the chemistry on last year's
Cal football team and dissension prompted by the two wide
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Ainsworth and Davenport were often the subject of disciplinary
actions, doing extra running drills for a variety of infractions.
Ainsworth was suspended for one game for violating a team rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys resented the way they acted,'' Holmoe said.
``There were some tremendous kids on the team last year that had
sacrificed a lot. . . .Academically and athletically, the players
ask a lot of each other and when players don't join in, that makes
it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal's investigation was conducted by Gloria Nevarez, the
athletic department's director of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   If the conference discovers any improprieties, the case could be
forwarded to the NCAA, where possible penalties could include
forfeiting games from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Associate athletic director Bob Driscoll said the school was
expecting the Pac-10 to clear the school of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've talked to a number of people and have come to
the same conclusions we did,'' he said. ``There's nothing there. If
they had something they certainly would have brought it forth.
We're pretty confident about this one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
