<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-19 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL GRIEVE FOR THE NASDAQ KNOW-IT-ALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There must be a place in the Bible where Jesus or one of the
Hebrew prophets inveighs against reveling in other people's
misfortunes; the precise passage does not come to mind. And yet how
can one not indulge a certain pleasure in the wipeout of the
dot-com stocks during the past few weeks?
</P>
<P>
   The odious stock jockey James Cramer, co-founder of
TheStreet.com, has canceled vacation this week to watch his equity
positions erode. Just a few months ago, Jim wanted me to pay $100 a
year to visit his Web site and read his dribblings on the market.
Now, I can read them for free.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's hot stock, which made paper millionaires of
those journalists clever enough to leave the dying
newsprint-and-ink business I work in, is now ``under water,''
meaning it is worth less that its initial offering price. It was
initially offered at $19; now it is worth $6. Paper millionaires no
more.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Schadenfreude Crash. Do you know the term? ``The
malicious enjoyment of the misfortunes of others,'' according to
the dictionary. It is not a pretty emotion _ we don't live in a
world of exclusively pretty emotions _ but it is a real one.
</P>
<P>
   How could you not feel battered by those ubiquitous, guileless
newsmagazine cover stories, A) cursing you for not being a
Web-savvy 23-year-old billionaire, B) damning you for not investing
our life savings in the latest lookalike-idea.com (this assumes you
are too stupid to notice that Peapod, WebVan, Streamline, and
HomeRuns are all in the same business), and C) assuring you that if
you, like, assemble cars for a living, you're a sap. In the future,
no one will drive a car! We'll all be traveling on Mr. Gore's
information highway!
</P>
<P>
   So let the ``tarantulas of resentment'' _ Nietzche's phrase,
effectively recycled by Tom Wolfe in his recent novel, ``A Man in
Full'' _ scutter forth! Where's my friend, the former surgeon
general C. Everett Koop? Glub, glub . . . he's under water, too!
From a high of $45, Drkoop.com is now trading at $2. The good
doctor and his henchperson, TV doc Nancy Snyderman, have been
bailing out on the way down: he's sold about $1 million worth,
she's dumped $2.6 million worth since the beginning of the year.
Would you were so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Joke stock of the year Healtheon MD has lost 84 percent of its
value. IVillage is off 88 percent. Stamps.com _ they never sent me
my free stamps! _ off 89 percent. Since its recent public offering,
Martha Stewart's multimedia empire has lost about $1.5 billion in
value. It is all too sad to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   What did I do in the new economy, you ask? I bought two stocks:
New York Times, at a substantial discount because they own the
Globe, and Phillip Morris, partly as a classic value play _ the
company's non-cigarette holdings are supposedly worth more than $18
a share, where I came in _ and partly for ideological reasons. The
feckless greed of the politicians and plaintiffs' lawyers preying
on Big Tobacco turns my stomach. Fine, the tobacco execs are no
choirboys _ what of it? I smoked; I screwed up my health. Whose
fault is that?
</P>
<P>
   But I digress. I'm up 16 percent in Phillip Morris, so I've
outperformed both the Dow and Fidelity's Magellan Fund in recent
months. The classic newspaper stocks like Times Mirror, Knight
Ridder, and New York Times _ despite its ill-advised investment in
Thestreet.com _ have held up pretty well. Alas, the same cannot be
said for our esteemed Web competitors, who predict the demise of
boring old newspapers several times a day. Did someone mention
Salon.com? If present trends continue, that stock will soon have
the approximate worth of Confederate currency, circa 1866.
</P>
<P>
   I recognized the market top about four months ago, when I
received an unsolicited job offer to join a dot-com. Just as J.P.
Morgan started to sell when he heard his shoeshine boy talking
about the stock market, I knew we had reached a turning point. The
dotcoms were so desperate, they wanted me! I advised a few friends
to start trimming their positions, but I doubt they listened. After
all, what do I know?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
