<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1258 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-REVERSAL-OF-FORTUNE-2     04-19 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVERSAL-OF-FORTUNE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HELL TO HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Liz Murray is standing on the stage of the auditorium
of PS 95 in the Bronx, telling 400 fifth- and sixth-graders about
her life. Several of the children are holding pieces of paper,
ready to snare her autograph. One girl has a strategic plan (which
she will later successfully execute) to pull out a strand of
Murray's hair.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old in faded jeans, worn sneakers, and flannel shirt
_ though statuesque and poised _ isn't the typical adolescent pop
icon, which one might expect given the audience adoration. She's
not a basketball star or a rock singer or an actress (though Minnie
Driver would be perfectly cast in the movie that will inevitably be
made about Murray one day.)
</P>
<P>
   The truth is far more spectacular. The daughter of two cocaine
addicts, Murray dropped out of school in the ninth grade, lived on
the streets of New York from the age of 16 until 18, slept on
subway trains and park benches, and finally, through sheer force of
will, reversed her fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Murray is headed to Harvard, accepted as a freshman
the year the university reported a record number of applications.
``It's surreal,'' says Barbara Franceschini, who was Murray's
teacher in the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   The story gets even more surreal. As word has gotten out about
her accomplishments (she won a prestigious New York Times College
Scholarship last year, which led to a segment about her in December
on ABC's ``20/20''), Hollywood honchos, always ready to glorify
despair, have taken her under their wing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, she's been a guest on ``The Montel
Williams Show,'' Candice Bergen's ``Exhale'' talk show on the
Oxygen network, and ``Leeza'' with Leeza Gibbons. Thursday, NBC's
``Later Today'' show will air a live segment about her on a show
celebrating extraordinary young people.
</P>
<P>
   Through her connections with the celebrity she now calls
``Candice,'' she has met actress Sigourney Weaver and playwrights
Wendy Wasserstein and John Guare; Guare took her last week to see
the Broadway production of ``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the girl who picked food out of trash cans and did her
homework in stairwells is checking her voice mail on her cell phone
and asking a reporter if she can ``expense'' the taxi she's
flagging down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely wild,'' says Murray of the arc _ from homeless
to Harvard to Hollywood _ that her life has made. ``For a long time
I was just stuck in one place, saying, `You were there, and now you
are here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But ask Franceschini and Helene Lorinsky _ two teachers in the
audience who taught her in elementary school _ and they'll say
nothing would surprise them about the girl they used to call
Elizabeth. ``She was very special,'' Franceschini recalls.
</P>
<P>
   They taught her at PS 261 in the Bronx, a windowless school so
decrepit it was declared a health hazard and closed the year Murray
graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Her teachers describe her as a tough and stoic child who was
placed in the intellectually gifted class, talented at math, and so
driven to work hard she chose to play Brutus in the class
production of ``Julius Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in her classroom, Franceschini pulls out a stuffed toy
penguin from under a desk and explains it is a cherished gift from
Murray the year she graduated elementary school. Murray gave it to
her because Franceschini had read the book ``Mr. Popper's
Penguins'' to the class, and because her maiden name was Popper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told her how much I loved penguins,'' Franceschini said,
``and Elizabeth wrote letters and made phone calls to zoos to find
where she could get me one. When she couldn't, she gave me this. I
don't know where the girl who had no money found the money for it.
It was so touching.''
</P>
<P>
   There were hints, big hints, that something was wrong at home.
Murray's mother once showed up at school in a nightgown, with feces
on her shoes. During one period, Elizabeth wore the same pair of
pants to school every day for months. But her teachers didn't have
the whole story. They knew her mother had been in and out of
hospitals, but not that she was an alcoholic, or that her parents
did cocaine in the kitchen, without trying to hide their habit. Nor
did they know that the apartment where she lived with her parents
and sister was filthy, not helped by the presence of two cats and a
dog which no one walked or cared for. (Murray would have to step
over piles of feces covered with maggots to get to her bedroom.)
</P>
<P>
   On good days, Elizabeth's mother read her Dr. Seuss stories and
listened to old records; her father _ he is ``extremely
intelligent'' _ would quote from 1940s novels but ``then go into
the kitchen and shoot up drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither parent was a provider. At the age of ``8 or 9,''
Murray recalls, she worked bagging groceries at a 24-hour
supermarket. ``I was the only one putting food in the fridge,'' she
tells the hushed schoolchildren in the PS 95 auditorium. She also
pumped gas for tips at self-service gas stations. Money was so
tight her mother once sold her sister's winter coat to get some
cash.
</P>
<P>
   After her parents separated when she was 13, her father ran out
of money and lost the apartment. Murray went into a city youth
facility for a few months but couldn't bear to stay there: ``It was
dehumanizing, and I'm too full of spirit.'' She went to live with
her mother and godfather. ``They were old drinking buddies,''
Murray explains. But that didn't last long, since her mother was
diagnosed with AIDS and tuberculosis; she died in December 1996.
(Her sister, Lisa, stayed on at the godfather's till finding her
own apartment last year.)
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth grade, Murray dropped out of school. To pass the
time and lift her spirits, she often went to libraries to read
``Hamlet'' and Shakespeare's sonnets. She quotes by memory a
favorite poem by Edgar Allan Poe, called ``Alone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From childhood's hour I have not been
</P>
<P>
   As others were; I have not seen
</P>
<P>
   As others saw; I could not bring
</P>
<P>
   My passions from a common spring.
</P>
<P>
   From the same source I have not taken
</P>
<P>
   My sorrow; I could not awaken
</P>
<P>
   My heart to joy at the same tone;
</P>
<P>
   And all I loved, I loved alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 16, Murray hit the streets. Sometimes, she'd sleep
at friends' houses, ``until I'd hear their parents talking in low
voices and I knew I was wearing out my welcome,'' she says later
that day in an interview. Other times, she slept on park benches or
subways, panhandling for spare change to get on the trains.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to return to high school came at the lowest point
of her life _ the day she saw her mother's coffin at the cemetery,
a donated pine box with her name misspelled in Magic Marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality really hit me,'' she tells the children. ``Everything
I knew about had messed up. And I understood it was important to
push myself, that I'd either make it good for myself . . . or
submit to everything that was happening and live a life of
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   One teacher she contacted recommended the Humanities Preparatory
Academy, a small progressive school in Manhattan known for working
with students who are lost in the conventional school system.
Despite the fact that her transcript was ``one big blank,'' says
Perry Weiner, the school's co-director, her intelligence impressed
officials, and she was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
