<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PASSOVER-MATZO-ART-BO     04-19 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER-MATZO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR PASSOVER, A KNEADING OF ANCIENT RITUAL, US SAVVY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just before sundown Tuesday, as his father and his
grandfather had done before him, Rabbi Naftali Horowitz led a small
group of Jews into the Blue Hills to draw fresh water for making
matzo.
</P>
<P>
   They will gather in the basement of Brookline's Beth Pinchas
synagogue, mixing that water by hand with special flour from New
York, kneading and perforating the dough, and baking it for not
longer than 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time-honored method of making unleavened bread for
Passover, a practice guided for millennia by tradition and Jewish
law.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike their ancestors, the vast majority of Jews in
America and throughout the world will not eat fresh, hand-made,
rough, round matzo when they gather for the first seder, the ritual
dinner that begins the eight-day Passover holiday commemorating the
Jewish exodus from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they will eat matzo that is machine-made and square,
with every piece looking and tasting the same and the package
featuring a well-known brand name such as Manischewitz.
</P>
<P>
   Now, research by a Brandeis University scholar reveals that the
dramatic transformation of matzo from a locally hand-crafted ritual
product into an international food commodity was the result of a
collision between the modernizing forces of industrialization in
America and the change-resistant strictures of the ancient Jewish
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it was round, and now it's square. Once it was varied,
and now every matzo is the same. It was a quintessentially local
product, and now it's become a brand,'' said Jonathan D. Sarna, a
historian of American Judaism who has been researching the
Americanization of matzo. ``How on earth did they persuade Jews to
buy this stuff, and how did they get the rabbis to say it's OK?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers, Sarna said, are classically American, as matzo
manufacturing was affected by the same economic forces that
reshaped the manufacture of many consumer products at the turn of
the last century.
</P>
<P>
   Behr Manischewitz, the founder of the well-known Passover
products company, created a new market by patenting machines that
could make matzo more economically and for wide distribution, and
he successfully turned change to his advantage, promoting a product
that had always been hand-made with the slogan ``no human hand
touches these matzos.''
</P>
<P>
   But the answers are also peculiarly Jewish, because the
modernization of matzo was almost blocked by the religious
authorities governing a tradition resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern European rabbinic authorities in the late 19th century
were adamant that machine-made matzo is unacceptable _ a position
some Orthodox rabbis still hold today _ and Manischewitz was forced
to spend years and dollars courting a new group of religious
authorities in what was then Palestine before winning the
rabbinical stamp of approval necessary before Jews would purchase
his matzo.
</P>
<P>
   The debate continues today. Despite the fact that hand-made
matzo can cost up to $25 a pound, compared with less than $2 per
pound for machine-made matzo, the Butcherie, a kosher grocery in
Brookline, has seen increasing sales of hand-made matzo in recent
years, and sold out this year's supply days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jews are commanded to eat matzo during Passover to honor their
ancestors who fled Egypt in such haste that they did not have time
to allow their bread to rise.
</P>
<P>
   In colonial America, matzo was generally baked in ovens in the
basement of synagogues, as Congregation Beth Pinchas does today.
But by 1886, when Behr Manischewitz emigrated from Prussia to
Cincinnati, most matzo in the United States was being made in local
Jewish bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1888 Manischewitz, who had been a ritual slaughterer in
Prussia, opened his own matzo factory, taking advantage of his
experience negotiating the complex regulations governing Jewish
ritual foods.
</P>
<P>
   Manischewitz and his son won more than 50 patents, including one
for a conveyor belt system that ensured that matzo did not bake for
longer than the 18-minute limit spelled out in Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to all of these innovations, Manischewitz could produce
more matzo, more cheaply, with less breakage, and with a much more
regular and pleasing appearance than had ever before been
possible,'' Sarna said.
</P>
<P>
   But Manischewitz ran into a problem _ the opposition of European
rabbis who raised religious and economic objections.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis said matzo, according to Jewish tradition, must be
made with human intent, which machines can't have. And, they
argued, machines would displace an important source of seasonal
employment for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Needing rabbinic approval and unable to get it in Europe,
Manischewitz aggressively courted the emerging rabbinate in
Palestine. He sent two of his sons to study there, and both married
into prominent Jewish families.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Manischewitz family established a yeshiva,
a school for training rabbis, and gave annual donations of money
and matzo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the Internal Revenue Service took the Manischewitz
company to court over its practice of deducting as a business
expense contributions to the yeshiva, and it is here, Sarna said,
that the interplay between business, philanthropy, and faith
becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   In tax court documents, Manischewitz argued that its
contributions would help ``overcome the impression . . . that
American machine-made matzos are not kosher.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax court sided with the company, ruling that, ``although
there can be little doubt that the contributions to the seminary
were prompted by a complex of motives . . . (there were) reasonably
evident business purposes to be served.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most obvious evidence that industrialization alone
would not have forced the transformation of matzo is the fate of
challah, the bread that Jews eat each sabbath, which is locally
made and varies in form and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism is not used to the kind of uniformity that we see with
matzo,'' said Rabbi William Hamilton of Congregation Kehillath
Israel in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process with matzo represents the confrontation
between Judaism and modernity,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Manischewitz is now part of a large private food distributor,
RAB Holdings, and the company sells a variety of Jewish products,
including matzo that is salted or unsalted, whole wheat or plain,
egg, and, of course, yolk-free egg. The matzo, some of which is not
kosher for Passover, now comes in big squares, thin tea sheets, and
bite-sized crackers.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the variety of machine-made matzo from savory garlic
to apple cinammon lining today's supermarket shelves, the debate
that almost prevented Manischewitz's success continues today among
the most observant Jews. A small but growing segment of Jews is
purchasing expensive and hard-to-find shmurah matzo, which is
prepared with purpose and is supervised from the time the wheat is
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Ruboy, one of the Butcherie's owners, said consumers
offer a variety of reasons for buying the old-fashioned matzo,
including, ironically, yet another trend in American consumerism,
the preference for premium products.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some families it's traditional, for others it's
fashionable, and for other people it's a very religious thing to
have,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
