<HEADLINE>
A TALL TALE ON A MAINE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEALS ISLAND, Maine _ Tricia Carver, a 6-foot-tall girls
basketball phenomenon, is more than familiar with the Tall Barney
theory.
</P>
<P>
   A broadshouldered blonde with swimming-pool blue eyes, the
Jonesport-Beals High School senior has a reach that made coaches
from competing high schools throw up their hands in despair.
</P>
<P>
   As the Royalettes advanced toward the state championships this
spring, the island celebrated Carver, the third of three
extraordinarily talented sisters. And a few older relatives _ the
ones steeped in five generations of Beals Island folklore _
silently thanked Carver's nearly 7-foot-tall forebear: Tall Barney
Beal, a legendary 19th-century strongman. Carver has a tolerant
affection for the stories of her great-great-great-grandfather, who
was so strong, according to local lore, that he once killed a horse
by punching it in the head. But she's leery of attributing the
town's athletic record to anything as far-fetched as a giant's gene
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun legend to have. You don't want to dispute it,''
said Carver, 18, from a house still decorated after the
championship win. ``As far as supporting the theory, I don't know
what you could find.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Beals Island, where 10 generations of Beals have made
their living on the sea from the time they were children, it
doesn't take long to find stories of abnormal physical strength _
tales of iron spikes being bent, rocks being lifted for sport, and
motor transmissions being tucked under the arms.
</P>
<P>
   And that mystique of physical prowess has survived in the arena
of high school basketball. Players from Beals, population 700, have
been amazing mainland observers with their strength and toughness
for years, and Jonesport-Beals High School, with its 120 students,
has won nine state championships in boys basketball and three state
championships in girls basketball. Since the early '90s, four women
from Jonesport-Beals have gone on to play Division 1 athletics in
college, an astonishing number for a school of 120.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems incredible that they produce these athletes year
after year after year. You'd think every now and then they'd take a
year off,'' said Rick Amero, who coaches the Monmouth High School's
girls basketball team, and has faced the Royalettes in tournaments.
Said John Holyoke, who has covered the high school basketball
tournament for the Bangor Daily News: ``What they always said is
that they come down to Bangor, and they bring a bunch of men to
play against boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this is still a community that values the kind of
physical strength that is not found in downtown gyms. While
shrugging off the idea that she is a Tall Barney throwback, Carver
brings up the phenomenon of her neighbor, Mitchell Beal, who is
said to have once kicked an 80-pound punching bag so hard that its
chain broke and it flew across the room. Beal, who stands 6-foot-5,
says he is ``nothing like as strong as they say (Tall Barney)
was,'' but tipped his hat to another neighbor, Findy Alley, who was
known during his lifetime for folding 50-cent pieces in half using
two fingers. It isn't unusual on this island, Beal added, for men
to have a ring size of 12 or 14. (``Enormous,'' said a Boston
jeweler, whose typical male client wears a size 9 or 10.)
</P>
<P>
   So, too, with Tall Barney, who was born to an island boatbuilder
in 1836 and grew to such proportions that women hid their best
chairs when they saw him coming, lest he destroy them by sitting
down. Estimates of his height range from 6-foot-7 to over 7 feet;
he slept with his feet sticking out of the window, the story goes,
and when he sat on a chair, his fingertips brushed the floor. For
the most part, Tall Barney folklore centers on heavy things he
lifted. There was the time he lifted a dory, or fishing boat, full
to the rim with clams; there was the time he pushed a wheelbarrow
loaded with a cord of wood. As the story goes, he hoisted two full
barrels of flour under his arms and sauntered down the street. When
he drank, especially in the company of his friend ``Short Barney''
Beal, Tall Barney grew more antic. He is famous for killing a horse
barehanded _ because the horse's owner had angered him, or, in
another rendering, because on a drinking binge in Portland he had
declared that he was going to hit the next thing he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years after the last islanders who knew Tall Barney
died, the only written compilations of the genealogy and folklore
are the work of Velton Peabody, a descendant of Tall Barney's who
left the island in 1965 to become a newspaperman and returned last
year with his accent nearly gone. In his efforts to spread the word
about Tall Barney, Peabody has pointed out that seven of the 13
girls on Jonesport-Beals's championship team this year could trace
their ancestry to Tall Barney. Marcia Beal Brazer, an Ogunquit
filmmaker, is working on a documentary about Tall Barney's
contribution to the school's athletic record.
</P>
<P>
   Avery Kelley's theory is that islanders are so familiar with
their own peculiar qualities that they don't even notice them.
``People here never did realize they was two-three times stronger
than the ordinary man, and it's a hard job to make them believe
it,'' said Kelley, 59, a great-great-grandson of Tall Barney's. He
offers Mitchell Beal as an example. ``He's a monstrous big guy, and
he thinks everybody's as strong as he is and as tall as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But the legends hold less sway for most of the island's
long-term residents, said Colleen Haskell, the high school
principal, who arrives at school many mornings to find 10 boys
playing basketball outside. The more common account here _ where
most houses are flanked by a pile of lobster traps and a basketball
hoop _ has to do with the work ethic of a seafaring community.
Coaches from other schools have long speculated that island players
practiced in hip boots until the season started, so when they
switched to sneakers they could jump higher. Others credit boredom.
Glenn Libby, the girls basketball coach, said when he was a
teenager he and his friends would play ``for two or three hours,
twice a day,'' shoveling snow off the courts in the winter and
playing with gloves on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what you do in the winter in Maine,'' said Haskell. ``And
the winters in Maine are long.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be that, as the seafaring life changes, the Tall Barney
legend has outlived its usefulness. Edward Ives, who taught
folklore at the University of Maine for 44 years, said that many
towns up and down the coast have spun stories about local
``strongmen,'' but that the legends could lose their relevance in a
culture where ``we don't need to be that strong anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Carver, Tricia's father, turned away college basketball
recruiters because all he wanted to do was go to sea. But he, like
many of the island's fishermen, worries that government catch
limits will make fishing into a business that doesn't reward
strength. Already, he said, the boys are more likely to turn on
their computers than compete to see who can lift the biggest rock,
as his friends did when he was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, in those days, strength was one of those things they
measured each other by,'' said Carver, 46. ``Now those things are
done hydraulically.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mitchell Beal, 38, wonders whether his young son _
a copperheaded boy in pajamas _ will live a life that demands the
physical power he will grow into. The strongest man on Beals Island
tapped the side of his head. ``It's all up here now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
