<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCSWEENEY'S SHINES; ATLANTIC TAKES ON BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIANA VERDONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After washing our hands, a friend and I opened the specially
designed carton and removed the 14 booklets that constitute the
2-pound Timothy McSweeney's Issue No. 4. ``If none of the stuff
inside is any good,'' he said as we eyed the lovely and peculiar
covers, ``it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   McSweeney's is tricky to describe, much less pigeonhole. To be
grossly reductive, the writing tends to be smart and funny, hip but
not snide, mostly fiction, essays, and letters. The editor, Dave
Eggers, is author of the memoir ``A Heartbreaking Work of
Staggering Genius,'' and his writing sets the quarterly's tone and
often outshines other contributors. (The booklet titled ``Notes and
Background and Clarifying Charts and Some Complaining,'' is his
doing and is laugh-out-loud good, with, appropriately for this
issue, an author's bill of rights on book design and a memorable
line that reads, ``IF YOU ARE SENDING POETRY: please do not.'')
</P>
<P>
   The boxed set is not only a quiet triumph in concept and design
(even the page numbers look good), it's pretty on the inside. The
range of material is broad and unruly, from a letter on nationalism
to alternate takes on ``The Egg'' by Sherwood Anderson and ``The
Trial'' by Franz Kafka. Twelve of the issue's booklets consist of
just one piece by one author, 11 of whom provided artwork for their
covers _ from professional designs to a child's scrawl.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the set are ``Notes'' and a booklet of ``Shorter
Stories'' by several writers. Amid company that includes Rick
Moody, Haruki Murakami, Lydia Davis, George Saunders, and Sarah
Vowell, the pick of the litter may be Denis Johnson's ``Hellhound
on My Trail,'' a three-part play that springs from a workplace
investigation about a woman, a man, and a proposition involving a
jar of jam. There's not a dull bit of dialogue among six characters
in nearly 70 brisk pages.
</P>
<P>
   Though the issue recently sold out through the Web site
(www.mcsweeneys.org and www.mcsweeneys.net), check there for a list
of vendors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not infrequently, The Atlantic Monthly will run a story that
makes you impatient for the cross-fire and, potentially, some
rearrangement of the truth that will come from letters to the
editor. Such is the case with the May cover story, ``The War
Against Boys,'' by the controversial Christina Hoff Sommers, author
of the 1994 book ``Who Stole Feminism?'' and W. H. Brady Fellow at
the American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers scoffs at the much-publicized notion that girls are
shortchanged in American schools, and presents evidence that
``shows boys, not girls, on the weak side of an education gender
gap.'' Among her conclusions: ``The typical boy is a year and a
half behind the typical girl in reading and writing; he is less
committed to school and less likely to go to college.'' She
maintains that girls participate more than boys do in
extracurricular activities other than sports, and that boys are
more likely to be held back or drop out, become involved in crime,
use alcohol and other drugs, and have a diagnosis of
attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers bases her provocative assertions on data from such
sources as the US Department of Education and the National Center
for Education Statistics. She makes a compelling case for the claim
that boys need more attention in school, but in doing so sounds
just as one-sided as some of the people she criticizes.
</P>
<P>
   In her first paragraph, Sommers suggests that the US women's
soccer team symbolizes ``the spirit of American girls'' and
Columbine High School is an analog for boys, an idea that is sure
to inflame. She reports that in 1997 five times as many boys killed
themselves as girls, while glossing over the fact that
significantly more girls attempt suicide than boys. All of this
makes a reader eager to hear from calmer voices.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Sommers's objections to studies conducted by Harvard's
Carol Gilligan and other researchers are justified (she takes them
to task for flawed methodology, politicized arguments about
``demoralized teenage girls,'' and/or for not making data public),
someone's got explaining to do. But Sommer's tone is irksome, her
language hyperbolic. She refers to the ``manufactured crisis of
diminished girls'' and says that Gilligan's central thesis these
days is ``that boys are being imprisoned by conventional ideas of
masculinity.'' Let the letters roll.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April's MAMM (published 10 times a year and subtitled ``Women,
Cancer and Community'') is a special issue on complementary and
alternative medicine. The opening letter from editor Gwen Darien
refers to a study published in the New England Journal of Medicine
last June showing that 28 percent of Massachusetts women with
early-stage breast cancer used such treatments. Darien writes that
MAMM ``examines that trend with both the skeptic's eye and the
believer's heart'' and says ``chemotherapy saved my life, yoga made
it bearable.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has articles about quacks (illustrated with incredible
ads provided by the Museum of Questionable Medical Devices in
Minneapolis), Chinese medicine, Buddhism, and journal writing. In a
longer story, writer and editor Cynthia L. Cooper talks about
complementary medicines with three providers &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   All three practitioners discuss approaches that can accompany _
not replace _ Western treatment. Webster runs 10-week stress
management groups with cancer patients and says the program's
assessments show ``statistically significant reductions in
depression and anxiety.'' (For MAMM subscription information, call
888-901-6266 or send e-mail to subscription(at)mamm.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-REVERSAL-OF-FORTUNE-2     04-19 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVERSAL-OF-FORTUNE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... was accepted.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terrified to fail and determined to distinguish herself, Murray
studied wherever she could find a place to sit and managed to
complete four years of high school in two, graduating with grades
``in the high 90s,'' Weiner says. Even he was not aware that she
was homeless. ``I knew she stayed at friends' houses a lot. . . .
New York is a very profound and unusual city. The lives of students
are really quite unfathomable here. I know kids who slept on
rooftops. I didn't question it closely. I knew her mother had died
of AIDS, but she didn't say much about her life.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that Murray ``was one of our really smartest kids in
a school full of smart kids. She was obviously driven. I think
persistence is a big part of her success here.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner describes her as ``genteel'' but also sad, yet ``very
personable and funny, and fun-loving in her own way. She is also a
very single-minded person, very intellectual, with a real love of
learning. She knew she needed to go to a very, very good college.
That was her agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Her opportunity came when she was selected as one of 10 top
students at the academy to take a field trip to Boston. ``That's
when she found out about Harvard,'' says Weiner. ``That's when she
had her first ecstatic vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in Harvard Yard, she had a look of pure awe on her
face, Weiner recalls. He says he knew what she was thinking. ``I
just walked over to her and said, `It's very improbable, but still
possible.' In fact, it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials declined to answer specific questions about
Murray's application, but indicate she fell into a particular
category of student the university looks for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at: How will this person contribute to the education
of his or her fellow classmates?'' says William Fitzsimmons, dean
of admissions and financial aid. ``And, based on the record of
accomplishments this person has, what can we guess about what kind
of contributions to society will this person make over his or her
lifetime? Given the cards this person has been dealt, how has this
person been able to maximize his or her opportunities? Has this
person reached out to others, served to stimulate and inspire
others? These are the standards we apply to everyone, and the
standards we applied to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has answered questions about her life's developments so
often her answers sound almost rote by now.
</P>
<P>
   Is she excited about going to Harvard, she is asked over lunch
at a diner in the Bronx. ``I've been to Boston all of a few
hours,'' she says matter-of-factly. ``It seems like a place I could
get used to.''
</P>
<P>
   What does she want for her future?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, to have good people surrounding me whom I love and
who love me back. To live every day to the fullest, cliche as that
is.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a directness, almost a flatness to Murray's responses,
that suggests she is weary of certain aspects of her newfound
celebrity. Indeed, when a student at PS 95 asked if she ever felt
sorry for herself while she was homeless, her answer was an
immediate no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt sorry for myself. That is a useless emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Until she starts school in the fall, she is keeping feverishly
busy. She has an apartment in the Bronx she shares with a friend.
She works as a clerk for The New York Times. She keeps a hectic
schedule of appointments, including going to the dentist for the
first time since she was 9. She sees her father frequently _ ``He
lives in the Bronx and has AIDS, but he's doing very well; his
viral load is undetectable and his T cells are up.'' She sees her
sister occasionally; she lives in the Bronx too, but they don't get
along well, Murray says. She has a boyfriend and a lot of friends
from her homeless days, whom she is helping out with money ``and in
every way I can.'' And she makes frequent appearances at schools
and other venues where she talks about the subjects close to her
heart: the danger of using drugs, the importance of embracing every
day, her disdain for people who have an ``apathy for living.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the manuscript she is working on, a draft of a
book about her life. ``Candice'' gave her the name of her own
literary agent, who has asked to see it. Another agent she met
plans to talk to Jodie Foster about Murray's life as a potential
movie project.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the shifts in her life is not lost on her, but she
is no longer consumed with how strange it is. ``For a long time I
kept saying that this makes no sense. But I think my life has
taught me it makes perfect sense. Everything I've experienced has
taught me that things in life can change in an instant. But this is
that lesson on a positive level, and it seems so gratifying and
exciting at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she says, she would relinquish all the
literary agents and talk shows in the world for just one thing,
something so simple most people take it for granted. ``Sometimes I
go to my friends' houses and hear them call for their mom. Or I am
with my sister and father and see an empty place where my mother
should be. If I could trade what I have now for that, I absolutely
would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
