<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-EASTER-BOS &LR;      04-19 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EASTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESHENING UP THE TRADITIONAL EASTER DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same ingredients seem to find their way onto the spring
holiday table every year, and yet they always seem fresh. Maybe it
has to do with the weather finally warming up, or the family
collecting in one place, or the children spending a morning hunting
for colored eggs. Perhaps it's the ending: strawberries heaped onto
shortcake. After all, cake, berries, and whipped cream are one of
the happiest combinations imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   So you don't need to reinvent the Easter menu each year. But you
can take what you already do and incorporate other ideas. All those
Easter-hunt eggs can find a use, halved and deviled, the yolks
mixed with mayonnaise, hot sauce, and paprika and stuffed back into
the shells. For a main course, rub a butterflied leg of lamb with
French mustard and herbs before roasting it in a hot oven. Pass a
cooling yogurt-mint sauce, slow-roasted onion wedges sprinkled with
balsamic vinegar, and a sheet of thinly sliced, golden brown
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   And then it's shortcake time: billows of whipped cream, lightly
sweetened, sandwiched with berries in a simple butter cake, topped
with more berries. The only thing more satisfying would be curling
up on the couch late at night, polishing off a handful of chocolate
Easter eggs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
DEVILED EGGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mayonnaise or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Generous dash of Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Generous dash of liquid hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon anchovy paste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon good-quality paprika
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Small handful Italian parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Extra paprika (for sprinkling)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Use a straight pin or an open safety pin to poke a very tiny
hole in the rounded end of each egg. Bring a large pan of water to
a boil and use a slotted spoon to lower the eggs into the water.
Move quickly. When all are added, use the spoon to make the eggs
start rotating in a circle. Continue moving them round and round
until the water returns to a boil. Then stir for 1 minute. (This
helps set the yolks in the center of the eggs.)
</P>
<P>
   Start counting from the moment the water returns to a boil. At
exactly 12 minutes, lift the eggs from the water and transfer them
to ice water. Let them sit for 10 minutes or until they are cold.
To hasten this, you can tap the eggs gently on the counter and
remove a strip of the shell from each one. Then return them to
their ice bath until they are cold.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the eggs by tapping them on the counter. Dry them with
paper towels. Halve them horizontally. Scoop the yolks into a bowl.
Cut the tiniest possible slice from the rounded bottoms of the
whites so they sit without rocking.
</P>
<P>
   Mash the yolks with the mayonnaise, Worcestershire sauce, hot
sauce, mustard, anchovy paste, paprika, salt, and pepper. Add more
mayonnaise if the mixture is too thick. Taste for seasoning and
make the mixture spicier if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Use a teaspoon to mound the filling on each egg white. Smooth it
around the edges. Arrange the eggs on a platter. Set a parsley leaf
on 18 of the eggs, decorating clusters of eggs and leaving the
empty ones here and there. Dip the tip of a paring knife into the
paprika and sprinkle a little paprika on one edge of each egg
(including those with parsley). Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
BUTTERFLIED LEG OF LAMB MARINATED IN MUSTARD WITH PROVENCAL HERBS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 leg of lamb (6 to 7 pounds), boned, butterflied, and well
trimmed of fat
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, cut into slivers
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped mixed fresh herbs (rosemary, thyme, oregano,
marjoram)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wipe the lamb with paper towels. Set it boned side up in a large
roasting pan. In several spots, you'll see that the meat is higher
and thicker than the rest of the leg. Use a paring knife to make
1/2-inch horizontal slashes in these thick parts so the meat cooks
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Use the paring knife to make small slits all over the meat, and
insert the garlic slivers into the slits. Rub both sides the with
oil, mustard, herbs, salt, and pepper. Set the meat in the pan fat
side up (there shouldn't be much fat). Cover it tightly with
plastic wrap. Refrigerate for at least a half-day or for as long as
2 days.
</P>
<P>
   Before cooking, let the lamb sit at room temperature for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 425 degrees. Roast the lamb for 15 minutes.
Carefully turn it over and continue roasting for 15 to 25 minutes
or until an instant-read meat thermometer inserted into the
thickest part of the lamb registers 125 to 130 degrees for rare
meat (135 to 145 degrees for medium).
</P>
<P>
   Let the lamb sit in a warm place for 5 minutes. Carve into
slices for serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
YOGURT-MINT SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole-milk or low-fat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated raw onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   Dash of liquid hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil (for drizzling)
</P>
<P>
   3 scallions, chopped (for garnish)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, whisk the yogurt until it is smooth. On a board, with
a blunt knife, mash the crushed garlic with a pinch of salt until
the garlic liquefies. Use a spoon to stir the garlic into the
yogurt. Stir in the onion, mint, and hot sauce. Taste for seasoning
and add more hot sauce if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the yogurt to a bowl, drizzle olive oil on top, and
garnish with scallions. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
SLOW-ROASTED EXTRA SWEET ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 Vidalia, Walla Walla, Sugar Babies, or other extra-sweet
onions
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar (for sprinkling)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil (for sprinkling)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Small handful fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Small handful fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 350 degrees. Have on hand a large shallow baking
dish that is nice enough to go to the table later.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the onions and trim the roots just to discard the dark
ends, but keep the root intact. Cut each onion into 8 wedges,
keeping a piece of root on each one so the wedges hold together.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the onions in the dish, cut sides up. Sprinkle with the
vinegar, oil, salt, and pepper. Cover the dish with foil, shiny
side down. Roast the onions for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the foil, baste the onions with the juices in the pan,
and continue roasting for 40 to 50 minutes or until the edges are
beginning to brown and the onions are meltingly tender.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can make the onions in advance and set them aside.
Just before serving, reheat them in the same oven with the potatoes
and lamb (make sure the baking dish will withstand that high heat)
for 15 minutes or until hot.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Chop together the thyme and parsley. Sprinkle them on
the onions, add more black pepper, and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
POTATO SHEET
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil (for pan and sprinkling)
</P>
<P>
   6 medium Idaho or russet potatoes, peeled and left in cold water
</P>
<P>
   1 half-gallon whole milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have on hand a jellyroll pan that won't buckle. Otherwise, use a
roasting pan. Lightly oil the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 425 degrees. Use a mandoline or other slicing
machine (not a food processor) to cut the potatoes lengthwise into
1/8-inch slices. You can also do this with a long chef's knife.
</P>
<P>
   In a large flameproof casserole, combine the milk with a
half-carton of water. Add plenty of salt and bring the milk to a
boil. Remove the pot from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   As the potatoes are sliced, add them to the milk mixture. When
all are added, return the milk to a boil. Cook the potatoes for 3
minutes or until they are almost tender. Watch them carefully so
they don't fall apart (they cook more later).
</P>
<P>
   Use a wide slotted spatula to lift the potatoes from the cooking
liquid, tap them to drain the excess liquid, and transfer them to
the jellyroll pan. Arrange them overlapping in haphazard layers.
Sprinkle the top with oil, salt, and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the potatoes to the hot oven and roast them for 45
minutes or until they are golden brown on top. Use a wide metal
spatula to transfer them to a warm platter. The potatoes will not
stay together in neat squares, but that's OK. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
STRAWBERRY SHORTCAKE
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes for shortcake call for individual biscuits. This
recipe, from a 30-year-old Pillsbury cookbook, makes a simple,
light biscuit-style cake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the berries and cream:
</P>
<P>
   1 quart strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 heaping tablespoons confectioners' sugar, plus extra for
sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Granulated sugar (for berries)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: Set the oven at 375 degrees. Grease a 9-inch round
cake pan and dust it with flour, tapping out the excess.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, sift together the flour, baking powder, and salt.
Stir in the sugar. Then use a pastry blender to cut the butter into
the flour until the mixture resembles bread crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the milk, eggs, and vanilla. Pour the liquid ingredients
into the flour mixture all at once, and stir only until all the dry
ingredients are moist.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the batter to the prepared pan and spread it evenly.
Bake the cake for 30 minutes or until the top springs back when
pressed with a fingertip.
</P>
<P>
   Let the cake cool in the pan for 15 minutes. Then turn it out
and set it on a rack right side up to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Split the cake horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the cake: Hull the berries and halve them
lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Use a cold bowl and cold beaters to beat the cream until it
almost holds a shape. Add the vanilla and confectioners' sugar and
continue beating until the cream is stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Spread a layer of whipped cream on the bottom half of the cake.
Arrange enough berries, pointed ends facing in, to make one layer.
Spread the berries with another thin layer of cream (you should
have berries and cream left over). Set the top of the cake on the
cream and dust it with confectioners' sugar. Refrigerate the cake
until serving.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the remaining berries into a bowl and sprinkle them with
granulated sugar. Cover and set aside at room temperature. Spoon
the remaining cream into a bowl, cover, and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the cake into wedges and serve it with the extra cream and
berries.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
