<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     04-19 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE TECH ROUT, FUND CHIEF IS STILL BULLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might have expected Ben Hock to be rattled.
</P>
<P>
   It was Friday, the Nasdaq Stock Market was plunging, Hock's
growth fund was plunging with it, and Frank Sinatra was singing
``That's Life'' in the background of the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But Hock, manager of the AIM Global Growth Fund, was taking the
news in stride. A longtime stock market and technology bull, first
at John Hancock Funds, now at AIM in Houston, Hock was in Boston
last week to meet with clients. His fund was up 52 percent last
year; at the close of the market Monday it was down nearly 11
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hock took some time out of his schedule to chat with us about
the market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you still bullish?
</P>
<P>
   A. I am still bullish. Pummeled recently, but still bullish.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you surprised by this dramatic sell-off?
</P>
<P>
   A. You are always surprised by severe movements. We had a luxury
for a time. We had not seen anything like this since 1998, and
things got overextended. We are just letting a little air out of
stocks that probably shouldn't have gotten to such lofty valuations
in the first place. The Nasdaq was up 86 percent last year. That
was a big number, and everyone knew it was a big number.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've always been a tech fan. Do you still own a lot of
technology stocks?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you look at the holy trinity _ technology, communications,
media _ they probably account for more than 40 percent of our
holdings. But remember, they are more than 40 percent of the S&AMP;P
also. That reflects the transformation of the US economy. Where do
you find earnings growth? In technology. And those earnings are
still superb. They may be up 35 percent this quarter. It's also
important to remember that technology spending is global. If you
are in Korea and Germany you have to lower your costs, and that
means more technology. Technology spending begets more technology
spending. Computers are like potato chips. You can't buy just one.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What specifically do you like in the tech sector?
</P>
<P>
   A. We remain extremely excited about the mobile-phone market.
The Europeans are still the leaders there. If you are in Finland
you can take your mobile phone, point it at a soft-drink machine,
and get a Coke. Before long, mobile phones are going to replace all
the date planners and Palm Pilots. Among the big names, we still
like EMC, Cisco, and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How about outside the technology world?
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the unsung stories of this market is that earnings
will be strong in lots of other sectors. We are getting a
broadening out in the market. We love retailers, for example. We
think they are an absolute layup in this market. Their customers
have jobs, incomes are rising, and they can buy cheap goods
overseas. When Kmart's earnings go up 17 percent in one quarter,
this is a very good market for retailers. Other areas that look
attractive are advertising stocks and media stocks. I am not trying
to be Pollyanna-ish, but the basic building blocks look good to me.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Aren't you afraid that Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan will raise rates and spoil the party?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think what Greenspan is trying to do is just put some
insurance into the system, and he would rather do that when times
are good. He has raised rates five times, and he may have two more
rate hikes in him. I think he would like to get out of the way
before the elections. The (consumer price index) was a little
higher on the core rate (Friday), but overall inflation really
hasn't budged much. In the fourth quarter, productivity was so
strong that unit labor costs actually fell. That is unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When you lie awake at night and worry, what do you worry
about?
</P>
<P>
   A. You always worry that you may be too optimistic. Then there
are always wild cards. Could there be a debt crisis? Does Japan
sink back deeper into recession? The Russian situation remains
unstable. Any of those things could occur, but I can't help it if
they do. I can't plan for the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think this sell-off will scare off the average
investor?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't see any evidence of that. In fact, I think the
individual investor has been a net buyer right through this period.
He has been conditioned to step in when the market is down. I think
it would take a prolonged period of bad days to break that
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hock apparently isn't the only one who is still willing to
put his money into technology.
</P>
<P>
   Qauntum Bridge Communications, an Internet infrastructure
company in North Andover, Mass., has raised $102 million in a
third-round financing. The round was led by Texas Pacific Group; a
long list of venture investors participated.
</P>
<P>
   The company is building a system it says is capable of providing
business customers with bandwidth services that are significantly
faster than existing alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
