<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOM-RUGBY-ART-BOS &LR;      04-19 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-RUGBY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ONLY THE TOUGH NEED APPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Halogen lights glinting off the mud puddles of an ugly
cold March night, and the spring cry goes up: ``Blue! Yellow!
Purple! . . . Baaaaall!''
</P>
<P>
   Out of a tangle of bare-skinned legs an oversized loaf of a
football squiggles free, and as it is snatched up, the grunting
confusion turns suddenly to motion and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Chang picks up the ball and runs, bursts through a swarm of
arms, gets tackled high, spins and laterals the ball to Archerbault
running full speed out on the wing. She sprints 10 troubled yards
before a pair of big arms wraps her up and throws her in the mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooof! Baaalll!''
</P>
<P>
   Play is momentarily stopped, instruction rendered as coach Jan
Rutkowski makes a fine point about stringing out the attack, and
with a sharp whistle, the grunting and whacking sound of bodily
collisions continue: The women of the Beantown Rugby Football Club
of Boston are getting ready to take on the world.
</P>
<P>
   This team has a host of enemies to dispatch, including the
Berkeley All-Blues and the Maryland Stingers, on their way to what
they hope will be their seventh national championship in a 10-year
span.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won it since '96,'' says Rutkowski, a former Regis
basketball and soccer standout. ``We want to do it again this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks of indoor training, the first snowfree days of
March bring the Beantowns out to Smith Field across from Harvard
Stadium, where they begin practice every Tuesday and Thursday
night, getting ready for the schedule that takes them to several
cities throughout the country, ultimately to Berkeley, Calif., in
mid-June for the Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   When the Beantowns were established in 1976, women's rugby was
about as rare as women's ice hockey. But, says Beantown assistant
coach Joan Morrissey, the need to find a collegiate fall sport
helped popularize rugby and make it the nation's fastest growing
sport among women.
</P>
<P>
   Full body contact, thrashing tackles, and jarring straightarms
with no pads or helmets, an oversized football to control, and
nonstop sprinting _ thundering sprints with 30 women on two teams _
are the marks of this English sport that is played widely
throughout Europe and the Commonwealth Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the US version _ called ``gridiron'' in countries that
play rugby (``football'') _ is a spinoff from the sport that was
first played in England in the 1850s. Rugby, in turn, had spun off
soccer, and a plaque commemorating the game's origin reads ``With a
fine disregard for the rules of (soccer), he (William Ellis) picked
up the ball and ran with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, when Ellis ran with the ball 150 years ago, he had no
idea that Alex Williams might be upfield waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 10 inches, 195 pounds, with legs that chug like
pistons, Williams, a Watertown native, is captain of the Beantowns.
There is a picture of her on the team Web page breaking past a
Berkeley tackler, running full ahead, a vicious straightarm having
thrown the defender back on her heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game that gets rid of tension,'' says the
consultant turned carpenter who started the rugby team while a
student at Radcliff in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   At 29, Williams still plays the game with passion, stopping in
practice to explain fine points to the younger players. ``I always
want to play rugby to the best of my ability,'' says Williams, who
sees the team like a big family that grows tighter by the year,
``to continue to learn, and to pass on what I know to younger
players whenever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is the very embodiment of the Beantowns. After
windsprints she gets the whole team, 30 or so mudcaked women
breathing hard and buzzing excitedly, into a scrum-like circle for
an inspirational pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel the spirit, going around. Going around. We made a few
mistakes. Let's learn from every mistake we make. Big squeeze.'' At
that, the team presses in tightly for a silent minute, then break
for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the physical intensity,'' says Rutkowski, ``and the
skills to master. We play a finesse game. It's physically rough,
but the players have to learn a lot about finesse. Not just
knocking each other down.''
</P>
<P>
   Widely recognized as one of the top teams in the country, the
Beantown A-side _ top 15 _ has amassed an overall record of 482-32
since 1982, with 6 firsts, 3 seconds, and 5 thirds in National
Championship play. While they maintain a core of veterans, a few
new players are recruited each year from the college ranks, or from
other clubs, such as the Boston Women's Rugby Football Club, who
provide local competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge part of our lives,'' says Alex. ``In college,
you have the college connections, but here the team becomes our
social life and our connections more than just a sport we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women stay at the game for 20 years, and play actively well
into their 30s. At the other end of the spectrum is Jenny von
Knoblauch, an 18-year-old exchange student from Germany who works
out with Beantown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing sport,'' she says. ``You just run run run all
the time. It's a sport where you really do something.''
</P>
<P>
   From doctors, lawyers, teachers, and social workers, the
Beantown women come from all walks, bound by the love for a game so
fresh and young in this country it so far defies the
over-organization that follows so many recreational sports.
</P>
<P>
   When the team travels to play in California, or even Europe, the
opposing players act as hosts to the visitors. ``That way we all
become very unified. We're all friends,'' says Morrissey. ``It
really is like one huge family.''
</P>
<P>
   Says one woman as she kneads her quad muscles with a rolling pin
after practice: ``There's just nothing that anyone here would
rather be doing tonight than be right here, playing rugby. It's the
most addictive thing there is. You start it for a little while, and
pretty soon, it's all you think about, looking ahead to the next
game, the next practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, the nonstop, no-substitution action makes this brand
of rugby nearly as compelling to watch as it is to play. The
Beantowns play weekly through June, then enter the national
tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
