<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TALENT-WAR-ART-BOS &LR;      04-19 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENT-WAR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAMPUS RECRUTING, MONEY TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with the lowest unemployment rate in decades and a
shortage of skilled labor, established brick-and-mortar companies
and upstart Internet firms are waging an intense battle for
recruits on the nation's college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   University counselors say recruiting by dot-com and old-economy
companies began earlier this year and is notable for higher
first-year salary offers. Companies are even making full-time
offers to first-year MBA students to lock in commitments early.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is so intense that one Internet firm, Trilogy
Software of Austin, Texas, placed a full-page ad in a student
newspaper near Cornell University's campus in Ithaca, N.Y., last
month promising an annual base salary of $200,000, plus benefits,
and a new BMW 323-Ci coupe to the top five seniors with technical
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Such offers and the feeling among many young people that
new-economy companies provide the best path to quick riches have
given Internet start-ups a big advantage in the recruiting wars.
But just as it seemed that many established companies were being
left behind, the sharp downturn in technology stocks that began
March 10 and continued last week appears to be realigning the
battlefield. Suddenly, stock options _ the lure many dot-com
companies use to attract talent _ are not as attractive in a
volatile market where paper riches can evaporate in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that prospects may be getting skittish about signing
with Internet companies, old-line firms are pouncing with promises
of high salaries and, perhaps most important, stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past two weeks we have seen a significant upswing in
accepts for our summer hires for full-time work,'' said Harry
Cederbaum, director of US university recruitment for Booz-Allen &AMP;
Hamilton Inc., a New York consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, consulting was a hot area that had its
pick of graduates. But like law firms and brokerage houses,
consulting companies have been hard put to compete in the new
high-tech economy. Now Cederbaum says the pendulum may be starting
to swing back to the traditional professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think students are beginning to reassess the risk'' of
joining start-ups, said Cederbaum, whose firm pays new hires with
an MBA $120,000 to $135,000 to start. ``We thought the year was
going to be tough because of the competition. Instead, it has been
extraordinary.'' He said the firm wanted to hire 120 interns, most
of whom will be offered full-time jobs after the summer, ``and
we've gone beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, employment specialists say that graduating seniors and
MBAs will continue to gravitate to the Internet world, but are
likely to focus on growing dot-com companies that have cleared some
initial hurdles and shown that they can survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of momentum and opportunity among the
better established dot-coms,'' said Wayne E. Cooper, president and
chief executive of New Hampshire-based Kennedy Information, which
tracks the recruitment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people already know that there is a fundamental shift
going on now in our economy, and they know the Internet firms are
the future,'' Copper added. ``So what the dip in technology stocks
will do is make students more discerning.'' He said that marginal
firms will have trouble attracting and keeping talent, but that
``those going to the quality dot-coms will likely tough through
this period because they realize the prospects will be brighter in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rush to hire, Internet firms are bypassing traditional
recruitment strategies and contacting potential candidates
directly, either through the Internet, through the friends of
student interns, or during class presentations and visits.
</P>
<P>
   Brad O'Neill, 28, dropped out of the MBA program at Babson
College last year to join StorageNetworks, an Internet data storage
firm in Waltham, Mass.. After a company official spoke to his
class, O'Neill introduced himself. He was offered a job on the spot
and went to work two days later, first as an intern. He became a
full-time employee in several weeks. He now is responsible for
directing corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who would have graduated this year, said he did not
want to wait ``to be at the center of the world in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Few companies actually offer that opportunity,'' said O'Neill.
``So, if you see that there is a chance, that rare chance, well,
you want to be a part of that, and you want to be part of it
quickly and early on.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato Monaco, 28, will receive an MBA in June from the Amos
Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth College in Hanover, N.H., but
the offers started coming last year. After considerable research,
he chose Bowstreet, an established New Hampshire Internet firm that
develops Web infrastructure for businesses. He received stock
options in the company as part of his compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I would miss a tremendous opportunity if I didn't
accept their job offer,'' Monaco said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nasdaq's recent tumble, he said: ``I think the market
will turn around. I am not concerned that, in terms of my equity,
my position will no longer be valuable. I'm in this for the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by the dot-coms, established old-economy
companies have increased their salaries and benefits in an attempt
to keep pace with the Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Booz-Allen engaged in a bit of
soul-searching. ``We began asking ourselves how to go about
competing against the dot-coms,'' Cederbaum said. ``We know that
the work we're doing is hot. We do e-business with the traditional
analysis, and the ability to teach e-business to traditional
firms.''
</P>
<P>
   When the company evaluated its Web-based competitors, it found
that, in addition to stock options, many were offering an
unstructured entrepreneurial environment that promised increased
mobility and the chance to make a lot of money in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   So, Booz-Allen has made some changes. It now accepts equity in
companies it advises in lieu of cash payments _ stock it then
divides among its young consultants, who are called associates. The
result is that the company is optimistic again about attracting
top-flight talent from colleges and business schools.
</P>
<P>
   But some who track both traditional and Internet consulting
firms say the new-economy businesses have the upper hand. The
old-line firms once hired as many as 35 percent of the best
graduates from the nation's top 10 schools, said Marshall Cooper,
executive editor of Consultants News. Now these students are
flocking to hot Internet consulting firms like Razorfish in New
York, and Viant and Zefer in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the established firms have more business than they can
handle and not enough good people. The campuses, both undergraduate
and graduate, used to be their domain,'' Cooper said. ``But now
there is leakage to the dot-coms, and older consultancies are no
longer in the driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   As the battle between old-line and new-line firms continues, the
main beneficiaries will continue to be college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, we are seeing substantial, sometimes even
spectacular, increases over what employers offered last year,''
said Camille Luckenbaugh, a spokeswoman for the National
Association of Colleges and Employers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Marc Perlman, 22, who will graduate from Cornell in
June with a bachelor's degree in engineering. Anderson Consulting
in New York offered him $54,000 a year to start and a variety of
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But Trilogy Software offered Perlman $69,000 a year, plus a
stock option package that contained 1,200 shares. He accepted and
is amazed by his good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have, in one year, surpassed my dad's salary,'' said
Perlman, whose father is a freelance photographer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
