<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-GRIZZLY-BOS &LR;      04-19 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-GRIZZLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS OPPOSE PLAN TO RELOCATE GRIZZLIES TO THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ When the Yanks started running off with the lynx, no
one paid mind. Canada's got lynx aplenty, so the attitude was: Help
yourself, neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   And when the United States Department of Fish and Wildlife
spirited off entire packs of gray wolves for transplant to
Yellowstone National Park, quite a few Canadians _ ranchers,
especially _ cheered good riddance to critters often despised as a
predatory nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   But an American grab for grizzly bears is getting growls from
Canadian environmental groups and ordinary folk, although prominent
wildlife biologists in the country support the ambitious if
little-noticed plan to reintroduce North America's fiercest land
mammal to Idaho's Bitterroot Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, the Wildlife Service hopes to start capturing small
numbers of grizzlies in the rugged Kootenay region of southeastern
British Columbia. The creatures will be freed in the
Selway-Bitterroot wilderness, a 25,140-square-mile region covering
much of east-central Idaho and extending into Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Activist groups in British Columbia and Alberta are beating the
drums against the scheme. Canada may boast far more grizzlies than
the Lower 48 states, they say _ but that doesn't mean it has bears
to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have this idea of Canada as untrammeled wilderness
just teeming with whatever wildlife gets finished off down there,''
said Michael Sawyer of the Castle-Crown Wilderness Coalition. ``But
we're on a slide toward the grizzly becoming endangered, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the project has taken on an anti-American tone,
with critics complaining that the US treats Canada as a bottomless
reservoir of wild species.
</P>
<P>
   Remarked one provincial environmental official: ``There's
definitely some resentment at the way you people treat our
wilderness as a sort of `Wolves `R' Us.' '' Many of the major
species reintroduction programs undertaken by the US Wildlife
Service rely on animals from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's no question that Canadian grizzlies are
hard-pressed in many of their home ranges these days, especially in
booming Alberta, where logging operations, agriculture, resorts,
roads and an expanding web of busy hiking trails are intruding on
critical bear habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, according to leading wildlife biologists, British
Columbia still possesses such an abundance of the giant beasts _
upwards of 10,000 _ that the removal of a few dozen would not harm
the population. They note that bringing bears to Idaho will mark a
huge leap for a long-range dream of restoring grizzlies to a
1,700-mile corridor stretching from Yukon Territory to Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinary effort to restore grizzlies to a
wilderness where they've been completely wiped out,'' said Stephen
Herrero, professor of environmental science at Alberta's University
of Calgary and one of Canada's foremost bear experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's never been done in North America,'' he said. ``It seems
a good and neighborly use of British Columbia bears.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the project is to revive a species all but eradicated
from the contiguous states. More than 50,000 grizzlies prowled the
American West before the arrival of 19th Century settlers. Today
there are only 1,000 in scattered pockets, mainly in Yellowstone
and Glacier national parks. (An estimated 35,000 grizzlies thrive
in Alaska, but their habitat is so different they are considered
unsuitable for transplant to the high Rockies.)
</P>
<P>
   The last lonely grizzly inhabiting the Bitterroot wilderness was
bagged by a hunter in the mid-1940s, according to the Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Idaho is a historic habitat for grizzly bears, but
there are none left,'' said Johnna Roy, a wildlife biologist with
the Service's Grizzly Bear Recovery project. ``We want to bring
this magnificent species back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Wildlife Service's primary missions is to revive
populations of endangered species _ from wolves to whooping cranes,
grizzlies to black-footed ferrets _ restoring them to their
original habitats where possible.
</P>
<P>
   For example, earlier this month 30 Canadian lynx captured in
Yukon Territory and British Columbia were released in Colorado's
high country, part of a program to restore the cat to its old
American haunts.
</P>
<P>
   The reintroduction programs can be extremely controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, for instance, Rocky Mountain ranchers
have howled bloody murder as Wildlife Service biologists
transplanted hundreds of wolves from Alberta to Wyoming and Idaho,
where they've occasionally preyed on sheep, calves and other
livestock _ and, most alarming to ranchers, foraged boldly into
neighboring states. ``Those Canadian wolves treat this place as one
big lunch counter,'' said Jake Cummins of the Montana Farm Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers and farmers have demanded a wolf slaughter. But a US
Appeals Court ruled this year that the wolf reintroduction program
serves a legitimate ecological purpose, and that the Canadian
wolves must not be molested.
</P>
<P>
   Now similar objections are greeting the proposed grizzly bear
project, which is undergoing final environmental review but seems
likely to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners of Custer County, Idaho recently passed a
resolution condemning the plan and ``authorizing'' the shooting of
any federally-protected grizzlies restored to the region _ although
the local prosecutor conceded the decree is probably illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, grizzlies almost certainly don't represent the
sort of threat to livestock posed by wolves. They are solitary
creatures _ each bear needs roughly 1,000 square miles of territory
in which to ramble _ and they usually keep as far as possible from
civilization. Moreover, 90 percent of their diet consists of
berries, bulbs, pine nuts, insects, roots and grasses. When they
eat meat, it's most likely to be carrion, usually dead fish or elk.
</P>
<P>
   But if sheep and cattle can relax, hikers and hunters will have
to tread a bit more warily into the Bitterroots if the grizzly is
restored.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, griz can be grouchy on their home ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real concern is for human safety,'' said biologist Roy.
``When grizzlies come back, humans are going to have to stop
thinking of themselves as Number 1 in the forest,'' she said in an
interview from Idaho. ``That means practicing some precautions.
Like keeping clean campsites _ garbage attracts bears _ and hanging
their (hunting) kill out of reach. And not trying to take snapshots
of that big female with her cute cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Service's plan is to loose five grizzlies a year
into remoter parts of the region over five years, starting in 2001.
This seed stock of 25 bears should grow to an optimum population of
280 animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very long-term program,'' Roy said. ``We are looking at
50- to 110 years to reach that population level.''
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies take their name from the silver-tipped hairs
protruding from their shaggy brown coats. Males tip the scales at
600 pounds while females hardly qualify as petite, reaching 350
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bears from southeastern British Columbia are ideal for the
project because their habitat is most similar to conditions found
in the Bitterroot region. But some Canadians fret that their bears
will only be hauled off to their doom, claiming they will likely
fall prey to trigger-happy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much of a Wild West attitude down there, too many
guns,'' said Evelyn Kirkaldy of British Columbia's People's Action
for Threatened Habitat. ``The Americans killed out their own
grizzlies, and now they want ours. So of course we're alarmed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
