<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FINDING-KIDD-ART-OS &LR;      04-19 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINDING-KIDD-ART-OS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PASSION FOR PIRATES BRINGS PAIR TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN, Mass. _ On a February night this past winter, an
estimated 78 million households tuned their televisions to the
Discovery Channel to hear Barry Clifford, bedecked in scuba diving
gear, break the water's surface of a small harbor off East Africa
and announce: ``Definitely, we have a big wreck here.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the show, everyone pretty much had concluded they
had the wreck of the infamous pirate William Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras had missed a conversation the swash-buckling
Clifford had had a few months earlier with his 17-year associate,
Kenneth Kinkor, a somewhat gangly, publicity-shy historian who has
spent a lifetime researching pirate culture.
</P>
<P>
   Both men recall the exchange went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Clifford: ``Ken, just how sure are you I'll find Kidd's ship?''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkor: ``Pretty darned sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford: ``I'm leading a major television crew 13,000 miles
around the world to a place at the left turn to nowhere. Ken, don't
embarrass me. Give me the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkor: ``Ninety-eight percent.''
</P>
<P>
   With such encouragement, Clifford went the distance and
eventually got to tell the world he believes he has found the
flagship of Kidd _ a man with Boston roots, no less. A confirmation
trip is scheduled shortly. Meanwhile, Kinkor, 46, went back to his
desk in a small, unkempt office at the end of Macmillan Wharf here.
No doubt he lit a pipe, opened some books, consulted some charts,
and pondered the next pirate mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one more example of how even an Iowa boy can quietly
tangle with the ghosts of history's saltiest seagoing legends,
emerge successful _ and, by choice, remain almost invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I call myself a piratetologist? Yes, I suppose I do. I like
the term. It has a counterelitist ring to it, much like the people
I study,'' Kinkor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional historians are like real estate agents; they
focus on the prominent features _ the kitchens and living spaces of
history,'' he said. ``I like like the dusty, musty crawl spaces
tunneled by the social dissidents who never wrote the books, who
never made the speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   He was reared in Calmar, Iowa (pop. 900), one of five children
raised on the salary of a rural letter carrier. Mom's name is
Clementine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago, I stumbled across a 25-cent book at a sidewalk
sale that had once belonged to the DeCorah County Library,'' she
recalled during a telephone interview. ``It was Howard Pyle's `Book
of Pirates.' ``On the inside cover where borrowers had signed their
names was the name of my son. Two dozen times.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinkor was reared on the magic of pirate stories read aloud.
Pirates were everywhere: on the curtains, on his wall paper, and
eventually a part of his master's thesis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Kinkor was midway through research at Illinois State
University on Palgrave Williams, a Rhode Island-born pirate of some
disrepute, when a television interview caught his eye.
</P>
<P>
   A guy named Barry Clifford from Cape Cod was saying he had found
the 1717-wreck of the pirate ship Whydah just off the Cape
shoreline. Kinkor knew that Sam Bellamy, the Whydah's captain, was
a thieving good friend of Palgrave Williams. Perhaps Clifford would
want to know something about it?
</P>
<P>
   Clifford, as it turned out, had gotten a little ahead of himself
(not the first or last time), because he would not actually find
the Whydah until the following year.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Kinkor had already shelved the thesis, quit graduate
school, moved to Cape Cod, and become Clifford's right-hand man,
conserving and scrutinizing artifacts from the wreck, and becoming
ever more awed by the democracy and racial tolerance practiced
aboard pirate ships. The Clifford/Kinkor association persists to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkor is acting director of the Whydah Museum here, where
Clifford keeps an apartment upstairs. Clifford, a divorced father
of grown children, has turned adventure into a career and travels
the world exploring shipwrecks. Kinkor travels in a beat-up 1984
Honda Civic from Provincetown to his Eastham home daily. Last
autumn, he and his wife stretched the limits with a drive to
southern Maine. Otherwise he travels in books.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford is intimate, convincing, boyishly handsome, and
enthusiastic when a camera turns on. Kinkor turns the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, theirs is an association based on the principle that
opposites attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the brains,'' Clifford said the other day. It seemed rude
to ask what that made Clifford. Down moments have not eluded the
duo; failing to find some Boston Tea Party chests, and locating the
remnants of an English king's wardrobe in a Scottish lake, are two.
One thing is certain: They know how to have fun, and somehow call
it work.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ritchie, a biographer of Captain Kidd and the director of
research at the Huntington Library in San Marino, Calif., had this
to say about Kinkor: ``He's the guy who keeps Clifford's show on
the road. And he really knows his stuff,'' which includes facts
about a pirate that has become the stuff of legends.
</P>
<P>
   In 1697, Kidd ditched his flagship Adventure in the harbor of
Saint Marie, an island near Madagascar off the east coast of
Africa. Quality control had eluded Kidd for the entire voyage, his
crew _ undisciplined from the start _ was sick, hungry, frustrated
by the lack of spoils, and mutinous. He also had a leaking boat.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his crew left him to join another pirate. So Kidd ran
the Adventure up on a shoal, burned it to the waterline to salvage
what metal parts he could from the rigging, then bartered and
schmoozed his way back to the American colonies where he owned a
large house in New York City and, by today's standards, a condo in
Boston. It was in Boston that he was arrested for piracy.
</P>
<P>
   As Ritchie notes in ``Captain Kidd,'' a 300-page biography of
the pirate, Governor Richard Bellomont of Massachusetts could have
greeted the pirate with a handshake because the governor was an
investor in Kidd's plundering business. Instead, Bellomont greeted
him with irons. The governor had done the math and figured out that
he would get more for the reward than his portion of Kidd's assets.
So Kidd was shipped off to London and, in 1701 at the age of 56
years, hanged for piracy _ twice. The rope broke on the first
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, Kinkor was researching the meanderings of
another pirate working the Madagascar neighborhood when he received
from a London archivist a copy of a curious document. It was a
lengthy, handwritten deposition by one Theophilus Turner who said
that in Saint Marie harbor ``there was likewise bottom of the
Adventure Galley in which Capt. Kidd sailed from New Yorke...''
</P>
<P>
   Piecing this reference together with facts culled from other
documents, Kinkor was able to lead Clifford to a section of a shoal
where he knew they would find the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The Adventure, which could also be rowed, was British-made. The
type of wood and hardware found by Clifford suggests he has the
right ship. The value of the find lies in artifacts that might
answer a few of the many questions historians have about pirate
life.
</P>
<P>
   It is conservatively estimated that 5,000 pirates plundered
trade in the early 18th century, a substantial force considering
the entire British Navy was roughly 15,000 strong at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pirate culture is poorly understood, yet what we do know
is often more interesting that romantic fiction,'' said Marcus
Rediker, a social historian at the University of Pittsburgh who has
written extensively about pirate culture.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Kinkor was captivated by the tales of buried bounty.
His quest now?
</P>
<P>
   ``A genuine pirate log book,'' he said without hesitation.
Because for Ken Kinkor, the most valuable treasure lies in the
written word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-19 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING AGGRESSIVELY, CUTTING RISK MAY ALLOW RETIREMENT AT 55 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My company's 401(k) plan is restricted to the four funds I
hold; I contribute 12 percent of my annual income. What suggestions
would you have for my allocation, and at what age could I retire
comfortably if I assume that I can live on 70 percent of my
preretirement income? In addition, I will receive an after-tax
bonus of $43,000, which I would like to earmark for a home purchase
in the next five years. What do you think of the alternatives for
investing such a sum? I am fairly risk tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   D.D., Burlington, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a good week to get a hindsight view of risk in a
stock portfolio. For the week ended last Friday, the funds you are
using behaved about as you might expect, with Fidelity Growth and
Income losing 9.5 percent, Fidelity Magellan losing 12.1 percent,
and Fidelity Aggressive Growth falling a sickening 26.2 percent.
Fidelity Diversified International was off only 6.3 percent. But as
of Monday, it seemed that overseas markets were catching up, or
down, with Wall Street. Of the four funds, the only one with a
positive year-to-date return is Fidelity Growth and Income, up 3.8
percent. The largest loss so far in 2000 was 17.9 percent, for
Fidelity Aggressive Growth.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention how your contributions have been allocated,
but given the balances in the funds, it's not likely that they are
divided evenly. I would go with 32.5 percent each in Magellan and
Growth and Income, both large-cap blend funds. I'd put 20 percent
in Diversified International and 15 percent in Aggressive Growth.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest the relatively minor position in Aggressive Growth not
because it isn't a strong fund within its category, but because it
seems to me that the managers of funds in this category tend to
feel that more or less by charter they are instructed to take heavy
short-term risks, which can result in mediocre long-term results.
Funds with more moderate objectives tend to out-produce in the long
run, and both Fidelity Magellan and Fidelity Growth and Income fall
into this category and represent excellent positions that can be
viewed as core holdings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the money that will likely be used for a home down
payment, even though you feel you can assume some risk, this is a
short-term savings project, and I would stay within traditional
short-term investment vehicles. The best rate on a one-year CD is
7.05 percent, and that's where I would go with that money.
</P>
<P>
   As for when you can retire, it's really a question of how much
you earn and save, and particularly how much bonus money you save.
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin with what you'll need. If we adjust a $77,000
current cost of living for an estimated 3.5 percent inflation rate,
you would need $148,032 a year at age 50, $175,816 at age 55,
$208,814 at 60, and $248,006 at 65.
</P>
<P>
   If you save $1,100 a month and the portfolio averages 10 percent
annual growth, the accumulations would be $1,221,412, 2,095,145,
3,531,700, and $5,700119, respectively. Based on those figures, the
target would probably fall somewhere between ages 60 and 65.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably your earnings will increase steadily during that
period, and if you continue to save 12 percent rather than a flat
$1,100 a month, the growth would speed up. And if you were to save
more than 12 percent of your bonuses after you achieve your real
estate goal, the accounts would grow even faster.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to follow such a course and achieve good earnings
increases and substantial bonuses, you could probably retire
between 55 and 60. Remember, when making these calculations you
want a substantial amount of money beyond what you will need to
produce an income stream, so you can invest money to protect you
against inflation later in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am self-employed social as a worker and try to contribute
the maximum to my SEP-IRA. My income isn't likely to go up greatly
in the future. I deposit money for the SEP-IRA into a credit union
account each week; every six to eight weeks I roll the accumulation
over into my funds. I have an $816 monthly mortgage payment, and
each month I pay $900 against the mortgage account. I do not have
other assets to speak of and am comfortable with my current level
of income. Are my investments sound? Am I investing enough? I don't
have dreams of being rich; I just want to save enough to live
comfortably in retirement, probably around age 65.
</P>
<P>
   D.B., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since you don't specify how much you are using to live on
now, I'm not sure how your retirement income is likely to compare.
If you continue saving at the current level and achieve average 10
percent annual investment gains, you would accumulate $1,034,590 by
age 65. If you then adjust that for an estimated 3.5 percent
inflation, it would be the equivalent of a little more than
$381,000 in today's money. It would be sufficient to provide an
income stream of $24,765 a year, based on an assumed 6.5 percent
yield from a fixed-income portfolio. If you combine such an income
stream with whatever Social Security benefits you can anticipate,
and assume a little additional growth, albeit modest, based on
higher future earnings, you should be in a fairly good situation.
</P>
<P>
   The big missing element here is the inflation that's likely to
occur after you retire. You should have some additional funds
stashed away in growth securities to provide a buffer. Two
suggestions: Plunge the lion's share of any unexpected funds you
may come across into a supplemental retirement savings plan. Or,
once your mortgage is paid off, divert what would have gone to
mortgage payments to that supplemental savings program.
</P>
<P>
   As for your portfolio, the funds are solid enough, and you have
touched the right bases. But I would be more comfortable if one of
the positions _ probably Citizens Index _ had a dominant, or core,
position. Moreover, both of the funds that would be most logical
for this position, Citizens Index and Alliance Premier Growth, are
a little too venturesome to be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   So I suggest you add a fund with a portfolio in the large-cap
blend arena, which you could eventually build to represent about 40
percent of the portfolio. You could then consign 40 percent of your
future investments to that fund, dividing the balance evenly among
the remaining holdings. My choice for the core position would be a
fund such as Vanguard Index 500, which doesn't have the
growth-oriented stance of Citizens investors. (It doesn't have
Citizens' focus on socially responsible holdings, either.)
</P>
<P>
   If you do build a supplemental retirement account, I would
suggest a solid and well-managed health care fund, such as a
Fidelity or Vanguard offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: Here's a pep rally for retirement investors:
</P>
<P>
   After the horrors of last week, I'll bet a lot of you are
looking at your losses and wondering where this is getting you. Do
not despair, and make no hasty moves. Stock-market plunges are
inevitable, especially after a boom such as we have had in the past
five years or so. This, too, will pass.
</P>
<P>
   The critical thing is to have the stamina and the courage of
your convictions to keep stoking the fires. This is precisely the
season that makes the dollar-cost-averaging strategy work, and any
retirement plan is basically a dollar-cost-averaging plan, whether
you are putting $166 a month into an IRA or simply plunking down
$2,000 a year. In markets such as the current one, those regular
contributions will buy securities at lower prices, thereby bringing
your overall average cost down.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who get the willies and skip their contributions
because of worries about the market _ or who switch from stock
investments to CDs, bonds or other instruments _ will defeat the
dollar-cost-averaging plan at the very hour when it is designed to
serve them best. If you have an investment showing a year-to-date
loss of 20 percent or worse _ and there are plenty of them out
there _ it's tough to cut the check that puts still more money into
that holding. But if you're truly investing for the long term, it
is critical that you do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
