u s BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-19 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPING KNIGHT'S END ISN'T A DARK TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's say a man chooses to defend Bob Knight. Is that something
like attempting to put in a good word for typhoid fever?
</P>
<P>
   You can't defend Knight, anyway. He wouldn't want you to. He'd
say he can take care of his own (censored) self, and he sure
doesn't need any (naughty word) help from the likes of you. He'd
say that his critics can kiss his (body area).
</P>
<P>
   He's in trouble. Have you heard? The people who want his silvery
head on a platter believe they have the so-called smoking gun in
the form of a videotape that shows him placing one hand on the
throat of an Indiana basketball player during a practice. Neil
Reed, whose allegations of physical abuse while he was an Indiana
player have triggered this latest Knight brouhaha, says the player
is him. It really doesn't matter. It's a player, and most people
are of the opinion that a coach who gets physical with a player is
crossing a very dangerous line.
</P>
<P>
   Knight is one of the great larger-than-life sports figures of
our time. People with very little knowledge about any other aspect
of college basketball have an acquaintanceship with the Bob Knight
persona. In their minds, Bob Knight is a connotation. It's a lot
like George Steinbrenner. Just as someone might be able to tell you
that this Steinbrenner fellow is an ogre who fires people with
regularity _ could any other comparable ownership figure be so
readily parodied, as Steinbrenner was on ``Seinfeld?'' _ so, too
might someone be able to tell you that there is this basketball
coach who had some kind of a run-in with the police in, where was
it, Puerto Rico, and didn't he throw a chair at someone once upon a
time? He may or may not be the best college coach of all time, but
he surely is the most infamous.
</P>
<P>
   He has manifested many behavioral improprieties that surely
would have brought down others, and he almost undoubtedly assumes
he will survive the latest crisis, but this time he may be wrong.
It is very possible that Knight will not coach another game at
Indiana. That would be sad. A man this talented should not go out
in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Knight is not an ogre. He is capable of great kindnesses and
charitable acts, and he can be a very charming companion. I can
bear personal witness to one act of extraordinary professional
compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who have found in him things to admire, I
always have worried that his career might end in what loosely could
be termed a ``Woody Hayes'' incident. He has been unaccountable for
so long, dating back to his six years at West Point, and he is
quite incapable of conciliation. He does not welcome any challenge
to his authority. He is certainly not good at apology.
</P>
<P>
   He always makes sense to himself, if not to everyone else.
People assume it is the wins and losses that most matter, and it is
an article of faith among those who know him that he would like to
coach long enough to pass Dean Smith as the winningest coach in
college history. But winning is not everything to Knight. Playing
the game properly is his prime interest. No other coach has spent
more time lamenting his own team's poor winning performances or
praising a defeated foe's gallant losing efforts. He always
believed that a team in possession of some talent would, if it
played the game correctly, win its allotted share of games. What
offends him are thoughtless displays, whether by his own team or
the referees, whom he always has held to a high standard.
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies in how he manifests his anger. For a man who
successfully has instilled life-skill virtues in three generations
of players, he has very little self-control. He is a bully, and a
rather vulgar one at that. He has an ``Animal House'' sense of
humor. It's all under the guise of ``trying to make them better
players,'' and, by extension, better people, but times have changed
and Knight has not. The public doesn't tolerate boorishness the way
it used to, even in Indiana, where basketball is a religion. Once
upon a time, Knight could do anything he wanted and still be secure
in the knowledge that the people of Indiana loved him. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis Star ran a poll a few weeks ago asking whether
Knight should remain as coach. A slight majority said no. We're
talking sea change here. A few years ago he would have had an 80
percent approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that the Hoosiers last won a national title in
1987 and last reached the Final Four in 1992? Well, sure. But the
reason people believe they haven't won big when it matters lately
is that Knight's ways don't work with modern kids. People grumble
about the new IU pattern in which the team annually gets off to a
fast start, only to deteriorate completely during the NCAA
tournament, worn out by the pressure of daily life with Knight.
Since he is incapable of change, they now believe he must go.
</P>
<P>
   Were Knight to plead for his job, citing his impressive
graduation rate and the fact that NCAA investigators don't even
know the route to Bloomington before even mentioning his three NCAA
titles, he'd be allowed to coach long enough to catch Smith and
Adolph Rupp combined. But we all know that Knight would never, ever
do that. He has done it his way, without the slightest
interference, for 34 years. They indulged him at West Point and
they have been indulging him at Indiana since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   If he quits now, it will be possible to save his reputation. He
has served the game of basketball honorably. He will be remembered
as the three-time national championship coach whose better teams
were joys to watch. He will be remembered as the ultra-successful
coach who never once had an NCAA investigator darken his door.
</P>
<P>
   But if he digs in, the end, whenever it does come, will be ugly.
He will be remembered as the cop-resisting, chair-throwing,
fan-stuffing, toilet paper-waving, throat-grabbing wildman who
lacked the personal discipline he demanded of others. If there is
any person on this earth to whom he listens, that person should
speak up now. He must be persuaded to retire with some degree of
dignity.
</P>
<P>
   In this other distasteful scenario, the perceived evil he
represents will live long after him, while the great amount of good
he has performed sadly will be interred with his bones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
