<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN WOMEN WILL FIND MUCH TO ADMIRE IN BRITISH CALENDAR  
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That hot calendar featuring the British club women wearing
little but pearls and pleasant smiles is to be in American stores
for Mother's Day. The calendar is obviously timed as the perfect
gift for the woman who has everything and wishes she had a little
less.
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies of Rylstone (a 19-month calendar starting with June)
will likely be as much of a smash hit here as it's been in England,
where a group of village friends came up with a unique way to raise
money for leukemia research. Their bravado, along with their ripe
bodies, has made them overnight sensations.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a movie about them in the works.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the start of something big. And I mean that in the
most fleshy of terms. I've been corresponding with Christine Clancy
in Skipton, England, who is ``Miss September'' she holds a teapot
to her bosom in her photo _ and agrees women seem to ``rather
identify with us rather than 6-foot-tall willowy models.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her friends had a great time shooting the calendar with
lots of laughs and several glasses of wine. They gathered ``round
in dressing gowns'' and ``dropped the gown when the photographer (a
husband of one in the group) was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine was shyer than some about disrobing, but reminded
herself it was for charity and ``just took a deep breath and got on
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A display of unadorned, gravity-sensitive bodies is timely not
only for Mother's Day but for the approach of summer, a definite
low self-esteem season for many women. As we get into the tank-top
months the average female needs all the encouragement she can get
to put on a brave front. The sun teases us to strip down and run
free, and the ego says, ``Please don't, at least not until you do
something about those arms and thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies of Rylstone are past that. So is actress Kathleen
Turner, now appearing naked, at least for a minute or so, in her
celebrated role as Mrs. Robinson in the stage version of ``The
Graduate.'' One critic called her Junoesque, which is a lovely way
of saying that Ms. Turner is bigger than a breadbox.
</P>
<P>
   There are more proud moments to come. NOW has declared Sept. 20
Love Your Body Day, when it asks consumers to talk back to media
and advertisers who create unhealthy and self-destructive images
for women and girls. Consider who makes money on your feeling bad
about yourself, says NOW. I like that a feminist organization is
part of the battle, since some purists think it's beneath
independent women to worry about their looks. As if Madeleine
Albright doesn't have photo op angst.
</P>
<P>
   You can't live in this culture and not feel self-conscious about
being imperfect. My friend Sissy in Los Angeles is looking for a
place she can move to where it will feel OK to wear sleeveless
dresses in the summer and not worry about her arms.
</P>
<P>
   We need all the inspiration we can get. Ginger is a longtime San
Francisco Bay Area artist model in a short, chunky, generous body
whose girth and spirit are currently celebrated in a show at a
Santa Rosa gallery. Ginger wears not much more than a red glove in
some of her portraits and says women are always coming up to her
and thanking her for being so unabashed about her body.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger knows by flaunting her flesh she gives other women a
boost of confidence in their own. ``It's the least we women can do
for each other,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Now pull up those spaghetti straps and get on with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
