 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Easter Brunch Is a Snap With Featherbed Eggs  By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Easter held great charm for me when I was a child,
and it still does. I'm no longer hunting for those hidden Easter
eggs that were so exciting to find when I was 5 or 6 years old.
This was in the late '20s when everyone in our neighborhood watched
their pennies, literally.
<P>
   Our Easter eggs were pink, colored in beet juice, and
pink-colored eggs (shells removed) often would be the centerpiece,
piled on a bed of lettuces, for the Easter dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Baked ham, candied pineapple, yams, frozen peas and cake were
the ritual Easter dinner. When my Italian grandmother and mother
bought their first bag of frozen peas, they cooked them and
absolutely loved them. My grandmother exclaimed, ``I'll never have
to shell another pea,'' and my mother said, ``Frozen peas are
greener than God made them.''
</P>
<P>
   If you like to celebrate Easter around your own table, invite
your family and friends to share a late brunch. Featherbed Eggs,
slices of ham and a bowl of fresh sliced fruit makes a very simple,
but pleasing Easter celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Featherbed Eggs must be made the night before you plan to bake
and serve them, so you have no last minute preparations. Cut up the
fruit early and serve cold slices of ham, or warm the slices while
finishing the Featherbed Eggs in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FEATHERBED EGGS
</P>
<P>
   You can double or triple this recipe if you have more than four
sharing Easter brunch.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 slices white bread
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups grated sharp cheddar, Gouda, provolone or Monterey
Jack cheese, or a combination
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Butter the sides and bottom of a 9 x 13-inch baking dish.
Arrange the slices of bread in the dish, trimming the edges, if
necessary. Sprinkle the bread with a little salt and pepper.
Sprinkle the grated cheese evenly over the bread.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the milk and eggs in a bowl and briskly stir until the
mixture is all one color and completey blended. Pour the milk
mixture over the bread and cheese. Cover and refrigerate for at
least 6 hours, or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Baking the Featherbed Eggs:  &LR; Because the dish will be chilled
when you are ready to bake it, start it in a cold oven and turn the
thermostat to 350 degrees. Bake for 1 hour, or until the bread
custard is puffy and lightly golden. Check at 45 minutes, in case
your oven is a little hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with ham and fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 450 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 26 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (14 g saturated), 373 mg cholesterol, 624
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
