 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: Hard-Cooking Eggs   By Noel Advincula  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When hard-cooking eggs, overcooking is one of the
most common mistakes. The result can be rubbery egg whites, chalky
yolks, or an undesirable dark greenish sulfur-smelling halo
surrounding the yolk.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no way to see inside an egg and a thermometer certainly
can't be inserted to test for doneness. Therefore, cooks must use
precise boiling procedures and cooking times to come up with tender
egg whites and moist, golden yolks.
</P>
<P>
   We tried three methods for hard-cooking eggs. First, we immersed
a single layer of eggs in a medium saucepan in enough cold water to
cover the eggs by an inch. The eggs were brought to a rolling boil
and cooked for eight minutes. For the second trial, we used a
slotted spoon to carefully place the eggs in a saucepan of boiling
water using the same amount of water as in the first test. The
water temperature lowered when the eggs were put in, but then
returned to a rolling boil. We cooked the eggs for 12 minutes after
they were put into the water.
</P>
<P>
   In the third method, we immersed the eggs in cold water and
brought the saucepan to a boil. We covered the saucepan and removed
it from the heat, set it aside and allowed the eggs to cook by
residual heat for 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both the first and second methods produced good results; the egg
whites were tender and the yolks were creamy and moist with no
green tinge. The results were similar for the third test _ evenly
cooked, creamy yolks and perfectly tender egg whites. Because the
first test took only eight minutes and yielded good results, we
concluded that it is the best way to cook the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we tested different methods to crack and peel eggs. We
first tried submerging the eggs in icy cold water for one minute
after removing them from the saucepan. They were then taken out of
the water, cracked, peeled and returned to the water.
</P>
<P>
   The second batch of eggs was transferred to a bowl and left to
cool in the refrigerator for five minutes, then cracked and peeled.
For the third test, we took the pot off the heat and left the eggs
immersed in the cooking water for another 20 minutes, then cracked
and peeled them.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, another batch of eggs was transferred to a colander
immediately after cooking and cracked and peeled under cold running
water.
</P>
<P>
   All of the eggs peeled easily. The only difference was that the
last test took the least amount of time. If you plan on storing the
eggs, transferring them directly to the refrigerator has the same
cooling effect as running them under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we tested freshly purchased eggs against week-old eggs
and cooked both batches the same way. The fresh eggs were harder to
peel under cold running water because the air pocket under the
shell is smaller than in older eggs. But this was resolved by using
a pin to prick a hole at the wider end of the egg before boiling.
The overall appearance and taste was the same.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hard-cook eggs by immersing placing them in a single layer in a
medium saucepan and adding enough cold water to cover by 1 inch.
Bring the water to a rolling boil and cook the eggs for eight
minutes. Remove them from the heat. Drain and rinse the eggs. Crack
and peel them under cold running water.
</P>
<P>
   It is best to use eggs that are a few days to a week old to
ensure easy peeling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
