<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Versatile and Nutritious, the Egg Is Perfect 
 Any Time   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When I think I don't have anything at home to
cook, I usually can find at least a few eggs. Excavating further
into the dark corners of the fridge for a half-empty can of beans,
crusty tortillas and a green-around-the-edges hunk of cheese, I
soon discover that a slap-dash version of huevos rancheros can be
one of the best things going.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides their general convenience, eggs are a very quick source
of protein. And they don't always have to be a part of a greasy,
potato-laden brunch concoction (not that I'm against that kind of
thing).
</P>
<P>
   For example, this week's Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, Japanese Egg Drop
Soup, is a light vegetarian dish with the nurturing flavors of
ginger and honey. Though most Japanese egg drop soup recipes call
for dashi, a stock flavored with dried fish and seaweed, I chose to
use miso because it is more readily available.
</P>
<P>
   Note that the medium-firm tofu in this recipe is a little wobbly
when you try to cut it, but it has a lovely texture next to the
delicate swirls of egg.
</P>
<P>
   In the Spaghetti alla Carbonara With Spring Peas, egg yolks form
the base of a thin sauce. A bit of shaved Parmesan, pecorino and
pancetta complement the fresh egg flavor, and fresh peas add
sweetness and a dash of green. For a dish this simple, freshly
ground pepper is a must.
</P>
<P>
   In the Now &AMP; Later recipe, a quiche with leeks and potatoes and
creme fraiche helps to create a luscious, thick custard. However,
there isn't too much cheese, so the richness isn't overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe makes three pies, so you can easily stash a couple in
the freezer. Then you don't have to worry when, heaven forbid, you
don't even have eggs in the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE EGG DROP SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   6 cups white miso soup, prepared according to package
instructions (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1-inch piece ginger
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces medium-firm tofu
</P>
<P>
   2 handfuls washed baby spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Lightly beat the eggs in a small bowl; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the miso and the honey in a medium saucepan and bring to
a simmer. Peel the ginger and place it in a garlic press. Squeeze
out the ginger juice into the broth.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the tofu into small cubes.
</P>
<P>
   When you are ready to serve the soup, bring the stock to a boil
and add the spinach to wilt. Add the tofu.
</P>
<P>
   Return the stock to a boil, then remove from heat. Using a
chopstick, gently stir the stock in a circular motion in one
direction. Add the egg in a thin stream and stir in the other
direction to create egg swirls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; To make the miso soup, I recommend using Westbrae
Natural's Mellow White Miso, a soup base of fermented soybean
paste, which you can find in the refrigerated ``natural foods''
section of most supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 140 calories, &LR;   &LR; 11 g protein, 11 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 7 g fat (1 g saturated), 105 mg cholesterol, 812 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   SPAGHETTI ALLA CARBONARA WITH SPRING PEAS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese + more for garnish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated pecorino cheese + more for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces thinly sliced pancetta (about 6 slices)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound spring peas
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning preparation, put a large pot of salted water on
to boil for the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Place the egg yolks in a large bowl and beat lightly. Add the
cream. Stir in the Parmesan, pecorino and a few grindings of
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pancetta into small dice. Shell the peas.
</P>
<P>
   Begin cooking the pasta according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Saute the pancetta in a medium saucepan until just crisp, 5
minutes. Remove from pan with a slotted spoon and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in the same pan; add the peas and saute until
just warmed through, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the pasta is done, drain it and add it immediately to the
bowl with the egg mixture. Toss it quickly so the eggs heat through
but do not cook. Stir in the pancetta and peas.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a sprinkle of the two cheeses and more freshly ground
pepper. Season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Editor's note: According to some studies, uncooked eggs may &LR; 
 &LR; not be safe since, in rare instances, they may carry &LR; 
 &LR; salmonella. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 714 calories, &LR;   &LR; 26 g protein, 89 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (13 g saturated), 266 mg cholesterol, 367
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   QUICHE WITH CREME FRAICHE, LEEKS &AMP; POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   To freeze, cool completely then wrap in aluminum foil. Defrost
at room temperature (defrosting in a microwave will make the crust
soggy), then reheat in a 350-degree-oven for about 10 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 (9-inch) prepared pie shells
</P>
<P>
   1 pound leeks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds medium-size red potatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch white pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Gruyere (1 cup shredded and packed)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Defrost the pie shells according to package directions. Line
with parchment paper or aluminum foil and fill with pastry weights
or dried beans. Bake until golden, about 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the leeks in half lengthwise and rinse under cold running
water to remove all grit between the leaves. Thinly slice the white
and light green parts.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large skillet over medium-low heat. Add the
leeks and saute until very tender, about 10 to 15 minutes. Season
with salt and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut in half. Cook in a saucepan of salted
water until tender when pierced with the tip of a sharp knife but
not falling apart, about 10 to 15 minutes. Drain and cool, then cut
into small dice.
</P>
<P>
   While the potatoes cook, beat the eggs in a large bowl. Whisk in
the creme fraiche, milk, nutmeg, 1/2 teaspoon salt, and white
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Distribute the leeks and potatoes evenly among the 3 pie shells.
Sprinkle cheese on top of each. Carefully pour in the custard
mixture, dividing it evenly (about 1 cup per pie), then sprinkle
each pie with a pinch of nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the custard doesn't jiggle in the center, about 15 to
20 minutes. Let cool 10 minutes before serving, or serve at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 425 calories, &LR;   &LR; 10 g protein, 32 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 29 g fat (12 g saturated), 113 mg cholesterol, 442
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
