<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Will Americans Shun Cabernet and Learn to Love 
 Syrah?   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Will Syrah overtake Cabernet Sauvignon as the red
wine Americans love to drink? That's one of the many intriguing
questions being asked by California winemakers as they try to keep
up with the changing tastes of American wine consumers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Syrah is a tidy red wine wrapped up in a neat package, making it
easy to like. The bright raspberry-black cherry aromas and flavors
appeal more than those of Cabernet Sauvignon. Also, Syrah's balance
and structure attract red-wine fans the way few Merlots can. And
Syrah has the same silky texture that fans of Pinot Noir love. Only
Zinfandel seems to offer the same attractive components as Syrah.
</P>
<P>
   The ancestral home of Syrah is the Rhone Valley of France,
although some theories hold that the grape was first grown in
Shiraz, Persia, known today as Iran. Other grape detectives now
claim that Syrah is native to the Rhone Valley and has a lot in
common with an obscure Rhone grape called Mondeuse. Syrah shows its
stuff best in Hermitage, Cote Rotie and St. Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the popularity of Syrah has been on the rise in
Southern France, especially the Languedoc region, where the wine
offers the same bright berry flavors, but lacks the concentration
and depth of a Northern Rhone Syrah.
</P>
<P>
   Shiraz is the name for Syrah in Australia and South Africa. In
the vineyard, Syrah and Shiraz are the same, but a Rhone or
California Syrah tastes different than an Australian Shiraz. Syrahs
are known more for their spice and black pepper, while Shiraz is
fruitier with notes of berries and plums, and hints of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Oak is another component that separates Syrah and Shiraz. French
Syrah, especially from the Northern Rhone, is aged exclusively in
French oak, while most Australian Shiraz is aged in American oak.
The belief among many winemakers is that French oak, with its
spiciness, is good with Syrah, but the vanilla-coconut of American
oak is a better match with Shiraz. Australia's premier Shiraz,
Penfolds Grange, has been aged in American oak since the first
vintage in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   California Syrah is being grown in many parts of the state, but
among those regions with the most promise are Monterey County, Napa
Valley, Mendocino and some parts of Santa Barbara County.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Syrah vs. Sirah &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before Syrah became popular, an early favorite of California
winemakers was Petite Sirah. Rough, rustic and alcoholic in the
early years, Petite Sirahs are now more refined and drinkable at an
early stage.
</P>
<P>
   Identified in the 1970s as Durif, a nearly extinct French grape,
Petite Sirah popped back into the wine news in the late 1990s, when
DNA fingerprinting suggested that what is called Petite Sirah in
California has been applied to Durif, Syrah and an obscure French
grape called Peloursin. Further confusion comes with winemakers in
the Northern Rhone distinguishing between a small-berry Syrah grape
they call Petite Syrah and the larger-berried Grosse Syrah.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, you should taste the differences among Rhone Syrah,
Australian Shiraz and California Syrah and decide for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Merry-Go-Round &LR;
</P>
<P>
   David Schlottman, a winemaker with Beringer Wine Estates for 25
years, has been appointed Senior Winemaker at St. Clement, a member
of Beringer Wine Estates. Schlottman established his reputation as
winemaker for Napa Ridge, a value line of wines, formerly a part of
Beringer Wine Estates. Bill Ballentine continues at St. Clement as
winemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Pezzi King, one of the rising stars in Sonoma County, has
appointed Cecile Lemerle, a French-trained winemaker born in
Champagne, as Director of Winemaking. Lemerle's previous position
was Director of Production for Opus One in the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ricardo Sander of Los Angeles was disappointed that Truchard
Vineyards was not mentioned in a recent Potpourri article on
Carneros Pinot Noir.
</P>
<P>
   The omission of Truchard certainly was not intentional . . .
their wines, especially Pinot Noir, Merlot and Syrah, are among my
favorites. But then, it's not possible to list or mention all of
the wineries that make good wine from Carneros grapes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Brandy and other spirits are made using two kinds of stills. The
most efficient method is called a continuous still, where a liquid
fermented from grains or other materials is fed continuously into
the still and the spirit drawn off at a determined point.
</P>
<P>
   The other method, used to produce most of the world's great
brandies, like Cognac and Armagnac, is called an alembic (also
alambic), or pot still. The word is derived from the Arabic
 &LR; al-anbig &LR;  for a still. It is less efficient than a continuous
still because each batch must be heated separately and the still
must be emptied and reloaded each time. However, the advantage of
pot still distillation is a spirit with deeper, more complex
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ATF Hearings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The California Wine Institute would like to alert concerned
consumers that the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF)
will hold public hearings in five locations across the country,
including San Francisco, to determine the impact of wine label
statements currently in use.
</P>
<P>
   Of concern is whether the ``negative consequences of alcohol
consumption or abuse'' disqualify wine, beer and spirits from
carrying any health-related statements.
</P>
<P>
   ATF wants to know if the so-called directional wine label
statements refer consumers to the Federal Government's ``Dietary
Guidelines for Americans'' to learn the health effects of wine
consumption, or to their family doctors for such information.
</P>
<P>
   Comments on the wine label issue should be submitted to ATF by
letter, fax or e-mail. Written comments will be accepted by ATF
until September 29, 2000, and should be addressed to: Chief,
Regulations Division, Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, P.O.
Box 50221, Washington, DC 20091-0221; Attn: Notice 892; or fax
(202) 927-8602; or e-mail  &LR; nprm &LR; atfhq.atf.treas.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A public hearing on the wine label issue will be held May 23-25
at the Embassy Suites San Francisco Airport, 150 Anza Blvd.,
Burlingame. Other public hearing locations, from April to August,
include Washington, D.C., Atlanta, Chicago and Dallas. For more
information, call Nancy Kern or Jim Ficaretta at ATF in Washington,
(202) 927-8210.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
