<SLUG> BC-SECRETBRUNCH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Liven Up Your Easter Brunch   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Bradley Ogden has come to the rescue for those who
want something different for Easter brunch with his Potato Skins
with Smoked Salmon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ogden is known for his brunch and breakfast dishes served at the
Lark Creek Inn in Larkspur. Housed in a charming Victorian, the
restaurant overlooks the proverbial babbling brook, and the outdoor
patio is ideal for weekend brunches.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can get more traditional brunch dishes at Lark
Creek, but one of my favorites is the potato skins. While a similar
dish with caviar has been popular in years past as an elegant
appetizer, it was Ogden who thought of adapting it to breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Many people love lox and bagels as a morning
repast. Of course, crisp fried potatoes are a natural morning
option, so putting them together makes perfect sense. For this
dish, the combination of roasted potatoes, salmon and lemony cream
is unbeatable. It truly is a great brunch dish, but it's also just
as good as a snack, appetizer or a passed hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   The red onion relish, made with lemon, chives and chervil, is
designed to be sprinkled around the plate, but you can sprinkle it
on top of the smoked salmon to replace the caviar, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lark Creek Inn, 234 Magnolia St. (at Madrone Avenue),
Larkspur; &LR;   &LR; (415) 924-7766. Lunch weekdays, dinner nightly, brunch &LR; 
 &LR; Sunday.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The potato skins. &LR;  The potatoes are boiled then the skins are
fried in grapeseed oil until golden brown, making a crisp contrast
to the silken salmon.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The horseradish creme fraiche. &LR;  Spooned into the potato and
on top of the salmon, this sauce adds a pleasant surprise to the
appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POTATO SKINS WITH SMOKED SALMON &AMP; HORSERADISH CREME FRAICHE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   20 (about 1 pound) 1-inch diameter yellow potatoes or Yukon
Golds, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced red onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh chervil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 quart grapeseed oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Horseradish Creme Fraiche (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 ounces smoked salmon, sliced paper thin (approximately
11/2 to 2 ounces per serving), and cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons smoked salmon caviar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon osetra caviar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   14 small sprigs fresh chervil for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the potatoes in a large saucepan with enough cold, salted
water to cover. Bring to a boil over high heat, then reduce heat to
a gentle simmer. Cook until the potatoes are just tender but still
firm, about 8 to 10 minutes. Drain and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   While the potatoes are cooking, combine the red onion, chives,
lemon juice, olive oil, chopped chervil and lemon zest in a small
bowl. Stir to mix. Season the relish with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the potatoes in half. Using a melon ball scoop, dig out the
center of each potato half and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the grapeseed oil in a large saucepan to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Working in batches, fry the potato skins in the hot oil until
golden brown, about 3 to 4 minutes. Using a slotted spoon, transfer
the potato skins to paper towels to drain. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the potatoes on 12-inch dinner plates, using 5 halves
per plate and forming them into a star pattern in the center of the
plate. Fill the center of each potato with 1 teaspoon Horseradish
Creme Fraiche. Arrange a few strips of smoked salmon over the
potatoes. Top each with a dot of Horseradish Creme Fraiche and a
little of each of the optional caviars.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the red onion relish around the plate. Garnish plates
with the chervil sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 200 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate,
14 &LR;   &LR; g fat (6 g saturated), 35 mg cholesterol, 350 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HORSERADISH CREME FRAICHE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated tart red apple
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peeled and finely grated fresh horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon finely grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the sour cream in a small bowl until smooth. Using a
rubber spatula, fold in the creme fraiche, apple, horseradish and
lemon zest. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 37 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 1 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 12 mg cholesterol, 6 mg sodium, 0
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
