<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: One Egg Stands White and Yolk Above the Rest   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Even though they're in just about every
refrigerator in America, deciding which eggs to buy can be
overwhelming. There are store brands, cage-free, vegetarian-fed and
vitamin-fortified, not to mention variation in size and color.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eggs also vary distinctly in price. One dozen large grade AA
white eggs can cost from $1.39-$3.59.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel of culinary professionals tasted 12 brands of
large white grade AA eggs, all available at local supermarkets. The
eggs were hard-cooked using the Best Way technique (see BESTWAY
EGG), and served at cool room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were all basically the same kind of egg and
were cooked the same, the panel noticed big differences in
appearance and flavor. Some eggs had a larger proportion of yolk to
white; others had very pale yolks in comparison to other brands.
Flavors also varied from bland to sulfurous.
</P>
<P>
   According to the panel, one brand stood out far above the rest.
Most of the others scored roughly the same, between 55 and 65
points.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's overwhelming favorite egg was  &UR; Andronico's &LR;  (1
dozen, $2.09 at Andronico's).
</P>
<P>
   Andronico's buys its eggs from Thayer Food Products, an
Oakland-based company with farms in the Central Valley. According
to Jill Benson of Thayer, the eggs are pretty generic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no special tricks to producing our eggs,'' says
Benson. The eggs are laid by white leghorn hens, which produce the
majority of white eggs. They're kept in cages and fed a natural
diet of corn, wheat and soybeans but may also be fed fish meal.
</P>
<P>
   The Andronico's egg is moderately priced, as well. ``Niche eggs
cost more to produce,'' Benson explains, referring to cage-free or
vegetarian-fed eggs. ``Even brown eggs are expensive because the
hens that lay them are larger and eat more.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel particularly liked the flavor of the Andronico's egg,
describing it as ``classic.'' One panelist noted the beautiful
yellow color; another liked the large yolk. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Cal &LR;  (eight-pack, $1.49 at Andronico's).
Three panelists commented on the soft texture of the yolks. Two
described the flavor as classic, but another detected a sulfurous
aftertaste. Two would buy it, two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trader Joe's Cage Free &LR;  (1 dozen, $1.69 at Trader Joe's) came
in third. One described the flavor as ``very clean and delicate;''
another thought the overall texture and flavor were good. But
others thought the yolk was too light in color and the white was
tough. Two would buy it, two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Veg-A-Pro &LR;  (1 dozen, $1.99 at Rainbow
Grocers), which is laid by hens ``fed a strict vegetarian diet,''
according to the package. Three panelists thought it was
flavorless, but others described it as creamy, tender and good
tasting. Two would buy it, one might buy it and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clover Stornetta &LR;  (1 dozen, $1.30 at Whole Foods) came in
fifth. One panelist thought the flavor and texture were good, but
others described the flavor as off and slightly sulfurous. One
panelist thought the egg was particularly rubbery. Two would buy
it, one might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth place went to  &UR; Eggland's Best &LR;  (1 dozen, $2.69-$2.99 at
many markets). One taster said it was very white, while another
called the white tough and rubbery. One would buy it, one might buy
it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Santa Rosa Egg Farms, Cotati, Cage Free,
Mollie Stone's and Veg-A-Fed and Gold Circle Farms, but they scored
too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Flo Braker, cookbook author and Chronicle
columnist; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Kim Severson,
Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
