<HEADER>
A1350 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-EGGS-SIDEBAR-SFCHRON &LR;      04-19 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGGS-SIDEBAR-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Guidelines for Buying and Using Eggs Safely
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eating a Caesar salad with raw eggs in the dressing is a
personal choice. Before you make it, consider that unpasteurized
eggs may contain a strain of salmonella bacteria that can make you
sick.
</P>
<P>
   Among the factors to weigh are the odds of infection. On
average, Americans eat 225 eggs a year. The United States
Department of Agriculture estimates that only one in every 20,000
eggs is infected with salmonella enteritidis, a strain of bacteria
easily killed if eggs are thoroughly cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella-related illness often produces symptoms much like the
flu: loose bowels, aches and fever. Healthy adults usually recover
within four days to a week. But the infection can be more severe,
and even fatal, among people with compromised immune systems, the
elderly and very young children.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you want to eat raw eggs in salad dressing, meringues,
sauces and other recipes is a personal choice. But public health
experts say you can avoid illness from eggs by knowing how to buy,
handle and cook them safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer need not live in fear of eggs but certainly needs
to handle eggs with respect,'' advises Linda Harris, a food
microbiologist at the University of California at Davis. ``For
healthy individuals who can't live without their Caesar salad, it's
a risk worth considering. But I wouldn't make that salad for your
grandmother or child.''
</P>
<P>
   The following are a set of government-approved guidelines for
safe egg handling:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Buy Safe. &LR;  Purchase eggs only if sold from a refrigerator or
refrigerated case. Open the carton and make sure the eggs are clean
and the shells are not cracked. Refrigerate as soon as possible.
Store eggs in their original carton in the coldest part of the
refrigerator. Use them within four to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Keep Clean.  &LR; Wash hands, utensils, equipment and work areas
with hot, soapy water before and after they come in contact with
eggs and egg-containing foods. If a piece of shell falls into the
egg while cracking, remove it with a clean utensil.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Cook Thoroughly. &LR;  Cook eggs until both the yolk and the white
are firm, usually at 145 degrees. Scrambled eggs should not be
runny. Casseroles and other dishes containing eggs should be cooked
to 160 degrees. Avoid recipes that call for eggs that are raw or
undercooked when the dish is served. Serve dishes containing eggs
immediately. On a buffet, hot egg dishes should be kept hot, and
cold egg dishes kept cold. Egg dishes such as quiches may be
refrigerated for serving later but should be thoroughly reheated to
165 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Keep It Cold. &LR;  Use hard-cooked eggs (in the shell or peeled)
within one week after cooking. Cooked eggs should not be held at
room temperature for more than two hours. Eggs should not be frozen
in their shells. Refrigerate leftover cooked egg dishes for up to
three or four days. When refrigerating a large amount of a hot
egg-containing leftover, divide it into several shallow containers
so it will cool quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Be Safe Away From Home. &LR;  Cooked eggs for a picnic should be
packed in an insulated cooler with enough ice or frozen gel packs
to keep them cold. Carry it in the passenger compartment of the
car, not the trunk. If taking cooked eggs to work or school, pack
them with a small frozen gel pack or a frozen juice box.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Avoid Hidden Risks. &LR;  Foods containing raw or lightly cooked
eggs, such as Caesar salad, homemade ice cream or eggnog,
mayonnaise or hollandaise sauce, and French toast can be dangerous,
especially for young children, the elderly and individuals with
weakened immune systems. Replace them with cooked versions or forgo
the recipe altogether.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EGGCETERA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Timing is everything.  &LR; A hen requires 24 to 26 hours to
produce an egg. Thirty minutes later, she starts all over again.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Porcelain.  &LR; An egg shell may have as many as 17,000 tiny
pores over its surface.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The chicken state.  &LR; About 240 million laying hens produce
approximately 5.5 billion dozen eggs per year in the United States.
An estimated 25 million of those hens are in California.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Shell game.  &LR; White-shelled eggs are produced by hens with
white feathers and ear lobes. Brown-shelled eggs are produced by
hens with red feathers and red ear lobes.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Spinning game.  &LR; To tell if an egg is raw or hard-cooked, spin
it. If the egg spins easily, it's hard-cooked. If it wobbles, it's
raw.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sign of spring.  &LR; During the spring (vernal) equinox, around
March 21, some people swear that an egg will stand on its small
end. Although some people have documented success, it is not known
whether such results were due to the equinox or to the
peculiarities of the particular egg.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Color it yellow.  &LR; Yolk color depends on the diet of the hen.
Natural yellow-orange substances such as marigold petals may be
added to light-colored feeds to enhance the yolk's hue.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Into the pan.  &LR; Howard Helmer secured the Guinness World
Record for omelet- making in 1990 by making 427 omelets in 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Eating large.  &LR; Californian Rick Royal created the world's
largest cr &LR; e &LR; me brulee in 1999. It weighed on at 1,000 pounds and
was 23 feet in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; _ Sources: The American Egg Board and the California Egg &LR; 
 &LR; Commission. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
