A1370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-19 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS U.S. MAY USE FORCE TO REUNITE ELIAN AND FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be updated as needed) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday that the U.S.
government might have to use force to take Elian Gonzalez from his
Miami relatives in order to reunite him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may come a time when there is no other alternative,''
Reno said at a Washington news conference Wednesday morning. ``But
we've got to do it in a careful, thoughtful way. No child should be
in that kind of never-never land for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the government would not take action until three
federal court judges in Atlanta ruled on a Justice Department
request that the court drop a temporary stay order that prevents
Elian from returning to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must take enforcement based on the facts, as they arise at
the time,'' Reno said. ``Pressure should not be the issue. What is
right should be the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The temporary stay was issued last Thursday by Judge J.L.
Edmondson of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta and
remains in effect until the three-judge panel makes a ruling on it.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, the judges have been reviewing copies of the
briefs, and a ruling is expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's comments Wednesday come during a week that holds
religious significance for many Cuban-Americans because of Good
Friday and Easter. The Miami relatives have asked the government
not to disturb them during the holy days. The anniversaries of the
Waco incident and the Oklahoma City bombing, both tragedies for the
federal government, also fall this week.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has made clear that she believes the Atlanta court should
not help Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's great-uncle, because he has
violated federal orders to turn Elian over to the government.
Gonzalez, whose Miami family has been taking care of Elian for
almost five months, defied instructions to bring the boy to a
nearby airport last Thursday, when Elian would have been flown to
Washington to reunite with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department officially revoked the great-uncle's
custody of the boy when that deadline passed. Elian had been placed
in Gonzalez's care after he was found clinging to an inner-tube off
the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy was one of three survivors of
a capsized refugee boat. His mother, who was divorced from his
father, drowned with 10 other Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Cuban-Americans, Gonzalez opposes President Fidel
Castro's communist rule and has refused to let Elian return to
Cuba. He is asking the Atlanta court to compel the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to grant Elian an asylum hearing. The court
is scheduled to hear oral arguments on May 11.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That decision will likely hinge on who the court decides has the
right to speak for Elian: the great-uncle or Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
the father, who flew from Cuba on April 6 to claim his son.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the court must decide on both the temporary stay and
a request for an injunction that would prevent Elian from leaving
the country until the court rules on the asylum hearing. That
request was filed last Thursday by lawyers for the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawyers also filed a similar lawsuit on Friday asking the
U.S. District Court in Washington to prevent federal officials from
returning Elian to Cuba unless they can guarantee that Castro's
government would not violate the boy's human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials had said that if the boy is turned
over to his father the government would order Elian and his father
to stay in the country until an appellate decision is reached on
the asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson issued the temporary stay last Thursday as tensions
reached a peak outside Elian's Miami home, where more than 4,000
protesters had gathered to prevent the government from removing
Elian. Wednesday morning the scene was much calmer, as dozens of
people waited behind police barricades outside the house. The 50 or
so Cuban-Americans who have been keeping a round-the-clock vigil in
the last several weeks have intensified their watch following
recent comments from federal officials that the government would
enforce the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sacred place for the child,'' Esteban Nunes, a
construction worker, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who tried in vain last week to negotiate with Elian's
relatives for the boy's return to his father, has refrained from
taking more forceful action. Born in Miami, she served as state
attorney in Miami-Dade County before taking her current post. In
1980, she watched as riots erupted in her hometown after she failed
to win convictions for four white policemen charged with beating to
death a black insurance salesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
