<P>
   (Coded ``e'')
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ART-THEFTS (Beijing) _ An anonymous letter tipped off
Chinese archaeologists to what they believe is a rampant global
problem: the theft of cultural relics that are given a phony
provenance and sold to private collectors and museums, at prices
ranging into the millions. Such thefts occur on the largest scale
in China, which is filled with unexplored tombs and other
archaeological remains as well as poorly guarded temples and
museums. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-IRELAND-FILM (London) _ While still in her late 20s,
Deborah Warner made her name as something of a wunderkind of the
British stage through innovative interpretations of classics at the
Royal Shakespeare Company and the Royal National Theater. She has
now turned to her first film, ``The Last September,'' a screen
adaptation of a much loved novel about Ireland by Elizabeth Bowen.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY (Undated) _ New developments in questions
surrounding the business practices of the Marlborough Gallery, the
international art gallery heavily fined in 1975 for defrauding the
Mark Rothko estate and accused in court last month of cheating the
Francis Bacon estate. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   BELLOW-BOOK-REVIEW _ Michiko Kakutani reviews
``Ravelstein,'' &UR;  &LR; by Saul Bellow.
</P>
<P>
   JUMP-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Lawrence Van Gelder reviews
``Do Jump.''
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ D.J.R. Bruckner reviews ``The
Lynching of Leo Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   MANCHILD-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ David Dewitt reviews
``Manchild in the Promised Land.''
</P>
