<P>
   CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS &UR;  &LR; (Undated) _ Nearly four years ago, Mount
St. Mary installed a high-speed wireless network that covers the
campus, including parking lots, dormitories and everything between.
Every faculty member and nearly 100 students have laptops equipped
with transceivers and antennas to pick up and transfer Internet
signals. Most students in the dormitories also have wireless access
through their desktop computers. By &UR;  &LR; Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-TRANSLATIONS (Undated) _ The idea of the Internet
as the ultimate global village _ the medium that will allow people
around the world to connect and communicate _ may be facing its
ultimate test. As the community of non-English-speaking people
grows online, companies are racing to handle the numerous languages
of the World Wide Web. By David Kushner.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MARKETING (Undated) _ In 1996, Melisse Shapiro's novel ``Lip
Service'' was rejected by every major publishing house in New York.
Shapiro, who writes under the name M.J. Rose, set out to prove them
wrong. She created a Web site where the book could be downloaded
for a fee, and waited for her audience to come to her. Few came.
She realized that she had neglected the final piece of the puzzle:
a marketing plan. By Bonnie Rothman Morris.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CENSUS (Undated) _ Equipping computers to make sense of the
scribbles on 1.5 billion pages from United States census forms,
which were sent to more than 121 million households. By Ian Austen.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DIGITAL-ENTERTAINMENT (Undated) _ Some entertainment and
computer executives have seen the future, and it is one in which
consumers surrender more of their privacy than they do today. By
Bonnie Rothman Morris.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ROBOT-DOG (Undated) _ On the Chinese calendar, this is the
Year of the Dragon, but a group of toy and consumer electronics
manufacturers would not be unhappy if it turned out to be the year
of the dog _ the interactive robotic dog, that is. By Michel
Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CARS (Undated) _ Electricity bills depend on how much
electricity is used each month. Soon auto insurance premiums, too,
may be metered, based partly on how much the car is driven. By Anne
Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MUSIC-KIOSKS (Undated) _ Music kiosks where people can burn
their own CDs.
</P>
