<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. MAYOR APOLOGIZES TO CHINESE RESIDENTS FOR THEIR TREATMENT
IN 1906 QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For the first time in all the years San
Franciscans have been observing the anniversary of the great 1906
earthquake, an apology shared equal billing with nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   At a predawn ceremony Mayor Willie Brown said Tuesday that San
Francisco owed an apology for its treatment of Chinese residents
before and after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the part of the city of San Francisco, we offer a heartfelt
apology to the Chinese community,`` the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also presented quake survivor Bessie Shum, 96, with a
proclamation making the city's apology official.
</P>
<P>
   Shum is the first Chinese American survivor to attend the
memorial gathering, a San Francisco tradition since it started in
1919.
</P>
<P>
   She was two years old when her family fled Chinatown as fire
swept the city in the aftermath of the quake. She was carried by a
neighbor. Her father carried her mother, whose feet were bound.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinatown was then the most densely populated section
of San Francisco, only a dozen Chinese names appear on the official
list of 674 dead and missing. Shum said the bones of many Chinese
had been shipped to China after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight survivors of the quake attended predawn Tuesday's
ceremony, the
</P>
<P>
   most for a decade. Among them was 101-year-old Mariam Cowan, a
theatrical
</P>
<P>
   performer and onetime major-domo a notorious madam named Sally
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment of silence at 5:12 a.m., then a mournful wail
from a dozen fire engines - and then the party started, with the
crowd singing ``San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicist Lee Housekeeper attributed the larger-than-usual
number of quake survivors to the Westin St. Francis' generous
gesture of providing rooms for all.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors were served the same breakfast that was on the St.
Francis menu when the earthquake struck: chilled rhubarb, stewed
prunes, thinly sliced fruit and berries with yogurt, pastries, rice
griddle cakes, southern hominy with cream and scrambled eggs with
black truffles.
</P>
<P>
   At noon the crowd of quake survivors grew to 50, five of them
centenarians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
