<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REQUESTED RECIPES POP, CRINKLE AND ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Morales sent along the requested recipe for microwave
caramel corn. She has the recipe thanks to her friend Pam Mauk, but
can't recall where Pam found it several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Haas sent ]a refrigerator roll recipe requested by Pat
Hardy of Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Henderson, Fort Worth, sent the molasses cookie recipe
with this note: ``Here is a recipe for molasses crinkles that my
mother baked for my family during the '60s and '70s. It is probably
my favorite cookie of my childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MICROWAVE CARAMEL CORN
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 cups
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter (1 stick)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   12 cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, combine butter, brown sugar, syrup and salt.
Microwave on high 5 minutes, stirring at halfway point. Next, stir
in soda (mixture will foam). Put popcorn in brown grocery bag. Pour
mixture over it and stir well. Put bag in microwave and cook on
high 1 minute. Stir well again. Cook again on high 1 minute. Stir
again. Cool in bag slightly, then transfer to bowl. Let cool
completely before covering it.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 194 calories, 8 grams fat, 30
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 21 milligrams cholesterol,
180 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REFRIGERATOR ROLLS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 dozen
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 package dry yeast, dissolved in 1/4 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup lukewarm water
</P>
<P>
   4 cups unsifted all-purpose flour or whole wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   Stir ingredients together in the order given. Refrigerate dough
for at least 12 hours. (Dough may be kept for several weeks.) Roll
dough into your favorite shape on lightly floured board and let
rise 2 hours before baking.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 375 degrees for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 86 calories, 3 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 69 milligrams
sodium, 33 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MOLASSES CRINKLES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 dozen
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup solid shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 beaten egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light molasses
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups enriched flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly cream shortening and sugar. Add egg and molasses;
beat well. Add sifted dry ingredients, mix well. Chill thoroughly
or overnight. Shape in balls the size of walnuts, and dip one side
in granulated sugar. Place sugared side up on ungreased cookie
sheet, 2 or 3 inches apart. Bake in 350-degree oven for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cookie: 99 calories, 7 grams fat, 10
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 6 milligrams cholesterol, 66
milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
