<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT &LR;      04-19 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FAUCETS, A VARIETY OF MATERIALS AND FINISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are three reasons to replace a kitchen or bathroom faucet:
If it is malfunctioning and cannot be repaired, if the finish is
worn and pitted or if you want to replace an old one with one that
is more stylish.
</P>
<P>
   If you have not shopped for fixtures in a while, you may be
surprised at the wide variety. Prices range from about $30 to more
than $400, and models are available in metal or plastic with an
assortment of finishes.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to buy a new faucet to fit an existing sink, then
you must buy a model of the correct size. This is determined by
measuring the distane, or spread, between the holes in the
lavatory or sink shelf. Usually there are three holes: two for the
faucets and a center one for the spout or stopper post. Measure the
distance between the center points in the outside holes.
</P>
<P>
   Some sinks have spreads of only 4 inches across. They require a
unit that has the spout and faucets mounted together on a single
base. You must purchase the new fixture to match this
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   After determining the size you need, consider the material the
fixture is made of. Cheap fixtures are made of plastic plated with
thin metal. The low price of these units may seem appealing, but
the metal finish is largely cosmetic and will quickly wear away.
</P>
<P>
   Faucets with die-cast zinc alloy bodies are more durable, and
also more expensive. These pieces are plated with chrome or brass
to protect the zinc from corrosion, and they will wear well until
the plating deteriorates; then they will start to corrode.
</P>
<P>
   Solid-brass fixtures are the most durable and also the most
expensive. They require less care than fixtures made from other
materials and are more resistant to the corrosion caused by
minerals in hard water. Solid-brass fixtures may have a chrome- or
nickel-electroplated finish. If not, they should have a proprietary
lifetime finish (Delta Brilliance, Moen LifeShine and Jado Diamond
are popular finishes for brass fixtures).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is difficult to tell what any fixture is made of
if it has chrome plating. The manufacturer should specify whether
the faucet is all-brass body or brass- or chrome-plated on the
package. Usually, you can judge the metal quality by the weight of
the piece. Brass fixtures are heavier than faucets made of plastic
or zinc alloy.
</P>
<P>
   Finish is important, because it determines the appearance of a
fixture and how easy it will be to maintain. Fixtures with pewter
or satin finishes are easy to care for because the matte surface
hides scratches, fingerprints and water spots. Fixtures with shiny
chrome and brass finishes show water spots and soap film readily,
so they must be polished often.
</P>
<P>
   Handle configuration is another important option. Traditional
fixtures have two handles, one for hot water, the other for cold.
Many modern faucets have a single handle that controls both hot and
cold water. Some safety experts feel that one-handle faucets are
safer in homes with small children. The handle can be left in the
cold water mode, so a small child opening the tap will not be
scalded by hot water. While this is a good safety feature, it is no
substitute for lowering the thermostat setting on the water heater
to 120 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Handle shapes include cross pattern, round knobs and lever
grips. Round knobs have a stylish look that works well with modern
design schemes, but they are difficult to grip and turn. Lever
handles are a better choice for older users or anyone who has
trouble manipulating round knobs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consider the valve mechanism inside the faucet, because
it can affect the price and reliability of the fixture. The
compression faucet is oldest type of mechanism. Turning the handle
raises the valve stem inside the faucet. This lifts the rubber
washer off the mouth of the valve and allows water to flow through.
The washers will deteriorate with exposure to hard water or if the
stem is overtightened, but replacement washers are cheap and easy
to replace.
</P>
<P>
   Faucets with ball valves have a single handle and an internal
ball mechanism that is turned to align with the hot and cold
openings. Ball valves are durable and require less maintenance than
compression faucets, but they have a number of small internal parts
so they can be tedious to repair.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeve-cartridge faucets have a single unit, a cartridge that
controls the water supply. The cartridges are used in one- and
two-handled faucets. Fixing a leaky faucet requires opening it up
and replacing the entire cartridge with a new piece of the same
configuration. This is a relatively simple task, but replacement
cartridges can run as high as $20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1543EDT &QL; 
