<HEADER>
A1456 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-LAHIRI-TEX     04-19 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LAHIRI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAHIRI TAKES THE PRIZE _ IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Interpreter of Maladies''
</P>
<P>
   by Jhumpa Lahiri
</P>
<P>
   Short fiction
</P>
<P>
   Mariner Books, $12
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Pulitzer Prize committee of 2000 knew something
about last year's published fiction that almost all the rest of us
missed: Jhumpa Lahiri's short-story collection, ``Interpreter of
Maladies,'' is fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Published by Houghton Mifflin in 1999, ``Interpreter'' didn't so
much fade quickly from sight as fail to make any impact at all.
Lahiri was an unknown first-time author, her name was hard to
spell, and the book's subject _ short stories about Indians in
India and America _ seemed less than spellbinding. Almost no
marketing effort was put into the title, and readers and critics
alike largely ignored it _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait. Go buy a copy while you can.
</P>
<P>
   Each of ``Interpreter's'' nine stories is a standout. Lahiri
writes in a deceptively simple style. Her characters truly talk to,
rather than at, each other; exquisite details _ the texture of
cereal, dust altering the color of a monkey's fur _ proliferate.
Perhaps it could be described as gentle Hemingway, except, unlike
Papa, Lahiri writes about people who aren't larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   The title story, for example, finds a tour guide/cab driver in
India unexpectedly hearing the confession of a young American
mother with a special secret. Discovering the secret, as our cab
driver does, is not what the story is about; instead, it's all
about how the characters respond to _ and how they are affected by
_ the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Each story has its own unique strength and perspective. But in
the course of ``Interpreter'' being read and discussed, it is
inevitable that the collection's concluding story, ``The Third and
Final Continent,'' will be hailed as the ultimate classic. Nothing
dramatic happens here, except the very real fact that all lives are
dramatic, each in its own way. A humble Indian comes to Boston to
work in a university library. Because he is approaching middle age,
his mother arranges a marriage for him; the bride is also older,
someone rejected by previous suitors for being too plain. They are
awkward with each other and uncomfortable in their new country, but
their initial gawky companionship turns into love, and we learn
their eventual fates 30 years after the story began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a son who attends Harvard University ... So we drive
to Cambridge to visit him, or bring him home for a weekend, so that
he can eat rice with us with his hands, and speak in Bengali,
things we sometimes worry he will no longer do after we die. I know
my achievement is quite ordinary. Still, there are times I am
bewildered by each mile I have traveled, each meal I have eaten,
each person I have known, each room in which I have slept. As
ordinary as it all appears, there are times when it is beyond my
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a moving, powerful story to be read over and over, with the
simple message that no life is ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Lahiri herself should be a potent literary force for decades to
come. Now 32, she was born in England and raised in Rhode Island.
She has a Ph.D. in literature from Boston University, and she
shuttles back and forth between the United States and her parents'
native India.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of her future fiction remains to be seen (she's
currently working on a novel). But if ``Interpreter of Maladies''
is any indication of what is yet to come, this young woman is a
literary treasure. We have the Pulitzer Committee to thank for
bringing her to our belated attention.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
