<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      04-19 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvesting Pea Vines
</P>
<P>
   Q. At a chic restaurant recently, I tasted tendrils from a pea
vine. Can I harvest the tips from the plant in my garden and still
have peas later on?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Long before pea vines became fashionable, a woodchuck taught
me that you can prune severely and still get a crop of peas. In
fact, since pruning forces the vines to branch, you might get more
peas than ever. But there is some risk, because pruning sets back
growth and delays flowering. If the weather turns hot before the
vines reach full size, you could end up with a smaller crop or no
crop at all.
</P>
<P>
   Start by deciding what kind of vine you want to end up with.
Trendy American chefs favor what might be called pea scribbles.
These tangles of tightly curled tendrils come from plants known as
afila peas. Marketed under such variety names as Godiva and
Novella, afilas make tendrils instead of leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   Asian chefs prefer the vine tops of snow peas such as Oregon
Sugar Pod and Snowflake. Though less dramatic-looking than afila
tendrils, snow pea vines are tastier and more tender. (The vines of
regular garden peas are edible, but tend to be fibrous and bland.)
</P>
<P>
   Sow seeds as soon as possible, following the directions on the
packet. When the plants are about 14 inches tall, cut off the top
six inches _ four inches for afila types _ making the cut right
above a leaf node. The plants will branch where you made the cut
and resume growing to the normal height for the variety. Depending
on weather, flowering will be about a week to 10 days later than on
unpruned plants.
</P>
<P>
   Snow pea seeds are widely available. Novella seeds are sold by
R.H. Shumway, P.O. Box 1, Graniteville, S.C. 29829 (803-663-9771).
A snap pea version, Sugar Lace, is new this year from Park Seed, 1
Parkton Ave., Greenwood, S.C. 29647 (800-845-3369). Catalogs from
both are free.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting pea-vine field study, conducted by Washington
State University, is available at
http://agsyst.wsu.edu/peareport.htm
</P>
<P>
   Happy Wanderers
</P>
<P>
   Q. While in Tasmania last August (the end of winter there,
beginning of spring), I saw a bush with a profusion of small purple
blooms. My guide said it is called ``Happy Wanderer.'' I also saw a
vine that shared the same name and appearance. Was is the botanical
name, and is it available in North America?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The botanical name of the plant Australians call Happy
Wanderer is Hardenbergia violacea, known in the United States as
coral pea. Here, Happy Wanderer is a specific variety of H.
violacea sold at some garden centers. Other purple-flowered
violaceas are available, and so are white and pink forms of the
same plant.
</P>
<P>
   Though H. violacea can be either a vine or a bush, only the vine
is sold in America. In Australia it's a rampant grower, but in most
parts of the United States, it can be grown only indoors. H.
violacea will survive an occasional dip to the mid-20s
(Fahrenheit), but grudgingly. Anything colder will kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Even in very warm areas where it can live outdoors, it tends to
be well behaved, said Kathy Musial, a curator at the Huntington
Botanical Gardens in Los Angeles, who has found it far more polite
than the wisteria it otherwise brings to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Since coral pea sets flower buds in fall, the sooner you start
growing yours, the better. It will put on size all through the
summer before it stops growing and starts making flowers, so you
will have more of them in the blooming season, December through
March. (Those flowers will be pea-like, by the way; H. violacea
also resembles wisteria in being a legume.)
</P>
<P>
   Purple and white H. violacea are sold by Logee's Greenhouses,
141 North St., Danielson, Ct. 06239 (888-330-8038); a catalog is
$4.95. Seeds of the pink and white vine forms, and of a related
variety, H. comptoniana, which has purple flowers, are available
from J.L. Hudson, Seedsman, Star Rte. 2, Box 337, La Honda, Calif.
94020; catalog $1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
