u f BC-STATES-BAYH-NAT     04-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BAYH-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        VERDICT STILL OUT ON BAYH AS VEEP
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Tania Anderson  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- There's no doubt that most Hoosiers would like to
see their former governor and current Senator, Evan Bayh, in the
vice president's seat. But whether he'll actually get the nod from
Democratic contender Al Gore is very much up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Observers from Indiana and Washington seem to be split on
whether the freshman senator has what it takes to beat out a list
of old school politicians and make Indiana important enough to the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The naysayers say things like: ``He has no stature,'' said
William Schneider, CNN's senior political analyst. ``It would not
be a choice for Gore to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bayh himself doubts he'll be picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's most likely someone else will be chosen,''
Bayh said in an interview Friday. ``I have no control over the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The optimists say: ``One of the things that makes Bayh such a
good possibility is that he's a strong young person that has
(focused) on many of those same issues that Al Gore has,'' said
Mike Panos, chairman of Gore's campaign in Indiana, who is based in
Merrillville. ``People in the Gore campaign feel good about Evan
Bayh.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of a running mate is a highly personal decision
for the candidates and one they keep private until the first party
convention of the year. It's also a decision based on the various
vote- getting qualities that a running mate could add to the ticket
like their home state, ethnic background and gender. Professional
and personal backgrounds also play a major role.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits say that what Bayh has in his favor is similarities with
Gore like growing up with fathers who were senators, both attending
St. Albans, a Washington private school, and both holding moderate
democratic views. Gore could be attracted to the fact that Bayh
helped establish a Democratic base in the state after two terms as
governor, especially in a traditionally faithful conservative
state. He also was the first Democratic senator from Indiana to be
elected in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in (Midwestern) states remember Birch Bayh,''
said Brian Howey, editor of the Howey Political Report, of Evan
Bayh's father, who served in the Senate for three terms. ``The name
really is a multi-generational name and packs some clout and punch
in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not in his favor is his inexperience and lack of exposure
as a U.S. senator, Indiana's small number of electorate votes, a
possible association with fellow Hoosier Dan Quayle and competition
from other potential running mates. Indiana has 12 electoral votes,
a small piece of the 270 votes actually needed to win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if he'll pick him,'' said Thomas L. Smith, chairman of
the fourth district's Democratic party. ``I think he's on a short
list but I don't know if he has enough experience and exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats mentioned for the Gore ticket are Florida Sen.
Bob Graham, California Sen. Dianne Feinstein, California Gov. Gray
Davis, Illinois Sen. Richard J. Durbin, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardsen and House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt from
Missouri. The Gore campaign refuses to comment on the list of
potential running mates. Former Secretary of State Warren
Christopher was recently appointed to help narrow down Gore's
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's vice presidential selection, which will most likely be
announced at the Republican Convention July 31 in Philadelphia,
weighs heavily in whether Bayh will get picked by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Some say if Bush chooses a female running mate like former
presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole or New Jersey Gov. Christine
Todd Whitman, Gore may be inclined to follow suit by also selecting
a woman. If Bush selects a state governor like Pennsylvania Gov.
Tom Ridge, Bayh's chances of getting selected could increase if
Gore also wants a running mate who worked as a governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good argument for Bayh,'' said Doug Davidoff,
communications director of the Indiana Democratic party. ``There's
always a chance (it'll) be somebody nobody's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bayh could help Gore win votes in Midwestern states, which
are the hardest to get in presidential races, some dispute whether
Indiana is strong enough to give Bayh that edge over other
midwestern politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana doesn't help you carry states like Michigan and
Ohio,'' Schneider said. ``In Ohio, Indiana is a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bayh is sheepish about the whole situation. He said he's
flattered by the rumor but is focused on his role as the state's
senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's an honor to be considered,'' Bayh said.
``Clearly it's the kind of thing that I wouldn't turn down but I'd
have to talk to (my wife) Susan about it before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
