<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1472 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-19 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKET, MCCAIN AND MIRANDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on current events:
</P>
<P>
   THE STOCK MARKET: What a way to make a living. I've known
professional horse players who faced less stress and uncertainty on
a daily basis than these folks who wager on stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   My total involvement with Wall Street consists of a 401(k) plan
that barely has enough money in it to justify the paperwork that
goes along with it. But I still call the investment company's hot
line to check the balance when the markets have these wild
fluctuations, just to see how I've been affected by the recurring
plunges, rebounds, crashes and recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, usually, is not much. But if those menacing ``Stocks
plunge'' headlines send chills up the spines of penny ante
investors like me, can you imagine what they must do to Wall Street
high rollers who can see their net worth evaporate in a matter of
hours?
</P>
<P>
   THE PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION: John McCain says he won't run as an
independent because he's loyal to the Republican Party. That's
nice. But if he's such a good Republican, why doesn't McCain stop
playing ``hard to get'' and declare his unequivocal, enthusiastic
support for the nominee-to-be, George W. Bush?
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, he's been getting rave reviews from the media for
his accessibility _ daily news conferences, frequent interviews,
etc. _ which is ironic, considering that he was previously
portrayed by the pro-McCain news hounds as a hermit who was afraid
to face the media hordes. Do you suppose the new assessment has
something to do with Al Gore's recent penchant for hiding from the
press?
</P>
<P>
   Reporters are so easy. They love anyone who talks to them.
</P>
<P>
   GUN CONTROL: Thursday is the one-year anniversary of the
Columbine High School shootings in Colorado, and the anti-gun
movement doesn't seem to be even slightly embarrassed by its crass
exploitation of the tragedy to promote its political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the National Rifle Association and other supporters of gun
rights can be stubborn and self-defeating, but the other side truly
ought to be ashamed of itself for trampling victims' graves.
Instead of using occasions such as the Columbine anniversary to
lobby for gun laws, couldn't the gun-haters just shut up and let
the victims' loved ones mourn in peace?
</P>
<P>
   THE MIRANDA WARNING: If you can't recite it _ ``You have the
right to remain silent ... anything you say can and will be used
against you'' _ then you haven't been watching all those
cop-and-lawyer shows on television. But the so-called Miranda
warning amounts to a heck of a lot more than TV dialogue: It
signifies the U.S. Constitution's guarantee against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Supreme Court is gearing up to decide if the police
really need to be bothered with Miranda. Seems that Congress passed
a law way back in 1968 that might have negated the Miranda
requirement, which had been imposed by the Supreme Court two years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   I know about as much about the law as I do about the stock
market, but here's a prediction: The Supreme Court will uphold
Miranda. The rule has become too ingrained in the criminal justice
system to just toss it out the window. Besides, how would TV cops
fill up all those hourlong shows if they didn't have to Mirandize
everybody they arrested?
</P>
<P>
   THE CUBAN BOY CONTROVERSY: Dr. Irwin Redlener, a professor of
pediatrics who has advised the government on the Elian Gonzalez
mess, says that the boy's Miami relatives are being
``psychologically abusive'' and that Elian should be returned to
his father immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child needs to be rescued,'' Redlener said.
</P>
<P>
   Amen to that.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL: A recent column about my ongoing baseball boycott
prompted a reader to send me his list of 51 reasons ``why baseball
is the sorriest sport of all.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of my favorites.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2: ``Seven players stand bored while two players play
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 4: ``Darryl Strawberry.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 11: ``Steve Howe.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 39: ``Too many `beer guts' (players and spectators) in the
park.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 49: ``Warning tracks are for sissies.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
