<HEADER>
A1473 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     04-19 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN LANCELOT OF OLDE-FASHIONED VICTUALS AT RENAISSANCE FAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is time for Scarborough Faire, which in Texas means you only
have a couple of months to enjoy the Renaissance festival before it
gets too hot to dress up in unflattering tights and steaming suits
of armor.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been to Scarborough Faire, in Waxahachie, south of
Dallas, though this is its 20th anniversary. The wardrobe is
probably part of it, the heat another. I know I don't really have
to go in costume, but beyond that, the whole idea of a Renaissance
festival is to enjoy the pleasures of the 16th century, and I'm not
convinced those were great times _ plagues, armadas, big bloody
wars and things like that.
</P>
<P>
   The food is the main thing for me at festivals like Scarborough
Faire. I guess the jousting is fun, and the falconry. Certainly we
guys all like to look at the wenches; the trick is not getting
caught.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't write me to say using the term ``wenches'' is not
politically correct. It is part of Scarborough Faire's own
publicity and they even have a ``Woo the Wench'' contest. Get a
life.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't want a Renaissance festival without wenches, or
roasted turkey legs, for that matter. I'm not sure they even had
roasted turkey legs back in the 16th century, but if they didn't,
they should have.
</P>
<P>
   They do at Scarborough Faire.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently they were big drinkers back in the 1500s. Doing some
reading on Elizabethan food, I found the following liquid measures:
``A tun is equal to 2 butts, or 4 hogsheads, or 252 gallons.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to love someone who measures their liquids in those
quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I found that meats were often cooked a little sweeter than
we do them now. The English cooks, and probably most Europeans,
cooked their meat with a lot of fruits for a sweet and savory
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Potatoes were still kind of a novelty, and folks still
considered tomatoes poisonous. Popular vegetables were turnips and
parsnips.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate was used only for medicinal purposes, and the
chocolate they had was unsweetened and bitter. Coffee and tea were
also considered medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Wild game was popular, but generally speaking, you had to be a
landowner to hunt the game, and most of the land was owned by
precious few. The peasants had to make do on bread dishes. Meat,
fish and fruit were rare.
</P>
<P>
   When the poor folks did get meat, it was often spoiled and they
had to use a lot of spices to cover the ripe taste. Also, it wasn't
uncommon to use oatmeal as a thickener for stews.
</P>
<P>
   They don't do that at Scarborough Faire. I have a sneaky
suspicion that some of the dishes they serve at the festival are
not really period recipes at all.
</P>
<P>
   There are 60 food items in all available at various food stands
on the Scarborough Faire site. Some of them have an
all-too-familiar ring to them.
</P>
<P>
   For example: I have a hard time thinking of a royal knight
riding along with his visor down, eating a New World fajita. How
about a grilled seafood salad? Try that with your falcon resting on
your forearm.
</P>
<P>
   And where does the shrimp etouffee come from, and the red beans
and rice? I just can't see a Cajun in a sheet-metal outfit.
</P>
<P>
   There is chicken on a stick, Canterbury pork pockets and steak
on a stake.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the menu looks good. There is something for
everyone, and if you can graze your way through the 35-acre
compound, it can't be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fair kicked off last weekend and will run through
June 4, Saturdays and Sundays, including Memorial Day. For more
information on ticket prices and special events, call (972)
938-FAIR (3247).
</P>
<P>
   Just for the heck of it, in salute to the 16th century and
Scarborough Faire's 20th anniversary, here is a legitimate
15th-century recipe for stewed capon that was still popular in the
16th century, or so they say. It is taken from ``Two Fifteenth
Century Cookery Books'' (1430-1450), Thomas Austin Ed., Early
English Text Society, Oxford University Press, 1964. The cooking
directions were translated by David Friedman and Elizabeth Cook.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEWED CAPON
</P>
<P>
   Original directions
</P>
<P>
   Take parcelly, Sauge, Isoppe, Rose Mary, and tyme, and breke hit
bitwen thi hondes, and stoppe the Capon there-with; colour hym with
Safferon, and couche hym in a erthen potte, or of brasse, and ley
splentes underneth and al about the sides, that the Capon touche no
thinge of the potte; strawe good herbes in the potte, and put
thereto a pottel of the best wyn that thou may gete, and none other
licour; hele the potte with a close led, and stoppe hit aboute with
dogh or bater, that no eier come oute; And set hit on the faire
charcole, and lete it seeth easly and longe till hit be ynowe. And
if hit be an erthen potte, then set hit on the fire whan thou
takest hit downe, and lete hit not touche the grounde for breking;
And whan the hete is ouer past, take oute the Capon with a prik;
then make a sirippe of wyne, Reysons of corance, sugur and
safferon, And boile hit a litull; medel pouder of Ginger with a
litul of the same wyn, and do thereto; then do awey the fatte of
the sewe of the Capon, And do the Siryppe to the sewe, and powre
hit on the capon, and serue it forth.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken, about 5 to 6 pounds
</P>
<P>
   First batch of herbs: 1/3 cup fresh parsley, 1 tablespoon dried
sage, 1 teaspoon dried rosemary, 1 teaspoon thyme, ground, 2
tablespoons hyssop, dried
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   6 threads saffron plus 1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   Second batch of herbs: 1/2 teaspoon tarragon, 1/2 teaspoon sage,
1/2 teaspoon rosemary, 1/2 teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour, enough water to make a stiff dough
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup currants
</P>
<P>
   Small pinch saffron
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Mix first batch of herbs and stuff chicken with
them. Put chicken and wine in a pot with a top; if you are using a
stove top rather than an oven, you may want to put wood pieces or
something under the chicken to keep it from sticking. Paint the
chicken with water with saffron crushed into it. Sprinkle on second
batch of herbs. Mix flour and water into a stiff dough, roll it out
into a string, and use it between pot and lid as a seal. Bake at
350 degrees, or simmer on stove top about 11/2 hours. Take out,
drain, separate out some of the liquid without the fat. Make a
thick syrup of wine, sugar, currants and a pinch of saffron. Boil
briefly. Mix another 1/4 cup wine with powdered ginger. Combine.
Add 1/2 cup of the broth from the chicken to this, heat, pour over
chicken, serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 369 calories, 17 grams fat,
19.7 grams carbohydrates, 31.5 grams protein, 97 milligrams
cholesterol, 96 milligrams sodium, 41.9 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can write him at Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort
Worth, TX 76101, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
