<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-MAGAZINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's next? It's Oprah - the magazine
 &HT;    By Dan Neal
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After yakking her way to zillionairehood
with her TV talk show, Oprah Winfrey shuts her yap today, puts pen
to paper and prepares to make another pile with a new career _
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out she ain't half bad.
</P>
<P>
   O, The Oprah Magazine hit newsstands nationwide Wednesday
morning, trumpeting on its cover an irresistible promise: ``Live
Your Best Life!''
</P>
<P>
   Does it deliver? Maybe _ if you're a woman age 25-49 in search
of ``a personal-growth guide,'' as Winfrey describes her mag.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-plus-page glossy tome is teeming with tasty stuff,
including Oprah's chat with Camille Cosby about the murder of
Cosby's son, columns from some big-name writers like Peggy Noonan
on relationships, finance, fitness, food, fashion, working and
more, excerpts from singer Jewel's diary, and, most intriguing of
all, ``What Makes Tina Turner Tremble?''
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 more things to look for in the premiere issue:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Book That Changed Oprah's Life: Oprah so loved ``The Four
Agreements'' by Don Miguel Ruiz that she bought 410 copies, passing
them out to befuddled brethren everywhere. The pop-psychology opus
presents deals you make with yourself to ``clarify'' your life,
including the pact that packed the most punch for Winfrey: ``Don't
take anything personally.'' The article ends with ``A Gift From O''
_ five colorful bookmarks you can tear out and use in your own
favorite works.
</P>
<P>
   _ 27 Ways to Get the Most Out of Sundays: Another Oprah-penned
piece, this one shows you how to ``create your own rituals of
reverence, harmony and sharing.'' Way No. 1: ``Loll Around: Wear
your most comfortable pajamas all day.'' Yikes! That's one tip most
of us don't need, but hey, there are 26 more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poems! Alice Walker contributes a couple of free-verse gems to
accompany a photo spread on flowers. Pretty _ and pretty doggone
literary for a magazine spun off a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personal Courage Calendar: Eeeeww! This two-page touchy-feely
spread offers inspiration and then some for folks who are feeling
feeble. Day 1: Buy a notebook to use as your Courage Journal. Write
down ``every brave, strong, surprising thing you've ever done.''
Other days include quotes to help process your feelings or specific
questions to address in the journal: ``Ask yourself, What was I
created to do?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Profile of the Perfect Job: Biomedical engineer? Ballplayer?
Blabbing for big bucks on TV? Heck, no. Shoe tester! Don't miss the
story of Raphaelle Tzen, 26, a ``fit model'' for DKNY shoes. She's
a perfect size 7, DNKY custom-builds shoes to fit her foot, and _
here's the best part _ she gets to keep the pairs she likes!
</P>
<P>
   _ Do-It-Yourself-Analysis: A ``Something to Think About''
section offers not only questions to aid in personal growth but
also a pretty space to write your answers. Sample question: ``What
is my heart's deepest desire?'' Sample response: ``More room to
bare my soul on this $&AMP;% form!''
</P>
<P>
   _ How to Suck, Sniff, Stroke and Really, Really Mean It: All
right, not the real title, but that's the idea of this article
offering tips for nourishing your senses. For the eyes: Choose one
window to be your ``frame'' on the outside world. Stare at it for a
long time. For the tongue: Assemble ingredients for a meal. Think
about ``the origins of each food _ the long, marvelous journey'' to
your table. Eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oprah to Go: Perforated punch-out cards with inspirational
quotes from Maya Angelou, Ralph Waldo Emerson, Martin Luther King
Jr. and Epictetus. Instructions suggest you ``slide them into
pretty frames, slip them into your handbag or paste them into your
journal.'' Common sense suggests you read more than one sentence by
these authors before you slap them on your mirror, but it's a
clever idea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Five Fabulous Things to Do With Fresh Strawberries: No. 1:
Scarf. Just kidding. Oprah, who claims she's now ``so over
dieting,'' is nevertheless calorie-conscious in O's food articles.
This one offers healthy recipes for jam, no-cook tarts, muffins,
goat-cheese salad and granita, a sorbet-like dessert.
</P>
<P>
   _ The O List: Oprah plugs her favorite products with pictures
and her own testimonials: ``I have a wardrobe of sunglasses, but
this pair in ebony by Fendi ($170) is my favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``wardrobe of sunglasses''? OK, so maybe Oprah is just
slightly out of touch with her audience in that last section.
Overall, O is a sharp mag that will hit the mark for millions of
middle-class women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
