<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 3-MINUTE EGG AND I: WHY'S IT SO HARD TO ONE THAT'S COOKED
RIGHT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed a simple enough request. A 3-minute egg for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Served in an egg cup. Maybe atop a paper doily. Perhaps soldiers
_ fingers of soft toast _ on the side.
</P>
<P>
   But no _ a journey through breakfasts in Tarrant County, Texas,
left me wondering about the fate of this simple culinary classic.
</P>
<P>
   First stop was at the beloved Ol' South Pancake House, the
24-hour kitsch cathedral to ham and eggs and all things breakfast.
No _ the eggs served up were peeled, shiny orbs of soft-boiled
eggs, the whites firm and the yolks nearly set.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, down the street, I ordered the same at
Denny's. The eggs were better this time _ served with shell intact,
the yolk was closer to the luscious, spoon-coating consistency of
memories. But sadly, the three eggs arrived in a cereal bowl,
leaving the diner to hold the shell with one hand and scoop out the
egg with a spoon in the other. Hardly genteel.
</P>
<P>
   Finally we tried the International House of Pancakes, a
dependable haunt since college days. Again, what was served were
three in-shell eggs nestled into a small bowl. And the yolks were
firm _ hardly the scoopable golden honey of a three-minute egg.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to this little bibelot of a breakfast, a
ceremony of manners that calls for a quick, but firm, thunk of a
knife blade against the shell to render it decapitated?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' says John Clark, restaurant consultant and co-author
of the new ``Country Egg, City Egg,'' ``people don't serve those.
Americans don't seem to cotton to an egg that's runny _ the
salmonella scare and all that. As a kid, I remember eating them in
a hotel. Now I think they're seen as old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``No restaurant I've ever worked for would have been equipped to
serve them, either,'' Clark says. ``They wouldn't have the egg
cups, for one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And, apparently, neither will young couples who are now setting
up households.
</P>
<P>
   Brides registering their china patterns at Neiman Marcus Ridgmar
are not including egg cups in their wish lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a bride order an egg cup,'' says Georgianna
Kiker, assistant to the manager of Gift Galleries at Neiman March
Ridgmar. ``Most of the manufacturers don't even make one. If any
company is going to offer an egg cup, it's going to be an older
pattern, and you'd have to look far and wide to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Simmons, author of the hot-off-the-press ``The Good Egg:
More than 200 Fresh Approaches From Soup to Dessert'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $26), is also sentimental about the disappearance of the
elegant 3-minute egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my major food memories is lingering over a soft-cooked
egg, with little soldiers next to it, on a Saturday morning,''
Simmons says. ``There was no school bus to run for, and I would
daydream over my breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is that we've had two generations now who
have been scared of eggs. To be extreme, we've thought that if we
ate an egg, we could die _ the cholesterol thing and then the
bacteria scares.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the science is that if a raw egg is cooked at 145 degrees
for three minutes,'' Simmons explains, ``any bacteria is destroyed.
Now what we've got to hope is that this nostalgic thing will come
around again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also in the age of instant breakfast, where even a
three-minute egg takes too long to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman's Kiker agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have leisurely breakfast anymore. It seems everyone
wants to drive-through McDonald's or Jack in the Box. It's like
breakfast has to be between two pieces of bread,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Not for us. Because they can't be found in restaurants, here's
our version of 3-minute eggs, perfect for any morning, including
Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3-MINUTE EGG
</P>
<P>
   1 egg Enough water to cover the egg, plus 1 inch more
</P>
<P>
   Bring water to a simmer. Lower the egg into the water (this can
be done by putting the egg in a strainer and placing the strainer
in the water). As soon as the water returns to a simmer, time it
for 3 minutes. Remove by lifting strainer from the water. Using a
dish towel, place egg in egg cup, fat side down, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: xx calories, xx grams fat, xx
grams carbohydrates, grams protein, milligrams cholesterol,
milligrams sodium, percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
