<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      04-19 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online Scents, Speed and Cleaner Windows
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it possible to transmit smell over the Internet? That
could be used to sell perfume or advertise a restaurant's cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   A. Although the notion of sending digitized scents from computer
to computer may have seemed a bizarre notion just a few years ago,
several companies are working to create hardware and software for
just that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware component usually uses a cartridge containing
chemicals that can simulate certain smells when they are mixed.
Codes in the scent software tell the hardware what scent to
manufacture. In an odor-enabled system, you could send a greeting
card to your significant other by e-mail and attach the smell of
roses to the card.
</P>
<P>
   A company called DigiScents (www.digiscents.com) has developed a
technology called iSmell that can be used to provide distinctive
scents that can be attached to e-mail, text and interactive
material on Web pages and interactive video games. The iSmell
hardware device attaches to the computer like a printer or any
other external device, but it generates scents instead of
printouts. DigiScents is also the home of the Snortal, a soon-to-be
Web portal that promises to offer an interactive smelling
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are developing scent-sending technologies. One
company, AromaJet.com, is working with video game companies to add
smell as a sensory component to gaming (www.aromajet.com). Another
company, TriSenx, has said that it expects to ship its own
scent-producing hardware later this month (www.trisenx.com). The
hardware, called FirstSENX, will cost about $400 and will allow
users to print scent sheets on cards and even taste the digital
concoctions.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a small monitor and the Windows 98 Taskbar takes up
too much room on my screen. Is there a way to get rid of it when
I'm not using it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Windows 98 has a built-in feature that will hide the Taskbar
unless you move your mouse pointer to the bottom of the screen to
make it reappear. To set up this function, go to the Start menu and
select Settings and then Taskbar and Start Menu. When you see a box
called Taskbar Properties, click on the Auto Hide check box and
then click OK When you click on the computer's desktop area, the
Taskbar should disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Personal computers keep getting faster, but how can I tell
how much speed I need? Is there really that much difference between
a 500-megahertz machine and an 800-MHz one?
</P>
<P>
   A. The speed in megahertz refers to the computer's processor,
and the bigger the number, the faster (in theory) the computer, in
terms of how quickly it can perform the tasks you tell it to. If
you want to know how much computing power you really need, you need
to ask yourself what you will be using the computer for.
</P>
<P>
   In general, faster chip speeds are better if you plan to use the
computer for things like animation-intensive videogames, digital
video production or image-editing and illustration programs. If you
just want to do common home-computing activities like Web surfing,
e-mail, word processing and spreadsheets, you will probably be
happy with a lower- to mid-range computer in terms of both price
and speed. The basic software requirements and video-processing
needs for those types of tasks usually need fewer megahertz than
graphics-oriented programs.
</P>
<P>
   The CNet Web site (computers.cnet.com) keeps a variety of
hardware reviews and comparisons that might give you a better idea
of what you need. If there are certain programs you know you will
want to run on your new computer, check each program's requirements
(always printed on the outside of the box, in catalogs and often on
the manufacturer's Web site), to make sure that the hardware you
are considering can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
