r f BC-401(K)-RETHINK-WORTH-     04-19 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-401(K)-RETHINK-WORTH-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL WITH A CAUSE: ONE MAN'S IDEA FOR A BETTER 401(K)    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Columbus, Ohio)   (This ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the April issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 850. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,175
WORDS.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a''
domestic/general news, ``f'' financial news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)     
 (STORY SUMMARY: Most 401(k) retirement plans ask employees to
manage their own investments. One man has an easier, cheaper _ and
more lucrative _ way.)     
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brooks Hamilton doesn't look like a revolutionary. For one
thing, he is a benefits attorney and 401(k) plan record keeper.
People in these vocations are better known for emptying rooms than
for filling them.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, Hamilton wears pinstriped suits, at least
when he's being lawyerly. But when he puts on sweats and settles in
front of one of his computers, Hamilton becomes a dangerous threat
to the established order.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hamilton, in a September 1998 ``Worth'' article on 401(k)
plans, who introduced the idea of ``yield disparity'' _ the
performance chasm that separates the top 20 percent of 401(k) plans
participants from the bottom 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hamilton who calculated that the top 20 percent would
retire with more than 100 percent of their preretirement income
while the bottom 20 percent would retire to a diet of cat food.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hamilton says he has found a way to close the yield gap. He
proposes to turn the 401(k) from a retirement plan dependent on
costly retail mutual funds into one that relies on low-cost
wholesale pension management.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton calls his solution the Freedom Plan. If it works the
way he says it will, the Freedom Plan could siphon much of the $593
billion in 401(k) assets now held in retail mutual funds into
managed pension accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ground zero for the Freedom Plan revolution is Safelite, a
privately-held company headquartered in Columbus, Ohio. With $877
million in annual sales, Safelite is the largest manufacturer and
installer of auto replacement glass in the country.
</P>
<P>
   It has 600 service centers in all corners of the U.S., 3,200
vans, 80 warehouses, two manufacturing plants, and 6,300 employees.
If you've ever had a broken windshield replaced, there's a good
chance you've done business with Safelite.
</P>
<P>
   Safelite management had for years struggled to spread the word
about the company's 401(k) benefit to its widely scattered, mostly
blue-collar work force. But as recently as 1994, the Safelite
401(k) was stumbling along with a 38 percent participation rate,
about half the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as bad, the average contribution of those who did
participate was a meager 2.3 percent of pay, also less than half
that in the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Safelite CFO Douglas Herron asked Hamilton how the
company could improve its plan. Hamilton had a few ideas.
</P>
<P>
   To spur participation, Safelite started automatically enrolling
new employees in the plan unless they specifically opted out of it.
And to reward job longevity, the company started matching 20
percent of an employee's contribution in the first two years of his
or her service, escalating to 40 percent after five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to encourage a long career at Safelite,'' says
Herron. And Safelite agreed to increase its match rate when overall
participation in the plan reached specific targets.
</P>
<P>
   When the participation rate was at 50 percent, for instance,
Safelite would increase its match by 10 percent. When the
participation rate hit 60 percent, the match would grow by 25
percent. When the participation rate exceeded 75 percent, the
company match would rise by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These incentives, Hamilton figured, would turn veteran Safelite
employees into plan evangelists, boosting participation and
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   To help the process along, all employees were mailed
personalized projections that showed how increases in contributions
would affect their retirement. The goal was to have employees
contribute enough to capture at least 90 percent of the potential
company match.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's final suggestion was the really radical one. Instead
of offering a wider range of investment choices or even a
self-directed brokerage account, as some plans do, Hamilton wanted
the company to float a new option called PDI, for Professionally
Directed Investment.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who selected the PDI option would have their money
invested by the same professional managers who were handling
Safelite's defined-benefits pension. This would lower the cost of
operating the plan and, very likely, increase the investment return
of the money under management.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a typical 401(k) plan, the money is managed by amateurs,''
says Hamilton. ``With PDI it's invested by pros.''
</P>
<P>
   In a final twist on accepted convention, Hamilton made PDI the
default option for positive enrollment. (Most plans make a money
market fund, perhaps the world's least appropriate retirement
investment, their default choice.)
</P>
<P>
   Unless a new employee specified otherwise, his or her money
would go into PDI. To Hamilton, making PDI the default option was
crucial, because it meant that even the most financially illiterate
Safelite employee would have a well-designed investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Many 401(k) savers have no such assurance. Investing may seem
like the new national pastime, but the reality is that to many
people, portfolio management is a mystery they have no interest in
solving. They spread their retirement savings across the choices
they are offered rather than making choices appropriate to their
age. &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One landmark study, by UCLA business school professor Shlomo
Benartzi and University of Chicago behavioral finance expert
Richard Thaler, found that the investment choices made by 401(k)
savers tend to reflect the number of options in the plan and its
implicit asset allocation.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, in a plan that offers more bond funds than
equity funds, participants tend to have low equity commitments.
Participants in a plan that offers more equity funds than bond
funds tend to have a higher equity commitment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, TWA's plan, according to the study, offers five
stock funds and one bond fund. Participants in TWA's plan have a 75
percent equity allocation. The University of California plan offers
four bond funds and one stock fund. In that plan, participants have
a 34 percent equity allocation. &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 150-WORD TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,175) &LR;  &QC;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safelite added PDI to its plan in January 1999. By Jan. 1, 2000,
Hamilton says, the participation rate had reached 73 percent and
the average contribution had hit 4.2 percent of pay. That enabled
employees to capture 75 percent of the potential match money.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming an ordinary level of employee turnover, Hamilton is
confident that Safelite will reach 90 percent participation by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of PDI on Safelite employees' retirement prospects is
dramatic. Hamilton estimates that the typical employee will see his
or her probable retirement income rise from only 14 percent of
final salary to 50 percent. Add Social Security benefits, and most
employees will approach 100 percent of final pay.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the joy of having choices? What about the subtle
pleasures of deciding between the growth of the Pacific Rim, the
security of real estate, and the undervaluation of small-company
stocks?
</P>
<P>
   If Safelite is any indication, most people won't miss the extra
options. Safelite's new plan-eligible employees in January still
had six mutual funds from which to choose, but only 5.9 percent
opted out of PDI.
</P>
<P>
   That means traditional mutual funds are missing 94.1 percent of
this year's new money. &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott burns is the
personal-finance columnist for the Dallas Morning News. His E-mail
address is scott(at)scottburns.com, and his Web site address is
www.scottburns.com.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,025-word (trimmed) ``WORTH'' magazine
article, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
