<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1480 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     04-19 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SMART TOOLS FOR THE HOME WITH CHIPS, LASERS, LCDs  
 (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Great Pyramids and the Taj Mahal were built with stupid
tools. The pictures in the Metropolitan Museum and the Louvre were
hung with stupid tools. Thomas Jefferson, a smart man, built
Monticello with stupid tools that did not contain a single
microchip, laser, diode, liquid crystal display or ultrasonic
transducer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not trying to build Monticello. I'm just trying to do some
simple remodeling and repair work around the house. If a smart tool
helps me do a better job, it would be dumb not to use it.
</P>
<P>
   I've been testing several IntelliTools from the Stanley Works,
makers of the Stanley brand of hand tools, including a digital tape
measure that uses optical sensors and a display screen, a digital
stud finder that is smart enough to look behind walls and tell the
difference between wood, pipes and electrical live wiring, an
ultrasonic measuring estimator with a laser pointer and a digital
level with a laser that can switch from a dot to a crosshair.
</P>
<P>
   None of these tools is going to replace its old-fashioned
counterpart in my toolbox, at least not yet. However, each of the
IntelliTools has a trick or two that comes in handy for certain
tasks under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Gadget fans will add one or more of these smart tools to their
toolboxes just because they are gadgets, and therefore cool. Tool
fans will buy them because they love tools. ``Any excuse to buy a
tool is a good excuse,'' noted Rick Schwolsky, chief editor of
Hanley-Wood's Tools of the Trade, (www.toolsofthetrade.net) a tool
magazine for professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, anyone who pays more than $100 for a laser torpedo
level just to hang a towel rack is probably half a bubble off
center himself. A simple, brainless spirit level works just fine
and is a lot cheaper. But if you do a lot of handyman (or
handywoman) chores, perhaps one of these tools makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   I've become especially enamored of the Stanley 77-007
IntelliMeasure Ultrasonic Estimator with Laser Pointer ($66.21 at
www.kenstool.com, or $80 at www.amazon.com), even though it is not
as accurate as a tape measure. The estimator, which looks like the
love child of the Star Wars robot R2-D2 and a beer can, uses sound
waves to measure distances up to 50 feet and is accurate to within
half a percent. That is, it may be off by as much as three inches
at 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want to use it to measure cuts for a marble
countertop,'' said David Wakefield, an engineer for Stanley's
IntelliTools line. But for doing a quick estimate of a room size
for carpeting, or when you're trying to figure out if your bed is
going to fit in what some Manhattan landlords charmingly refer to
as ``the second bedroom'' (didn't this used to be a closet?), it
comes close enough. The display can be set for feet and inches,
decimal feet or metric units.
</P>
<P>
   After measuring the length width and height of a room (measuring
ceiling height without a ladder is one of the nicest features), the
estimator can also calculate the area and volume of a room with the
push of the button. The estimator has to be held perpendicular to
the wall or surface being measured, or it gets confused. When I
bounced an oblique scan at a wall no more than 5 feet from me, it
sent back the startling news that the wall was 45 feet 11 inches
away, indicating that ultrasound waves were ricocheting around the
room.
</P>
<P>
   It won my heart, however, when I had to measure a long hallway
that had become soaked after a spectacularly unfortunate plumbing
problem. There are some places you don't want to go with a tape
measure.
</P>
<P>
   For places you do want to go with a tape measure, there is the
Stanley IntelliTape 25-foot digital tape measure ($40). It combines
a traditional steel tape measure with optical sensors and a liquid
crystal display.
</P>
<P>
   Optical sensors inside the measure keep track of tiny holes in
the tape itself and calculate the distance based on how many holes
are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Distances are displayed on the small screen in your choice of
units: inches, feet and inches, centimeters, or decimal meters. The
IntelliTape uses a chip to store the distance in case I can't
immediately find a pencil to write it down.
</P>
<P>
   Zircon (www.zircon.com), which competes with Stanley in the
smart tools for consumers market, has a 25-foot tape measure called
The Repeater ($30), which comes with a built-in, 20-second voice
recorder. It seems more useful for recording job-related to-do
lists rather than tape measurements.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley IntelliTape is somewhat heavy and clunky, and it was
difficult to unscrew the case to insert the three button-style
batteries. But it had some features I liked a lot, like a button
that instantly calculates the midpoint of any measurement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, I was trying to center a picture on a wall that was
415 16 inches wide. I could have done the math, but it was easier
to push the ``mid'' button, and bingo: 2011 16 . Here at the Close
Enough Construction Co., we don't quibble over a measly 32nd of an
inch.
</P>
<P>
   Once I had measured the wall, I wanted to make sure that I
didn't add to my excitement by pounding a nail into a hidden pipe
or a live electrical wire. Enter the Stanley IntelliSensor DigiScan
stud sensor (about $40), which is the next-best thing to X-ray
vision, at least when it comes to looking through drywall.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned magnetic stud finders work by sensing the nails in
wooden studs behind the wall. They work well for simple tasks like
hanging a picture, but for more elaborate tasks, like installing a
recessed bookshelf, it is often necessary to know the exact
location of studs and joists, live electrical wires and plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   As it is moved slowly across a wall or floor, the IntelliSensor
DigiScan sends out an electromagnetic field that detects hidden
wood, metal and live wiring. Be careful, however, because live
current might not be detected in shielded wires or live wires
inside a metal casing. The display screen shows the proximity of
the material on a bar graph, and the type of material as simple
icons (a tree for wood, a lightning bolt for live wires, and so
on). If it detects both metal and wood, like a nail in a stud, it
shows both icons.
</P>
<P>
   The IntelliSensor can penetrate standard three-quarters-inch
drywall with ease, and in ``deep read,'' according to Stanley, it
can detect pipes up to three inches deep in concrete. In my tests,
it pinpointed the exact edges and centers of hidden studs. It also
chirps excitedly when it finds something, as when I accidentally
held it against my laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The most dispiriting tool of the four I tried was the
IntelliPoint Plus laser torpedo level (about $115), because it
largely confirmed my hunch that my house had no right angles or
level surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   The IntelliPoint Plus is a conventional nine-inch, three-bubble
torpedo level with an adjustable vial (for measuring angles) and a
built-in laser pointer. The laser is accurate to about 100 feet and
is set exactly one inch above the level's base plate. A small lens
can be switched to focus the beam into a dot or a cross-hair
pattern, which is handy for laying out grids for tile, for example.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few examples of new smart tools, and others are
undoubtedly on the drawing board. As the price of electronic
components falls, so will the price of smart tools. If smart tools
become popular, that could distress purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is beauty in the tradition and legacy that follows these
tools through evolution,'' Schwolsky said. ``Part of that tradition
is learning how to use the tool, and knowing each tool's quirks.
There is something lost in the relationship between craftsman and
tool when the tool becomes smarter than the user.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
