<SLUG> BC-401(K)-RETHINK-WORTH-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL WITH A CAUSE: ONE MAN'S IDEA FOR A BETTER 401(K)    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Columbus, Ohio)   (This ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the April issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 850. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,175
WORDS.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a''
domestic/general news, ``f'' financial news and ``l'' lifestyle
news files.)     
 (STORY SUMMARY: Most 401(k) retirement plans ask employees to
manage their own investments. One man has an easier, cheaper _ and
more lucrative _ way.)     
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brooks Hamilton doesn't look like a revolutionary. For one
thing, he is a benefits attorney and 401(k) plan record keeper.
People in these vocations are better known for emptying rooms than
for filling them.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, Hamilton wears pinstriped suits, at least
