<HEADER>
A1486 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS-A     04-19 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS-ART-420(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPLUGGED ON CAMPUS, BUT ALWAYS CONNECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT3, 4 and 5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Nolan, a freshman at Mount St. Mary College in Newburgh,
N.Y., was hanging out in her cramped dormitory room on a recent
Wednesday, typing intently on her laptop. She was exchanging
instant messages with an online buddy in Chicago when the phone
rang. The caller was a friend down the hall, asking Nolan to come
by and talk.
</P>
<P>
   In most places, Nolan would have had to make a choice: She could
quit her online chat or tell her friend she would visit later. But
on this tiny campus, just west of the Hudson River, Nolan did not
even think about choosing her friend over her laptop. ``I just took
it with me down the hall,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked, the computer was still on, her Internet
connection was still intact, and messages from her online buddy
continued to appear. When she reached her friend's room, she sat on
a couch, put the computer on a table and resumed her two
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount St. Mary, portable communications are common. Nearly
four years ago, the college installed a high-speed wireless network
that covers the campus, including parking lots, dormitories and
everything between. Every faculty member and nearly 100 students
have laptops equipped with transceivers and antennas to pick up and
transfer Internet signals. Most students in the dormitories also
have wireless access through their desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Nolan goes with her laptop _ whether it is the library,
the cafeteria or the lawn outside her dormitory _ the Internet
follows her.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, experts in wireless technology say,
people throughout the world will be tapping into similar local
wireless networks at work, at home and even in public places like
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has made the access speeds for these networks far
faster than the connections used by people with wireless modems for
Internet service. And compared with the limited Web access that
comes with today's fancy cell phones, local networks allow people
to use the full power of their laptops to download files, design
Web pages and listen to MP3 files without ever having to plug in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a manifestation of a larger shift,'' said Brian Cotton,
director of consulting for Frost &AMP; Sullivan, a technology
consulting company. Before wireless networking evolved, he said,
``people would go  &UR; to &LR;  information,'' whether they walked to the
library or sat down at an Internet-connected computer. Now the same
information can come to them, as long as they are within range of a
wireless network.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mount St. Mary, a liberal arts college with about 2,000
students, is one of several colleges leading the way. Its
experience provides a glimpse of a future in which online access is
literally everywhere, all the time. Being wirelessly connected,
students and professors say, has turned the Internet into a fluid
and almost invisible part of their day-to-day work. They have
developed an automatic reflex to go to the Web for information, no
matter where they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``You forget that you don't have the wireless capability at
home,'' said Dr. Tom Sarro, a biology professor. ``I'll be in my
living room with the laptop and I'll say, I need an image of
this.'' He will pull up his Web browser to do a search and a
message will appear on the screen telling him he has no Internet
connection. ``Then it's, Oh, I forgot,'' he said. ``I have to go
downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk around the campus and the implications of the wireless
network become apparent. In the library one afternoon, a woman was
walking toward the stairwell holding her laptop as if it were a
serving tray. A mouse attached to the laptop had been placed on the
keyboard to keep it from dangling as she walked. The lid was
half-closed.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, a librarian named Sherly Fang, explained that she did
not want to close the lid completely because that would put the
computer into standby mode, interrupting her work. She was updating
a library Web page and was about to start her shift on the
reference desk, where she would continue to work on the Web site.
``It's quite convenient,'' she said before heading up the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Fang's laptop-carrying method, it turns out, is standard
throughout the library. People move from desks to the stacks with
their laptops half open, like oversize clamshells. Nolan, the
freshman who was sending messages to her friend in Chicago, said
she had perfected another technique: ``I can hold the laptop in one
arm and type with the other hand as I walk down the hall,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   If people are not on the move with their Internet connections,
they are often using them in unusual locations.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Geisler, a media studies professor, said he kept his
laptop in his car and pulled up Web sites as he sat in the parking
lot, doing some last-minute preparation for class lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Malecki, a freshman who plays on the women's basketball
team, said she did research on the Internet while reclining on her
bed, sitting on the dormitory's front stoop or hanging out with her
boyfriend in the lounge. Last fall, when she could not play because
of an injury, she browsed the library's online catalog from the gym
while her teammates practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Some students say the wireless network has helped avoid
conflicts with roommates. Daphne David, a premed student, was
checking e-mail messages and working on a chemistry assignment one
night when her roommate decided that it was time for bed. ``To not
disturb her, I took my laptop to the lounge and was still
connected,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   The more students talk about the network, the more it sounds
like a luxury. But at Mount St. Mary, a little-known college where
lawns are rimmed with mud and elevators creak with age, technicians
installed the network as a way to save money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when most colleges were wiring every room in every
residential hall so students could have broadband access to the
Internet, administrators at Mount St. Mary were trying to figure
out how they could afford to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The computer laboratories and offices were already wired for
high-speed access, but the dormitory rooms and classrooms were not.
John Bucek, the college's executive director of information
technologies, found that the price tag would be as much as
$150,000, not including labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to pay that price,'' Bucek said.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, he read an article on wireless technology.
The estimated cost to put in a network that would cover the area
needed for the dormitories at Mount St. Mary's was $10,000 to
$15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw that, I said, `Wow, we have to look into
this,''' Bucek said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as some analysts have talked about how wireless technology
might let developing countries skip the costs of building a wired
infrastructure, Bucek wondered if Mount St. Mary could skip the
wiring stage, at least in its dormitories. Several other colleges,
including Cornell University and Johns Hopkins University, have
since tried the same thing in some classrooms. And Carnegie Mellon
University has recently installed a wireless network to supplement
its wired one.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Campuses usually lend themselves to these networks because they
are self-contained, technology managers say. Campus populations are
relatively constant, so administrators can predict how many people
need access, send out memorandums to users and set up systems for
technical support. For the same reasons, some retail companies,
like rental car agencies, have already adopted the technology. Now
corporate offices and medical centers have also started to embrace
the notion of being unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   To get started at Mount St. Mary, Bucek approached Proxim, a
wireless network company, and persuaded the company to consider
Mount St. Mary as a test. He also asked the company to provide
discounts for the wireless adapter cards that the students could
install in their computers. The company eventually agreed to lease
the cards, which include tiny antennas, for $45 a semester or $95 a
year. Typically, such cards cost at least $400 each.
</P>
<P>
   Bucek and his technology team also decided to lease laptops for
every professor and librarian. (In a few years, he said, the laptop
computers may be required for admission so everyone will have the
same mobile communications.)
</P>
<P>
   Supplying the laptops to professors was a strategic decision,
Bucek said. With mobile access, they might be more likely to create
online syllabuses and integrate the Web into their class
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   According to many professors, the strategy worked. Sarro, the
biology professor, uses the Web in class to supplement his botany
lectures. Geisler, the media studies professor, asks his students
to review drafts of writing assignments that have been distributed
via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't live without it,'' said Dr. Lucy DiPaola, an education
professor who walked out of her office carrying a laptop case. ``I
can download at any given moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the wireless adapter cards, the network consists
of access points, the industry term for book-size hubs that plug
into the college's wired network, its Ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount St. Mary, cables and wires were laid to carry the
Ethernet to a few dormitories and buildings. Twenty-eight access
points were then installed at the Ethernet's endpoints, and in a
few places, extensions were added to push the wireless network's
range beyond its typical diameter, 300 feet indoors and 1,000 feet
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the system, which cost the college about $63,000, provides
Internet access at 1.6 megabits per second to more than just the
dormitory area. It covers every corner of the 41-acre campus.
</P>
<P>
   The connection is not as fast as the 10 mbps that students in
most wired dormitories have, and that has prompted a few complaints
from parents, Bucek said. But in interviews with students, none
mentioned any problems with the slower speed. And a few praised the
system as being much better than the dial-up access they have
off-campus. Soon, Bucek said, he hopes to take advantage of even
faster technology that is now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up the network did present some challenges. One was a
steel elevator shaft in a building at the top of the main hill on
campus. It blocked signals and made it difficult for people nearby
to get access. To solve the problem, Bucek added access points on
the back and front of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Interference was also a concern, especially since the wireless
system uses a frequency of 2.4 gigahertz, a part of the radio
spectrum that does not require a license from the Federal
Communications Commission. Before the network was installed, Bucek
walked around the campus with an analyzer, scouting out who else
might be using the frequency. He was relieved to find that the air
around Mount St. Mary was relatively free of intrusions _ aside
from one particular microwave oven in a faculty lounge. Bucek calls
the microwave the ``dreaded enemy of the wireless network.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Bucek and Arthur Emerson, his network
manager, showed just how far their network extends. Emerson opened
a Web browser, found a site that plays MP3 files, turned up the
volume, held the laptop upright and started to walk down the hall.
The music blared as he left the building and walked onto the
street. It became slightly weaker for a moment, as he reached the
midpoint between two buildings with access points, then blasted
through again a few steps later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a student walking around holding their laptop
out to listen to music,'' Emerson said, tuning the Internet radio
to a new station. ``But I'm sure that's not far off.''
</P>
<P>
   While students may not be depending on the system for their
music, they have already learned to appreciate Internet access that
is available anywhere, any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already asked my mom,'' David said. `` `Can we have
wireless at home?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
