<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV03-     04-19 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV03-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV03 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: CAJUN VEGGIE PIZZA; ARUGULA TOMATO SALAD  
 (FOR RELEASE WED., MAY 3, 2000, AND THEREAFTER)
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of us who really like pizza but don't want all the fat
and calories that come along with it, the discovery of a delicious,
truly vegetarian pizza on the lower level at the newly restored
Grand Central Terminal in New York City a few weeks ago is worth
heralding.
</P>
<P>
   After sampling it twice I can now make a reasonable facsimile of
it. The secret is the sauce. Its intense savory flavors take the
place of the absent cheese in the sense that you don't miss the
rich gooeyness that it provides. Instead you have hot pepper flakes
that wake up the taste buds instantly as well as a little bit of
ground cumin and of fennel seeds that make it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing a little of the sauce with the sauteed vegetables pulls
everything together so that every bite provides a lot of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Other cheese and meatless pizzas I have had in the past did
nothing to enhance the sauce and make it interesting so that there
was some boring sauce plopped on the dough, topped with some bland
vegetables that had been only barely sauteed.
</P>
<P>
   Why not give it a try? If you don't agree you can always
sprinkle on some Parmigiano Reggiano and run the pizza under the
broiler.
</P>
<P>
   I use whole wheat tortillas as pizza dough. You can use white
flour tortillas but you will lose whatever fiber there is in the
whole wheat version.
</P>
<P>
   A simple arugula and tomato salad is tarted up with a couple of
tablespoons of the Reggiano. If you cannot find the tiny cherry
tomatoes use larger ones. Size is not critical here. When buying
out-of-season tomatoes it is critical that you buy the ones that
have stems. That distinguishes the better tomatoes from the
run-of-the-mill cherry tomatoes, which are flavorless at this time
of year.
</P>
<P>
   CAJUN VEGGIE PIZZA
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups tomato puree or ground tomatoes, no salt added
</P>
<P>
   1/8 to 1/4 teaspoon hot pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces whole onion or 5 ounces chopped, ready-cut (1 1/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole zucchini or 7 ounces chopped, ready-cut (1 1/3
cups)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces whole red peppers or 11 ounces ready-cut strips (2 1/2
cups)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 9-inch whole wheat tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1. Turn oven to broil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mince garlic. Combine with tomato puree, hot pepper flakes,
cumin and fennel in a small pot and heat to a simmer. Simmer while
preparing the rest of the dish.
</P>
<P>
   3. Chop whole onion. Heat large nonstick pan to high; reduce
heat to medium high and add oil and onion and saute until onion
begins to take on color.
</P>
<P>
   4. Wash and trim the whole zucchini and cut into small chunks.
Wash, trim and seed red peppers and cut into small strips. Add the
zucchini and peppers to the onion and continue cooking over medium
heat until vegetables soften.
</P>
<P>
   5. Meanwhile place two of the tortillas on foil on a broiler pan
and broil until hot and browning. Watch carefully because they will
brown quickly.
</P>
<P>
   6. When vegetables are cooked stir about 1/4 cup of the tomato
sauce into the vegetables. Spread one third of the remaining sauce
on each of the two toasted tortillas. Top with one third of
vegetables and serve.
</P>
<P>
   7. Repeat with remaining tortilla, sauce and vegetables; cut in
half and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   ARUGULA AND CHERRY TOMATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces arugula
</P>
<P>
   16 tiny cherry tomatoes (fewer if tomatoes are larger)
</P>
<P>
   1 small piece Parmigiano Reggiano to yield 2 tablespoon coarsely
grated
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash the arugula, trim tough stems and dry. Wash tomatoes,
cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk together oil and vinegar and mix with tomatoes and
arugula.
</P>
<P>
   3. Grate cheese and sprinkle over salad.
</P>
<P>
   Yield 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pizza through step 4
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salad through step 1
</P>
<P>
   Continue with pizza through step 5
</P>
<P>
   Finish salad
</P>
<P>
   Finish pizza
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   Onion
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil and extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   Large can no-salt-added tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole zucchini or 7 ounces chopped ready-cut
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces whole red peppers or 11 ounces ready-cut strips
</P>
<P>
   Package 9-inch whole wheat tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Bunch arugula (3 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Box tiny cherry tomatoes (or larger size)
</P>
<P>
   Nutrition Information per serving: 365 calories, 12 grams fat, 5
milligrams cholestrol, 365 milligrams sodium, 15 grams protein, 55
grams carbohydrate
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Marian Burros by electronic mail. Her
address is: marbur(at)nytimes.com. The (at) represents the symbol
on your keyboard. Please include your name and daytime telephone
number. Questions of general interest will be answered in this
column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
20MINUTE-MENUS and other features. &QL;
</P>
