<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-CYBER-HACK-ATTACKS-WO     04-19 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-HACK-ATTACKS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB TERRORISTS ARE HOLDING ONLINE TRADERS HOSTAGE    
</HEADLINE>
   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' story is from the April issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)     
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)     
 By GREG KNAUSS  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the ensuing governmental and media hubbub, the ``denial
of service'' attacks that cut off access to some of the Web's most
popular destinations in early February affected only a very few
people.
</P>
<P>
   Even active users who were temporarily shut out of their
favorite sites _ Amazon.com, eBay, Buy.com, for example _ could
simply pick up where they left off after service was restored.
</P>
<P>
   Or most of them could, anyway. Two sites were unfortunate
exceptions: online brokerage houses E(asterisk)Trade and Datek.
</P>
<P>
   DoS attacks take advantage of a weakness in the underlying
protocol on the Internet. IPv4 (for ``Internet Protocol Version
4'') is the lingua franca of the world's computers, and while the
system has worked well up to this point, it was never intended to
prevent strikes like those in February.
</P>
<P>
   There's no method for authenticating the origin of an IPv4
packet; it's possible to fake, or ``spoof,'' the source address of
a request. An attacker can send messages with a spoofed source
address through a so-called amplifier, flooding his target with
responses to messages it didn't send, slowing or stopping the
delivery of legitimate data.
</P>
<P>
   Although details remain sketchy, this is apparently what
happened in February _ major sites laid low with a simple trick,
using easily obtainable tools. And while the results were
spectacular, the technical know-how required is minimal, allowing
almost anyone to accomplish the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much additional security a site claims to have,
nothing can eliminate these DoS attacks as the Internet currently
stands.
</P>
<P>
   And that's frightening to anyone who trades online. Unlike the
other sites that were hit in the attacks, everything that happens
on E(asterisk)Trade and Datek (and on all Internet-based trading
sites for that matter) is time-critical, tied to events in the real
world. A half-hour can be a lifetime if your core holding is
tanking.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ease and anonymity of the DoS attacks that shut the
sites down, they pose a significant risk for anybody who actively
trades online, simply by closing down an investor's link to the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term solution to the problem is replacing IPv4 with a
more robust protocol, and IPv6, which doesn't allow spoofed source
addresses, is the leading contender.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, making the switch from one protocol to another is
an immense task, and moving to IPv6 entirely _ thus preventing
anonymous DoS attacks _ is estimated to be a decade-long process.
</P>
<P>
   It will require replacing every piece of software on the Net,
from low-level router code and operating systems to Windows and
your Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   No one site or user can do it alone, though industry leaders
such as standards committees, network infrastructure providers, and
Microsoft could lead the push.
</P>
<P>
   Because, until then, nobody is safe. &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 475-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
