A1500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-BOMB-400&AMP;ADD-N     04-19 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BOMB-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRETON SEPARATISTS SUSPECTED IN BOMBING OF FRENCH MCDONALD'S  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A bomb exploded at a McDonald's restaurant in a small
city in Brittany Wednesday, killing a restaurant worker, and the
Interior Ministry suggested that it was the work of an obscure
Breton separatist movement.
</P>
<P>
   A second bomb found outside a post office in Rennes, 35 miles
away, was defused.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in Dinan went off at about 10 a.m. near the
restaurant's drive-through window. The force of the explosion
hurled the body of Laurence Turbec, 28, into shrubbery near the
parking lot. Few customers were in the restaurant at the time.
</P>
<P>
   No one took responsibility for either bomb, but the police said
three sticks of dynamite found in Rennes were from a cache of eight
tons stolen at gunpoint from an industrial depot last September.
The police eventually recovered five tons and arrested on robbery
charges members of the small Brittany Combat Group and the
better-known Basque separatist movement ETA.
</P>
<P>
   Another Breton separatist group, the Revolutionary Breton Army,
has long been suspected of links with Basque and Corsican
separatists as well as the Irish Republican Army. It has a history
of bombings in the region, which have surged in the months since
the theft. The robbers also took miles of detonating cord and
thousands of detonators. The Revolutionary Breton Army has claimed
responsibility for four recent bombings. But previous attacks have
been on government buildings, electrical pylons or other property
and have killed no one.
</P>
<P>
   Such acts ``never before had such dramatic consequences,'' said
a statement from the Interior Ministry, which sent an antiterrorism
unit to investigate. ``Their authors don't hesitate to put human
life in danger, and they should be forcefully condemned.''
</P>
<P>
   In an event that may not be connected, three bullets were fired
at the same restaurant a month ago, the mayor of Dinan said
Wednesday. The incident remains unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Wednesday why a McDonald's was targeted. It is
hardly a symbol of the French state. As a symbol of America, the
restaurants in France have been attacked by farmers protesting
globalization and U.S. sanctions on French foods. But Jose Bove,
leader of the Confederation Paysanne farmers union, condemned
Wednesday's attack ``in the strongest possible way,'' saying his
organization conducts its protests openly and without injuring any
people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brittany, in northwest France, historically has its own Celtic
language and was an independent dukedom for centuries until 1491,
when its ruling Duchess Anne married Charles VIII, setting the
stage for annexation in 1532 when their daughter, Claude, became
Queen of France. Its provincial autonomy was further usurped during
the Terror that followed the French Revolution in the 1790s.
</P>
<P>
   Many Bretons supported the monarchy and Catholicism, and the new
government suppressed them, massacring thousands and outlawing the
language. It remained banned for more than a century, but a revival
of its use in schools was tolerated after the Socialist government
took power in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A desire to speak Breton and celebrate its Celtic culture
(including bagpipe music) is strong in Brittany, said Maguy
Kerisit, who is working on a Breton dictionary, but sentiment for
actual independence from France is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement was supposed to have disappeared in the 1970s,''
she said. ``But in the past few months it's been created again.
It's an illegal movement that's said they've done bombings, so
people are in jail in Paris for being members.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittany is rich in agriculture and tourist income, with no
obvious reason for more than the normal discontent with the French
government. ``The independentists say France takes the benefits of
our wealth and gives back less in exchange,'' Kerisit said, ``but
the majority of the population doesn't agree with bombings or
extreme political movements.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said dynamite from the September theft seems to have
been used by ETA in a car bomb attack that killed a Socialist party
leader, Fernando Buesa Blanco, in Spain last February.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonald's worker killed Wednesday was identified as
Laurence Turbec, 28. There were only a handful of customers in the
restaurant at the time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
