<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET SOMEONE ELSE LOOK FOR BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughters and I are impatiently awaiting the arrival of our
first online cosmetics purchase, an order that includes something
described as ``nose strips.'' We also are getting deep pore
cleanser and _ here is the one we are most eager to acquire _ six
packets of self-heating masks.
</P>
<P>
   While we do not know the exact purpose of most of this stuff, my
11-year-old has heard that the mask product consists of a little
package of white lotion flecked with tiny blue specks. She says
that when you rub it on your face, the specks break open and heat
the skin. Her 9-year-old sister thinks this sounds very soothing.
</P>
<P>
   You only need imagine how tense a 9-year-old can get to see how
badly we needed this multi-item Biore beauty kit, which usually
lists for $25.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, my daughters, who have dedicated their lives to the
scientific study of cosmetics and recently tested 41 shades of
lipstick at a sleepover, would have no qualms over the $25 list
price of this Biore multi-item beauty kit. No, their concerns were
research-oriented: Would the specks burn? Would the dye turn their
skin a permanent blue? Would their friends be very, very jealous?
</P>
<P>
   But there was another reason we ordered the kit: It was free _
to any first-time customer at PlanetRx who placed an order of $10
or more at the Web site (www.planetrx.com). Since I needed to buy
Band-Aids and children's vitamins anyway, the blue specks cost me
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I love a good deal. In fact, whenever I shop online, I feel
obligated to get one. Competition among Internet retailers has
become so fierce that I have become conditioned to getting
something _ free shipping, a coupon, half off, something _ for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem has been creating a systematic shopping
strategy. I knew the bargains were out there, but finding them was
hit or miss. Until a couple of weeks ago, I didn't even know
PlanetRx existed. Then I found out about Bargaindog.
</P>
<P>
   Bargaindog points shoppers toward the latest discounts, freebies
and sales offered by about 300 online merchant partners _ including
well-known retailers like J.Crew, Amazon, CDNow and eToys _ who, in
return, give Bargaindog a commission.
</P>
<P>
   I registered at Bargaindog (www.bargaindog.com) and filled out a
survey about my shopping interests. The site tracks 15 categories
of merchandise, like electronics, cooking equipment and pet
supplies. Figuring that no serious shopper would pass up
information about any bargain, I checked all the boxes, indicating
that I was interested in hearing about special deals in all 15
categories.
</P>
<P>
   So what if I never planned to purchase an item like a Lutron
Rotary Dimmer (marked down 50 percent, to $5, at eLights.com) or a
re-sealer to keep potato chips fresh (marked down from $19.99 to
the incredibly low price of $5.95 at YouCanSave.com)?
</P>
<P>
   Once a week, Bargaindog sends me a free, personalized e-mail
newsletter listing more than a dozen of the latest discounts,
freebies and sales in each category. If I am interested in
anything, I can click on the link embedded in the newsletter. That
way, while I shop directly at the retailer's site, the merchant
knows to give Bargaindog credit for referring the sale.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bargaindog has a searchable database of all
bargains that have not expired. As of last week, the list numbered
522, including the PlanetRx offer.
</P>
<P>
   But after I ordered the Biore beauty kit, I had second thoughts.
How did I know if Bargaindog was steering me toward its partners'
offers without bothering to ascertain whether they were the best
deals? So I phoned Josh Schanker, the founder of Bargaindog. ``How
do I know these are real bargains?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Schanker assured me that Bargaindog applied strict criteria.
``Depending on the product category,'' he said, ``we have different
levels of discounts that each product must adhere to. For instance,
all books have to be at least 50 percent off. Electronics, 25
percent. For apparel, at least 35 percent off list price.''
</P>
<P>
   The markdown requirements are based on how much of a discount a
customer might expect to see in specific categories, Schanker said.
``We found that the apparel and home categories are likely to be
deeply discounted. But electronics is probably our least discounted
category. There's a small margin of profit on those items.''
</P>
<P>
   Schanker said Bargaindog employees screen prospective bargains
to ensure ``that merchants will not try to publicize items that are
not really deep discounts.'' So only selected sale items offered by
merchant partners are featured on Bargaindog.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last week I found dozens of items listed for sale
at J.Crew online, marked down as little as 20 percent. But when I
searched for J.Crew on Bargaindog, only two (deeply discounted)
items were listed: corduroy pants, marked down from $49.50 to
$24.99, and a long-sleeve, v-neck sweater, marked down from $20 to
$9.99.
</P>
<P>
   When I searched independently for some of Bargaindog's items
online, I did not find lower prices. For instance, a 10-minute
search for ``Biore'' turned up an offer for six self-heating masks
for $5.99 at shopinprivate.com. I also found the chips re-sealer at
www.asotv.com for $5.99.
</P>
<P>
   Bargaindog also encourages shoppers to rate the bargains.
Concerning the v-neck sweater, for instance, one shopper wrote,
``You can buy the same thing at local discount stores and not have
to pay $5 for shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Schanker said, his favorite way to search the
Bargaindog database is by rating _ choose a category, then click
Sort by Rating _ to see which deals shoppers thought were the best
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you've jumped on bargains yourself?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an occupational hazard,'' he said, describing a time he
ordered 10 personalized Post-it Notes pads from iPrint.com (a
$22.99 value) for $3.20 to cover shipping. ``I think that bargain
is still available,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   You can see why I would need 10 personalized Post-it Notes pads,
can't you? I went to iPrint.com and spent 15 minutes choosing paper
color and font. When they arrive, the pads will say ``ALERT'' in
handwriting that looks like a ransom note.
</P>
<P>
   I am not sure what we will use them for. Maybe to blot
lipstick. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1649EDT &QL; 
