<SLUG> BC-EASTER-COLUMBINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLUMBINE -- AS EASTER -- THE PAIN WILL RECEDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    One year since Columbine. With the passing months, those of us
far from the tragedy have thought of it less often than in those
first few terrible weeks following the rampage. But for those close
to the shooting _ especially the friends and parents of the slain
teenagers_ this must have been an unspeakably painful year.
 &HT;    This week, as thousands of reporters and pilgrims converged to
mark the anniversary of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold's assault,
most locals were leaving town to escape the gaze of national
voyeurism into their private grief.
 &HT;    The reporters and the curious did not necessarily want to
recount the awful details of the killings. They wanted to know
about the healing. Has death brought resurrection to Columbine? A
year has passed. Perhaps Columbine is normal again.
 &HT;    But on a recent ``Nightline,'' ABC's John Donovan reported that
healing is slow and sometimes nonexistent. Anger, rage and despair
are still palpable. During the last year, the people of Littleton,
Colo., have experienced more death: Strange suicides and murders
have riddled the community around the high school.
 &HT;    For those of us who embrace Christianity, this grisly
anniversary parallels another tragic commemoration: Holy Week and
its culmination in Easter. On Thursday, as we marked the memorial
of Columbine, millions also marked the memorial of Jesus' last meal
with his disciples.
 &HT;    In both, unexpected betrayal led to murder of innocents.
Interlaced violence and deathcenturies apartyet undeserved,
unexpected and unwelcome.
 &HT;    This year's eerie correspondence between Columbine and Easter
point toward a discomforting aspect of our national character: We
want quick resurrections. American Christianity has never
emphasized Holy Week _ a supposedly morbid exercise in churchgoing
best left to Lutherans, Episcopalians and Roman Catholics. Most
American Christians ignore Tenebrae (the service of ``darkness''),
Maundy Thursday, Good Friday and Holy Saturday in favor of Easter
celebration.
 &HT;    We celebrate life,not death. We skip the hard part.
 &HT;    If we skip the hard part, however, Easter quickly devolves into
a sentimental celebration of spring_ a sort of demi-Christmas with
a 6-foot bunny who seems cheap in comparison to Santa. But we
prefer it that way. Cute baby chicks and new church clothes delude
us into thinking that faith is an eternal spring.
 &HT;    After all, Christians are called an ``Easter people.'' The
Resurrection is the basis of Christian belief. Why dwell on the bad
stuff that comes before?
 &HT;    The answer is quite simple: Without death, there can be no
resurrection. Winter always comes before spring.
 &HT;    Perhaps Columbine is a spiritual national winter _a long, cold,
unrelenting winter. The kind of winter people in Minnesota and the
Dakotas know. The darkness breaks, the snow melts, and days of
sunshine bring forth daffodils and tulips. It is over!
 &HT;    Then, from nowhere, a blizzard closes in as if it were once
again December. Will spring ever come? Will it ever end?
 &HT;    Holy Week is much the same. Of its shocking events, the mystery
writer Dorothy Sayers once said, ``God was executed by people
painfully like us, in a society very similar to our own.He was
executed by a corrupt church, a timid politician and a fickle
proletariat led by professional agitators. His executioners made
vulgar jokes about Him, called Him filthy names, taunted Him,
smacked Him in the face, flogged Him and hanged Him on the common
gibbet_ a bloody, dusty, sweaty and sordid business.''
 &HT;    Jesus diedbetrayed, tortured and executed. Evil, violent and
maliciously slow. ``He descended to the dead,'' says the ancient
creed. The winter of faith.
 &HT;    Christian tradition proclaims that ``on the third day he rose
again.'' To us, three days seem so short, but to Jesus' followers
it must have seemed as forever. They did not expect resurrection.
Their friend and teacher was dead. They_ especially his mother _
must have been nearly paralyzed by fear and grief from the sudden
violence of his death.
 &HT;    Columbine recalls that ancient suffering while reminding us of
death's wasteland and the agony of healing. Resurrections do not
happen quickly. Nor do they arrive on the cue of the calendar, on
yearly anniversaries, or while reporters are watching.
 &HT;    Healing comes in fits and starts as unexpectedly as spring.
Christian tradition proclaims that new life emerges only from the
darkness of the earthjust as the fragile blades of grass make their
way through frosty soil toward light.
 &HT;    We would prefer an instant miracle, jumping over suffering into
eternal life. But it just does not happen that way. Not even for
God. Easter faith does not avoid pain. It only recognizes that
somewhere, sometime, in some unexpected way, pain will recede in
the gentle grace of God's love.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER20-COX     04-19 2167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: McCain flip-flops, folds flag
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain went to South Carolina Wednesday to say the
Confederate battle flag ``should be removed'' from atop the
Statehouse. He also said he compromised his principles in not
saying so earlier, when the question was a major issue during the
state's Republican primary in February. McCain and George W. Bush
said then they thought it was up to the people of South Carolina
alone to decide. Wednesday, McCain said, ``I feared that if I
answered honestly, I could not win the South Carolina primary. So I
chose to compromise my principles. I broke my promise to always
tell the truth.'' He still lost to Bush. At the time, McCain had
said that his ancestors had ``fought honorably'' on the side of the
Confederacy. Today he said, they had ``fought on the wrong side of
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   SO NEW YORK WOULD BECOME LIKE OTHER STATES?
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Senate approved a plan that would knock down
the state's notorious barriers to putting candidates on the
Republican presidential primary ballot, and would make the primary
a winner-take-all contest. Candidates would get on the ballot if
they raise at least $5,000 in each of 20 states; are certified with
the state elections board as being a nationally recognized and
serious candidate; or collect 5,000 signatures from New Yorkers.
The state Assembly is expected to pass the bill. Republican Gov.
George Pataki, who proposed the changes, had tried to use the
complex access rules to exclude everyone but George W. Bush. A
federal judge eventually opened the ballot to John McCain and other
GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONABLE DONATIONS IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign said Wednesday it will
return a $22,000 donation from a businesswoman linked by
congressional investigators to a drug trafficker. The donation was
made by Vivian Mannerud, whose Airline Brokers Co. runs charter
flights between Cuba and Miami. Mannerud has been linked to drug
smuggler Jorge Cabrera, who made a $20,000 contribution to the
Democratic National Committee in 1995 from a bank account in which
he kept profits from drug trafficking. Clinton's opponent, Rudy
Giuliani, also faced similar questions Wednesday. The New York
Times and Newsday reported that the mayor's campaign committee
received a $100,000 donation from the Renco Group, whose holdings
include Utah-based Magnesium Corporation of America, identified by
the Environmental Protection Agency in 1998 as the nation's top
dumper of toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   SQUEEZING OFF A GUN CONTROL ROUND
</P>
<P>
   To mark the first anniversary of the shootings at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., Al Gore is going to Bergen County,
N.J., today to press for gun control and safe-school initiatives.
Gore will visit Fort Lee High School, near the George Washington
Bridge. Gore is hoping, according to ABC, that his gun control
message will strike a chord in New Jersey, considered an election
day swing state. Gore's staff said Fort Lee High was picked because
of student leaders' efforts to emphasize school safety. ``This is a
school and a community that have been in the forefront of combating
school violence,'' said campaign spokesman Peter Ragone.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING TO THE FAVORITE IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said he would consider offering the No. 2 spot on
the GOP ticket to John McCain. At a press conference in Michigan,
where McCain bested Bush in the primary, Bush said, ``I know he's
said he's not interested, but until I talk to him and find out how
interested or not interested he is, I'll give him consideration.''
Said McCain spokesman Todd Harris : ``Talk like this is always
flattering whether it's from Governor Bush or Jesse Ventura.
However, Senator McCain has made it more than clear that he is not
interested in being vice president.'' Still, the topic may come up
on May 9 in Philadelphia when they have their first face-to-face
meeting since the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION COPS SEE DRESS REHEARSAL
</P>
<P>
   When protesters shut down parts of Washington this week, police
from Los Angeles and Philadelphia were there taking notes. They
hoped the visit would help them prepare for this summer's
Democratic and Republican national conventions _ and learn how to
prevent the kind of violence and vandalism by demonstrators that
marred the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle in December.
Philadelphia police said pepper spray and nightsticks would be used
judiciously _ and only if protesters assault police, resist arrest
or charge barricades. All Los Angeles police officers' vacations
and days off during the mid-August Democratic convention have been
canceled, and the officers are undergoing special training.
</P>
<P>
   THIS WWW. LAUGHS AT W.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission has dismissed a complaint filed
by George W. Bush's campaign committee against a parody Web site.
The FEC said it would rather spend its limited resources
investigating more significant complaints. At issue was a parody
Web site posted by Zack Exley of Somerville, Mass., who satirized
Bush's presidential bid. The home page, for example, features a
campaign logo with the slogan, ``All grown up now.'' Another page
proclaims, ``Hypocrisy with bravado.'' Bush complained about the
Web site last May, calling Exley ``just a garbage man.'' You can
find the Web site at www.gwbush.com _ pretty close to Bush's own
www.georgewbush.com.
</P>
<P>
   WAKING UP FROM THE DREAMWORKS
</P>
<P>
   The news that Hollywood's most prominent Democratic fund-raisers
_ DreamWorks founders Steven Spielberg, David Geffen and Jeffrey
Katzenberg _ plan a break from hosting the glitzy affairs after
November's election may be a sign the industry is reaching its
donor saturation point. ``Donors are getting tired of it. These are
true-blue Democratic donors. You just cannot keep saying `yes'
forever,'' said Larry Makinson, director of the Center for
Responsive Politics. ``I think they may be the first, but they're
not going to be the last.'' Said DreamWorks spokesman Andy Spahn:
``Every political candidate in the country from city council on up
to White House aspirants is likely to call us, write us, ask for a
meeting looking for support, looking for help. It is nonstop, it is
year-round every year. It is a system run amok.''
</P>
<P>
   SILICON VALLEY FERTILE FOR CASH
</P>
<P>
   In the hunt for campaign cash, the Democratic Party is looking
to the high-tech sector, an industry at odds with traditional party
allies such as labor unions and trial lawyers on some key issues.
Republicans hope to use the split to hinder Democratic high-tech
industry fund-raising, but Silicon Valley, unlike most business
groups, has divided its loyalties between the two parties. Computer
companies have made $8.5 million in campaign contributions since
Jan. 1, 1999, according to an Associated Press computer analysis.
These companies donated more than the $8.1 million in 1997-98.
While most business groups lean Republican, more than half of the
high-tech money has gone to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   RESIGNATION HIGHLIGHTS REFORM PARTY RIFT
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party's press secretary resigned, signaling a
widening rift between presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan and allies
of party founder Ross Perot. ``I think she resigned because she
feels that the Buchanan campaign is attempting to take over the
party and is preventing her from being able to do her job,'' said
party secretary Jim Mangia. Donna Donovan will remain chairman of
the Connecticut Reform Party and active in other leadership roles,
Mangia said. Donovan declined to comment, but her resignation is to
take effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan opened a three-week effort to collect the 56,000
petition signatures necessary to appear on Texas ballots as an
independent. Meanwhile, the Reform Party, whose presidential
nomination Buchanan is seeking, is conducting a separate petition
drive to ensure that their candidate, if not Buchanan, also is
listed. ``(Buchanan's) probably just trying to play it safe,'' said
Elizabeth Hanshaw, director of the Texas secretary of state's legal
division. ``You can't appear twice on the ballot, so if he gets the
Reform Party nomination he would probably just withdraw as an
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE PLATFORMS
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is breathing new life into political party
platforms, those long, dry-as-dust documents that in the past often
went unread _ even by the presidential candidates themselves. Two
weeks ago, Cox News Service's Andrew J. Glass reports, Al Gore
launched a plan that lets anybody draft a plank online for the
upcoming party platform. By Tuesday, more than 2,000 people had
done so and received ``personalized'' thank-you letters from Gore
and Democratic national Chairman Joe Andrew. Speakout.com, a
for-profit site, supplies sophisticated software that lets users
easily cut, paste and edit parts of the 1996 Democratic platform to
create their own 2000 version. Jim Nicholson, the GOP chairman, has
bought into a more modest set of interactive tools from the same
site, including chat rooms, surveys and e-mail messages to
candidates and other political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   THEY AIN'T JUST WHISTLING `DIXIE'
</P>
<P>
   Defying the NAACP's tourism boycott of South Carolina, the newly
formed Southern Party will hold its national convention June 30 and
July 1 in Charleston. ``Please join us in the marvelous festivities
we are putting together to celebrate the rebirth of the South's
political effort to regain independence and self determination
through the ballot box,'' the party announced on its Web site,
www.southernparty.org. Among the party's aims are ``to defend the
proud heritage of Dixie from attack,'' with the ultimate goal of
``a free and independent Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH RAMPS UP, GORE GEARS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Sounding almost like a Democrat, Republican George W. Bush
unveils an education agenda one day, headline-grabbing health care
and environmental initiatives the next, an affordable-housing plan
after that. But where's Al Gore? It may seem as though the real
Democrat in the race is taking a nap during this springtime lull in
the campaign. But Gore put his policy proposals on the table months
ago. And after one splashy misstep in the Elian Gonzalez firestorm,
Gore is executing a low-watt strategy to gain consistency for his
message, cash for his party, and a homespun shine to his public
image. Gore's schedule these days is dominated by almost daily fund
raising _ with severely restricted press coverage.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY GAP IN PENNSYLVANIA
</P>
<P>
   For months, Democrats have believed that Sen. Rick Santorum,
R-Pa., was one of the more vulnerable targets in their bid to
recapture control of the Senate. But the Democratic nominee, Rep.
Ron Klink, a moderate from the Pittsburgh area, won a very costly
victory in his party's primary. Klink's treasury is saddled with
more than $446,000 in debts and he has only $119,000 in the bank,
according to the latest Federal Election Commission records.
Because Santorum faced no opposition in the Republican primary, he
enjoys an enormous financial edge. He's raised $6 million and has
more than $3.7 million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   FEINSTEIN'S OPPONENT THIS TIME NOT AS RICH
</P>
<P>
   For months, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., has held an
overwhelming lead in the polls over her Republican challenger, Rep.
Tom Campbell, and in the latest fund-raising period, she collected
nearly twice as much money. From Feb. 17 through the end of March,
Feinstein took in $988,000 and spent about $360,000. All told, she
had about $2.2 million in cash on hand. By contrast, Campbell
reported raising $565,000 in the latest period, and spent almost
$700,000, leaving him with $615,000 in his war chest. In
Feinstein's last race, in 1994, her opponent, Michael Huffington,
spent $26 million, much of it his own money, and she spent less
than $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   ONE BY THE WAYSIDE IN NEBRASKA
</P>
<P>
   One of five candidates for the GOP nomination for retiring
Democratic Sen. Bob Kerrey's seat dropped out of the race. Dr.
Elliott Rustad, 66, was a distant second in the Republican field
behind state Attorney General Don Stenberg, according to his
polling. ``In order to win I would have to wage a (negative)
campaign that could divide the Republican Party and that I'm not
willing to do,'' he said. Rustad's decision narrows the GOP field,
but not by much. Stenberg, agribusinessman David Hergert, Secretary
of State Scott Moore and former state Sen. John DeCamp are still in
it. Ex-Gov. Ben Nelson is the likely Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
