<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX     04-19 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's fuss about Internet page draws more negative light than
site
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Dubya made a big mistake when he sicced his guard
dogs onto New Yorker Zack Exley, who launched a Web site named
gwbush.com.
</P>
<P>
   Exley is no Bush fan. He grabbed up the gwbush domain name, paid
his registration fee and built a Web page that does its best to
trash the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a lot of people searching for the authentic George W.
Bush Web campaign page (georgewbush.com) will be drawn to Exley's
anti-Bush Web page.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt this is what Exley, a computer consultant, had in mind
when he registered his gwbush.com Web page that announces ``George
W. Bush For President'' and then goes on to parody and skewer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   By publicly complaining about Exley's Web site and filing an
official objection to the site with the Federal Election
Commission, Bush managed to send many thousands of viewers to
Exley's Web site who quite naturally wanted to see what all the
fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   Now the FEC has dismissed the official Bush complaint because
the commission has bigger fish to fry. The commission doesn't want
to waste valuable bureaucratic time on such a low priority issue.
</P>
<P>
   FEC officials really didn't want to rule on the Bush complaint.
Bureaucrats don't last long in Washington by sticking their necks
out, even if they stand up for something as basic as freedom of
speech.
</P>
<P>
   After all, like everyone else, the bureaucrats heard Bush
explain his opposition to Exley's Web site by telling reporters,
``There ought to be limits to freedom.'' Anyone willing to limit
freedom might also be willing to limit bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   To show what a big mistake it was to complain about gwbush.com,
Bush's remark about limiting freedom sent more thousands of people
in search of the Web page. Now the remark appears on bumper
stickers and T-shirts sold on the Web site along with other
anti-Bush paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as well that the FEC punted on the Bush complaint
because the agency has shown a tendency to crack down on citizens
who post Web pages in order to express their political opinions,
either for or against specific candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC has warned that if citizens spend enough money building
Web pages that support or oppose political candidates, then those
people might be required to register as political action
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the agency ruled that a Web site that supported a
Connecticut congressional candidate should be treated as a campaign
expenditure for committing the sin of urging voters to support a
specific candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That may be what Bush had in mind when he said there ought to be
limits on freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for Congress to limit the free flow of unlimited
cash that currently pours into the coffers of the major political
parties _ a campaign reform idea that Bush opposes _ and quite
another thing to limit a private person's expression of his own
political opinions in support or opposition of specific candidates.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush or FEC bureaucrats are really worried about corruption
of America's electoral process, they should oppose unlimited soft
money donations from wealthy special-interest corporations, unions
and others that distort the principle of one-person, one-vote.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Internet is like a giant soap box.
Everyone is free to stand on their Internet soap box and spout off.
It's a global marketplace of ideas, facts, distortions and
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it's free.
</P>
<P>
   The gwbush.com Web site is a thorn in the candidate's side. The
barb would not be in so deep, nor would it be so infected, had Bush
ignored it. Self-inflicted wounds are always a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
