<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EASTER-COLUMBINE-NYTS     04-19 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-COLUMBINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLUMBINE -- AS EASTER -- THE PAIN WILL RECEDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    One year since Columbine. With the passing months, those of us
far from the tragedy have thought of it less often than in those
first few terrible weeks following the rampage. But for those close
to the shooting _ especially the friends and parents of the slain
teenagers_ this must have been an unspeakably painful year.
 &HT;    This week, as thousands of reporters and pilgrims converged to
mark the anniversary of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold's assault,
most locals were leaving town to escape the gaze of national
voyeurism into their private grief.
 &HT;    The reporters and the curious did not necessarily want to
recount the awful details of the killings. They wanted to know
about the healing. Has death brought resurrection to Columbine? A
year has passed. Perhaps Columbine is normal again.
 &HT;    But on a recent ``Nightline,'' ABC's John Donovan reported that
healing is slow and sometimes nonexistent. Anger, rage and despair
are still palpable. During the last year, the people of Littleton,
Colo., have experienced more death: Strange suicides and murders
have riddled the community around the high school.
 &HT;    For those of us who embrace Christianity, this grisly
anniversary parallels another tragic commemoration: Holy Week and
its culmination in Easter. On Thursday, as we marked the memorial
of Columbine, millions also marked the memorial of Jesus' last meal
with his disciples.
 &HT;    In both, unexpected betrayal led to murder of innocents.
Interlaced violence and deathcenturies apartyet undeserved,
unexpected and unwelcome.
 &HT;    This year's eerie correspondence between Columbine and Easter
point toward a discomforting aspect of our national character: We
want quick resurrections. American Christianity has never
emphasized Holy Week _ a supposedly morbid exercise in churchgoing
best left to Lutherans, Episcopalians and Roman Catholics. Most
American Christians ignore Tenebrae (the service of ``darkness''),
Maundy Thursday, Good Friday and Holy Saturday in favor of Easter
celebration.
 &HT;    We celebrate life,not death. We skip the hard part.
 &HT;    If we skip the hard part, however, Easter quickly devolves into
a sentimental celebration of spring_ a sort of demi-Christmas with
a 6-foot bunny who seems cheap in comparison to Santa. But we
prefer it that way. Cute baby chicks and new church clothes delude
us into thinking that faith is an eternal spring.
 &HT;    After all, Christians are called an ``Easter people.'' The
Resurrection is the basis of Christian belief. Why dwell on the bad
stuff that comes before?
 &HT;    The answer is quite simple: Without death, there can be no
resurrection. Winter always comes before spring.
 &HT;    Perhaps Columbine is a spiritual national winter _a long, cold,
unrelenting winter. The kind of winter people in Minnesota and the
Dakotas know. The darkness breaks, the snow melts, and days of
sunshine bring forth daffodils and tulips. It is over!
 &HT;    Then, from nowhere, a blizzard closes in as if it were once
again December. Will spring ever come? Will it ever end?
 &HT;    Holy Week is much the same. Of its shocking events, the mystery
writer Dorothy Sayers once said, ``God was executed by people
painfully like us, in a society very similar to our own.He was
executed by a corrupt church, a timid politician and a fickle
proletariat led by professional agitators. His executioners made
vulgar jokes about Him, called Him filthy names, taunted Him,
smacked Him in the face, flogged Him and hanged Him on the common
gibbet_ a bloody, dusty, sweaty and sordid business.''
 &HT;    Jesus diedbetrayed, tortured and executed. Evil, violent and
maliciously slow. ``He descended to the dead,'' says the ancient
creed. The winter of faith.
 &HT;    Christian tradition proclaims that ``on the third day he rose
again.'' To us, three days seem so short, but to Jesus' followers
it must have seemed as forever. They did not expect resurrection.
Their friend and teacher was dead. They_ especially his mother _
must have been nearly paralyzed by fear and grief from the sudden
violence of his death.
 &HT;    Columbine recalls that ancient suffering while reminding us of
death's wasteland and the agony of healing. Resurrections do not
happen quickly. Nor do they arrive on the cue of the calendar, on
yearly anniversaries, or while reporters are watching.
 &HT;    Healing comes in fits and starts as unexpectedly as spring.
Christian tradition proclaims that new life emerges only from the
darkness of the earthjust as the fragile blades of grass make their
way through frosty soil toward light.
 &HT;    We would prefer an instant miracle, jumping over suffering into
eternal life. But it just does not happen that way. Not even for
God. Easter faith does not avoid pain. It only recognizes that
somewhere, sometime, in some unexpected way, pain will recede in
the gentle grace of God's love.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-EASTER-COLUMBINE-NYTS     04-19 0937
