<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TRANSLAT     04-19 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TRANSLATIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS WEB USE EXPANDS WORLDWIDE, TRANSLATION SOFTWARE MUST ADJUST 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of the Internet as the ultimate global village _ the
medium that will allow people around the world to connect and
communicate _ may be facing its ultimate test. As the community of
non-English speaking people online grows, companies are racing to
support the numerous languages of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The demographics of the Internet are changing fast. Non-English
speakers make up nearly half of the online population, researchers
say. As a result, companies are looking for ways to allow these
Netizens to communicate in their native tongues. One of the
obstacles to achieving that goal has been the limited state of
machine translation services and multilingual communication tools.
</P>
<P>
   Based on international polls and census information, Global
Reach, a technology research firm in San Francisco, estimates that
128 million of the almost 280 million people who use the Internet
speak languages other than English. Jupiter Communications, a
technology research group in New York City, estimates that the
number of non-English speakers will surpass English speakers in
2001. Jupiter estimates that online households in Europe and on the
Pacific Rim will more than double by 2002. In response to this
international boom, companies like Yahoo!, Amazon and eToys have
created local versions of their sites that include specialized
information in the appropriate language. But these customized sites
are in the minority. Jupiter reports that fewer than one-third of
major online companies have localized sites for their international
customers. With the increased globalization of Web denizens,
companies are improving and developing software to meet growing
demands for translation services.
</P>
<P>
   Machine translation, introduced in the 1950s, has become one of
the more common ways of breaking down the language barriers online.
In December 1997, the AltaVista search portal introduced a popular
version of machine translation for the World Wide Web. Called
Babelfish _ a term used by Douglas Adams, the author of ``The
Hitchhikers Guide to the Galaxy,'' to describe an imagined
universal translation device _ AltaVista's service
(http://world.altavista.com/) translates text between 13 language
pairs, including English to French, Italian to English, and German
to French. To use the site, visitors type or cut and paste text
into a window, select the appropriate language pair and click on a
button for a quick and easy translation.
</P>
<P>
   Many surfers have made sport of trading the sometimes comical
results of translation devices. In one popular example, ``Melts in
your mouth, not in your hands'' becomes, in French, ``Fontes dans
votre bouche, pas dans des vos mains.'' But, when translated back
into English, the phrase becomes: ``Pig iron and cast iron in your
mouth, not in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the developers of the software see the problem. They often
refer to their work as ``gist'' translations, automated conversions
that, at best, let the user know the main thrust of a particular
bit of text from an e-mail, word-processing document or Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Creating effective machine translation software requires a
formidable effort. Lernout and Hauspie, a Belgium-based developer
of speech and language technologies employs a staff of linguists
and lexicographers from 18 countries. Systems are designed
according to language pairs. The company has 15 pairs and is
working to add others, but developing just one pair of languages _
Korean and Chinese, for example _ can take up to 18 months, said
Jeff Hopkins, vice president of engineering for L&AMP;H.
</P>
<P>
   First, Hopkins said, lexicographers translate words and
structures according to the rules of the target language, deciding,
for example, what is a verb and what is a noun. Next, they connect
words in appropriate pairs. Then the selected words are rearranged
according to the rules of the target language. The process is
nearly instantaneous, and, almost always, is less than perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we're trying to model the human brain,'' Hopkins
said, ``and since no one really knows how the brain works, no one
knows how to truly model it.''
</P>
<P>
   While engineers try to solve this problem, translation companies
like L&AMP;H and the French company Systran are trying to customize
their gist services. L&AMP;H's iTranslator Enterprise is specialized
for medical, legal and business languages. Like L&AMP;H, Systran offers
customized services to corporate customers who would like
translation software tailored to their particular business needs.
``If a visitor comes to their site and can't communicate,'' said
Denis Gachout, Systran's president, ``then that site is
increasingly going to lose sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving customers a means to communicate is the most recent step
in the evolution of the multilingual Web. Because of the limits of
most PC keyboards and machine translation sites, it has been
difficult, if not impossible, for non-English speakers who do not
use the Roman alphabet to, say, compose e-mails or post messages on
a Web site in their own languages.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail programs of Microsoft and Yahoo allow users to
receive messages in a handful of languages, but require special
software. Now, competing start-ups have created free software that
allows users to quickly and easily type in non-Roman characters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Umair Khan, the 30-year-old founder of eGlyphs Inc.
(www.eglyphs.com), a start-up in Palo Alto, Calif., that
specializes in multilingual applications, devised such a program
after he found that could not send e-mails to other Pakistanis.
Three years ago, Khan, a former Intel engineer, developed a Web
site that allowed people to communicate with each other in Urdu.
</P>
<P>
   The success of that site led to the Everymail.com last November.
Everymail, an onscreen virtual keyboard program, allows users to
type characters in 34 languages including Thai, Icelandic and
Vietnamese. To type, users either click each letter with the mouse
or type with matching keys on the keyboard. Similar programs expand
these services into other communication areas online _ Everychat,
for chat, and Everyforum, for message boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our offerings share one goal,'' Khan said, ``to let you go
on the Web and start immediately typing in your own language.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jerusalem company, Slangsoft.com, has developed similar
technology that allows Internet surfers to interact with any Web
site in a choice of 42 languages. The software, called Emule, uses
the Java programming code so that users can instantaneously
communicate in the languages without having to download special
fonts or large plug-in files.
</P>
<P>
   Like Everymail, Emule creates a virtual keyboard with customized
language characters. The Emule technology is in use on sites like
AltaVista and Looksmart.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, like Tegic and Zi Corp., are developing
multilingual text-input programs, and companies are also working to
bring their services to wireless devices like cellular phones and
personal digital assistants. Lernout and Hauspie's iTranslator
Wireless is available for users of the Palm VII digital organizer.
Like the desktop version, the iTranslator Wireless language pairs
include English and French, English and German, and Spanish and
French.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
