<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific tops profit predictions
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia-Pacific Group easily beat estimates for
first-quarter earnings, thanks in part to soaring prices in the
pulp and paper business.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group said Wednesday that first-quarter profit
nearly doubled to $194 million, or $1.11 a share, compared with
year-ago profit of $99 million, or 56 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded by nudging Georgia-Pacific's stock up 18
3/4 cents to $36.50.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group was expected to earn $1.02 a share, based
on a survey of analysts by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the first quarter jumped 60 percent to $5.38 billion,
up from $3.35 billion, boosted by last summer's acquisition of
paper distributor Unisource Worldwide. Unisource, the nation's
largest distributor of paper products and janitorial supplies,
contributed $1.73 billion in revenue during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Global demand for paper is strong as the Asian markets continue
to recover. And that's pushing prices up. Prices for some paper
grades jumped more than 35 percent over the past year, while prices
for the pulp used to make paper surged 40 percent, according to
industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific is the world's second-largest supplier of pulp,
behind Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
   Most major players in forest products surpassed expectations for
the first quarter. International Paper, Champion International,
Boise Cascade and Weyerhaeuser all recently reported profits that
easily beat estimates. Mead was the exception with an earnings
report on Wednesday that fell short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Strong paper markets helped to boost profit all around.
Georgia-Pacific's pulp and paper business had a 10-fold increase in
operating profit, to $129 million. The paper distribution business
reported operating profit of $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific's containerboard and packaging segment posted a
sharp increase in first-quarter operating profit, to $131 million
from $35 million one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lower prices for plywood and lumber, though, dragged down profit
in other segments. Georgia-Pacific's building products business had
a sharp decrease in operating profit to $191 million, against $248
million.
</P>
<P>
   And the distribution segment of the building products business
reported operating profit of $14 million in the first quarter, down
from $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s timber business also
reported better-than-expected results for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. posted net income of $40 million, or 49 cents a
share, compared with $47 million, or 54 cents a share, in the
year-ago period. Timber Co. was expected to earn 46 cents a share,
according to a survey of analysts by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue was $102 million against $141 million.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. shares closed Wednesday at $24.43, up 93 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
