<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SURVEY FINDS PARENTS ARE KEY TO HALTING SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year after the nation's worst outbreak of school
violence, most Americans believe that parents _ not school
officials _ bear responsibility for preventing future campus
tragedies, according to a survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the survey said the findings underscore that the
shootings at Columbine High School in suburban Denver last April 20
``shape the way parents and non-parents alike view the issue of
school violence.'' About 71 percent of parents surveyed said the
attack has colored their perceptions of school safety.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1,000 adults, including 283 parents, was conducted
by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Some 85 percent of respondents said parents are responsible for
raising their children not to commit violence while only 9 percent
said the responsibility rests with teachers and counselors at
schools.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why kids commit such violence, a plurality of
respondents, 42 percent, placed the blame squarely on poor
parenting, while 26 percent cited violence in the media that
children are exposed to and 14 percent singled out peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Only 40 percent of respondents with children felt that their
kids were ``very safe'' at school, and 50 percent rated schools
only ``somewhat safe.'' However, 17 percent of parents said schools
were downright dangerous places and that there have been ``serious
threats of violence'' involving children at their own local
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted April 12 _16.
</P>
<P>
   Around lunchtime last April 20, Columbine students Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold, both armed with automatic weapons and
explosives, began a terrifying rampage that ended when they shot
themselves after fatally shooting 12 students and one teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the attack at Columbine, other recent school
shootings have drawn national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, a teenager opened fire with a rifle, wounding six
classmates in Conyers, Ga. In December, a 13-year-old student
opened fire at a middle school in Fort Gibson, Okla. In February, a
6-year-old was accused of fatally shooting a classmate in Mount
Morris Township, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Columbine, President Clinton and some members of
Congress have been pushing for new gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey found that most Americans continue to support gun
control _ nearly two-thirds of respondents said gun restrictions
are more important to uphold and enforce than the rights of gun
owners.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also found that Americans are not convinced that
additional gun control measures would lessen overall violent crime.
In fact, in a separate survey of 1,184 adults by the Pew Research
Center in March, a majority _ 59 percent _ said it was more
important that law enforcement officials enforce existing gun
control laws than to enact new ones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
