<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COCONUT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plain or fancy, symbol of southern hospitality always has a
place on holiday tables
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sand may not be the best addition to a coconut cake, but it's
the one I remember best.
</P>
<P>
   Orange-tinted, the cake was sprinkled with dried flakes and
wrapped in crinkly cellophane, purchased hurriedly at a grocery
near the beach. And it was enough to make me feel mighty special.
</P>
<P>
   If you're as big a coconut-lover as I have been since before
that fifth birthday, any time a coconut cake appears ... well,
nothing is going to mar the occasion _ not even a stinging
windstorm that blows it full of sand. You will eat it anyway, grit
and all, feeling lucky indeed even if it is store-bought.
</P>
<P>
   But if someone makes you a coconut cake, now that is the royal
treatment. Not only are they catering to your fancy, they are
tackling a cake that is not the easiest or quickest to make. I have
heard of coconut cakes that take eight days to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know somebody loves you if they make you a coconut cake,''
says Nathalie Dupree, standing in her Social Circle kitchen
revising a relatively quick scratch version for her next cookbook.
It takes just over an hour from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend and employee for almost 30 years, Kate Almand,
presides over a pot of gurgling, gritslike goo that she will gently
pat onto the still-warm layers.
</P>
<P>
   Every Christmas, Almand cracks a few coconuts to make two cakes
and freezes some of the liquid and grated meat for birthdays and
Easter, when tinted green flakes hide jelly bean eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut sales peak around holidays. Baker's Coconut says its
sales at Easter follow only Thanksgiving and Christmas, and sales
are consistently strongest in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners have embraced the coconut palm seed pods since they
were used as ballast on ships during the Civil War and unloaded
cheaply. It didn't take long to transform them into a symbol of
Southern hospitality at its grandest _ a feathery white cake
sitting on a crystal stand, a slice nearby on a bone china dessert
plate flanked by an ornate silver fork and starched linen napkin.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants, too _ from the homey to the tony _ like to set out
the old-fashioned favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Mother's Day, Easter and Christmas are peaks for Emma Bridges'
coconut cake at Historic Green Manor in Union City. Her whipped
cream and sour cream cake is in the top three every day, but on
special occasions soars to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Barbara Green said out-of-state customers call ahead to
make sure there will be some on the buffet table.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges doesn't remember where she got her recipe, but said her
grandmother had a cake on the table every Sunday. As she's
developed the recipe, Bridges said she's come to prefer frozen
coconut but has made the cake in a pinch with a mix and dried
flakes.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Levy, an Atlanta food stylist and writer, adores coconut
cake so much, she confesses that she sometimes goes to Capri
Italian American Cafe in Tucker and orders a bowl of soup and slice
of coconut cake as her meal.
</P>
<P>
   For this article, she tested the ultra-extravagant version from
Carroll Street Bakery in Cabbagetown to fulfill a reader's request
for the recipe _ and proclaimed it the best, bar none, she's ever
tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heart attack on a plate, but what a way to go,'' she
sighed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far less experienced baker Dupree is aiming for while
revising the recipe from her ``New Southern Cooking'' published in
1986. Changes include describing the coconut that shoppers may
encounter in stores, stressing using coconut and liquid drained
from a whole coconut and adding to the icing's cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to cook it (the icing) till it makes an almost vulgar
sound,'' Dupree says. Butter and sugar won't be ``creamed,''
they'll be ``stirred,'' a concession to new bakers who didn't grow
up around somebody like Almand, who makes a cake of some kind every
week.
</P>
<P>
   With three children, 10 grandchildren and two
great-grandchildren, Almand, 74, has tried lots of recipes for
special-occasion cakes and observed preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most little ones like a chocolate cake better than anything,''
says Almand, who has often seen tastes turn when the kids reach
their teens and embrace her own favorite _ her coconut cake. This
is not the pristine white cake with fluffy Seven-Minute Icing many
think of as the Southern standard. Nor does it go for a wider
audience with additions like pineapple or lemon filling or cream
cheese or whipped cream frosting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cake is a nothing cake, really. But it's a perfect foil
for the coconut,'' Dupree says, claiming it's best after sitting
three days but rarely lasts through one.
</P>
<P>
   Almand and Dupree both believe it's best to start with a whole
coconut, draining and straining the liquid and grating the meat.
But they test it with substitutes more likely to be used by readers
_ canned ``lite'' coconut milk and fresh frozen unsweetened grated
coconut. Dried packaged or canned flakes or shreds may be
acceptable on some other cakes with ``a little more personality on
their own,'' Dupree says.
</P>
<P>
   After they've considered a range of options and coconut products
they agree: This is the one to make for a coconut-cake lover.
</P>
<P>
   Proof is in the first warm bite.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
