<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1547 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-TALK20-COX     04-19 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TALK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's gift: Country ham
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yumiko Baron, by all reports, is not one to shy away
from a culinary adventure. A chef in Boulder, Colo., she didn't
flinch one bit when her husband brought home a country ham, even
though she had no clue how to prepare it. She studied up and set
about baking.
</P>
<P>
   Then she called South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the directions and I soaked it for nearly a day,''
Baron told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's fine,'' I replied. (Soaking times can vary; some
skip it and scrub the skin instead.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I baked it in the oven,'' she went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' I said. (Some boil it, but most don't have a pot that
big, so oven steaming is the way to go.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's very, very salty,'' Baron said next. ``And kind of
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I exclaimed. ``You've got country ham!''
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause. ``Well, what do I do with it now?'' Baron
asked.
</P>
<P>
   For the unaccustomed, I suppose country ham is an acquired taste
much like the sushi from Baron's home country of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the South, ham that is dry-cured with salt and aged
is worth a celebration, especially this time of year when the fall
hams have had time to put on six months of flavor. It's no wonder
country hams have been a part of post-Lenten celebrations for ages.
There's nothing restrained about its toothsome-chewy texture and
lusty-salty taste.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in western Kentucky, I came to adore the neighbors
who offered country hams as holiday gifts. Now, I always stop by
Broadbent's in Cadiz on my way to Kuttawa. Or I search out the
packs of Clifty Farms ``biscuit cuts'' (small slices) in the meat
department of area grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Split biscuit sandwiches are the best way to enjoy country ham,
as I explained to Baron. I prefer a palm-size, soft and tender
biscuit to pair with thick, chewy ham slices. The ladies in
Louisville slice thinly and serve with silver-dollar-size beaten
biscuits, which are crackerlike and not to my liking.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond biscuits and breakfast, ``even the tiniest sliver of
country ham contributes rich flavor to a simple dish,'' explains
Marietta resident Elaine J. Harvell and her co-author Jeanne Voltz
in ``The Country Ham Book'' (University of North Carolina Press,
$16.95).
</P>
<P>
   For country ham lovers and novices alike, this book is a must.
Harvell and Voltz offer ham history, personal history and a hog's
worth of ideas for using country ham, from seasoning greens to
slicing paper-thin and serving with grilled figs.
</P>
<P>
   Below is the recipe for the classic country ham sidekick _
red-eye gravy _ from Harvell's book. Inside(bottom of page),
there's a source list and a divine recipe for country ham and sage
bread. You'll want to make it for Easter brunch I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   red-eye gravy
</P>
<P>
   Fry small, thin pieces of ham in a heavy skillet until browned,
adding a bit of oil if the ham is very lean. Keep the fried ham
pieces warm. Skim off some of the fat, but not too much because the
bubble of fat is the ``red eye.'' Pour 1/2 cup or so of hot coffee
or hot water in the pan over medium heat. Boil a minute or two and
scrape up the brown bits. You'll have an excellent sauce for
biscuits, grits or rice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   I first made this bread (a Barbara Kafka recipe) last spring,
and since then it has held its place as my all-time favorite
homemade bread. I served it throughout the spring, at my Fourth of
July brunch and again during fall vacation on Jekyll Island. When
it bakes, it fills the house with the most savory aroma. Hot from
the oven, slice and butter. The next day, make toast or the world's
best grilled cheese sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Country Ham and Sage Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Rising time: 2 hours, 40 minutes
Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sage leaves, thinly sliced crosswise and then finely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil, plus additional for oiling
</P>
<P>
   rolling pin and pan
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces country ham, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   (about 1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   Pour 3/4 cup warm water into a medium mixing bowl and sprinkle
yeast on top. Allow to sit for 5 to 10 minutes, or until top of
water is covered with a beige foam. Stir in the sage, olive oil and
1 cup of flour until smooth. Stir in salt and remaining flour,
until flour is absorbed and dough comes together in a ball around
the spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Turn dough out onto a work surface. With lightly floured hands,
knead dough until smooth and elastic, about 4 minutes. Shape into a
ball. Place in a lightly oiled bowl and turn to coat with oil.
Cover with a clean kitchen towel and place in a warm spot for 1
hour or until doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil a rolling pin. Turn dough out onto work surface and
roll into a 11-inch square. Place half the ham dice over the dough
in a diamond pattern; the points of the diamond should be at the
midpoints of the sides of the dough square.
</P>
<P>
   Take the corners of the dough and fold them in so that they meet
at the center of the dough square. Pinch dough together to seal in
the ham. Roll dough out again into an 11-inch square. Arrange
remaining ham over dough in a diamond pattern as above. Fold
corners into the center and seal once more. Let dough rest for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Roll dough back into an 11-inch square, then roll dough up like
a jelly roll. Tuck ends under and place in a well-oiled 8 1/2-by-4
1/2-inch loaf pan. Cover loosely with a towel. Let stand in a warm
place until doubled in bulk, about 1 hour 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Position rack in lower third of
oven, place loaf pan in center and bake 50-60 minutes, until bread
sounds hollow when tapped on top. Turn out of pan and cool
completely before serving (if you can wait that long).
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 110 calories, 4 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 37), 13 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 383 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Kithchen conversations with Reagan Walker for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
