<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A welcome throwback
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Standing over the body of Bad Boy Records, the referee that is
general public opinion thought Sean ``Puffy'' Combs' label was down
for the count.
</P>
<P>
   One! Bad Boy artist and one of hip-hop's best, the Notorious
B.I.G., killed three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two! Mase, Bad Boy's burgeoning sex symbol, gives up the music
for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Thr...wait a minute. Bad Boy struggles back up and releases
rapper Black Rob's impressive debut. Now comes Carl Thomas, an
undisputed heavyweight in the small ring of real soul men.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' engagingly simple first single about loving a married
woman, ``I Wish,'' and ``Summer Rain'' _ and, really, most of this
record _ feel old. As if from a time when black music was broadly
arranged, as on ``Hey Now.'' And instead of artists' using lyrics
as a launching pad for their technical abilities, they were used to
tell stories, as this supple vocalist does with ``Givin' You All My
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Making ``Emotional,'' overall, substantive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotional''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Thomas. Bad Boy/Arista. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
