<HEADER>
A1550 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX     04-19 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ecstasy''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Reed. Reprise. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   For Lou Reed, the glass is rarely half full or half empty. More
often it's shattered, the shards sparkling like diamonds in dim
light. That dark perspective illuminates the world Reed has
inhabited since his Velvet Underground days. Rock's street-poet
laureate, Reed crafts songs of hustlers and hoods that have the
repellent draw of a roadside wreck: you hate to look; you have to
look. ``Ecstasy'' offers another of Reed's through-a-subway-window
glimpses of the dark side. And the view, while not pretty, is a
thing of strange beauty that ranks with his best. Some of what's
here hinges on self-parody, with Reed's half-spoken vocals dull and
affected. But rockers like ``Modern Dance,'' the riveting ``Like a
Possum'' and pornographic ``Rock Minuet'' are worthy successors to
his ``Walk on the Wild Side.''
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Punishing Kiss''
</P>
<P>
   Ute Lemper. Decca. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Germans have long had a flair for the dramatic. From Wagner to
the metal maniacs in Rammstein, it seems part of their nature. Ute
Lemper carries on the proud tradition. Though best known as a
cabaret performer, Lemper has won an Olivier (the Brit equivalent
of the Tony) for her performance in Kander and Ebb's ``Chicago.''
She takes on modern pop songs here, but her theatrical roots show
in every line she sings. The word sing, though, is inadequate to
describe what Lemper does to these songs, written by such
formidable songwriters as Scott Walker, Elvis Costello and the
Divine Comedy's Neil Hannon. She gets inside them, taking
possession of them with her versatile voice _ alternately gruff,
sweet or sexy, but always captivating. She's right at home with
Brecht/Weill's ``Tango Ballad,'' and a Brechtian heaviness
permeates the album. You get an inkling of that before you even
hear the album, with song titles such as Costello's ``Couldn't You
Keep That to Yourself'' and Tom Waits' ``The Part You Throw Away.''
It's dark, but what gorgeous gloom.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on Carl Thomas, Bad Boy Records:
www.badboy-ent.com/
</P>
<P>
   More on Ute Lemper: www.deccaclassics.com
</P>
<P>
   More on Lou Reed: www.repriserec.com/loureed
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
