<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-SHELBYLYNNE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retro '60s sounds from a soul sister today
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember soul music? That hip-grinding, gut-wailing sound that
was the sweaty, Brut-drenched essence of Al Green and Marvin Gaye?
Just when it seems like rap has pretty much made the genre passe,
here comes a 31-year-old former country singer from Alabama to show
us what we've been missing.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby Lynne has recorded what is possibly one of the smartest
and most provocative albums to arrive in stores since Aretha
Franklin wore a size 12. She's done it by dusting off late 1960s
production techniques that became the signature sound of legendary
labels such as Stax, Volt and Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   It's Aretha's ``Do Right Woman'' meets Dusty Springfield's
``Dusty in Memphis,'' the album most often cited as Lynne's
inspiration. And it works. This is not just clever mimicry. The
tunes, all penned by Lynne, are contemporary pop/soul masterpieces.
Lynne's voice is equally as crafted, infused with a Southern
earthiness. After nearly a decade of spinning her wheels in
Nashville, Lynne has emerged a major talent as a soul sister.
</P>
<P>
   `I Am Shelby Lynne'
</P>
<P>
   Shelby Lynne / Island / 10 tracks / Our critic's grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : For more information on Shelby Lynne:
www.geocities.com/Nashville/3139/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
