<HEADER>
A1552 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-COCONUT-SIDE20-COX     04-19 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCONUT-SIDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coconut tips
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh green coconut
</P>
<P>
   A truly fresh coconut is a green coconut, sometimes sold at
farmers' markets. Scoop the jellylike insides out with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Ripe coconut
</P>
<P>
   The ripe, brown, barklike coconuts common in produce sections at
most grocery stores are dried, though they are often referred to as
``fresh'' to distinguish them from the further-dried flaked or
shredded products sold in packages and cans.
</P>
<P>
   When a recipe calls for fresh coconut, it more than likely means
draining and cracking a brown coconut. These tips, unless otherwise
noted, are from Kate Almand, who works with Nathalie Dupree.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buying: Look for coconuts with no dusty or moldy appearance in
the ``eyes.'' Shake to make sure they are full of liquid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To drain: Use a hammer and clean nail or screwdriver to poke
holes in two of the ``eyes'' all the way through to the liquid
center. Drain liquid into a bowl, then strain through cheesecloth.
If you notice a musty odor when the coconut is drained, discard it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To grate: Heating a drained coconut helps loosen the flesh
from the covering. If after heating 10 minutes in a 375-degree oven
the coconut is not cracked, TV chef Sara Moulton suggests wrapping
it in a kitchen towel and whacking it on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A microwave method comes from Barbara Kafka in ``The Microwave
Gourmet'': Put drained coconut in a microwave-safe bag, seal
completely and heat on high for about 6 1/2 minutes. Remove from
the bag, add any liquid that has collected to the liquid reserved.
The husk should be cracked and the flesh can be lifted out.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the brown papery coating can be pared away with a
vegetable peeler or small sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   Put chunks in the food processor to grate. You should have about
2 to 2 1/2 cups of grated coconut.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coconut milk: Milk is made by boiling coconut liquid with some
of the grated meat, which includes the fat. If you don't want to go
to the trouble of draining, cracking and grating a brown coconut,
the next best thing is buying chunks of white flesh, sold at some
farmers' markets. Even though you didn't start with a whole nut,
you can still make coconut milk if needed in a recipe using a
method from Elizabeth Schneider in ``Uncommon Fruits &AMP;
Vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Boil equal amounts of water and grated coconut. Put in a food
processor and process 30 seconds. Let mixture stand 20 minutes.
Strain, mashing the pulp to make sure you get all the juice.
</P>
<P>
   If you want thinner milk, let stand a few minutes and skim off
cream; or pour boiling water over the coconut meat a second time to
extract a bit more flavor.
</P>
<P>
   If the recipe calls for fresh coconut milk and you haven't
drained one yourself or made it from coconut meat, a good
substitute is Hokan brand ``lite coconut milk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  `Fresh' frozen: If you don't want to grate your own coconut,
the next best thing is frozen coconut labeled as ``fresh frozen''
and sold in many grocery stores in the South. It is usually
unsweetened or very lightly sweetened.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Flaked, shredded, sweetened, packaged, canned: Other recipes
have been created especially for the more widely available flaked
or grated, sweetened or un-, in packages and cans. Canned coconut
is moister than packaged.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Toasted: To toast coconut, spread on a baking sheet and bake
in a 350-degree oven about 20 minutes, stirring often, until
golden. Or microwave on high for 1 to 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tinting: Put 1 cup shredded coconut and 3 drops food coloring
in a jar. Close tightly and shake until evenly tinted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
