<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX     04-19 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Easter bread is a sweet colorful treat
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dannie Bell's grandchildren will be the lucky ones now that
their grandmother's hunt for an Easter treat turned up a recipe she
sought. Bell asked for a version of the often-seen brunch sweet
bread with tinted eggs on top.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes we uncovered varied in ingredients _ with some including
candied fruit and spices _ and in whether to tint and/or hard-boil
the eggs before setting them into the dough and baking.
</P>
<P>
   This one uses uncooked eggs, which bake with the bread. Our
tester notes that if you tint them before baking, some of the food
coloring may bleed into the dough. You may want to paint coloring
on after the ring has baked and cooled.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Easter Egg Ring
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 ring, 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Brunch bread and eggs bake all at once in this colorful twist
ring.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 1 teaspoon granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 tablespoon) active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   9 eggs, divided
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups (about) all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoon crushed aniseed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped candied fruit
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   In small saucepan, heat milk, 1/4 cup sugar, butter and salt
until butter has melted. Cool to lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve 1 teaspoon sugar in warm water; sprinkle in the yeast
and let stand for 10 minutes or until frothy.
</P>
<P>
   In large mixing bowl, combine yeast mixture, milk mixture and 2
lightly beaten eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Put flour in a bowl. Stir in orange rind and aniseed. Using
electric mixer, gradually beat 1 1/2 cups of the flour mixture into
the yeast mixture; beat until smooth, about 2 minutes. With wooden
spoon, gradually stir in enough of the remaining flour mixture to
make soft, slightly sticky dough.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out dough onto lightly floured surface and knead until
smooth and elastic, 5 to 10 minutes. Place in lightly greased bowl,
turning to grease all over. Cover with plastic wrap (or greased
waxed paper and tea towel); let rise 1 to 1 1/2 hours or until
doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Punch down dough; knead in raisins, candied fruit and almonds.
Divide dough in half. Roll each piece into 26-inch long rope and
twist together. Transfer to greased baking sheet. Bring ends
together to form into ring, pinching ends to seal. Gently pull
twisted ropes apart and tuck 6 whole uncooked eggs (tinted if
desired) into openings, placing eggs evenly around ring. (Eggs will
become hard-cooked during baking.)
</P>
<P>
   Cover and let rise about 1 hour or until doubled in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Separate remaining egg. Mix yolk
with milk and brush glaze over ring. Bake for 25 to 30 minutes or
until crust is golden brown and bottom of ring sounds hollow when
tapped. Remove from pan and let cool on rack. _ From: Canadian
Living
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 282 calories, 9 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 39 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 301 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Published recipes
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of a recipe previously published in the newspaper,
call the Stacks at 404-526-5668.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
