<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-BOYS20-COX     04-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-BOYS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gender switch remarkable for Swank
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This intense, disorienting, rawly unsettling film is based on
the true story of Teena Brandon, a 21-year-old woman who fiercely
believed she was a man. She cut her hair short, reversed her name
and started hanging out with some hard-drinking rednecks in rural
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Things don't work out. The movie is a bit unrelenting, a bit too
low-budget rough-around-the-edges. But it's still a remarkable
achievement and Oscar-winner Hilary Swank gives a stunning
performance.
</P>
<P>
   `Boys Don't Cry'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : For links, some with R-rated content,
involving the true story:
www.zeitgeistfilm.com/current/brandonteena/brandonlinks.html
</P>
<P>
   OTHER VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stuart Little (PG) _ Based very loosely on E.B. White's 1945
children's book, Stuart is a 3-inch-tall computer-animated wonder
voiced by Michael J. Fox. He brushes his teeth, gargles and
aw-shucks smiles with such convincing visuals you'll swear he's the
next best critter since ``Babe.'' But his movie, at first charming
and angelic, turns into run-of-the-mill slapstick. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``End of Days'' (R) _ Bigger than ever, the movies' biggest
he-man Arnold Schwarzenegger leaps into action, going mano a mano
with a beady-eyed Gabriel Byrne as the devil in this
explosion-happy thriller. Awash in often too-dark cinematography
and bloated with bombs, gore and gross-outs, ``Days'' is a movie
full of punches but no spark. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Music of the Heart'' (PG) _ The Meryl Streep Show _ and what
a show it is. Streep and her unlikely collaborator, director Wes
Craven (``Scream''), have delivered a rarity: an inspirational
movie that actually is, well, inspirational. Based on a true story,
the film follows a single mom (Streep) who overcomes reluctant
kids, confrontational parents and an indifferent school board in
her battle to teach violin (and more, of course) to inner-city
kids. Yeah, at heart it's a glorified TV-movie, but it's got Streep
and that's all it needs.Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Red Violin'' (unrated) _ Francois Girard's
centuries-spanning saga is as florid and emotional as his
``Thirty-Two Short Works about Glenn Gould'' was spare and
sophisticated. The film follows the fortunes _ and, more often,
misfortunes _ of those who come in contact with the so-called Red
Violin, carved in 1681 by an Italian master. Holding the different
stories together is a present-day auction during which violin
expert Samuel L. Jackson struggles to unravel the instrument's
tragic secret. Too melodramatic in spots, too schematic in others,
this is still a film for anyone who's ever felt a chill as a tarot
card is turned over. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mumford'' (R) _ Writer-director Lawrence Kasdan delivers a
sunny, low-key crowd-pleaser about a therapist named Mumford (Loren
Dean) whose effect on his clients changes the mood of their whole
town (also called Mumford). With a crack supporting cast, it's a
gentle vacation from the high-concept bangs and lowbrow laughs so
often found in the multiplex. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``House on Haunted Hill'' (R) _ A redo of the 1958 Vincent
Price spookfest, it's a loud assault on the senses and a (literal)
bloody mess. But as a meat-and-potatoes (or guts-and-eyeballs)
scare machine, it has its moments. Geoffrey Rush invites five
strangers to spend the night in a haunted house to win $1 million
each. Then the gore begins. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Bachelor'' (PG-13) _ Chris O'Donnell plays Jimmy, a San
Francisco playboy who loses his girl, Anne (Renee Zellweger), then
finds he'll inherit $100 million if he marries within 24 hours. A
clumsy remake of Buster Keaton's silent classic ``Seven Chances,''
it retains the original's surreal image of thousands of potential
brides chasing the groom-to-be. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
