<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slam-dunk movies to stay ahead of game
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With March Madness over, what's a round ball fan to do? Well,
you could check out ``Love and Basketball,'' a new movie starring
Omar Epps and Sanaa Lathan that opens Friday in metro Atlanta. Or
you could hold your own video Final Four at home. Here are a few
ideas, some more hoop-centric than others:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hoop Dreams.'' This extraordinary documentary may be the
finest film ever made about basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers Steve James, Frederick Marx and Peter Gilbert have
delivered a movie that's about far more than backboards and
rebounds. They've served up a richly observed, superbly nuanced
slice of the American dream as they follow the hopes, hard work and
heartbreak that dog two inner-city phenoms as they struggle to make
it to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Agee and William Gates are 14 when we meet them. Both
have grown up on the rubble-strewn, drug-littered courts of
inner-city Chicago. Both have exceptional ability that gets them
recruited by a tony suburban high school. From there, it's a matter
of luck, timing and true-life unpredictability. This marvelous film
scores a slam-dunk by showing us the rules of the game on and off
the court.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hoosiers'': The corn is as high as an elephant's eye in this
movie about the little Indiana team that could, but the impact is
undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1951, and Gene Hackman is the new coach in a hick
burg, looking for a second chance for himself and a state
championship for his underdog team. The film captures a time when
high school sports was about playing the game, not college
recruiting, drug tests and no pass-no play.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hopper managed a best supporting actor nomination for his
role as a former high school star offered a position as Hackman's
assistant coach if he can stay off booze. He later joked that he
and Hackman couldn't understand why the filmmakers kept shooting
``all those damned basketball games. We were sitting on these
wooden benches saying, `Here's the big money. Why aren't you
shooting us?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``He Got Game'': Spike Lee shows us the money and the groupies
and the cars and the rent-free digs and the
anything-your-heart-desires temptations routinely dangled in front
of hot, young high school prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressures on these young Nike endorsers in the making
are only part of the story. There's also an acutely observed
father-son relationship in which a jailbird father (a wonderful
Denzel Washington) is made an unusual offer by his warden (Ned
Beatty): If he can convince his son, a budding star from the
projects (Ray Allen, whose real job is playing for the Milwaukee
Bucks), to sign with the governor's alma mater, he'll get a reduced
sentence. One not so small problem: Father and son have been
bitterly estranged for years.
</P>
<P>
   Look for some cameos by real-life players and coaches, including
Georgia Tech's gone-but-never-forgotten Bobby Cremins.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Forget Paris'': Most of you have probably forgotten there
ever was a movie named ``Forget Paris,'' and if you do remember it,
you've almost certainly forgotten that it had anything at all to do
with basketball.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was really more of a romance about what happened
after Billy (Crystal) met Debra (Winger). But Crystal, who also
directed, let his passion for basketball seep through by making his
character an NBA referee. It not only gave him a chance to hang out
with some of his idols but taught him something about being a ref.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes them,'' he told an interviewer. ``The best thing
you can say about a referee is nothing. That means he did a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : Fan page devoted to basketball and movies:
www.people.cornell.edu/pages
</P>
<P>
   /dkp6/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
