<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYERS-EDGE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give your decor a kick-start by updating your lamps with a a new
look that starts at the top
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing like the right lampshade to shed new light on
everything.
</P>
<P>
   A shade is like a fashion accessory. It can dress up a naked
light bulb as well as update Aunt Edith's prized porcelain lamp,
your favorite ginger jar or a classic candlestick base. Often, it's
more cost effective to simply buy a shade than invest in a new
lamp. To help you find the bright spots in shades, we scoped out
decorating experts to learn the light stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of things
</P>
<P>
   Replacement shades, said Carolyn Uhl, owner of Sunlighting Lamp
&AMP; Shade Center on Roswell Road, come in seven basic shapes: bell;
coolie (like the hat); empire (straight-sided, with bottom 16
inches, the top 8 inches); hexagonal, oval, rectangular and square.
They are made from plastic, parchment or papers (hardback shades)
or from fabrics, including silks, linens and polyesters (soft
shades).
</P>
<P>
   Price-y points
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive shades _ some start as low as $7 _ are
machine-made and usually imported. The more expensive ones,
starting around $50, are partly hand-sewn, partly machine-made,
usually in the United States. Box pleating and any kind of trim _
including tassels, fringe and braiding _ also up the ante. ``The
more `fun' a lampshade is, the more expensive it becomes,'' says
Uhl, who custom makes and designs shades as well as carrying
ready-made versions in her shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people haven't bought a shade for several years, they are
shocked about the prices,'' says Roger Cohen, the owner of Aaron's
Lamp &AMP; Shade Center on Northside Parkway. ``A shade dries out from
heat, if the light is used constantly. And it should be replaced
every five to six years. However, if you use a lamp moderately with
low bulb wattage, a good shade will last 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Revamp a lamp
</P>
<P>
   Different-size shades can work on the same base, says Carl
Smith, manager of Sharon's Lighting in Chamblee Plaza, which keeps
about 4,000 lampshades in stock. To adjust, simply try a larger or
smaller harp, which is a pair of vertical metal supports on which
the shade rests. A harp comes in half-inch increments between 5 1/2
inches and 14 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finishing touch for any lamp is the finial, the decorative
screw on top of the shade,'' says Smith. ``Once that is in place,
and all the proportions are correct, your whole lamp should sit up
and sing.''
</P>
<P>
   A tip from Ladies' Home Journal on figuring the dimensions of
the right shade for your lamp: The height of the shade should equal
the height of lamp base divided by 3. The widest diameter of shade
should equal the widest diameter of the base times 2.
</P>
<P>
   See watts new
</P>
<P>
   To take the guesswork out of shade buying, Target stores just
introduced its Mix &AMP; Match Lighting. More than 70 types of shades
in patterned parchment and textured papers will mix or mate with 70
different bases, including pewter, brushed silver, wood and wrought
iron. You can create a lamp to give a room its own personality.
Shade prices: $6.99-$29.99.
</P>
<P>
   Color notes
</P>
<P>
   The perennials _ white, off white, cream, ecru, taupe, gold _
are the most popular. Gaining ground are black, red and green.
Remember: Neutral shades allow more light through the shade.
``And,'' says Smith of Sharon's Lighting, ``shades in a room don't
have to match in color. They should blend in with other fabrics and
upholstery in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
