<P>
   COKE-LAWSUIT _ WILMINGTON _ Former and current black employees
who are attending Coca-Cola's annual meeting have threatened a call
for a national boycott of the company's products if it doesn't do
more to treat black employees fairly and settle a racial
discrimination lawsuit quickly. The Rev. Jesse Jackson also is
attending the meeting to lend his support. We're watching to see if
a boycott will be called. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-DAFT _ WILMINGTON _ A look at how Doug Daft handles himself
at his first annual shareholders meeting as chairman. (Saporta,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAPACIFIC-EARNINGS _ Georgia-Pacific Group easily beat estimates
for first-quarter earnings, thanks in part to soaring prices in the
company's pulp and paper business. Georgia-Pacific Group, which
excludes the Atlanta-based company's timber business, said today
that first-quarter profit nearly doubled to $194 million, or $1.11
a share, compared with year-ago profit of $99 million, or 56 cents
a share. Georgia-Pacific Group was expected to earn $1.02 a share,
based on a survey of analysts by First Call. (Bond, Atlanta
Joujrnal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHLINK-EARNINGS _ EarthLink announces Q1 earnings with
comment from McQ. (Katz, Atlamnta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
