<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look, Doc, No Pad! Rx for Prescriptions &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The poor quality of doctors' handwriting has long been a source
of jokes. But to Glen Tullman, chief executive of Allscripts, a
company in Libertyville, Ill., doctors with poor penmanship are
also a serious health risk. ``A significant number of medical
errors come from physicians' handwriting,'' he said. ``When you
rent a car they use a computer because they don't want to make an
error. Here you're dealing with something that's a life-and-death
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Tullman's company is one of a growing number trying to persuade
doctors to dump handwritten prescriptions in favor of those
produced by a wireless, handheld computer. Allscripts packages its
TouchScript software in Hewlett-Packard Jornada Series 600 handheld
computers, which use the Windows CE software system.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors use touch screen commands to create prescriptions and
then send them electronically to patients' pharmacies. Before
doctors commit to a particular drug, they can also use the computer
to review warnings about possible drug interactions and see if the
product is covered by patients' insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Allscripts has sold about 3,000 units, Tullman said. Doctors pay
about $200 a month for the service, plus a setup charge. Limited
memory means the handheld units are unable to function alone.
Instead, they swap data wirelessly with a conventional desktop
server in the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively slow speeds of wireless Internet connections make
it currently impossible for the units to go to directly to the Web,
Tullman said. That is an issue, he said, that is closely linked to
another common gripe about doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians, in some cases, only spend three minutes with
patients,'' he said. ``So it's got to be lightning fast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ian Austen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voyeur Cams in Nests Offer Bird's-Eye Views Of Fine Feathers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a voyeur cam that the whole family can watch. Cornell
University's ornithology laboratory is again presenting its Nest
Box Cams, small birdhouses equipped with internal video cameras so
that Web surfers can observe as birds settle down and raise a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Two nest boxes, in the Carolinas, are up and running on the
site, birdsource.cornell.edu/birdhouse/camframe.html, and a third,
in New York, is expected to be active soon.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras, which offer bird's-eye views of the floors of the
nest boxes, refresh every minute, and an annotated archive of
images is available.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina nest box has been particularly active, with a
Carolina chickadee laying six eggs, at least five of which have
hatched. The North Carolina box was off to a slower start.
Chickadees and then bluebirds brought in moss and grass for use in
making a nest. But strong winds blew the material out, and a male
bluebird was spied stealing some. And now, wasps have taken an
interest in the box. Stay tuned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Fountain &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Personal Surfing at Work Is Not So Extensive, Study Finds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Companies that monitor how their employees use the Internet
usually argue that they have no choice: Workers, the companies say,
are surfing the Web on company time, distributing confidential
information willy-nilly, and receiving or sending offensive
messages.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study commissioned by Elron Software, a maker of
monitoring software, tries to prove that point. Of more than 500
employees surveyed by NFO Interactive, a market research company,
27 percent say that they have received e-mail messages that leak
confidential data about other companies. And more than 50 percent
said that they had received offensive e-mail messages on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the results don't sound so bad. According to the
survey, only one-third of respondents said they spend more than 25
minutes per day using the Internet for personal reasons _ hardly
enough time to even post a sale item on eBay. The other two-thirds
spends even less time on the Web for matters outside of work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Guernsey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Keyboard Disasters Come In on Little Cat Feet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sleeping cat curled up on a warm, toasty computer monitor can
be quite an adorable sight, but when Fluffy takes a stroll across
your keyboard while the computer is on, bad things can happen.
Desktop shortcuts could be deleted, Internet connections lost, and
if you have left any files open on screen, you may not appreciate
the cat's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   PawSense, by BitBoost Systems, (www.bitboost.com/pawsense) is a
$20 software utility for Windows that offers to keep unintentional
cat computing to a minimum. The software runs in the background
until it detects unusual activity on the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Once ``catlike typing'' has been detected, the PawSense blocks
input from the keys to prevent unwanted commands or deletions to
your computer and files. It can also emit a loud noise to scare the
cat away.
</P>
<P>
   PawSense distinguishes little cat feet from humans with lousy
typing skills by analyzing the key combinations pressed by cat
paws. ``Cats' patterns of overall movement in walking or lying down
also help make their typing more recognizable,'' the site says.
Several cats helped test the software, created by Chris Niswander.
</P>
<P>
   The program will let you record your own sound to shoo Kitty off
the keys, or you can use one of the noises included in the program.
According to PawSense, the harmonica is a sound that cats dislike.
</P>
<P>
   A Mac version is under construction, but until then, concerned
Mac users might want to keep a Little Walter album playing in their
CD-ROM drives all day while the cat is home alone with hardware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. Biersdorfer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
