<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WARNER-IRELAND-FILM-A     04-19 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-IRELAND-FILM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: A FIRST FILM, BUT DEFINITELY NOT AN AMATEUR IN
CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ All too often, first films are ``written and directed
by'' affairs, with friends cast as extras, a small budget put
together by begging and borrowing and a less-than-even chance of
finding a distributor. But if an aspiring moviemaker has already
won a drawerful of prizes for directing everything except cinema,
well, perhaps things are easier. That, at least, has been Deborah
Warner's experience.
</P>
<P>
   While still in her late 20s, Warner made her name as something
of a wunderkind of the British stage through innovative
interpretations of classics at the Royal Shakespeare Company and
the Royal National Theater. Subsequently she directed opera at
Glyndebourne and Covent Garden. And most recently, she has done
experimental stagings of T.S. Eliot's poem ``The Waste Land,''
Janacek's ``Diary of One Who Vanished'' and Bach's ``St. John's
Passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Moviemaking seemed like a logical next step, and when the
invitation came, the unsurprising answer was, Why not? At the age
of 40, she was ready for a new test. And thanks to her reputation,
she could count on being shielded from the usual headaches by
people far more seasoned in the business.
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Last September,'' which opens in New York on April 21
and in other American cities April 28, is not exactly a typical
first film. Working with her, Warner had Neil Jordan, the
Oscar-winning Irish director (``The End of the Affair''), as
executive producer; John Banville, the award-winning Irish novelist
(``The Book of Evidence''), as screenwriter; and Slawomir Idziak, a
respected Polish cinematographer (``Blue''), as director of
photography. Also, budget and distribution were not her problems.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to casting the movie, a screen adaptation of a much
loved novel about Ireland by Elizabeth Bowen, Warner needed no
introductions. Two giants of the English stage, Dame Maggie Smith
and Michael Gambon, came on board, as did Jane Birkin and Lambert
Wilson. And Fiona Shaw's inclusion was a given _ she has played the
lead role in several of Warner's most successful stage productions,
including ``Electra,'' ``Hedda Gabler,'' ``Richard II'' and ``The
Waste Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the start of filming approached, Warner was hardly
nonchalant. In fact, she was worried. ``We had one rehearsal week,
which was quite terrifying for me because I'm used to eight
weeks,'' she said over tea in her north London apartment. ``But I
had one good idea. We hired a country house near our location, and
we spent a week together eating, with Maggie at one end of the
table and Michael at the other, and we gradually became our
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly good idea because ``The Last September''
is set almost entirely in a country house in southern Ireland. The
time is 1920, with the Irish independence struggle gathering pace
and the Anglo-Irish aristocracy installed by Cromwell 250 years
earlier beginning to suspect _ and anxiously deny _ that its days
are numbered. At Danielstown, the bucolic seat of Sir Richard and
Lady Myra Naylor (Gambon and Dame Maggie), the tennis parties go
on, but the British Army is already patrolling the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   This was a world all too familiar to Elizabeth Bowen, who was
born in Dublin in 1899 and spent her early summers in Bowen's
Court, the family seat in County Cork, which served as the model
for Danielstown when she wrote ``The Last September'' in 1929. It
was a world in which the landed class sounded entirely English,
sent its sons to English boarding schools and traveled to London
for medical attention, but nonetheless described itself as Irish.
Irish nationalists naturally saw things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so interesting about this story is watching these
Anglo-Irish characters in great denial,'' Warner said. ``They
didn't want to know there were tigers at the bottom of the garden,
and the tigers were green.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last September'' follows the coming of age of Sir
Richard's 19-year-old niece, Lois (Keeley Hawkes), who herself
personifies Anglo-Irish ambivalence: she is wooed by a young
British officer, Capt. Gerald Colthurst (David Tennant), but her
secret passion is for a childhood friend-turned-nationalist
fighter, Peter Connolly (Gary Lydon). Adding to the mood of
confused identity and frustrated love are Danielstown's house
guests, the Anglo-Irish Hugo Montmorency ( Wilson); his English
wife, Francie ( Birkin); and the Anglo-Irish Marda Norton ( Shaw),
who once loved Hugo and who now alone seems aware that the end is
nigh.
</P>
<P>
   Banville's screenplay veers from the novel by building up the
character of Peter Connolly as a counterweight to Captain
Colthurst. But it remains faithful to Bowen's portrayal of the
gradual asphyxiation of life at Danielstown as rebellion comes
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bowen wrote like a filmmaker, with wonderful dialogue,
exquisite descriptions and a brilliant use of light as a
metaphor,'' Warner said, adding with a laugh, ``We tried hard not
to make it too Chekhovian.''
</P>
<P>
   The very beauty of the location, with its autumnal colors
constantly changing under rushing clouds, contributes to the
feeling of impending doom. For capturing this in the movie, Warner
credits Idziak, without whom, she said, she would have been lost.
When it came to directing actors for the screen rather than the
stage, however, her initial fears were unwarranted: the long delays
between takes as lighting was repositioned provided ample time for
rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   On location, no one was better equipped than Shaw to judge how
her friend the rookie movie director was faring. ``The thing she
never did was to tell people what to do in terms of the scene,''
Shaw said. ``Say, leaving a dinner. Onstage, it could take weeks to
work out. Here it just happened. But what she does that is exactly
like in theater is to give one note to each actor, an idea that can
make all the difference, like, `You must think about what you left
behind.'''
</P>
<P>
   Warner said she made a point of directing Hawkes since the
character of Lois _ ``so determined to be in love,'' as Marda
Norton puts it _ defines the tone of the movie. But with the
experienced actors, she admitted, she was more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did direct Michael Gambon, but he gets bored very quickly so
you have do it very quickly,'' she said. In contrast, Smith was
``incredibly open'' to suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw chimed in: ``Maggie was like a student. She was always
poring over the screenplay in the evenings, studying, studying,
studying.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner got another new experience in the editing process, which
she said was a revelation. ``I learned a lot about novel writing,
all the things a novelist holds in his mind,'' she explained. ``And
of course it's so different from theater. Here the filming is like
rehearsing and the first night is the editing.''
</P>
<P>
   So has making ``The Last September'' altered the direction of
her career?
</P>
<P>
   ``What changed my life in the last five years was being able to
move between different media, from theater to opera and now to
movies,'' she said. ``Making a movie doesn't make me want to stop
everything else, but it does make me think I can blend more.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, it is the theater that is calling again.
At the end of May, she will be directing Shaw in ``Medea'' at the
Abbey Theater in Dublin. And, as always, there will be a touch of
the experimental. The chorus in Euripides' tragedy will speak on
alternate nights in English and in Gaelic. Not that Warner speaks
Gaelic. But on Irish matters, Cork-born Shaw is always there to
keep her straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
