</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES20-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer Notebook:
 &HT;    Manchester United eliminated in European Cup semis
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manchester United's ambitions to expand its dominance beyond
England this season ended Wednesday on its home pitch at Old
Trafford.
</P>
<P>
   The defending European Cup champions were beaten 3-2 by Real
Madrid and eliminated by the same aggregate score in the European
Cup quarterfinals. Three Spanish clubs are among the last four.
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona, which got two extra-time goals Tuesday to prevail 5-1
over Chelsea, 6-4 aggregate, will meet Valencia, which ousted
Lazio, in the first semifinal leg on May 2.
</P>
<P>
   On May 3, Real Madrid will play Bayern Munich in the other half
of the draw. The German club bested Porto 2-1, 3-2 aggregate, on a
goal by Thomas Linke in stoppage time, just moments after Porto's
Mario Jardel scored to tie the match.
</P>
<P>
   United, which controversially pulled out of the F.A. Cup to
compete in the World Club Championship, crashed out of the latter
event in group play. All that's left for the world's richest sports
club is to put the finishing touches on its sixth English Premier
League title in eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid benefited from poor United defending 20 minutes in,
when Roy Keane slid to push the ball away from the near post but
instead sent it into his own goal.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, Raul Gonzalez finished an electrifying
run by maneuvering around Jaap Stam to put home a 25-yard bender
for a 2-0 game. Three minutes later, in the 53rd minute, all
Gonzalez had to do was knock home an open shot, thanks to some
nifty byline work by Fernando Redondo.
</P>
<P>
   David Beckham and Paul Scholes pulled two back later on for
United, which suffered its first home loss to a Spanish club.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA CUP: DEATH THREAT CLAIMED
</P>
<P>
   Galatasaray defender Gheorghe Popescu said Wednesday that he and
several teammates had received death threats, in anticipation of
tonight's second leg UEFA Cup semifinal match at Leeds. Two Leeds
fans were killed in Istanbul two weeks ago, the night before the
first leg, won 2-0 by Galatasaray.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Turkish club have been banned from attending the
match, and Galatasaray players will be accompanied by a Turkish
anti-terrorist brigade, for extra security.
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal, Arsenal plays at Lens with a 1-0
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD CUP: HAITI, T&AMP;T ADVANCE
</P>
<P>
   Haiti will play Trinidad &AMP; Tobago next month in the third round
of qualifiers in The Football Confederation, which includes North
and Central America and the Caribbean. Cuba also advanced out of
the Caribbean zone. El Salvador advanced to the third round with a
3-1 win over Belize, as Raul Diaz Arce had his third goal in as
many qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   A full round of South American qualifiers will take place
Wednesday, highlighted by Colombia at Bolivia. Peru is at Chile,
Ecuador at Brazil, Uruguay at Paraguay and Argentina visits
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling Germany and Italy are under pressure for good
showings at home Wednesday, as several Euro 2000 teams are in
action in friendlies. Germany plays non-qualifier Switzerland,
while Italy meets Portugal. Other matches include Belgium-Norway,
Denmark-Sweden, France-Slovenia, The Netherlands-Scotland and
Turkey-Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia did not qualify, but will play host to the U.S. on
Wednesday in Moscow in the first visit by a senior men's American
team to the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: MONACO ROLLS TO CROWN
</P>
<P>
   As Monaco put the finishing touches on an anti-climactic race in
Le Championnat on Saturday. Dado Prso scored in stoppage time to
earn a 2-2 draw with Nancy. The title was the seventh for Monaco,
which has 62 points, 10 better than Lyon, with three matches
remaining. ... The historic win by Calais last week to reach the
French Cup finals was more than coach Ladislas Lozaro could bear.
He was hospitalized after suffering a mild heart attack as his
fourth-division club, composed mainly of amateurs, shocked reigning
French first-division champions Bordeaux 3-1. Lozaro is expected
back for the May 7 final against defending French Cup holders
Nantes.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: LIONS DOUBLE UP BAYERN
</P>
<P>
   1860 Munich has taken both Bundesliga contests with archrival
Bayern Munich this season. Bayern defender Jens Jeremies tapped in
an own-goal in a mix-up with his keeper Saturday, and the Lions won
2-1 to move into fourth place. Bayer Leverkusen crushed Arminia
Bielefeld 4-1 to take a three-point lead. ... The Deutsche Fussball
Bund, the German federation, has fined Eintracht Frankfurt nearly
$250,000 for incurring debts of nearly $7 million. But the damaging
blow is the loss of two points that will be docked at the end of
the season. Frankfurt is only one point and two spots out of the
relegation zone, despite playing better recently under new manager
Felix Magath.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: RIVER ROLLS
</P>
<P>
   River Plate lost two players to red cards in the first half
Sunday, then got early second-half goals from Eduardo Coudet and
Leonel Gancedo to beat Gimnasia de Jujuy 2-0 to take a one-point
lead in the Clausura (closing) championship.
</P>
