<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will return to the Northeast as a front slips
southward through New York. Thickening clouds and developing
onshore winds will turn a bright morning in New England into a
dull, cool afternoon. A surge of warmer, humid air will reach the
Middle Atlantic states and Ohio Valley on a freshening breeze from
the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   A strong disturbance moving east from Illinois will produce a
heavy, cold rain from Wisconsin to western New York. Farther north,
wet snow may fall in northern Michigan. To the south, powerful
thunderstorms may erupt in the Ohio and Tennessee Valleys as a cold
front sweeps east.
</P>
<P>
   The Plains will be noticeably cooler with clearing in western
sections. Clouds may persist over sections of the eastern Rockies.
A jet stream disturbance moving into the west will keep ocean
clouds near the coast and trigger a few showers inland.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: CANYON WINDS
</P>
<P>
   High winds lashed much of the Southwest on Tuesday as a potent
cold front swept across the region. Wind gusts of 50 to 90 mph were
measured from northern Arizona to eastern Utah and western
Colorado. As usual, some of the strongest winds were noted in
canyons. Canyon winds get a boost in speed since air that is forced
to flow through the constriction of a mountain pass always
accelerates. The same effect can be felt in large cities as winds
whistle through urban canyons formed by large buildings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
