<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, April 20. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Ned Kilkelly; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ A federal appeals court Wednesday extended
its order keeping Elian Gonzalez in the United States, the latest
development in the long-running custody dispute over the 6-year-old
boy whom the government wants to return to his father. (Summary
from wires.) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ Miranda's moment of truth, a
richly symbolic test of whether this landmark of the Warren Court
will survive the much more conservative era of the Rehnquist Court,
arrived Wednesday morning in a crowded Supreme Court with the
justices armed for battle. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-LOUISXVII (Paris) _ Scientists said Wednesday that DNA
tests ``support very strongly'' the assertion that a child who died
in prison in 1795 was the uncrowned King Louis XVII, undercutting
two centuries of speculation that the young royal had been replaced
by someone else in jail and whisked to exile. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIBER-CANCER (Undated) _ Two large and rigorous studies
involving thousands of people have failed to confirm one of the
most widely held beliefs about diet and health _ that eating
low-fat, high-fiber foods can reduce the risk of colon cancer. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AFRIKANERS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ One of the
most surprising shifts in the economic landscape here since the end
of apartheid is the growing confidence and increased prosperity of
wealthy Afrikaners under black rule. Even in a country of countless
ironies, this development may someday be listed among the more
notable. After all, the Afrikaners, who are descended from Dutch,
German and French settlers, invented the brutal system of racial
segregation known as apartheid. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Desperate to procure
Louisiana's final riverboat gambling license in 1997, Edward J.
DeBartolo Jr. had already delivered $400,000 in cash to his
father's old friend, Edwin W. Edwards, the former governor of
Louisiana. He had fended off suggestions that he grant consulting
contracts worth millions more to Edwards and his eldest son,
Stephen. Then, even after DeBartolo's partnership had won its state
casino license, he received another proposal, this one for a
$10,000-a-month attorney's retainer for Stephen Edwards. DeBartolo
could not have been more exasperated. ``They don't quit,'' he
complained to his closest associate, Ed Muransky. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   HACKER-ARREST (Edmonton, Alberta) _ The Canadian authorities
have arrested a 15 year old and charged him with carrying out an
attack that crippled a major Web site for several hours in
February. The suspect, who was identified only by his computer
handle, Mafiaboy, is accused of attacking CNN's Web site and could
face two years in prison as a juvenile. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
