<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-D'AMATO-PROFILE-ART-N     04-19 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D'AMATO-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING FAR TOO MUCH FUN TO RUN FOR MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT36 was sent Tuesday to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don't try reeling Alfonse D'Amato in with that
cautionary cliche about never saying never. He's saying never.
Shrilly. Al D'Amato become head honcho of the city that granted him
celebrity license the minute he was voted out of his 18-year stint
on Capitol Hill? Neh-vuh!
</P>
<P>
   His weak eyes fire up behind their strong eyeglasses (he was
legally blind until he had surgery in the fifth grade) and his
voice zeros in like a stinging insect to deliver an unconditional
thumbs down on resurfacing as New York's next Republican mayor
should Rudolph W. Giuliani levitate to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances would I run for the job,'' sputters the
former senator, bouncing around in his leather chair for added
oomph. ``No way, no how, no place!''
</P>
<P>
   No, sir. The turncoats who deserted him in his 1998 re-election
campaign (his only defeat in 28 years) won't have this insurance
salesman's son, now presiding over a Manhattan law office and
consulting firm well stocked with billionaire clients who seek his
advice with open checkbooks, to kick around anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, he doesn't qualify (Hillary Clinton, are you
listening?) as a true city resident. He's a Long Island bachelor
after business hours with a rented house in Lido Beach, a mere ZIP
code away from his hometown, Island Park, where he's religious
about showing up for Sunday dinners cooked by his mother,
Antoinette, an octogenarian.
</P>
<P>
   In the second place, why scale down to local when you've already
gone national?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't live in the city,'' notes D'Amato, 62, whose
socializing and womanizing skills keep him in its gossip columns,
``and I certainly wouldn't move just to put myself in position to
run.'' When he calls the office ``an onerous thing,'' he means it
as a compliment. He just doesn't need the grief.
</P>
<P>
   As for attention, which he thrives on, he still gets plenty:
he's not wearing a telegenic red tie by accident.
</P>
<P>
   He's found the lecture circuit way more fun than
speeches-on-the-stump: ``I can say whatever I want and don't have
to worry about if I offend you because I may lose your vote,'' he
says. ``And they pay me for it now! Isn't that wonderful!''
</P>
<P>
   Today D'Amato, whose cluttered desk signals an owner with a Type
AAA personality, has been to court (as special master in the
Holocaust settlement case), taped a Rudy-Hillary sound bite for Fox
Television, huddled with a new client and conducted a flurry of
negotiations in language best described as locker room legalese.
Later on, there's a taping with Paula Zahn.
</P>
<P>
   He's also sandwiched in a newspaper interview, but that doesn't
stop him from taking care of business _ much of it in histrionic
telephone soliloquies that conclude when he slams down the receiver
in lieu of a sign-off _ whenever the mood strikes, which is
constantly. Everything, including his Friday tee time and golf
lessons for the grandsons, is tackled with urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Get him! Beep him! Track him down!'' he barks at his executive
assistant, one of three female aides who call him The Senator,
exercise his Rolodex, fetch his Diet Cokes and grace his dinner
table at Manhattan restaurants on those rare evenings when he's
dateless and his buddy Donald J. Trump hasn't provided leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato reports himself recovered from his pining over the
socialite Hilary Geary, who dumped him shortly before the voters
did, but he professes he's not the party animal the news media make
him out to be. Come on, show some respect: He's a grandfather of
12!
</P>
<P>
   He's also recovered from losing his Senate seat to Charles E.
Schumer, but it stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has a bulletproof ego, no one,'' says D'Amato, whose
bluster suggests he comes close, ``but I hope I have a greater
sense of inner worth than to suggest the loss of one election
determines one's outlook on life. That would be a really sad
commentary on anybody. To think that I was going to go into some
kind of retreat zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the man who claims he ``made a difference every day''
in the Senate has gone into the attack zone. ``You think there's a
better advocate than me? There isn't!'' brags D'Amato, counting a
$2 billion merger of Bell Atlantic and Metromedia Fiber Network,
and the rescue of the moribund Islanders hockey franchise with a
$175 million offer from his friend Charles Wang of Computer
Associates, as just the tip of the iceberg in his transition from
Senator Pothole to Senior Deal Maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel dethroned,'' he says. ``I don't think I ever
acted imperial.'' Whether he ever acted with impropriety kept the
Senate Ethics Committee guessing, but D'Amato insists he's as
ethical as the next guy: ``I enjoy me; I'm a good person. But if
you're disrespectful or nasty to me, you know what I'm going to
do.'' Just ask his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The smear-fests are history. Now he and Edward I. Koch (the
Siskel and Ebert of partisan critics spar weekly for New York
magazine over a free Four Seasons lunch) are having a ball
handicapping the Giuliani-Clinton race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely preposterous that Hillary comes in on
the basis that she wants to help New Yorkers,'' D'Amato rants about
the first lady. ``She's not worried about the interests of the
homeowner in Levittown. I mean, give me a break. She's here to
launch her political career so she can run for president! That's my
opinion!''
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, is there anything he doesn't have a handle on?
Just golf. ``Nobody can be as bad as me,'' pouts D'Amato, who came
to the game late in life and is desperate to make up for lost time.
``My golf pro, this poor guy,'' he says, beaming as he primes his
punch line, ``I think he's gone for psychiatric counseling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
