<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-KEYLIME-PIE23-COX     04-19 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYLIME-PIE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key lime pie has never been more popular, but there's trouble in
the Florida groves
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORIDA CITY, Fla. _ On the edge of the sawgrass wilderness,
where the road to Everglades National Park takes a hard left turn,
there's an overgrown produce stand with the odd name ``Robert Is
Here'' painted across the roof like a Rock City barn.
</P>
<P>
   Robert is Robert Moehling, the thicket-bearded proprietor, whose
easy smile and roomy midsection suggest that he enjoys his work.
Among the bins of oranges and kumquats, he offers passing tourists
almost anything that can be made with Key limes: honey, syrup,
curd, cookies, fudge, milkshakes, marinade, marmalade, dip, salsa,
salad dressing, mustard, hot sauce, barbecue sauce, moisturizing
cream _ not to mention the people's choice, Key lime pie.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the products under the big shed, the most exotic may be
Key limes themselves. Moehling's were actually grown within an
hour's drive of the Keys. You can't say that about many Key limes
these days; almost all of the sour little suckers are imported from
Mexico and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Key limes are the pink flamingos of Florida food. They're a
celebrated part of local color, but the reality pales before the
reputation. Thanks to hurricanes and disease and encroaching
development, the state hasn't produced a crop to speak of since the
1950s. Nowadays, most Florida-grown Key limes are plucked from
stray trees in people's yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here three years, and I haven't seen a Key lime tree
yet,'' says Dolphus Broxton, the head of marketing for Brooks
Tropicals in Homestead, Florida's largest lime supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic limes are particularly scarce this year. The citrus
canker, a blight that makes fruit fall prematurely and can kill a
tree, has swept through the flat, steamy fields south of Miami,
from where 90 percent of the limes grown in the United States come.
Half of Florida's lime groves have been bulldozed and burned, and
the canker may not be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``People I've known all my life are losing everything. It's a
hurtful thing to watch,'' Moehling says, as he sorts navel oranges
in back of the produce stand. Off in the distance, a column of
smoke rises in the cloudless sky _ another infected grove going up
in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Key limes account for very few of the fresh limes consumed in
the United States. The ones you usually see in the grocery store
are Persians, a seedless hybrid picked early so the fruit will look
as green as a new lawn.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Key limes look like confused lemons. They're
smaller than a golf ball, with yellow-green skin sometimes
splotched with brown. They yield seeds and a pallid juice that's
considerably tarter than that of the Persians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Coke and Pepsi _ they just taste different,''
Moehling says.
</P>
<P>
   The higher pucker quotient makes Key limes perfect for the pie
that food writer Craig Claiborne once called his favorite American
regional dessert. The fruit's acid balances the sweetened condensed
milk used in almost all Key lime pie recipes, interacting with the
protein to form a custardlike consistency. The condensed milk
tradition dates from the 1800s, when canned milk was the only kind
available on the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   As any chef can tell you, fresh Key limes make a far tangier
pie. But they can be hard to find outside of Latin groceries and
the larger farmers markets. Most home piemakers rely on bottled
juice instead.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oldest and most popular brands is Nellie and Joe's.
It began in Key West during the 1940s when two Cubans, Nellie and
Joe Suarez, started selling hand-squeezed juice in recycled Coke
bottles. Today a Canadian owns the company and imports the juice
from Mexico, where the limes are pressed and the squeezings
concentrated and then shipped to a processing plant in Key West to
be reconstituted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sent a truckload to Atlanta,'' says the owner, Rod
Millar, referring to one of his biggest customers, the Edwards
Baking Co. in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at Kenny's Key Lime Pies in Smyrna, a former
bartender named Kenny Burts has built a thriving business supplying
premium pies to restaurants such as the Longhorn Steakhouse chain.
He uses nothing but fresh Key limes _ 96 tons of them last year.
Hardly any came from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Key lime doesn't have to come from the Keys,'' Burts says.
``Some of the best Key limes I've ever tasted came from Haiti.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, most people in this hemisphere don't even call
them Key limes. In Latin America, where cooks use them in
everything from salad to ceviche, they're known as Mexican or West
Indian limes. Whatever they're called, all limes originated in
Southeast Asia and came to the New World with the Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when limes were a larger slice of Florida
agriculture. Before Hurricane Andrew struck in 1992, more than
10,000 acres of south Dade County were planted in limes. The storm
leveled much of them, and the acreage dwindled by two-thirds. Fewer
than a dozen growers still cultivate limes on any scale, all of
them within a few miles of each other in the fertile truck farming
region around Florida City and Homestead. Only one of the growers
bothers with Key lime trees, which have sharp thorns and can be the
devil to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Yamamura wears a worried expression on his thin,
bespectacled face as he rides around inspecting his groves. The
owner of Limeco _ the word is stitched in green on his knit shirt _
he immigrated from Japan during the '50s and worked his way up from
field work. Today he plants 290 acres of limes, five of them in Key
limes _ the largest plot in the state.
</P>
<P>
   He stands to lose most of it to the canker.
</P>
<P>
   The wind- and rain-borne disease first appeared 4 1/2 years ago
in a yard near Miami International Airport and has spread into five
counties at the southern tip of Florida. To contain the blight, the
state is examining groves and marking exposed trees with red paint.
Every plant within 1,900 feet has to be destroyed. No replanting is
allowed for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' Yamamura says, coming to a halt on the edge of
a 25-acre stand of Persian limes. ``I've got 4,700 trees in here,
and they're all going to be destroyed because of this one tree.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses over a branch flecked with red paint and holds a leaf
between his index finger and thumb. The green is perforated by
brown circles, as if someone stubbed out a cigarette. Limes dangle
like Christmas ornaments from the rest of the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that fruit,'' he says. ``I can't pick any of it. It makes
me want to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun is sinking into the Everglades as Yamamura leaves the
grove, stopping to wash his hands and spray the underside of his
Chevy Blazer with germicide. Andrew flattened all this land; the
replanted trees have taken six years to reach maturity. Now this.
No wonder Yamamura says he could use a drink. So he drives down the
road to a sports bar he owns in Homestead and settles into a front
booth with a gin and tonic, a plate of catfish and a piece of Key
lime pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stay in the packing business,'' he says, ``but I'll
probably sell my land and import my limes.'' He stares into his
glass, then picks out the lime wedge and gives it a hard twist, as
if it were a chicken neck instead of a slice of citrus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 66. At my age, I won't be replanting again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
