<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-KEYLIME-RECIPES23-COX     04-19 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYLIME-RECIPES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Green won't fly in this pie
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 23.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rod Millar, who bottles Nellie and Joe's Key lime juice, was at
a food show in Boston recently when someone brought him a slice of
Key lime pie. He took one look at the bright green filling and
winced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't make myself take a bite,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Floridians and other purists recognize several permissible
variations in Key lime pie. You can use a pastry shell or graham
cracker crust. You can add eggs or not. If you don't use eggs, you
don't necessarily have to bake it.
</P>
<P>
   Under no circumstances, however, should you add green food
coloring. The filling of authentic Key lime pie is a wan yellow.
While some restaurants dye it green to distinguish it from lemon
pie, we discourage that sort of flimflammery in Georgia. Florida is
too close; we don't want to hear them laughing at us.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Classic Key Lime Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Baking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   One of the attractions of Key lime pie is simplicity; it's one
of the easiest desserts to make. This recipe is the classic
version. We tested it with fresh Key limes and regular Persian
limes; the latter was a pale imitation of the former. If you must
use Persians, throw in a teaspoon of zest to intensify the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Key lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 9-inch graham cracker crust
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine the yolks and condensed
milk in a medium-size bowl, and mix well. Add lime juice a little
at a time and beat until the filling is smooth and creamy. Pour
into crust, and bake in preheated oven for 10 minutes. Serve
thoroughly chilled, topped with whipped cream and garnished with
lime slices.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 350 calories, 8 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 37), 48 grams carbohydrates, 123
milligrams cholesterol, 266 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
