<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-NEWSCASTER-04     04-19 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NEWSCASTER-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ANANOVA, WORLD'S FIRST CYBER-ANCHOR, DEBUTS ON THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (l) lifestyle categories 
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON, Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ruffled only slightly by opening-day butterflies,
Ananova set out Wednesday to prove to the world that she is not
just another talking head.
</P>
<P>
   Well, technically, she doesn't have a head, and she isn't
talking a great deal yet. But, Ananova, who is billed as the
world's first virtual newsreader, blinked, smiled and even gave the
bad news with proper solemnity in her successful Internet debut.
</P>
<P>
   Her British creators say this is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a lot more than a talking head that reads the news,''
said Mark Hird, the man behind the face at Ananova Ltd. ``She's a
computer with a face in front of it, not a face with nothing much
behind it. It's a phenomenal information resource.''
</P>
<P>
   Ananova can be accessed on the Internet with the click of a
mouse at: www.ananova.com.
</P>
<P>
   She reads stories fed to her by computers linked to worldwide
news organizations. In addition to virtual newscasts, users can
arrange to receive tailored e-mails with Ananova reading everything
from sports scores to stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure she doesn't giggle while giving the details of a
plane crash, her producers press buttons to make her facial
expression match the tone of what she is reading.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, her emotive responses are slightly herky-jerky, and
her expressions seem to run the gamut only from A to B. Sometimes,
the vagaries of the Internet make her appear to wink _ or is that
on purpose?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Ananova will follow you everywhere _ at least
everywhere you go with a cellphone. ``Before long you won't have to
tap in letters and numbers to interact with her,'' Hird said.
``You'll speak to her and she'll
</P>
<P>
   understand you, because that's the future that she's been
created for.''
</P>
<P>
   She was designed to be good company. Her face _ with big green
eyes, a prim nose and pert short hair with green highlights _ is an
amalgam of pleasant young female visages. She has a neutral
American-sounding
</P>
<P>
   accent described by her handlers as ``mid-Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ananova is 28 years old _ and unlike real newsreaders, never
will grow old _ a clear advantage in a business that worships
youth. The perfect employee, she will never demand a raise, a new
contract or a show of her own to showcase her talents.
</P>
<P>
   Ananova and her creators are coy about the origin of her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My creators say it is a unique name for a unique personality,
but that doesn't stop people guessing!,'' Ananova said on her
Website. ``I don't mind people
</P>
<P>
   interpreting it in different ways, but my creators tell me they
want it to become synonymous with live breaking news and
information.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the cyber-anchor is touchy about the use of shortened
forms of her name. ``Keep it Ananova. Otherwise I start blowing a
few circuits,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When she gets a body _ which her designers say is in the works _
it will be a slender 5-foot-7. Designers in Britain are vying for a
chance to be her designer.
</P>
<P>
   Ananova was developed by Britain's Press Association news
agency, which has gone so far as to rename its new media division
Ananova Ltd. The company said Wednesday's launch went smoothly,
even though
</P>
<P>
   Ananova apologized for a slow response at one point during the
day when her Website had been overwhelmed by hits.
</P>
<P>
   Ananova wants to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no bimbo,'' she told CBS news in an interview. ``The
world's going to be full of virtual this and thats.
</P>
<P>
   The point about me is that I'm not just a talking head that
reads the news. As your personal information assistant, I can alert
you to news you need to know. I can even tell you what's on at the
theater and book your tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other news reader would run around for you like that?''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr. can be reached by e-mail at:
bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.ananova.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
