<HEADER>
A1603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS20-COX     04-19 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS BUREAU SAYS RESPONSE TO LONG FORM FELL
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau reported Wednesday that the
mail-in response rate for its long form, used to collect data
crucial to administering major federal programs, fell significantly
from 1990's rate.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-census rhetoric from politicians was partly to blame,
census officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-question long form, delivered last month to one in six
U.S. households, became the target of talk-show hosts, Internet
chat sites and Republican Party leaders who said some of the
questions were intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   While the once-a-decade head count is mandated by the
constitution and all questions are approved by Congress, Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush and Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, among others, suggested that Americans should not have
to answer questions they believe violate their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials believe the controversy in recent weeks had a
chilling effect on their efforts to convince Americans to answer
and return their forms. Most of America's 120 million households
received the short form, with eight basic questions.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau director Kenneth Prewitt said Tuesday that the
rhetoric ``needlessly put the Census Bureau in the crossfire''
between the government's vital need to collect data and public
concerns about privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census-as-a-civic-duty message was compromised for those
who received the long form. A garbled message was sent that somehow
statistical information threatens privacy,'' said Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal statistics are not about individuals, therefore they
are not about privacy,'' he said. ``I believe that this elemental
distinction got lost in the public discussion and that the return
rate on the long form suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Census questions are intended to gather data called for by law
or judicial rulings. The numbers are used to apportion seats in
Congress and to fairly distribute about $185 billion in federal
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Only 54 percent of households that received the long form had
returned them to the Census Bureau by the end of the day Monday,
compared to 60 percent who returned them during the same period in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   The return rate for the short form remained roughly the same, at
66 percent this year and 66.8 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall places more pressure on the census-takers as they
enter the next phase of the count. On April 27, 500,000 census
workers will go into the field for follow-up operations where they
visit households that did not mail back their forms.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials will be closely monitoring that effort, which
continues through mid-summer, to gauge whether the reluctance among
some Americans to respond will result in active resistance to the
census-takers.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to collect the statistics could threaten the quality of
data in some parts of the country and have consequences on state
redistricting and federal funding, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was an encouraging sign that over all, about
two of every three households returned their forms, ending a
three-decade slide in response to the census.
</P>
<P>
   The initial response period, which ended Tuesday, showed that 65
percent of households returned their forms, equal to the 1990 rate.
In 1970, 78 percent of Americans returned their forms and 75
percent returned them in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said the result reverses a ``decades-long decline in
meeting our civic responsibility,'' noting that the Census Bureau
and the Government Accounting Office had expected the response rate
to fall to as low as 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in coordinating the $6.8 billion count, which included an
extensive, prime-time advertising campaign, the Census Bureau had
hoped for a 70 percent national response this time. Only 15 percent
of local governments _ about 6,000 cities, counties and tribal
lands _ increased their 1990 response rate by 5 percent of more.
Among them was Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt called the 70 percent national target an ambitious goal
that the Census Bureau probably never had a hope of achieving. But
he said the response rate probably would have risen above 65
percent had the public debate not cast a cloud over the agency's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Texas and Florida each matched their response rates
from 1990, with Georgia at 63 percent, and Florida and Texas at 61
percent. Colorado increased its response rate one point, to 68
percent. North Carolina dropped two points, falling from 63 percent
to 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio recorded one of the largest slides, from 75 percent in 1990
to 70 percent this time. It joined a number of other states in the
Midwest which fell dramatically, though they remain at or above the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials said they had not had time to analyze the
results of specific localities and demographic groups to determine
why the response rate fell sharply in some states.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, states in the South and West followed an historic
pattern of falling below the national average. Demographers believe
the result stems from the rapid growth and more mobile society in
the Sun Belt and the higher proportion of new immigrants, factors
that make the regions harder to count.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau will being targeting specific areas with
lower-than-expected response rates with a new round of ads. Prewitt
also called on public officials to support the efforts of the
door-to-door census takers.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that some Republicans on Capitol Hill were backing
away from the issue, the Senate last week quietly shelved a
nonbinding resolution that had passed on April 7 urging that ``no
American will be prosecuted, fined or in any way harassed by the
federal government'' for not answering certain questions on the
form.
</P>
<P>
   Under law, the Census Bureau cannot share the identifying
information on the form with any other government agency or private
organization. But most polls show that a majority of Americans,
whether they are inclined to return their forms or not, do not
believe that the government's vows of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
