<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-CANCER2     04-19 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GALARRAGA-CANCER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga's return an inspiration to cancer community
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was like a movie, Andres Galarraga said.
</P>
<P>
   In the third at-bat of his first regular-season game after a
year spent battling cancer, Galarraga hit a home run. He said he
didn't have the words to express his happiness.
</P>
<P>
   But lots of people do. That home run did more than help the
Braves beat the Colorado in the season opener; it lifted up a
community of cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   They might not be studious baseball fans, but they are expert in
words like multiple myeloma and non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   They also know cancer doesn't care if you hang curve balls or
dry wall. They all relate to the road Galarraga traveled to return
to first base at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   For cancer patients, watching Galarraga's comeback _ a defensive
play that saved Opening Day; four home runs in the first six games,
including a grand slam that beat the Giants _ has been inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   He has rewritten the definition of ``hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the guys that could throw for 400 yards in a game or
catch five touchdown passes or run for three touchdowns were
heroes,'' said Kim King, the former Georgia Tech quarterback and
radio analyst who has cancer in his back. ``But true heroes are
people that do things under pressure, with grace and style.
Galarraga, he's a real hero.''
</P>
<P>
   King was home watching the Braves' opener a couple of weeks ago.
When Galarraga put Pedro Astacio's fastball into the
left-centerfield seats in the seventh inning, tears filled King's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just bawling like a baby,'' King, 54, said. ``Chills
were going up and down my spine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of triumph and joy that only someone who has had
to endure chemotherapy or radiation, or both, could comprehend
fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great victory, because I can share with what
he's been through this last year,'' King said. ``All the chemo and
the sickness and all the side effects you go through. And all the
pain and the discomfort of the back. It makes you feel like a dog.
To see him come back and do that was just great.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, King kept feeling a pain in his back while playing
golf. ``Like an idiot, I guess, my football training told me you're
supposed to play through pain,'' he said. But he fell to his knees
after hitting a drive and couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   The first doctor he saw told him it was bone spurs, nothing to
worry about. Then it got worse, and his personal doctor discovered
a crushed vertebra. Further tests revealed worse news.
</P>
<P>
   ``They diagnosed me in June, saying that I had multiple
myeloma,'' King said. ``It's a blood cancer that manifests itself
in tumors and in the bone system, primarily in the hip and spine.''
</P>
<P>
   King began intense treatments right after the Fourth of July. He
just finished his second bone-marrow transplant. ``I'm pretty well
finished with the real heavy treatment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors are encouraged with his progress. ``My back is
pretty well healed,'' King said. ``I'm able to do a lot of the
things that I was doing before, but not as well. I'm not able to
play golf the way I used to, but I can play golf and do some
hunting and things like that. I haven't responded like Galarraga
has.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he admires Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he symbolizes is, if you catch (that you have)
cancer early enough, you have a very good chance of beating it or
at least containing it to where you can lead a full, productive
life,'' King said. ``The key for me was having regular annual
checkups.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga might not understand how big a symbol he has become.
But he got a clue during spring training. On March 5, before the
Braves' exhibition against Tampa Bay, he was visited by youngsters
fighting cancer.
</P>
<P>
   They sat in the dugout talking baseball. And cancer. Mark
Daugherty, 7, treated for leukemia since he was 2, wanted to know
all the details of Galarraga's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andres answered every question and pinpointed where it was,''
said Steve Daugherty, Mark's father. ``He talked about the
radiation and the chemo that he had. He said he did lose his hair,
just like Mark, and it was a little painful. He did get a little
sick. The same thing Mark goes through every week.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a boost to the boy, who plays soccer and practices even
on days that he gets chemo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of seeing some of the successes that he has been
around and, obviously, the Andres thing, he doesn't miss a
practice,'' Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-tennis pro, Steve said he thinks that Galarraga's example
helps the mental attitude of cancer patients, which may play a
significant part in recovery. ``It's probably 49 percent as
important as the 51 percent of the medical side of it,'' he said.
``You've got to be positive and upbeat every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Guthrie, at 58 ``too damn young for this,'' is trying
desperately to be positive and upbeat, but some days it's just not
there. The former lineman for Tech and the San Diego Chargers has a
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a glyoblastoma in a stage four, which is the worst
you can have,'' Guthrie said. ``Isn't that the way hurricanes come
in, stage fours or fives? This is worse. It's a turbulent stage.''
</P>
<P>
   At Thanksgiving, his left arm went numb and paralyzed. He has
been undergoing treatment since December, radiation since February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say the worst is behind me. I don't even know
that,'' Guthrie said. He recently built a golf driving range in
Atlanta to operate with his children, but his future is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's the beacon of hope in a Braves uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galarraga's situation is an inspiration to me to hang on and
work hard to get back to the position he's in, but I don't know
with a brain tumor if I'm going to get there,'' Guthrie said. ``I
know he had a tumor on his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having a hell of a year playing baseball,'' he said.
``It's miraculous, isn't it? I imagine he's giving a lot of people
a lot of hope. For a lot of people with cancer, there ain't a lot
of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Campbell, 35, is bursting with hope and happiness now that
her eight-month battle with breast cancer is nearing a successful
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know exactly how Galarraga feels,'' Campbell said. ``Like a
giant, like he can conquer the world, like nothing else can bother
you or tear you down. I share how he feels right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She also shares how he felt when he was diagnosed. ``I was
diagnosed in September. I was only 35. No one in my family had had
it,'' Campbell said. ``I was too young to even go for the
mammograms because they say start at age 40. It was devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who works in a medical office, had her last treatment
last week. She said she feels like a new person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer for me has been more like a blessing and I would have
never traded it,'' she said. ``I know it sounds kind of crazy. It's
got me so in tuned with myself. That's why I say I can relate to
how Galarraga feels. It's like a rebirth. You come out fighting.
The small things in your life are nothing anymore. It's been a good
thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   If they did not share a common disease, Campbell probably never
would have heard of Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I don't follow baseball that much,'' she said,
``but the fact that he had the non-Hodgkins lymphoma, that sparked
me to get into what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she thinks she will finish the novel that she has been
writing for three years. ``I think that the Lord kind of brought me
through this because I was really struggling with a character that
was supposed to have gone through this illness. That's probably
crazy, but since the day I finished my treatment, I have been
writing like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the colon cancer that he was diagnosed with in
December, Nick Peterson, 35, can't hang dry wall anymore. But he is
battling back, inspired by what Galarraga has done and by his two
children, Ashley, 13, and Mitchell, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to raise my young-uns,'' Peterson said, ``so I want
to be around a little bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson's been encouraged by a surgery that removed a foot and
a half of his colon and chemotherapy that has reduced seven tumors
on his liver to one. It hasn't been an easy battle. ``Just the
thought of going through the chemo on Fridays makes me sick to my
stomach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former baseball player, he appreciates what Galarraga has
done. ``It's unbelievable, really,'' Peterson said. ``I didn't
think he was going to play baseball again. He sure has proved
everybody wrong, hasn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Klodnicki identifies with Galarraga's status as a survivor.
Her lung cancer has been in remission for two years. The teacher's
aide dedicates a lot of her time to a cancer-support group at the
Catholic Church of St. Ann.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, as soon as they're diagnosed with cancer, think
it's a death sentence,'' Klodnicki, 43, said. ``I want them to
realize that there's hope. I'm trying to show that it can be
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Galarraga, whom she cheered in that first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Galarraga's doing a great job of it, going out there
and playing ball like he's never been sick,'' Klodnicki said.
``People always call it being sick. Well, I was never sick. I just
had cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
