<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-RENO20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO DEFENDS HER HANDLING OF THE ELIAN CASE
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. With CUBA-ELIAN. Moving in (w) Washington and (a)
national categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A beleaguered Attorney General Janet Reno defended
her handling of the Elian Gonzalez case Wednesday, but conceded
that others in the Justice Department disapprove of her tactics in
trying to reunite the 6-year-old refugee with his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the criticism of me is that I'm trying to avoid violence,
if the criticism of me is that I'm trying to avoid that little boy
being hurt or being snatched in a way that can scar him further, I
plead guilty,'' Reno said at her weekly meeting with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time,'' she said, ``I'm going to enforce the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, Reno said the Justice Department would ``abide
by'' an appeals court ruling that extended an order keeping Elian
in this country. However, she said the ruling ``does not preclude
me from placing Elian in his father's care while he is in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   At the earlier session, Reno replied to rumblings that she had
become too emotionally involved in the months-long federal effort
to wrest the child from his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``high-ranking officials,'' the Washington Post reported
Tuesday that some of the attorney general's colleagues wonder
whether she has lost her way in a frustrating case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where I'm going,'' Reno responded.
</P>
<P>
   However, she acknowledged that there is disagreement even within
her agency over her intense personal involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have something that is of this magnitude, you're
going to hear from people who have differing views,'' Reno said.
``I want people to speak their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The case stirs echoes of the most traumatic episodes in Reno's
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resolution of the Elian case hinges on Janet Reno's inner
conflicts, her Waco flashbacks, and her post-traumatic-stress
syndrome from the Miami riots during her time as prosecutor
there,'' opined New York Times columnist Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   This week marks the seventh anniversary of the fire at the
Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, in which members of an
armed religious sect died when their compound burned after a siege
by federal agents. Although she accepted responsibility, Reno later
acknowledged that she was not informed of all the actions
undertaken by FBI agents at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   With Elian's relatives in Miami resisting his return and
protective anti-Castro demonstrators surrounding the house where he
is staying, many believe a violent confrontation could result if
federal agents are sent in to seize the boy.
</P>
<P>
   As with Waco, President Clinton has turned the Elian affair over
to his attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel her loneliness,'' observed Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, federal agencies have repeatedly extended the
deadline for Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, to surrender the
boy. Last week, Reno took the extraordinary step of flying to Miami
to meet with family members. Controversy intensified when she left
without securing his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard more comments about that,'' Reno said. ``Somebody
said I did the right thing. Somebody said I did the wrong thing.
Somebody said I was too personally involved. Somebody said I was
too remote.''
</P>
<P>
   She then referred to a quotation from Abraham Lincoln that she
keeps on her office wall: ``If the end brings me out right, what
people said about me won't make any difference. And if the end
brings me out wrong, 10 angels saying I was right won't make any
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the best advice for us all in these
circumstances,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Wednesday that her strategy to conclude the Elian
saga, which some have criticized as timid, have not been unduly
influenced by her past.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all these situations you try to draw from experience,'' she
said. ``But each case is different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Waco, you had people who had killed federal officers and
who had injured others. You had people who had not only defied the
law but killed people in the process,'' she said. ``There's a lot
of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the much-televised video in which Elian told his
father that he did not want to return to Cuba ``made me very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a wonderful little boy, by all accounts. His father had
a role in raising him. His father cares a great deal about him,''
Reno told reporters. ``He has been under the most stressful of
conditions, beginning with this most stressful of all, floating in
the ocean. It is so important that all of us turn off the TV
lights, stop writing on your papers, start thinking about a little
boy and getting his life to some permanent resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   She wondered aloud about some critics who said the government
should have moved sooner to take Elian from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed somebody said that we should have done it when it
wasn't an unusual case,'' Reno said. ``I think anybody who has
followed this case from the beginning understands that it has never
been a usual case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
