<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK-EARNINGS20-     04-19 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-EARNINGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EarthLink earnings drag due to merger
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The costs of its recent merger with onetime competitor
MindSpring pushed EarthLink Inc.'s first quarter loss, reported
Wednesday, to $108.5 million or 95 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   That's compared to a loss of $27.8 million, or 29 cents a share,
for the same quarter a year ago. These numbers include acquisition
costs of $31 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the cost of the acquisition is excluded, the
nation's second-largest Internet service provider had a loss of
$50.9 million, or 43 cents a share. That's 6 cents a share better
than the expected loss of 49 cents, the average estimate of
analysts surveyed by First Call. That compares to a profit of $3.2
million, or 3 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sadler, an analyst with FAC Equity in Boston, says
EarthLink ``did very well. When you merge equals like that, you
come up with issues you are not aware of, but they've done a good
job of budgeting for that.''
</P>
<P>
   First quarter revenues were up 69 percent to $219.7 million vs.
revenues of $129.9 million for the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Chief operating officer Garry Betty said the company added
340,000 new subscribers in the quarter ending March 31, giving it
about 3.5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Of that number, roughly 45,000 were broadband customers,
representing a 400 percent increase over the first quarter of 1999,
and an 80 percent increase over the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McQuary, EarthLink president, said: ``If you look back a
year ago, there was a lot of doubt we'd even be able to participate
in broadband. With the advent of DSL providers opening up their
wires, we've not only been able to participate but become one of
the leaders in broadband deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Customer churn _ or the number of customers that leave the
service, was 5 percent, higher than the company would like. McQuary
attributed the defections to users moving to high speed access
services in areas where the company does not yet offer broadband
access. He also factored in the proliferation of free Internet
service providers and computer makers who offer discounts with the
purchase of a particular ISP.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have to get their churn down from where it
is now,'' said Sadler. ``The critical factor is: Can they get churn
under 4 percent. Going over 5 (percent) is going in the wrong
direction Hopefully, that's the high.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuary said he was confident EarthLink could meet its
projections of 4.5 million subscribers and $1 billion in revenue by
the end of 2000 without offering free Internet access. He did not
think it would be necessary to forge other deals with computer
makers, other than an existing deal with Apple. He also said
EarthLink will have wireless products available on the Sprint PCS
wireless service sometime during the second quarter of this year.
(Sprint owns a 14 percent share in EarthLink.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Merger issues and the difficulty deploying high speed
telephone access were EarthLink's biggest challenges,'' Sadler
said. ``As you are switching systems over, systems failures are
part of that. You're shifting vendors and locations and you are
alienating people who are trying to call in at that time. You never
know how those are going to get resolved. They not only had to
integrate these (EarthLink and MindSpring) but MindSpring was
wrapping up its own mergers of their own with SpryNet and Netcom.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink's sales and marketing costs more than tripled to about
$119 million from $31.1 million in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
