<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WINESHOPPPER-AMAZON-N     04-19 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINESHOPPPER-AMAZON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM PROVIDES NEW CLOUT FOR WINESHOPPER.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB NORBERG   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Wineshopper.com, a Napa- and San
Francisco-based Internet wine sales site, has announced an
agreement with Amazon.com that gives Wineshopper significant
financial backing plus access to the online retailing giant's
marketing clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a $30 million investment and we get access to their
customers, potentially through direct e-mail marketing campaigns or
packaging of printed material in their shipments to customers,''
said Wineshopper spokeswoman Suzanne Gannon. ``It definitely gives
us a leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   What Wineshopper.com isn't getting, at least initially, is a
direct link to its site on Amazon.com's Internet site, which has 17
million customers, although Amazon spokeswoman Kristin Schaefer
said that could happen in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a straight investment for us and we are not contemplating
adding a tab at this time,'' Schaefer said. ``We will be working
with them as they roll out nationally, but we don't have any
specific plans at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced Tuesday in San Francisco, although
the investment _ $30 million from Amazon.com and $16 million from
venture capital giant Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers _ was made
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon said they wanted to wait until Wineshopper.com, which has
been plagued during the past year with technology glitches, was
finally able to launch. The site quietly went live Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers say the investment and access to Amazon's
marketing expertise alone are significant benefits, but because
there is no specific vehicle to drive Internet traffic to the
Wineshopper site, it doesn't make Wineshopper a contestant yet in
the crowded field of Internet wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com of Napa is by far the biggest online wine retailer,
with $96 million in backing and the advantage of the ``wine.com''
domain name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine.com is the largest by a factor of 100,'' said Ken Orton,
chairman of the board of Wine.com, which ships wine to 42 states.
``Wineshopper is the only perceived competition, and they are only
in California.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the market is segmented by Drinks.com, WineBins.com,
aficion.com, ambrosiawine.com, eVineyard, eWine.com and
WineAccess.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of wine are expected to be one of the hottest markets on
the Internet, accounting for 5 percent to 10 percent of all retail
wine sales by 2005, according to a report released in March by
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Wine sales via the Internet were less than $100 million in 1998,
but should reach to between $1.4 billion and $2.9 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, online book sales will be 17 percent of all
retail book sales, and toy purchases will be 14 percent of retail
toy sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is unusually well suited for online sales,'' said Salomon
Smith Barney analyst Mark Swartzberg. ``It has the lack of touch
element, like books and toys. And the Internet resolves several
problems, such as the intimidation consumers feel when selecting a
bottle and the information intensity of selecting a bottle of
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wineshopper.com is unusual because it doesn't ship wines itself,
but funnels requests from consumers to the producers and retailers
in the consumer's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Wine.com, in contrast, ships directly from its Napa warehouse,
which its officials say assures quality customer service, while
Wineshopper leaves its customer service up to the individual
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Wineshopper.com touts its links to other Internet wine sites,
including The WineSpectator, with its database of 77,000 wine
tastings, and Winetoday.com, with its database of 6,000 wines, but
plans to taste 8,000 wines a year by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Winetoday.com is part of New York Times Digital, a division of
The New York Times Co. New York Times Digital has a minority stake
in Wineshopper.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of The New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
