<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-ART-THEFT-ART-9     04-19 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ART-THEFT-ART-940-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLEN CHINESE RELIC A SHOWPIECE IN JAPAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM with CALVIN SIMS  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 7 is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In late December a leading scholar of ancient Buddhist
sculpture, Yang Hong, received a mysterious envelope here in the
mail. Inside was the lavish catalog of the Miho Museum, a major new
antiquities museum near Kyoto, Japan, that was designed by I.M. Pei
and was opened in 1997 by a wealthy religious sect.
</P>
<P>
   A slip of paper marked the page bearing a photograph of one of
the museum's masterpieces: an elegant 47{-inch stone carving from
China of a Buddhist figure known as a bodhisattva, with a large
halo and singular features including an extremely rare cicada
figure on the crown. Scrawled on the bookmark were the words
``National treasure!''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the envelope was a copy of a 1983 article from the
Chinese journal Cultural Relics describing, with photographs, a
group of newly excavated stone carvings from Boxing county in
Shandong Province. The carvings were early fruits of a major new
discovery of ethereal Buddhist sculptures from a sixth-century
dynasty in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Marked in that article were a photograph and description of a
statue that appeared to be identical to the Miho's showpiece _ the
same halo, the same cicada, the same measurements, the same stone
and exactly the same pattern of damages to the arms and body.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous letter tipped off Chinese archaeologists to what
they view as a clear-cut example of a rampant global problem: the
theft of cultural relics that are then given a false provenance and
sold to private collectors and museums at prices ranging into the
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest number of such thefts occur in China, which is
filled with unexplored tombs and other archaeological remains as
well as poorly guarded temples and museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see so many Chinese relics appearing overseas, and they've
virtually all been stolen and spirited out,'' said Yu Weichao,
retired director of the National Museum of Chinese History. ``As
one who has worked in archaeology for a lifetime, I feel
heartbroken.''
</P>
<P>
   The statue described in that 1983 journal, it turned out, was
stolen from Boxing county offices on the night of July 4, 1994, in
an unsolved case.
</P>
<P>
   The Miho purchased its apparently identical statue from a major
London dealer in October 1995 for an undisclosed sum. The dealer,
J.E. Eskenazi of Eskenazi Ltd., said in a faxed reply to questions
that he had purchased the sculpture from ``a long established and
reputable gallery in London'' but declined to name the gallery or
provide evidence of the item's prior history.
</P>
<P>
   The Miho Museum says it has not yet been proved that the two
statues are one and the same, though it is now taking steps to find
out. Regardless, it says, it bought the object ``in good faith''
and will not necessarily return it.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese experts in Beijing and in Boxing county say that based
on the clear photographs and data in the Miho catalog, they are
certain that the Miho figure is the one stolen in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yang, who received the initial tip, is a senior fellow of the
Institute of Archaeology of the Academy of Social Sciences. ``It's
definitely the same statue,'' he said. ``It's not just the cicada,
but also the damage and cracks on the statue, and all the other
identical features.''
</P>
<P>
   Shu Lichuan, director of the Boxing County Relics Bureau, said:
``We had the statue here for so long, up to 1994 when it was
stolen, and so we knew it very well. As soon as we saw the museum
photo we were quite sure that it's the same statue.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an illustration of the legal and bureaucratic obstacles
to fighting such thefts, Chinese agencies have not yet taken
official action to seek the statue's return. If they do, they could
be hamstrung by Japan's not having signed the 1970 UNESCO
convention requiring member countries to return relics proved to be
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese experts do not accuse the dealer or the museum of
knowingly purchasing stolen goods. But they lament a system in
which traders and buyers all too readily accept implausible claims
about treasures that seem to appear out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of illicit trafficking has never been greater,
according to the International Council of Museums, an organization
based in Paris that has tried to fight the problem with a code of
ethics for its 15,000 member institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows certain things are stolen, or should know it,
and yet these things still appear on the market,'' said Manus
Brinkman, secretary general of the council, in an interview. ``This
involves famous dealers and art houses, not just shady operators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not only from China,'' Brinkman added. ``It's
Cambodia and Thailand, Peru and Bolivia, Nigeria and Eastern
Europe, where icons are disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskenazi, the London dealer, countered that it was usually
impossible to thoroughly check the histories of Chinese antiquities
offered for sale. ``Many millions of objects have been exported
from China over hundreds of years,'' he said. ``Rarely do they come
with a provenance going back to their origin.''
</P>
<P>
   In defending their 1995 deal, Eskenazi and the Japanese museum
both said that Chinese officials never made an international report
of the statue's theft, which might have alerted them to a problem.
Boxing county officials say they reported the theft to their
provincial office in 1994, and it is unclear today to what level
the report was relayed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Eskenazi also said that the sculpture had been featured in a
widely distributed 1995 sales catalog seen by many Chinese experts
and officials and that no one raised any questions then.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A common problem in detecting questionable sales is that many
objects are taken abroad without ever being recorded by experts, in
well-organized operations that may involve the bribery of local or
higher-level officials. In China, farmers, construction workers and
criminal gangs unearth thousands of relics, large and small, each
year and quickly sell them to smugglers. In some cases thieves hack
panels off temple walls or steal items from poorly guarded museums
or storerooms, at times with the complicity of the keepers.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen artifacts are often smuggled to Hong Kong, officials
say, where they are given fake histories. Eventually they are sold,
often by top-flight dealers, galleries and auction houses in
Europe, the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The world's museums have generally set stricter standards for
acquisitions over the last decade, experts say, so that today
private collectors provide the major market for smuggled relics.
Pressure on the museums has grown as a result of bad publicity, the
1970 Unesco convention and the museum council's own code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   The Miho Museum has not joined the International Council of
Museums, but its curator says that the museum tries to avoid
trouble by purchasing from reputable dealers. ``If we buy it
indirectly, we have a sort of safe feeling,'' said Hiroaki
Katayama, chief curator of the Miho.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is now studying the Unesco convention with an eye to
possible signing, said Lyndel Prott, the Unesco official in charge
of implementing the convention. If it does join, the rules would
not apply to earlier imports.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty, the subscribing countries, which include
China, the United States and most other Western nations, agree that
when a theft is proved, the object must be returned, in some cases
with compensation to unknowing buyers. Negotiations are supposed to
occur through official diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the system works: on March 28 at Christie's auction
house in New York, American customs officials seized a marble wall
panel that had been chiseled off a 10th-century tomb in China in
1994. But often it is impossible to prove the source of suspicious
items.
</P>
<P>
   There is no simple definition of a legal or ethical acquisition
since many relics held in the West, including treasures in major
museums, were taken abroad in an earlier freewheeling era.
</P>
<P>
   The Unesco convention has provided a rough benchmark, Prott
said: if an object was first seen outside its country after 1970,
then ``a respectable museum should not buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The missing Shandong Buddhist figure is an exceptional case
because it had been photographed and described in a journal. Even
so, China may have to rely more on moral pressure than on legal
action to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   Katayama, the Miho's curator, said in an interview that even if
it is proved that the sculpture was the one stolen in 1994, the
museum might not return it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make every effort to check the origin of works in our
collection,'' he said. ``If a problem arises we deal with it in the
context of international law, and our lawyer says that with regard
to this statue, we don't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we purchased it in good faith, it is our asset and we
cannot return it for free,'' he added, implying that with
compensation, a return might be possible. ``Of course we need to
keep friendship with China, so we are willing to consult and
negotiate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   China has tried to fight relics smuggling and has made numerous
arrests of pillagers, but officials acknowledge that they are
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the mid-1980s, criminal activities to steal relics
stored in museums or from tombs have been incessant and growing
worse,'' Zhang Wenbin, the director of the State Cultural Relics
Bureau in Beijing, said in legislative testimony on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smuggling of relics is rampant,'' Zhang said. ``These problems
are related to the lax enforcement and inadequacies of relics
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the missing Shandong sculpture, confusion seems
to reign in the official system for combating theft.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the state relics bureau, Wang Limei, said in
an interview, ``This matter is being directly handled by the
Shandong Provincial Cultural Relics Bureau.'' But Zhang Congjun,
deputy director of the Shandong relics bureau, said: ``We have had
no contact with the Miho Museum, and this is a matter for the state
bureau to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Miho Museum officials have bypassed China's responsible national
and provincial agencies and visited Boxing county directly to
discuss the matter with local cultural and political officials in
the poor and isolated region.
</P>
<P>
   Some archaeologists and officials in Beijing question whether
local officials should negotiate the fate of an important relic
governed by national law.
</P>
<P>
   Katayama, the Miho curator, quietly traveled with colleagues and
a Swiss consultant to Boxing county in February and met mainly, he
said, with Li Shaonan, the county relics officer who originally
described the statue in that 1983 article.
</P>
<P>
   Katayama said that the museum had invited Li and five others,
including Shu, the county relics director, as well as a county
political leader, to visit the Miho in late May at the museum's
expense to examine the statue and discuss future steps. The
officials are now applying for passports.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
