<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN PREMIER QUITS AFTER ELECTION SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Closing down Italy's 57th government since World War II,
Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema resigned Wednesday, leaving his
battered center-left coalition to look for someone else to govern
until parliamentary elections a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   But Silvio Berlusconi, the center-right opposition leader who
was the big winner in the regional elections on Sunday, insisted
that President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi dissolve parliament right away
and call early elections.
</P>
<P>
   So Italians are left puzzling whether a center-left successor to
D'Alema can be found or whether they will head back to the polls
this spring, for the fourth parliamentary elections since 1992.
Ciampi also has the option of appointing a caretaker government,
even if the divided center-left majority can agree on a candidate,
or calling a snap election.
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi said he would begin consulting party leaders on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a final speech to the Senate Wednesday, D'Alema admitted some
failings that had led to his coalition's humiliating defeat. But he
urged his colleagues not to allow early elections that would
jettison a referendum on May 21 that he insists would bring greater
stability to the hybrid _ and volatile _ electoral system. D'Alema
wants to introduce a two-bloc system and eliminate proportional
representation, which accounts for 25 percent of the seats in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be paradoxical to go to a vote with an election
system that all political forces regard as inadequate to guarantee
government stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, however, many small parties in his own coalition oppose
changes in electoral laws that could wipe them out of parliament.
Berlusconi and some center-right allies also oppose the change.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema submitted his resignation to Ciampi on Monday, but was
told to consult parliament. Wednesday, he listened as senators
debated his rocky tenure and then returned to Ciampi's office and
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, his fate seemed obvious enough for his coalition
partners to begin weighing the chances of other leaders. Among the
names under hurried review was that of Treasury Minister Giuliano
Amato, a socialist who was prime minister for just under a year in
1992 and who is respected for his economic expertise.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, who turns 51 on Thursday, took office 18 months ago in
a parliamentary maneuver after his predecessor, Romano Prodi, had
lost a confidence vote by one vote. D'Alema was the first former
communist prime minister in Western Europe. But he steered a
centrist course, supporting the NATO conflict in Kosovo and passing
budgets aimed at keeping the Italian economy within the confines of
the euro.
</P>
<P>
   But his government majority was slim at the outset, and after
narrowly surviving a no-confidence vote in December, it shrank even
further. He was unable to push through welfare and pension reforms,
but alienated unions by trying. He had only moderate success
tackling the unemployment rate, which remains above 20 percent in
southern Italy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His government's lack of popular support was underlined in the
regional elections, when the center-right coalition won eight of 15
contests for regional presidents, who are roughly akin to U.S.
governors, including in Lazio, the region of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, 63, who was prime minister for less than a year in
1994, is a business and media baron. In the regional elections, his
party, Forza Italia, joined forces with the Northern League, which
rose in the late '80s as a separatist movement and still favors
great autonomy for the prosperous North. It is also
anti-immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the center-right coalition did better than expected,
hammering on issues like unemployment, crime and immigration. But
Berlusconi also made an issue of D'Alema's communist roots,
adopting ``freedom'' as his slogan and accusing the government of
undemocratic methods.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, even some staunch capitalists gave the
departing D'Alema good marks. ``He quit with a lot of style,''
Gianni Agnelli, a life senator and the honorary chairman of Fiat,
said after D'Alema's speech. ``As they used to say in the
regiments, it doesn't matter if you get off a horse or fall off of
it, the important thing is to do it with style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
