<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILLION-MOM-MARCH-HNS     04-19 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MOM-MARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILLION MOM MARCH IN WASHINGTON GETS LOCAL SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Local officials here said Wednesday they support
efforts by mothers across the country to march for gun control
legislation in the nation's capital on May 14.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference march promoters said they are seeking
passage of ``common-sense gun legislation,'' including measures to
prevent gun sales to criminals and make it easier to track guns
that are used to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C. Mayor Anthony Williams said, ``We don't need
another Columbine to know that it's time for licensing and
registration of handguns for background checks (and) strong
enforcement of our laws.'' He was referring to the shooting spree a
year ago at Columbine High School near Denver in which two
teenagers killed 12 students, a teacher and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and others insisted that Congress should approve gun
legislation even though some localities have already enacted strict
statutes. He noted that Washington, D.C. has banned the sale of
handguns within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters of the so-called Million Mom March said
Congress favors the National Rifle Association over the safety of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barnes, a former Maryland Democratic congressman who
heads Handgun Control Inc., a pro-gun-control group, said that
``because there is a very powerful gun lobby in this country,
nothing is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that on May 14, Mother's Day, ``tens of thousands of
Americans, led by our moms, will be here on the (National) Mall
calling for action.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited statistics showing 12 children die each day from gun
violence and that 4,000 children have been killed by guns in the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Albert Wynn, D-Md., said that ``unfortunately, the
Republican leadership hasn't listened to (gun control supporters).
Well I think on the 14th maybe they'll listen to the moms,'' he
said. ``We want sane, common-sense gun control laws now.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Del. Eleanor Holmes Norton, Washington, D.C.'s
nonvoting House member, noted that the 17 children killed in the
city so far this year were shot by people with handguns purchased
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has not met its national obligation to prevent
gun-running even into cities that have made handguns illegal within
their borders as we have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Local mothers who have lost children to gun violence, expressed
sorrow at their losses and anger at what they said are lax gun
control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Price, the Maryland coordinator of the march, vowed that
``Congress on May 14th will be forced to do something about this
national crisis that we are in or we, the mothers of this country,
will do something about Congress in November.'' Price's 13-year-old
son was accidentally shot and killed in 1998 by a nine-year-old
boy.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
