<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1634 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-ELIAN-ANALYSIS-1STLD-     04-19 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-ANALYSIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT SAYS SIX-YEAR-OLD ELIAN HAS LEGAL STANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     A News Analsysi  
 &HT;     (EDS: INSERTS new grafs 17-18 with Reno comment)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a federal appeals court order keeping Elian
Gonzalez in the United States, a key question raised by the court
is whether the six-year-old boy can apply for political asylum
against the wishes of his father.
</P>
<P>
   According to Charles Keely, an immigration law expert at
Georgetown University, Elian and his Miami relatives likely will
lose that argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds odd to me that a six-year-old would be presumed
capable of making a life-altering decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keely said that allowing Elian to apply for asylum would be
breaking a fundamental tenet of U.S. law, which is that minors
cannot speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where you draw the line,'' he said. ``If not at
six years old, then what about five years old, or maybe four years
old.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta upheld a restraining order keeping Elian in
the country. The appellate court said the U.S. government should
have taken the boy's wishes into account in determining whether he
should remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-page ruling bars anyone from attempting to remove Elian
from the United States until all court proceedings have been
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   But the court did not specifically forbid the INS from taking
custody and it did not address government efforts to reunite Elian
with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has been waiting in
Washington since April 6. The father says he wants to take his son
back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was one of three survivors of a shipwreck in which his
mother, her boyfriend and nine others drowned when their boat sank
as they were fleeing Cuba for the United States last November.
</P>
<P>
   The three appeals judges expressed support for efforts by
Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez of Miami, to win an asylum
hearing and questioned the Immigration and Naturalization Service's
handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the record, plaintiff _ although a young child _
has expressed a wish that he not be returned to Cuba,'' the judges
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that never have INS officials attempted to
interview plaintiff about his own wishes,'' the ruling said. ``It
is not clear that the INS, in finding plaintiff's father to be the
only proper representative, considered all of the relevant factors
_ particularly the child's separate and independent interests in
seeking asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   In a home video released to the public last week, Elian told his
father he does not want to return to Cuba. Elian's Miami relatives
say the boy wasn't coached about what to say and that the tape
proves he wants to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Keely said that the tape would mean ``very little'' in any
U.S. court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless someone can show why Juan Miguel shouldn't speak for
the child, the idea that courts should take a 6-year-old boy's
wishes over his father's is ludicrous,'' he said. ``What if a child
decides he doesn't want to go to school or eat anything but candy,
would our society tell his parents to let him? Of course, not.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which the government could appeal to the full
circuit court, is considered a critical step in the international
custody dispute that has lasted for nearly five months. The judges
had been asked by the government to overrule an emergency order
issued last week that delayed government efforts to bring Elian to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, in Oklahoma City to commemorate the
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building, promised to abide
by the appeals court's ruling, but pointed out that the decision
made no mention of where Elian should live with during his time in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not say the boy cannot be reunited with his father
while in the country,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly news conference Wednesday morning, Reno reiterated
that she would be willing to use force to reunited Elian with his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will utilize all law enforcement options if appropriate
under the 11th Circuit order,'' Reno told reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also brushed off criticism of her handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the criticism of me is that I'm trying to avoid violence,
if the criticism of me is that I'm trying to avoid that little boy
being hurt or being snatched away in a way that can scar him
further, I plead guilty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general rejected reports that the 1993 attack on
the Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, in which 78 members
of the Branch Davidian sect died, has caused her to hesitate on
taking action in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Waco, you had people who had not only defied the law but
killed people in the process,'' she said. ``There's a lot of
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she declined to comment on how she plans to end the
department's standoff with Elian's Miami relatives, Reno emphasized
that she had not ``lost her way,'' as some critics have charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where I'm going,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
