<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUMP-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DO JUMP!': TAKE OOHS AND AHS AND MIX WITH GIGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (EDITORS: production notes at end of review)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Where else in town can you find a nice set of
disembodied hands or a bridge chair that snaps shut to the music
from ``Jaws''? Where else do kites fly without wind or hand carts
turn into vehicles for inventive choreography?
</P>
<P>
   Well, once again the answer is the New Victory Theater, where a
talented troupe called ``Do Jump!'' is performing in a show of the
same name for a dozen more performances through April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Although the New Victory is dedicated to entertainment for
children, ``Do Jump!,'' with a succession of highly creative
vignettes that range from tap dancing to a power lunch by four
acrobatic women who mean business to clever audience participation
in performance and song, offers satisfying entertainment for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do Jump!,'' subtitled ``Extremely Physical Theater'' and
conceived and directed by Robin Lane, arrives from Portland, Ore.,
as a fusion of mischievous comedy, circus, dance and movement
enhanced by atmospheric lighting and buoyed by the wide spectrum of
propulsive music performed by the versatile four-member,
multi-instrument ``Do Jump!'' band.
</P>
<P>
   Visually and aurally this show adds up to yet another relaxing
treat, even if the final vignette, ``Doors,'' involving the entire
company and a two-level set of perverse wooden doors, might profit
from shortening.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that ``Do Jump!'' furnishes fun in
profusion. Laughter and cheers greet ``Walk Person,'' in which
instructions from headsets turn adults and children chosen from the
audience into a performing ensemble. Awed oohs respond to the
ethereal ``Fly,'' in which David Brittain sends his kites soaring
and swooping over stage and audience; and genuine ah's, ha's and
oh's are the audience's contribution to ``Ah Ha,'' a sing-along
determined by the constantly changing positions (including
upside-down) of two performers wearing shirts emblazoned with the
letters A, H and O.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked are the performers on rings and trapeze,
whose graceful postures are enhanced by the lighting of Tad Shannon
and the music created and performed by Mike Van Liew, Courtney Von
Drehle and Chris Monroe who, with Joan Szymko, constitute the band.
</P>
<P>
   As for the most praiseworthy ``Do Jump!'' troupe, its members
include Wendy Cohen, Heather Pearl, Daniela Steiner, Aaron
Wheeler-Kay, Kelli Wilson and Robin Woolman.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to all, ``Do Jump!'' keeps the New Victory jumping.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DO JUMP!'
</P>
<P>
   Conceived, choreographed and directed by Robin Lane; composers,
Joan Szymko, Mike Van Liew and Courtney Von Drehle; lighting by Tad
Shannon; costumes by Annie Warnock, Daniela Steiner, Katharine
Salzmann, Poppy Pos and Heather Pearl. Presented by the New 42nd
Street Inc. At the New Victory Theater, 209 W. 42nd St., Manhattan.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Wendy Cohen, Heather Pearl, Daniela Steiner, Aaron
Wheeler-Kay, Kelli Wilson, Robin Woolman and David Brittain.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
