<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COLUMNBINE-SCENE20-CO     04-19 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMNBINE-SCENE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Columbine tragedy etched in students' memory a year later
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ On the porch of a house on a broad street
that winds through steep hills south of Columbine High School,
Linda Gallegos tries to explain what was unthinkable one year ago
today: the killings that brought her neighborhood to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never dreamed we would have to deal with something so
monumental in our lives,'' said Gallegos, 53, mother of four
children who attended Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the area, subtle reminders of the tragedy abound.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher leads a group of students in from recess at nearby
Leawood Elementary School, where disbelieving parents and family
members of the 14 students and one teacher who died at Columbine
gathered in the gym a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the small children walk hand-in-hand in a long
snaking line. The teacher clutches a walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school, students are governed by a ``zero tolerance''
discipline policy. Trenchcoats are banned and teasing is strictly
controlled, punishable by suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the rows of homes clustered at the base of the
foothills are re-evaluating their relationships with their
children. They are tired of answering questions of the reporters
who have flocked to the area for the better part of a year.
</P>
<P>
   In the clusters of strip malls that surround the sprawling high
school, students discuss algebra over coffee at lunch. A group of
laughing girls with backpacks at their feet talk about boys.
</P>
<P>
   Three junior boys mull over the unfolding impact of the
shootings. They describe a transformation from what until a year
ago was a typical American high school experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents, right now, still want me to go somewhere else,''
said Dan Yager, 16. ``I just want to stay with it and beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager, who was eating in the school cafeteria when Eric Harris
and Dylan Klebold walked in shooting, said he never saw the gunmen.
He simply hit the floor when he heard gunshots and then quickly got
up and ran out.
</P>
<P>
   It took about three months for his fear of loud noises to
subside, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Stephens, 17, is angry with Harris and Klebold. He says the
outcasts who wore dark trenchcoats and chalky white face makeup to
school should have expected to be ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   But he holds a glimmer of understanding about why they killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised at all, those kids got bitched at day in
and day out,'' Stephens said. ``If you're different like that, if
you're going to be like that, you have to expect that, and they
didn't expect it. It's high school, it's going to happen, you've
got to expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Zimmerman, 17, said many of the students who a year ago
didn't fit into the cliques at Columbine have adapted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of those kids that used to hang out with them
last year changed a lot this year,'' Zimmerman said. ``They moved
or cleaned up their act. They quit wearing all of the black.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything that happened changes the way people
treat each other,'' he said. ``I haven't experienced any change.
They're still the groups, there's still the cliques.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Columbine are asking more questions, all three
boys said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give you pep talks before you leave on weekends,''
Stephens said. ``They want to know where you are, where you're
going, what kind of friends are you hanging out with.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they acknowledge the prospect of easily hiding things
from their own parents, all three boys place an amount of blame on
the parents of the two killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of the parent to teach their kid
morals, like not to kill people,'' Yager said.
</P>
<P>
   The killings should wake up a community that must be more
accepting of those who are different, Gallegos said. After all, she
said, the young killers didn't grow up in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't just happen to the children, it happened to all of
us,'' Gallegos said. ``I think it's an eye-opener. Those young men
were victims _ in a sense _ of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people have moved out of the quiet neighborhoods that wrap
around the high school, said Bob Schott, a 49-year-old computer
programmer whose daughter spent nearly four hours trapped in the
Columbine choir director's office on the day of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That particular day was the longest day of my life,'' said
Schott, who was a soccer coach to Steven Curnow, one of the
students who was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Some good has come from the shootings, Schott said. His company
donated funds to the victim's families and neighborhood residents
banded together to shovel snow and to do chores for the family of
Patrick Ireland, a neighbor who was severely injured in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are more willing to talk to students about personal
issues unrelated to school work, several students said.
</P>
<P>
   Cliques at Columbine have more respect for each other in the
aftermath of the shootings, said Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the kids that aren't popular, they don't get made fun of
as much as they would if nothing happened,'' Stephens said. ``Kids
finally understand what could happen as a result if you do say
something bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after the rampage, the children of Columbine are
beginning to understand how Harris and Klebold changed them. In
between the football games and lunch periods and walks home
dragging books linger thoughts that are strikingly unrelated to
normal high school experiences.
</P>
<P>
   They are teen-agers who have been exposed early to the prospect
of their own mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will affect them forever,'' Yager said, of his
classmates at Columbine. ``It just depends on the person, whether
they want to let it set them back or not. Some people take it, you
know, and some just don't do too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
