<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1641 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WHERE-THE-HEART-IS-FI     04-19 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHERE-THE-HEART-IS-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SITCOM SAVANT BRANCHES OUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Ohio)   By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People don't get much more alone in the world than Novalee
Nation in the early scenes of ``Where the Heart Is.'' She's 17,
very pregnant and even barefoot _ since her shoes fell through a
huge hole in the car floor somewhere between Tennessee and
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive from her trailer-park home to a new life in
California, she makes the mistake of asking her boyfriend to stop
at a Wal-Mart so she can go to the bathroom. When she returns to
the parking lot, he and the car are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Novalee (Natalie Portman, looking radiant but very un-Queen
Amidala-like) does the only thing she can think of, since she
doesn't know a soul in Sequoyah, Okla. She goes back into the
store, and when it closes for the night (while she's in the ladies'
room) she just stays.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the camping, patio furniture and exercise equipment
departments and shelves full of magazines and working alarm clocks,
she's quite comfortable for six weeks. After she goes into labor
there she's a local celebrity, and little by little she builds a
life in Sequoyah, with the usual ups and downs, weddings and
funerals, kidnappings and tornados.
</P>
<P>
   If a Hollywood studio had gone looking for the ideal director
for ``Where the Heart Is,'' which opens on Friday, it probably
would not have looked twice at Matt Williams, a bicoastal
television mogul resting on his laurels after helping create sitcom
megahits like ``Roseanne'' and ``Home Improvement,'' a man in his
late 40s who had never directed a film in his life.
</P>
<P>
   But when Wind Dancer, the production company he and two partners
run, acquired the rights to Billie Letts' down-home 1995 novel,
Williams got involved, looked around and eventually gave himself
the job. In the end, the choice made a lot of sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it more than anything else I've ever done in my
life,'' Williams says over beer and calamari at an Upper West Side
Italian restaurant near his apartment. ``Everything I've done that
I have understood from the inside out has succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   And he does know the people of ``Where the Heart Is,'' he
contends, even though his hometown, Evansville, Ind., may seem less
like Wal-Mart country than the film's Oklahoma setting. ``Indiana
is almost like three states,'' Williams says, ``one urban, one
rural, one Southern.'' Evansville, a blue-collar town on the Ohio
River, falls into the third category; cross the river and you're in
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved my childhood,'' he says. ``We rode horses and fished
in the creek for bluegill. But even in kindergarten I went, `I
don't believe there isn't more than this.' I just had no idea what
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   He was determined to find out, though. In fact, Williams' story,
like Novalee's, seems to prove that if you know what you want and
work hard to get it, you can create the life of your dreams. For
Novalee, that meant finally living in a home without wheels;
Williams' ambitions became a little grander.
</P>
<P>
   But they started out decidedly blue-collar. His father worked on
the assembly line for Whirlpool; his mother was a waitress. Their
son's summer jobs included laying brick and driving a dump truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I hadn't gotten a scholarship, I would have been a
bricklayer,'' he says. (There was creative influence at home,
though. On weekends his father was ``a passionate artist'' who
often discussed his paintings with his son.)
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams received two scholarships, in football and drama _
and says that he probably would not have been able to afford
college otherwise. He got a bachelor's degree in acting from the
University of Evansville and master's degrees in directing from the
University of New Orleans. His plan was to teach theater on the
college level, he says, and he thought it might be good to have
actual professional experience first.
</P>
<P>
   So in the mid-1970s, like a million young graduates before him,
he headed for New York. And like 99.9 percent of them, he did not
set the city on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Walking in and announcing, ``Hi, I'm a director and I'm 24 years
old,'' he recalls, did not get him very far. Still, he had to pay
the rent on his studio apartment in the East 80s. He had married
right after college, but his wife's salary as a Wall Street
beginner wasn't going to support them both. (She eventually became
a bond broker; they divorced after 11 years together.)
</P>
<P>
   Williams was a good-looking man (still is) _ an all-American
young-dad type, as he'd been told _ so he decided to give modeling
and television commercials a try.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked in the door for his first interview at a modeling
agency, the receptionist looked up and said: ``No. You're not our
type.'' Interview over. Luckily Williams is the kind of person who
reacts to rejection with renewed determination, rather than
crumpling and going to bed for a week. He made a grid of Manhattan
with agency addresses and walked the streets, sliding photographs
under doors.
</P>
<P>
   At home he practiced holding up products. He devised a
three-year plan, aiming for three national commercials in the first
three months. He got six in the first eight months and was soon
making more than $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   He then used the same methods to break into theater and
eventually wrote some one-act plays that were staged in the early
'80s at a small theater in Manhattan. They came to the attention of
the Emmy Award-winning sitcom director Jay Sandrich (``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show''), who asked Williams if he knew how to write for
television. Sandrich was just starting work on a new series that
would star Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This is where Williams' career begins to sound like a list of
familiar credits. He worked on ``The Cosby Show,'' which was a huge
NBC hit of the mid-1980s, for three and a half years. He helped
create its spinoff, ``A Different World.'' He was introduced to a
comedian known then as Roseanne Barr and was a co-creator of her
sitcom, ``Roseanne,'' but left after the first 13 weeks. (Don't
ask.)
</P>
<P>
   He did the unusual comedy anthology ``Carol and Co.'' with Carol
Burnett in 1990 and 1991. Then he was introduced to yet another
successful stand-up comic, Tim Allen, with thoughts of turning his
act into a television series. After their first lunch with Allen,
Williams turned to Carmen Finestra, one of his Wind Dancer
partners, and predicted the project would turn into a top 10 show.
It did. ``Home Improvement'' was a huge hit on ABC from 1991 to
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never about power tools,'' he says of the show, which
starred Allen as the host of a fictional how-to cable show called
``Tool Time.'' ``The series is about men and women. They shouldn't
live together, but they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been married to Angelina Fiordellisi, who owns and
manages the Cherry Lane Theater in Manhattan, for 13 years. They
have a daughter, Matisse, 12, and a son, Fredrick, 10. And they are
all full-time New Yorkers, which was not the case toward the end of
the ``Home Improvement'' years.
</P>
<P>
   That was, Williams says, the unhappiest period of his life. ``I
fell into what's known in the industry as mogulitis,'' he says. ``I
had become a business manager.'' So he downsized Wind Dancer and
decided to focus on feature films. That was about the time Susan
Cartsonis joined the company, raving about ``Where the Heart Is,''
a book she had almost gotten produced at her last job, with 20th
Century Fox. Wind Dancer obtained the rights and started looking
for writers.
</P>
<P>
   They chose Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel, whose past films
include ``City Slicker,'' ``Splash,'' ``Parenthood'' and ``EdTV.''
Although Ganz knew little about Williams at first _ ``To me, he was
like a tycoon. He was the guy who had struck gold in the TV sitcom
world'' _ he now describes him in glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the kind of director,'' says Ganz, ``who says, `What
do you think?' and means, `Don't you love it?' When Matt says that,
he really wants to know. He's like Ron Howard in that way. It's so
much better if you're not tiptoeing around someone's ego, if ego
doesn't get bruised by the normal collaborative process.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockard Channing, who plays against type in ``Where the Heart
Is,'' compares Williams in some ways to Mike Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that same sort of eye-of-the-hurricane quality,''
Channing says. ``He's so calm under fire. He really held his
ground, and that is a good 90 percent of being a director.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is also like Nichols, she added, in that both believe
``you hire the best people, then just step out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly worked with Channing's character, Sister Husband, a
colorful Oklahoman who runs a welcome wagon from a backfiring
turquoise Dodge pickup truck, bakes for neighbors even when a
tornado is coming and asks God's forgiveness for her latest act of
fornication whenever she says grace.
</P>
<P>
   In the novel Sister was a blue-haired 70-year-old; as Channing
she's more of an earth mother (inspired partly, Channing says, by
her friend Colleen Dewhurst, who died in 1991).
</P>
<P>
   While moviegoers decide whether they will take Channing,
Portman, Ashley Judd, Sally Field, Joan Cusack, James Frain and the
rest of the ``Where the Heart Is'' cast to their hearts, Williams,
who turned 49 last Tuesday, is moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that television money is going back into New York
theater. Wind Dancer has commissioned several plays which will be
produced Off Broadway. Williams is producing ``The Bubbly Black
Girl Sheds Her Chameleon Skin,'' Kirsten Childs' coming-of-age
musical, at Playwrights Horizons. And on the side he's at work on
the script of the next film he will direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly intense, a little darker in tone'' than ``Where
the Heart Is,'' he says, declining to give specifics. ``In the
Midwest everything is not Rockwellian.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
