<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY-N     04-19 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER ARTIST'S HEIRS FIGHT MARLBOROUGH GALLERY
</HEADLINE>
  By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marlborough, the international art gallery heavily fined in 1975
for defrauding the Mark Rothko estate and accused in court last
month of cheating the Francis Bacon estate, is also fighting a
legal battle over the estate of Kurt Schwitters, the German Dadaist
known for his collages, who died in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   In the Schwitters case, a lower court in Norway ruled against
the gallery in 1998, deciding that Marlborough's actions gave the
artist's heirs grounds for terminating the gallery's contract. But
an appeals court in Oslo reversed that decision on March 29 and
awarded Marlborough $1.2 million in compensation, about a third of
the sum the gallery had sought, plus court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Both courts made narrow decisions on the contract dispute,
briefly criticizing Marlborough, a global network of galleries
founded in 1946, but not commenting at length about the way it
conducts business.
</P>
<P>
   The lower court had awarded the Schwitters family nearly $4
million, plus court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kurth, the Cologne lawyer for Marlborough International
Fine Art, the Liechtenstein branch that is party to the Schwitters
suit, said he was delighted by the victory and the size of the
award.
</P>
<P>
   In Oslo, however, Dag Thorstensen, a lawyer representing Lola
Schwitters, the widow of Ernst Schwitters, the artist's son and
heir, and their son, Bengt, said they would appeal the decision to
Norway's supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements over artists' estates are not uncommon, lawyers
said, but they rarely involve such high-profile artists or such
serious allegations. And galleries usually prefer to settle them
out of court, away from the headlines that have dogged Marlborough
since the legal spectacle between its New York gallery and the
children of Rothko, the abstract expressionist who committed
suicide in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   In that 11-year-long court battle, which has some similarities
to the Schwitters and Bacon cases, Marlborough was found to have
sold more than 100 paintings at less than market value to favored
clients while it collected inflated commissions at the expense of
the estate. The court fined the gallery, its founder, Frank Lloyd,
and the estate's executors more than $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bacon case, filed in London on March 21, lawyers for his
estate accused Marlborough branches in London and Vaduz,
Liechtenstein, of wrongfully exploiting Bacon in a relationship
that began in 1958 and was ``manifestly disadvantageous'' to him
until his death in 1992, and then to his estate. The suit alleges
that Marlborough in London grossly underpaid Bacon for his works
and then resold them through its Liechtenstein branch at much
higher prices. It also contends that Marlborough has never supplied
a complete accounting of Bacon's works and sales and that
Marlborough handled some works it has never accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Marlborough in London declined to respond to
questions about the Bacon suit. Georgiana Gibbs, their spokeswoman,
said that Marlborough's lawyers would answer the allegations when
they file their defense.
</P>
<P>
   Although the three cases differ in substantial ways, the
disputes do resemble one another. They began decades ago, when
Lloyd, a charming and ambitious refugee from Vienna, ran the
galleries, paying at least as much attention to business as he did
to art. In all three cases, Marlborough had exclusive rights to
sell the artists' works. According to court documents, it
controlled the artworks, kept the records and, on some occasions,
refused to provide complete information about them to the heirs.
</P>
<P>
   It set prices, often low, with little or no consultation. It
moved art among its branches, most frequently to Liechtenstein. The
Liechtenstein office often buys works from other Marlborough
branches, then resells them at higher prices _ allowing Marlborough
to reap its largest profits in low-tax Liechtenstein, which is also
known for its secrecy laws. (Few other galleries, if any, have
copied Marlborough's Vaduz strategy, which is legal.)
</P>
<P>
   Marlborough's movement of the art complicated the three
disputes: when heirs or their lawyers asked one gallery for
information, it stalled or claimed no knowledge and referred the
inquirer to another Marlborough branch.
</P>
<P>
   Rothko, Bacon and Ernst Schwitters each used Marlborough
employees or people associated with the company as lawyers,
accountants or both and in two cases as estate trustees, creating
potential conflicts of interest. And Marlborough is known or said
to have moved potential evidence _ paintings or documents _ out of
the courts' jurisdiction in the first two cases.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Swiss bank accounts and other financial arrangements made
with Francis Bacon and Ernst Schwitters also figure into those two
cases, suggesting that the two may have colluded with Marlborough
to evade income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley N. Bergman, a lawyer in New York who represents
Marlborough's owners, five trusts established for the heirs of
Frank Lloyd, rejected the idea that the cases are similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Rothko case, the gallery made a mistake,'' he said.
``Frank Lloyd was wearing two hats. But in the Bacon and Schwitters
cases, the deals were made with the artists while they were alive,
and the heirs are looking for something more. Maybe the heirs feel
that because of the Rothko case they should investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew of no other such suits against Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, the lawyer in Germany, added that the Norwegian courts
had rejected efforts to introduce testimony about the Rothko case
in the Schwitters dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwitters case, which began in the mid-1990s, is
complicated. It involves a fight between Lola Schwitters and Ernst
Schwitters' mistress as well the gallery, specifically Marlborough
in Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
   When Kurt Schwitters died, Ernst, a Norwegian citizen, inherited
nearly 700 artworks now worth tens of millions of dollars. In 1963
he began a relationship with Marlborough. The last contract, signed
in 1986, gave Marlborough International Fine Arts the exclusive
right to sell art from the estate and entrusted all works to
Marlborough for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1989, Ernst Schwitters began an affair with an
Englishwoman, eventually leaving Norway to live with her. Four
years later, Schwitters suffered a stroke that left him paralyzed
and unable to speak. His wife tried to move him back to Norway, but
the mistress objected, and the dispute landed in British courts.
Because of that battle, a Norwegian court appointed Tone Bjorn, a
Norwegian lawyer, as Ernst's guardian in 1994. Schwitters returned
to Norway, and Bjorn began asking Marlborough for information about
his assets.
</P>
<P>
   But Marlborough contested her appointment in court and declined
to give her information, according to the courts' chronologies,
arguing that the requested data were ``trade secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
