<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY-2     04-19 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLBOROUGH-GALLERY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: ``trade secrets.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marlborough also refused to pay Bjorn's expenses from bank
accounts that Ernst Schwitters had established in Switzerland (and
not declared to the Norwegian tax authorities, court documents
say). Schwitters had given control of the accounts to his mistress
and to Gilbert Lloyd, Frank Lloyd's son, who is based at
Marlborough's London branch.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn's guardianship was also approved by Swiss courts, but
Marlborough then moved the Schwitters' bank accounts to
Liechtenstein, again out of her reach.
</P>
<P>
   Marlborough also delayed payment to the estate of nearly $6
million raised from the 1994 sale of 39 Schwitters works to a
German museum. Marlborough maintained that it could not pay
proceeds from the sale because of legal uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Bjorn gave notice to Marlborough terminating its
contract. She claimed that the gallery, among other things, had
failed to provide a usable inventory of the Schwitters works, had
refused to disclose the location and value of the works and had
made late and only partial payments from the sale to the German
museum. Marlborough promptly sued for breach of contract and loss
of income on future sales. Bjorn countersued to obtain the
Schwitters works in Marlborough's possession.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Norway, Bjorn, 47, who had experience as a
court-appointed guardian before the Schwitters case, said: ``I had
never been treated that way before. Their hostility was difficult
to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But after a while,'' she added, ``I understood that
Marlborough had its own agenda and that's why they acted the way
they did. They wanted to keep Ernst Schwitters in Britain because
that made it easier for them to sell more pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Marlborough, Kurth said that he in turn found it
hard to understand her comments. ``We tried to assist her in every
conceivable way,'' he said. Marlborough employees wrote letters
explaining the workings of the art market, he said, and offered to
meet with her.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Schwitters died in December 1996, leaving everything to
his wife, Lola, who succeeded Bjorn in the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Marlborough agreed out of court to surrender the works
in its possession to the Schwitters family. Subsequently, both
Norwegian courts have considered only the question of whether
Marlborough's behavior toward the estate was justification for
terminating its contract.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 lower-court decision, the judge said that
termination of the contract by Bjorn was justified and called
Marlborough's conduct toward her ``reprehensible.'' He ruled that
Marlborough had defaulted on its obligation to pay the proceeds
from sales into an account she could have access to. But it said
the estate had failed to prove that this act was part of an attempt
to misappropriate its assets.
</P>
<P>
   The March 29 ruling, however, said that Marlborough did face
ambiguity about where the proceeds from the art sales should go and
that its actions did not breach its contract. The decision
reproached Marlborough ``for not having given Ms. Bjorn information
about earlier transactions and about the works of art at an earlier
point in time than May 9, 1995,'' and it criticized Bengt
Schwitters for adopting an ``uncompromising attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The family now has control of the Schwitters artworks, and it
has not yet appointed another gallery as agent. And it vows that
its court battle with Marlborough will continue. Thorstensen, the
family lawyer, said that an appeal would be filed by June 3.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
