<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BOMB-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNEXPLODED GERMAN BOMB CAUSES EVACUATION IN BRITAIN
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON, Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Nearly 60 years after German airplanes menaced the
skies overhead, hundreds of suburban Londoners were evacuated
Wednesday after workmen discovered a 1,000-pound World War II bomb
at a
</P>
<P>
   construction site.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb was discovered Tuesday at a building site in
Bexleyheath about 12 miles southeast of central London. It was
positioned nose-down about six feet underground.
</P>
<P>
   Still demonstrating the stubborn resolve Britons displayed in
the face of Hitler's relentless air assault, some residents
resisted attempts Wednesday to move them out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some residents were reluctant to leave their homes,'' said
police Maj. Bob Tomkins, who oversaw the bomb disposal operation.
``I think that while it might have been quite laudable in the 1940s
with the great
</P>
<P>
   British Bulldog spirit, I don't think it appropriate any more.
They could do more to assist those who are here to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   After several hours, everyone agreed to leave, providing
military sappers the space they need to go about the delicate work
of disarming the massive weapon. When the bomb was deposited in
Bexleyheath by the Luftwaffe, it was capable of throwing shrapnel
about 6,000 feet from the point of impact.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 people were evacuated from nearly 1,000 homes,
police said. Traffic was diverted away from the bomb site, causing
rush hour chaos for commuters. As night fell, a 15-member bomb
squad worked
</P>
<P>
   gingerly with the bomb in a defusing process that was expected
to take 10 hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   Unexploded bombs are found fairly regularly in Britain. On the
approach to primary targets in the city, Bexleyheath was hit by 486
bombs in 1940 and 7,500 in 1941, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, air raid wardens tried to keep track of where
bombs fell but there were far too many bombs for them to accurately
record. Nearly 19,000 tons of high explosives were dropped by the
Luftwaffe on
</P>
<P>
   the capital between September 1940 and May 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The government has identified at least 100 bombs beneath homes,
businesses and parks in London. Officials have decided that it is
best to let the bombs alone unless they become unstable.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr. can be reached by e-mail at:
bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
