A1646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-DAFT20-COX     04-19 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DAFT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daft deftly handles intense annual meeting
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ The Coca-Cola Co.'s annual meeting Wednesday
was unlike any other in its history.
</P>
<P>
   The Playhouse Theater provided the perfect setting for a
corporate drama that unfolded over two hours and 40 minutes, the
longest Coca-Cola annual meeting anyone can remember. And it could
have gone on much longer. More than a dozen people were still
standing at six microphones at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Daft's first annual meeting as chief executive and chairman
held numerous plot twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   A call to boycott Coca-Cola products was made by current and
former African-American employees. Civil rights leader Jesse
Jackson was invited to make a statement in the middle of the
meeting. There was also the threat of a possible future boycott by
people opposed to the use of genetically engineered crops in
Coca-Cola's products.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder after shareholder rose to criticize the company,
though hardly any mention was made of the dramatic drop in
Coca-Cola's stock price over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the meeting did not come as a surprise to company
executives. The first frame of an opening video at the start of the
meeting flashed a quote from Albert Einstein: ``In the middle of
difficulty lies opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the message Daft wanted to convey to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite telling shareholders they would be given three minutes
each to speak, Daft repeatedly allowed speakers to exceed the time
limit. He stood silently at the podium until speakers were finished
and then invariably offered a personal response or anecdote,
seeking to connect with the shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting proceeded in an orderly manner with one exception.
In the middle of the meeting, someone shouted from the audience,
calling for the company to recycle more of its containers. Then a
group of students in the balcony begin to chant, ``Promise to
recycle, promise to recycle.'' After waiting a moment, Daft looked
up at them and said, ``I think you are a bit out of tune.'' The
meeting continued with no further outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Directors seemed pleased with how Daft conducted himself at the
sometimes tense meeting. ``Anytime you have a lot of protests at an
annual meeting, it tests the patience of the executive officer,''
said former Sen. Sam Nunn, a partner with King and Spalding law
firm. ``Doug Daft was cool, calm, collected and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Daft handled the meeting perfectly,'' said Herbert
Allen, another director. ``I think his statements toward diversity
couldn't have been more appropriate. He held an open meeting. I
don't think there was a person in the room, whether their
statements were pertinent or not, who did not feel they had an
opportunity to speak their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Ronald W. Allen, retired CEO of Delta Air Lines, noted
the meeting was quite different from other annual meetings he has
attended. ``There was a lot more open discussion and subjects
discussed at this annual meeting than in other years. I thought it
was a good open discussion from people with sincere concerns. I
think the chairman did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Warren Buffet, the largest individual shareholder of
Coca-Cola, wasn't quite as generous in his assessment: ``I'm not in
a commenting mood today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
