<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PRISONERS-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLYING WITH COURT ORDER, ISRAEL FREES 13 LEBANESE PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After spending years in prison in Israel without
charges, 13 Lebanese detainees were driven Wednesday morning in a
caged van to the border. There they waited into the late afternoon,
blindfolded and handcuffed, while a last legal wrinkle was ironed
out in their case.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after the Israeli Supreme Court rejected an 11th-hour
petition to keep the men behind bars, Israeli soldiers handed them
over to the International Committee of the Red Cross and the men
crossed back into Lebanon. Boarding a bus at the Fatma Gate, one
detainee raised his hands to the sky, covered his face and shook
his head in relief and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lebanese town of Kfar Tibnit, relatives and supporters
had been waiting for days to greet the men, whose release date kept
getting postponed. By the time the detainees' bus arrived, hundreds
mobbed it, some throwing rice, some weeping, and some fainting from
emotion. The men flashed the ``V-for-Victory'' sign out the
windows.
</P>
<P>
   But, to their relatives' frustration, their bus then rolled on
for a two-hour tour through the Lebanese countryside, orchestrated
by the Hezbollah Shiite Muslim group. The relatives followed
behind, in a convoy that snaked back 100 vehicles. Only at
Hezbollah headquarters, after the men kneeled at the feet of the
leader, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, did the families finally get to
embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Hijazi, who was ``a baby without a beard'' when his older
sister last saw him in 1986, looked pale and slight and overwhelmed
by the many relatives who smothered him with affection.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hijazi, several of the men had been imprisoned for more
than a decade, since they were teen-agers. Starting in the
mid-1980s, they had been abducted from Lebanon, convicted as
guerrilla sympathizers, and, after serving brief sentences, held as
``bargaining chips'' for missing Israeli soldiers. Some never stood
trial at all.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, reversing a decision it issued in 1997, the Israeli
Supreme Court ruled that the men posed no threat to state security
and that their continued detention was illegal. It ordered them
freed, setting off a fervid week of debate in Israel about whether
the ends justify the means in the society's search for their
missing soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Pressured by the relatives of missing soldiers, Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, a former general, secured his cabinet's approval to
craft legislation that would allow Israel to hold ``illegal
fighters'' as hostages to retrieve missing or captured soldiers.
The cabinet said it would seek to do so in a way that would not
contravene the High Court decision or international law, although
legal experts said that would be tricky, if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   To the disappointment of the relatives, Barak and his ministers
refused to intervene in the case already decided by the court. That
sent the relatives of a missing Israeli airman, Ron Arad, scurrying
back to the Supreme Court on Tuesday night to file their second
petition of the week seeking to block the detainees' release.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Wednesday, punctuated by the sobs of relatives,
lasted several hours as the judges heard arguments that the
detainees should remain in custody until the new legislation was
passed. Batya Arad, the mother of Ron Arad, pleaded with the
judges, telling them that her son, who was captured by Lebanese
guerrillas in 1986, had been missing for 4,969 days and nights. His
family believes that he is still alive, held by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look me straight in the eyes,'' Arad implored with a trembling
voice. ``What would you do if your son or grandson were in the same
situation?''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Aharon Barak said the state would continue to do
everything possible to obtain information about missing soldiers,
but that it had to be done ``within the confines of the law.''
Earlier in the week, several Israeli officials, including the
justice minister and the internal security minister, argued that,
moral and legal issues aside, the detention of the Lebanese simply
had not worked to secure information about Israeli prisoners of war
or their release.
</P>
<P>
   Israel did not release two remaining detainees, Mustafa
al-Dirani, who was a militia leader of the Amal guerrilla group,
and Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid, a spiritual leader of Hezbollah. The
government argued that those two men did represent threats to
national security, and a hearing on their case was scheduled for
May 8.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Kfar Tibnit, waiting on the one-lane country road as the
rumors ebbed and flowed about whether the men would actually be
released, Malik Yassine, 53, said he felt like he had been waiting
forever. Hezbollah trucks blared patriotic music and military
marches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This last week felt as long as the whole 14 years,'' Yassine
said. He was waiting to welcome home his brother-in-law, Abou
Biklal Bikrou.
</P>
<P>
   Sikna Khoul, 65, who is the mother of Hijazi, said her son was
abducted at the age of 14 by officials of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
   The officials took him because of a dispute with the family, she
said, insisting that her son was not a resistance fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a broken leg at the time,'' his sister, Jamila said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last four years, they had received both letters and
videos from Hijazi. He always told them that he was in good health,
and that someday he would enjoy his freedom. They worried about him
incessantly. Today, when they caught their first glimpse of his
face through the window, they simulataneously burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Alia, another sister, had kept his watch for
safekeeping. ``It's no longer ticking,'' she said. ``It's been too
much time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
