<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      04-19 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRIAL SET FOR SUSPECT IN MISSING ATHEIST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Gary Karr, the only person charged thus far in
connection with the disappearance of atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair,
will go on trial May 15 in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, who has been behind bars for the past year, is charged
with five federal counts, including kidnapping and robbing the
O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray
O'Hair, disappeared in late September 1995 after receiving $500,000
in gold coins in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FBI believes the O'Hairs were kidnapped, killed and
dismembered, their bodies have not been found. The government
claims to have recovered genetic evidence from an Austin storage
shed indicating they were murdered there.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyer, Thomas Mills of Dallas, says federal prosecutors
will first have to prove the O'Hair family is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several issues we'll seriously contest, including
whether the O'Hairs were in fact murdered or if they are out of
sight due to other circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn affidavit filed last spring in federal court in
Austin, authorities claimed Karr, David Waters and a third man
named Danny Fry abducted the O'Hairs and then murdered them for the
gold.
</P>
<P>
   Fry later turned up as a headless, handless corpse in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Karr has acknowledged that he helped Mr. Waters in
assisting the O'Hairs to dispose of assets and leave Texas, and
that is not a crime,'' said Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who is serving a lengthy state prison term for stealing
$54,400 from the O'Hairs while their office manager, has not been
charged in their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have described him as the mastermind of the plot to
do in the O'Hairs. Karr and Waters have long criminal records, and
the two met as inmates in the Illinois prison system.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's case will be heard by U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks, who
has a reputation for keeping things moving in his courtroom. Sparks
has allotted three weeks for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The case is going to trial after government efforts to cut a
deal with Karr in exchange for his testimony against Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Carruth, the assistant U.S. Attorney who will present the
government's case against Karr, declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
