<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS &LR;      04-19 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON POSTS $181 MILLION LOSS IN FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. Wednesday posted a first-quarter loss of $181
million, chiefly related to the sale of its heavy-construction
unit, compared to net income of $205 million for the corresponding
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Income from continuing operations at the Lexington, Mass.
defense contractor was $80 million, or 24 cents a share, down from
$240 million, or 71 cents a share, for the same period a year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Net revenue dipped 3 percent, to $4.23 billion from $4.34
billion a year before, a decrease driven by lower sales of missiles
and information systems.
</P>
<P>
   The results were in line with the expectations of analysts
tracking the company's efforts to restore its profitability after a
series of earnings disappointments and a steep decline in its share
price.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Morrison Knudsen Corp. of Boise, Idaho, said it will
buy Raytheon's Engineers &AMP; Constructors unit for about $10 million
in cash and assume about $500 million in liabilities. Raytheon
recorded a $191 million loss on the sale, equivalent to 77 cents a
share, and has classified the unit as a discontinued operation for
accounting purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Some had hoped the unit might fetch more cash for Raytheon,
which forecasts it will have net debt of $9 billion to $9.2 billion
at the end of this year. Problems at the construction unit
contributed to the quarter's losses, as Raytheon had previously
warned.
</P>
<P>
   But on a conference call with analysts, chief executive Daniel
Burnham said Raytheon's performance otherwise was ``an important
first step in repositioning the company for 2001 and beyond.'' He
cited new revenue the company may receive for upcoming missile
contracts and work on the National Missile Defense Program.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham and chief financial officer Frank Caine wouldn't rule
out additional sales. But they said they would focus on selling off
smaller divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also praised a draft report prepared by a Pentagon panel
that suggested changes in the way the military buys and pays for
its equipment, such as allowing contractors to keep a greater share
of their cost savings.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report also contains criticism of defense-company
management. But if certain of its suggestions are implemented,
Burnham said, they would benefit Raytheon's bottom line by
``hundreds of millions of dollars of pretax profit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a wonderful job of taking costs out'' through
quality-control programs, he said. ``But the reality is we have to
give a lot of it away'' to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Following the sale of the construction unit, Raytheon revised
its profit outlook for 2000. It now expects profit of $1.40 to
$1.55 a share. Analysts had expected the company to report $1.50 to
$1.75 a share for the year, according to First Call/Thompson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's widely traded class B shares in New York Stock
Exchange trading after the results were announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
