<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG20-COX     04-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain says he misled voters, urges flag be taken down
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Dragging South Carolina's fight over the
Confederate flag back into the national spotlight, Republican John
McCain said Wednesday he misled voters about his opposition to the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator, who was defeated in the GOP primary
campaign by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, said he believed all along
that the flag should be removed from atop South Carolina's capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A descendent of Confederate soldiers, McCain said he was
dishonest when asked during South Carolina's presidential primary
for his personal views on the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he repeatedly said the issue should be decided by South
Carolinians. He noted that some view it as a racist symbol, and
others cherish its heritage.
</P>
<P>
   McCain admitted Wednesday the answer was a politically motivated
dodge that ''broke my promise to always tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I feared that if I answered honestly, I could not win the
South Carolina primary,'' McCain told the South Carolina Policy
Council on his first visit to the state since Bush easily won the
Feb. 19 primary. ''So I chose to compromise my principles.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spoke bluntly Wednesday, saying Confederate soldiers
''fought on the wrong side of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jake Knotts, R-Columbia, said he was disgusted by
McCain, whom he had supported during the state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he would lie on the campaign trail, he is no better than
Bill Clinton,'' said Knotts, a flag supporter. ''I feel he should
not come to South Carolina and inject his opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vince Ellison, a Republican running against James Clyburn,
the incumbent Democrat in South Carolina's 6th Congressional
District, said McCain ''cleared his conscious, which is good. A lot
of politicians could learn from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating criticism from ''all sides for my late act of
contrition,'' McCain said he decided several weeks ago to travel to
Columbia, after deciding to apologize. He said the trip was not
intended to pressure Bush to reexamine his flag stance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, too, had said it was an issue for South Carolinians to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Eskew, Bush's press secretary in South Carolina, said
Bush had predicted that after the primary, ''South Carolinians of
good will would make progress toward a resolution. He was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a state House Judiciary subcommittee began debating
flag proposals, including a bill the state Senate passed last week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain offered advice, though he said his ''dishonesty'' had
''severely diminished'' its value in the flag fight.
</P>
<P>
   He urged South Carolinians to ''find common ground on which to
bury past injustice and commemorate a heritage, an American
heritage, that respects the dignity of all mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   It's up to the state Legislature to move the flag, which the
body raised atop the Statehouse in 1962 as part of a Civil War
centennial. Tens of thousands of people on both sides have marched
in Columbia, including a 120-mile, Charleston-to-Columbia trek led
by flag opponent Joseph Riley, Charleston's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think marches and comment from third-party outsiders
is going to resolve this issue,'' House Speaker David Wilkins said
Wednesday before the subcommittee's public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenville Republican said he was ''cautiously optimistic''
about the Legislature reaching a flag compromise before the body
adjourns June 1.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the bill passed by the Senate provides the
best opportunity for a speedy resolution, though he acknowledged
its many critics.
</P>
<P>
   The state NAACP on Wednesday reiterated its opposition, saying
it may seek to join forces with staunch flag supporters who also
oppose the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would remove the flag from atop the Statehouse. It
would be replaced by a different, smaller Confederate flag, hoisted
on a flagpole behind the Confederate soldiers' monument on the
Statehouse grounds at Main and Gervais streets.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP, which has vowed to continue its national economic
boycott of South Carolina, says that busy downtown intersection
provides the flag too visible a location. Flag supporters say the
flag deserves a place of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This state is in trouble because of this flag; people are torn
asunder,'' said state Rep. Joe Neal, D-Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill's sponsor, Sen. Robert Ford, D-Charleston,
warned House Judiciary Committee members that tinkering with the
legislation will doom it, leaving little hope for removing the flag
this session.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you do not vote for this bill, you are in bed with the
Confederacy,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   But several House members said the Senate bill fails to bring
''finality'' the the flag dispute.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Gilda Cobb-Hunter, the African-American House
minority leader, said she and colleagues were preparing an
amendment to the Senate bill that ''will bring closure, with
healing.'' Borrowing from other proposals, she said the plan would
include a healing pool and a circle of flags on the Statehouse
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
