<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, April 20, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   LA-BUSINESS (Los Angeles) _ So much for Mayor Riordan's vow to
make the city more business friendly. Somebody goofed in Los
Angeles City Hall and the city mailed 11,000 erroneous notices to
business owners, mistakenly chastising them for not paying their
business license fees. By Alexa Haussler. (Will move in the ``a''
national and the ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DA-RAMPART (Los Angeles) _ The public defender's office is
asking for sanctions against the district attorney, claiming it is
hiding the reason it is overturning Rampart scandal cases behind
boilerplate language, hurting efforts to free more people. By Beth
Barrett and Greg Gittrich. (Will move in the ``a'' national and the
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SMOG-INDEX (Los Angeles) _ Just as Los Angeles comes off its
first year without a smog alert, the region's air pollution monitor
will unveil a new index Thursday that could lead to forecasts of
seemingly smoggier days. By Robert Monroe. (Will move in the ``a''
national and the ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-FOLLOW (Washington) _ A week from today, census workers
will start knocking on doors at homes that did not return their
census questionnaires. Now that phase-one of the census has ended,
the U.S. Census Bureau will release figures Thursday showing the
``initial response rate'' in each city, county and state. Burbank
is among a small handful of cities that improved their response
rate by 5 percent or more, compared with a decade ago. Los Angeles
was up 1 percent. California improved by 2 percent, a notable
turnaround because the state's rate kept falling in previous
decades. By Bill Hillburg. (Will move in the ``a'' national and the
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
</TEXT>
