<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1674 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     04-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A SMALL BOY HAS REPLACED MISSILES AS THE SYMBOL OF U.S.-CUBAN
RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Long ago when the elegant, young John F. Kennedy
was president, the symbol of U. S.-Cuban relations was an array of
Soviet-made missiles capable of firing deadly nuclear warheads into
our country.
</P>
<P>
   That was 38 years ago. Since then, we have witnessed dramatic
changes, including a remarkable switch in the symbol. Now it is a
six-year-old boy named Elian Gonzalez, whose custody has triggered
a bitter dispute between Cubans living in Miami and those in Fidel
Castro's island domain.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1962, the Cold War was hot, the Soviet Union was run
by the bombastic Nikita Khrushchev, and nuclear confrontation was a
constant threat to a tenuous peace. In an effort to project Soviet
military power into the Western Hemisphere, Khrushchev had secretly
ordered the shipment of offensive ballistic missiles to Cuba, where
launching pads were being constructed.
</P>
<P>
   When American U-2 spy planes confirmed Khrushchev's provocative
deception, Kennedy ordered a quarantine of Cuba. He also demanded a
halt in the shipment and installation of the missiles, which posed
a perilous threat to the United States and other Western Hemisphere
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly four decades later, relations between Washington
and Havana remain prickly, and Castro is celebrating his 41st year
as Cuba's dictator. At the same time, the United States is
preparing to elect its 10th president since Castro seized power in
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   He has stage-managed efforts to return Elian to his father and
then to Cuba, while Elian's relatives in Miami have fought to
obtain custody of the boy. Elian was plucked from frigid waters off
the Florida coast last November after the boat carrying him and his
mother to this country capsized.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation between America and the Soviet Union in 1962
propelled the world closer to nuclear war than it ever has been. No
one, including Kennedy and his top advisers, knew how far
Khrushchev would go to gain a military foothold just 90 miles from
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Had the conflict reached the point of a probable nuclear
exchange, the president and his national security team were to fly
to a heavily-fortified underground command post in the Blue Ridge
mountains of Virginia, and we who covered the White House on a
regular basis were to go with him.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I packed the trunk of our car with canned food,
blankets and water. If I was able to get advance word to her that
Soviet missiles might soon be headed our way, she and our two
children were ready to drive into Virginia to stay with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 22, 1962, a somber Kennedy told the American people in a
televised speech, ``My fellow citizens, let no one doubt that this
is a difficult and dangerous effort. No one can foresee precisely
what course it will take or what costs or casualties will be
incurred. But the greatest danger of all would be to do nothing.
Our goal is not victory of might, but the vindication of right _
not peace at the expense of freedom, but both peace and freedom,
here in this hemisphere and, we hope, around the world. God
willing, that goal will be achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also warned Moscow that ``it shall be the policy
of this nation to regard any nuclear missile launched from Cuba
against any nation in the Western Hemisphere as an attack by the
Soviet Union on the United States, requiring a full retaliatory
response upon the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   The desperate interlude finally ended when Khrushchev sent two
conflicting letters to the White House and Kennedy chose to answer
only the one that was reasonable and offered a way out of the
missile crisis. As a result, ships heading for Cuba loaded with
Soviet missiles turned around and sailed back to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   This year there is no threat of war over the actions of Fidel
Castro. The Soviet Union, which had bankrolled him, broke apart
when the Cold War ended. And Moscow's financial and military
support of Castro presumably ended shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle over the fate of little Elian recalls the many
troubles America has had with Castro since he claimed absolute
leadership over Cuba in 1959. The Dwight Eisenhower administration
in Washington was pleased at that time to see the departure of
Cuba's dictator, Fulgencio Batista, described by Ike's biographer,
Stephen Ambrose, as ``corrupt and reactionary.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Ambrose wrote, the tall, bearded Castro was
``young, romantic, dynamic and full of promises about free
elections, social reform, new schools and economic justice.''
Eisenhower, therefore, extended full diplomatic recognition to the
Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   But early in 1960, Ambrose continued, it became apparent that
Castro's regime was becoming ``a complete communist dictatorship.''
The CIA began training and arming a force of 1,400 exiled Cubans to
prepare for an invasion to overthrow Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had been in the White House a mere three months when the
invasion began at Cuba's Bay of Pigs in April, 1961. The new
president ruled out the commitment of U.S. troops to help the
rebels, and within three days of the landing, the invasion force
was decimated.
</P>
<P>
   After Kennedy's assassination in 1963, some Americans decided
that although Lee Harvey Oswald pulled the trigger that killed
President, the evil force behind the plot was Castro. At the same
time, word circulated that Kennedy had approved an American plan to
kill Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Against such a background of conspiracy and violence it is
ironic that a tiny Spanish-speaking lad who knows nothing of past
or present world tensions should now emerge as the symbol of
U.S.-Cuban relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
