<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-AFRIKANERS-2T     04-19 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AFRIKANERS-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRIKANERS ARE PLEASANTLY SURPRISED BY LIFE UNDER THE MBEKI
GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ The telephone rang on his desk that workday
morning, and when Neil van Heerden snatched it up, the voice on the
line asked: Will you join some prominent businessmen in signing a
declaration of support for President Thabo Mbeki?
</P>
<P>
   For decades, van Heerden had worked as a diplomat for the
apartheid regime. He is a proud Afrikaner, who speaks eloquently
about the dislocation and depression his people felt after they
finally surrendered power to a black government six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also a practical man who has learned to adapt. So when
the call came from a friend two months ago, he did not hesitate.
With a flourish, he joined more than 30 Afrikaner business leaders
who praised the president's ``vision and leadership'' and landed on
the front pages of South African newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If that's what you want to say, I'm with you,''' said
van Heerden, who now runs the South Africa Foundation, an
association of more than 40 of the country's biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected pat on the back for Mbeki is a reflection of one
of the more surprising shifts in the economic landscape here since
the end of apartheid: the growing confidence and increased
prosperity of wealthy Afrikaners under black rule.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Afrikaners, descendants of 17th-century Dutch,
German and French settlers, invented the brutal system of total
racial segregation known as apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   But when government finally changed hands, many Afrikaners
decided to stay put. After more than 300 years in South Africa,
most had nowhere else to go. By contrast, a sizable number of
English-speaking descendants of British colonialists _ who were
less numerous than the Afrikaners but controlled much of the
economy under apartheid _ did leave, enabling Afrikaners to fill
the gaps. Though emigration statistics are not broken down by
ethnic group, the exodus of English-speaking whites has been
perceptible in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1996 and 1999, Afrikaner businessmen saw their share of
the Johannesburg Stock Exchange surge from 24 percent to 36 percent
as they snapped up companies shed by emigrating firms and began
dominating the growing technology and electronics sectors,
according to a new study by Robin McGregor, a prominent analyst who
has tracked several decades of corporate ownership.
</P>
<P>
   And many Afrikaner businessmen, who once viewed a black
government with suspicion, now believe their economic prospects
will only improve under Mbeki, who is taming the deficit and
reducing taxes, and has promised to relax tough labor laws and
speed the privatization of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, which stood at 12.5 percent in 1994, dipped to 5.2
percent last year. And the economy, which grew by only 1 percent in
1999, is expected to grow by at least 6 percent during the next two
years. In February, the credit rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's
upgraded South Africa's debt rating to investment grade, noting
that Mbeki's administration ``had stepped up the pace of structural
reform.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the business magazine, Financial Mail, recently wrote
about the nation's black president, the black Reserve Bank chairman
and the black finance minister under the headline, ``We've Never
Had It So Good,'' many Afrikaner businessmen found themselves
nodding their heads in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What has impressed me is Mbeki's uncompromising pursuit of
these economic goals, which is extremely important for this
country,'' said Paul Kruger, the chairman of Sasol, the country's
largest fuel and chemicals company. ``I just believe one should
give credit where credit is due.
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't to say that I'm going to vote for this
government,'' added Kruger, who was a proud and long-time member of
the National Party, the Afrikaner-based party that
institutionalized apartheid. ``This doesn't mean joining the ANC.
But this government is on the right track. I am positive about the
future. And I wanted to get that message of hope across,
particularly to Afrikaans-speaking people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of news that left Mbeki's supporters jumping
with glee and his critics grumbling about publicity stunts.
</P>
<P>
   For the government, it was a moment of sweet vindication, a
chance to proclaim that those who had assumed that Mbeki would
alienate whites were just plumb wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be Nelson Mandela, the great reconciler. But his
supporters say he is a leader who delivers, a man who wins hearts
and minds with smart and practical policy.
</P>
<P>
   And while Mbeki does not need Afrikaners to win elections _ they
are only about 7 percent of the population _ the endorsement from
their business leaders may help him win greater credibility abroad
at a time when his government is actively seeking foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If bankers and captains of industry believe Mbeki is the right
man for the job, why should the others not believe?'' asked Parks
Mankahlana, the spokesman for Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
   But some Afrikaners are quick to accuse rich Afrikaner
businessmen like Kruger; G.T. Ferreira, chairman of FirstRand, the
financial services giant; and Christo Wiese, chairman of Pepkor, a
retailing company, of simply trying to curry favor with a black
government.
</P>
<P>
   Such wealthy people, these critics say, have lost touch with
ordinary whites who distrust a government that aggressively
promotes affirmative action but has had a hard time battling crime.
Certainly the percentage of whites that support the government
remains small.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Human Sciences Research Council found that
11 percent of whites surveyed in November 1999 were satisfied with
national government. That is up from 6 percent the previous year,
but it is still no ringing endorsement of black rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``These rich people sit on the top of the mountain and say to
the average Afrikaner, `It's OK here. It's nice here,' but that is
definitely not the feeling we have from the people on the ground,''
said Dirk Hermann, the spokesman for the Mine Workers' Union, which
represents 65,000 Afrikaners in mining, telecommunications and
electrical engineering. ``Most Afrikaners are alienated by this
government's policies.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the gesture by the Afrikaner businessmen, small as it may
be, is one of a number of recent examples of whites and blacks
reaching tentatively across the racial divide.
</P>
<P>
   In January, for instance, Roelof F. Botha, the long-serving
foreign minister for the apartheid regime, stunned the nation when
he announced plans to join the governing party, the African
National Congress, and urged other whites to do the same. ANC
officials say Botha now holds an ANC membership card. In February,
the Democratic Party, which has become the pre-eminent party among
whites in this country, announced that its leaders would start
visiting townships and squatter camps as part of a five-year
campaign to win the hearts of black voters.
</P>
<P>
   And in June, for the first time ever, the youth leagues of the
most influential Afrikaner and black organizations _ the
Afrikanerbond and the African National Congress _ will hold a joint
conference to focus on building trust and unity among the next
generation of leaders. The Afrikanerbond is the post-apartheid
incarnation of the Broederbond, the powerful secret society that
advanced Afrikaner interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two worlds meeting,'' said Jan du Plooy, president of the
Afrikanerbond Youth League, who admits he was astonished when the
ANC sent an invitation for a meeting late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to look forward,'' said du Plooy, who is also a
lieutenant colonel in the South African National Defense Force.
``We're trying to focus on commonalities. We want to get away from
just being a Zulu, a Xhosa or an Afrikaner. What is it to be a
South African?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the ANC youth league say Mbeki suggested the
rapprochement between the two organizations. It was Mbeki, after
all, who initiated some of the first contacts between black exiles
and white businessmen in the 1980s, before the end of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Mbeki's old friend from those days, Professor Willie
Esterhuyse of the University of Stellenbosch, who rallied support
in the business community for the recent declaration.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sense among many blacks here that Afrikaners, despite
their history of racial intolerance, are more committed to this
country than English-speaking whites. And since his election to the
presidency last year, Mbeki has continued to woo this constituency.
</P>
<P>
   He has addressed Afrikaner organizations in speeches peppered
with verses of Afrikaans poetry, has promised to protect their
language and, more recently, has agreed to consider amending the
law to allow for the continued existence of Orania, a white
homeland, which is scheduled to merge with a nearby black town.
</P>
<P>
   Some people dismiss these actions as smart politicking, not
genuine sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   But in this polarized society, where the sturdy walls of race
still divide much of the country, even polite, self-interested
gestures across the color line still make for front-page news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concerted effort to reassure Afrikaners, and that's
certainly significant,'' said J.P. Landman, the editor of Finance
Week, a business weekly which is published in Afrikaans and in
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks through the traditional pattern of animosity between
the ANC and the Afrikaans-speaking community,'' Landman said. ``My
sense is that the government has taken a decision somewhere in the
recent past to build more bridges between themselves and the
Afrikaners.'' By signing the declaration, several businessmen said
they had hoped to build bridges, too. They said they wanted to show
other Afrikaners that they had overcome their fears, even though
the transition was not an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   Van Heerden, who served as a diplomat in Brussels for two years
under Mandela, vividly describes the struggle to adjust to the new
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that there was a sense of loss, of
confusion, of fear of the future,'' said van Heerden, as he
pondered the psychological impact of the power shift one recent
morning in his office here. ``Suddenly, I'm being ruled by my
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I believe since 1994, the Afrikaner has taken stock,'' he
said. ``He has sort of caught his breath. He says, `Here I am. I'm
still alive. I still have my house and my car and the heavens
haven't fallen.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looked at the quality of the people who are now his
rulers, and he's beginning to say, `Although we have black
empowerment and affirmative action, I can find standing room in
this country,''' van Heerden said. ``I think that is what Mbeki is
saying, too. There is room for all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
