<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OMAR-EPPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPPS CALLS HIS SHOTS IN `LOVE &AMP; BASKETBALL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Omar Epps got his start in movies when most films
about black people concerned urban violence, from ``Menace II
Society'' and ``Boyz N the Hood'' to his own debut at 18 in 1992's
``Juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's happy to have grown along with the movies.
</P>
<P>
   His latest film, ``Love &AMP; Basketball,'' which opens Friday, is a
romance about two kids from affluent families (Epps and Sanaa
Lathan) who mature and fall in love while sharing a love of hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad (black films) are changing,'' Epps, 26, said during a
recent visit to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, whatever's making money, that's the films they'll
be making. But lately films like `The Best Man' and `The Wood' (in
which Epps also starred) are doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like those movies, ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' has humor and heart, as
the kids (first played by child actors) grow into adults who become
serious about basketball but also each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is two-thirds love and one-third basketball,'' said
Epps, who trained for two months with coaches at UCLA after
director-writer Gina Prince cast him.
</P>
<P>
   Epps, who's 5 feet 10 and plays guard, had played basketball
while growing up in Brooklyn, N.Y., where he still spends time with
his family when he's not in Los Angeles, where he moved three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But his ``playground ball'' was insufficient for portraying
Quincy, who becomes a star in college and goes on to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to learn disciplined ball, organized ball, but that was
fun,'' he said. ``I've got some moves I never had _ a nice little
jumper. When we wrapped I was blazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But last week when I shot the ball again, I said, `Well, I
guess that movie is over.' I hadn't played for two months, and now
I'm back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps also has starred in a football movie, ``The Program,'' as
well as a baseball film, ``Major League II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit athletic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There, his steadily ringing cell phone signaled how busy Epps
has become.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``The Wood,'' he's also appeared recently in ``Breakfast
of Champions,'' ``In Too Deep,'' ``Scream 2'' and ``The Mod
Squad.'' Next up is ``Brother,'' about Japanese gangsters known as
``yakuza.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, Epps starred for one season on ``ER,''
playing Dr. Dennis Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Although he declines TV offers now, ``That was big for me,'' he
said. ``It introduced me to the mainstream. I was in 40.7 million
people's living rooms across the country, and that ain't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   His career path began with studies. Epps is a graduate of New
York's High School for the Performing Arts, the setting for 1980's
``Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   While the school's real students don't necessarily enact musical
numbers in the cafeteria, Epps said the school ``was wild and
interesting. It was like a microcosm of New York _ like the
Internet but in human form.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the ``Fame''-school graduate is getting parts written
especially for him. Prince wrote her script with Epps in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time that's happened,'' he said. ``That's
definitely flattering _ another mark in my career that I'll look
back on. It's a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of ``Love &AMP; Basketball's'' producers was filmmaker Spike
Lee. But though Lee put his weight behind the production, he didn't
interfere with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike was like a big brother,'' Epps said. ``He helped get the
film rolling and then left it alone so Gina could do her thing. I
think he only came to the set (in L.A.) one time.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Basketball'' has ``tested really well'' in advance
screenings, Epps said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies don't have to have an alien or a gun,'' he said. ``They
just need to tell a story that people like. In this one you see the
characters grow and learn what it means to love one person. I think
it is eloquently done.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps is pleased that Prince didn't hammer home a feminist
message, although the film concerns inequities in pro basketball
before the WNBA's emergence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want to use the film as a podium to make a
statement about women's athletics,'' Epps said. ``It's a love
story. It's not preachy, and I like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you do see how women had to go overseas to be pros, like
Coop did,'' Epps said, referring to the Houston Comets' Cynthia
Cooper, whom he admiringly calls ``the one.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps' and Lathan's characters are depicted as virtual equals on
the court, as shown when they compete one-on-one. (Lathan also has
starred in ``Blade,'' ``The Wood'' and ``The Best Man.'')
</P>
<P>
   But those games were just role-playing, Epps said when asked
who's the better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, come on. She'd never played basketball _ ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I will say this: When they were casting her part, Sanaa
was the best actress in the room, hands down. She did a great
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandishing his hoops skills wasn't Epps' first priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern in doing a sports film,'' he said, ``is that I
can't get hurt.'' (Films can lose millions in lost production time
if a star is injured.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the basketball scenes, I only gave about 40 percent and let
the camera do the rest,'' Epps said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thought was, `I can't get injured.' There is no `what
if?' And in basketball, there are so many ways you can get
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps did not get hurt, but problems arose in other ways. Some of
his opponents on the screen were recruited from college ranks or
the fringes of pro basketball. Those guys had something to prove,
regardless of a scene's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing hard,'' Epps said with a laugh. ``We had to
keep saying, `Hey, it's a movie. No matter what you do, I'm
supposed to make the shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
