<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NUCLEAR-ART-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION AND MISTRUST BUILD AT BRITISH NUCLEAR COMPLEX
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: NYT Photo 27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALAN COWELL c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  SELLAFIELD, England _ When John Storer took over a new
high-profile job at Britain's most dispute-ridden nuclear complex
in September, he expected ``a fairly steep learning curve.''
Instead, he said, ``World War III started shortly afterward.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as Storer,  &UR; a  &LR; 40-year-old engineer &UR; , &LR;  settled into his
position overseeing a troubled nuclear fuel reprocessing unit, he
was told that workers had falsified documents involving fuel rods
even then in transit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The implications were not lost on Storer. It was the first
shipment of such fuel rods to Japan _ a crucial customer of British
Nuclear Fuels, the government-owned company that operates the
sprawling Sellafield complex. The discovery, moreover, coincided
with efforts by the company to secure government approval for
plutonium processing at a gleaming new unit here designed to turn
out ``mixed oxide'' fuel _ a blend of uranium and plutonium. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``The timing was a disaster,'' Storer said in an interview.
``And worse still, it was self-inflicted. We had shot ourselves in
the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, things turned out far worse than he had imagined,
causing the equivalent of a commercial meltdown at this complex on
England's wild northwestern coast, which has been a cauldron of
environmental, commercial and social tension ever since the opening
of the first unit, a nuclear power station, here in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to rebuild its reputation, British Nuclear on
Tuesday announced a leadership shake-up, promised an overhaul of
safety procedures and said it had embarked on measures to prevent a
recurrence of the falsification of documents. It also said it would
streamline Sellafield's management to introduce greater
accountability and to unify myriad safety and management practices.
Government inspectors said they would watch the company closely to
make sure it followed through.
</P>
<P>
   The falsification of documents, by some accounts to cut corners,
was only the opening chapter in a chronicle of woes that has
hammered the company's standing in much of Europe, Japan and the
United States, and it is fighting to hold on to an estimated $9
billion worth of contracts to dismantle and clean up nuclear sites.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the crisis has started a debate about just what business
the company should be in _ reprocessing spent fuel for use in power
plants, or disposing of nuclear waste and cleaning up nuclear
sites, a business that some analysts say has huge potential,
without the controversies associated with reprocessing. There is no
easy answer. If the reprocessing unit is closed, there will be no
raw materials to produce mixed oxide fuel, leaving the Sellafield
complex with little but its nuclear waste storage operations and an
aging nuclear power station. That would cost thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company and the British government remain formally
committed to reprocessing, Hugh Collum, chairman of the company,
hinted that change might be inevitable. ``We must be in a position
to consider the unthinkable,'' he told a parliamentary panel in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the debate has spread across Europe to the whole
business of selling mixed-oxide fuels, which are more expensive
than uranium but which enable plant operators to re-use spent fuel
without buying new uranium. Germany, which also says it received
shipments from Sellafield with falsified documents, has raised
concerns about ``irregularities'' in reprocessed fuel, known as
MOX, from France.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the wave of mistrust, the environmental group Greenpeace
said recently that MOX from Belgium, France and Britain ``cannot be
guaranteed safe to use.'' And in southern England, a group of
dignitaries from the Channel Island of Jersey plan to travel to
France to press for the end of reprocessing at a government-owned
plant at La Hague on the French coast that is Sellafield's main
rival in MOX production. In the United States, reprocessing has
been banned since the administration of Jimmy Carter, and British
Nuclear's only other competitor is in Belgium. Germany, Switzerland
and Sweden have suspended shipments of spent fuel that was to be
reprocessed at Sellafield. Japan wants the company to take back the
fuel it shipped there.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is surprising considering the catalog of problems
at Sellafield. After the falsification debacle, a routine inquiry
by government inspectors discovered ``systematic management
failures.'' Those conclusions were published in February. In
mid-March, the company acknowledged that a saboteur had severed six
cables on a robotic arm in a nuclear waste disposal unit. At the
end of March, Ireland and Denmark revived a long-running campaign
against the company's environmental record on radioactive pollution
of the atmosphere and of the Irish Sea, demanding the closing of
the six-year-old, $2.88 billion Thorp plant _ the spent-fuel
reprocessing part of the Sellafield complex.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the British government has postponed a plan to
sell off 49 percent of the company, raising further questions about
the opaque financial underpinnings of the reprocessing business.
</P>
<P>
   And in this region, caught by history and geography between a
long-gone industrial past and an uncertain nuclear future, between
the slate-gray wash of the Irish Sea and the soaring majesty of
England's Lake District, the fate of Sellafield's 10,000 jobs has
become the single greatest topic of debate in pubs and stores and
cafes and homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's business around here is a spin-off from
Sellafield,'' said Elvina Quayle, 53, who sells cut flowers and
groceries from a modest store in Egremont, an old market town just
north of Sellafield, and whose husband, Alan, has worked at the
Sellafield complex for 38 years. ``Sellafield has bought luxury for
everybody in this area,'' she said. ``If it's forced to close,
it'll kill off the region.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Indeed, said Irene Banks, 43, who serves tea and sandwiches at
the Apple Tree cafe in Egremont, ``we are just in denial here,
trying to pretend none of this is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After a partial tour of the complex, though, it seemed clear
that the troubles stemmed from a blend of high-level, long-range
management decisions and low morale among some of the same workers
whose livelihood depends not just on the way the complex functions
but also on the way customers and critics see its record.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, critics point out, Sellafield's ultramodern $480
million MOX unit was commissioned and built before the government
gave approvals for it to handle uranium or plutonium. John Barbour,
a British Nuclear spokesman, said that was because ``there's no
mechanism'' to win the approvals before a plant is built. Yet the
company took orders to deliver MOX that it was producing at a far
less sophisticated demonstration unit that can turn out eight tons
of MOX a year and began operating in 1994. The new plant,
reflecting an assessment of likely demand, has a 100-ton annual
capacity, but even with an array of computerized controls it has
yet to start operating.
</P>
<P>
   A Sellafield spokesman, Nigel Monckton, projected profits of
$480 million over the plant's life span. He did not say what the
life span was expected to be, but other reports have put it at 20
years. It was in the older, smaller plant, where data are punched
manually into computer terminals along the production route, that
the falsification took place. Workers called up a spreadsheet
accompanying an old order, Storer said, and simply punched in a new
batch number.
</P>
<P>
   The incident raised questions about the ties between workers and
overseers. ``Clearly there was commercial pressure'' to meet
customers' demands, said John Cane, a union representative. But
``that plant was never designed to be a commercial facility,'' he
said, despite the company's insistence that the older plant had
been designed with some commercial use in mind.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the customer, Kansai Electric Power, had demanded
an additional check on the fuel pellets being produced. Normally,
Storer said, clients were satisfied with three checking procedures.
The fourth involved a random manual sampling of the diameters of 5
percent of the pellets, a crucial measure because the pellets must
fit precisely into a fuel cell's long, slender tubes.
</P>
<P>
   The workers who were supposed to undertake those checks, Cane
said, ``had difficulty understanding the relevance of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior managers, too, acknowledge problems relating to the
demonstration unit, where work has been suspended since September.
``It was a prototype, but it was designed to produce a certain
amount,'' said Jeremy Rycroft, a British Nuclear executive.
``Things weren't designed as ergonomically as at the new plant. It
was a small-scale facility. But things should have been right.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the more recent case of sabotage, Cane said, the
suspects in the severing of robotic cables seem to have borne
grievances against the company over issues like a new pension and
work contract negotiated with the union. A report by Britain's
nuclear installations inspections agency found fault with
Sellafield's entire ``safety culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear reprocessing, which takes spent fuel from reactors and
turns it into reusable uranium and much smaller amounts of
plutonium, is a long-range business. When the Thorp plant opened in
1994, it boasted some $19 billion in contracts for the first 10
years of its life. In the deep, iridescent indoor ponds _ lined
with stainless steel _ huge, silvery casks of highly radioactive
spent fuel glimmer from far below the surface for as long as five
years until radiation levels begin to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Monckton said, the ponds contain some 2,800 tons of spent
fuel, a backlog that, at the current reprocessing rate, would take
three years to clear. But of course, if reprocessing was halted,
the raw materials for MOX production, uranium and plutonium, would
also come to an end. And MOX production was projected to earn $80
million in its first 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the company pretends that the crisis will be resolved
easily, permitting new contracts to be struck, particularly in
Japan, a key market that gave the complex a third of its initial
reprocessing orders in 1994. ``New business is an issue,'' said
Rycroft, the commercial director of the Thorp reprocessing
division. ``We won't win new business until we solve the issue of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics insist, however, that the issue is not simply confidence
but safety and overall strategy. Many have seized on Sellafield's
vulnerability to pursue long-running campaigns against emissions
levels from the plant's many nuclear processes, even though the
company says the emissions have fallen radically since the
mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is mass hysteria,'' said Robin Simpson, a local Labor
politician who also works at Sellafield. ``Everyone is jumping on
the anti-Sellafield bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   The reprocessing plant draws particular ire from environmental
campaigners because it produces its own highly radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want Sellafield closed,'' said Jill Perry, the local
representative of Friends of the Earth. ``But where we see its
future is in cleaning up nuclear waste, and that's where its
expertise should be focused.'' Indeed, she argued that halting the
reprocessing business that accounts for roughly half of
Sellafield's jobs could help the regional economy. ``No responsible
employer would open a factory or any other kind of business because
of the radioactivity in this area. So stopping reprocessing might
actually bring jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
