<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-RENO-BOS &LR;      04-19 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-RENO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION ON BOY PUTS PRESSURE ON RENO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I know where I'm going,'' Attorney General Janet
Reno said Wednesday morning, before a US appeals court appeared to
make the course she has chosen _ to reunite Elian Gonzalez with his
father, Juan Miguel _ that much harder to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department had banked on the appeals court
clearing Reno's path for removing the Cuban boy from the home of
his Miami relatives. Instead, in ruling that Elian can't
immediately leave the country, the judges in Atlanta seemed to
undermine Reno, the champion of the father's rights, and suggest
there may be merit to the Miami relatives' claim on the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court order does not preclude me from placing Elian in his
father's care while he is in the United States,'' Reno said late
Wednesday afternoon in Oklahoma City. ``We are going to consider
all our options, and take the course of action we deem appropriate,
under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   What will Reno do? Not even her aides know exactly where the
attorney general is heading or how she will accomplish her goal.
All along, the Gonzalez case has been her special cause. ``She
signs off on every detail. Nothing is too small for her,'' a
Justice Department spokeswoman said. ``She is up to her eyeballs in
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Reno is likely to face a fresh round of criticism for
allowing the situation to smolder for so long that the Miamians and
their lawyers have won a new day in court. And she likely will be
chided for acting more like a social worker than attorney general
as she patiently, personally tried to mediate the custody case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the criticism of me is that I'm trying to avoid violence,
if the criticism of me is that I am trying to avoid that little boy
being hurt or being snatched in a way that can scar him further, I
plead guilty,'' Reno said. ``But at the same time...I am going to
enforce the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, coincidentally, was the seventh anniversary of the
debacle at the Branch Davidian compound at Waco. Reno, under
pressure from the FBI and informed that children were being abused,
ordered a tank and tear-gas assault that left some 80 adults and
children dead in its fiery aftermath. The horror haunts Reno as she
ponders another rescue that involves child welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the American public is getting impatient with the
standoff over the six-year-old, and the White House has let Reno
know it is weary of watching the street scenes from Little Havana
on CNN. But Wednesday Reno defended her handling of Elian's case,
calling it ``unusual'' and noting it had none of the urgency of
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Waco, you had people who had killed federal officers, and
who had injured others,'' Reno said. ``You had people who had not
only defied the law but killed people in the process. There's a lot
of difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure should not be the issue; what's right should be the
issue,'' Reno added. ``Every day that goes by in which Elian is not
reunited with his father and this matter is not brought to a
conclusion, can be disruptive. No child should be in that kind of
never-never land for that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's compassion for children has not changed in the last seven
years, colleagues say. What the public is also seeing, aides say,
is a battle-scarred attorney general, trained in crisis management,
absorbed with doing the right thing, and tugged by her deep roots
in the Miami community.
</P>
<P>
   Her personal approach has tested Reno's authority and
credibility. She has comforted Elian's grandmothers, reassured
Elian's father, and taken the advice of Cuban-American entertainer
Gloria Estefan, who urged Reno to fly down and meet with the Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The session last week was exhausting and a failure. According to
aides on hand, Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, lectured the
attorney general. Marisleysis, his daughter, wouldn't stop crying.
Elian kept running in and out of the room, and at one point bit the
arm of one of the psychologists present. Afterward, Reno held a
midnight news conference, said she would press on, and spent
another 30 minutes shaking hands and thanking Justice Department
staffers for their hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Krikorian, executive director of the private Center of
Immigration Studies and a frequent critic of White House policies,
says by letting deadlines slip for releasing the boy, the
government has probably emboldened the Miami relatives to make more
demands. But he gives Reno high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expected the administration would have caved in by
now,'' Krikorian said. ``I don't know why they are sticking to
their guns, but it could be Janet Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's approval ratings soared after Waco because people liked
her ``buck-stops-here'' bluntness. But her indepedence has annoyed
some of the president's top aides and kept her out of the inner
circle, even though she is the longest-serving attorney general
since the Eisenhower administration. Republicans on Capitol Hill
have demanded her resignation for failing to appoint an independent
counsel to investigate Democratic fund-raising in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But no other case has stirred Reno quite like this one. She grew
up in Miami, where he father was a longtime police reporter, and
she served as the elected state's attorney in Dade County for 15
years. Friends say she understands the psychology, passions, and
patriotism of the people of Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno knows and respects that community, and to see it
perceived as a banana republic, and to hear people say, `What do
you expect from crazy Cubans,' must be very painful to her,'' said
Mary Coombs, a law professor at the University of Miami. ``She's
always assumed she would come back to where her roots are, and now
there may be people who don't want her here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno got her job as attorney general because two other women
named first were disqualified for child-care tax evasion. It's
ironic that Reno, who has called herself ``an awkward old maid,''
is the administration's premiere parent advocate in a high-profile
custody struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Friends aren't surprised. As state's attorney, Reno stressed
that discipline starts with parents, and she made social work a
pre-eminent part of law enforcement. She earned the nickname ``Root
Cause Reno'' because she convened special grand juries to deal with
juvenile problems, including child abuse, and constantly was
probing family dysfunction for clues to criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Janet McAliley, a former member of the Dade County School Board
and a lifelong friend, remembers when Reno investigated the
corporal punishment case of a kindergartner and found that both
state law and local school boards permitted it. Alarmed, she
prodded officials until the law was changed and spanking rights
were banned in Dade county schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all Reno, caring enough about one little boy to get the
law changed,'' McAliley said. ``I think about her concern for this
child, Elian, and it is consistent with what she has tried to do
with so many, many other children.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno Wednesday refused to reply to a letter from Dr. Irwin
Redlener, a pediatrician-consultant, who advised the Justice
Department to remove Elian at once from what he called a
psychologically abusive home. But she said was disturbed by the
video, released by the Miami relatives, of Elian denouncing his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me very sad,'' Reno said softly. ``I have been
concerned that the boy has been separated from his father in a most
difficult situation, where it appears that he is not able to lead a
normal life, get sleep, go to school,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a wonderful little boy, by all accounts,'' the attorney
general told reporters. ``He has been under the most stressful
conditions, beginning with floating in the ocean. It is so
important that all of us turn off the TV lights, stop writing on
your papers, and start thinking about a little boy and getting his
life to some permanent resolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
