<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-FLAG2-BOS &LR;      04-19 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-FLAG2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SAYS PRINCIPLE DEMANDED HE CORRECT FLAG STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Two months after he lost a key primary in this
state, his candidacy a fading memory to most here, Senator John
McCain apologized Wednesday for betraying what he called the single
most important principle of his bid for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkably self-critical speech, Senator John McCain said
he had not spoken his true feelings during the campaign when asked
his personal view of the Confederate battle flag flying over the
state house here. He did not tell reporters at the time that he
believes Confederate soldiers ``fought on the wrong side of
American history'' and that the flag should be taken down.
</P>
<P>
   He said he considered those omissions ``unprincipled,'' and that
he fully deserves the criticism that he expects to rain down upon
him because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The lapse has so eaten away at the senator, aides said, that he
journeyed all the way back to South Carolina, for the first time
since his drubbing in the Feb. 19 primary, to make his act of
contrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared that if I answered honestly, I could not win in the
South Carolina primary. So, I chose to compromise my principles. I
broke my promise to always tell the truth,'' he told members of the
South Carolina Policy Council here.
</P>
<P>
   While some of McCain's supporters here saw McCain's mea culpa as
a testament to his character and integrity, others were incensed by
what they saw as a betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He abused, misled, and lied to the people of South Carolina in
order to accomplish a political goal,'' said state legislator Jake
Knotts, who was a member of McCain's steering committee. ``I'm
ashamed of the fact that I took him at his word, and took him
around this state, portraying him as the new horizon in politics,
and then he betrayed the people just like he did.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's rejoinder? Knotts, he said, ``has every right to feel
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign in South Carolina, McCain tried to avoid
being drawn into the acrimonious dispute over the Confederate flag.
At various times, he said he understood each side of the debate,
that conservative voters might see the flag as a symbol of
heritage, and that minority residents would see it as a symbol of
racism and slavery, but that he thought the matter best left to the
people of South Carolina to decide.
</P>
<P>
   He often cited the fact that his own ancestors had fought as
Confederate soldiers, and that their service was honorable and
should be recognized. Wednesday, however, he said his view of his
forbears was more complicated than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe their service, however distinguished, needs to
be commemorated in a way that offends, that deeply hurts, people
whose ancestors were once denied their freedom by my ancestors,''
he said. ``They fought to sever the union of our great nation, a
cause that would have terribly harmed America, perhaps irreparably,
and, for a time at least, perpetuated the grave injustice of
slavery. . . . That, my friends, is how I personally feel about the
Confederate battle flag. That is the honest answer I never gave to
a fair question.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain added that he thought the flag should be removed from the
capitol, but that he also was encouraged the state seemed to be
resolving the situation for itself. Last week, the state senate
voted to take the flag down from statehouse dome, and to move it to
a nearby Confederate soldiers' monument. The NAACP, which began an
economic boycott of the state at the height of the controversy,
opposes the relocation, arguing the new location will make the flag
even more prominent than it is now. Black and conservative
legislators in the House of Representatives say they may also
oppose the relocation, though for opposing reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's apology was extraordinary by modern political
standards, but not out of character for McCain. The senator has
taken many a trip to the public confessional. He has apologized
repeatedly for his role in the Keating Five influence-peddling
scandal, for example, and for allowing the South Carolina contest
to degenerate to a level which disillusioned a young Spartanburg
boy. Throughout the campaign, he often said the cynicism young
people feel about national politics ``shames me.''
</P>
<P>
   But even by McCain's standards, this was a spectacular act of
contrition. He did not seek forgiveness, he said. His only
objective was confession, and he expected to be punished. He even
started the recriminations himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be criticized by all sides for my late act of
contrition,'' he said. ``I accept it, all of it. I deserve it.
Honesty is easy after the fact, when my own interests are no longer
involved. I don't seek absolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He added his hope that, ``in the end, my character is judged by
the totality of my life, and not by its flaws alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quinn, one of McCain's South Carolina advisers and a
founder of the conservative Southern Partisan magazine, said he
thought McCain had been far too hard on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he said (during the campaign) was factual,'' Quinn
said. ``When he was asked `How do you feel personally?' he held
back. I think he was harsh on himself to say that was dishonest. He
was just not forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been easy for him to just stay out of it, but he
came back, so I have a lot of respect for him,'' said Vince Ellis,
a Republican candidate for Congress who is African American. But
Ellis conceded it would sent an even more powerful message if
McCain had risked such complete honesty during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have made it easier for minorities to be comfortable
with this party if he had done that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knotts was less forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd lie on the campaign trail, then he's no better than
Bill Clinton,'' the legislator said. ``He'd lie in Washington or in
the White House.'' Still, he said, he would probably have supported
McCain even if he'd known his true views on the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sinclair, one of several men who waved huge Confederate
flags outside the meeting, as motorists in pick-ups honked and
hollered their support for the stars and bars, said McCain's
comments were ``a disgrace. If he is running for office he needs to
be honest up front and tell people what he believes, and if he
doesn't have convictions, he doesn't need to be in public office.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, who defeated McCain for the
nomination, has stuck to his view that the flag controversy is a
state matter, even in the face of McCain's reversal. The campaign
of Vice President and apparent Democratic nominee Al Gore Wednesday
tried to capitalize on McCain's speech by calling upon Bush to
clearly state his honest personal opinion on the flag.
</P>
<P>
   McCain vehemently denied that his mea culpa had anything to do
with his erstwhile rival, or was meant to put pressure on Bush, who
has been trying of late to regain the trust of more moderate
voters. Several of McCain's former supporters have argued Bush can
capture moderate voters by inviting McCain to be his running mate,
and Bush recently said he had not ruled the Arizona Senator out.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has long been trying to head off the vice presidential
speculation. Asked whether he would consider becoming Bush's
nominee for Vice President, McCain gave an unambiguous reply
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no interest in being Vice President. I believe I can
serve the country better in the US Senate,'' he said. ``I do not
seek and do not want to be considered for Vice President of the
United States. I would categorically state to Governor Bush...that
I do not wish to be asked.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are due to meet to try to patch up the wounds of the
primary campaign in Pittsburgh on May 9th. An aide to McCain said
he thought the senator would be unlikely to endorse the governor at
that meeting, though a subsequent endorsement is probable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
