   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-COURT (Miami) _ An Atlanta appeals court rules that Elian
Gonzalez, the Cuban boy found adrift off the Florida coast, must
stay in the country until all appeals are settled. By PATTY REINERT
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-ANNIVERSARY (Oklahoma City)_ Five years after the most
deadly terrorist attack in the United States, a bronze and stone
memorial is unveiled at the site of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal
Building where 168 people died in a bomb blast. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-MISSING (San Antonio) _ Gary Karr, the only person
charged thus far in connection with the disappearance of atheist
Madalyn Murray O'Hair, will go on trial May 15 in Austin, Texas.
Karr, who has been behind bars for the past year, is charged with
five federal counts, including kidnapping and robbing the O'Hair
family. By JOHN MacCORMACK./
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ With a federal appeals court
ruling keeping Elian Gonzalez in the United States, the question
turns to whether a 6-year-old boy can apply for political asylum
against the wishes of his father. (1stld-writethru.) By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court considers the
future of Miranda warnings given by police, the phrase made famous
on television when the suspect is told, ``You have the right to
remain silent.'' By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ A year after two teenagers at the
Columbine High School near Denver shot and killed 12 students, one
teacher and then themselves, most Americans believe that parents _
not school officials _ bear responsibility for preventing future
campus tragedies. That finding is reported in a new survey by the
Pew Research Center for the People and the Press. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-MOM-MARCH (Washington) _ Washington, D.C. officials
voice support for the so-called ``Million Mom March'' planned for
May 14 on behalf of gun control legislation. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Thirty-eight years ago, when John
F. Kennedy was president, the symbol of U. S.-Cuban relations was
an array of Soviet-made missiles capable of firing deadly nuclear
warheads into our country. Now the symbol a six-year-old boy named
Elian Gonzalez, whose custody has triggered a bitter dispute
between Cuban Americans in Miami and the residents of Fidel
Castro's island domain. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
