u a BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-19 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY LEADERS SAY SUIT POSSIBLE OVER SHOOTING OF POLICEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ The day after authorities said a state grand
jury would not indict two police officers in the shooting death of
a black off-duty patrolman, community activists made it clear: that
result is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Following a tense afternoon meeting with Mayor Vincent A.
Cianci, members of the Rhode Island Ministerial Alliance said
Wednesday that they may file a federal civil lawsuit against the
Providence Police Department and the two officers, if the family of
slain Sgt. Cornel Young Jr. assents.
</P>
<P>
   Those same leaders later met behind closed doors with US Rep.
Patrick J. Kennedy in Pawtucket and asked him to spur on a federal
review of the Jan. 28 shooting and the grand jury's results. And
they spoke by telephone with Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder,
Janet Reno's top aide at the US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the grand jury findings, there still has not been
closure,'' Kennedy said at a press conference after the meeting.
``Questions are still out there. We need to find out how we get to
the bottom of this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said he, Cornel Young Sr. and a Ministerial
Alliance delegation are planning a trip to Washington soon for a
meeting with Holder and Bill Lan Lee, who operates the Justice
Department's civil rights divison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to support anyone who can come forward to find out
what happened to my son that night,'' the elder Young said at the
press conference. ``I want no stone left unturned.''
</P>
<P>
   US Rep. John Lewis, a Democrat from Georgia, and U.S. Rep. John
Conyers, a Democrat from Michigan _ both veterans of the civil
rights movement _ will be in Providence next month to discuss the
shootings with the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no faith in the system,'' said the Rev. Marlowe V.N.
Washington, a member of the alliance. ``We have an out-of-control
police department that is not accountable to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday if Cornel Young Sr. _ a Providence
Police major and the department's highest-ranking black officer _
and his ex-wife, Leisa, plan to allow the Alliance to move forward
with the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Since their son was killed, Young's parents have repeatedly
urged the federal governement for an independent investigation into
the late-night shooting outside Fidas Restaurant, a 24-hour diner
in South Providence.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who had stopped for a sandwich around midnight, charged
outside with his weapon drawn to break up an armed confrontation in
the parking lot. Officers Carlos Saraiva and Michael Solitro III,
two of Young's comrades who had been dispatched to the scene,
apparently thought Young was one of the combatants as he held a
suspect, Aldrin Diaz, at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Solitro and Saraiva opened fire when Young did not
obey their commands to drop his weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers were removed from duty pending a grand jury
investigation into the shooting, conducted with evidence collected
by a specially-appointed, nine-member law enforcement task force _
which included six Providence police officers. The grand jury's
conclusions were announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and other community activists spent much of Wednesday
condemning city officials for failing to actively heal the wounds
left by Young's death _ and their dispassionate reactions to the
grand jury's decision not to indict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a great deal of insensitivity,'' Washington
said, referring to Providence Police Chief Urban Prignano Jr.'s
remarks that he would welcome both Saraiva and Solitro back on
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police chief is supposed to be neutral. But he's not being
neutral when he makes these kinds of statements,'' Washington said.
``There's no respect for the dead and the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Washington and five community representatives met with
Cianci at City Hall for about an hour, but reached few conclusions,
participants said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he made it clear that he can not prevent Saraiva
or Solitro from getting their badges back, though he has heard that
Solitro has no plans to rejoin the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting started off a little rocky,'' Cianci said, ``but I
think it turned out to be a good exchange.'' But the community
representatives said Cianci seemed hostile and defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's going to change the grand jury results,'' said
Cianci, in an interview before the meeting. ``We have to move
forward in harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Leisa Young was expected to attend the meeting with the mayor,
but Washington said she changed her mind because ``she's lost
confidence'' in local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Many others here say they, too, are disillusioned by recent
events, but still hope to win justice for Young's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a shock, but it still doesn't lessen the blow,''
said John Osmand, a grassroots activist with the Campaign Against
Wrongful Convictions. ``It's still enraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmand and others say they're glad authorities decided not to
prosecute Diaz, 30, for the murder of Young. Police maintained he
was responsible because his actions ultimately led the officers to
shoot Young, but activists said he was merely a scapegoat for the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Paula Diaz, 59, said she's angry that her son still faces
up to 50 years in prison on charges of assault with a dangerous
weapon and possession of a pistol without a license in connection
with the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who had drawn a gun but dropped it just moments before
Solitro and Saravia opened fire, was sentenced to 12 years in
prison for a weapons-related probation violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are still trying to cover themselves,'' Paula Diaz
said. ``My son is mad because he's sitting in jail and he's never
killed anyone, but the officers who killed Sgt. Young are being
welcomed back on the police department. Now that's just stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
