<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-FATHE     04-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER TRIES TO DEAL WITH STUNNING GRAND JURY DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Police Major Cornel Young Sr., dressed in
faded jeans and a grey sweatshirt, groaned slightly Wednesday as he
hoisted a large photograph of his slain son toward a tiny hook on
his living-room wall.
</P>
<P>
   The balancing act didn't work, and the picture dipped
precariously off-kilter.
</P>
<P>
   Young's life, too, is dramatically askew.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview Wednesday, Young said that, in his
heart, he does not know whether grand jurors made the right
decision when they cleared two police officers who killed his son.
After a stellar 25-year career, he said he is considering turning
in his badge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still confused,'' said Young, the highest-ranking black
officer on the Providence police force. ``I mean, this grand jury
just brings all the sorrow back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the wind's knocked out of you. I'm reliving this all
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Rhode Island grand jury cleared two white officers
who apparently mistook Sergeant Cornel Young Jr., a black man in
civilian clothes, for an armed suspect during a late-night fracas
on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, one day after the judgment, Young's searing loss
was laid bare again during an incessant media blitz. His son, a
three year veteran of the force, was only 29.
</P>
<P>
   Young, whose comments carry great weight among an angered
minority community here, said he ``has to have confidence'' that
the secret grand jury process was fair. But the family's doubts and
questions about what really happened outside a Providence
restaurant that night seemed painfully apparent.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he believes the grand jurors rendered the correct
decision, after reviewing all relevant evidence, Young put his
hands to his head and replied: ``In my heart, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I hope is that the investigation was done thoroughly, with
nothing misrepresented and nothing omitted,'' Young said. ``Being a
police officer, I expect nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   Although still proud of his department, Young said he might turn
in his badge despite pleas from family, friends, and community
leaders that he is needed more than ever on a police force often at
odds with minority residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I go back, or don't I go back,'' asked Young, sighing, his
arms outstretched as if seeking help with an impossible question.
``I've had many letters, saying that if I retire I'm giving up, and
I'm not going to be able to fix this problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, my family, everyone wants me to go back. But I have
to,'' he said, pausing and thinking, ``I have to make up my own
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Young had made up his mind, even before Tuesday's announcement,
that the grand jury would clear officers Carlos A. Saraiva and
Michael Solitro III. ``It's what I expected,'' Young said, adding
that an investigation by a federal or out-of-state agency probably
would have reached the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   That said, however, Young welcomes further inquiry into the
shooting, including an ongoing probe by the Boston office of the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the truth to come out,'' Young said. ``I don't care if
there are 100 agencies involved in the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said that community skepticism about the grand jury, which
examined evidence collected by a nine-member law-enforcement team
that included six Providence officers, could have been addressed by
assigning the case to investigators from outside Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the community's not satisfied. I don't expect them
to be,'' Young said. ``I do hope that everyone can remain calm and
can get through this thing and concentrate on getting something
positive from this tragedy so it doesn't happen to another police
officer, black or white, male or female.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he has not spoken to Saraiva or Solitro, although he
has been approached on their behalf. ``I expect I'll bump into them
at some point,'' he said softly.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Young added, his family needs time _ once again
_ to heal. ``I'm hoping, once the media attention dies down, I can
spend some time with my family, and my son's mother, and come to
some sort of solution, some kind of closure for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Young rose from the chair, walked his visitor to the
door, and returned to the memento-filled living room of his modest
South Providence home.
</P>
<P>
   And there, against a wall, leaned the picture of his son, a
striking man looking confidently at the world from under a
Providence police cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Young said, ``if we'll ever find out what
happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
