u a BC-FELLS-ACRES-AMIRAULT-     04-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-ACRES-AMIRAULT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-DAY-CARE OPERATOR SEEKS RELEASE IN '80S ABUSE CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A team of high-profile attorneys asked Governor Paul
Cellucci Wednesday to free Gerald ``Tooky'' Amirault, the last of
three family members still imprisoned for sexually abusing children
at their day care center in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be a model citizen,'' Amirault, 45, told reporters at a
press conference at Bay State Correctional Institution in Norfolk.
``I never was a criminal before, and I wouldn't be afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Amirault, his mother Violet, and his sister Cheryl
Amirault LeFave _ all of whom were convicted of raping and
assaulting children at Fells Acres Day School in suburban Malden _
was the first of several such cases that sprouted coast-to-coast in
the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But as more and more cases popped up, a national debate on the
reliability of testimony gathered from children ensued, and soon,
defendants in similar cases were being released from prison _
including Amirault's sister and mother.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as Gerald Amirault's case came to symbolize the
problems inherent in taking testimony from young children, he
watched his appeals fail time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, with hope of a judicial remedy all but dead, Amirault
got his most high-profile support yet, as Harvard Law professor
Charles J. Ogletree and noted criminal defense attorney Harvey A.
Silverglate announced they would join his bid for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a press conference at Harvard Law School, the two
attorneys said they was drawn to the case after watching with
disbelief as Amirault's several attempts to have his conviction
overturned were thwarted over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that a grave injustice has been done to a
family, not because of a crime, but because of mass hysteria that
ensued as a result of the horrible allegations,'' Ogletree said, as
members of the legal team and Amirault's family nodded.
</P>
<P>
   In a memorandum to Cellucci, they asked the governor to grant
executive clemency in the case, and commute Amirault's sentence to
time already served _ 14 years _ rather than force him to finish
his 30- to 40-year term.
</P>
<P>
   His sister was freed last fall. Their mother, freed on appeal in
1995, died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he would keep a ``very open mind'' about the
petition, saying he would weigh the evidence and arguments from
both sides before uttering an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure justice is served,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex County District Attorney Martha Coakley, whose
predecessors won the Amirault convictions, said in a statement that
commuting Amirault's sentence would be ``neither appropriate nor in
the interest of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All legal and factual issues relating to this case have been
resolved in the courts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   James L. Sultan, Amirault's lead attorney, accused Coakley's
office of treating his client's case differently than those of his
sister or mother solely because Amirault is male. The cases, he
said, were identical in every way but the gender of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spin is, in these kinds of cases, the women aren't really
that important, but there's a man, an evil man, who's the real
wrongdoer,'' Sultan said.
</P>
<P>
   A parent of one of the children involved in the case said
Wednesday that such claims are preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Amirault) is the only one who testified, so he hung
himself,'' the mother said. ``He got more years not because he was
male or female. He got more time because he was even worse than the
others. They can ask for whatever they want, but they were all
guilty. How many judges and juries have to agree on the same thing
before they finally give up?''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley concurred, saying ``This case must be viewed on its own
facts and aggravated circumstances related to sentencing. A review
of the facts and legal issues demonstrates that the conviction was
sound and the sentencing fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine children who contended they were abused at Fells Acres
between 1981 and 1984 testified against Gerald Amirault, and four
testified against his mother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   The children, ages 3 to 6 years old, said the Amiraults had
sexually assaulted them, used objects to abuse them, and
photographed them in a ``magic room.''
</P>
<P>
   Some said Gerald Amirault dressed as a clown while abusing them,
and one 6-year-old boy said he was bitten by a robot at the school,
tied naked to a tree in front of teachers, and forced to watch
LeFave pull the legs off a squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Amirault's wife, Patricia, and his three children made tearful
pleas to Cellucci to disregard their father's conviction and take a
dispassionate view toward his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister and brother and I have lived our whole lives without
our father,'' said Katie Amirault, a college sophomore. ``He's
missed out on so much. He's missed out on our graduations from
elementary school, high school, and I'm really hoping he won't miss
college. We need him back home where he belongs. He doesn't deserve
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Crowley of The Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 1938EDT &QL; 
