u a BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT &LR;      04-19 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEDERATE SYMBOL IN GEORGIA FLAG DRAWS GROWING OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ark., Fla., Miss., S.C.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The banner that has convulsed South Carolina flies
from a single flagpole. But next door in Georgia _ often regarded
as the template for a New South state _ the symbol of the old
Confederacy flies from a thousand poles as the main element in the
official state flag, and the movement to change it is gathering
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is one of five states that incorporates Confederate
elements into its flag, but it does so more prominently than
anywhere else. The red-and-blue St. Andrew's Cross that was used as
the battle symbol of the Confederacy occupies fully two-thirds of
the Georgia flag, and visitors to the state often mistake it for
the battle flag itself. In 1991, when Clarence Thomas was being
confirmed as a Supreme Court justice, several of his antagonists
remembered seeing the Confederate flag on his desk in the past, but
it turned out to be the flag of his native Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi also displays the diagonal cross in the upper left
corner, or canton, of its flag. Alabama, Arkansas and Florida have
less recognizable symbols of the Confederacy in their flags.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia and Mississippi, there have been several unsuccessful
efforts over the decades to change the flag and remove elements
that are considered by many black residents to be celebrations of
slavery and secession. But the damage inflicted by the NAACP's
boycott of South Carolina _ where the Confederate flag flies under
the state flag atop the Capitol dome _ has heartened flag opponents
elsewhere in the South, who believe they now have the momentum to
bring about a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the old redneck, racist Georgia it was in 1956,
when the all-male, all-white Legislature decided to desecrate the
flag as an act of defiance against the federal government,'' state
Rep. Tyrone Brooks, an Atlanta Democrat, who is black, said of the
Legislature's decision to add the Confederate symbol to the state
flag. ``The climate's different now, in part thanks to South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and other Georgia legislators said they decided not to
push the issue in the legislative session that recently ended,
fearing that a change would have a more difficult time in an
election year. But they will spend the rest of the year building
support for a new flag for next year's session, and hope to have
the support of Gov. Roy Barnes, a Democrat who says there are not
enough votes in the Legislature right now to change the flag. In
1994, Gov. Zell Miller's advocacy of a new flag almost cost him his
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference called
for a tourism boycott of Georgia if lawmakers did not make a change
in next year's session. Legislators say they have already begun
receiving calls from business and tourism lobbyists, urging them to
find their way to a compromise to protect the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, where the flag has borne the Confederate symbol
since 1894, there is even less support for change. On Monday, a
lone black legislator, Rep. Jimmy Thornton of Greenville, began a
procedural protest of the Legislature's refusal to consider a flag
bill, demanding that every bill under consideration be read aloud
and in full. Although this is the prerogative of any legislator,
the full reading has sharply slowed the progress of the House this
week, and has annoyed many of Thornton's colleagues, who tend to
walk out of the chamber when a bill is read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if they walk out,'' Thornton, a Democrat, said.
``They all tell me it's political suicide for a white member of the
Legislature to vote to change the flag, so I have to do this to
shake things up. And we're going to have to have a boycott, to get
the business community on it. It will be hard, but it will get
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the City Council of Jackson, the state capital,
voted to stop displaying the state flag in the council chambers. A
few days later, some legislators began advocating a law that would
cut off financing to cities that did not display the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has refused to fly the state flag on any municipal
buildings since 1990, and some jurisdictions around Georgia have
occasionally flown the previous state flag, which lacks the
Confederate cross. The Legislature added the Confederate symbol in
1956, less than two years after the Brown vs. Board of Education
decision rendered school segregation illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Although some former legislators have said the flag was changed
in preparation for the centennial of the Civil War in 1961, many
historians believe the change was an act of defiance against
federal civil rights legislation. Gov. Marvin Griffin, a Democrat
who signed the new flag into law, was a strong proponent of
segregation, and often said he was elected to prevent ``mixed
schools'' in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by Georgia State University this year said that 56
percent of state residents want to keep the current flag, and
Barnes said in a recent interview that the ``public isn't ready
yet'' for a new flag. He said he wanted to begin a dialogue with
both sides while working on more important priorities, like
education and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Many white legislators from rural areas like the flag the way it
is, but there was a sign of movement recently when a white
Republican state senator, Mike Egan of north Atlanta, introduced a
bill to change the flag. The bill never made it out of committee,
but Egan, who is retiring after this term, believes that most of
his colleagues understand the time has come for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to put it in quietly, so it would pass without Al
Sharpton coming down,'' Egan said. ``It's going to be harder now,
with everybody demanding it. But everyone knows it's going to
happen eventually. Let's do it before the boycott starts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
