</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-STIMULI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY DOWNPLAYS ROLE OF GENES IN STIMULATING BRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young animals with ``rewired'' brains proved able to see using
structures in the brain normally reserved for interpreting sounds,
MIT scientists report.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments showed that areas of the brain designed by
nature to perform one highly specialized task can adapt to doing
another simply by being exposed to different information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a profound discovery that addresses age-old questions
about whether the brain is genetically programmed or shaped by the
environment,'' said Mriganka Sur, professor and head of the
Department of Brain and Cognitive Sciences at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers said the results challenge current thinking by
showing how powerfully information from the environment can
override the effects of genes in shaping the brain as it develops.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, they said this newly revealed ``plasticity''
of the brain might be used to recruit healthy parts of the brain to
take over the tasks of areas damaged by accident or illness.
</P>
<P>
   Sur and his colleagues are authors of two papers about their
discoveries being published in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Sur said he has been working for a decade on
the question of ``how the brain becomes the brain.'' Specifically,
he added, he has asked ``why do certain areas of the brain process
specific tasks,'' such as information for seeing, hearing, and
touching.
</P>
<P>
   In light of all the new discoveries about the importance of
genes in determining now the body operates, Sur said he wanted to
find out whether the brain's specialized areas are innately that
way.
</P>
<P>
   The animals used in the experiments were ferrets, which are born
very early in their development _ at a point comparable to the late
second or early third trimester in humans, Sur said.
</P>
<P>
   In delicate surgery, the scientists rerouted nerves coming from
the back of the ferrets' eyes so that they led to the primary
auditory center, which is reserved for nerve impulses from the
ears.
</P>
<P>
   When they matured, testing showed that the ferrets could respond
to visual information _ juice spouts placed in different positions,
for example _ that was processed by the formerly hearing-oriented
brain structures.
</P>
<P>
   And other experiments showed that the auditory brain structures
had undergone physical changes, so they more closely resembled the
visual centers of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   But how does receiving different nerve impulses create all this
change? That's still being studied, Sur said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to imagine intuitively how sound might have the
properties of vision, and I don't have a good sense of how that
might be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists did the brain rewiring just after the animals
were born. It will take more research to find out how long the
brain is so flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kaas, a professor of psychology at Vanderbilt University who
studies similar questions, said the reports ``are major papers''
that challenge the recent emphasis on the power of genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will push people back toward more consideration of
environmental factors in creating normal brain organization,'' Kaas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Merzenich, a researcher at the University of California
in San Francisco, wrote in an article accompanying the Nature
reports, that the ``fascinating papers'' provide ``some of the most
compelling evidence yet for the exquisite sensitivity of cortical
(higher brain) development to external cues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
