<HEADLINE>
FROM U.S. TO GERMANY AND BACK TO BUILD A MEMORIAL IN OKLAHOMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan, Okla., Ill., Wis., Texas)  (With OKLA-BOMB-ANNIVERSARY)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although they were the unanimous choice of the judges _ who
reviewed 624 designs from 50 states and 23 countries _ the
husband-and-wife team of architects who designed the Oklahoma City
memorial, Torrey and Hans-Ekkehard Butzer, are young and until now
have had little recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Butzer, 33, was born in Nowata, Okla., and spent her childhood
in Wichita, Kan. Butzer, 34, was born in Madison, Wis., to German
parents, and grew up there and in Chicago. The two met as
architecture students at the University of Texas, where they
decided to become business partners before they got married.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after graduation, the pair moved to Germany, where
reunification had sparked a building boom. They settled in Berlin
and founded a firm called Locus Bold Design with Sven Berg, a
German architect. Since then, Butzer has worked on designs for
public housing, hospitals, an auto showroom and other commercial
ventures, while Butzer has focused on design competitions for
museums and civic projects in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   This was their first memorial design, and Butzer has said he
wanted to convey the idea that ``good will prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
