u w BC-CENSUS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-19 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS RESPONSE IS SHORT ON LONG FORMS, LONG ON SHORT FORMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sixty-five percent of American households have
returned their census forms, matching the mail-in rate of 10 years
ago and enhancing prospects for a successful count, relieved
federal officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gratified with the nation's response,'' Commerce
Secretary William M. Daley said in a statement issued after Census
Director Kenneth Prewitt gave an optimistic briefing that
contrasted starkly with one he gave two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious achievement,'' Prewitt said. The latest
results constitute a heartening reversal in ``the trend toward
civic disengagement,'' he added, turning to a phrase he has used
often of late.
</P>
<P>
   He used the same words on April 4, when he lamented that only 55
percent of households had mailed back their census forms, versus
the 61 percent the Census Bureau had hoped for by then.
</P>
<P>
   He said then that he hoped for a flood of mail returns, so that
the mail-response target of 70 percent _ 5 percentage points over
the 1990 response level _ might be reached. He said Wednesday he
hoped late returns might nudge the final mail results closer to 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on April 27, Prewitt said Wednesday, census workers
will try to contact all who did not return their forms ``so that we
can achieve a 100 percent count of our nation's population.''
</P>
<P>
   That ultimate goal may be too optimistic, especially in view of
the 1990 census. It is undisputed that the 1990 census counted
millions of people twice and missed many millions of others
altogether, for an undercount of several million people.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy of the final count has profound implications,
affecting the number of congressional representatives each state is
allotted, the amount of school aid, anti-poverty money and other
social assistance that flows from Washington to local governments,
and where roads, schools and sewers are built.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 count was met with less cooperation from the people
than the one of 1980, and it was recognized as having been less
accurate than the one of 1980 as well. Intent on keeping the 2000
census from being less accurate still, federal officials have tried
to defuse comments from politicians' voicing concerns about privacy
issues, and they have tried to persuade immigrants _ traditionally
suspicious of the federal bureaucracy _ that they have nothing to
lose and much to gain by cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   Returns of the short form are actually running slightly ahead of
the pace of a decade ago, Prewitt said, but returns of the long
form, which is sent to about one in six households, are running
several percentage points behind the 1990 pace.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as in 1990, much of the South has recorded relatively
low returns, under 60 percent in several states, while the Midwest
has seen the best response rate, more than 70 percent in some
states.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the door-to-door visits of households that did
not mail back their returns, Prewitt asked for the public's
cooperation. Census officials have estimated that each percentage
point the mail-return rate goes up means 1.2 million fewer
households that must be visited _ at a cost of up to $35 a
household.
</P>
</TEXT>
