<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-04/20-COX     04-19 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-04/20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURTS EXTENDS BAN ON REMOVING ELIAN FROM U.S.
 &HT;    With CUBA-RENO
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tears flowed and shouts of joy rang out through Cuban
Miami Wednesday after an Atlanta federal appeals court extended a
temporary ban on removing Elian Gonzalez from the United States and
raised serious questions about the federal government's approach to
the controversial case.
</P>
<P>
   But the showdown over the boy is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling does not stop federal officials from taking Elian to
his father as long as the pair stays in this country, and a
confrontation over the boy's immediate future still seemed
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's order does not preclude me from placing Elian in
his father's care,'' said Attorney General Janet Reno, shortly
after the 16-page decision was issued. But the court turned down
Reno's request that it order the Florida family to immediately turn
the boy over to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives broke into tears on hearing news of the
ruling, a family attorney said, and crowds outside their Little
Havana home cheered, hugged, cried and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gonzalez family continues to believe in the laws of the
U.S. and will continue to pray so that all of this may come true
for Elian,'' said Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, who has
cared for the boy since he was rescued at sea last November.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, was at the
Cuban Interests Section when the ruling was announced. He made no
public statement, but his attorney firmly demanded that Reno
reunite him with his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the order issued today undermines this father's
legal and moral claim that he be given immediate custody of his
son,'' said Gregory Craig. ``We call upon the U.S. government to
take immediate action. It is unconscionable to wait one day
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been living at the home of a top Cuban diplomat in
the Washington, D.C. area since arriving in the United States two
weeks ago. He has promised to remain in this country until the
court case is resolved _ if he is reunited with his son.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling seemed to shift the momentum to Elian's Miami
relatives, who have argued for months that the boy shouldn't be
removed without a day in court and that he should have an asylum
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ordered Elian reunited with his father in January, but the
Florida family went to federal court to block the order and request
the asylum hearing. A Miami federal judge upheld Reno's order in
March, and the family immediately appealed to the Atlanta court.
</P>
<P>
   The court is scheduled to hear the full matter on May 11, but
last week issued the temporary ban on Elian's removal from the
United States. Wednesday's order extended the ban until the outcome
of the May 11 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But the court raised pointed questions about the government's
arguments in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to extend the ban on Elian's removal from the U.S. could
``deprive the Plaintiff (Elian) forever of something of great
value: his day in a court of law,'' the three-judge panel ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In their motions, lawyers for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service argued that Elian has no right to an asylum hearing because
his father is the only one who can legally speak for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But the court pointed out _ as have lawyers for the Miami family
_ that U.S. laws plainly spell out that ``any alien who is
physically present in the United States....may apply for asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian ``appears to come within the meaning of 'any alien,''' the
court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The panel went further, citing INS's own regulations that
specifically address how immigration officers should handle cases
involving children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing INS regulations do envision situations where a
minor may act on his own behalf in immigration matters,'' the court
stated. ``Moreover, the regulations contemplate that a minor, under
some circumstances, may seek asylum against the express wishes of
his parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also gave weight to Elian's own desires _ expressed in
a controversial video tape made by his Miami relatives and in court
papers _ to stay in the United States. The judges also echoed a
repeated complaint of the family _ that federal officials have
never examined or interviewed the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that never have(cq) INS officials attempted to
interview Plaintiff about his own wishes,'' the ruling said. ``It
is not clear that the INS, in finding plaintiff's father to be the
only proper representative, considered all of the relevant factors
_ particularly the child's separate and independent interests in
seeking asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded by cautioning that the parties should make
no predictions on how it would ultimately rule, although it said
the Miami family clearly had strong arguments that must be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   The decision seemed a blow to the government.
</P>
<P>
   At a press briefing prior to the ruling, Reno indicated that she
was awaiting the ruling before she would act. Afterwards, she
maintained that she can still reunite Elian with his father, but
now she will have to do so without the Atlanta court's explicit
backing.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what the next step in the long-running drama
might be.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Cuban exiles were happy, but cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day, but it's only a little victory,'' said Rene
Iturrey(cq), 41, a real estate salesman who has taken off several
days from work to come to the house and protest. ``This family has
been able to find refuge in the federal courts. This family
reunification must take place, but you don't accomplish that by
dragging the child out of this home and demonizing this family.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
