<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-420&AMP;     04-19 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT VOWS TO OPPOSE NORMAL TRADE TIES WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-POLITICS) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Democratic leader, Dick Gephardt, said
Wednesday that he would oppose permanent normal trade relations
with China because it would relinquish U.S. leverage over Beijing's
behavior on human rights and religious liberties.
</P>
<P>
   In a passionate rebuttal to many of the Clinton administration's
pro-trade arguments, Gephardt said that giving up Congress' annual
review of China's trade status would be ``a recipe for serious
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America should not trust the Chinese government to make
progress on its own and unilaterally surrender our nation's ability
to influence Chinese policy through trade,'' Gephardt said in a
speech in St. Louis, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's announcement puts him at odds with virtually every
senior Democrat in his party, from President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, the presumptive presidential nominee, to the
Senate Democratic leader, Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   But given Gephardt's strong ties to organized labor, which
opposes the measure, his decision came as no surprise. He has
spoken to Clinton about his views, most recently last week, and
called Gore on Tuesday to explain his decision, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Nichols, Gephardt's spokeswoman, said the call to Gore was
``a simple notification call.'' A spokesman for Gore said the vice
president, who has been calling wavering Democrats in recent days,
had no comment on Gephardt's decision or their conversation. Gore's
Republican presidential rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
supports the measure.
</P>
<P>
   More important for Gore and for congressional Democrats eager to
retake the House this fall, Gephardt has vowed not to let the vote
divide the party in the fall elections. He says he will not make
the China trade vote a litmus test of party loyalty or lobby his
colleagues, leaving that chore to the No. 2 House Democrat, David
E. Bonior of Michigan, who also opposes the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on China's trade status will determine to what degree
the United States benefits from China's expected entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manner in which Dick has conducted himself has really
allowed us to secure a significant number of Democratic votes,''
said Rep. Cal Dooley of California, a top Democratic vote counter
for the measure who Wednesday predicted victory.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial vote is set for the week of May 22. As many as 150
Republicans will likely support the measure, leaving Democrats in
favor scrambling to scrape up the rest needed to reach the 218
votes for passage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   About 40 undecided House Democrats control the measure's fate,
and in interviews Wednesday, many expressed conflicting views on
the significance of Gephardt's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll really affect my decision,'' said Rep.
Diana DeGette, D-Colo. ``I'm trying to weigh what the best decision
is for my district and for the economy of my district.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also tried to play down Gephardt's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Pa., said: ``It helps move me in a
similar direction. Dick Gephardt is widely respected, particularly
on trade matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Gephardt's announcement is significant because the
House is in a two-week recess, and during this last extended time
at home before the vote, uncommitted lawmakers will be the target
of lobbying from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at Webster University to an audience of students
and civic leaders, Gephardt at one point sought to calm a debate
over China trade that he said ``has become overly polarized.''
</P>
<P>
   But then in animated remarks, he assailed arguments for the
deal, which he said put the nation's economic interests ahead of
its equally important commitment to human freedom and liberty
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustainable development and worker rights must be at the core
of our trade policy,'' Gephardt said. ``Otherwise, we have no
assurance that trade will contribute to enhanced living standards
at home and abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the global economy is transforming market
forces, Gephardt said he was neither ``a protectionist, nor am I a
free-trader,'' but rather an advocate for trade accords that
incorporate tougher labor, environmental and human rights
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no debate about whether America should engage China,''
he said. ``The question is how to engage so trade access can be
matched with steady progress toward greater human rights and rule
of law in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gephardt said he tried to broker a measure with the
White House, business and labor groups, and their allies, that
would lock in ``suitable enforcement mechanisms'' for those
standards. But he said he failed.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt suggested maybe that wasn't such a bad outcome. He
challenged the predictions made by the measure's supporters that
broader access to Chinese markets would necessarily pry open a
repressive regime.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders, who had been suspicious of Gephardt's
silence until now on the trade bill, criticized him for being out
of step with new economic realities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gephardt's decision is based not on sound economic
principles,'' said Speaker Dennis Hastert. ``Rather, it is based on
fear, fear of the political power of big labor, fear of the
implications of the new economy, fear of the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
