<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-FARMS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENTATIVE AGREEMENT TO END VIOLENCE TOWARD WHITE FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ President Robert Mugabe, under international
pressure to end violence as he heads into elections that could dent
or even end his party's 20-year dominance of Zimbabwe, on Wednesday
brought together leaders of white farmers and the black former
guerrilla fighters who have led recent raids on white-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   The first meeting between the two sides in the growing
confrontation over land reform yielded a tentative agreement to end
the violence that has claimed the lives of two white farmers since
Friday. But there was no sign of an end to the occupation of
white-owned land by blacks who are disappointed that they are still
landless two decades after their successful war for independence
from Britain, nor was there mention of halting the violence
directed at a new opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe met with Tim Henwood, the president of the Commercial
Farmers' Union, and Chenjerai Hunzvi, president of the War
Veterans' Association. Afterward the three described their meeting
as a first step toward a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've agreed is the hostilities should end,'' Hunzvi told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Henwood said in an interview that, ``We found some common
ground, and we agreed to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The two said they planned further meetings to try to reach an
understanding on the future of land reform _ a crucial issue for
race relations and for Zimbabwe's crumbling economy, since
agriculture is the country's biggest hard-currency earner.
</P>
<P>
   Grappling with political and economic crises and falling
popularity ahead of next month's parliamentary elections, the
government has been accused by critics of using land redistribution
to win votes among poor blacks, thus fanning racial and political
animosities.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, two white farmers have died, and two black
supporters of a new opposition party were killed when when their
car was firebombed, apparently by supporters of the governing
ZANU-PF party. Earlier this month, two other opposition party
figures were killed in yet unexplained circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   With the killings, international pressure has mounted on Mugabe
to take strong action to stop the violence, end the farm
occupations and restore stability.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few days, Mugabe had mixed tentative steps toward
a resolution with belligerent statements that seemed likely to
encourage more confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed satisfaction at Wednesday's meeting. ``It has
created an atmosphere of understanding even though there may not
have been the necessary solution on both sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A halt to violence and intimidation aimed at the new opposition
movement seems less certain.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the trade union leader Morgan Tsvangirai, the movement,
which is less than a year old, is mounting the most serious
challenge ever to Mugabe and his party, ZANU-PF. Opposition members
charge that Mugabe loyalists have countered with intense
intimidation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, the opposition party's
secretary-general said the offensive was pushing otherwise peaceful
citizens closer to striking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting very, very angry, and ultimately we will
not be able to guarantee that they will not resort to self-help,''
Welshman Ncube, the secretary-general, said. ``The only way they
will continue to abide by the law is if they have confidence that
the law will protect them.``
</P>
<P>
   The current climate in rural areas has made fair elections all
but impossible, Ncube said.
</P>
</TEXT>
