<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS STAY THE SAME, LIKE YANKEES BEATING RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many a sad and disturbing story currently stains the jock
kingdom landscape. For an example of what kind of week it's been
thus far, consider these items:
</P>
<P>
   Waco conspiracy kooks and other social misfits gather in Atlanta
to welcome Big Johnny Rocker back to baseball with a rousing
standing ovation. (Told you so, Mr. Commissioner. Your overreaction
made this brainless rock pile a hero to the fringe element.)
</P>
<P>
   Two able-bodied competitors were disqualified for entering and
racing in the wheelchair division of the Boston Marathon. There was
no mention if their cars were also found in handicapped parking
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, hockey fans in Edmonton boo the pregame playing of the
``Star-Spangled Banner''. But as a U.S. citizen who has made many a
hockey-related visit to Edmonton, here's a confession _ I've booed
everything about that gawd-awful place, except for the currency
exchange rate and the sportswriters, who always have entertaining
stuff in the papers.
</P>
<P>
   Old friend Roman Turek whines about ``lucky'' San Jose goals as
the top-seeded Blues struggle in what was considered a gimme
series. It's a long, long way from last season, when Roman simply
watched as Eddie made the playoffs look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban out-Jerrys Jerry by repeatedly yukking it up on the
Reunion Arena P.A. mike before an overflow crowd in the Mavs' home
finale of the NBA season. Here's a suggestion, Mark. Next time,
make it only a very sincere ``thank you'' to the fans, then muzzle
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   And finally:
</P>
<P>
   Yankees torment Rangers at The Ballpark in Arlington. Does this
nightmare ever end?
</P>
<P>
   But the great thing about the jock kingdom, unlike the real
world, is none of the above will impact day-to-day life for the
masses. Actually, a select few have reaped financial reward because
of what happened this week. Local witch doctors and palm readers
saw a jump in business as confused Rangers fans sought an
explanation for the obvious voodoo involved in that
still-mysterious 11th inning on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday afternoon _ a 5-4 New York victory in 10 innings
and a series sweep _ the Yankees have left town, and the Rangers
will not see them again until mid-August, which is way too soon,
but it is four months of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Having played New York five times in eight days gives a totally
distorted picture of where this team is and where it might be later
on. But those are just facts of baseball life for the local lads.
Due to some unfortunate calamities against the pinstripes in the
postseason the past two years, both media and fans have a phobia
about how the Rangers ``measure up'' to the Yankees. It is probably
accurate to also expand that phobia to Tom Hicks, Doug Melvin,
Johnny Oates, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, however, is obvious. At the moment, nothing has
changed. The Rangers still don't measure up. But this is not
exactly a disgrace. For the past two seasons no team in baseball
has been in the Yankees' league, and it remains to be seen if any
of that changes this season.
</P>
<P>
   But control yourself. Do not assume all is lost in April just
because of more domination by the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors have combined to lower this opening month deep into
the negative side, and both factors came in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back blown saves by John Wetteland made it look worse
than it really is. If what has been the most dependable stopper in
baseball converts on Sunday in Cleveland and in the ninth inning
against the Yankees on Monday, the early outlook swings 180
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, left fielder Rusty Greer went out for up to six weeks due
to ankle surgery, further disrupting what was already a batting
order that had been deprogrammed for runs batted in consistency.
Greer's absence makes the lineup appear even more puny, which, by
the way, it now is.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Wetteland. Is there a problem here?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' answered pitching coach Dick Bosman before yesterday's
game. ``Not physically and not mentally. He's fine in both those
areas. Outside of Lee Smith, John is the most resilient closer I've
ever been around, and the one with the shortest memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Closers have to be able to forget bad outings. Forget in a
hurry. If Wetteland bounces back and is his usual self, this will
be a good season for the Rangers. If not, it will be an awful year.
In today's game, a closer makes or breaks a team. The way Bosman
views it _ and he'd better be right _ Wetteland is not a worry.
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said about Greer's absence. The Rangers were
already without Juan Gonzalez, Todd Zeile and Lee Stevens from last
season. That's a subtraction of 87 home runs and 307 RBI. Now,
Greer's 20 home runs and 101 RBI are gone for a month, and the
reworked batting order lacks proper balance and pop, which is why
the Rangers haven't scored more than four runs twice since
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, judge not. Five games in eight days against
the Yankees overloads the brain. Instead, just be thankful those
people are gone. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
