<HEADLINE>
PLASTER CAST MANHOLE COVERS: NOT YOUR AVERAGE LITTLE HOLE ON THE
WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN P. WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Horowitz and Christopher Bailey rolled
into the gas station at the corner of 14th Street and 10th Avenue,
the manager gave them a harried look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir, we need to register the imprint of that manhole cover out
by the pump,'' Horowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That manhole is a new issue, newly manufactured, and we
haven't recorded that model,'' said Horowitz, with the bureaucratic
confidence of a building inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's private property,'' the manager said warily, a bead of
sweat rising on his forehead on this foggy, early spring day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take a record of that design up to the studio,''
Horowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, he and his co-conspirator have roamed the streets
of Manhattan, making plaster casts of more than 70 manhole covers,
which they call urban fossils. Manhole covers seem to have a
strange allure in our culture. They have been lionized in
coffee-table books, rendered on canvas and hung in exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the designer Karim Rashid designed one for New York
in honor of the millennium, and recently the city of Hartford cast
228 of them out of melted-down handguns confiscated by the police.
But the urban fossil collectors were taking their manhole fetish to
a new level.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz led the gas station manager out to an official-looking
white Jeep Cherokee and pulled out two casts he and Bailey had made
earlier on Waverly Place. They were peculiarly beautiful objects,
marked by street trash embedded in the plaster during the casting
process. The manager finally gave in with a wave of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time Bailey is the plaster expert at Horowitz's
restoration and artistic surfaces company, Terra Firma. But he
seems happiest applying his trowel to the filthy New York City
streets. Fortunately, what started as an artistic obsession
recently became a paying job. A Manhattan developer, Capital Real
Estate, is having the two men install a wall inlaid with manhole
covers in the cavernous lobby of an early 20th century factory at
95 Morton Street, soon to be offices. The permanent 14-by-30 foot
wall will extend in an arc across the lobby and through the glass
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw David's manholes, I was amazed,'' said Ilan
Itzhaki, the project manager. ``But I also thought, Am I crazy to
let some artist put manholes in my lobby?''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the three dozen manhole covers that will decorate
the wall are from the 19th and early 20th century, the one at the
gas station was only a few months old and decorated with an almost
pop-art flower design. As if anxious to get the job done before
Itzhaki came to his senses, Bailey spread plaster over the steel
cover. Within minutes the hardening plaster sent wisps of steam
into the 45-degree air.
</P>
<P>
   A homeless man pushing his shopping cart paused to smile but
said nothing. A police car continued up 10th Avenue without
stopping.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Terra Firma studio, above Chelsea Market, Horowitz
and Bailey made negative rubber molds of the plaster casts, and
then bent them to fit a prototype of the wall's elliptical shape.
After casting these curved forms in plaster, the artists sullied
the white finish with detritus they had swept up from the street,
including shattered windshield glass, nails and dirt. One wall of
the studio became a mockup of the final version, which they will
install in the lobby next month, after the construction crews
leave.
</P>
<P>
   The roving pair are already itching to move on. Horowitz said he
had heard there were some interesting fossils in the streets of old
Shanghai. ``Do you think the airlines will let us check some
plaster along with our bags?'' Bailey wanted to know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
