u e BC-MANCHILD-THEATER-REVI     04-19 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANCHILD-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-346-9867.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `MANCHILD IN THE PROMISED LAND:' STRUGGLES IN 1950s NEW YORK  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or (EDITORS: production notes at end of review)  
 By DAVID DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strip ``Manchild in the Promised Land,'' Claude
Brown's acclaimed autobiography of 1950s New York, down to its
heart. There beats a tale of boyhood and manhood, of low life and
high hopes, that could find moving expression as a play.
</P>
<P>
   It works in theory. But in practice, at least in the one-actor
version at the American Place Theater, ``Manchild in the Promised
Land'' is a disappointingly bland, theatrically unimaginative
coming-of-age tale.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's sprawling 1965 book, almost an archetype of American
urban life, tells of Claude's growing up in crime-plagued Harlem
and struggling with race, poverty, sex, family, friendship,
religion and education on his way to a soulful, mature
independence. Focused by its personal narrative voice, ``Manchild''
has an epic reach as it depicts the journeys of a generation of
black families who traded one hard life for another in their move
from the South.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Edward plays Claude and others who populate the landscape
of this ``promised land'' of the urban North. He gives an energetic
performance with a nuanced feel for the rhythms of the book. Among
his characters, the women and drug addicts are particularly
compelling. But perhaps no actor could sustain this adaptation, by
Edward and his director, Wynn Handman. The play faithfully delivers
many units of the book's narrative, but they're not enlivened by a
workable dramatic structure. Edward seems but a storyteller, so
busy squeezing in the text that he can't inhabit his roles with
much depth.
</P>
<P>
   Handman's direction seems loose to a fault. Sometimes Edward
plays both roles in a two-character dialogue; other times he
listens awkwardly to recorded voices delivered with all the flavor
of a rice cake. Sometimes he stalks the stage with a focused,
hip-hop ferocity; other times he wanders around the uninspired set,
a character in search of something to do.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz, the musical movement that helps transform Claude's life,
remains part of this adaptation, but its theatrical opportunities
are reduced to brief recorded snatches and a seldom-used piano.
What a shame.
</P>
<P>
   There are worthy moments in this show, which ends with a sweet
epiphany for the title character: the boy is now a man, and he has
overcome. But without an inventive theatrical substitute for the
book's rich literary texture, this stage ``Manchild'' has not
overcome its unique challenges.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MANCHILD IN THE PROMISED LAND'
</P>
<P>
   Adapted for the stage by Joseph Edward and Wynn Handman from the
autobiography of Claude Brown; directed by Handman; set and
costumes by Beowulf Boritt; lighting by Chad McArver; sound by
David D. Wright; production stage manager, Judith M. Tucker;
production manager, Pamela J. Traynor. Presented by the American
Place Theater, Handman, director; Carl H. Haynes, general manager,
with permission from Michael Skipper, Tom Stovall and Buzz Hirsch.
At 111 W. 46th St., Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Joseph Edward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
