<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILL-HOLLIDAY-GOLDBERG-MOSER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON AD FIRM TO TAKE OVER CALIFORNIA AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos will take over San
Francisco-based Goldberg Moser O'Neil, the advertising firms said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Communications giant Interpublic Group, which owns both firms,
opted to combine them to ``give us a bigger canvas to paint on,''
said Jack Connors, chief executive of Hill Holliday. He will run
the merged firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts us in another big market with all the opportunities
that entails, and it will allow us to go to other, bigger
clients,'' Connors said. ``It makes us a national player.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined firm, GMO/Hill, will have annual billings of about
$1.2 billion and 1,000 employees. Hill Holliday already has offices
in Boston and New York with a large portfolio of financial
services, along with high-tech and health care accounts and plum
accounts like Dunkin' Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   With the San Francisco operations, the firm gains accounts with
fast-growing West Coast companies, including Priceline.com and
Fatbrain.com, an Internet bookstore. The new firm's headquarters
will remain in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic, the second-largest advertising company in the
world, with income last year of $4.6 billion, bought Hill Holiday
in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggested to them early on that they let us take on the San
Francisco office,'' Connors said. ``After having the opportunity to
watch us for a couple years and see what we can do, they decided to
go ahead with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The merged firm will cut some jobs in so-called back-shop
operations such as accounting, most likely in the San Francisco
office, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Goldberg, chairman and chief executive of the San Francisco
agency, will stay on as chairman until the end of the year, when he
plans to retire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
