<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers paint opposing picture of ex-Louisiana governor as case
nears close
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ The criminal corruption case against one of
the nation's most famous and flamboyant politicians is coming to a
close, and soon jurors will ponder: Who is the real Edwin Edwards?
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors describe the 72-year-old, four-term former governor
as a lying, greedy extortionist who forced riverboat casino
operators to pay him for his influence over the licensing process.
</P>
<P>
   His defense attorney portrays him as a legendary public servant
who is being hounded by a federal case built on scant and
inconclusive evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys in a federal court in Baton Rouge this week distilled
nearly four months of testimony into clear, if conflicting,
conclusions. Closing arguments in the sprawling case _ seven men
are on trial for 33 crimes in connection with five proposed
riverboat casinos _ began Tuesday and are scheduled to end today.
After a break for Easter and Passover, the jury will get
instructions from the court and begin deliberations next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Between 1991 and the date of the indictment, a criminal
enterprise operated,'' said U.S. Attorney Jim Letten, one of
several prosecutors to give closing statements. ''These defendants
associated themselves together and participated in the Edwards
enterprise, and each committed at least two crimes. Edwards was the
nucleus; he directed, but stayed in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors reviewed highlights from more than 2,000 hours of
FBI surveillance tapes filmed at Edwards' home and office. In many
of the tapes, Edwards and others talk about cash payments _ money
they say is for legal consulting work, but which the government
says are payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Legitimate consultants don't get paid in secret,'' U.S.
Attorney Michael Magner said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most dramatic were the attacks on Edwards's
character. Magner said Edwards' testimony last week was ''evasive''
and ''smart-alecky.'' He said the former governor's trademark charm
have helped him escape trouble all his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''That builds arrogance,'' he said. ''What we have here is
greed, what we have here is arrogance, what we have here are
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Letten finished the prosecution's case by comparing Edwards to
''the man behind the curtain'' in ''The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the unmasking of a state governor,'' he said. ''He was
a liar, a thief and a phony. Edwards was that man behind the
curtain, but he wasn't a benign wizard, he was a greedy,
self-serving wizard.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense reacted Wednesday by poking holes in the
government's case. Attorney Dan Small said the secretly recorded
tapes are full of ''gossip, innuendo and lies.'' He pointed out
that nowhere on the tapes is Edwards directly talking about payoffs
from casino operators, nor is there any direct evidence that he
coerced licensing board members to vote his way. He also attacked
the casino operators who pleaded guilty and testified for the
prosecution, saying their cries of being victimized by Edwards and
his co-defendants are ''nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Another defense attorney, Sonny Garcia, found himself shouting
in the courtroom Wednesday, saying to convict the defendants based
on testimony from people who made a deal with the government would
be ''outrageous.'' He noted that Eddie de Bartolo Jr., former owner
of the San Francisco 49ers, pleaded guilty and did not get any jail
time. Robert Guidry, a former casino owner, pleaded guilty and got
to keep more than $100 million in what would have been confiscated
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't convict based on someone who had a motive to lie,''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   John Volz, a former U.S. attorney who prosecuted Edwards on
unrelated fraud and racketeering charges in 1986 _Edwards was
acquitted - said if the government doesn't convict him this time,
it never will.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this were anybody else, it would be a foregone conclusion
that they're history,'' he said. ''The unknown is Edwards' impact
on the jury. But in this case, it would be a stretch to believe his
interpretation of the taped conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
