<HEADLINE>
SWANK'S TRIUMPH HIGHLIGHTS `BOYS DON'T CRY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Two dots go over e in Chloe) 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
`BOYS DON'T CRY'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This fact-based independent film richly deserved its Oscar bids,
with Hilary Swank winning as best actress and Chloe Sevigny
nominated as best supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   Swank plays Teena Brandon, a young lesbian who assumed the guise
of a man _ ``Brandon Teena'' _ while looking for love in rural
Nebraska in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With her short hair and gawky amiability, Swank is persuasive in
playing Brandon as an earnest guy who just wants to be one of the
boys and falls for Sevigny's wayward but good-hearted girl.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy for women to portray men convincingly, but Swank
almost pulls it off _ and the ``almost'' is fitting, since her
character isn't male.
</P>
<P>
   Swank and director-writer Kimberly Pierce insist on calling her
``he,'' but Brandon was physically and legally female, and
acknowledging that brings no dishonor.
</P>
<P>
   Her courageous character and Sevigny's wistful one are tenderly
explored, but the film falters in its depictions of Brandon's male
friends (Peter Sarsgaard and Brendan Sexton III).
</P>
<P>
   Their shift from loutish carousers to unthinkably cruel and
homophobic murderers and rapists is impossibly abrupt. If it
weren't so painful, grisly and true, it would seem like a bad
dinner-theater version of ``In Cold Blood.''
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't their story. It's Brandon's, and Swank's
remarkable performance turns this movie into a powerful and
hauntingly memorable experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' also underscores the waste of Hollywood's
customary gloss. It was shot for just $2 million. And by the way,
that's the Dallas area standing in for Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A minus
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MUMFORD'
</P>
<P>
   One of the great unsung gems of late, ``Mumford'' is further
evidence that Lawrence Kasdan is our greatest living director of
ensembles. Take that, Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   The writer-director of ``The Big Chill'' and ``Grand Canyon''
delivers another rewarding human tapestry in this tale of an
idyllic small town where newcomer Mumford (Loren Dean) is wildly
popular as a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to tell him their secrets _ even rival shrinks.
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is, the quietly charismatic Mumford isn't a
psychologist. In an era when attention is torn by cell phones and
Web sites, he's simply a guy who listens.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from threats to his identity, the film isn't driven by
plot so much as it is by feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Its interlocking characters are warm, funny, sad and endearing,
from Hope Davis as Mumford's love interest to Alfre Woodard as a
cafe owner and Jason Lee as a young computer tycoon who loves to
skateboard and wishes he could get a date.
</P>
<P>
   Kasdan's script is brilliant, and, as usual, so is his choice of
music. Bob Seger's ``Till It Shines'' never sounded better than it
does in the context of this meaningful and gloriously humanistic
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $32.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`STUART LITTLE'
</P>
<P>
   What fun. A couple (Geena Davis and Hugh Laurie) ``adopt`` a
parentless mouse (the computer-animated Stuart) as a brother for
their little boy (Jonathan Lipnicki).
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second! Adopt a mouse?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but don't knock it, not when E.B. White's story is set in
an otherworld of retro fashions and critters who speak (though,
strangely, not all of them speak to humans).
</P>
<P>
   Voiced by Michael J. Fox, Stuart has a ``poor little me''
neediness that serves the tale's sentiments but not its sense of
fun. For that we have the disdainful family cat voiced by Nathan
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   When his Snowbell beholds Stuart, he hears dinner bells. When
you behold Snowbell's antics, you'll hear your own laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B plus
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG, Columbia, CC, VHS $24.96, DVD $27.95 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
`HOUSE ON HAUNTED HILL' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The key to this ``House'' is not to confuse it with another
recent horror remake: the bloated effects orgy ``The Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   With its unapologetic exploitation-film bent, ``Hill'' is more
spryly entertaining. It's also a faithful spin on '50s
schlockmaster William Castle's movie about guests invited to spend
a night in a haunted house.
</P>
<P>
   Because of inflation, survivors will get $1 million. In the old
days it was just $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Rush and Famke Janssen play the hateful hosts, and Rush
is in fine, hammy form. He relishes taking Vincent Price's role,
from the pencil-thin mustache to his deceptive, dapper charm.
</P>
<P>
   Taye Diggs and Peter Gallagher are among the guests who stumble
across evil spirits lurking in the ``house,'' which is a towering
former sanitarium where tortures once occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Much mayhem ensues, and the film works well enough in a
slasher-flick mode until surrendering to the same effects nonsense
that burdened ``The Haunting'' from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Look for singer Lisa Loeb in a nice bit as a reporter (``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer's'' camp vamp, James Marsters, plays her
cameraman), as well as Jeffrey Combs of ``Re-Animator fame'' _ or
infamy _ as a ghostly surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Grade: B minus
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
