<SLUG> BC-FBN-DUNGY-HAMILTON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamilton will buck NFL bias
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This all sounds familiar. Faster than you can say
Charlie Ward, those who run the NFL propaganda machine are churning
out garbage about another ACC quarterback after he got at least his
fingerprints on a Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   To hear them tell it, Joe Hamilton is too short, too light, too
something. I mean, who cares that he prospered at 5 feet 10 behind
an offensive line at Georgia Tech that was as thick, tall and
talented as many in the pros?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the pros, Hamilton destroyed a Florida State team
last year that was good enough to rank in the AFC East. He
completed 22 of 25 passes for 387 yards and four touchdowns. Later,
Hamilton threw five touchdowns passes against Clemson and four
against Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered to the many around the NFL who believe
only in the cookie-cutter approach to building a roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there definitely are a lot of similarities between
Charlie and Joe,'' Tampa Bay Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said
Wednesday, recalling a conversation we had six years ago about the
silliness of those who run the machine.
</P>
<P>
   This was back when Ward was picked as college football's top
player after taking Florida State to a national championship. Even
so, those who run the machine said the same things about Ward that
they said about Hamilton, but they also said Ward was too dumb and
too vague.
</P>
<P>
   As for the latter, they said Ward mostly wasn't drafted because
he also was interested in the NBA and wouldn't say he'd definitely
play for an NFL team. You know, just like some guy who left
Stanford, threatened to go to the New York Yankees instead of the
Baltimore Colts and pouted until the Colts used their No. 1 pick in
the draft to ship him elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some guy named Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NFL didn't consider Elway to be a munchkin, he was
given a chance to become rather significant with the Denver
Broncos. If you're a Ward or a Hamilton, you're not given a chance.
Well, not unless a Dungy slips into power.
</P>
<P>
   Dungy couldn't help Ward back then, because Dungy was only the
defensive coordinator for the Minnesota Vikings. As head man of the
Bucs, Dungy gladly chose Hamilton last weekend in the draft's
seventh round after others yawned. In fact, Hamilton will be among
those opening the Bucs' minicamp today for rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll treat Joe like we did (starting quarterback) Shaun King
last year, and that is, we'll have Joe spend his first year
learning our system,'' said Dungy, whose new offensive coordinator,
Les Steckel, likes mobile quarterbacks such as King and Hamilton.
``In Joe's second year, he should be ready to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dungy says it, you can believe it. By drafting Hamilton,
Dungy continued his wonderful habit during his four years in Tampa
of spitting at the NFL's stereotypes. Warrick Dunn. Derrick Brooks.
John Lynch. King. Those are just some of the munchkins that Dungy
hired along the way to taking the Bucs to within a blown
instant-replay call last season of Emerald City.
</P>
<P>
   Just so you know, the Bucs' Emerald City is the Super Bowl.
They'll eventually get there with Hamilton as their latest
munchkin, and those who run the machine will melt on their
broomsticks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
