<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER CITES SALES GAIN, BUT STILL HAS PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ DaimlerChrysler AG reported Wednesday that
sales climbed 17 percent in the last three months, but it paid for
that increase in the form of lower profit margins on both Chrysler
and Mercedes-Benz automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The results indicate that Daimler has yet to overcome the
problem that has bedeviled it since it was formed last year through
the acquisition of Chrysler Corp. by Daimler-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   That problem is the unrelenting price competition in the U.S.
car market, which has forced the major manufacturers to offer
buyers generous discounts, rebates and financing deals.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts expect Daimler's position to improve when it
introduces new Chrysler minivans in the fall, they caution that the
new models will not have an impact on the company's financial
results until the last quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted accordingly, sending Daimler shares down 1.5
percent in Frankfurt, to 67.70 euros, or $63.67. On the New York
Stock Exchange, Daimler fell 75 cents, or 1.2 percent, to $63.875.
In the last 12 months, shares of DaimlerChrysler have slumped 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's annual meeting in Berlin on Wednesday,
executives reported that sales increased to $39.2 billion in the
first quarter of this year, a 17 percent jump from the
corresponding period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Net income in the quarter rose 3 percent to $1.62 billion,
helped by changes in German tax law.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Chrysler soared 24 percent to $18.2 billion, while they
rose 7 percent at Mercedes-Benz and at the Smart division, and 11
percent in Daimler's truck and bus companies.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news was that the company's overall operating profit
slipped by 3 percent, a decline it attributed to ``intense
competition, especially in North America.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler profit margins decreased to 7.1 percent from 9.5
percent, reducing operating profit by 7 percent, to $1.3 billion.
Margins also slipped slightly for Mercedes passenger cars, to 6
percent from 6.3 percent, but the Mercedes operating profit climbed
11 percent as a result of higher volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they have bought their customers by giving them
lower prices,'' said Rolf Woller, an automobile analyst at
Hypovereinsbank in Munich. ``If you look at operating profit, there
was only one segment that had both higher profits and higher
margins, and that was commercial vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Breitsprecher, an industry analyst at Deutsche Bank,
said the Chrysler results were actually worse than they appeared,
because profit had been affected by the rising exchange value of
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar has appreciated 15 percent and more against the euro
since the first quarter of last year, so Chrysler's profit increase
_ given by Daimler in euros _ incorporates that percent currency
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put together the 7 percent decline in profits'' and the
appreciation of the dollar, Breitsprecher said, ``and profits are
actually down about 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's chairman, told the
shareholders meeting Wednesday that the company was poised for
strong growth in both sales and profit. ``The new millennium is off
to a great start for DaimlerChrysler,'' Schrempp said. ``From
today's perspective, we anticipate a further increase in earnings
per share for the full year.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed to DaimlerChrysler's proposed $2.1 billion
investment in Mitsubishi Motors of Japan, which he hopes to
complete by the end of the summer. Under an agreement in principle
reached last month, Daimler would acquire 34 percent of Mitsubishi
and install several executives in the company's top ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp, who received approval Tuesday from Daimler's board to
begin formal negotiations, hopes to repair two of his company's
strategic weaknesses: a presence in Asia and an increased place in
the market for small cars.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mercedes nor Chrysler has much strength in small cars,
which are expected to be the fastest-growing market in years to
come. Daimler's most prominent attempt to build small autos, the
Smart car, remains a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp's biggest problem is DaimlerChrysler's share price,
which has slumped badly since the acquisition in contrast to the
broad market's advance.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp said Tuesday that the company would ask stockholders
for approval to buy back shares. Stock buybacks, illegal in Germany
until a few years ago, have become increasingly popular among some
of the the country's biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp also wants to introduce a stock option program for
DaimlerChrysler executives that is modeled more closely on American
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans have been well received by institutional investors,
but they anger many traditionalists in Germany who view them as a
crass attempt to enrich top executives at the expense of workers
and ordinary shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
