<HEADLINE>
BC, DUKE PLAN TWO-YEAR SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After two weeks of negotiating to find dates suitable
for both schools, the Boston College and Duke men's basketball
programs have reached a tentative agreement on a two-year series,
starting January 2001 in Durham, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles will travel to Duke for a game Tuesday, January 16th,
2001. The Blue Devils will return the visit to Conte Forum the
following season _ most likely in January _ but those particulars
have yet to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for our program to have a quality opponent like that
on the schedule,'' said BC athletic director Gene DeFilippo, who
tried various scenarios before coming up with the January date.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan had been for Duke to come to Boston next
season, but the Devils already had an ambitious non-conference road
schedule, with games at Temple, Stanford, and St. John's. While
Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski wanted the New England exposure so
forward Matt Christensen, who lives in Belmont, could play a game
near home, he also didn't want to tax his team with too many road
games. Thus the flip-flop of home dates.
</P>
<P>
   The other stumbling block was a Big East rule which stipulates
that all non-conference games from mid-January through the
remainder of the season have to be on national television. After
some negotiating, ESPN agreed to pick up the game, although it
could still be on ESPN 2 as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After moving to the head of the pack in the hunt to replace Paul
Hewitt at Siena, BC associate head coach Tim O'Shea apparently has
fallen behind a new candidate. Lafayette head coach Fran O'Hanlon
interviewed for the position Wednesday and, according to sources,
has become the front-runner, although there is a faction on the
search committee that still favors O'Shea.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon has taken Lafayette to the NCAA tournament the last two
years and has been looking for a chance to jump out of the
non-scholarship Patriot League.
</P>
<P>
   While Siena would not be a quantum leap to a major conference
job, it is in a solid mid-major conference _ the Metro Atlantic
Athletic Conference _ and will allow O'Hanlon to recruit
scholarship athletes for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   If all things go as expected, an announcement could come as this
week, although O'Hanlon drove home to Easton, Pa., Wednesday night
without getting a definitive word from Siena officials, with whom
he met all day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Hanlon decides that he does not want the job, sources
familiar with the search process feel that O'Shea would receive the
first call over Syracuse assistant Louis Orr, who also interviewed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
