<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-ARRESTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL YOUTH CHARGED WITH CYBER-ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 15-year-old Montreal youth known online as ``Mafiaboy'' has
been charged with a cyber-attack on CNN's Web site, becoming the
first person arrested after a series of strikes on corporate Web
pages in February.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities said the youth pled not guilty to two
charges of ``mischief to data'' after they raided his home Saturday
and seized at least two computers.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest, made with the help of the Justice Department and the
FBI, came as the two US agencies face pressure to track down those
responsible for the attacks that crippled e-commerce companies like
Yahoo., Amazon.com, and eBay for hours earlier this year, the
biggest intentional online disruptions to date.
</P>
<P>
   Those attacks, which used relatively simple technical methods,
raised concerns about security standards at dot-com operations. In
messages posted in Internet chat groups, authorities said, Mafiaboy
took credit for several of those intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   So far the charges against the Canadian youth related only to
the attack on CNN, leading skeptics to suggest the authorities have
not apprehended a ringleader.
</P>
<P>
   US and Canadian officials said the arrest at least showed
progress in the investigation. The arrest ``demonstrates our
capacity to track down those who would abuse this remarkable
technology and track them down wherever they may be,'' US Attorney
General Janet Reno told reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they may file more charges against the Canadian
suspect or others as they review Mafiaboy's electronic files for
more clues. ``We don't know the specific motivations of Mafiaboy,
but we will try to establish before the courts that he wasn't doing
it just for fun, that he had a criminal intention,'' said Royal
Canadian Mounted Police inspector Yves Roussel at a press
conference in Montreal, Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they couldn't name the youth because of his
age, and didn't know why he chose his online nickname. A Mounted
Police spokesman wouldn't say whether the youth is represented by
an attorney. The youth remains free pending a June 6 hearing in
Montreal juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted the boy could face up to two years in prison on the
``mischief to data'' charges, which were added to Canadian law in
1997. An adult facing similar charges could face as much as ten
years in prison. CNN hasn't specified the cost of damages it
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Mafiaboy concerns attacks he allegedly launched
against server computers maintained by CNN in Atlanta on Feb. 8.
Around 7 p.m. administrators there noticed a flood of signals from
other computers, slowing the site's response time and blocked other
users from accessing it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   By 8:45 p.m. programmers had put filter programs in place and
restored the site's performance, though the attacks continued for
several more hours, said a company spokesman. He said network
adminstrators weren't sure exactly how many users encountered
problems.
</P>
<P>
   A break in the case came the following day when a system
adminstrator at the University of California at Santa Barbara
noticed a computer that was apparently used as a conduit for the
attack, and spoke with CNN and FBI officials.
</P>
<P>
   The administrator, Kevin Schmidt, said in an interview Wednesday
that some of the traffic originated in Canada, but that he had been
asked by the FBI not to discuss exactly where. Schmidt said the
unauthorized traffic didn't seem to relate to the attacks on other
corporate Web sites, however, and that the methods used by the
intruder _ apparently Mafiaboy _ weren't advanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw nothing here that was at all sophisticated,'' Schmidt
said. ``This is like a juvenile putting graffiti on the local high
school.''
</P>
<P>
   According to investigators, Schmidt's tips, computer logs and
other material helped them determine Mafiaboy's residence by Feb.
15. By the end of the month they had also learned his identity. He
was arrested April 15. Citing their ongoing investigation,
officials wouldn't discuss the reasons for the delay in the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   According to a summary of the case prepared by Canadian
officials, the boy was released to his parents Monday afternoon on
condition that he remain at home most of the time and any refrain
from any contact with ``three of his best friends,'' who
authorities also wouldn't identify.
</P>
<P>
   The youth was also prohibited from using a computer except at
school. At school, he ``must be under direct and constant
supervision of a teacher or another supervisor,'' according to the
summary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
