<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-19 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY MUST STAY IN US DURING APPEALS PROCESS, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal appeals court ignited a wildfire of
celebration among Cuban Americans here Wednesday by extending a
legal ban on Elian Gonzalez leaving this country and chiding the
federal government for its handling of the 6-year-old boy's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gonzalez family continues to believe in the laws of the
United States and we will continue to pray so ... he may be able to
remain where his mother wanted him to be, in a country of
freedom,'' Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro, said a few hours after an
announcement of the court's decision set off cheers, screams of
``Liberty,'' and a sense of euphoria in the crowd assembled outside
the elder Gonzalez' home and throughout the Cuban American
community in the Little Havana section of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Janet Reno said the ruling did not preclude
returning the boy to his father in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   While the 11th US Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta did not
provide Elian's relatives with a final victory, and while they
could ultimately lose their fight to prevent his return to Cuba,
Wednesday's ruling markedly improved the family's legal prospects.
In the process, it set the stage for a potentially
precedent-setting change in US immigration procedures and
effectively increased the pressure on Reno to take dramatic action
if she wants to make good on her her vow to reunite Elian with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, a three-judge panel from the 11th Circuit said
everyone seeking asylum, regardless of their age, deserves to be
heard in court. This country's laws don't specify how old an asylum
applicant must be, but in practice, young children are assumed to
be incompetent to make such critical judgments for themselves and
are routinely returned to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this regard, not taking Elian's wishes into account as
his Miami relatives have insisted they should be, that the judges
in Atlanta leveled their harshest criticism at the Immigration and
Naturalization Service's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the record, plaintiff _ although a young child _
has expressed a wish that he not be returned to Cuba,'' they wrote
in their decision, which the government is entitled to appeal. ``It
appears that never have INS officials attempted to interview
plaintiff about his own wishes. It is not clear that the INS, in
finding plaintiff's father to be the only proper representative,
considered all of the relevant factors _ particularly the child's
separate and independent interests in seeking asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   The three judges, who had granted Elian's family a temporary
injunction last Thursday, Wednesday ordered Elian to stay in this
country at least until the full appeals court can hear his case
during the week of May 12. But they pointedly did not grant the
Justice Department's request for an order to immediately turn over
Elian to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did they specify where the boy should live, however, as
long as he does not leave the country. And that apparently
deliberate void in guidance left Reno -- who clearly had hoped for
a favorable ruling to give her legal cover for seizing the boy, if
necessary -- standing unshielded as she now has to decide whether
to order Elian's forcible removal from Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City, where she traveled with a Clinton
administration delegation for ceremonies marking the anniversary of
the worst domestic terrorism in US history, the attorney general
sounded disappointed by the court decision but said she would abide
by it. She also pointed out that the Justice Department and Juan
Gonzalez had already agreed in writing to keep Elian in the United
States while the judicial process unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to ... take the course of action that we deem
appropriate under the circumstances,'' Reno added, hinting that a
federal effort to gain physical custody of Elian may soon be
coming.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Washington earlier in the day, she
offered an even more direct warning of impending action. ``There
may come a time when there is no other alternative,'' she responded
when asked whether she would order Elian's seizure if his Miami
relatives did not relinquish control over him voluntarily. ``But
we've got to do it in a careful, thoughtful way.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Reno mounted not only as a result of the court's
decision in favor of Elian's Miami relatives, but also because of
the response it triggered from the attorney for Juan Gonzalez.
Sounding angry, Greg Craig told reporters in Washington that it
would be ``unconscionable'' for the Justice Department ``to wait
another moment'' before reuniting father and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call on the US government to take immediate action,'' said
Craig, who added that Wednesday's ruling places the responsibility
for quick action ``squarely on the shoulders of the attorney
general.''
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that Elian's well-being had deteriorated and would
continue to do so if he remains in Lazaro Gonzalez' home, Craig
said that if the boy is not removed, the US government ``will bear
responsibility for the harm that continues to be inflicted on Juan
Miguel and his beloved son.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has maintained from the start that
Elian's disposition is an immigration matter that could legally be
decided solely by the INS without any court participation. US
officials have made no secret of the fact that they viewed this
case as so explosive, however, that they preferred to be seen as
doing everything possible to avoid a confrontation with the Cuban
exile community in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, Reno took the extraordinary step of
flying to Miami herself last week to negotiate a resolution that
might be acceptable to all sides. After a late-night meeting at
which she failed to accomplish that, the government stripped the
Miami relatives of legal custody over Elian and ordered Lazaro
Gonzalez to deliver his greatnephew to an airport for transport to
his father -- an order that was very publicly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities subsequently released a letter from a
pediatrician in which he suggested that Elian was suffering such
severe emotional trauma from living in his relatives' home that he
should be ``rescued'' as soon as possible. The authorities also
demeaned the Miami family's claim to the boy, describing them as
``distant'' relatives who had little if any legal standing compared
to a father who had been an active participant in raising his son.
</P>
<P>
   On this count, too, Wednesday's 16-page decision takes the
Justice Department to task and raises questions about future
instances -- say, in cases of child slavery or when girls claim a
fear of ritual genital mutilation if they are returned to their
parents in Africa -- in which children's interests or desires might
clash with a parent's assumed or requested right to repatriation.
</P>
<P>
   The judges in Atlanta said Lazaro Gonzalez does indeed have a
legitimate stake because he is Elian's ``blood relative'' and his
interests ``to say the least, are not obviously hostile to the
plaintiff's interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
