<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-MIDEAST-EASTERCHU     04-19 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MIDEAST-EASTERCHURCH-0421 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAN OVERSEES CATHOLIC RIGHTS TO HOLY SITES
 &HT;    With photos
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (i) international and (l) lifestyle
categories
 &HT;    Optional Trim at 650
 &HT;    Advance for use on or after Friday, April 21
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ He moves among awestruck pilgrims in the Holy Land,
but this priest from Texas has little time or inclination for
starry-eyed devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's preparing for a papal visit, as he did last month,
or for Easter, the Rev. Athanasius Macora(cq) has to stay focused
on the details.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old priest, an American from Austin, is one of a
group of Franciscans who keep a centuries-old watch over Catholic
access to holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Within his jurisdiction are the Church of the Holy Sepulcher,
where Catholics and Orthodox Christians believe Jesus was crucified
and resurrected, and Bethlehem's Basilica of the Nativity, where it
is believed Jesus was born.
</P>
<P>
   The churches have been the subject of legendary quarreling
between the Christian communities who share them _ primarily
Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian Orthodox. Access is allotted
through a ``status quo'' agreement imposed by Ottoman rulers in
1852.
</P>
<P>
   Macora handles day-to-day negotiations on status quo issues for
the Franciscan entity called ``The Custody of the Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   He was assigned the post in late 1998 and notes with some
trepidation that his predecessor held it for 45 years. There's a
lot at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us wants to be the one who drops the ball,'' Macora
says. ``Nobody wants to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Crimean War, a famously bloody European affair
of the mid-1800s, started after Catholics and Greek Orthodox
disputed the placement of a star on the floor of the Basilica of
the Nativity.
</P>
<P>
   So, Macora maintains his polite, just-doing-my-job demeanor even
in a land that inspires others to hyperbole or religious zealotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impressive, but I'm kind of caught up in the nuts and
bolts of it,'' he says. ``For us, it's business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his duties, he reviews alterations to the church, making
sure the other churches don't try to expand their rights and that
Catholics pay for their share of the upkeep, thereby maintaining a
claim to ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he arranged written permission from the Orthodox
churches for the microphones and television wiring that broadcast
the Holy Sepulcher mass of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   After Easter is over, he will take in a few days of prayer and
silence in a monastery. Until then, the onslaught of worshippers
will keep the priest too busy for much prayer of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role is to defend the rights of the Catholic Church,'' he
says. ``That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent walk in the sprawling Church of the Holy Sepulcher,
Macora views hundreds of tourists and pilgrims from Italy, Turkey,
North America and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   They stoop to kiss the anointing stone, where it is believed
Jesus was prepared for entombment. They climb the steep steps to
Calvary, the rocky point of the crucifixion. They line up to get
into the tomb chamber, empty as testimony to Jesus' resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just come down here to make sure everything is OK,'' he
says, wearing the brown robe of his Franciscan order and
maintaining a Joe Friday-candor.
</P>
<P>
   When two Italian women ask him to bless souvenir rosary beads,
he obliges, saying, ``That's what we're here for.''
</P>
<P>
   With prodding, he admits that there is something special about
this work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I am very inspired by the pilgrims,'' he says.
``They come with a lot of faith, and for somebody that's jaded like
me _ you can use that word _ it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Awestruck pilgrims tell him they will renew their faith and
start praying again. Some send him letters of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was ``impressed'' last month when he saw Pope John
Paul II, only the second Catholic pope in history to visit the
church. He won't say if he reacted, as many others, with tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I want to go on the record with that,'' he says.
``You know, big boys don't cry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Macora was born Stephen Macora on an air base in Great Britain.
His father, Stanley, was in the U.S. Air Force. They moved every
three years until going to Austin when Macora was 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There, he went to Crockett High School and then studied botany
at the University of Texas. His father retired from the air force
and still lives in Austin with his wife, Esther.
</P>
<P>
   Macora has four younger siblings, including a sister, Mary
Birozes(cq), in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Raised Roman Catholic, Macora says he considered the priesthood
during college and answered the calling shortly after graduation.
He says he loved UT, but was ``unsatisfied'' by the secular life.
</P>
<P>
   He studied in Jerusalem and spent a year living in the Church of
the Holy Sepulcher, participating in the daily masses that both
celebrate Jesus and help maintain Catholic access there.
</P>
<P>
   After three years at a parish in Damascus, Syria, he was tapped
to return to Jerusalem as the ``delegate for the holy places and
status quo.'' Technically, he represents the region's top
Franciscan official on a committee of Franciscans who oversee the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   In the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, which was built in the 4th
Century and then destroyed and rebuilt repeatedly since, the status
quo outlines who owns every level, alcove and altar.
</P>
<P>
   A Muslim family, seen as neutral by the Christians, keeps the
foot-long iron key to the only door.
</P>
<P>
   In one shared area, the Catholics, Armenians and Greeks
alternate who will clean the area every week. Cleaning is an act of
ownership and, if someone went a few cycles without cleaning,
another church might edge them out.
</P>
<P>
   But, the churches work together more now than ever. Evidence of
that could be seen in the ``excellent'' cooperation that Macora
says he received for the papal mass.
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge is Easter. Thousands of Catholics will come,
followed by thousands of Greek Orthodox, who celebrate Easter a few
days after the western date.
</P>
<P>
   It will bring an ``overlapping of pilgrims'' that Macora calls
``chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he notes, the mix inside the church is a microcosm for
religious relations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only solution,'' he says, ``is to have a wide tolerance
for other peoples' rights.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be reached by e-mail at:
larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
