<HEADER>
A1753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-COMMENT-BOS     04-19 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO PATIENT   TO A FAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ She who hesitates is lost.
</P>
<P>
   The mindboggling ruling by the 11th Circuit Court Wednesday did
more than temporarily block anyone from taking Elian Gonzalez out
of the country. The ruling renders the government's threats to
remove him from the home of his Miami relatives by force far more
difficult to implement.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the three-judge panel came as a surprise even to
advocates of Elian's continued presence in Miami. But far more
surprising was the vehemence with which the court declared that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service had not taken the six
year-old's wishes to stay in the country properly into account. The
government's presumption that a 6-year-old can only be spoken for
by his parent was called into question, as was the Justice
Department's entire strategy in this case.
</P>
<P>
   As is sometimes the case, the judges appear to have been guided
by anything but common sense. The relatives in Miami openly defied
an order to turn over Elian last week. His great-uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez, has declared publicly that he has no intention of
complying with any order to reunite Elian with his father. The
repeated declarations of their legal team that the family will
``obey the law'' have become a mockery. After all that, they win on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Attorney General Janet Reno has no one to blame but
herself. Through deadine upon deadline, threat upon threat, she sat
on her hands. How likely is she to send in US marshals today, after
losing in court? Legally, she held all the cards, but couldn't pull
the trigger. Basically, the protesters stared her down.
</P>
<P>
   Had Reno acted any of the times she threatened to, she wouldn't
appear as she does now _ the chief law enforcement officer
unwilling or unable to enforce the law. Reno has said that she
would prefer not to act in an authoritarian manner, which is
commendable, but she has erred badly in not acting at all.
Meanwhile, Gregory Craig, the lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
pounds her daily for refusing to keep her pledge to reunite father
and son. Some top cop.
</P>
<P>
   Reno put the best spin she could on the ruling Wednesday. She
noted that there was nothing in the ruling that prevents the
Justice Department from taking custody of Elian and delivering him
to Juan Miguel. She didn't say anything about moving to do so,
though _ sparing the world yet another deadline or ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilation filled the streets of Little Havana after the ruling.
A crowd of perhaps 300 (a number easily equaled by the media
throng) cheered wildly. Horns blared. Drivers waved the Cuban flag
from their windows. A group of female Elian supporters, Mothers
Against Oppression, formed a circle in front of the house and
prayed and sang. Even if it proves a minor victory, a temporary
triumph, they saw every reason to savor it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a great victory for the rights of this child
and this community,'' said activist Sylvia Iriondo. ``This says
that this is not just a crazy community. Essentially the court has
ruled that this appeal has merit. The best American values have
been suppported today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Saul Sanchez of the Democracy Movement, a grassroots
anti-Castro group, had predicted eventual defeat just moments
before the court granted its reprieve. More guarded in his
jubilance than other protesters, he still appeared to expect to
lose in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had hope,'' Sanchez said. ``But of course there are
a lot of forces that don't understand what we're fighting
against.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't Reno's fault that a court issued a silly ruling; they
do that all the time. But her dithering has allowed a bad situation
to steadily worsen. The government will likely prevail in the end,
but for Miami the effects of the Elain affair will linger for a
long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is renowned for keeping her own counsel, and maybe she
really does have a plan. Maybe we will all awake some morning soon
to discover that the rule of law has been restored. But right now,
the might and majesty of the US government don't seem to add up to
much around here. Elian's legal team has successfully stalled and
stalled, and there seems to be no end to Janet Reno's patience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
