<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1754 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ALMEIDA-THEATER-2TAKE     04-19 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALMEIDA-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON'S TINY, BUT MIGHTY, ALMEIDA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   Benedict Nightingale is the chief theater critic for The Times of
London.  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As a theater reporter for The Times of London wryly
wrote the other day, ``The Almeida's bid for world domination
progresses apace''; and that seems no great exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the tiny but hungry playhouse is reaching out from
mission control in North London to colonize a bit of East London, a
bit of Central London, eventually a bit of New York, and, if NASA
ever opens up the planetary system to space thespians, one day no
doubt bits of the Moon or Mars or both.
</P>
<P>
   If we discount the much-hyped London debut of Kathleen Turner in
a stage version of ``The Graduate'' _ of which more in a moment _
the Almeida has been gobbling up the London critics' attention in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the premiere of Harold Pinter's ``Celebration''
at the company's grungy headquarters in Islington. Then it
presented Nicholas Wright's new ``Cressida'' in the West End, with
a magnificently dilapidated Sir Michael Gambon as a trainer of the
boy actors who took female roles in early-17th-century England. And
now it has reopened the doors of the East End film studios once
used by Alfred Hitchcock and staged ``Richard II'' with Ralph
Fiennes as the king, a production expected at the Brooklyn Academy
of Music, along with ``Coriolanus,'' in early September.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Almeida has a habit of dispatching major performers across
the Atlantic. Fiennes as Hamlet, Diana Rigg as Euripides' Medea,
Liam Neeson in David Hare's ``Judas Kiss,'' Kevin Spacey in
O'Neill's ``Iceman Cometh'': all have appeared in the company's
productions in New York, the first two of them picking up Tony
Awards for their pains.
</P>
<P>
   But most artistic exporter-importers would not regard ``Richard
II'' as an especially valuable addition to that inventory.
Shakespeare's inept English king is not, after all, as massive a
creative challenge as his emotionally turbulent Danish prince. The
surprise at the Gainsborough Studios, then, is that Fiennes finds
almost more in a lesser role.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a double surprise, since there is something about
that elegant profile that makes you half-expect a reprise of the
graceful, willowy, vocally exquisite Richard with which John
Gielgud established his importance in London 70 years ago. But
barely has Fiennes been ferried onstage in his glistening white
robe and glistening white throne than he's suggesting why almost
all the English nobles will be delighted to see him lose his crown
to the usurping Bolingbroke.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his thin smile either to mock them or to seek
reassurance from his flatterers, and his tongue to flaunt his wit
or, at one bizarre point, to stick out and wiggle at his angry
uncle, John of Gaunt. He is disdainful, petulant, malicious and
smug.
</P>
<P>
   But there are political as well as personal reasons for
dethroning him. Fiennes' king is clearly improvising public policy
as the whim takes him, whether that means taking charge of Irish
wars, banishing dangerously influential men, raising taxes,
anything. He seizes the exiled Bolingbroke's lands while picking
the petals off a flower, and just as casually.
</P>
<P>
   Never have I seen a Richard II who made me so aware of how quick
and quixotic his key decisions are, and I have seldom seen a
production that so lucidly posed a question still alive when
Shakespeare wrote: is there a point when mortals are entitled to
depose God's deputy on earth, the divinely anointed king?
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kent, who directs, brings energy and pace to a play
that can seem a classroom slog, getting good supporting
performances from Linus Roache, a Bolingbroke with the resolution
and the sureness of political touch that Fiennes' Richard lacks,
and Oliver Ford Davies as a Duke of York less torn than dismembered
by his conflicting loyalties. But in ``Richard II'' it's the title
character who matters, and, despite his unsentimental
interpretation and coldly chiseled profile, you couldn't call
Fiennes inhuman or finally unsympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he displays a self-infatuated glee when he steals
Bolingbroke's birthright, and, yes, he thrusts his head forward
like a venomous cobra when he rejects a man he pretends to love.
But adversity brings out more than just self-pitying bluster and
manic mood swings. There is unexpected majesty in Fiennes' outrage
when, high on a balcony, he confronts the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   There is a moving realism in his recognition that ``I live with
bread like you, feel want, taste grief, need friends.'' And there
is a mournful wisdom when, alone in his prison cell, he confesses
that ``I wasted time and now doth time waste me.'' Even arrogant,
unself-knowing despots can grow _ and Fiennes' Richard proves it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cressida'' at the Albery is set in the 1630s, 40 years after
``Richard II'' was first staged and 20 after Wright's real-life
protagonist joined Shakespeare's company, the King's Men, and
became what contemporary records describe as one of its ``principal
actors.'' And John Shank, as he was called, isn't the only
historical character in the play.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone on the cast list existed: a slick operator
called Blagrave, who simultaneously owned one theater and licensed
plays in rival houses; John Honyman, who was one of Shank's most
successful apprentices; an actor called Richard Robinson, who
married the widow of Richard Burbage, the tragedian who first
played Hamlet and Lear. There was also a boy called Stephen
Hammerton, who was described by one witness as ``a most noted and
beautiful woman actor who afterwards acted, with equal grace and
applause, a young lover's part.''
</P>
<P>
   With much of Nicholas Hytner's production occurring in and
around Shakespeare's Globe, the play's milieu will fascinate any
theater buff. The thespians exchange nostalgic anecdotes and bitchy
complaints in the same colloquial style their successors might
adopt now, but they also evoke a seedy, perilous London, where boys
may be kidnapped, traded, starved or used for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Yet plays need effective plots as well as fascinating settings,
and that is where ``Cressida'' falters. Where is the tension
promised by the opening scene, in which Sir Michael's Shank
descends from the flies on a cloud, explaining he has had a
killer-stroke and denouncing Stephen Hammerton as a traitor? There
is also insufficient point, purpose and narrative clarity in the
long flashback that follows.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Michael Legge's earnestly effeminate Stephen
helps save Shank, who has unwisely invested in a rival company,
from financial disaster and debtor's prison. Therefore the
explanation for his dying master's incoherent rage is to be found
elsewhere, presumably in the triumph that the boy enjoyed when he
played the female lead in Shakespeare's ``Troilus and Cressida'' in
a more womanly style than his master thinks proper.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But how can we be sure, when we never see Stephen in
performance? Still, there are compensations for the play's
uncertainties and occasional longueurs, and most of them are called
Gambon. Think of a Jacobean minotaur, big and bovine but mentally
as well as physically agile, who can roar yet wheedle, sneer yet
bring a fierce intensity to his calling _ and you have a
wonderfully commanding, varied performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebration,'' the most recent of the few plays Harold Pinter
has written in the last two decades, comes in a double bill with
his very first, which he wrote in 1957. It is a happy conjunction,
for ``The Room'' sheds a misty, Pinteresque light on almost
everything the dramatist has produced in the last 43 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Duncan's pinched, nervous Rose babbles out banalities to
her grimly impassive husband and to the strangers who intrude on
her small, shabby flat, obscurely threatening both it and her. As
often with Pinter, there is a sense of unease and embattled dread
in ``The Room,'' a sense that nameless horrors may slip like
mustard gas through the cracks into private spaces.
</P>
<P>
   There is poison in the air of ``Celebration,'' too, though its
smell rises more strongly from the text than from Pinter's own
production, which is often and unexpectedly hilarious. At one of
two tables in a chic London restaurant, two mobsterlike brothers
are noisily enjoying themselves with their spouses, themselves two
slatternly sisters. At the other, a genteel husband is apologizing
to his wife for an amour with his secretary, only to be tauntingly
informed by her that she, too, has had plenty of affairs, including
one with the most obnoxious and foul-mouthed of the diners a few
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again Pinter contrasts the surface bonhomie _ ``What a
wonderful restaurant this is!'' _ with the ugly drives below. There
is insecurity, anger, sexual envy, contempt and even hatred behind
the strenuous smiles and the brash bravado.
</P>
<P>
   You get a pretty clear idea of the emotional truth when Keith
Allen, playing the louder brother, boozily declares that he knows
that his friends and family love him, trust him, and wouldn't like
``to see me hung, drawn and quartered,'' or when Steven Pacey as
the unfaithful husband declares that he feels a wonderful sense of
harmony and for once doesn't want to ``kill everyone in sight.'' It
doesn't take a phrase book to Pinterland to decode the menace
behind the rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with ``One for the Road'' in 1983, Pinter has produced
several terse, tough plays that deal openly with torture, political
wrongdoing and the abuse of human rights. ``Celebration'' is,
perhaps, a surreptitious addition to the same files. The coarse,
crude brothers turn out to be ``strategy consultants'' dedicated to
``keeping the peace worldwide.'' The well-bred adulterer is a
banker, keen to do a deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   Only one character, an eccentric waiter who bores customers with
tall tales of a grandfather who met everyone from T.S. Eliot to
Winston Churchill, reminds us that there are or were alternatives
to the society Pinter damns with such sly panache: the consumerist,
philistine, sinister and brutal Britain of A.D. 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How could anyone who saw them forget Dustin Hoffman's solemn
young Benjamin Braddock and Anne Bancroft's infinitely cool
performance as the middle-aged mistress he never calls anything
more intimate than Robinson?
</P>
<P>
   Those with fond or even unfond memories of ``The Graduate'' will
wonder why Terry Johnson has transposed the 1967 film of Charles
Webb's novel to the stage, and may not feel that the production at
the Gielgud, also directed by Johnson, provides a sufficient
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the story of Ben's seduction and his growing attachment
to Robinson's daughter Elaine skims along amusingly enough, thanks
to banks of louvered wooden walls inside of which a bedroom, a
nightclub, even a church can be economically suggested. There are
strange miscalculations, though. Anne Bancroft would never have
lolled on the floor with Katharine Ross' Elaine, like two sorority
girls, and had a boozy rap session about Ben.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the sudden sight of the elegant Bancroft face, twisted
and aged by the discovery that her daughter knows her secret, gave
the movie one of its great, wordless moments. Nor would film buffs
have been impressed by an ending in which Robinson offers Elaine
shrugging permission to elope with Ben in the middle of her wedding
to a boring admirer.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the play follows Webb's novel in stressing that
very 1960s subject, the need to resist overwhelming parents and
oppressive suburbia. That is why Matthew Rhys' Ben is far more the
restless, insecure post-adolescent than Hoffman's prototype, whose
rebellion largely consisted of glum silences.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner, too, exudes svelte contempt for her
surroundings, giving a performance that lacks Bancroft's
vulnerability but is packed with comic assurance.
</P>
<P>
   The British newspapers, I fear, have devoted much space to
salacious descriptions of a moment in which she briefly displays
her voluptuous body to a gibbering Ben; the curt sophistication of
her acting deserves better than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
