<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TACKLE CONSTITUTIONALITY OF `MIRANDA WARNING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday grappled with
whether an obscure federal law blunts the justices' 34-year-old
admonition that police warn those they arrest of their right to
remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   The court, hearing a case from Virginia, considered the
continued vitality of the court's well-known ``Miranda warning,''
which has become a staple of law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The warning, which arose from the court's 1966 decision in
Miranda vs. Arizona, calls for police to tell those they arrest of
their constitutional right to remain silent and that anything they
say can and will be used against them in court.
</P>
<P>
   The legal issue before the justices Wednesday was whether the
Constitution requires police to warn suspects or if Congress can
enact a law, as it did in 1968, allowing officers to forgo the
warning and accept confessions so long as they are given
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The court is expected to render its decision by July.
</P>
<P>
   The justices seemed split on the issue as they considered
whether a suspected bank robber's incriminating statements should
be allowed at trial even though he was not warned of his rights.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and David H. Souter, for example,
said the Miranda warning is constitutionally required because it
ensures that suspects are fully apprised of their Fifth Amendment
privilege against self incrimination before they choose to confess.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing his colleagues, Justice Stephen G. Breyer hailed the
Miranda warning as ``a hallmark of American justice.'' He added
that ``at least 2 billion people around the world know'' of a
criminal suspect's right to remain silent in the United States
because of the fame the warning has garnered through television
shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Antonin Scalia said the Constitution requires no
such police warning and allows confessions to be admitted in court
so long as they were given voluntarily, without any coercion from
officers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case before the justices, the U.S. District Court for
Eastern Virginia refused to admit into evidence suspected bank
robber Charles Dickerson's statement to police that he had driven
the getaway car and stored a gun at his apartment after the January
1997 theft of $876. The court said police had failed to warn
Dickerson of his right to remain silent before he spoke and was
charged with bank robbery, conspiracy and using a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the decision
in February 1999, saying the statements could be used at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit, citing the federal law, said Dickerson knew his
rights and made his statements to the police voluntarily. In
addition, the court said the Miranda warning is not required under
the Constitution but is a guideline police could adopt to ensure
valid confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the justices, Dickerson's attorney, James
Hundley, urged the court to rule that the incriminating statements
should not be admitted at trial because officers had violated the
Constitution by not warning Dickerson of his right to silence.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley of Fairfax, Va., said the Miranda warning serves to
``fully inform'' suspects of their constitutional right and ensures
that those who opt to confess do so in a ``knowing and
intelligent'' manner.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Solicitor General Seth Waxman echoed Hundley in pressing
the Clinton administration's support for the position that Miranda
warnings are constitutionally required.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stability in the law is important,'' Waxman said, adding that
police for the past 34 years have regarded Miranda as a
constitutional mandate.
</P>
<P>
   But Scalia said that the Miranda warning is a ``procedural''
rule that helps guide police in questioning suspects but is not
constitutionally mandated. Congress can enact a law, as it did,
that gives police greater leeway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for the prosecution, attorney Paul Cassell told the
justices that they have often permitted confessions to be admitted
at trial even when police had not warned defendants of their
rights. These confessions could not have been admitted had the
Miranda warnings been constitutionally required, said Cassell, of
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
