<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WEIGHS RIGHTS OF SUSPECTS IN ARGUMENTS OVER MIRANDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Miranda's moment of truth, a richly symbolic test
of whether this landmark of the Warren Court will survive the much
more conservative era of the Rehnquist Court, arrived Wednesday
morning in a crowded Supreme Court with the justices armed for
battle.
</P>
<P>
   For the justices who favor upholding the 34-year-old precedent,
which requires police to inform suspects of their rights to remain
silent and to consult a lawyer, the weapon of choice was Miranda
vs. Arizona itself. They read aloud excerpts that appeared to
anchor the decision directly in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   For the justices who over the years have expressed doubt about
the decision's wisdom or continued viability, the weapons were a
series of subsequent rulings that limited Miranda, suggesting that
its famous warnings were merely ``prophylactic'' rather than
constitutionally required and allowing prosecutors to use
confessions obtained in violation of Miranda for purposes other
than direct evidence against a defendant. A decision is expected by
late June.
</P>
<P>
   As theater, the argument was first-rate. As a predictor of the
outcome of this case, which asks the court to weigh Miranda against
a long-ignored 1968 federal law by which Congress sought to
overrule it, the session was less satisfying. Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy, who are widely perceived as in
positions to cast the swing votes, were obviously deeply interested
in the case but did not tip their hands.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, nothing that happened in the courtroom provided an
answer to the question of whether even those justices who, like
O'Connor, have been critical of Miranda were actually prepared to
bury a ``hallmark of American justice,'' as Justice Stephen G.
Breyer, clearly a Miranda supporter, described the precedent on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth P. Waxman, arguing for the Clinton
administration in support of Miranda, tailored his argument to the
court's inherent institutional preference for standing by its
precedents. ``Stability in the law is important, and it is nowhere
more important than in this case,'' Waxman said. He said that by
giving police and courts clear rules for handling confessions,
Miranda ``has proven workable, and its benefits to the
administration of justice have been repeatedly emphasized by this
court and documented by this court.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman urged the justices to recall the court's ``extremely
unhappy'' experience, during the 30 years that preceded Miranda, of
trying to find a way to test, on a case-by-case basis, whether a
confession was truly voluntary. In three dozen prior cases, he
said, ``the court was simply unable to articulate manageable rules
for the lower courts to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   While retaining ``voluntariness'' as the ultimate test of
whether a confession could be admissible in court, the Supreme
Court in Miranda vs. Arizona announced that a confession by a
suspect in custody would be presumed involuntary unless the suspect
had been informed of his right to remain silent and given ``a
continuous opportunity'' to exercise that right.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, two years later, in Section 3501 of the Omnibus
Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968, an anti-Miranda
majority in Congress provided that the warnings were not necessary
and that federal trial judges instead should ``take into
consideration all the circumstances'' in deciding whether a
confession was voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond
startled the Justice Department and much of the legal world by
ruling that Section 3501 had effectively overruled Miranda for
federal prosecutions. Ruling in the case of an indicted bank
robber, the 4th Circuit applied Section 3501 and found that
incriminating statements by Charles Thomas Dickerson were
admissible. The U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va., had
suppressed the statements on the ground that the police had not
given Dickerson the Miranda warnings before questioning him.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, while still intending the Justice
Department to prosecute Dickerson on bank robbery charges, agreed
with the defendant that Miranda, and not Section 3501, was the
proper test to apply. The administration therefore joined in the
Supreme Court appeal, Dickerson vs. United States, No. 99-5525,
leaving no one to argue before the court in support of the 4th
Circuit's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Such a circumstance is rare but not unknown to the justices, who
when they agreed to hear the appeal appointed a former Supreme
Court law clerk, Paul G. Cassell, a law professor at the University
of Utah, to argue in support of Section 3501. Cassell is perhaps
the best known academic critic of Miranda and, on behalf of the
Washington Legal Foundation, a conservative legal organization
here, had presented the winning argument to the 4th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The central question for the Supreme Court in this case is the
constitutional status of Miranda vs. Arizona. Indisputably, the
court intended in Miranda to safeguard the Fifth Amendment right
against compelled self-incrimination. The question is whether, as a
strategy to accomplish that goal, the essence of the decision is
itself constitutionally compelled, in which case Congress cannot
overturn it simply by passing a law, or whether the court was
adopting one permissible alternative among several.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subtle distinction,'' James W. Hundley, Dickerson's
lawyer, told the justices Wednesday. While the precise language of
the warnings is not itself constitutionally compelled, he said,
``the constitutional requirement of Miranda is that there be
protective procedures in place to fully inform a suspect of his
rights, so that he knows his rights, so that he knows he can
exercise those rights, he knows that his interrogators will honor
those rights, and so that the court will know that any waiver of
those rights was made knowingly and intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Section 3501 was deficient, he said, because it ``simply reverts
the analysis back to the totality-of-circumstances test'' the court
had found ``unworkable and inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassell, however, described Miranda as no more than a
``provisional, interim judgment about how to go about enforcing
Fifth Amendment rights.'' He paraphrased the court's holding in
Miranda as: ``In the absence of appropriate congressional or
legislative action, the following procedures are prerequisites to
the admissibility of confessions.'' Then Cassell added, ``Ah, but
of course we now have appropriate congressional action.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Section 3501 was in fact, and was intended by Congress
to be, an adequate substitute for Miranda, and he suggested at one
point that it offered more expansive protections for criminal
suspects. Justice John Paul Stevens, a Miranda defender, cut him
off. ``You make a wonderful argument on a lot of points,'' Stevens
said, ``but I think it's going to be tough to convince me that 3501
was intended to expand the protection granted by Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   There was much attention paid Wednesday to Chief Justice Earl
Warren's statement at the end of his Miranda opinion that ``the
Constitution does not require any specific code of procedures for
protecting the privilege against self-incrimination during
custodial interrogation.'' The court went on to say there that
``Congress and the states are free to develop their own safeguards
for the privilege'' _ a phrase often used in debates about Miranda
to support the position that the warnings are not constitutionally
required.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, another Miranda supporter,
quoted to Cassell the second half of that phrase: ``so long as they
are fully as effective as those described above in informing
accused persons of their right of silence and in affording a
continuous opportunity to exercise it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've certainly accurately quoted the opinion, Justice
Ginsburg,'' Cassell replied.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that the sentence was ``not at all necessary'' to the
court's decision in Miranda but that in any event, Section 3501 met
the court's test. The law gave ``clear incentives'' to police to
continue administering the equivalent of Miranda warnings as a way
of ensuring that a confession would be voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ```Incentive' is not `required,''' Justice David H. Souter,
another clear Miranda supporter on the court, said to Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly a difference,'' the lawyer replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet,'' Souter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
