<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS HOST TO HEAD PRESS STUDY CENTER AT HARVARD  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alex S. Jones, the host of the PBS television program ``Media
Matters'' and a winner of the Pulitzer Prize as a reporter for The
New York Times, has been named director of the Joan Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The center examines how the news media affect politics and
government.
</P>
<P>
   Jones replaces Marvin Kalb, the former CBS and NBC correspondent
who stepped down last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 53, said he intended to increase the center's attention
to the emergence of the Internet and how it is complicating
politics and public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is the Eugene C. Patterson Professor of the Practice of
Journalism at Duke University, a position he shares with his wife,
Susan E. Tifft.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Tifft wrote ``The Trust: The Private and Powerful
Family Behind The New York Times,'' (Little, Brown, 1999) a
chronicle of the Ochs and Sulzberger family, which has owned The
Times for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   Jones won the Pulitzer Prize in 1987 for his coverage of the
collapse of the Bingham family's newspaper empire in Louisville,
Ky.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1997, he was the host of ``On the Media,'' a
program on National Public Radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     04-19 1060
