<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A TRAINER'S HEARTACHE IN A CLAIMING RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By   GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leah Gyarmati received the bad news moments after the race. She
could live with finishing second _ she is, after all, 10 for 10 in
the money since becoming a trainer _ but having her horse claimed
was enough to rock her backward.
</P>
<P>
   Gyarmati muttered an inelegant word she certainly never heard
when she was earning her master's degree in theology at Samford
University, but might have acquired in her two years as a jockey.
Then she commiserated with her jockey, Diane Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Women are still a distinct minority at the racetrack, but
Gyarmati and Nelson have had a good bit of success since linking up
with the modest partnership called Castle Village Farm. Wednesday
they paid the price in heartache. Adverse went off the favorite,
and before the gates opened, another trainer, Pat Reynolds, had
claimed him for $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word is out _ Leah nurtures a horse,'' said Dr. Larry
Marcus, a surgeon from Hartford, Conn., one of about 40 investors
who have kicked in an average of $1,000 to form Castle Village
Farm, which has no white fences, no barns, no precious acreage in
horse country, just four stalls at Belmont and a new trainer who
happens to be a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Gyarmati loves her four horses but loved Adverse most of all
because she had been an exercise rider back when he was a fractious
youth in Jimmy Jerkens' stable. The horse nearly bit off the finger
of the managing partner, Steve Zorn, and Gyarmati placed a large
red cone in front of Adverse's stall at Belmont to warn people
away, with the pride of a parent who knows her offspring is
difficult but just may grow up to be somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd get loose at Saratoga once a week and snap at people,''
Gyarmati said fondly.
</P>
<P>
   She had trained Adverse only since March 11, when she convinced
her investors that he was worth $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to use the income to strengthen our stable,'' said
Alice Olson, a partner and also director of continuing education at
Sarah Lawrence College. ``If the partnership makes money, we get
paid just enough to settle the taxes. We're happy to pay taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ground rules of the partnership are that the investors want
to have fun, that they will work through the managing partner, that
women have a place in racing, and that everybody listens to the
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Gyarmati had followed Adverse as he was claimed twice and gelded
once. She knew she was taking a chance entering him in a claiming
race because he has traces of Seattle Slew in him, was bred at
George Steinbrenner's Kinsman Farms, and has raced for stakes
higher than the claiming price of $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   She hoped, however, that the horse's reputation for temper would
scare claimers off, but word of her hot hand was getting around,
including several places in Wednesday's Racing Form.
</P>
<P>
   Gyarmati grew up riding show horses, worked nine years for Allen
Jerkens and Mike Hushion, then earned two degrees and was starting
her doctorate in theology at Drew University when she decided to
try riding. After two years and 15 trips to the winner's circle,
Gyarmati was ready for law school, but Steve and Jean Zorn, both
law professors, asked her to train for the new partnership.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered Flippy Diane and No Bad Habits for the group and
Storm Magest for a subgroup called the Snowbirds, and recently
added four other horses. She still exercises her own horses, and
thinks women have a particular touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman may try to find out why,'' Gyarmati said. ``A man
might say, `You're going, whether you like it or not.' There, I
said it.''
</P>
<P>
   For those same reasons, she said, she uses Diane Nelson on her
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's as good as anybody you can get,'' Gyarmati said.
``She's a thinker. I can sit and talk with her. She'll tell me more
than I want to know. She'll take a horse for a walk, trying to
figure out what's best. She also follows instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in the paddock, Gyarmati glanced at Wolf Boy, the No.
6 horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode him 15 times,'' Gyarmati said softly, with obvious
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty investors gathered in the mostly empty owners' box at
Aqueduct, whose official attendance was exactly 3,488. (All the
action these weeks is in Kentucky, where a female trainer, Jeanine
Sahadi, will saddle a Derby favorite, The Deputy.) The Castle
Village Farm folks outcheered a first-place finisher a few weeks
ago, quite unusual behavior at the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be losing money, but now I'm a bit of a shtarker, you
know, a Jewish word for a big shot,'' said Dick Zausner, the owner
of the Port Washington Tennis Academy, who has no experience in
racing but joined a few partnerships for fun. ``I park in the
owners' lot, I get a pass to the paddock.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Adverse took the early lead in the slop while his
owners chanted the familiar track litany: Stay in front! Come on,
Diane! Cut the corner! Uh-oh! Stay away from the rail! Uh-oh! Hang
on, Diane! Lost by a nostril! Wolf Boy, on the outside, had won by
a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always in the money,'' one partner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perfectly happy,'' Alice Olson said. ``They're safe.''
</P>
<P>
   They were safe, but then Sal Sciarra, the clerk of scales, broke
the news that Reynolds had claimed the horse. The partnership had
won $6,500 for finishing second, and had now made a profit of
$40,000 on the claim, but they were out one very impetuous horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' said Nelson, who had lost one of her mounts. ``You
have to enter races like this. But you get attached to a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, Gyarmati approximated a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult,'' she said. ``But you know what? In a race
or two, he'll be back in the claimers again, and I'll have to
persuade my owners to claim him again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's yours if you want him,'' Alice Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a few minutes, as soon as Adverse passed his drug test,
Gyarmati would officially hand him over to the new owners. Then she
would pick up her daughter at school. There was no need to go back
to the barn this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had eight horses,'' Gyarmati said. ``Now I have seven.'' Her
record for 10 races is four firsts, four seconds and two thirds,
for earnings of $178,250. The odds are getting shorter on Castle
Village Farm and Leah Gyarmati.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
