<HEADLINE>
RALLY FIZZLES AS STOCKS DROP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Disappointment with first-quarter reports from IBM
and Intel helped send stocks lower Wednesday, ending the two-day
surge that followed last week's drastic sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline should not have been a surprise. After a two-day
rally that saw the Nasdaq composite index jump 14.2 percent and the
Dow Jones industrial average rise 4.5 percent, a pause was likely.
During the rallies on Monday and Tuesday, even bullish analysts
were cautioning that the market did not move up in a straight line.
Many of the other stocks that fell Wednesday, including Cisco,
Oracle and Microsoft, had rallied Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People needed to catch their breath,'' said Thomas M. Galvin,
chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 87.16 points, or 2.3 percent, to 3,706.41, while
the Dow industrials dropped 92.46 points, or 0.9 percent, to
10,674.96. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was off 14.1
points, or nearly 1 percent, to 1,427.47. All three indexes were up
for the day until around noon.
</P>
<P>
   The once high-flying dot-com stocks that have fallen so sharply
recently were down again Wednesday more than the broader market.
The Street.com index of these stocks dropped 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. also played a big role in
Wednesday's decline. After it announced that for reasons of safety
it was delaying its request for government approval of its Vanlev
blood pressure drug, the stock plunged 14|, or 22.4 percent, to
50|. It was the second biggest drag, after Intel, on the S.&AMP; P.
500.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's stock market decline shows how important
first-quarter earnings reports will be to the outlook for the near
term. At the end of last week, after the Nasdaq had fallen 25.3
percent and the Dow 7.3 percent, strategists cautioned investors
not to panic, in part because they expected strong first-quarter
earnings, especially in the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   But with the mood as fragile as it is, investors may decide to
focus more on whatever bad news they may find in an otherwise good
profit report. Or good earnings just may not be good enough.
Caterpillar reported first-quarter earnings Tuesday of 73 cents a
share, well above analysts' forecast of 58 cents a share.
Wednesday, shares of Caterpillar dropped 2{, to 37|.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Salamone, research director at Schaeffer's Investment
Research in Cincinnati, said, ``We take as a negative sign over the
short-term'' the decline after the IBM and Intel earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, IBM reported that it had beaten profit estimates.
But it also said that its revenue had fallen 5 percent in the first
quarter. And that is what disturbed investors. In after-hours
trading Tuesday, IBM shares dropped 3], to 111{. They fell 10}, or
9.3 percent, Wednesday to 104].
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which also reported its earnings after the market closed
Tuesday, said both profits and revenue rose. But the company said
that revenue growth in the current quarter would just match the
first quarter. Wednesday, shares of Intel dropped 9 15/16, or 7.7
percent, to 119 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a momentum driven market,'' Galvin said,
referring to the fact that many investors have been buying the
stocks just because they think they are hot, without regard to
company performance and profits. ``Revenue is the better indicator
of momentum,'' Galvin added, ``and a revenue slowdown won't be
tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally on Monday and Tuesday, even with Wednesday's setback,
has probably made a lot of investors feel better, especially those
with concentrations of technology stocks. One way to measure how
much better they may feel is to tabulate the overall performance of
stocks compared with last Friday, when both the Dow and the Nasdaq
had their biggest one-day point losses in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
