<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE REPORTS BIG PROFITS AND 2-FOR-1 SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer reported earnings Wednesday that
handily beat analysts' estimates for its second fiscal quarter. In
contrast to the slowing sales for many PC makers, Apple reported
strong demand across its product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting a one-time gain from a stock sale, Apple reported
earnings per share of 88 cents. Analysts had expected 81 cents,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Apple also beat the
so-called whisper number of 87 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company capped the earnings report by announcing a 2-for-1
stock split, to take effect on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Apple reported its results after the market closed. Amid a broad
decline on the Nasdaq, its shares closed at $121.125, down $5.75.
But in after-hours trading, the stock moved as high as $125.5625.
</P>
<P>
   After years of suffering for being outside the ``Wintel'' PC
standard set by Microsoft's Windows operating system and Intel's
microprocessors, Apple is benefiting from its proprietary hardware
and operating system software, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   While several mainstream PC manufacturers reported a slowdown in
the first quarter as corporate customers waited for the release of
Windows 2000, which is geared toward business networks, Apple sales
surged and continued to outpace the growth of the industry as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended April 1, Apple reported earnings of $233
million, or $1.28 per diluted share, compared with $135 million, or
84 cents per share, in the comparable period a year ago. Revenue
for the quarter was $1.94 billion, up 27 percent from $1.53 billion
in the second quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter's results included a $73 million after-tax gain from
the sale of 1.5 million shares of ARM Holdings PLC, which
contributed 40 cents to earnings per diluted share. Without
nonrecurring items, Apple earned $160 million, an increase of 72
percent from the year-ago quarter. Apple still owns 9.4 million
shares in ARM.
</P>
<P>
   Apple sold slightly more than a million computers in the
quarter, 26 percent more than the same quarter last year. Of these,
100,000 were Powerbook laptops, and 350,000 were G4 PowerMacs, the
company's high-end line. Sales of these higher-priced models,
together with lower freight costs and lower memory chip prices,
helped spur gross profit margins to 28.2 percent, up from 26.3
percent in the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt really good about the numbers,'' Steven P. Jobs,
Apple's chief executive, said in a telephone interview. ``We think
there was really good demand for the pro products, and there's
really good demand for the consumer products too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple said 28 percent of the consumer-oriented iMacs sold in the
quarter went to first-time computer buyers, and 17 percent to
buyers converting from Windows-based machines. Although Apple did
not provide similar analysis for its pro models, Jobs said there
was some evidence the company was gaining new users, or regaining
old Macintosh users there as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the creative professional market, Apple has always had a
pretty strong market share, and it is possible people are coming
back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said he thought
Apple gained sales from longtime Macintosh users who had waited
until the company's recovery to buy new machines. ``I suspect
there's a deferred upgrade cycle going on, where people who were a
little doubtful are finally convinced that, OK, now I can buy
myself a new Mac,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has formed a partnership with Earthlink to provide
Internet services, and last quarter said that the relationship
would add an incremental $25 million to $30 million to earnings
this year. ``We're trending toward the high end of that,'' Jobs
said. ``We think we're going to be one of the most profitable
Internet companies this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
