u a BC-MCCAIN-SC-FLAG-480&AMP;AD     04-19 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SC-FLAG-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN ADMITS HE LACKED CANDOR ON CONFEDERATE FLAG ISSUE  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Sen. John McCain apologized Wednesday for not
having called for the removal of the Confederate battle flag from
the South Carolina Statehouse when he campaigned in the state's
Republican presidential primary, saying he had compromised his
principles out of political self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who built his presidential quest on a reputation for
candor and patriotism, said he had equivocated on the flag issue
because he feared that if his true feelings had been known they
would have undermined his effort to wrest the nomination from Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. McCain said in the campaign that the
divisive issues should be left to the state, as had Bush, who stood
by the position Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a subdued speech at a luncheon a stone's throw from the
Capitol where the Confederate battle flag flies, McCain, a former
Navy war hero whose ancestors fought for the South, indicted
himself for a lapse in honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared that if I answered honestly, I could not win the
South Carolina primary,'' McCain said. ``So I chose to compromise
my principles. I broke my promise to always tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain lost the Feb. 19 primary, a defeat that severely hurt his
chance to derail Bush's drive to the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the pivotal primary campaign, McCain repeatedly was asked his
opinion on whether the flag should be removed from atop the Capitol
dome. Many liberal and civil rights organizations, led by the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, have
been pressing to have the flag known as the ``star and bars'' taken
down, declaring that it is a symbol of slavery and oppression of
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In January, McCain said that he considered the flag a ``symbol
of racism and slavery.'' The next day he called it a ``symbol of
heritage,'' a phrase used by supporters of the flag. At all times
he declared that the issue should be left up to the people of South
Carolina to decide without interference from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday McCain said that both of his characterizations of
the flag were accurate, and that he still believed the matter
should be handled by state officials. But, McCain went on to say
that his Confederate forefathers ``fought on the wrong side of
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe their service, however distinguished, needs to
be commemorated in a way that offends, that deeply hurts, people
whose ancestors were once denied their freedom by my ancestors,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's statement Wednesday may place pressure on Bush to
clearly state where he stands. But McCain refused to be drawn in to
a discussion of what his action might mean for his one-time rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an issue that affected my campaign,'' he told
reporters after his speech. ``I don't believe it will affect anyone
else's.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's appearance Wednesday before the South Carolina Policy
Council, a conservative, business-oriented research group, was his
first trip back to the state since his defeat in the primary. In
his absence the issue of the flag has continued to simmer. Last
week, the South Carolina Senate passed a compromise measure that
would remove the battle flag from atop the dome and place a smaller
version in a monument to Confederate soldiers on the Capitol
grounds. That measure is now before the South Carolina House of
Representatives. The outcome there is uncertain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In response to questions, McCain also repeated his insistence
that he would ``categorically state to Governor Bush that I do not
want to be asked'' to be the presumptive Republican nominee's
running mate in the fall. The Texas governor has said he wanted to
discuss this directly with McCain at a meeting scheduled for early
May.
</P>
<P>
   As for flying the battle flag, ``Governor Bush believes on
principle that this is a state issue for the people of South
Carolina to decide, and, as he predicted, they are working to
address,'' said Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a prepared text at the luncheon, McCain
acknowledged that his belated confession would not shield him from
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not intend for this apology to help me evade criticism
for my failure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be criticized by all sides for my late act of
contrition,'' McCain added. ``I accept it, all of it. I deserve it.
Honesty is easy after the fact when my own interests are no longer
involved. I don't seek absolution.''
</P>
<P>
   How McCain's comments will affect the debate here is an open
question. After his speech he was given a standing ovation by most
of the about 60 people at the luncheon. Later, several pressed
forward to shake his hand and say they admired his candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took a lot of courage to come back down here and do
this, to admit a mistake and to admit he may be criticized for the
mistake,'' said Cordell Maddox, a Democratic representative from
Anderson, S.C., who supports the Senate measure. ``What I'm hoping
is that it's going to give some courage to people who are on the
fence about the Senate compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who did not join in the acclaim for McCain was Jake
Knotts, a state Republican representative from Lexington County
outside Columbia who sat in stony silence while others applauded.
Knotts was one of the few Republican legislators who supported
McCain in the primary. He is also a flag supporter who said he had
pressed McCain in the campaign on his true feelings about the
Confederate icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm disappointed in him, very disappointed in him,''
Knotts said to reporters after the speech. ``I'm not only
disappointed, I'm ashamed of him. I'm ashamed that he lied to the
people of South Carolina in order to further his political
career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
