<HEADLINE>
$25.5 MILLION IN GRANTS GO TO TEXAS SCIENTISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas) 
 
By TODD ACKERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Welch Foundation announced Wednesday it has
awarded $25.5 million to scientists doing basic research in
chemistry at 26 Texas institutions, the foundation's biggest outlay
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based organization's funding for 2000 will support
129 existing projects and 53 new ones, which range from the study
of plant chemistry to the reaction of molecules to varying
wavelengths of light. None involve research with an immediate
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``History teaches us that the biggest breakthroughs in science
come from an improved understanding of nature's fundamentals, not
because someone set out to find it or invent it,'' said Richard
J.V. Johnson, chairman of the Welch Foundation. ``Our guiding
objective is the pursuit of knowledge for its own sake _ wherever
the intellectual curiosity of dedicated scientists may lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The funding includes $7.25 million for 52 projects at seven
Houston-area schools, including the University of Houston, Rice,
Baylor College of Medicine, the University of Texas-Houston Health
Science Center, University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center,
University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston and Texas
A&AMP;M-Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The funding reflects a 26 percent growth over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Each grant provides a minimum of $135,000 over three years to
support research by a full-time, tenured or tenure-track faculty
member who serves as principal investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The Welch Foundation was established in 1954 by the estate of
Robert A. Welch, an oil and minerals entrepreneur. In 45 years, it
has awarded more than $411 million to support chemical research. It
also annually bestows the Welch Award in Chemistry, a $300,000
prize that is considered one of the most prestigious chemistry
honors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
