<SLUG> BC-U-57-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLES IN PLOT SINK THIS SUB
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2{ stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the World War II submarine adventure ``U-571,'' everybody
needs a good mechanic. German skipper, American lieutenant
commander, it doesn't matter which side they're on; just give 'em a
guy who knows his way around a diesel, and they can win the war.
</P>
<P>
   The film's own helmer, writer-director Jonathan Mostow
(``Breakdown''), believes in that strategy, too. ``U-571'' is the
most mechanical nail-biter to come down the tube in many months.
It's technically impressive and produces tense, life-and-death
situations with assembly- line efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it seems entirely made by, and often about,
robots.
</P>
<P>
   It's also historically suspect, fundamentally preposterous and
apparently unaware of its own best dramatic possibilities. Other
than that, it's a straight-ahead thrill machine.
</P>
<P>
   Set in early 1942, soon after the United States entered the war,
the film starts out with a ``Das Boot''-worthy U-boat attack and
destroyer counterstrike (much of the movie, which employed
``Boot's'' production designer Gotz Weidner, is unashamedly
influenced by the great German film _ except, of course, that ``Das
Boot'' wasn't hokey). Left bobbing and powerless somewhere in the
mid-Atlantic (for want of a mechanic ... ), U-571 anxiously awaits
a Nazi resupply sub.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Navy has gotten wind of the ship's predicament, and
a Trojan Horse plan is soon put into action. A World War I vintage
U.S. sub is outfitted to look like a U-boat, a couple of
German-speaking Americans are brought on board, and it's sent out
to rendezvous with U-571. The idea is to get a boarding party onto
the drifter and capture its valuable Enigma encoding machine before
the crew catches on _ and before word can get back to Fortress
Europa that the Allies can break Axis communication codes.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that, in real life, the British pulled off
essentially the same maneuver a year earlier, before we were even
in the war.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that things don't go quite according to
plan. Matthew McConaughey's second-in-command, Andrew Tyler, finds
himself in charge of a skeleton crew on the damaged U-boat when its
own ride home is unexpectedly torpedoed.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite ready for captaincy yet, Tyler has one ace up his
sleeve _ a good mechanic! U-571 is soon outmaneuvering and
outfighting shipshape German subs and destroyers, surviving plunges
to depths that should crush it like an accordion and, in general,
winning the war.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is viscerally exciting, as far as it goes. But
without any real idea of who these brave young men are, we're not
exactly wrapped up in their dire fates. McConaughey plays Tyler
with close-cropped hair, sockeyed self-doubt and nary a one of his
movie star smiles. You mainly notice the haircut, and his
interchangeable, expendable crew of co-stars _ Bill Paxton, Harvey
Keitel, Jon Bon Jovi and a bunch of kids who can't be told apart _
have even fewer distinguishing characteristics. When one of them
dies, you have no real clue who's missing.
</P>
<P>
   A stranger casualty, though, is ``U-571's'' most intriguing
premise. These American sailors are dressed like Germans on a
U-boat. Only two of them speak the language, and one of them is an
African-American, played by T.K. Carter. Now wouldn't some close
encounters with unknowingly ``friendly'' Nazi boarders have been
deliciously nerve-wracking (not to mention opportunities for some
of the faceless cast members to stand out as individuals?). And how
about trying to convince Allied planes and ships, whom the
imposters certainly couldn't fight against, not to attack them on
sight?
</P>
<P>
   Such possibilities remain missing in action, however, their
space taken up by more and bigger explosions. Their absence doesn't
exactly sink ``U- 571.'' But they could have plugged some serious
narrative leaks, as any decent script mechanic could tell you. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``U-571'' (PG-13; violence, language). &QL; 
The stars: Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Harvey Keitel, Jon Bon
Jovi, Jake Weber, T.C. Carson, Jack Noseworthy. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Jonathan Mostow. Written by Mostow,
Sam Montgomery and David Ayer. Produced by Dino and Martha De
Laurentiis. Released by Universal Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 17 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
