<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1776 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-McCONAUGHEY-SIDEBAR-L     04-19 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCONAUGHEY-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RETROSPECT, YOU GOTTA LAUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use with U-571 review and feature) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't as heroic as commanding a battered submarine under
constant attack. In fact, it was downright embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew McConaughey is bravely trying to laugh off his
arrest last October, in which police responding to a noise
complaint entered the actor's Austin, Texas, home after observing
him through a window playing bongos in the nude.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference in making a joke out of something and
having a sense of humor about it,'' the tall, 30-year-old Texan
notes. ``It happened and I got a sense of humor about it, man. It
made it easier coming out of jail the first time, going, `You know
what, Matthew? I can't figure out anything wrong you did. It's all
right. You've done it before and you'll do it again. If everyone
can't see the absurdity of this then I don't want to know them
anyway.' I just want to keep it simple. I think everyone kind of
agrees it's just ... silly.''
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey was cuffed for telling the officers to get out of
his house and charged with drug paraphernalia possession and
resisting transportation. The drug charge was dropped almost
immediately and the resisting one a few weeks later, when
McConaughey agreed to pay a $50 fine for the noise violation.
</P>
<P>
   But as absurd as the whole situation obviously was, the actor
can't help but feel a little violated himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, how did we get from a class-C noise infraction
into jail cuffed?'' he asks rhetorically. ``Even the judge _ and I
think everybody, when they stop and think about it after the humor
_ has to go, 'Wait a minute? They came in your house?' No, that's
not right, that's not how anything needs to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against the blue and I don't want anyone to be against
them, man,'' he says. ``We need law and order. But there was a
place where this one person got out of line.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1778 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CRACKER-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      04-19 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRACKER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKER-JACK SOUND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past 10 years, it sometimes felt as if Cracker might
be the last honest-to-goodness rock band on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Unapologetically sticking to verse-chorus-verse songs in the
traditional guitars-and-drums format, the group embodied the
classic-rock gold standard at a time when pop became increasingly
fragmented and unfocused.
</P>
<P>
   Led by ex-Camper Van Beethoven singer-guitarist David Lowery and
guitarist-singer Johnny Hickman, Cracker travels a relatively
mainstream path and scored radio hits with the tuneful ``Low'' and
``Euro-Trash Girl'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years and four albums, Cracker's just-issued ``Garage
D'Or'' (Virgin) is a collection of radio hits, new studio tracks,
soundtrack-only offerings and oddities. The disc represents a
decade in the life of one of the few '90s bands to have impacted
die-hard rock fans and their alternative-leaning cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put it together in an odd sort of way,'' Lowery explained
from his home in Richmond, Va. ``First, we polled our fans through
e-mail and made a list of about a dozen songs they wanted. We
weren't exactly looking for our greatest hits. It was more like
what songs you'd use to introduce somebody to Cracker. It turned
out entirely different from what I would have imagined. Our friends
say it's the definitive Cracker.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Cracker's chemistry is the partnership between Lowery
and Hickman, longtime friends who moved from Santa Cruz to Virginia
at the start of the '90s to launch their new band.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the crudest terms, I sing something and he plays something
and it's like a foil to what I do,'' Lowery, 39, said. ``There's
always a dialogue going on between us. He comes from a more
down-and-dirty, rootsy-folky side than me ... an earthier side of
things. My songs can seem kind of spacy until he starts putting
parts on them.''
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the regular-issue release of the 16-track
``Garage D'Or,'' a bonus disc of oddities and live tracks is
available on a limited- edition basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an odd sense of humor,'' Lowery said of his often
ironic lyrics. ``I like the way people speak as opposed to how they
write. I like the way written English is entirely different from
spoken English. Sometimes when I write a song, I'll take something
I've overheard and take a phrase and it will imply a character and
then I'll let the character speak. There's this one dominant
narrative style in rock _ 'what I did on my sixth-grade vacation' _
but if you look at rap or country, those forms of music play with
the narrative voice. I look for absurdity, sarcasm and irony. It
doesn't seem that weird to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cracker, augmented by extra musicians, plays about 100 shows a
year, including a recent, packed date at the House of Blues. And
while the band has a high profile in Europe, Lowery feels the group
should focus on more familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I should spend my royalties to go play for
the French,'' the good-natured singer joked.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Lowery owns what he calls ``the only professional
recording studio in town.'' Richmond, he adds, has a busy
college-oriented music scene that spawned local hero Dave Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town gets no press because there's not a particular sound,
so you never hear about it like you did with Seattle,'' he said.
``There's a lot of neat stuff going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the band's mid-'90s radio success, Lowery is pleased
Cracker has held onto a loyal cult audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 16 years in the business, I've learned to be quite jaded
in my own twisted way,'' he said. ``The radio stations have these
annual festivals full of one-hit wonder bands, yet we get offered
to play them, too. And I always say, `You played one song by us in
10 years.' But they pay us, and we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That one song was ``Low,'' recorded for Cracker's sophomore
``Kerosene Hat'' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember feeling really strongly about that song,'' Lowery
said. ``I was talking to Johnny in the studio, and I said once we
get a really good take of `Low,' we would be 50 percent done with
the record. We had the music for a while, and I remember playing
around with it at sound check on our first tour. When we began
performing it in concert, I noticed people really liked it. It's
rare that you play a new song and people really react to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Cracker's other really popular song, ``Euro-Trash Girl,''
which began life as a word-of-mouth hit _ since it wasn't listed on
the ``Kerosene Hat'' album credits _ Lowery says it still draws
people to the band's shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not listing the song made it more important in a weird way,
although that wasn't our intention,'' he said. ``We knew we should
include it, but the label thought the record was getting too long.
So I told our producer to put it on the album but not to list it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It intrigued people because it was kind of a hidden thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
