r s BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     04-19 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKY HAS LIVED QUITE A LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He grew up near the corner of Vermont and 35th near the Memorial
Coliseum, and he remembers riding the Red Cars and attending fights
at the Olympic Auditorium and watching movies at the Orpheum and
United Artists on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers serving as a batboy for Gene Mauch's baseball team
at Fremont High and gathering with young pals behind the Shrine
Auditorium where differences would be settled with fists.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers going out to 42nd and Avalon where Wrigley Field
was located and where the Los Angeles Angels of the Pacific Coast
League would play their home games.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers going out to Fairfax and Beverly where Gilmore
Field was located and where the Hollywood Stars of the PCL would
play their home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, what days!'' he says nostalgically. Great days. Memorable
days. Wonderful days. Little did I know one day I'd play in the
PCL.''
</P>
<P>
   George ``Sparky'' Anderson would do more than play professional
baseball, including being employed as a second baseman for the
Angels in their final PCL season in 1957 a year before the arrival
of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1953 graduate of Dorsey High would go on to become one of
the legendary managers of the sport during his nine seasons with
the Cincinnati Reds and his 17 with the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   His Cincinnati teams were known as the Big Red Machine, and they
were among the most fearsome in baseball history with names like
Pete Rose, Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan, Tony Perez, Ken Griffey, Dave
Concepcion, George Foster and others dotting the roster.
</P>
<P>
   His Detroit teams also were formidable with people like Kirk
Gibson and Alan Trammell and Lou Whitaker and Lance Parrish,
although the ones near the end of his career struggled.
</P>
<P>
   But Sparky Anderson was more than just an extraordinary field
commander. Like another old school baseball graduate, Tom Lasorda,
Anderson became a much-quoted goodwill ambassador for a game he so
passionately liked and became a popular fixture among the media,
players and fans.
</P>
<P>
   And, on July 23rd at Cooperstown, N.Y., Sparky Anderson will be
awarded for his achievements that included two World Series titles
with the Reds and one with the Tigers by being inducted into the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate honor for anyone who is involved with
baseball,'' says Anderson, who also will be honored Saturday night
at the Great Sports Legends Awards banquet for the Paralysis
Project of America at the Ritz-Carlton in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Sparky Anderson is now 66, and still lives in Thousand
Oaks---he's lived there the past 34 years with wife Carol---and
still offers candid opinions on varying subjects just as he did
when he was overseeing the Reds or Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson thinks it's a terrible injustice that the most prolific
batsman in all the seasons of baseball, Pete Rose---he wound up
with 4,256 hits---doesn't already have his plaque hanging in the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can show me a piece of paper that proves that Pete was
gambling on baseball when he was a player, then I might look at it
differently,'' he says. ``He should be voted in for what he did as
a player, and, believe me, he was hardest-playing player I ever
had, with Kirk Gibson second. Pete showed up to play every day,
never took it easy, played hard all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has faults. Sure, Pete might have his, but I have
mine. No one is perfect. Before a season would start, I'd always
gather up my players and say, `Gentlemen, we have some talent on
this team. If you can tolerate me, I can tolerate you. And you all
have to tolerate each other.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Crimneysakes, Pete Rose isn't Jack the Ripper. No one ever has
said he altered the outcome of a game. We shouldn't be so
judgmental of other people. Pete should be given another chance. He
ain't like me, but that doesn't make him worse or better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson still thinks his Big Red Machine teams were the
strongest he's seen, but he has fond admiration for the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see how the Yankees do for the next five years
before I put them ahead of our Red teams,'' he says. ``The Yankees
might have a little better pitching than we did, but I don't think
anyone had a better starting lineup. But you have to give a lot of
credit to the job Joe Torre and Don Zimmer have done with the
Yankees. All their players know how to play the game properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had staggering success as a manager---his 1975 Red team
went 108-52---and also great frustration---his 1989 Tiger team went
59-103--- and never took himself seriously, one of his alluring
charms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the players who do it for you, but you have to get them
to the watering trough,'' he says. ``You just have to let them
play. I'll never forget Charlie Dressen (one-time Brooklyn Dodger
manager) saying to me, `I'll tell you anything you want to know
about managing, but, please, ask me the day after the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of managers. One who has bad players,
loses games, and gets fired. Then there's the Einstein. One who has
good players, leaves them alone, lets them win, and stays around a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparky Anderson was only 35 when he was hired to manage the Reds
in the winter of 1969, and he was 60 when he departed the scene
with the Tigers in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just realized that I had had my time in the sun, and it was
someone else's turn,'' he says. Sure, there are times I miss the
wars and the players. But I don't miss all the politics upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't off somewhere giving speeches to corporate groups
and fraternal organizations, Anderson maintains a regular routine
in Thousand Oaks, walking an hour each morning before playing golf
at nearby Sunset Hills.
</P>
<P>
   He weighs a trim 155, 10 pounds less than when he managed.
</P>
<P>
   He says Roberto Clemente was the best player he ever saw, but
admits he didn't see Willie Mays and Hank Aaron in their primes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never seen a player who could do as many things on a
ball field as Joe Morgan,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a lot of others in athletics who depart high profile
positions, he doesn't attempt to remain in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see him renewing acquaintances at Dodger Stadium or
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I was doing broadcasting with the Angels, I never
went down on the field,'' he says. I don't want my presence to be a
distraction. I had my time on the baseball fields. Now it's time
for others to enjoy the experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
