u a BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-2TAK     04-19 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-2TAKES(930)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA TRIAL DISSECTS IMAGE OF FORMER GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
  By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Desperate to procure Louisiana's final
riverboat gambling license in 1997, Edward DeBartolo Jr. had
already delivered $400,000 in cash to his father's old friend,
Edwin Edwards, the former governor of Louisiana. He had fended off
suggestions that he grant consulting contracts worth millions more
to Edwards and his eldest son, Stephen. And then, according to
court testimony, even after DeBartolo's partnership won its state
casino license, he received another proposal, this time for a
$10,000-a-month attorney's retainer for Stephen Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, the former owner of the San Francisco 49ers, could
not have been more exasperated. ``They don't quit,'' he complained
to his closest associate, Ed Muransky, according to Muransky's
testimony in Edwards' racketeering trial here.
</P>
<P>
   Distilled into three syllables, that is the essence of the case
that federal prosecutors have laid bare against Edwards, who some
consider to be Louisiana's official state rogue, in a captivating
four-month trial that will go to the jury next week. In testimony
about five separate casino licensing extortion schemes, the
prosecution has portrayed the 72-year-old Edwards as relentlessly,
reflexively, almost pathologically corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you grow up with an insatiable greed for things, for
material things,'' said Michael W. Magner, an assistant U.S.
attorney, who compared Edwards to a compulsive cookie thief during
closing arguments on Tuesday. ``The key word is insatiable. It's
never satisfied. The more you have, the more you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, of course, has been so thoroughly investigated over the
years that many Louisianans said in interviews that this trial had
barely altered their perception of him. But the casino case has
clearly provided the richest portrait ever presented of Edwards'
unconventional blending of politics and business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his two trials in the 1980s, one of which ended in a
mistrial and the other in an acquittal, in this case, Edwards has
had to contend with hundreds of hours of audiotapes produced by
clandestine wiretaps. Prosecutors also had the benefit of extensive
testimony from DeBartolo and two other former business associates
who turned state's evidence against Edwards as part of their plea
bargains with the government. Each testified that they made payoffs
either to Edwards or to other defendants who they assumed were
paying a share to Edwards in exchange for his help in winning
riverboat gambling licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his son, Stephen, and five other defendants that
prosecutors characterized as the former governor's cronies and bag
men, Edwards is charged in a 33-count indictment with heading a
moblike enterprise that conspired to extort millions of dollars
from businessmen seeking riverboat licenses. The shakedowns took
place both during Edwards' final term and after he left office in
1996, when he still exerted tremendous influence over legislators
and gaming commission members, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo may have provided the most damaging testimony, telling
jurors that Edwards wrote ``$400,000'' on a scrap of paper and
pushed it across a restaurant table as the men discussed
DeBartolo's pursuit of a Louisiana casino license. Edwards
maintained that the money was a legitimate consulting fee and that
DeBartolo insisted on paying in cash to hide his association with
Edwards from his business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Another businessman, Robert Guidry, a wealthy tugboat operator
who was seeking a licensing hearing for a casino he hoped to open,
testified that he made $1.5 million in payoffs to the Edwardses,
sometimes leaving stacks of $100 bills in paper bags deposited in
garbage bins. Guidry testified that the deal was negotiated in 1994
by one of Edwards' gubernatorial aides, Andrew Martin, and was
sealed in a face-to-face meeting with the governor in a hotel
conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand you and Andrew got an understanding,'' Edwards
told Guidry, according to Guidry's testimony. ``I'm going to see
about getting you your hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors heard prosecutors depict Edwards as a man who was
both audaciously bold and exceedingly cautious, who endlessly
hatched plots to enrich himself but typically delegated the
riskiest work to middlemen and cloaked his intentions in code. He
covered his tracks, prosecutors said, by taking payments in cash,
transporting it cross-country in a money vest and then spending it
lavishly. Thousands of $100 bills were spent on his home, a ranch,
furniture, landscaping, an airplane, yachts and diamond earrings.
Prosecutors place the total earnings from the schemes at nearly $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   One tape recording seems to catch Edwards in a plot to launder
cash payments by falsely inflating rental payments that Guidry
would make for the use of a tugboat. Another captures him advising
former Rep. Cleo Fields on how to conceal a $20,000 cash payment
from Edwards by disguising it as a campaign donation from a friend.
A third tape reveals Edwards asking DeBartolo for tickets to the
1997 Super Bowl that prosecutors say he then scalped for $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Wednesday, Edwards' lawyer, Dan Small,
warned the jurors that all was not as it appeared, and that
prosecutors had built a case long on suspicion and short on proof.
``The government has put on a case based on gossip, innuendo and
lies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's strongest witnesses, including DeBartolo, had
fabricated testimony in order to secure plea bargain agreements,
Small contended, and the prosecution had manufactured a sinister
spin for innocent comments caught on the tapes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The bewildering thing, prosecutors suggested, is that by
virtually any measure, certainly by the standards of his
impoverished Cajun childhood, Edwards seemed to be doing well
enough. By the time he left office, he was worth an estimated $4
million to $5 million, according to prosecutors. He lived in one of
Baton Rouge's most exclusive neighborhoods with his second wife,
Candy, who is 35.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the 1980s, he had escaped conviction on charges that he
took payoffs to exert his influence _ while out of office _ to help
various patrons win state hospital licenses. By his own count, he
had been investigated by 22 grand juries. The trials took a
political toll. He lost his re-election bid in 1987 and then won
the office back in 1991, though perhaps only because his ultimate
opponent was David Duke, the former Ku Klux Klan leader.
</P>
<P>
   Yet through it all, Edwards remained Louisiana's lovable
scoundrel, damaged but not defeated, re-elected rather than
reviled. Why press his luck? the prosecution asked in its closing
argument. Why such hubris? Why not quit?
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine you're the smartest kid around and you've got a silver
tongue that can talk your way out of everything,'' Magner told the
jury. That effortless charm, when combined with Edwards' lust for
money, bred arrogance, Magner said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors pleaded with the jurors to not let Edwards get away
again, to not let him defraud them as he had defrauded their state.
``You must avoid the snares of deceit and clever lies and devilish
charm,'' said Jim Letten, the lead prosecutor. Edwards, he said,
was shrewd but also unburdened by conscience or remorse. ``He's
cold,'' Letten said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Edwards can talk his way out of his latest troubles
remains to be seen. He gave it his best shot last week, when he
spent four days on the stand, the only defendant to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the governor of the state,'' he told the jury as he
denied all the charges against him . ``That was a wonderful
achievement for me. I wasn't going to demean my office by hustling
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his testimony on Friday, Edwards sought to
impress upon the jury that he could spend the rest of his life in
jail. ``I'm 72 years old,'' he said, in response to questioning by
his own lawyer. ``I've already lived my biblically allotted time.
Statistically, I have about five or six years. If I'm lucky, maybe
eight or nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Letten quickly objected to Edwards' monologue, and U.S. District
Court Judge Frank Polozola put an end to it. Minutes later, Edwards
finished his testimony. As he headed toward the defense table, he
stopped by Letten's chair, leaned over and whispered with enough
volume to be heard by spectators: ``You missed a good speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury seems to be taking its responsibilities with deadly
seriousness, maintaining a stern composure even as spectators
chuckle at Edwards' antics. But for no other reason than that this
is the way it has always been, many Louisianans assume that Edwards
will go free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's crooked but he's going to get off,'' said John
Franklin, a 65-year-old retired store owner who was interviewed
Wednesday morning in New Orleans. ``They never got him before and
they don't have him now.''
</P>
<P>
   And while most of those interviewed said the trial had only
reinforced Edwards' existing reputation, some said the prosecution
had succeeded in changing his image from that of a harmless scamp
to something more malevolent. ``Let's face it, this is Louisiana
and people kind of enjoy things like this,'' said Joe Knight, a
36-year-old New Orleans artist. ``But there have been moments when
people realize just how serious this is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
