u f BC-DOWNTURN-MARKETPLACE-     04-19 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTURN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: BARRING ANOTHER DIVE, LASTING DAMAGE IS LIKELY TO BE
MINIMAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock prices have regained some of their lost ground, but the
enormous hit to wealth last week is likely to knock the nation's
economy only partly off its stride _ unless the rout on Wall Street
resumes in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   From early January through last Friday, sell-offs have destroyed
an estimated $2 trillion to $3 trillion in total wealth, including
$1.5 trillion in household savings. Most of that was wiped out in
last week's steep decline.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the household decline over the roughly half the
population that owns stocks and the loss averaged more than $12,000
a person. What if that turned out to be long-lasting, and each
foray upward in stock prices soon gave way to another slide, as
this week's rally began to do Wednesday?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market stays just where it was, there will be weeks of
news media discussion about what went wrong and a lot of
person-to-person conversation,'' said Robert J. Shiller, a Yale
economist whose new book, ``Irrational Exuberance,'' argues that
stock markets are driven in large part by emotion and mimicry.
``People learn what to do from one another.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk, the damage to the overall economy is
likely to be minimal _ unless markets take another severe dive,
pushing stock gauges well below their lows so far this year. If the
market merely fails to rebound, the growth rate of the economy
should slow by this summer to about 3.6 percent, compared with last
year's growth of 4.6 percent, according to estimates by
Macroeconomic Advisers, a St. Louis firm whose computer simulations
of the economy's expected behavior are widely followed by
government officials and economists.
</P>
<P>
   Under the firm's projections, the unemployment rate could drift
gradually upward to 4.5 percent next year from 4.1 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers tend to respond fairly quickly to sharp declines in
household wealth,'' said Kenneth J. Matheny, senior economist at
Macroeconomic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that downshift represents only a comparatively modest
deceleration from the 4.2 percent growth Macroeconomic Advisers
expected in the absence of a stock market correction. The red-hot
American economy was already projected to cool off slightly in
response to a series of interest rate increases engineered by the
Federal Reserve. There have been five quarter-point rate increases
in the federal funds rate since last June, and Macroeconomic
Advisers allows for more, pushing the current level beyond 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This assumes that stock prices move sideways for six months,''
Matheny said. ``If there is another big correction in the next few
weeks, then we could seriously entertain the possibility that the
Fed won't tighten again, and might even ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Fed does, the market downturn is likely to arouse
much more debate about interest rate policy. With the gross
domestic product expanding at more than 4 percent on average in
recent years, and much more in recent months, the Fed's rate
increases have met with relatively little opposition. To most
economists, the demand for goods and services seems to be
outstripping supply, threatening inflationary shortages.
</P>
<P>
   But if growth slows to around 3.5 percent, partly in response to
weakness on Wall Street, that could bring the nation's increase in
economic output within the range that many experts believe is
sustainable without risking a serious escalation in prices. In that
case, the Fed may not have to lift interest rates very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's play with one percentage point of economic growth,''
said Alan S. Blinder, a Princeton University economist and a former
vice chairman of the Fed. ``To the extent the stock market takes
this purchasing power away, the Fed has less to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question mark is the extent to which the so-called
wealth effect will come into play. While some experts think such
estimates are exaggerated, the rule of thumb held that on the way
up, consumers spent perhaps 3 to 5 cents more for each dollar of
increase in their households' stock portfolios. But some new
research suggests that on the way down, the pullback in spending
might be greater than 3 to 5 cents _ concentrated in high-end
merchandise like luxury cars, jewelry, watches, boats and the like.
</P>
<P>
   While the spending of high-end households is hit the hardest,
changes in stock prices appear to ``affect spending by households
that do not own stock because they affect consumer confidence,''
James Poterba, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, reports in an article soon to be published in the
Journal of Economic Perspectives. ``Unfortunately, the only way to
learn more about these effects may be by experiencing a downturn in
stock market values.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill Lynch, estimates
that the stock market wealth effect added about three-quarters of a
percentage point to economic growth over the last year. ``What
stimulated spending will soon evaporate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from consumption, the downward pressure on economic growth
from an enduring stock market correction comes from changes to
capital spending, stock options, pension fund contributions and
debt. As consumption eases, so does the pressure to expand
production through capital investment in new equipment. Less demand
means less output, and capital spending may fall about 15 percent
short of projections this year in response to the market downturn,
Matheny said.
</P>
<P>
   The economy could take another hit if stock options become less
popular. The companies that issue these options do not have to
carry them as a labor cost until they are cashed in. But in a
market that is moving sideways or down, stock options lose their
appeal and employees may press for cash raises or bonuses. These do
count as a labor cost, cutting into profits that drive expansion
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies will take a wait-and-see attitude,'' said Rhoda
Edelman, managing director of Pearl Meyer &AMP; Partners Inc., a firm
that advises companies on compensation practices. ``But there is a
potential for higher labor costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, rising stock prices have increased the value of
corporate pension funds in recent years, thus reducing or
eliminating the need for cash contributions. The market correction,
if it holds, means that companies will have to inject additional
cash, cutting further into profits.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest unknown is what will happen to heavily indebted
families, many of which borrowed against the value of their homes
or stock portfolios to pay for consumption or the purchase of more
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people must feel vulnerable if the stock market
correction holds and therefore the flow of borrowing is likely to
be lower,'' said Wynne Godley, an economist and debt expert at the
Jerome Levy Economics Institute. ``If the flow is lower, spending
will be lower. We don't know the magnitudes yet, but that is the
central point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
