<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-REACTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN AMERICANS CHEER A COURT DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CUBAN-BOY)  
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the crisp, navy blue T-shirts of the private Our Lady
of the Rosary School, 16 children, 3 to 5 years old, fidgeted with
their beads and pressed their hands in prayer at the chain-link
fence in front of Elian Gonzalez's home in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for the children of all nations,'' Teresa Hernandez,
the school's director of the evangelization program, said into her
bullhorn. ``We pray for President Clinton to be guided and
enlightened by the Holy Spirit. We pray to the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Then at 2:45 p.m., before the children could say ``Amen,'' a
deafening, joyous roar rose from the 200 or 300 Cuban Americans
keeping vigil on the street. A federal appeals court had determined
that Elian could remain in the United States at least a while
longer, until an asylum hearing next month. The ruling, upholding
an earlier stay, was the latest in a series of victories for
Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Two men in the crowd, the first to hear of the ruling, leaped
from the barricades and hugged. ``He is saved!'' someone cried.
Members of Mothers Against Repression, clad in black and wearing
straw hats to fend off the sun, wiped tears and linked hands in a
circle to pray. Horns blared. People formed a procession and
chanted, ``Elian no se va''_ Elian will not go _ and ``Fidel
loco.''
</P>
<P>
   To cheers, Elian's great-uncle, who has defied federal officials
by refusing to turn the boy over to his father, bounded out of the
patch of lawn inside his fence. Lazaro Gonzalez, a part-time car
mechanic, about 5-foot-6, broad-shouldered and compact, was wearing
a red form-fitting T-shirt tucked into the waist of his jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gonzalez family continues to believe in the laws of the
United States,'' Lazaro Gonzalez told the crowd. ``We will continue
to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was nowhere in sight at first, but soon he came out,
played on his swing set and high-fived his cousin, Marisleysis,
Lazaro Gonzalez's 21-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   As the news circulated, people saw this as another skirmish won,
not the war. Attorney General Janet Reno could still try to turn
the child over to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has been
waiting in Bethesda, Md., to regain custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Wednesday was by a three-judge panel of the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the 11th Circuit, in Atlanta. The federal
government could seek to have the stay lifted by the full court or
by a Supreme Court justice. Or it could wait until a scheduled May
11 hearing before the federal appeals court on the asylum request
by the Miami relatives. The Immigration and Naturalization Service
had denied that request.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is all we've been asking for _ his day in court,''
said Luis Montoto, 42, who emigrated from Cuba when he was 11. ``If
the court rules that he goes back to Cuba, whether we like it or
not, he goes back.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Fernandez, a 38-year-old teacher who arrived here when he
was 8, said, ``This is a small victory in this long battle. All the
time people have said that we don't have a leg to stand on, but
this proves our system of government works.''
</P>
<P>
   But something else might be at work here, too, many vigil
keepers said. As the cheers for the ruling subsided, Hernandez
lifted her megaphone again to give thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Praise the Lord!'' she said. ``Praise the Lord! Praise the
Lord!'' She led the children in singing ``Jesus Loves the Little
Children'' and the chorus to ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   As she led the children off, a 5-year-old boy named Chi-Chi
explained why he came today. ``So Elian could stay here,'' Chi-Chi
said. ``In Cuba, they don't have freedom and cannot pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
