u a BC-NEW-CIGARETTE-NYT &LR;      04-19 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CIGARETTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REYNOLDS TO PROMOTE CIGARETTE AS POSING LOWER CANCER RISK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Texas)  By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holding Co. said Wednesday that it
would start promoting one of its brands as posing a potentially
lower risk of cancer and chronic bronchitis than traditional
cigarettes, the first time that a producer has made such
advertising claims.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the company said they would make the claims in
connection with its Eclipse cigarette, a brand that heats rather
than burns tobacco. The brand has been on the market for five years
but has found few customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's claims are the first in what may be a new thrust
by tobacco producers in the coming years to develop and market
cigarettes that could pose reduced health risks to smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's action quickly came under criticism from
antismoking groups and others who said there were no independent
scientific criteria to determine what constituted a reduced-risk
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a spokeswoman for the Philip Morris Cos., the
nation's largest cigarette maker, said it did not intend to make
reduced-risk claims for any of its current or future products until
a federal regulatory plan was in place to assess the issue. Philip
Morris has urged that the government be given authority over such
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds officials said they believed that they had strong
data to support their claim and that they would start test
marketing the new advertising campaign this week in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to tell smokers about the potential benefits of
Eclipse and see if they are interested in switching,'' Andrew J.
Schlinder, chairman of R.J. Reynolds told a meeting of company
shareholders Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it would make direct mailings about
Eclipse to doctors and other medical professionals so they could
discuss the product with their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Eclipse, the major brands of the company, which is in
Winston-Salem, N.C., are Winston, Salem and Camel.
</P>
<P>
   David Townsend, the company's vice president of product and
process development, said in an interview that the claims for
Eclipse were based on new scientific data including studies
involving a small number of smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that such data had been reviewed by an
independent panel of experts it had retained and that a summary of
their findings had been submitted for publication in a scientific
journal. It declined to disclose the names of all panel members or
the journal's name.
</P>
<P>
   A special carbon tip on Eclipse smolders, creating a minimum of
smoke with less tar, a full dose of nicotine but high levels of
carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   The company's advertisements emphasize that quitting smoking is
the best way to reduce tobacco risks but add that Eclipse ``may
pose less risk of cancer'' to smokers and that it ``reduces
respiratory inflammation,'' which ``may lower risk of chronic
bronchitis and possibly emphysema.''
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette could, however, increase the risk of heart disease
to smokers and complications to pregnant women who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Some antismoking groups attacked the new promotions as
self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without an independent government agency to verify these
claims there is no scientific way to verify RJR's claim that they
have developed a cigarette that can save lives,'' said Matthew
Myers, an official with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Several decades ago, tobacco makers implied that cigarettes with
lower levels of tar and nicotine than traditional ones might also
pose a reduced risk to smokers. Because smokers tended to drag more
deeply on those cigarettes they produced a certain type of lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court recently ruled that the federal Food and Drug
Administration did not have any authority over cigarette producers
or claims that they might make in connection with their products.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, secretary of health and human services said in a
statement that the government had significant concerns about the
company's marketing plans. ``It is not at all clear that a
sufficient science base exists to support a bold claim that this
tobacco product may reduce the risk of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission has taken action on other tobacco
advertisements that it believes are misleading or deceptive
including some advertisements for R.J. Reynolds cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Peeler, associate director of advertising at the commission
said the agency had not seen the new Eclipse advertisements and
declined to say whether the agency planned to investigate them.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds officials said they had met recently with
officials of both the food and drug agency and the federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention and provided them with health
data about Eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Judge Jack B. Weinstein of the U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn, who is presiding over several tobacco lawsuits, asked
lawyers for tobacco companies and smokers on Tuesday to see if they
could develop a plan to resolve all smoking litigation nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said that such a plan could prove extremely
difficult to make but that the initiative could lead to a new round
of settlement talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
