<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SORRY, WRONG NUMBER IF YOU'RE CALLING THE 1999
KNICKS  
 WILLIAM C. RHODEN  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Knicks closed out their regular season in Boston
Wednesday night. They did so quietly, without incident.
</P>
<P>
   This was an efficient, workmanlike resolution. Last year, in a
lockout-shortened season, the abbreviated schedule forced a mad
sprint to the finish. This season was a long, boring grind.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was something dramatically different about the Knicks
this season _ perhaps an odd, updated, up-tempo version of the
``Knicks basketball'' that evolved in the late '60s and '70s:
intelligent team play, distinguished by ball movement and wise
passing. The concept underwent a major overhaul in 1999 but
returned, as fundamentals always do.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, the sky nearly caved in on the Knicks.
On April 19, they lost to Philadelphia, 72-67, their season-high
fourth consecutive loss. With eight games left, the Knicks were in
danger of missing the playoffs for the first time in 12 season
</P>
<P>
   Writers used phrases like ``broken-down machine'' to describe
the Knicks and said the team was ``filled with flaws and defects.''
There were calls to trade Patrick Ewing and fire coach Jeff Van
Gundy. Ewing said that if the coach were fired, he wanted to be
traded.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the nasty internal feuds that had festered in
and out of public view came to a head when Dave Checketts,
president of Madison Square Garden, fired Ernie Grunfeld as Knicks
president and appointed himself to run the club.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Knicks were exhilarating, intriguing, compelling. This
season's Knicks are better, yet on the surface, they seem boring.
</P>
<P>
   But we've been given the most riveting drama of their season in
an otherwise unspectacular season: the silent movie of Ewing's
return.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing tore his Achilles' tendon during the playoffs last spring,
and the injury was the defining point _ some say the turning point
_ of the Knicks' season and yet another turning point in Ewing's
career.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are in the spring of 2000 and Ewing has climbed a steep
mountain to get back to playoffs. He's endured an excruciating
process of healing: waited for the tendon to heal and listened to
biting criticism that the Knicks might not have reached the NBA
finals last year had he been with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the critics who wrote the Knicks off last season are
predicting gloom against Toronto, their first-round opponent. Van
Gundy is the greatest gloom leader of all. He points out that
Toronto has beaten up on the Knicks for two seasons now. The
Raptors are young and athletic, with a superstar in Vince Carter,
the heir apparent to Jordan, and a hardened veteran in Charles
Oakley, the former Knick.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are not a one-day fling. A team doesn't zip in for
a game then zip out to face another opponent in another city.
Playoff series eliminate luck and ensure that the best team wins.
Toronto will have to be the best team, not just on one night but on
three, four or five nights.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks whom Toronto will face have gone from a team playing
largely on emotion _ improvising the script as it went along _ to a
methodical team dispensing emotion when needed, riding the highs
the lows with matter-of-factness and brevity. The dramatic sense of
urgency that existed this time last season has been replaced by an
intense but unstated sense of mission.
</P>
<P>
   This, more than anything else about the Knicks, is the handiwork
of Patrick Ewing. His harshest critics concede that his greatest
virtue _ underlined this season _ is resiliency. Will we say that
about Vince Carter in 2015?
</P>
<P>
   Carter is too young to know the rivers Ewing has known: long
summers of rehabilitation, the process of gradually feeling his way
back, exploring the range of what can and cannot be done with
skills diminished by age and eroded by injury. Finally this season,
shedding part of a superstar's ego, discovering when to let the
team carry him, when to carry his team. Finally the payoff:
barreling into April and reaching this point, where it all began
for the Knicks last time around. And ended for Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto had the Knicks' number during the regular season. But
they are entering the playoffs _ a time of career-defining moments
of sports life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Under these circumstances, I'll take my chances with Ewing. The
young Raptors will dial the Knicks' number they used to have and
receive heartbreaking news that it has been disconnected.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
