<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BOYCOTT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's hard to make boycotts stick, experts say
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's relatively easy to call for a boycott, but
another matter to do it successfully, say experts who follow them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger and better known the organization calling for a
boycott, the more likely it's going to receive attention in the
news media and among consumers at large,'' said Monroe Friedman, an
expert on consumer protest activity and author of a book on
boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman was reacting Wednesday to calls for a national boycott
of Coca-Cola products by a group of former and current
African-American employees. The group is headed by former Coca-Cola
human resources manager Larry Jones, a 15-year employee who was
laid off as part of a massive downsizing. The group wants Coca-Cola
to settle a racial discrimination suit quickly and improve its
treatment of black employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relatively easy to call for a boycott, but it's quite
another thing to mount an effective campaign that will endure over
a substantial time period,'' said Friedman, a professor at Eastern
Michigan University. He said organizers would have to access funds,
staffing and organizational skills to keep the momentum going.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said one factor working against Jones and the others
was the lack of initial support by major civil rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Holmes, director of the Southern Center for Studies in
Public Policy at Clark Atlanta University, said calls for a boycott
against Coca-Cola may be a bit premature.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who acknowledged he was a Coca-Cola investor, suggested
that calling for a boycott against Coca-Cola was not the same as
calling one to bring down the Confederate battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   It's also ``the timing of it,'' Holmes said. ``You're basically
innocent until proven guilty. I think they need to let the courts
decide first or see if the company agrees to a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he might support a boycott if talks to settle the
lawsuit failed or if Coca-Cola decided to appeal a court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Putnam, former publisher of The National Boycott News in
Seattle, said companies fear boycotts because of the hit they can
take to the bottom line, as well as the blow to their image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some boycotts can have long-term implications,'' Putnam said.
``They (companies) might think it's better to settle now and move
on. ``
</P>
<P>
   The threat to Coca-Cola's image is a major concern to observers
inside and outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly is not a positive for the company in terms of
image,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I believe the company will very quickly resolve the
underlying situation so it will not have a lasting or significant
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Russell Grantham
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
