<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE EARNINGS DROP, BOEING EXECS UPBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Wall Street Wednesday rewarded The Boeing Co.'s
recovery from last month's strike _ despite a decline in earnings _
with the biggest one-day gain in its stock price in more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing came through the 40-day strike by its engineers in good
shape and should be able to get its backlog of airplanes delivered
by the end of the second quarter, company executives said reporting
first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Although earnings fell 11 percent as a result of the strike, the
company easily beat reduced Wall Street estimates, and executives
painted an upbeat picture of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, our work force is back together as a team, we are
executing our recovery plan and operating margins are continuing to
improve,'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said during a teleconference
with industry analysts and media.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted by sending Boeing's stock up $2.50 a share
to close at $37.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this strike had happened two years ago, it would have been
a complete disaster for the company,'' said analyst Bill Fiala of
Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Boeing's production system was in chaos and its stock
price and and earnings were falling like rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could not have come through this as healthy as they
have,'' Fiala said. ``For them to maintain respectable profit
margins with a $2.5 billion shortfall is phenomenal. Their
operations are in much better shape than they were two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That $2.5 billion figure was how much Boeing lost in commercial
revenue in the quarter because of delayed airplane deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Wood, aerospace analyst and vice president with Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, upgraded Boeing's stock to a ``strong buy''
after Wednesday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just warming up,'' Wood said of Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Boeing had total revenues of $9.91
billion, down 31 percent from the same period in 1999. Net income
was $418 million, or 11 percent less than a year earlier. That
translated to earnings of 48 cents a share, down from 50 cents a
share in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding special items, Boeing earned 41 cents per share for
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial had estimated
profits at 35 cents a share, down from a consensus forecast of 56
cents before the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in
Aerospace began a strike on Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the work disruptions caused by the strike, it was
a very respectable quarter,'' said analyst Peter Jacobs of
Seattle's Regan MacKenzie Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the outlook for 2001 is firming up nicely,''
Jacobs said. ``Management believes revenue will be up slightly but
earnings should be up handsomely.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said total revenue this year will be $50 billion, and
projected revenues of $51 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said the company expects only ``modest'' revenue growth
over the next three years, but profitability will continue to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Heading in to Wednesday's earning's announcement, analysts were
not overly concerned about the expected drop in revenue due to the
strike. They were mainly focused on Boeing being able to make its
all-important airplane delivery commitments for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had said it would deliver 490 planes in 2000
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strike, Boeing delivered 75 jetliners in the
first quarter _ 50 fewer than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we will essentially be back on our original delivery
plan by the end of the second quarter,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   That means Boeing will need to deliver around 180 planes this
quarter, analysts said. As of Tuesday night, Boeing had delivered
102 jets since the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The strike mainly disrupted the company's commercial operations,
which had revenues of $5.17 billion in the first quarter, compared
with $9.8 billion a year earlier _ a 47 percent drop. Boeing was
producing many more planes in 1999, when it delivered a record 620.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, the commercial group had net income of $259
million, down 35 percent from the $396 million in the first quarter
of 1999. Commercial profit margins were 5 percent for the quarter,
an improvement over the 4 percent margins a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But commercial margins fell from the fourth quarter, when they
peaked at 7 percent. That was primarily due to the delayed
deliveries and some cost impacts associated with the strike, Jacobs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Debby Hopkins, Boeing's chief financial officer, said the
commercial side of the business continues to see significant
productivity gains, especially in the 737 and 777 programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lean manufacturing efforts are really starting to bear some
fruit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing performed well across its three main business units _
commercial airplanes, space and communications, and military
aircraft and missiles, Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's military aircraft and missiles unit had earnings of
$298 million on revenues of $2.9 billion for the quarter. Revenue
was flat from a year earlier. Profit margins increased slightly to
10.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Space and communications, which executives have said will
eventually become the company's fastest growing segment, had
earnings of $60 million on revenue of $1.66 billion. A year ago,
the unit had earnings of $61 million on revenue of $1.54 billion
</P>
<P>
   Operating margins for the space and communications unit in the
first quarter were 3.6 percent, down slightly from a year ago.
Hopkins said research and development spending, much of it for the
Delta 4 rocket program, kept margins down.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's total research and development spending for the quarter
was $288 million, down from $361 million for the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marks the low point for our R&AMP;D spending as a company,''
Hopkins said. This year, Boeing will spend about $1.5 billion in
research and development, up about $100 million from last year, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Boeing delivered its fourth quarter 1999 earnings report in
January, analysts expressed concern about a sharp drop in research
and development spending.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said research and development is ``a key component of
what we are as a company. We see the value of it increasing as we
look over the next few years at some of the exciting programs we
are working on.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Boeing's engineers have complained the company has cut
back on research and development to boost profits, a charge the
company denies.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said Boeing is paying ``direct attention to its future by
long term research and development.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company needs to do a better job of sharing its
vision of the future with its work force, especially in the
aftermath of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``major'' meeting with the SPEEA union will be
tonight, Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important information and building effort for the
long term,'' Condit said. `` ... People want to know what their
role is ... how do they fit in ... We are going to have a lot of
very exciting engineering to do ... but you have to paint that
picture. ... with a lot of face to face communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can send out so many little letters, but in the end people
want to understand and get a good strong gut feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
