u f BC-GREY-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-19 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GREY'S CHIEF BEGINS TO ADDRESS SUCCESSION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, Madison Avenue has wondered when Edward H.
Meyer, the supreme commander of Grey Advertising in New York, would
relinquish some of his power and authority.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman, president and chief executive, Meyer has long
declined to designate an heir apparent or delegate some of his
duties, eliciting comparisons to dominant executives in other
industries like Henry Ford and William S. Paley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriarch Ed Meyer's failure to make known a clear succession
plan has left his agency, an industry institution, with an
indistinct and murky future,'' the trade publication Advertising
Age said in an unusual editorial that led the Viewpoint page of
last week's issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Meyer, 73, is finally making the first steps toward
outlining the future of Grey, which has estimated billings of more
than $8 billion from clients like British American Tobacco, Mars,
Oracle, Procter &AMP; Gamble and SmithKline Beecham. But those who
emulate Regis Philbin and seek a final answer to the succession
issue will have to wait because, he said, ``the next obvious step
is a year away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reorganization described Wednesday to Grey employees, Meyer
will become the chairman and chief executive of a new holding
company, Grey Global Group, which will be formed subject to
shareholder approval _ considered probable because Meyer owns about
70 percent of Grey's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior managers will join Meyer in stepping up from the
core advertising agency operation, to be renamed Grey Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good news for Grey,'' said Meyer, ``and it's very
good news for me because I don't want to work so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking out some of the older, wiser souls from the
advertising business,'' he added, ``to help grow our other exciting
lines of businesses.'' Those graybeards _ or Greybeards, if you
will _ include Robert L. Berenson, 60, president for North American
operations at Grey Advertising, who will be vice chairman and
general manager at Grey Global, and Steven G. Felsher, 50,
executive vice president for finance at Grey Advertising, who will
be vice chairman and chief financial officer at Grey Global.
</P>
<P>
   The other business lines apart from Grey Worldwide that will
report to Grey Global include Beyond Interactive and Grey
Interactive, specializing in Internet marketing; GCI, public
relations; Grey Direct, direct marketing; and Mediacom, media
services.
</P>
<P>
   While each of those operations is to be run by a chairman,
president, chief executive or managing director, or a combination
of those, no one at Grey Worldwide _ representing 60 percent of the
total revenue of the new Grey Global _ will have titles that broad.
The most senior titles at Grey Worldwide will be geographic, for
regions or offices. The worldwide account directors at Grey
Worldwide, who handle important clients including Mars and P&AMP;G,
will report directly to Meyer and other executives at Grey Global.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is get a new management team'' at Grey
Worldwide, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``North America comes next, in a very short period of
time, and then we'll go from there. In a year, there'll be a
chairman and a president of the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two executives seemed poised for promotion at Grey Worldwide.
One is Steven Blamer, who turned 44 yesterday; he is leaving
London, where he had been chief executive at Grey Advertising, to
become president for New York at Grey Worldwide. The other is
Carolyn Carter, 44, executive vice president and global account
director on the Mars account at Grey Advertising. She will become
president for Europe, the Middle East and Africa at Grey Worldwide,
based in London and New York, while continuing her Mars account
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving Steve the largest agency in the system, New York,
and saying `Go run it,''' Meyer said. ``He will do that and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolyn is also of the right generation and age'' to be an
heir apparent, he added.
</P>
<P>
   There will be two other regional managers for Grey Worldwide.
One is Bernd Michael, 54, chairman and chief executive for Europe,
the Middle East and Africa, based in Dusseldorf, Germany, and
London; he had been deputy chairman for Europe and chief executive
for Germany at Grey Advertising. The other is Eric Rosenkranz, 47,
president for the Asian-Pacific region, based in Hong Kong; he had
been executive vice president and regional director for Latin
America at Grey Advertising. A president for Latin America at Grey
Worldwide is to be named soon.
</P>
<P>
   On the creative side of Grey Worldwide, just as on the account
management side, there is to be no top executive. Stephen A.
Novick, 59, executive vice president for worldwide creative
services at Grey Advertising, will become vice chairman and chief
creative officer at Grey Global while still overseeing creative
output at the advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve will wear two hats as he and I form a partnership,''
Blamer said. ``Over time, we will look for who the obvious partner
should be for me, and Steve will have a role in that.''
</P>
<P>
   That partner could come from a cadre of creative managers at
Grey Worldwide. They include five executive vice presidents and
executive creative directors in New York: Rob Biaocco, Richard K.
Mahan, Mark A. Schwatka, Robert Skollar and David G. Tutin. Other
top creative executives at Grey Worldwide are Tim Mellors in
London, Alain Godefroid in Belgium, Rob Dow and Jeff Orr in the
Asian-Pacific region and Carlos Perez in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years, this is the plum job,'' Blamer said of his new
duties. ``The person who really appreciates this is my mother. She
called and said, `Steven' _ and she's the only one who calls me
Steven _ `this is a nice birthday present.'''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said Blamer was indicative of ``the dynamic, youthful
management'' that is to lead Grey Worldwide, adding: ``Since I have
been taunted so often about succession and my age, I want to point
out with great glee that the people coming in to run the
advertising agency are an average age of 46, 47.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the complaints that he dragged his feet in developing a
succession plan, Meyer said: ``I was the architect of this, the
sole architect of this. I was going as fast as my little feet would
carry me. I wish to put to rest all the questions: `Where's the
young blood?' `Where's the succession?'''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not ``Where's the beef?'' _ but there's a ring to
it.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, other appointments in connection with the
reorganization. At Grey Global, Alec Gerster, 51, becomes media
ventures director while continuing as chairman at Mediacom, and
Neil I. Kreisberg, 55, becomes group executive vice president; he
will hold the same post at Grey Worldwide and will also be
executive managing director there, overseeing the P&AMP;G account.
</P>
<P>
   At Grey Worldwide, O. John C. Shannon, 62, was named president
for international, and these managers were named executive vice
presidents and executive managing directors: Joseph A. Celia, 40,
overseeing British American Tobacco; Jonathan E. Fox, 54; and Clive
Holland, 56, overseeing SmithKline Beecham from London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
