<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMA-MEMORIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING MEMORIAL DEDICATION DRAWS THOUSANDS TO REMEMBER, AND DRAW
HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Thousands of people filled the streets of
downtown Oklahoma City on Wednesday to dedicate a national memorial
for those who died _ and for those who survived _ the bombing of
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno attended the
dedication ceremonies and implored Oklahomans to think of the
memorial as a shrine of triumph, rather than a mark of tragedy,
triggered by the most treacherous act of terrorism on American
soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is such sacred ground,'' Clinton said, speaking at
the site where the bomb took 168 lives, 19 of them children. ``We
may never have all the answers about what happened here,'' he said,
``but as we continue our journey towards understanding, one truth
is clear: What was meant to break, has made you stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The president called convicted bombers Timothy McVeigh and Terry
Nichols ``cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, speakers marveled over how Oklahoma City
citizens have rebounded from the enormous blast, triggered from a
truck filled with and explosive mix of fuel and fertilizer, on the
morning of April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the people of Oklahoma City, thank you for showing America
how to stand up to evil, an evil ... spawned from hell,'' Reno said
at the early evening ceremony. ``In the face of evil that would
stagger the soul, you demonstrated the triumph of the American
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a much smaller, but more emotional, memorial
ceremony was held primarily for bombing survivors, the relatives of
the dead and for the rescue workers who helped pull victims from
the mangled Murrah building.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Biddy said he had to force himself to attend, but did so
for his two young sons, who on a different day would have been
inside the ``America's Kids'' day care center when it was ripped to
pieces by the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of enduring'' the memorial, said Biddy, who
lost his mother, Oleta Biddy, to the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're trying to live with and not dwell on,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the blast, survivors and victims'
families were able to walk where the Murrah building once stood. It
is now replaced by large bronze memorial walls, acting as ornate
gates to a reflection pool, and 168 granite-and-glass chairs, each
containing the name of a person killed by the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is beautiful,'' said Teresa Corall, who came from Akron
to pay tribute to her brother, Rick Tomlin, a Department of
Transportation worker who was killed on the fourth floor of the
Murrah building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask for a better memorial for my brother,'' Corall
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Graves, who lost her daughter, Cassandra Booker, in the
bombing, said she was not quite as impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chair is real nice, but the Lord is who gives me
strength,'' Graves said, adding: ``It doesn't do any good for me to
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile from the anniversary and dedication ceremonies,
Nichols was in the Oklahoma County Jail, awaiting trial on state
murder charges in connection to the bombing. The state of Oklahoma
is seeking the death penalty for Nichols, who has already been
convicted in U.S. district court and sentenced to life in federal
prison.
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh has been convicted on federal charges of murder and
conspiracy and was sentenced to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   Out of breath after walking up a steep hill from the chair
commemorating her dead son, 78-year-old Clarissa Harding said she
does not know whether she is healthy enough to ever return. Harding
said she would like to, though, because the memorial ``makes you
realize you're not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, however, that she is uncomfortable that Nichols is
jailed so close to where her dead son, Ronald, is memorialized. ``I
don't want him hanging around here,'' Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
