<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 20
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-MORDECAI-NYT (moved on Sunday, April 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, April 16,
about an Israeli police recommendation that Transportation Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai be prosecuted on charges of sexual assault
misstated his background. Although he is a former defense minister
and a former general, he did not serve as army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-WASHBURN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 18)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Sherwood Washburn, sent by the New York Times
News Service on Tuesday, April 18, misstated the area of Africa
where he befriended the fossil-hunting Leakey family. It was East
Africa, not South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-VAROS-NYT (moved on Monday, April 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, April 10,
about Remedios Varo, a painter who metaphorically depicted
scientific concepts like Einstein's special theory of relativity,
misspelled the name of the physicist whose equations were used in
the theory. He is Hendrik A. Lorentz, not Lorenz.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CAMBODIA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Tuesday, April 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 18,
about two first-person accounts of life under the Khmer Rouge in
Cambodia misspelled the given name of one author and at some points
used that name as her surname. The author of ``First They Killed My
Father'' is Loung Ung, not Luong Ung.
</P>
</TEXT>
