<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OKLA-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HELPS DEDICATE OKLAHOMA BOMBING MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA City _ Marking the fifth anniversary of the worst act
of domestic terrorism in US history, President Clinton called the
site of the bombing of the Oklahoma City federal building ``sacred
ground,'' and said, ``America will never forget'' the tragedy that
happened there.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling here for the dedication of the Oklahoma City National
Memorial, Clinton paid tribute to the 168 people killed, including
19 children, and the 850 who were injured in the bombing of the
Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building on April 19,1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places in our national landscape so scarred by
freedom's sacrfice that they shape forever the soul of America _
Valley Forge, Gettysburg, Selma. This place is such sacred
ground,'' Clinton said, at a public dedication ceremony attended by
many survivors and family members of the bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that five years has not been long enough for the
families and survivors to heal, he said, ``I know the last five
years have not been easy. I hope you can take some comfort in
knowing that _ just as I said five years ago _ America is still
with you, and that, with this memorial, you can know American will
never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   At the somber outdoor ceremony that took place under a hot
evening sun, Clinton kept his remarks brief, and relied on
Scripture and the writer Ralph Ellison, a native of Oklahoma City,
to help comfort the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols, who were
convicted in federal court in the attack, as ``cowards.'' McVeigh
has been sentenced to death; Nichols has been sentenced to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Standing near a gate to the victims' memorial, Clinton said,
``Five years ago, the cowards who killed them made a choice _ a
choice to attack this building and the people in it, because they
wanted to strike a blow at America's heartland _ at the core of our
nation's being. This was an attack on all America, and every
American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years later, we are here because you made a choice: A
choice to choose hope and love over despair and hatred,'' he said.
``I know there are still days when the old anger wells up inside
you; still days when tears fill your eyes, when you think your
heart will surely break. On those days, I hope you can come here
and find solace in the memory of your loved ones, in the honor of
your fellow citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton helped untie the ribbon to mark the opening of the $29
million memorial, which stands on 3.3 acres and the site of what
used to be the federal building. The memorial features 168 granite
and bronze chairs on a lighted glass block pedestal _ one for each
person killed. A black reflecting pool runs alongside the chairs
and on opposite ends of the pool are two 42-foot bronze and
concrete gates.
</P>
<P>
   One gate is marked 9:01 and the other 9:03, intended to
symbolize the lives that were lost at 9:02 a.m., the time the
bombing occurred. The memorial also includes a wall inscribed with
the names of the survivors of the bombing. Other plans for the
project include construction of museum and an international
institute for the study of non-violence and the prevention of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Before he spoke, Clinton toured the memorial with two women who
lost relatives in the bombing as well as some survivors and rescue
workers, offering them pats on the back and hands on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he knelt down and ran his hand over one of the
glass and granite chairs that symbolizes one of the children
killed. He picked up flowers that the wind had blown off a chair
and put them back, and he stepped to the edge of the reflecting
pool, and placed his hand in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may never have all the answers for what happened here,''
Clinton said, in his remarks. ``But as we continue our journey
toward understanding, one truth is clear: what was meant to break
has made you stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who along with several other
administration officials joined Clinton at the dedication, told the
crowd, ``Thank you for showing us how to stand up to evil.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that Department of Justice pledged to ``never stop in
its pursuit of peace, in its effort to stop violence, in its
determination to stop terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that as he left the White House to fly here for the
dedication he glanced over at the dogwood tree on the South Lawn
that he and Hillary Rodham Clinton had planted five years ago in
memory of the lives lost in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years later, that tree stands a little taller, its spring
flowers are a little fuller, its roots have dug in a little deeper.
But it's still a young tree,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   `` Five years isn't a very long time for trees to grow, or for
wounds to heal and hearts to mend. But today, like your beautiful
dogwood tree on the White House lawn, Oklahoma City is blooming
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
