<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-YATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSED PROSTITUTE KILLER DESCRIBED AS `AVERAGE JOE' AND FAMILY
MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Lee Yates Jr. seems the epitome of ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   He is balding and polite and hardly worth a second look on the
streets of Spokane. He was an ace pitcher back in his high school
days on Whidbey Island, Wash., but his ball-playing is now limited
to playing catch with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only thing that made the 47-year-old aluminum worker
and ex-soldier stand out was his ability to fly helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yates, soft-spoken and courteous, sat in a tiny courtroom in
Spokane as a judge ordered him held in jail unless he comes up with
$1.5 million cash bail. Prosecutors accuse him of killing a
16-year-old prostitute. And they believe he may be a serial killer
_ responsible for a string of prostitute slayings that have
obsessed Spokane police for years.
</P>
<P>
   From his South Hill neighborhood to his old home town on Whidbey
Island, the news stuck in the throats of those who knew him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Yates, he was a great guy. He really was,'' said Gary
Berner, an Oak Harbor, Wash., dentist.
</P>
<P>
   He and Yates graduated together from Oak Harbor High in 1970.
For a couple of summers, the pair worked long hours in Skagit
County vegetable fields to earn spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Yates pitched on the high school team and belonged to clubs open
to lettermen. As a junior, his fastball won him seven games in a
16-game season, said Harry Ferrier, who played on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of quiet,'' said Ferrier. ``He was kind of like
Joe Average.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the least likely guy I would think of if you mentioned
something like that,'' Berner said of the Spokane murders. ``He was
a solid, solid guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Oak Harbor kids were military brats. Their fathers
worked at the Navy air base in town. Berner was one, but he said
Yates apparently wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrier can still remember a sonnet Yates read aloud in sixth
grade. The teacher led the students to believe that Yates had found
it in a book. In fact, the youngster had written it.
</P>
<P>
   Yates' parents moved, and he ended up in Walla Walla. He
attended community college there and met Linda Brewer. The two
would later marry and have five children together.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief time in the 1970s, he worked as a correctional
officer with his father-in-law, Bill Brewer, at the Washington
State Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer told The Spokesman-Review of Spokane that his son-in-law
is ``a real loner'' who he never really got to know _ even after 24
years of marriage to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said Yates left his prison job one day and joined the
Army. Among his postings were Fort Drum in northern New York, where
the 10th Mountain Division is based. He was also at Fort Rucker,
the Alabama base where the Army's aviation branch is headquartered.
His Army tour also apparently included Desert Storm, the war to rid
Kuwait of Iraqi troops, and the peacekeeping mission to Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   After close to 20 years in the military, however, Yates quit and
moved to Spokane in 1996. He failed to get a pilot's job there, The
Spokesman-Review reported.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up in factory jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Givens, owner of Pantrol Inc., a Spokane firm that puts
together electronic instruments for heavy machinery, said Yates
worked at his business until 1997. He assembled components.
</P>
<P>
   Givens described Yates as a good worker who mostly kept to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really stuck out about him,'' Givens said. ``He was
just an average Joe _ pretty quiet. I didn't talk to him much. But
he seemed friendly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Givens said Yates was closer to his direct supervisor. The two
men sometimes spoke fondly to each other of their families. The
supervisor, who Givens declined to name, was so upset about Yates'
arrest Tuesday that he took the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all been quite a shock for all of us, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Orders dried up at Pantrol in 1997. Givens had to to lay off
Yates and hasn't heard much from him since.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Yates turned to a Kaiser Aluminum smelter to
support his family. The regular workforce was on strike. Yates
hired on as a replacement worker, regularly crossing a picket line
to earn his pay.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Russell, president of the striking Local 329, said Yates
initially worked as a carbon setter _ intensive work that requires
respirator-equipped laborers to toil around pots of molton ore that
reach up to 1,700 degrees Farenheit. Sometime later, Russell said,
Yates' job changed to overhead crane operator in the pot room.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kaiser spokeswoman Susan Ashe: ``By all accounts he was a
good worker. He had a very good work record.''
</P>
<P>
   Yates maintained his military ties. He joined the National Guard
in April 1997, spending one weekend a month training with
helicopters at Fort Lewis south of Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to us very, very qualified. In the three years he was
assigned to us, he was a good performer. He did an excellent job,''
said Lt. Col. Rick Patterson, a National Guard spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Yates was part of the 66th Aviation Brigade attached to Fort
Lewis. He trained other pilots, and federal records show he held
civilian licenses as a commercial and helicopter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   His Spokane neighbors said they didn't know him well. There were
brief chats. He borrowed a tool or two.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed devoted to his four daughters and one son _ and to a
1977 white Corvette. It is the same Corvette from which
investigators took evidence that they believe ties Yates to
Jennifer Joseph's death.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who lived near the house Yates rented in 1996-97,
before buying the South Hill home, remember the ordinary-looking
man and his cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He washed his cars incessantly,'' said Judy Kauffman. ``He was
always out in the front driveway, changing the oil'' of the
Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman described Yates as ``cordial,'' but said other members
of his family kept to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very close neighborhood,'' she said. ``It's a
neighborhood where if you reach out, people will pull you in and
they didn't really reach out.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Lewis Kamb and The Associated Press contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
