<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: Shut Up and Read My Zipped Lips  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When  &UR; George W. Bush &LR;  became a member of Skull and Bones, the
Yale secret society to which his father had belonged, he was asked
to give himself a nickname, which is said to be that group's
custom. The Atlantic Monthly reports that he couldn't think of
anything, so they called him ``Temporary.'' They're still calling
him that.
</P>
<P>
   Magog, ``the nickname given to the incoming Bonesman deemed to
have the most sexual experience,'' was the name borne by George
W.'s pop, says the Monthly. But when a report regarding ``Magog''
appeared in the Washington Post, Skull and Bones members responded
by saying papa George's nickname was Barebones. The history,
therefore, is cloudy; further illumination would be welcome, if
Bonesmen dare blab.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Hush-husher:  &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR; , who cited the First Amendment
when sued by the beef industry for bad-mouthing burgers, doesn't
think freedom of speech is such a good thing for former employees.
Illinois courts have upheld a confidentiality agreement she
requires, in which employees promise for the rest of their lives
not to discuss her personal or business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; A NEW IDEA EVERY MINUTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Toto, a Japanese company that makes a sophisticated line of
bathroom fixtures, says that Chloe, its ``multi-tasking toilet
seat,'' has a built-in bidet device and a seat-warmer, ``all
activated by the touch pad control panel that is handily beside the
seat. The photograph of this latest piece of equipment pictured a
laptop computer _ but why couldn't that be built into the seat? _
at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Milky Way Dark Bar, produced by M&AMP;M/Mars, has been renamed
Milky Way Midnight. Advertising Age calls this important
development ``a test case to determine how to reach teens and young
adults in lifestyle-driven alternative media.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest in African adventure travel is the ``darting
safari,'' reports Outside magazine. This gives ``hunters'' the
chance to shoot straw-sized tranquilizer darts into their prey,
while wildlife specialists use the animals' down times to affix
identification tags or collect genetic samples.
</P>
<P>
   The animals are on private reserves in Botswana, Kenya, Zimbabwe
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like sticking a rhino in the butt from about 20
feet,'' said  &UR; Steve Camp &LR; , one of the satisfied ``hunters.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR;  has pointed the way to  &LR; www.mimeistry.org &LR; , Web
site of a ``Christian not-for-profit interdenominational
organization'' promoting the use of mime in religion.
</P>
<P>
   _ A shoulder to cry on:  &UR; Zillah Bahar &LR;  forwards a craigslist.com
notice from the founders of a ``web-based community to support
individuals who have recently gone through a startup that failed.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad goes on to say the site hopes to help individuals
``bounce back. ... The promotion and growth of the community and
content should naturally lead to an excellent book opportunity for
the web content writer and editor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Happy Passover. Commenting on the greeting card picturing ``a
seder plate for the new millennium,''  &UR; Dane Gleason &LR;  points out
that the millennium is a figment of the Christian calendar, not the
Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you hear a cell phone ringing, look for the bird: Signs
posted in San Francisco's Richmond District seek the return of
Peanut, a lost parrot who lived at 45th Avenue and Cabrillo Street.
``Imitates pagers and telephones (very realistically),'' says the
notice.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Alan Cumming &LR; , who will host the Webby Awards 2000 on May 11,
will hold award winners ``to the Webby's trademark five-word speech
limit,'' say organizers.
</P>
<P>
   _ A show of 310 photographs owned by  &UR; Elton John &LR;  will open at
the High Museum of Art in Atlanta _ John's American hometown _ in
November. Among the 2,500 photos owned by John, says artnet.com,
are ``substantial numbers'' by  &UR; Man Ray &LR; ,  &UR; Robert Mapplethorpe &LR; ,
 &UR; Dorothea Lange &LR;  and many more modern artists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote as he did because that's how people talked, and
that's what they understood. Ordinary people then were so much
smarter than they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Alicia Silverstone &LR; , who stars in a new movie based on
``Love's Labours Lost,'' telling W why she's a fan of William
Shakespeare's.
