<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
REPORTS CAUSE STOCK SLIDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disappointment with first-quarter reports from IBM and Intel
helped send stocks lower, ending the two-day surge after last
week's sell-off. The dot-com stocks that have fallen so sharply
recently were down again.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 87.16 points, or 2.3 percent, to
3,706.41, while the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 92.46
points, or 0.9 percent, to 10,674.96. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index was off 14.1 points, or nearly 1 percent, to
1,427.47.  &QL; 
APPLE TOPS PREDICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer posted earnings that handily beat analysts'
estimates for its second quarter. In contrast to the slowing sales
for many PC makers, Apple reported strong demand across its product
lines. Apple reported its results after the close of the market.
Amid a broad decline on Nasdaq, its shares closed at $121.125, down
$5.75. After-hours, they traded as high as $125.5625.  &QL; 
TRADE DEFICIT WIDENS
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit widened to a record $29.2 billion in
February from $27.4 billion during January, elevated by surging oil
prices and growing demand for imports, government figures showed.  &QL; 
CHRYSLER SALES UP
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler reported that sales climbed 17 percent in the
last three months, but it paid for that increase in the form of
lower profit margins on both Chrysler and Mercedes-Benz
automobiles. Net income rose 3 percent, to $1.62 billion, helped by
German tax reform. The results indicate that Daimler has yet to
overcome the unrelenting price competition in the American car
market.  &QL; 
LOWER-RISK CIGARETTE
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco said it would start promoting one of its
brands, Eclipse, as posing a potentially lower risk of cancer and
chronic bronchitis than traditional cigarettes, marking the first
time that a producer has made such advertising claims.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VISION FOR GREY
</P>
<P>
   Edward H. Meyer, 73, the chairman and chief executive of Grey
Advertising in New York, is making the first steps toward outlining
the future of the agency. In a reorganization described to Grey
employees, Meyer will become the head of a new holding company,
Grey Global Group. Based on the appointments at Grey Worldwide, the
new name for the core advertising agency, two executives seemed
poised for promotion. One is Steven Blamer, who will become
president for New York at Grey Worldwide. The other is Carolyn
Carter, who will become president for Europe, the Middle East and
Africa at Grey Worldwide.  &QL; 
CHASE MANHATTAN PROFIT GROWS
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan said its first-quarter profit rose 16 percent,
exceeding forecasts, as a surge in trading revenue and fees from
advising on mergers, plus gains on investments, lifted results.  &QL; 
AIRLINES POST RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   UAL and AMR, the parent companies of the world's two biggest
airlines, United and American, posted first-quarter results that
beat Wall Street expectations, while a strike threat hurt earnings
at US Airways, which posted a bigger-than-expected loss.  &QL; 
EARNINGS UP AT LUCENT
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, the world's leading phone-equipment maker,
said its second-quarter profit rose 41 percent, to 23 cents a
share, on higher sales of wireless and fiber-optic gear. The
company had warned in January that net income would be 21 to 23
cents a share when analysts were expecting 26 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
