<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFF-SCHEDULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATINGS AND REST FOR PLAYOFFS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Round 1 of the National Basketball Association playoffs will
give some teams three days of rest between games as part of a plan
to help Turner Sports get higher ratings than last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks-Toronto series, for instance, is expected to start
Sunday and resume Wednesday. It may continue the following Sunday,
April 30. If it lasts beyond three games, Game 4 might be played
Wednesday, May 3, and Game 5 possibly on Friday, May 5. So, a
five-game series might last from April 23 to May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current schedule, Game 1 of each of the eight
first-round series will be played Saturday or Sunday. The second
games will be staggered from Monday to Thursday. The Game 3s will
be played from April 28 to April 30, said Brian McIntyre, a
spokesman for the NBA. The Game 4s will be seen the following
Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. The Game 5s will be played May 4 or
May 5.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling change is part of Turner's current television
deal, but could not be implemented last season because the lockout
forced a tight playoff schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The extended first round will eliminate doubleheaders carried by
Turner's TNT and TBS networks in competition against each other.
The NBA felt it was counterproductive to have playoff games compete
against each other. Now, TBS will primarily carry Monday night
games, and TNT will show the doubleheaders, a plan that is expected
to yield higher ratings. No games in the playoffs on TNT, TBS or
NBC will air in competition against each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
