<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS &LR;      04-19 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS TO COACH BRUINS FOR ANOTHER YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harry Sinden had said he didn't like the Bruins' style
of play during Pat Burns' three years as coach. The
president/general manager also said it was going to take some
convincing while meeting with Burns that the team's fortunes and
style could change if he was kept on.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Sinden, Burns, and assistant GM Mike O'Connell
huddled again for another two-hour meeting, and Sinden came away so
confident that all involved are on the same page that he announced
Burns will be back to fulfill the fourth and final year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel that we have to change some things and Pat
agrees,'' said Sinden. ``He thinks we have to change some things
and we agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden acknowledged that he did need to be convinced a bit that
there wouldn't be a repeat of the Bruins' disastrous season
(24-39-19, out of playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think there was some of that,'' he said. ``If all of a
sudden someone would've felt that nothing had to change, I might
have felt different but that didn't come up at all. The three of us
recognized that there have to be a lot of things changed. Personnel
is a big question mark. (For example), if we get the personnel, how
are they going to play? I was pleased (with the discussions).''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he understood the speculation about Burns's job
security, which was rampant for much of the year and reached a
fever pitch on April 9, the Bruins' final regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny that there should have been speculation, there's
no doubt about it,'' he said. ``It started two-thirds of the way
through the season and just grew. We had to sit down and have these
conversations. Pat needed them as much as we did. We've got a plan,
we're going to made efforts to do what we didn't think we did last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call, Burns said he was thrilled to be
coming back, even though he was under stress due to his uncertain
job status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always worry about that,'' said Burns. ``I would've had to
live with it if it were that but I don't think that's what I
wanted. We've made New England our home. We love Boston, we love
the area, we love the Bruins and we didn't particularly want to go
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I just purchased a home in New Hampshire and we
love it up here and this is where we want to be. I felt part of
this team and I grew with a lot of these players and the players
grew with me. Last year's season was difficult for everyone and
some of the players stressed that they didn't want me to go and I
didn't want to leave because we really truly believe this team can
accomplish something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said communication from management to coaching staff
could be improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to be a little more accountable to each other
than we were this year and we talked about that,'' said Sinden.
``Sometimes losing begets a lot of things that would never surface
if you weren't losing. We didn't dwell much on what went on this
year. We spent 95 percent of our time talking about what has to be
done for next year. We really got into what we think, the three of
us, has to be done both in terms of the way we play and personnel.
These meetings were extensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he didn't think communication was so much a problem
as that there needs to be more of it. He admitted that he and
O'Connell had problems in the past but they were overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was something that had to be addressed,'' he said.
``When losses pile up, the speculation of me and Mike not getting
along or having a rift. Yeah, we had one rift a long time ago about
Sergei Samsonov and Harry sat us down like two children and gave us
a slap in the head and said, `You two have got to talk.' He was
completely right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lines of communication have to be open a lot more.
Mike can help me and I can help Mike and we can help the team. The
only disagreement we had is we didn't talk enough and we're going
to have to talk a lot more. That's something I'm definitely going
to work on and Mike's going to work on. It's not a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest issue was how the Bruins were going to get back to a
style that would bring success, not continual failure like last
year when the club was too passive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some things we do have to address and one of
those is the checking style of the team,'' said Burns. ``A couple
of years ago, this club finished probably with the best defensive
record it had ever had. I think we had some success that way and we
have to get back to that grinding style of Bruins' hockey. If we
don't do that, we're not going to have a whole lot of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the course of the year, we certainly tried some things
but I think I tried to stay with the same system with a different
type of team. If there's a responsibility, probably it's that. I
believe in good hard checking and there are two ways to play the
game _ the game with the puck and without the puck and our game
without the puck for us this year wasn't very good. That's
something we're definitely going to have to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties also talked about acquiring some sorely-needed
defensive help and will likely pick up some free agents in the
offseason. Add that to the core of the team coming into training
camp healthy and signed and Burns said he sees nothing but a
positive future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said. ``I'm very excited and happy about being
part of this team. If I would've had to go somewhere else, I
would've because I have to work but I definitely want to be part of
this black and gold team and build for the future of this club. I
always said I'd like to stay here forever and if I could, I would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel this club has something to prove and I think
this club will prove something. This is aside and now I'm just
dying to get back to work and enjoy the rest of the playoffs and
have that mind going about hockey again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
