u a BC-GOLDEN-STATUE-NYT &LR;      04-19 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-STATUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T GOLDEN BOY STAYS SUBURBAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)  By SHAILA DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard enough for a regular New Yorker to find the
perfect home. But if you're 24 feet tall and weigh 10 tons, it is
apparently impossible. Especially if you're picky.
</P>
<P>
   In January, AT&AMP;T Corp. offered to return Golden Boy, the
gold-leafed, Apollo-like statue that originally crowned the
company's lower Manhattan headquarters, to its native city. But two
weeks ago, the company decided to keep Golden Boy, a k a the
``Spirit of Communication,'' outside the company's operational
headquarters in Basking Ridge, N.J., where he has resided in
suburban bucolia for the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   John Heath, an AT&AMP;T spokesman, said it was a matter of giving
the statue proper placement. ``We were not able to find a suitable
home for him elsewhere,'' he said, ``given the history and
tradition that Golden Boy has.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parks Commissioner Henry J. Stern, who had eagerly welcomed
the offer, said he had been working to find a site that met AT&AMP;T's
approval when word came, two weeks ago, that the company had
changed its mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York welcomes Golden Boy,'' Stern said. ``We would put him
on a pedestal with the Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't, that is, for AT&AMP;T's request that the statue be
situated downtown, where large parks are scarce. The directors of
Washington Market Park, a two-acre park in TriBeCa, rejected the
offer of the statue because of its size.
</P>
<P>
   The city offered AT&AMP;T two other sites, Stern said. One was the
statue's original home atop 195 Broadway near Fulton Street, now
owned by Peter S. Kalikow, a developer. The second was 346 Broadway
near Worth Street, a city-owned office tower that was formerly the
home of New York Life Insurance Co. and once had a bronze eagle on
its roof. But Stern said he would prefer for the statue to be on
the ground, where people could enjoy it ``up close and personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he had been told by the director of the AT&AMP;T
Foundation, Tim McClimon, that AT&AMP;T was also reacting to longtime
employees who objected to moving the statue.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Heath confirmed that ``a handful'' of employees had sent e-mail
messages saying the statue should stay put, but would not elaborate
on AT&AMP;T's decision to keep the statue, except to say that the
company wanted to put it in a museum or park and was unable to find
one. Asked if AT&AMP;T would reconsider if an appropriate site were
found, Heath said: ``We've decided to leave it where it is. I think
that's the best answer to the question.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Golden Boy's official name has changed over the years,
reflecting the evolution of AT&AMP;T. Originally called ``Genius of
Telegraphy,'' the name was changed to ``Genius of Electricity''
after AT&AMP;T was forced to sell Western Union, and then later to
``Spirit of Communication.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by Evelyn Beatrice Longman, the first female
sculptor to be elected to the National Academy of Design. The
winged statue, which clutches a quiver of thunderbolts in one hand
and an electrical cable in the other, was cast at the Roman Bronze
Works in the Greenpoint section of Brooklyn and erected in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the statue had become a Lower Manhattan landmark, it
was removed in 1980, restored and installed in 1983 in the lobby of
AT&AMP;T's new headquarters on Madison Avenue and 55th Street. When
AT&AMP;T decamped again, to 32 Avenue of the Americas, there was no
room for Golden Boy so he was carted to New Jersey in 1992. ``He
goes where we go,'' the AT&AMP;T chairman, Charles L. Brown, explained
after one move.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he can't just commute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
