<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS: MICHIGAN AND VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABRAHAM HAS CASH EDGE
</P>
<P>
   With seven months before the election, Sen. Spencer Abraham, the
freshman Michigan Republican, has reached his fund-raising goals
for his re-election campaign, Federal Elections Commission figures
show.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham raised $1.68 million in the first three months of this
year, bringing his total to $6.4 million, according to a commission
report on Saturday. Abraham has $5 million on hand and his campaign
manager, Joe McMonigle, said Abraham hoped to raise $5 million
more.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic opponent, Rep. Debbie Stabenow, has raised $3.4
million since announcing her candidacy, $922,803 of which was
raised in the last three months, the report said. She has $2.1
million on hand. Kerin Polla, a spokeswoman for Stabenow, said her
goal is $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   DEMEANOR AT ISSUE IN VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James P. Moran, D-Va., has found himself in the midst of a
strange situation. On April 7, in the parking lot of an elementary
school and recreation center, Moran was approached by an 8-year-old
boy, who, the congressman said, tried to steal his car. Moran said
that boy told him that he had a gun, and that he would use it.
Moran ``apprehended'' the boy, he said, and took him into the
recreation center to have the authorities take ``appropriate
action.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boy's family says he only told Moran that he liked his
car and thought he was being kidnapped by the congressman. The
family said it might sue the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Moran's Republican challenger, Demaris H. Miller, has called for
Moran to apologize to the family. ``I question such a person's
ability to serve effectively in an institution such as Congress,''
Miller said of Moran. ``This boy is guilty of nothing more than
standing, while black.'' Moran has amassed more than $800,000 cash
on hand for his campaign; Miller has about $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH Temple, Texas
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE Fort Lee, N.J. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
