United Bronx Parents, Inc. in October, 1999. (Librado Romero/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- NY-WAX-MUSEUM-2 -- An
artist with Madame Tussaud's Wax Museum works on a model of Frank
Sinatra. The museum will open a New York exhibit hall near Times
Square next October. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- NY-WAX-MUSEUM -- Forget the
Royal Family or Jack the Ripper. When Madame Toussaud's Wax Museum
opens in New York, the waxed headliners will include, from left,
Whoppie Goldberg, Donald Trump, and Larry King. (The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- NY-PAVAROTTI -- Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York, left, joins in applause for Luciano
Pavarotti during a news conference, Wednesday. Pavarotti paid a
visit to City Hall to announce a concert at Madison Square Garden
this fall to celebrate the start of the tenor's 40th season of
performances. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- WARNER-IRELAND-FILM -- The
director Deborah Warner, foreground, with Fiona Shaw, who appears
in Warner's new film, ``Last September.'' Warner made her name as
something of a wunderkind of the British stage, directing
innovative interpretations of classics in London. Then she directed
opera; most recently, she has done experimental stagings of T.S.
Eliot's poem ``The Waste Land,'' and Bach's ``St. John's Passion.''
Moviemaking seemed like a logical next step. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) MONTPELIER, Vt. -- April 19, 2000 -- VT-GAY-MARRIAGE --
A bill that would create the closest thing in America to gay
marriage won final approval in the state Senate Wednesday. The bill
now returns to the state's House for consideration of changes to
the House-approved version. Vermont Sen. Mark McDonald in the
Senate chamber after the vote. (Paul O. Boisvert/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- JUMP-THEATER-REVIEW --
Aaron Wheeler-Kay, left, and Heather Pearl, in action in ``Do
Jump,'' at the New Victory Theater through April 30. The
production, with a succession of highly creative vignettes that
range from tap dancing to a power lunch by four acrobatic women who
mean business to clever audience participation in performance and
song, offers satisfying entertainment for all. (Sara Krulwich/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W --
There are three reasons to replace a kitchen or bathroom faucet: If
it is malfunctioning and cannot be repaired, if the finish is worn
and pitted or if you want to replace an old one with one that is
more stylish. If you have not shopped for fixtures in a while, you
may be surprised at the wide variety. Prices range from about $30
to more than $400, and models are available in metal or plastic
with an assortment of finishes. (Edward R. Lipinski/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TACUNA, Peru -- April 19, 2000 -- ANDES-TURMOIL-2 --
Alejandro Toledo, the opposition candidate who will face President
Alberto Fujimori of Peru in a run-off presidential election, during
a campaign appearance in March. With guerrillas and cocaine
production on the ascent in Colombia, a discredited court system in
Venezuela and an autocratic head of state in Peru trying to
maintain himself in power through electoral fraud, all of a sudden
it seems as if all the Andes are in tumult. (Ana Cecila
Gonzales-Vigil/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN --
Smart tools include Stanley's IntelliMeasure Ultrasonic Estimator,
left, and IntelliTape tape measure. None of these tools is going to
replace its old-fashioned counterpart in your toolbox, at least not
yet. However, each of the IntelliTools has a trick or two that
comes in handy for certain tasks under certain circumstances. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-GEEK-NOTES --
Allscripts, a company in Libertyville, Ill., is one of a growing
number trying to persuade doctors to dump handwritten prescriptions
in favor of those produced by a wireless, handheld computer.
Allscripts packages its TouchScript software in Hewlett-Packard
Jornada Series 600 handheld palmtop computers, which use the
Windows CE software system. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- MANHOLE-COVERS-2 --
Christopher Bailey, emerging from beneath the street, David
Horowitz and at work prowling for the perfect manhole. For two
years, the co-conspirators have roamed the streets of Manhattan,
making plaster casts of more than 70 manhole covers, which they
call urban fossils. Their wall of manhole cover casts will soon be
installed in the Capital Real Estate lobby on Morton Street.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- MANHOLE-COVERS-1 --
Christopher Bailey, left, and David Horowitz and their wall of
manhole cover casts, soon to be installed in the Capital Real
Estate lobby on Morton Street. The permanent 14-by-30 foot wall
will extend in an arc across the lobby and through the glass front.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PORTLAND, Ore. -- April 19, 2000 -- SNOUT-HOUSE -- The
``snout house,'' left, is out; porches and inviting front doors are
welcome. For the last eight months, Portland has made the snout
house - with its all garage, muscled front facade - illegal, going
to a frontier of design dictate where no other big American city
has gone before. (Shane Young/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LA GABARRA, Colombia -- April 19, 2000 -- ANDES-TURMOIL
-- Capt. Marceliano Costiblaco, right, and fellow members of the
Colombian National Police, at a guard post near the town in January
where they were protecting the population from paramilitary
organizations in the area. Not only in Colombia but it seems as if
all the Andean region is in tumult. Fractures in each society have
been exposed, and one Wall Street firm went so far as to warn its
clients last week that the region is becoming ``the Balkans of
Latin America.'' (Dominic Chavez/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 19, 2000 -- SCI-FIBER-CANCER --
Neither eating a low fat diet with abundant fiber, fruits, and
vegetables nor eating extra fiber in the form of wheat bran cereal
made any difference in colon cancer risk according to two large and
rigorous studies led by scientists at the National Cancer Institute
and University of Arizona. While some researchers say there still
is a chance that fiber will prevent colon cancer, others say it is
time stop telling people that it can. A consumer shopped for
cereals in a Manhattan supermarket in 1998. (Ruby Washington/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- SCOTUS-MIRANDA -- Miranda's
moment of truth, a richly symbolic test of whether this landmark of
the Warren Court will survive the much more conservative era of the
Rehnquist Court, arrived Wednesday morning in a crowded Supreme
Court with the justices armed for battle. The Miranda warning,
shown on a card carried by an agent for the Drug Enforcement
Adminstration. (Tony Cenicola for The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- April 19, 2000 -- CENSUS -- Kenneth
Prewitt, director of the U.S. Census, looks back to talk with
reporters while going over his notes before a news conference on
Wednesday. Sixty-five percent of American households have returned
their 2000 Census forms, tying the 1990 return rate with some forms
still coming in, Prewitt said Wednesday. (Justin Lane/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WILMINGTON, Del. -- April 19, 2000 -- COKE-MEETING --
Rev. Jesse Jackson, left, speaks with ``Ride for Corporate
Justice'' protest leader Larry Jones, following a Coca-Cola
shareholders meeting at the Wilmington, Del. Playhouse Wednesday,
April 19, 2000. A bus load of current and former Coke employees
travelled from Atlanta to attend the meeting. The activists claim
that the company discriminates against black workers. (Tim
Shaffer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- CHINA-ART-THEFTS -- A
carving from China of a Buddhist figure known as a bodhisattva.
Chinese experts say that based on photographs and data in the
catalog at the Minho Museum in Japan, they are certain that this
figure is one that was stolen from China in 1994. The Miho Museum
says it is looking into the allegation but believes the statue is
similar to the one stolen but not the same one. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-ROBOT-DOG -- On the
Chinese calendar, this is the Year of the Dragon, but a group of
toy and consumer electronics manufacturers would not be unhappy if
it turned out to be the year of the dog -- the interactive, robotic
dog, that is. The new mechanical palm puppies like Poo-Chi, from
Tiger Electronics, are less sophisticated, but also less expensive.
(Tony Cenicola/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEWBURGH, N.Y. -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS-3
-- At Mount St. Mary College, students like Lisa Malecki, can surf
the Net from anywhere on campus. Nearly four years ago, the college
installed a high-speed wireless network that covers the campus,
including parking lots, dormitories and everything in between.
Bruce Geisler, a professor, checked his email in the parking lot
while Daphne David, 21, used her laptop in a lounge. (Joyce
Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS-2 -- At
Mount St. Mary College, students can surf the Internet from
anywhere on campus. Nearly four years ago, the college installed a
high-speed wireless network that covers the campus, including
parking lots, dormitories and everything in between. The wireless
network consists of access points like the book-size Ethernet at
right, and adapter cards for laptops. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEWBURGH, N.Y. -- April 19, 2000 -- CIR-WIRELESS-CAMPUS
-- At Mount St. Mary College, students like Lisa Malecki, can surf
the Net from anywhere on campus. Nearly four years ago, the college
installed a high-speed wireless network that covers the campus,
including parking lots, dormitories and everything in between.
Every faculty member and nearly 100 students have laptops equipped
with transceivers and antennas to pick up and transfer Internet
signals. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- April 19, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY -- Attorney
General Janet Reno speaks with reporters Wednesday at the Justice
Department during her weekly briefing. Reno said that the United
States government might have to use force to take Elian Gonzalez
from his Miami relatives in order to reunite him with his father.
``There may come a time when there is no other alternative. But
we've got to do it in a careful, thoughtful way,'' Reno said at the
news conference. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM -- April 19, 2000 -- ISRAEL-PASSOVER -- The
ritual of burning bread, Hametz, for Passover, is distrupted by a
sudden gust of wind Wednesday. Their shopping and cleaning done,
Israeli families gathered at sundown Wednesday for the Passover
meal, a ritual feast that commemorates the exodus of the Jewish
people from ancient Egypt. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
