<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-T     04-19 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RECIPE, SAME OLD DISASTER FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ In the span of about 10 minutes, Rangers second
baseman Luis Alicea, his teammates and 39,294 fans ran the gamut of
emotions, ranging from incredible elation to sinking depression.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea watched Ivan Rodriguez hit a game-tying home run off New
York Yankees reliever Mariano Rivera in the ninth inning, ``I said,
`Now, we're going to win. I figured, we come back and shut them
down, then we'll come back in the 10th and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   That vision went poof a few minutes later when Yankees infielder
Clay Bellinger smashed a home run into the left-field bleachers.
``I thought... man, here we go again,'' Alicea said.
</P>
<P>
   He got that right. Bellinger's home run off reliever Jeff
Zimmerman in the 10th inning proved to be the latest fatal blow to
the Rangers against the Yankees, sending them crashing to a 5-4
loss at The Ballpark in Arlington yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Rangers' fifth consecutive to the Yankees this
season, three this week at The Ballpark coupled with two last week
at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Rangers were left fumbling for words in trying
to explain their futility against the defending world champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain,'' starter Rick Helling said. ``We seem
to lose every way imaginable to these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates, ``We should have won today if we make
the pitches we should make and get the hits we should get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't, and that _ more than any jinx, whammy or
voodoo _ explains why they haven't beaten the Yankees this year.
</P>
<P>
   The starting pitching has been good, but the bullpen has allowed
10 runs in 111/3 innings. And Rangers hitters were 6-for-45 with
runners in scoring position during the five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro said.
``We either overcome it and become a better team, or we don't. I
don't think they're that much a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   What truly hurts the Rangers is that twice this series they've
rallied against Rivera to tie the score and were unable to win
either time. Rivera had converted 27 consecutive save opportunities
going back to last year until Rodriguez hit his two-run homer in
the ninth inning yesterday to erase the Yankees' 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to their main guy,'' Alicea said, shaking his head.
``The guy's unhittable, and we got to him twice.''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't do any more good yesterday than it did in Monday's
5-4, 11-inning loss.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman had struck out three consecutive hitters when he got
ahead 1-2 on Bellinger with one out in the 10th. Zimmerman then
tried to throw a fastball low and away and instead threw it up and
in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge hits a two-run home run, and that's when you go
one-two-three,'' Oates said. ``We gave it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, who also allowed a home run to Bernie Williams in the
ninth, struck out the next two hitters, but the Rangers had no more
comebacks against Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about my line,'' Zimmerman said. ``Anytime
Mariano gives you two runs, it's a huge emotional lift for your
team. You've got to go out there and shut them down. ... That's
what eats at me.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run is Bellinger's second in 65 major-league at-bats.
This is a guy who spent 11 seasons in the minor leagues before
becoming a spare part for the Yankees last year. He was a pinch
runner/defensive replacement yesterday after Jim Leyritz walked
while pinch hitting for Wilson Delgado in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could only shake their heads at the wonder of it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Said Palmeiro, ``Just don't look back.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
