u s BC-UTENN-ATHLETES-NYT &LR;      04-19 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTENN-ATHLETES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE ACADEMIC ABUSES CITED BY PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERI BOSTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A review of the academic records of 39 football players and
other athletes at the University of Tennessee found a pattern of
questionable practices, including many juniors and seniors who
never declared a major, many altered grades and a bunching of
athletes in the urban studies department, according to an English
professor who is a longtime critic of the athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Linda Bensel-Meyers, plans to release copies of
the records Thursday. She said Wednesday that the athletic
department ``consciously manipulates the athletes' programs of
study to keep them eligible for sports participation with little
regard for a student's progress in a degree program.''
</P>
<P>
   The records, which mainly involve football players and did not
include the students' names, appear to show a number of academic
abuses. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifteen of the 39 student-athletes were juniors or seniors who
had not yet declared a major. Most students do so during their
sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 39 students had accumulated a total of 105 grade changes.
Some changes involved ``incompletes'' that eventually became F's or
D's, not uncommon on many campuses, but many other changes involved
Fs that became much higher grades, including As.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twenty of the 39 students had been on academic review at least
twice. Students are placed on academic review when their
grade-point average falls below a C, and nonathletes are generally
allowed only one semester on academic review before they are
subject to serious penalties. Student-athletes at Tennessee are
exempt from those rules because of the demands on their time, and
may remain on academic review for many semesters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the 18 athletes who had declared a major, 11, or 61
percent, were in urban studies.
</P>
<P>
   Such a concentration of students in one major suggests that it
is a relatively easy course of study and that the faculty members
may be more understanding of athletes with severe demands on their
time, Bensel-Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, her review showed that five of the athletes who had
not declared a major were ultimately dismissed from the university
for academic reasons, Bensel-Meyers said. Four of the five were
dismissed after they had used up their athletic eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome, along with much of the other findings in her
review, shows that the university works hard to find ways to keep
athletes eligible, but that many do not make appropriate academic
progress, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the core of the problem here,'' she said. ``But no one
is willing to touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers was among several current and former professors
and administrators at Tennessee who said publicly last September
that tutors had written papers and done school work for at least
five football players. The university began an investigation into
the allegations, which included the charge that midlevel officials
in the athletic department had tried to cover up instances of
plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   The university ultimately determined that violations of National
Collegiate Athletic Association rules had not occurred, and the
NCAA declined to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Burton English, an economics professor who was chairman of a
faculty panel that looked into the allegations, said on Tuesday
that no major problems had been found in the tutoring program. But
he did say, at a meeting of the executive meeting of the Tennessee
faculty senate in Knoxville, that greater oversight was needed of
the tutoring of athletes. Among his panel's recommendations were
barring tutors from typing papers for athletes and closer faculty
monitoring of many tutorial services, such as note-taking for
athletes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In response, Bensel-Meyers, who still believes that academic
fraud occurred at Tennessee, presented her review of athletes'
academic records to the faculty senate's executive committee on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers said she had collected information from the
records of all 22 starters on the 1999 football team and of many
other athletes who entered the university in 1995; the sample
included some swimmers and track athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the university provost's office seeking comment were
not returned. But English also said of Bensel-Meyers' allegations
and her review of students' records, ``We believe we have addressed
her concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers disagreed. ``There's a conflict when athletics
oversees academic tutoring or counseling,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
