<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND MRS. CLINTON ARGUE ON DONATIONS AND ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON, N.Y. _ Seeking to draw links between the candidates
and the donations they receive, the Clinton and Giuliani Senate
campaigns Wednesday accused each other of accepting soft-money
contributions from questionable donors.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton called on the Giuliani campaign to return
a $100,000 donation that was made to a soft-money committee
supporting his candidacy by a company that she referred to as ``No.
1 polluter in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign officials, meanwhile, questioned how a
soft-money committee supporting Clinton could have accepted a
$22,000 check from a Miami businesswoman who investigators said
once solicited a large Democratic campaign contribution from a man
who later pleaded guilty to smuggling heroin into the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign returned that contribution, from Vivian
Mannerud, on Tuesday. ``Some information came to my campaign's
attention and we immediately returned a donation that was
questionable,'' Clinton said, ``and I would ask the mayor if he
intends to keep $100,000 from the No. 1 polluter in America.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to a $100,000 check made to a soft-money
committee supporting Giuliani, the Giuliani Victory Committee, by
Renco Group, a New York company that owns a Utah company that
federal officials had identified as the top toxic chemical dumper
in the nation. The donation was then transferred to the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, which is also supporting
Giuliani's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not say whether the check would be returned. ``They
haven't given a donation to my campaign,'' he said, emphasizing
that the money was going to the senatorial committee.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Giuliani campaign questioned how the Clinton
campaign could have accepted a soft-money contribution from
Mannerud. Congressional investigators found that in 1995, Mannerud
solicited a $20,000 contribution to the Democratic National
Committee from Jorge Cabrera, who later pleaded guilty to smuggling
6,000 pounds of heroin into the country. The contribution was
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign officials also noted that the Renco Group had
also donated to Democrats and quickly fired off a list of Clinton's
donors they found questionable, from Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, the
hip-hop impresario facing gun charges in New York, to Christie
Hefner, the chief executive of Playboy Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's communications director, Howard Wolfson, called the
list a distraction. ``The issue is that the single biggest
contributor to Rudy Giuliani is the largest polluter in America,''
he said. ``That speaks for itself.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The barbs that were traded over campaign contributions
threatened to overshadow Clinton's main theme of the day, the
environment, and the barbs the candidates traded over that.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with environmentalists in Huntington on Wednesday
at Coindre Hall, a former Gold Coast mansion that is now a park
overlooking Long Island Sound, Clinton cited a judge's 1999
decision holding New York City responsible for dumping pollutants
from its sewage plants into the sound, the East River and Jamaica
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly hope that the mayor and the city would do
what is necessary to end the illegal dumping in the sound and take
the steps that are required to protect the watershed,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that if she won a seat in the Senate she would work to
pass legislation to spearhead a cleanup of the sound.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Nolan, a spokeswoman for the Giuliani campaign,
retorted in a statement, ``Maybe Mrs. Clinton will blame the vast
right-wing conspiracy for killing the lobsters in Long Island
Sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign, in turn, accused Clinton of representing
Tyson Foods, the Arkansas chicken company that was accused of
polluting neighboring bodies of water with its chicken waste.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laughed when she was told of the accusation, saying that
while her old firm, the Rose Law Firm, represented Tyson Foods, she
personally did not.
</P>
</TEXT>
