u a BC-NY-WAX-MUSEUM-ART-2TA     04-19 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WAX-MUSEUM-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING TO TIMES SQUARE: MADAME TUSSAUD'S WAX MENAGERIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT24 and 25 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in 1996, the issue wasn't all that complicated.
If Madame Tussaud's of London brought its legendary wax museum to
the Big Apple, exactly what would New Yorkers want to see?
</P>
<P>
   But Manhattan focus groups provided answers that were
underwhelming at best, said Andrew Tansley, the English director of
the Tussaud's Group Ltd. Tansley would observe through a one-way
mirror as city residents mumbled politely about seeing a mix of
urban icons, historic figures, rock stars, politicians and sports
legends. But few city residents in the focus groups had actually
been to Tussaud's, only half had ever heard of it, and many said
that the American wax museums they had seen were awfully cheesy.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tansley would open a door and bring in Arnold
Schwarzenegger.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it wasn't really Arnold. It was a life-size Tussaud wax
sculpture dressed in a tight white T-shirt and slacks. It had cost
$50,000 and had taken six months to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were gob-smacked by the uncanny likeness, and the
reaction was extraordinary,'' Tansley recalled. ``They said things
like, `Look at the tiny veins,' and, `Those eyes are really
creepy.' And that's exactly the tremendous sense of excitement
we're aiming to bring to New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, very much like the excitement Tansley will try to create
next week: at a press conference outside Tussaud's in Times Square,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will present to the world the $50,000 wax,
um, dummy for which he posed. (No, Hillary Rodham Clinton, his
opponent in the U.S. Senate race, is not yet ready for her close-up
with a wax sculptor.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This is the beginning of a $2.5 million publicity blitz for
Madame Tussaud's New York. (In England, the surname is generally
pronounced tuh-SAWDZ, but Francophiles pronounce it to rhyme with
modes.)
</P>
<P>
   The new Tussaud's museum intends to bring the English
institution's fixation with fame to the new Times Square,
showcasing the company's patented high-camp amalgam of breathtaking
portrait artistry, creepy glitz and what can only be called a jolly
fascination with gruesome spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story $50 million wax palace is under construction at
234 W. 42nd St., between Seventh and Eighth Avenues, behind the
landmark facade of the old Harris Theater &UR; .  &LR; Tussaud's is aiming
for an opening date in October.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nearly 200 planned wax-prone notables in the new
museum will be a Who's Who of celebrities appearing only in the New
York Tussaud's. They include Woody Allen, Maya Angelou, Josephine
Baker, Katie Couric, Joe DiMaggio, Amelia Earhart, Henry Ford, Bill
Gates, Wayne Gretzky, Ernest Hemingway, Matt Lauer, Annie
Leibovitz, Mickey Mantle, Joe Namath, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis,
Yoko Ono, Dorothy Parker, Gov. George Pataki, Gen. Colin Powell,
Christopher Reeve, Sitting Bull, Liz Smith, Donald Trump and Andy
Warhol.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair guess that few focus groups floated the names of
Sitting Bull or Dorothy Parker, and Andy Warhol's 15 minutes have
long since slipped through the glass. But Tussaud's generally goes
for a certain level of renown, ``those who have shaped history of
one sort or another,'' said Tansley _ a conviction that perhaps
explains why the Spice Girls will be present and accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the New York Tussaud's will also offer crowd-pleasing
wax images that appear in the London Tussaud's, including Diana,
Princess of Wales; the Beatles, Mick Jagger, Larry King, Nelson
Mandela, the Dalai Lama and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Tussaud's Group, which attracts revenues
estimated at $55 million a year, will not reveal its sensations
cheaply. Ticket prices will range from $12.75 to $19.95; visitors
are expected to stay an average of two hours.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After customers are beamed up to the top floor in two exterior
glass-walled elevators, they will be welcomed to Tussaud's by wax
sculptures grouped in a fantasy ``Opening Night Party'' for a
mythical Broadway show. Downstairs, a summit of world leaders will
be arrayed in a United Nations-ish room called the Gallery. An
adjacent exhibition, ``Behind the Scenes,'' will feature a
multimedia description of the monthslong creation of a likeness of
the television weatherman Al Roker.
</P>
<P>
   And for an extra fee, in an attraction called ``It Happened in
New York,'' visitors under a 40-foot dome will be transported on a
virtual hansom-cab ride to a series of iconic events in New York's
history, including Elvis Presley's first appearance on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show'' and the Broadway ticker-tape parade for the Apollo
11 moon voyagers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tony Peluso, Tussaud's American director, said that the New York
museum would not be a replica of the ones in London, Amsterdam or
Las Vegas. ``We don't want to be the same in any city, anywhere in
the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the grander ambition of Tussaud's is to import the
implacably weird spirit of the original. For all its strangeness,
the London Tussaud's has acquired a certain brummagem elegance
because of its relationship with the celebrities who pose for
portraits, including the Royals (every reigning British monarch
back to George III has sat for a museum sculptor). ``We hope to
create a similar cachet and tradition in New York City,'' Tansley
said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tussaud's is going for traffic as well: 6,000 to 7,000 people on
peak days, or 1.8 million visitors a year. But it may prove
difficult to transplant one of London's most popular tourist
attractions (it draws 2.7 million visitors a year) to a city where
it must compete with everything from Broadway shows to the Statue
of Liberty and the new Rose Center planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   Another daunting task for Tussaud's is ``to overcome the
negative association that Americans have with the poor-quality wax
museums here,'' said Jim Garber, an independent Los Angeles-based
consultant for entertainment attractions that include Disney World,
Universal Studios and the Six Flags amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tussaud name isn't known in the United States,'' Garber
said, ``and it will be a challenge to educate Americans about what
they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tussaud's strengths are that ``their likenesses are done very
well, they have a legacy going back to Madame Tussaud, and they
encourage visitors to go right up to the wax figures and have their
pictures taken with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, with its new 49-year lease with a 50-year extension,
Tussaud's is bullish on America, and perhaps not without reason.
Since the 18th century, Tussaud's has made much of the artistry of
its wax images, created using the technique of the founding diva,
Madame Tussaud.
</P>
<P>
   Its likenesses are prepared by artisans who take 250 intricate
measurements of celebrities' body proportions and create the
sculptures from visual observation and photographic analysis. Each
face is built up from a 30-piece plaster mold, which is filled with
wax, then painted. The acrylic eyes are positioned from inside the
mask, and hair is inserted strand by strand.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Celebrities have offered vast sums for their own Tussaud's
portraits; such requests are rejected. Many celebrities, or
would-be celebrities, have volunteered themselves for waxdom, only
to be rejected by Tussaud's. The museum itself has been turned down
_ it won't say by whom _ most frequently by movie stars working too
hard on film locations to spare the three hours for a proper
sitting. Others try to stiff-arm the Tussaud's sculptors until they
have lost a few more pounds. Unlike other such museums, Tussaud's
prefers subjects to pose, although it has created sculptures from
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Marie Tussaud was sprung from imminent guillotining in
revolutionary Paris so she could create death masks of aristocrats,
including Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing the Napoleonic wars to England in 1802, she toured her
portrait museum on wagons throughout Britain for 33 years before
establishing a permanent London museum in 1835. Tussaud's has
occupied its current location near the Baker Street subway station
for 116 years.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers will be spared the full gory London experience:
victims being garroted in a torture chamber, Marat being knifed in
his bath, Joan of Arc being burned at the stake, and the figure of
Vlad the Impaler with a victim's bloody head on a stake. Indeed,
the very phrase ``chamber of horrors'' was coined to describe the
grisly sights in Tussaud's basement, and the phrase has been
appropriated by Tussaud's ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned, though: in the new museum, there will be an
exhibition called ``Madame Tussaud's Story.'' It will show her
hobnobbing with Benjamin Franklin, Napoleon and Josephine, all of
whom she sculpted. And, as might be expected, customers will be
offered tableaux of the guillotine, and Madame hunting through
piles of bloody chopped-off heads so she can create her legendary
death masks, some of which will be on view.
</P>
<P>
   As for the tableaux depicting Madame Tussaud rising above
historical gore, Tansley said: ``This is not something that we made
up; this is actually what happened to the real woman who founded
our company. She was put in the Bastille and had her head shaved in
preparation to having her head chopped off.'' Spared thanks to her
experience as a sculptor, she died in London in 1850 at the age of
89.
</P>
<P>
   But those New Yorkers with more delicate constitutions will be
alerted. Tansley said that there would be a large sign outside the
guillotine room that will warn the squeamish, so, he said
helpfully, ``those who have no lust for blood can bypass this
completely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
