<SLUG> BC-GAYMARRIAGE-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY MARRIAGE BALLOT PETITION FAILING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CHRISTOPHER HEREDIA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Two California brothers' uphill battle to
qualify a gay marriage ballot measure for the November general
election ballot is expected to fail Thursday, falling hundreds of
thousands of signatures short.
<P>
   And while that's no surprise after the passage of Proposition
22, which banned gay marriage in the state, many gay rights
advocates worry that legislative support for less sweeping domestic
partners bills may suffer because of the proposition's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have an impact,'' said Eric Astacaan, a lobbyist with
the gay rights advocacy group, California Alliance for Pride and
Equality. ``That's why we're trying to lobby members of the
Legislature to tell them that while people voted for Proposition
22, that was about marriage and this is about domestic partnership.
Even the pro-22 campaign pointed out that gay and lesbian
relationships should have equal protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, others are looking enviously upon Vermont where the
Senate Wednesday passed a bill creating ``civil unions,'' a legal
structure parallel to marriage for gay and lesbian couples.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the political spectrum in California, the
conservative Committee on Moral Concerns is working hard in
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Committee ... opposes any steps toward equalizing domestic
partnership with marriage,'' said the group's executive director
Art Croney. ``It's misplaced compassion to affirm the most
dangerous lifestyle in America, which is the gay lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Legislature, some California lawmakers are seeking
incremental rights for gay partners. There are five domestic
partner bills covering everything from making medical decisions in
an emergency to inheriting property to making funeral arrangements
to the right to sue for wrongful death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step-by-step quest for liberty,'' said openly lesbian
Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco, who last year
authored a bill establishing a domestic partner registry for both
gay and straight couples whose members are 62 years of age or
older.
</P>
<P>
   The law also granted health benefits to the domestic partners of
state workers and hospital visitation rights to all registrants.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Migden has introduced a bill that would grant
domestic partners the right to consent to have his or her partner's
organs donated in the event of death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Knight Initiative's passage, Migden said she thinks
a majority of her colleagues in the Legislature will support the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think gay marriage is timely,'' Migden said. ``These
bills have to do with entirely different subject matter. They're
very mundane and straightforward, basic parity issues which are
largely uncontroversial.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assembly Minority Leader Scott Baugh, R-Huntington Beach,
said he can't predict the outcome. He hasn't studied the bills, but
differed with Migden's assesment.
</P>
<P>
   He said his general philosophy is to not grant ``special
privileges'' to gays.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of Proposition 22, he said, ``may impact the
governor's decision, but not votes in the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Majority Leader Kevin Shelley, D-San Francisco, said
the governor's opposition to Proposition 22 and his nod last year
to the domestic partner registry may be an indication of his
support for the domestic partner bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not marriage,'' Shelley said. ``That's a significant
stretch. What Proposition 22 did was show that a majority of
Californians are not comfortable with gay marriage. What the polls
indicate is that they are supportive of strengthening domestic
partner rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition drive to qualify a gay marriage initiative hasn't
gotten much publicity or received the funds spent by the
Proposition 22 campaign, an estimated $6 million. It's been largely
Internet-driven and without much door-to-door campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Henning a single, 35-year-old San Francisco teacher, who
began the petition drive with his brother last year, conceded it's
a ``formidable effort'' to get the measure on the ballot, but
that's not stopping him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying it's the wrong timing, but ...
we're not trying to be pragmatic,'' Henning said. ``If we're not
successful this time, we'll be back again. This issue is very much
in the forefront of the minds of gay and lesbian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Henning calls domestic partnership ``a poor second cousin to
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   About a week ago, his group, Californians for Same Sex Marriage,
had gathered nearly 100,000 of the 670,000 signatures needed. They
have until Thursday to complete their effort.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco's Castro District one recent afternoon, some
said the petition drive is an exercise in futility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a worthy endeavor,'' said Levi Stolove, a 22-year-old
teen center coordinator from San Francisco, ``but I think a lot of
work needs to be done to convince people that if heterosexuals can
get married, then gays should be able to as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
