<HEADLINE>
BOMBING SUSPECT ORDERS LAWYERS NOT TO ARGUE AGAINST DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A defendant in the bombing of a U.S. Embassy in
Africa has ordered his lawyers not to go to Washington next week to
argue against the death penalty with Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Mohamed Rashed Daoud al-`Owhali, has been charged
with helping carry out the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya in
August 1998. The government has described al-`Owhali as a would-be
suicide bomber who wanted to die in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The government charges that al-`Owhali rode as a passenger in
the truck that carried the bomb to the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, and
that he later admitted to investigators that the bombing was
intended to be a ``martyrdom operation in which he did not expect
to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-`Owhali's lawyers had been planning to appear before a
committee of Justice Department lawyers in Washington, in hopes of
persuading Attorney General Janet Reno not to seek al-`Owhali's
execution, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Al-`Owhali's request that his defense lawyers forgo the meeting
apparently so troubled them that they went before Judge Leonard B.
Sand of U.S. District Court in Manhattan last Friday, seeking
guidance on how to reconcile their ethical duties with their
client's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really primarily at a loss to know what our
obligations were,'' one lawyer, David I. Bruck, said in court,
explaining that al-`Owhali's request appeared to conflict with
their duty to represent his interests zealously.
</P>
<P>
   Sand, after receiving assurances that al-`Owhali was of sound
mind, said the request could be followed.
</P>
<P>
   Al-`Owhali, who has pleaded not guilty, is one of three
defendants in custody who could face the death penalty for their
roles in the attacks on the embassies in Kenya and in Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania. The two attacks killed more than 200 people and
wounded thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Under Justice Department rules, the death penalty decision
begins with local government prosecutors, in this case the office
of U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White in Manhattan. She and prosecutors on
her staff met last month with al-`Owhali's defense team, after
which she indicated that she would seek the death penalty. White
then sought formal permission from Reno, who has the final say.
</P>
<P>
   But after the defense lawyers were invited to appear before
Reno's staff, al-`Owhali told them not go, two of his lawyers told
Sand last week. The lawyers' attendance is not mandatory, and Reno
can act without hearing from them.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, Bruck and Leonard F. Joy, the federal defender for
New York, initially appeared before the judge in a closed hearing,
out of the presence of prosecutors and the public. Al-`Owhali was
also present.
</P>
<P>
   Such private meetings are sometimes held when the defense has a
particular issue to raise that could reveal defense strategies.
Later, a transcript was filed publicly.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Joy explained that the lawyers had planned to meet
with Justice Department officials to argue against the death
penalty, but said al-`Owhali ``has informed us that he does not
wish us to go down to that meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruck then explained the ethical quandary. ``We felt on the one
hand that we did not want to do something contrary to the wishes of
our client,'' he said. ``On the other, we are officers of the
court, and we felt that this is an integral part of the process in
a matter in which not only the defendant and the government, but
the court and the public as a whole has a very substantial
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruck told the judge that the defense lawyers had made an
earlier written submission to the government opposing capital
punishment, a document that has not been withdrawn. He said
al-`Owhali had told his lawyers why he did not want them to go to
the meeting, but he did not reveal the reasons in court. Al-`Owhali
did not speak at the hearing, the transcript shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sand asked, ``Is there any doubt in your mind as to your
client's mental capacity or the rationality of his instructions to
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, your honor,'' Bruck said.
</P>
<P>
   Sand indicated that he saw no problem in the lawyers' following
their client's request. ``The question of whether the government
will seek the death penalty is one with respect to which the
defendant has a very great interest,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   A legal ethics expert, Stephen Gillers, professor of law at New
York University, said the lawyers acted ``entirely appropriately in
asking the judge to approve their decision to comply with their
client's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're dealing with gray areas,'' Gillers said, ``and the
gray areas involve death as one of the possibilities, you don't
want to guess wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
