<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL SKINNER IS NEW CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD FOR
TRANSPORTATION.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Transportation.com, an Overland Park, Kan.,
Internet company for shippers and the trucking industry, has named
former U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner as chairman
of its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who also served as chief of staff during the Bush
administration, said he agreed to work with Transportation.com
because technology is on the verge of changing the way freight is
moved, both in the United States and globally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was comfortable they had a good business plan,'' Skinner
said, ``and they thought I could bring some real value.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner said he was introduced to the Overland Park company by
EnerTech Capital Partners, one of the three firms that invested $30
million in the start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation.com is an online marketplace for shippers and
trucking firms. The company plans to match truckers with available
loads; provide tracking, maintenance and other information; and
help shippers cut prices. It also will offer an auction service for
used equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow Corp. and two venture capital firms invested $30 million
to form Transportation.com earlier this year. About a dozen
customers are testing the system, which is expected to be launched
late this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation.com will give small and medium-size businesses
``the same type of technology and services available to companies
like General Electric and General Motors,'' Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small and medium-size company has traditionally done its
own shipping, and it probably hasn't been the most efficient way to
do it,'' Skinner said. ``Right now, with business going globally
and just-in-time shipping requirements, the need for efficiency is
greater than it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   James D. Ritchie, chief executive of Transportation.com, said he
was ``surprised and enthused'' when Skinner agreed to take the
chairman's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I think I can add value to your company. If you're
just looking for a spokesmodel, I'm not your guy,' '' Ritchie said.
``He's taking a hard look at a lot of things, asking, `How do you
really change the industry?' He's looking far out into the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   As secretary of transportation in the Bush administration,
Skinner oversaw a budget of $30 billion and 105,000 employees.
Later he served as president of Commonwealth Edison.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an individual of Sam Skinner's background to step out and
join the e-revolution going on in the transportation industry is
important for the industry as a whole,'' said Ting Piper, program
manager for e-logistics services with IDC, an Internet market
research company based in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Skinner sits on several corporate boards and is a
lawyer and co-chairman of Hopkins &AMP; Sutter, a Chicago law firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
