<HEADLINE>
TWA BLAMES LARGER QUARTERLY LOSS IN PART ON SOARING FUEL PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Trans World Airlines on Wednesday said higher
fuel prices contributed to a larger loss for the first quarter of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seventh consecutive quarterly operating loss for the
St. Louis-based airline.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's operating loss was $103.92 million for the three months
that ended March 31, compared with a $37.59 million loss in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, TWA executives said that the airline's financial
results began improving in March and that the turnaround was
expected to continue through the second quarter. One industry
analyst said that could lead to a better performance for the
struggling airline in the spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, TWA's net loss was $76.12 million, or
$1.16 a share, on $809 million in revenue. During the same time
last year, TWA lost $21.56 million, or 42 cents a share, on $764.59
million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's fuel costs in the first quarter nearly doubled compared
with the same period last year, said William F. Compton, TWA's
president and chief executive officer. In addition, the company had
higher aircraft leasing expenses and labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, which operates its main jet overhaul base at Kansas
City International Airport, also experienced lighter passenger
traffic in January because of year 2000 concerns, Compton said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the quarterly loss would have been greater if
TWA had not begun replacing its older planes with a newer fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fuel costs would have been $29 million higher if we had
not started to renew the fleet in 1996 and accelerated (the
renewal) in 1999,'' Compton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that TWA was beginning to see productivity improvements
as its work force gradually continued to shrink through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   TWA also started seeing revenue improvement in March, which has
continued into this month, Compton noted. Regional jet service,
recently introduced into TWA's route structure, has begun to show
benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said TWA's first quarter was in line with
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't stunningly good, but it wasn't exceedingly bad,''
said David W. Levine, contributing editor to PlaneBusiness, an
electronic financial newsletter on the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said TWA's yield, an industry measure of financial
performance, seemed to have improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barring a substantial surprise, TWA could post a modest profit
in the second and third quarters,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's on-time performance, which has been the best among the
major carriers for most of the past year, also should begin to draw
more business travelers, Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a lag time, but we're getting close to where
people will start to take notice,'' he said. ``If they continue to
put up those on-time numbers, it will help.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA was unchanged at 1 7/8 in trading Wednesday on the American
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
