<HEADER>
A1874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     04-19 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' START BRINGS TO MIND THE WONDERS OF '98 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Even to the New York Yankees who experienced
it, the 1998 season is mythic in their minds. Unbelievable, they
say of winning 114 games during the regular season. Unreal, never
to be repeated. They might as well be talking about feats of
Hercules.
</P>
<P>
   They have played just 14 games in this season, but the plot
lines have an uncanny similarity to 1998, as if genes were
extracted from that team and injected into the first evolving cells
of these Yankees. Victories are drawn from the most remote parts of
this roster, just as in '98: Lance Johnson made a rare start
Wednesday and pitched in with four hits and two stolen bases, and
Clay Bellinger hit a tiebreaking home run in the top of the 10th
inning as the Yankees edged the Texas Rangers, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees win games that maybe they should not win.
Wednesday, Mariano Rivera blew his first save chance since July 16,
1999, surrendering a two-run homer in the ninth inning to Ivan
Rodriguez, and Bellinger bailed him out the very next inning. Most
notably, these Yankees, like the '98 Yankees, do not lose. They
have won eight consecutive games, their longest winning streak
since 1998, and they are 11-3 over all, the best record in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   The '98 Yankees had superlative starting pitching, and the
Yankees' rotation is evolving into a formidable force this year.
Orlando Hernandez has been dominant, David Cone is beginning to
pitch effectively again, and Wednesday, Roger Clemens had his first
strong outing, allowing two runs in the first seven innings before
a strained back forced him out of the game at the outset of the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was great,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, who does
not believe Clemens' injury will prevent him from making his next
scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
   Torre wanted to see Clemens throw more strikes Wednesday, get
ahead in the ball-strike count and exploit hitters. Clemens _ who
had been annoyed by suggestions that he was being tentative with
his fastball _ attacked the Rangers with his signature pitch
Wednesday. He fired strikes on the first pitch against 14 of the
first 18 batters he faced; his first 11 pitches were fastballs,
thrown 91 to 94 mph.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy wind blew through this area Wednesday afternoon, and
Clemens began feeling stiff in the fifth inning, with the Yankees
ahead, 1-0. Johnson scored that first run and, after the Rangers
tied the score in the bottom of the sixth, he led off the seventh
with a double into the right-field corner. When the Rangers' Rick
Helling forgot to check Johnson at second, Johnson stole third and
scored on a groundout. In the eighth, Jorge Posada doubled and
swiped third base before Johnson singled him home. The Yankees led,
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens threw only 85 pitches in the first seven innings but, as
he warmed up for the eighth, Torre could see him struggling to get
loose. Clemens fell behind, two balls and no strikes, against the
leadoff batter, Chad Curtis. Torre went to the mound and relieved
Clemens, patting him on the back as he departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was fine, and I told him that,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed 12 walks in his first 18 innings this season, but
against the Rangers, Clemens permitted just one walk in the first
seven innings. ``That's the Roger Clemens we know,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson relieved Clemens and surrendered a run-scoring
double before Torre called for Rivera with one out in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   With Rafael Palmeiro was coming to bat, Torre would usually use
the left-hander Mike Stanton. But Palmeiro had two hits in two
at-bats against Stanton this season, a double and a homer. Knowing
that the Yankees have Thursday off, Torre called on Rivera and
asked him to get the last five outs.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera maintained the lead into the ninth inning, when Bernie
Williams increased the advantage to 4-2 with a remarkable home run.
Williams reached far over the plate, his weight shifted to his
front foot, and he drove a low pitch to straightaway center field,
over the wall. When Williams returned to the dugout, the coach Don
Zimmer squeezed Williams' left biceps and asked how in the heck he
could have hit that particular pitch so far.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera got two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning,
sandwiched around a double by Ruben Mateo. Rodriguez, the Rangers'
All-Star catcher, was inserted into the game as a pinch-hitter.
Rivera planned to throw him a fastball inside, and catcher Posada
set his target. Inside.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera's darting fastball broke over the outside corner
instead; Rodriguez leaned and drove the ball down the right-field
line. Paul O'Neill raced toward the corner, toward the foul pole,
looked up and saw the ball land just inside the yellow screen.
Rivera barely reacted, his vacuous stare never changing, even
though it was the first time he failed to convert a save chance in
nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should've won in the ninth,'' he said later, ``but I blew
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, 4-4, after nine. In 1998, the Yankees
expected to win in these situations, assumed they were going to
win. As they returned to the dugout Wednesday, Bellinger said
later, there was no sense of disappointment over Rivera's failure.
Somebody said aloud that it was time to get a run; another player
suggested two runs. Business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman threw a high fastball to Bellinger, and Bellinger
bashed it, breaking into a home run trot almost immediately as he
watched the ball depart. His teammates burst from the dugout to
greet him. Yankees 5, Rangers 4.
</P>
<P>
   Torre wanted Rivera to get another chance, hold another lead _
and Stanton had been struggling _ and so the closer pitched the
bottom of the 10th inning. His outing of two and two-thirds innings
was his longest in almost four years.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was shaking hands with teammates, observing another
victory, another sweep, and the Yankees headed for Toronto, looking
to build on their winning streak.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
