<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY'S-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR RAISES QUESTIONS ON SOTHEBY'S BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ronald Baron, the New York money manager whose funds
are the largest shareholders in Sotheby's Holdings Inc., has
questioned the auction house board's independence in a filing with
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Baron funds have invested about $500 million in Sotheby's,
which is a target of a federal antitrust investigation, and the
filing may signal an effort by Baron to elect new directors to the
board, now dominated by people aligned with Sotheby's former
chairman, A. Alfred Taubman.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman resigned from the board Feb. 21 as a result of the
investigation, which people involved in the case say has focused in
part on him. He has denied wrongdoing. Taubman retains voting
control of Sotheby's through ownership of a majority of the Class B
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's Antitrust Division is looking into
whether Sotheby's and its rival auction house, Christie's,
conspired in 1992 and 1995 to fix commissions charged to buyers and
sellers and engaged in other collusion. Christie's has said it is
cooperating with the inquiry, and Sotheby's has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about the independence of Sotheby's board were in
a filing by Baron with the Securities and Exchange Commission that
became public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The filing said Baron had hired an investment banker,
Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co., to give advice on the Sotheby's holdings
of his four funds. It did not mention an intention to sell, and
Baron has described himself as a passive, long-term investor in
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing, Baron has had conversations with the
management and directors at Sotheby's that involved the board's
``composition and independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The filing said Baron supported Sotheby's executive officers but
opened the possibility that he would seek to elect his own
directors,
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's is to expand its board to 14 members from 10 at its
annual meeting on April 27 in London. Holders of Class B stock will
elect 10 members, and the additional members are to be elected by
the Class A stockholders. The Baron funds hold 55.2 percent of the
Class A stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
