<HEADER>
A1877 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-COLUMBINE-LEGACY-KAN &LR;      04-19 1583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-LEGACY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE COLUMBINE SHOOTINGS CHANGED US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD, ERICA WOOD and STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Columbine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A year later, that word still has the power to disturb us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In suburban Littleton, Colo., two teen-age boys gunned down 12
classmates and a teacher in a rampage fueled by pent-up anger and
alienation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our first reaction was horror. But then the worries grew more
personal. Could this happen here? Are we doing everything we can to
make sure it doesn't? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The shock of Columbine has receded, but Kansas City-area
parents, teachers and students still feel its shadow. Today, six
area residents talk about how the events of April 20, 1999, have
made them more vigilant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The counselor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time they're teen-agers, it may be too late. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine High School massacre made that clear, and the
recent shooting death of a Michigan first-grader underscored the
point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So now counselor Debbie Kern pushes her fourth- and fifth-grade
students to talk about what's bothering them. She teaches them how
to handle the peer pressure and teasing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do it here, we can't blame the middle school and
high school,'' said Kern, who works at Cottonwood Point Elementary
School in the Blue Valley district. ``There's got to be a pattern
somewhere before that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One strategy is to prepare students to cope without resorting to
violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of her students, for example, worried about being stuffed
into lockers when they got older. So last week Kern took them to a
middle school. They measured the lockers and discovered how hard it
would be to cram someone inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long before Columbine, Kern had worked with the Stop Violence
Coalition Inc. in Kansas City, helping parents and teachers
recognize bullying. Demand for the program has skyrocketed since
the Littleton shootings, where the teen-age killers were said to
have been victims of bullying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National statistics show that 160,000 children stay home from
school every day because they fear classmates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Kern strives to reach children early. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to frighten them. Yet it's kind of a frightening
time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Through a student's eyes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No trench coats at school. More security cameras. New course
work about staying ``connected.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, high schools went on high alert after Columbine.
But for the ``different'' kids at school, the ones receiving more
scrutiny, the changes felt strange, even repressive. And sometimes
still do a year later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hewitt, a 17-year-old from Gladstone who's a junior at Oak
Park High School, is drawn to Goth themes, industrial music and
black clothing. All things Goth became suspect in the early days
after Columbine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the tragedy, Hewitt distributed a flier at
school explaining that Goths were fascinated with the topic of
death but had no connection to racial intolerance or violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying that just because we're all upset about this we
don't need to point fingers,'' said Hewitt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's Goth-ness isn't necessarily evident. She dresses ``in a
million and one ways'' besides black. She's an athlete and a rugby
player. And she floats fairly easily among the high school
subcultures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An impact of Columbine, she has noticed, is that the
``different'' students, feeling a bit besieged, have kept more to
themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And adults continue to size students up based on clothing, she
said. The trench coat ban makes no sense to her: ``I see a trench
coat as I see cargo pants; I mean, 14 pockets, how can you beat
that?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt realizes teachers and parents are trying to read the
warning signs. But to prevent something like Columbine, she said,
peers, teachers and parents need to look beyond the clothes young
people wear. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The officer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Prindle is a cop. His beat: Grandview High School. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Columbine, the school resource officer has delved deeper
into the lives of teens who are overly aggressive or prone to
violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several times, he's heard from students that a classmate is near
the boiling point. Prindle and the principal let the student know
they're there to help. If needed, Prindle may send a student to a
counselor or even to family court. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prindle always keeps an eye out for students who threaten or
tease others. He says it's smart business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take a little extra time in evaluating what we
think we're seeing,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prindle thinks schools need more than prevention. He plans to
show the school staff a training video, developed after Columbine
by Kansas City police, that outlines how police respond to mass
shootings and how teachers can minimize loss of life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even before Columbine, Grandview school officials had decided to
set up a tip hot line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the tip line made its debut in October, most of the 15 to
20 calls have been about drugs or fights. Nothing worse. Next year,
Prindle hopes to give out gift certificates and other incentives to
call in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine is probably a good wake-up call with every school in
America,'' Prindle said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The student mediator &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two young men in high school, and one accuses the other of
swiping a dollar off his desk. Sharp words and glances. Bumps in
the hall. Threats about what tomorrow would bring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like such a small thing _ a missing dollar bill _ but
Leslie Patterson knew how disputes could escalate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to fight,'' said Patterson, an 18-year-old
peer mediator at Central High School in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of Columbine for Patterson is that small slights have
a way of boiling up over time. In this clash, no one had mentioned
guns or knives _ yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it made us realize, you never know what will affect
another student,'' Patterson said about the Littleton, Colo.,
shootings. ``You never know how and when somebody will react to
being bullied or talked about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patterson sat down with the feuding students to ask questions
and take notes. The accuser acknowledged he couldn't be sure who
took the dollar. Still, emotions were too high for a handshake.
Instead, the two agreed to steer clear of each other: no comments,
no gestures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They signed a contract and they stuck to it,'' said
Patterson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's an outcome that makes Patterson proud. At least since
middle school, she's had a knack for bringing people together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a psychologist,'' she said. ``I like talking to
people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If she does pursue a career in counseling, Columbine will stick
with her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's opened a lot of people's eyes,'' she said.
``Students are capable of doing something like this because they
have so much bottled up inside, or because of something going on at
home, and they just explode.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A principal's view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When principal John Laurie heard rumors about a gun at school,
he reacted swiftly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He ordered police dogs to search Shawnee Mission West High
School and directed staff members to question students. The rumors
turned out to be false. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools have always taken the threat of a gun seriously,''
said Laurie, who has been an administrator for 25 years. ``But
since Columbine, schools have more procedures and more options in
place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sometimes feels overwhelmed at the idea of trying to
keep his 1,950 students safe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students at Shawnee Mission West are much like the ones at
Columbine, Laurie thinks. They are culturally diverse, middle- to
upper-middle-income kids who strongly support their school's sports
teams and activities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like students everywhere, they have more exposure to
violence than kids of generations past. They can find it easily on
the Internet, in video games and in movies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fears bred by Columbine have prompted schools to be less
flexible when students cross the line. Suspensions for threats are
almost a certainty now, Laurie said, even for a ``good kid.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a positive note, though, parents and students are more likely
now to report a problem at the first hint of something wrong. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``More kids are talking to teachers about things they notice
outside school,'' Laurie said. ``The kids have caught on that
talking about things helps make school a safer place.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A worried mom &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ginefra naturally worries about her two daughters. But
Columbine has intensified those worries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She calls their school, Rosedale Middle in Kansas City, Kan.,
more often than before. The wail of sirens sometimes prompts her to
dial the school _ she knows the number by heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And she frets until someone answers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're almost afraid to hear what it is,'' Ginefra said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When someone let off pepper spray earlier this year, the
stay-at-home mom jumped in her '80s-model Jeep Cherokee and headed
to Rosedale to be with her daughters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Columbine, Ginefra said, the middle school has added metal
detectors. They annoy her children, but have been a relief to
parents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``(The kids) are there every day, but parents aren't there so
they worry more,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ginefra said the media have overblown coverage of school
violence since Columbine, and she wants to hear more about students
being educated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are kids out there making beautiful music with a bow and
strings,'' she said. ``I think people are ready for those kinds of
stories.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-19-00 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
