<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-TROOPERS-NYT &LR;      04-19 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROOPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW JERSEY PROFILING CASE, DEBATE CENTERS ON DRIVER'S STATEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In the two years since two New Jersey State
Police officers wounded three unarmed men _ all members of minority
groups _ in a van on the New Jersey Turnpike, the case has set off
an intense policy debate about ways to prevent troopers from
targeting black and Latino drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But as the criminal case against the two officers advances,
defense lawyers have begun using the van driver's own words to
argue that, whatever discrimination problems may afflict the state
police force, the shooting was justified because the troopers
believed their lives were in danger when the van accelerated toward
them.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed this week, a defense lawyer revealed that
the van driver, Keshon Moore, told the grand jury that he might
have accidentally stepped on the gas pedal, causing the vehicle to
lurch toward the troopers. Moore made a similar statement to police
the night of the incident, according to Robert Galantucci, a lawyer
for Trooper John Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that `I can't blame anyone but myself, it was my
mistake,' '' Galantucci said in an interview Wednesday. ``To me, it
seems like an honest kid trying to tell the truth, and the fact
that he said it before he lawyered up makes it all the more
believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's lawyer, Peter Neufeld, said that his client's statement
on the night of the shooting was a symptom of survivor's guilt _
that Moore felt obliged to claim responsibility for the situation
because his three friends had been wounded and he had not. But
Neufeld insisted that Moore never told the grand jury he stepped on
the accelerator and argued that the expert witnesses who examined
the scene concluded that the van did not accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not Keshon Moore's position when he spoke to the grand
jury that he put his foot on the accelerator,'' Neufeld said. ``And
the experts testified that there was no evidence that the car ever
accelerated. It was moving approximately 4 mph. So whatever guilt
he might have felt that night, whatever he might have said, it is
really not relevant.'' He added, ``I defy any Police Department
anywhere to give an example of a case in which, simply because a
van was moving backward at a couple miles an hour, lives may have
been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's statement, however, has clearly become a central part of
the troopers' defense strategy. Hogan and his partner, James Kenna,
both face charges of attempted murder for the shooting on the night
of April 23, 1998, when they stopped the van as it drove southbound
near Exit 7A in Cranbury.
</P>
<P>
   Galantucci contends that Moore's statements bolster the
troopers' report that the van accelerated, and he has asked that
Judge Andrew Smithson of Mercer County Superior Court Judge dismiss
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This young man, in a moment of honesty, admitted that he made
the mistake that set everything in motion,'' he said. ``When you
put yourself in the position of what these officers knew at the
moment that van was heading toward them, it's clear they were
justified. The law doesn't demand perfection of people. It only
demands that what these troopers did was reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Special Prosecutor James J. Gerrow is scheduled to file his
response to the motions next month and has declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever weight the legal system eventually gives to Moore's
statements about the incident, the shooting has already changed the
way the New Jersey State Police operates.
</P>
<P>
   Although all three of the wounded men survived, the severity of
their injuries and the fact that officers fired 11 shots set off a
blaze of headlines and brought angry protests by civil rights
leaders who said that racial profiling had been a common occurrence
on New Jersey highways for years.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and two of his passengers are black; the third passenger
is Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, whose administration for years disputed a
judge's ruling in 1996 that found evidence of profiling, eventually
ordered her attorney general to investigate the department.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also led to the ouster of Col. Carl A. Williams,
the state police superintendent. The governor forced Williams to
resign after a newspaper published his assertions that blacks and
Latinos were primarily to blame for the state's drug problems.
</P>
<P>
   And in April 1999, Whitman became the first state official in
New Jersey to acknowledge that some troopers did indeed engage in
racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1999, after the U.S. Justice Department completed a
three-year investigation, the state entered a consent decree that
allowed a federal judge to appoint a monitor to ensure that the
state deterred racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal investigators said they found evidence that
some troopers, including Hogan and Kenna, intentionally
misidentified the race of the drivers in their written reports, to
conceal the race of the people they stopped. Those allegations have
led to criminal charges of filing false records against the
troopers. They have pleaded not guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
