<DOCNO> NYT20000419.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILLIES20     04-19 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILLIES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' offense wakes up
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With John Rocker's return came bullpen heroics Tuesday
night. So why not some offensive firepower to follow Wednesday as
Brian Jordan returned to the lineup for the first time since
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   Putting up their highest run total of the season, the Braves
broke out with a 10-1 victory over the Phillies, for their third
win in a row, Tom Glavine's third in a row and the 190th of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won the game on a bases-loaded two-run single from
Javy Lopez in the sixth inning and proceeded to rub it in with a
six-run eighth, five of which were scored before the Phillies
bullpen had recorded an out.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez added a two-run home run in the seventh to match his
career-high with four RBIs. Andruw Jones scored three runs and
homered for the third time this season. Andres Galarraga collected
three hits and drove in a pair of runs to raise his team-high RBI
total to 13. Glavine got in on the act with a single, his third hit
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate Glavine's going, he'll be at 200 in no time.
Fittingly, he got off to a nostalgic start, one of those where he
loaded the bases in the first inning. He got out of his jam _
allowing one run on a Rico Brogna groundout _ when he struck out
Mickey Morandini, but not before he had expended 34 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed one runner past first base from then on until he was
through with seven innings, and that came with the aid of a Walt
Weiss error.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones started the game-turning sixth-inning rally with a
single up the middle after Randy Wolf hit Jordan and Galarraga.
Lopez, who was facing Wolf for the first time Wednesday night,
bounced a single up the middle off him two pitches into his at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones and Lopez had bounced double plays their first
trips to the plate, making that 12 double plays for the Braves in
the past five games. But by the second time through, the Braves had
shaken those tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   They are 6-2 at Turner Field this season and winners of four of
their past five after being swept three games in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gant did his best to keep the Braves offense in check,
playing an acrobatic left field to take two more hits away from the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   After robbing Chipper Jones of an RBI hit Tuesday night, he was
back at it Wednesday making two awkward-looking catches in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
