<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFF GORDON DESERVES A ROUSING ROUND OF CHEERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years on the receiving end of a relentless chorus of boos
has taught Jeff Gordon one thing.
</P>
<P>
   You were right, NASCAR fans.
</P>
<P>
   He deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody likes a winner,'' Gordon said Sunday at
Talladega Superspeedway, ``but nobody likes somebody that wins too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   That self-effacing observation was delivered on the occasion of
Gordon's landmark 50th career Winston Cup victory. Equally
important, Gordon's run to the checkered flag in the DieHard 500
broke a 13-race winless streak that began on Oct. 11 and matched
the longest drought of his Cup tenure.
</P>
<P>
   For new crew chief Robbie Loomis and the revamped ``Rainbow
Warriors'' pit crew, the non-winning streak stood at only eight as
they lined up for the second restrictor plate race of 2000.
Qualifying did little to indicate that Sunday would mark Gordon's
triumphant return, as he started 36th in the 43-car field. A former
three-time series champion, Gordon stood a so-what 12th in points
on Sunday morning after finally scoring his first top-five finish
(fourth) of 2000 at Martinsville Speedway a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Boo this Jeff Gordon?
</P>
<P>
   Made about as much sense as booing Robby Gordon. Or Michael
Waltrip. Or Ricky Craven.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? Because this certainly wasn't the same Gordon who
won a record-tying 13 Cup races and his third championship in 1998,
with crew chief Ray Evernham calling the shots from high atop Mount
Sinai. Nor apparently was it the same Gordon who won a mere seven
races in 1999, the last two with Brian Whitesell running the team
as Evernham's hand-picked replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Boo Gordon when he's down? Where's the sport in that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says it's much easier at the top,'' said Gordon,
whose nose dive began when he failed to finish higher than 10th
during the final five races of 1999. ``Sometimes that's true, but a
lot of people try to tear you down when you're at the top. I can
tell you when you get knocked down a notch, it's very tough. And I
think you just earn a little more respect, especially in this
garage area and from the fans, when you're not winning and you
slide some wins in there.''
</P>
<P>
   As the victories piled up from 1995 to 1999 and the boos
proliferated, Gordon seemed immune _ smiling and waving through
every catcall. His demeanor did not go unnoticed in the garage
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered why they were booing him, because it wasn't
like Jeff had ever done anything to anyone,'' said Dale Jarrett,
the popular and reigning Cup champion. ``He was just doing his job.
He was in a very enviable position ... because we would have all
liked to have had that opportunity to dominate like that.''
</P>
<P>
   True. True. But Gordon heard you, NASCAR fans.
</P>
<P>
   And you were right.
</P>
<P>
   He deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the boos started coming, I'd sit back and say, `I don't
blame 'em,' '' said Gordon, who denied Mike Skinner of his first
Cup victory by approximately two car-lengths at Talladega. ``You
win 13 races in a season or 10 races in a season and it's unheard
of ... and I was just as baffled with it myself as other people
were. I was sitting there being one of these fans, sitting out here
in the grandstands and knowing exactly why at times they'd pull
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   This was especially true during 1998, when Gordon tied NASCAR
legend Richard Petty's single-season victory mark of 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that I took them \Rvictories\S for granted,'' said
Gordon, synonymous with the No. 24 DuPont Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
``I think the whole time we knew how special of a season we were
having, but I've got to be honest with you. When you pull into
Victory Lane the 10th, 11th, 12th, 13th time, it's not the same
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it the same feeling that Gordon, Loomis and team manager
Whitesell experienced on Sunday, when they raised themselves out of
mediocrity as the season's record-setting ninth different winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that just one win is going to turn things
around for us, but I think it's definitely going to be a boost,''
said Gordon, anticipating the tour's visit to the California
Speedway on April 30. ``I think this has been a great test for all
of us. It's really been a test for our faith in one another, our
faith in God, and I think we've done good up against this test.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough for a round of cheers.
</P>
<P>
   So give it up, NASCAR fans.
</P>
<P>
   He deserves it.
Indy-car team quickly regroups after tragedy
</P>
<P>
   When Robby McGehee joined Treadway Racing for the 2000 Indy-car
season, he did so as teammate and understudy to Sam Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   But the crash in practice in January that left Schmidt paralyzed
has changed all that. McGehee, 26, now occupies the No. 1 seat on a
team that is capable of winning the season's next two races _ at
Las Vegas and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Treadway Racing has, in fact, won the last two Indy Racing
Northern Light Series events run at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, site
of Saturday's Vegas Indy 300. Schmidt scored his first series
victory at his home track last September, thrusting himself into
the thick of a championship chase that ultimately was won by
Plano's Greg Ray at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, two-time Indy 500 champion Arie Luyendyk
notched the final victory of his career on the 1.5-mile trioval.
Luyendyk last drove for car owner Fred Treadway at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway in May, where an accident while in the lead cheated
the Dutchman out of his dream of retiring as a three-time Indy 500
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that same race saw McGehee _ in his series debut _
finish fifth for Conti Racing en route to being chosen Rookie of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   While neither Schmidt nor McGehee combined could equal the savvy
brought to the team by Luyendyk, they loomed as a young, aggressive
and articulate combination. But Schmidt's crash at Homestead-Miami
Speedway changed all that, for McGehee and crew chief Skip Faul.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with Sam ... we don't have to talk about how bad
that is,'' said McGehee, who has nine series races on his resume.
``I raced with Sam in 1996 in Formula 2000. He's had more years in
Indy-car, but our overall experience is similar. I was looking
forward to working with Sam because I knew him and he always gave
me great advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it \Rthe crash\S makes every race car driver
reconsider what they're doing for a living, and do I want to do
this as a career? But the passion is still there. He had the same
passion I have. We have to chug along with Sam on the sidelines and
pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   McGehee said he spent the first two races of 2000 adjusting to
the fact that his No. 5 Mall.com/Energizer G Force-Aurora is a car
that can keep going and going.
</P>
<P>
   Faul, Luyendyk's longtime chief wrench, said he and Schmidt went
through a similar learning curve during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about this time that it started to click,'' Faul said.
``So the honeymoon is over and Robby knows what he's got to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely got the ambition and aggressiveness to be a
good race car driver. We've got to channel it a little bit. But we
know he's got good car control, and gives good chassis setup
information. And when he gets in the race, he's a go-getter. Those
add up to being a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:FRACTION ALERT \Nsubheds:Plate remains in place
NASCAR's one-day aerodynamic experiment at the Talladega
Superspeedway on Monday came wrapped with this disclaimer:
carburetor restrictor plates never came off the two cars tested.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Chevrolet Monte Carlo provided by Richard Childress
Racing and a Ford Taurus from Roush Racing, NASCAR officials tried
a number of aero tweaks to slow the cars down via downforce.
Changes included using a 65-degree rear spoiler, raising the front
valance from 31/2 inches to 6 inches, and adding a 1-inch wicker
bill to the roofs near the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, the Winston Cup Series director, reiterated that
the plates remained in place during the approximately 50 laps run.
</P>
<P>
   ``With some of the things we tried,'' Nelson said, ``we were
able to increase them \Rplates\S a quarter-inch more than what we
had during Sunday's race at Talladega.'' Cars ran the DieHard 500
with a seven-eighths-inch restrictor plate for the first time this
season. \Nsubheds:NHRA five-for-five NASCAR's Winston Cup Series
has produced a record nine different winners in as many races this
season.
</P>
<P>
   A similar scenario is playing out in the National Hot Rod
Association's Top Fuel ranks. The first five national events have
produced five different winners: Gary Scelzi (Pomona), Tony
Schumacher (Phoenix), Doug Kalitta (Gainesville), Kenny Bernstein
(Las Vegas) and Larry Dixon (Baytown).
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, the reigning champion, has forged a 66-point lead
over two-time champion Scelzi with a run of consistency. Schumacher
has advanced to four finals in five starts in the Exide Batteries
Dragster, missing out only at The Strip at Las Vegas.
\Nsubheds:Tracy off, running With top-three finishes in the first
two races of 2000, perennial CART bad-boy Paul Tracy is enjoying
the fastest start of his 10-year FedEx Championship Series career.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, of Team Kool Green, finished third in the season-opener
at Homestead, Fla., and posted his 16th career victory in the Long
Beach Grand Prix last Sunday. In seven previous years as a
full-season Championship Auto Racing Teams competitor, Tracy never
had posted back-to-back scoring finishes in his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy has an eight-point championship lead (34-26) over Jimmy
Vasser of Target/Chip Ganassi Racing heading into the Rio 200 at
Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, on April 30. It is the first time the
Canadian has led the points chase since 1997. \Nsubheds:TMS
packages on sale Ticket packages are available for the inaugural
Hav-A-Tampa Series Wolf Brand Chili 100 at Texas Motor Speedway's
Dirt Track April 28-29.
</P>
<P>
   Late Model drivers from 10 states are expected to compete in an
event staged in conjunction with the ``Star-Telegram'' AutoFest
featuring the Pate Swap Meet.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can buy a one- or two-day combination ticket for a reserved
seat for the Hav-A-Tampa race(s) that also includes a one- or
two-day admission to AutoFest. Packages are $15 for a Friday combo,
$25 for a Saturday combo or $35 for both Friday and Saturday races
and AutoFest. General admission tickets are $10 for Friday and $20
for Saturday, with a $25 two-night ticket also offered.
</P>
<P>
   Fans purchasing Hav-A-Tampa tickets at the gate will receive $5
off a reserved seat by presenting that day's AutoFest ticket.
Tickets may be purchased at the speedway or by calling 215-8500.
