<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING PITCHING GIVING RANGERS A CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rick Helling has a simple credo, sort of a
starting pitcher's mantra, that he takes to the mound with him for
every outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is give the team a chance to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did his part against the New York Yankees yesterday at The
Ballpark in Arlington, surrendering two runs on seven hits in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, didn't win. They were beaten yet again by
the New York Yankees, this time, 5-4, in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   They lost for the fourth consecutive game, beginning Sunday in
Cleveland and continuing with a three-game sweep by the Yankees at
home.
</P>
<P>
   But in three of the four games the starting pitcher accomplished
the basic goal, giving the team a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   The starters' earned-run average in the four games was 3.10.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza pitched 71/3 shutout innings against the Indians
on Sunday, but the Rangers lost, 2-1, when closer John Wetteland
gave up two homers in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver allowed two runs in eight innings against the
Yankees on Monday, a game the Rangers lost in 11 innings, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   And Helling pitched effectively yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The worst outing in the four games was by Kenny Rogers, who
struggled against the Yankees on Tuesday, allowing six runs on nine
hits. But at least he was able to work into the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of the intent of the off-season, to strengthen
our rotation and take some wear and tear off the bullpen,'' Helling
said. ``It's an indication of what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   That indeed was the idea when the Rangers signed Rogers and
Oliver as free agents and traded for Justin Thompson, who is
scheduled to make a rehabilitation start tonight at Double-A Tulsa
and could be close to joining the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that our starting pitching was going to be a strength,
and it should get even stronger with Justin Thompson coming back,''
manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   It's something new for a Rangers team.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a four-game losing streak occurs when the starting
pitchers get hammered and the offense can't keep up. This one
happened because the hitters didn't do enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying our pitching will carry us early, and it
shows,'' Rangers first baseman-designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro
said. ``We had a chance to win every game. If we execute
offensively, we win.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
