<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CONTEMPORARY-DESIGN-A     04-19 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPORARY-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING, NOT MAKING THE MOLD IN MILAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, Finland, Italy, Britain, France, New Zealand) (ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Crossing the tram tracks that cut the cobbled
streets, and traversing the iron and glass arcaded gallerias that
canopy the 19th-century shopping arcades like grand hotel palms, a
visitor to Milan and its annual furniture fair encountered an
unsettling fact: that the 20th century is now the past, too.
</P>
<P>
   The future has arrived. But have we? Is a candy-striped plastic
chair what we have to show for the last 1,000 years?
</P>
<P>
   At the 2-million-square-foot Salone, the world's largest
exhibition for contemporary design, as well as at two large tandem
events and 320 gallery shows taking place simultaneously in the
city designers ignored the future, embraced the future or, in a few
select instances, took a sledgehammer to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch partnership Do Create, in collaboration with Droog
Design, showed a steel cube that the buyer bashes into a cove of a
chair in a kind of vicious do-it-yourself: consumer frustration
with existing choice as a tool for change. The sledgehammer comes
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening everywhere now, what's interesting, is the
whole crossover of media _ sound, film, theater, art, furniture,''
said the artist Robert Wilson, whose installation ``Anna's Room''
was part of an exhibition of meditations on interiors by artists.
``I had a retrospective at the Centre Pompidou 10 years ago, and I
worked with all the departments _ architecture and design, painting
and sculpture, audio and video. Times have changed. It's all
incredibly mixed now.''
</P>
<P>
   The British artist Rachel Whiteread, who was included in the
Brooklyn Museum's ``Sensation'' show, exhibited an upholstered
daybed, her first, for the English retailer SCP Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   There was the stylish status quo: Ronan and Erwan Bouroullec,
two brothers from Brittany, introduced a wafer-thin lounge chair
upholstered in felt with a spring-loaded attached ottoman that
would be easy to see in psychiatrists' offices during the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   But the true prototypes proposed not new materials or shapes,
but models for environments, from the technological to the ironic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in making new typologies of furnishing,'' said
Matali Crasset, a French designer who exhibited plaid plastic
shopping bags, popular in immigrant neighborhoods in Paris, foam
filled to make cheap, versatile tables and chairs. ``Why not take
the objects around with you, and make your own proposals for
design?'' Crasset said. (The Italian company Edra, which
commissioned them, will sell them, complete with handles.)
</P>
<P>
   Snowcrash, a young Finnish company, showed
voice-and-music-activated wall and ceiling lighting in flat panels
and soft clouds that permit a space to interact in a conversational
style with its inhabitants by modulating its colors and forms.
Andreas Murray, the president of Snowcrash, said he thought high
technologies like LED display, which are now inexpensive, and young
consumers' comfort with computers would help shift the design of
homes from traditional furniture to mood-responsive atmospheres for
work or play: a kind of functional fun.
</P>
<P>
   Other young designers lowered their sights to the floor with
lamps that rested like pets, yoga-mat rugs and legless inner-tube
seating. Like furniture afloat, they freed the constraints of space
by disregarding walls. At Alterpoint, an exhibition in the city,
Anthony Tammaro, 29, an American student at Domus Academy in Milan,
showed latex, rubber and plastic lamps that he said were designed
``to curl up next to, with a book.'' The lamps look like portable
fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Lindfors, 37, a Finnish designer whose Housemix
exhibition included a soup-to-nuts range of domestic solutions,
from architecture to toothpaste, said he thought designers had a
renewed responsibility to ``the everyday.'' Lindfors' Qubico house
was erected in less than a week, developed by a Finnish company
that manufactures modular wood ``timbers'' integrating wiring and
plumbing. Lindfors' Abaqus stacking chair is recyclable: both
plywood and plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Shigeru Uchida, a Japanese designer, presented simple wooden
wall cabinets with sliding lacquered-metal doors that involved the
user in a small ceremony of poetic display as with the shoji
screens of a traditional Japanese teahouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 20 century depended on machinery and mass production,''
Uchida said. ``In the 21st century, designers should realize things
more basic to our life styles. We need to focus on spirit _
interiors that can release the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The future, at its brashest, showed up at the parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donatella Versace! Donatella Versace!'' wailed the young man
with the brunet bowl-of-noodles hair as he staggered out of the
Ford Motor Co. party at Fendi, struck by his celebrity sighting. He
collapsed in the street at midnight. It was like the last five
minutes of a Verdi opera.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the ex-factory, several thousand guests from around the
globe pushed and posed, drinking shots of straight liquor served in
test tubes.
</P>
<P>
   At the eye of the cyclone, like the revolving vortex of a drain,
was a huge turntable rotating a bright bug-green automobile: the
O21C, Ford's Jetsons-like prototype for pushing Generation Ys pedal
to the metal. Marc Newson, the shag-haired New Zealand designer who
designed it, rode the turntable with his creation. Wearing a
multicolored, party-animal-skin frock coat, he cavorted for
television cameras with a woman in fake diamond cuffs, satin
hip-hugger trousers and Telly Savalas-style gold Gucci aviator
eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe we're here to see a car,'' said a redhead in
Prada to a redhead in Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, watching Newson swing by.
</P>
<P>
   Design is the new corporate club drug, being used to sell
excitement in products _ fruit-gel laptops, titanium snowboards,
single-malt Scotches in Swedish jiggers _ to the young, affluent
and advertised-to.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it. ``Design is the DNA for a whole group of people who
want to live a type of lifestyle, and see it mirrored in everything
they own,'' said Jay Mays, the vice president of design at Ford,
who hired Newson. The O21C, a kind of super-model T, has yet to get
the green light for manufacture, though ``what was an extremely
weird car a year ago,'' Mays added, ``looks pretty mainstream
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which left the 39-year-old April trade event in a desperate
disco sweat. It smelled like middle-aged panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milan's gotten too big for it's own good,'' said Tom Dixon, a
designer and ex-outsider, who is now directing the design program
at the Habitat chain. Dixon walked into the party for G7, a New
York group sponsored by Totem, where martinis and champagne were
being served, wearing a matted mock-teddy-bear-fur coat to keep his
rebel credentials on view. ``If you had seen this stuff in
isolation in Prague, you'd go `Oh, wow,'' he said, speaking of the
deadness induced by Milan's scale.
</P>
<P>
   Two women circled a violet plastic inflatable lounge chair, as a
man seated in it tipped over to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things you don't want to get too close to
with a cigarette,'' the woman who was smoking said, raising her
glass.
</P>
<P>
   For young designers and young companies eager for corporate
matchmaking, is Milan still the best place to be looking for love?
</P>
<P>
   ``Milan was, is, and will always be the center of design,'' said
Philippe Starck, the French designer, at a press breakfast with his
new wife. ``Is Hollywood the place for the movies?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But to a world quickened and acquainted by the Internet, is that
increasingly irrelevant?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, absolutely,'' said Murray of Snowcrash, who is gunning
for contracts with Apple and its universal iMac audience, not the
traditional design cognoscenti whose taste and trends are
established by Italian showrooms like Cappellini. ``Why produce our
things as they did in the 1950s, when we live in the 21st century?
Beautiful things that communicate with who? Ten thousand, 50,000
people in the world? It's nice to be here, looking at what others
are doing, but for us, the consumer electronics show in Las Vegas
would be a better place for our next exhibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Engesvik, 29, showing with Norway Says, a Finnish
collective, at the Salone Satellite, an exhibition of experimental
design, said, ``We're young and we're big-mouthed, but we have to
be that.'' He had found generational similarities, not national
disparities, with other young designers from as far as Singapore
and Tokyo. ``Our thoughts are so similar, when it comes to what
design is about,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Engesvik designed a briefcase-like, wall-mounted desk that
attracted the attention of Raymond Kennedy, general manager for
Herman Miller for the Home. ``Design for the last two or three
decades has been so excluding, and so expensive,'' Engesvik said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``designing products that are easy to produce,
that don't require expensive new tools'' was the real problem on
the drawing board, not creating new styles. And, he said,
accessibility to design must improve. ``It's very popular to talk
about the Web, but existing structures are not flexible, or dynamic
enough,'' Engesvik said. ``Every young designer I've talked to
wants to make the leap, out of the existing system.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, then, will give the parties?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
