<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CHANGES, NEW YORK BALLOT OBSTACLES PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ While state lawmakers may sweep away New York's
notoriously tough rules for letting candidates onto Republican
presidential primary ballots, state law still puts an array of
obstacles in the way of people who would run for lesser offices, in
any party.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators and good-government groups say it is still far
too difficult for insurgent candidates, without the backing of
party organizations, to go through the painstaking process of
gathering the signatures needed to get on primary ballots for
statewide office or for seats in Congress and the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incumbency protection system,'' said Rachel Leon,
executive director of the New York state branch of Common Cause.
``The problem now is that we have party bosses still in charge,
instead of voters, in deciding who gets to run for office in this
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and the Legislature changed the rules in
1996, eliminating some of the law's most picayune requirements,
like a provision that demanded that each petition list each
signer's Assembly district and local election district number _
information that few people know. Critics say those changes were
laudable but did not go far enough. The number of candidates whose
petitions are challenged in court by their opponents has not
declined since that change.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Republican-led state Senate approved a bill,
proposed by the Republican governor, that would allow major
candidates to get on a Republican presidential primary ballot
automatically, much like the rules for Democratic presidential
primaries. The Democratic leaders of the Assembly have not said
what they will do with the bill, but they are not expected to stand
in the way of the Republicans' changing their own system.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other Republican leaders embraced the change
after their efforts to keep Sen. John McCain off the March 7
presidential primary ballot backfired. The episode proved
politically damaging for the state's top Republicans, who were seen
as unfairly manipulating the process, and in the end, a federal
judge ordered that McCain be allowed on the ballot. He lost the
primary to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed changes do not affect any contests except
Republican presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   For primaries for statewide offices like governor or U.S.
senator, candidates can get on the ballot with the support of 25
percent of the delegates at a state party convention. In recent
years, Democratic Party leaders have stretched the rules to help
all serious candidates reach 25 percent, but the Republicans have
occasionally used the rule to knock out people who would challenge
the party favorite.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide candidate who does not get 25 percent support from a
convention can still get on the Republican or Democratic primary
ballot by gathering at least 15,000 signatures of voters registered
in that party over a six-week period, including at least 100 in
each of 16 of the state's congressional districts. For minor-party
candidates, the law requires the signatures of 5 percent of their
party's registered voters statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for congressional or legislative seats have no choice
but to go the petition route. Major-party candidates for Congress
must gather 1,250 signatures from voters in their parties and in
their districts, candidates for state Senate need 1,000, and
candidates for the Assembly need 500. Minor-party candidates need 5
percent of their party's voters in that district.
</P>
<P>
   The signature requirements mean a candidate needs a large team
of people doing the collecting _ an easy thing for an incumbent or
someone with the backing of the party machinery, but hard for an
outsider. And there is a daunting set of rules by which the
signatures must be collected, including one that requires that
voters list their addresses by city or town, not by the villages or
postal zones that they might normally use.
</P>
<P>
   Each party has at its disposal a cadre of lawyers who are expert
at going to court to challenge signatures, or even whole petitions.
Candidates routinely collect three times as many signatures as are
legally required, to ward off such challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
