<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2036 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     04-19 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKJACK SOFTWARE MAY EVEN THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In casinos, the house has the advantage. If you don't believe
it, look around. They didn't build palaces like these by giving
away free drinks and big jackpots all the time, but by grinding
down players little by little.
</P>
<P>
   But at some games, the players have a slightly better advantage
of winning, or _ for the gambling realists _ not losing as much.
When bets are placed correctly, the house has only a slight edge at
the craps table. And blackjack tables offer a fairly level playing
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackjack 6-7-8'' is a program that seeks to help players make
that field even more level. The program, which costs about $60 and
is for Windows, is the outgrowth of Hal Marcus' 1971 visit to Las
Vegas. It was a trip to the bookstore _ rather than a blackjack
table _ that really started Marcus, a computer programmer, on his
way to eventually cofounding Stickysoft Corp. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On that trip, Marcus purchased Edward O. Thorp's ``Beat the
Dealer,'' a blackjack system developed by a mathematics professor
at the University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Marcus learned that players could do better at the
blackjack tables if they would follow certain betting strategies _
some of which seemed to run against common sense. For instance,
Thorp's strategy is to double the bet when the player has an
ace-seven showing and the dealer has a three.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Marcus purchased his first personal computer, and four
years later wrote a blackjack program to test various strategies.
Although the program was graphically crude by today's standards, he
found people who played it were fascinated by it. He also found
that most of the people who played it made decisions based on
hunches.
</P>
<P>
   And thus ``Blackjack 6-7-8'' was born. It allows players to play
at a blackjack table just like in a casino. However, it can also be
told to provide hints during game play and teach players to make
the proper decisions that will give them an edge over the dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one plays alone at a blackjack table, the computer will
supply up to six computer controlled players to play, using one to
25 decks, with rules that can be customized to fit any casino in
the world. The human player can also control the actions of some or
all of the other players at the table rather than letting the
computer do the work.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not sure the program can really help improve your
blackjack game, put your theory to the test: Set up the computer
players to use various strategies, then run simulated hands _ up to
2 billion of them _ to find out how the systems worked.
</P>
<P>
   While users play their hands, the program tracks how many
decisions were made correctly and helps players find where they may
be able to beat the dealer by acting differently given the same set
of cards.
</P>
<P>
   A training section allows players to concentrate on specific
hands. There are no other players, and the hands aren't finished _
only the choices count. That way, players can train in an area of
weakness, go to the playing area, then track their decisions to see
if they've improved.
</P>
<P>
   The program teaches betting strategy as well as playing strategy
and can be set to alert the player if either of those strategies is
violated during play. For players who want to try counting cards,
the program can display a running count and true count as well as
the number of cards left in the shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Nice features, good graphics, simple play and sophisticated
teaching make this a top-notch piece of simulation software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackjack 6-7-8'' is available from StickySoft Corp. of
Buffalo Grove, Ill. For information, visit the company's Web site:
www.blackjack678.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
