<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-FRANCE-LOUISXVII-1STL     04-19 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-LOUISXVII-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETICS OFFERS DENOUEMENT TO MYSTERY OF PRINCE'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS spelling of ``Brinkmann''   in 12th graf)   
(ART ADV: Photo NYT34 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The question has intrigued historians for 200 years. Was
the disease-riddled little boy who died in 1795 after years alone
in a prison cell really the son of Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette?
</P>
<P>
   Or had royalists managed, at the height of the French
Revolution, to spirit the young heir from harm after his parents
were sent to the guillotine?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, two scientists said they could offer proof that the
10-year-old was indeed Louis XVII. He had endured two years in
Temple prison, where he was left unattended and in the dark for
long stretches, with skin tumors, scabies and increasing signs of
madness.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, after examining all that remains of the boy _ a
dried heart _ said they had been able to match the boy's DNA with
that of other members of the royal family, including DNA taken from
a lock of Marie Antoinette's hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of 200 years of uncertainty,'' said Philippe
Delorme, a historian who had pressed for the test and helped
announced the results. ``It is a very exciting day for historians.
It puts to an end a mystery that has absorbed so many of us. Now we
have an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, more than 500 books have been written about
the young dauphin, and many theories emerged about his possible
escape and presumed exile.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mark Twain could not resist tweaking the issue. In ``The
Adventures of Huckleberry Finn,'' Huck tells Tom about ``the little
boy dolphin'' who might have been king but was shut up in jail and
may have died there, though others said the boy might have gotten
away to America. In 1905, speculation on the subject was so intense
that a monthly review was founded.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of the young prince's death, rumors circulated that
he had been spirited out in a bathtub and that the dead boy was a
substitute. Would-be heirs have popped up all over Europe claiming
to be the true descendants of the Bourbon line.
</P>
<P>
   One such man, Charles-Guillaume Naundorff, was so convincing
that the government of the Netherlands allowed him to be buried
there in 1845 under a tombstone indicating he was the true heir to
the French throne.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on the royal family say dozens more claim to be direct
descendants, though few have been as public with their claims.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday the scientists said they were all impostors. They
said they had been able to extract three samples of mitochondrial
DNA from the heart and compare them with samples from locks of hair
taken from Marie Antoinette, two of her sisters and samples from
two living maternal relatives, Queen Anna of Romania and her
brother Andre. In all cases, they said, they had found
``identical'' sequences.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, both specialists in human genetics, Jean-Jacques
Cassiman of the University of Louvain in Belgium and Bernd
Brinkmann of the University of Muenster in Germany, said they had
found enough matching DNA to determine that Marie Antoinette was
the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the new evidence will end all conspiracy theories in the
rarified world of royal intrigue remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the news conference announcing the results, some members
of the audience questioned whether the scientists could be
considered truly independent, given that they were paid by the
royal family trust. Others speculated whether the dead boy might
not have been another son of Marie Antoinette that no one knew
about.
</P>
<P>
   But royal-gazing does not really interest the French much. The
French Revolution and its many aftershocks wiped out a great many
members of the royal family and stripped most of their wealth.
Since the last reigning king, Louis-Philippe, was removed from
office in the revolution of 1848, there has been much feuding over
who is the real heir to the throne, but very little effort to
restore anyone to it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his part, the duke of Beauffremont, who heads the Memorial
of France at St.-Denis, the private organization that oversees the
royal graves and paid for the DNA tests, said that he was grateful
that science had provided an answer and that he would now push for
a proper burial for the boy's remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see him placed between his mother and his
father, which would be very fitting,'' the duke said. He said last
December that he had decided to have the heart tested because the
question of the boy's death just would not go away.
</P>
<P>
   Cassiman was at first unsure that any DNA testing could be
accomplished because the heart was in such bad shape. The story of
how it survived is a crazy saga that can hardly be a scientist's
dream.
</P>
<P>
   It was never meant to be preserved. But one of the doctors
present at the child's autopsy decided to keep it as a memento. The
doctor, Philippe-Jean Pelletan, stole it and wrapped it in his
handkerchief when no one was looking. At home, he put it in a glass
vial filled with alcohol, but the liquid evaporated and the heart
dried up, hard as a stone. A few years later, one of the doctor's
assistants stole it. When he died, his widow returned it to the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the monarchy was briefly returned to power in 1815,
the doctor apparently tried to return the heart to Louis XVIII, who
wanted nothing to do with it. So, just before Pelletan died, he
decided to entrust it to the archbishop of Paris. But in 1831 the
archbishop's palace came under attack during civil disorders, and a
printer named Lescroart tried to save the relic and the paperwork
that proved its authenticity in the hopes of giving it back to the
doctor's son for safekeeping. But he got caught in the mayhem, and
as he wrestled with a national guardsman, the crystal urn
containing the heart was smashed.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, when all was quiet, Lescroart came back with
Pelletan's son and they found the heart lying among shards of
glass, some engraved with royal fleurs-de-lis. The son kept the
heart until his death. In his will, he bequeathed it to members of
one of the branches of France's royal family, who kept it in their
chateau for more than eight decades. In 1975, it was put into the
custody of the Memorial for France at St.-Denis.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their doubts, both Cassiman and Brinkmann were able
to get an adequate sample of DNA by cutting tiny slices from the
heart with razor blades. The DNA samples were not perfect, both
scientists said, but they were complete enough.
</P>
<P>
   Cassiman has tried before to answer royal mysteries. In 1998, he
tried to compare the DNA from Naundorff to that from Marie
Antoinette's hair and her sister's hair found in a locket belonging
to their mother. In his findings in the European Journal of Human
Genetics, he said it was highly unlikely Naundorff was related to
the young queen, whose Austrian blood line and fancy ways helped
ignite the French Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Delorme, who has written two books on the young prince's life,
said the DNA results were a form of justice for the child. ``Until
now, his death was stolen,'' he said. ``It was not admitted that he
died in such a horrible way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
