<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: INTERNET CALLS MAY BE FREE, BUT THEY'RE NOT
AS  GOOD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: &LR;  I've heard that you can use your PC to make free &LR; 
 &LR; long-distance calls to any telephone. Is that true, and if so, &LR; 
 &LR; how can I do it? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: To quote Madeline Kahn from ``Blazing Saddles,'' ``It's twu!
It's twu!'' A company called Dialpad.com ( &LR; www.dialpad.com &LR; ) is
offering just such a service for calls in the United States. And
there's no software to download _ it's all done with Java over the
Internet. You can also use the market leader, Net2Phone, but it
will cost you 1 cent per minute and you'll have to download special
software. In either case, you'll need a headset with a microphone _
which you can pick up at a computer store for less than $30.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the caveat. Don't expect an Internet phone call to be as
good as a regular phone call. Even if you have a high-speed
connection, you're likely to experience at least a little latency _
a delay between the time someone says something at one end and it's
heard at the other. That can be disconcerting enough to make you go
back to your phone. But you know what they say _ you get what you
pay for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Expanding the Cell
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Is there a way to enter text in an Excel cell without the type
spilling past the right border of the cell in one long line?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Sure. Right-click the cell and choose Format Cells from the
context menu. Tab over to Alignment, and in the Text control
section, check the box labeled Wrap text. Then click OK. Any text
you enter in the cell will stay inside it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Video Memory
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My PC at home is unable to play some of the more
graphics-intensive CDs like the new Disney Toy Story 2 Action Game.
The reason I was given was my video card has only 2 megabytes of
memory, and the game requires 4Mb. Does this mean I need a new
video card? If so, where can I get one, and can I install it
myself? My system runs on a Pentium II chip and Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Video memory is just like regular computer memory. Every time
you think you have enough, somebody comes up with software that
gobbles up more. Many of today's shoot-'em-up action games can use
16 megs of video memory or more. Now to your problem. You may have
a video card in your PC, or the video may be embedded on the
computer's motherboard. Either way, it may be possible to simply
add video memory, so the first thing to do is contact the PC-maker
about that.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not possible to upgrade the video you already have, then
it's time to buy a new 3-D card _ which you can easily install
yourself. Before you go shopping, though, open up your PC to make
sure there's a place to put the card. You'll need an open PCI or
AGP expansion slot. The PCI slots are the white ones, which all
newer PCs have. The AGP slot is smaller, usually black, and it's
located just above the PCI slots. You may or may not have an AGP
slot. If you do, get an AGP card, because the AGP slot is designed
for high-speed graphics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Automatic Reply
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I've seen an automatic reply forwarded to me when I e-mail
someone who's on vacation or out of the office. How do I get my
computer to do the same thing when someone e-mails me and I am away
on vacation? I have a small home office. I have Office 2000, but I
can't seem to find this on any of the pull downs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The automatic response you've been seeing is generated by the
mail server at the person's company. Since you don't have a mail
server of your own (you use your ISP's server), you can't do the
same thing from home.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a DSL line or cable modem, however, there's an
alternative option. Set up a mail ``rule'' in Outlook or Outlook
Express that will send an automatic reply (which you can create) to
every incoming message (you'll find the rules options in the Tools
menu of both programs).
</P>
<P>
   For this to work, you'll have to leave your computer on all the
time you're gone with the e-mail software running. The software
should already be set to check for new mail regularly. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  For users of the AOL /Netscape Instant Messenger: End your chat
session by pressing the Control key and the number 1. It will bring
a smile to the face of the person at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   David Einstein is West Coast bureau chief of Forbes Digital
Tool. Got a question about computing? E-mail it to
 &LR; computers &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate &LR; . &LR; com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
