<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HP-PRINTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HP REINVENTING THE PRINTING WORLD  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Continuing its yearlong campaign to reposition
itself as a hip Internet player, Hewlett-Packard on Wednesday
announced a series of alliances, appliances and initiatives
designed to transform the $40 billion desktop printing business
into a $100 billion ``Internet ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   That plan, Chief Executive Officer Carly Fiorina told a San
Francisco press briefing Wednesday, involves changing home and
office printers from ``simple beige boxes'' into ``information
appliances.'' Their value, she said, will be measured not by their
print speeds but by the services they deliver, such as printing
stamps and tickets, automatically generating customized newspapers
and outputting documents sent over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The network, Fiorina said, is bringing about a fundamental shift
across the printing industry. Today, documents are printed
centrally, then distributed in physical form. In the emerging
Internet age, they'll be distributed in electronic form, then
printed locally, in the recipient's home or office.
</P>
<P>
   To foster this transformation, she said, HP is working on
technologies that will enable users to print directly from devices
such as cell phones, pocket organizers, digital cameras and even
TVs.
</P>
<P>
   HP's stake in this transformation? Since it controls more than
half the worldwide market for desktop printers and supplies, it
stands to reap rich rewards as more printing shifts from
traditional commercial printing to the desktop. Fiorina said HP
holds the No. 1 position in every part of the printer business in
which it competes.
</P>
<P>
   While margins are increasingly tight on both laser and inkjet
printers, the market for ``consumables'' _ ink, toner cartridges
and paper _ remains ``enormously profitable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   HP also hopes to leverage its leadership in the printing market
into increased sales of servers, software and professional services
to companies providing print-related products and services.
</P>
<P>
   It announced new partnerships with several such startups,
including NewsPaperDirect, which helps hotels and cruise liners
offer their guests locally printed versions of newspapers from
around the world; Stamps.com and EncrypTix, sibling companies that
offer secure printing of documents such as tickets, stamps,
traveler's checks and gift certificates; printCafe, which auctions
and brokers commercial printing contracts; and ImageTag, which
attaches bar-coded stickers to companies' documents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Palo Alto, Calif.'s HP said it has made an equity
investment and taken a seat on the board of Mimeo.com, a New York
company that offers overnight printing and binding and guaranteed
delivery of documents sent over the Net to its facility in Memphis,
Tenn., adjoining FedEx's hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing really earth-shattering,'' said Jim Lundy,
Gartner Group research director, ``but it's a new strategy and a
good one.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more concrete announcements of the day, FedEx
announced a new version of its free interNetShip software that lets
users print their own shipping labels on HP inkjet printers.
Previously, the program required a laser printer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at &UR;  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
