<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-RESULTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPLE OUTSHINES ESTIMATES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Crediting strong sales of its professional
products and a continuing influx of new users for its iMac models,
Apple on Wednesday announced second-quarter results that handily
topped analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino, Calif., computer-maker's revenues for the three
months ended April 1 were $1.94 billion, up 27 percent from $1.53
million in the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for the quarter totaled $233 million ($1.28 per
share). In the same period last year, earnings were $135 million
(84 cents). This year's figure, however, included a $73 million
after-tax gain (40 cents) from the sale of shares in ARM Holdings,
a British chip designer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Excluding the investment windfall, Apple earned $160 million
(88 cents). Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had
forecast earnings of 81 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding nonrecurring items from net income for both this year
and last, earnings were up 72 percent in all and 47 percent on a
per-share basis.
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose shares are up roughly tenfold since January
1998, also announced plans for a 2-for-1 stock split, its first in
13 years.
</P>
<P>
   In Nasdaq trading before Apple released its results, the
company's shares fell $5.75, to $121.13. But in after-hours trading
after the announcement, the price jumped to as much as $127.81.
During the most-recent quarter, Apple said, it sold 1,043,000
computers, a year-over-year increase of 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   About 350,000 were Power Mac G4s, the high-performance systems
the company markets mainly to graphics, publishing and multimedia
professionals, and 100,000 were PowerBooks, Apple's high-end
laptop, Chief Financial Officer Fred Anderson said during a
conference call after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Non-U.S. sales accounted for 51 percent of revenues for the
quarter, Apple said. Gross margins climbed from 25.9 percent in the
first quarter to 28.2 percent. Anderson credited the increase to
lower freight charges (because the company didn't have to resort to
the rush shipments it used to meet holiday demand), lower RAM
prices and a product mix that included more high-end, higher-margin
models.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also reported that 28 percent of iMac buyers, according
to company-sponsored surveys, were purchasing their first computer,
while 17 percent previously owned a Windows system. Before the
easy-to-use iMac, Apple had trouble attracting new users. For
several years, most of its sales had been to its base of loyal
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be skeptical about Apple's long-term ability to win
over Wintel (Windows-Intel) users,'' said analyst Kurtis King of
Banc of America Securities in San Francisco. ``But I've come around
_ they simply offer a better product than the competition, and
they've shown the ability to take substantial market share.''
</P>
<P>
   King said he's maintaining a ``strong buy'' recommendation on
Apple's stock and increasing his target price for it to $150.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
