<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HACKER-EVIDENCE-SFCHR     04-19 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-EVIDENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA EVIDENCE POINTED TO MAFIABOY  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK AND CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Using evidence uncovered in California,
investigators have arrested a 15-year-old Canadian boy in
connection with a high-profile attack against CNN's Web site, one
of several popular sites hit in February.
</P>
<P>
   The teen, known by the handle ``Mafiaboy,'' was originally
fingered two months ago by Michael Lyle, a Palo Alto, Calif.,
computer security consultant, who said the youth had boasted in an
Internet chat room about plans to hit the Web sites of CNN and
Menlo Park, Calif.-based E-Trade shortly before those sites were
temporarily shut down. He was arrested over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators tracked him down by following clues left
behind at two computers at the University of California in Santa
Barbara, one of which was used in the attack against CNN's Web
site, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle, co-founder and chief technology officer at Recourse
Technologies, said one of the computer's logs, which records all
activity on the machine, contained an address at Sympatico, a
Canadian Internet service provider. Kevin Schmidt, a network
programmer at the university who first detected the break-in, said
accounting logs and other files ``pointed to several sites in the
U.S. and Canada.'' Presumably, investigators could then obtain
subpoenas to check the logs at each of those other sites for
additional clues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say (the UC Santa Barbara logs) pointed to him
explicitly and directly,'' Schmidt said yesterday, but ``we had
information that did point in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police, who announced the arrest at a
news conference in Montreal on Wednesday, so far have charged the
juvenile only with attacking CNN. The Mounties said that Mafiaboy
jammed CNN and 1,200 sites it hosts for four hours. But authorities
said they are investigating whether he might be responsible for
hitting other sites.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a dozen commercial sites, including Yahoo,
E-Trade and eBay, were attacked over a span of three days in
February.
</P>
<P>
   All of the sites were hit by so-called ``distributed denial of
service'' attacks, in which Internet users use dozens of powerful
computers to swamp a Web site with phony requests for data, keeping
real users from getting through.
</P>
<P>
   Several experts doubted Mafiaboy could have been responsible for
all of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems incomprehensible to me that one 15-year-old could
have done all that,'' said William Eyres, a security management
expert who has worked with police and Congress on hacking problems
in the past. ``That's an awful lot of work and coordination.''
</P>
<P>
   Security experts also said the vandals used different methods to
knock out some of the Web sites. Mafiaboy, for instance, used a
software program called Tribe Flood Network, which is widely
available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyle said the people behind the initial attack on Yahoo used
custom-designed software and several more sophisticated methods.
Apparently, they also left fewer clues, which could help explain
why they haven't been arrested. ``Mafiaboy was a copycat,'' Lyle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet hackers, including one who goes by the name of
Coolio, also reportedly bragged that they were involved in the
attacks. Police arrested Coolio, a 17-year-old teen, last month for
defacing several Web sites, including an anti-drug site in Los
Angeles and one run by a computer security firm. But the teen,
Dennis F. Moran, said he was only joking when he confessed in an
Internet chat room that he was responsible for shutting down Yahoo
and other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Mounties said they tracked down Mafiaboy's location less
than a week after CNN was hit, and knew the identity of the boy two
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the teen could be sentenced to serve up to two
years in prison, although juveniles charged with hacking are
normally just asked to make restitution and are put on probation.
He could also be prohibited from using a computer.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN spokeswoman declined to comment on the arrest. But Richard
Power, editorial director for the Computer Security Institute, an
association of security professionals in San Francisco, estimated
that the attacks on all the Web sites, including shopping sites
like Amazon and eBay, may have cost them as much as $10 million in
lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the attacks, the White House and others called on
Web sites to increase security. The FBI even distributed software
to help spot programs that could be used in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But security experts acknowledged that Web sites are still
vulnerable, in part because denial of service attacks are so hard
to fend off. Attackers typically use dozens of computers, and often
forge the return addresses of traffic, making it difficult for Web
sites to quickly identify where the fake traffic is coming from and
shut it off.
</P>
<P>
   And although major Web sites are always beefing up their
security, hackers are working just as quickly to identify new
flaws. ``The same kind of thing could happen tomorrow,'' said
Marketta Silvera, head of Alameda security firm Pilot Network
Services. Hacking ``techniques evolve around the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and other security experts plan to speak
at a ``town hall'' meeting in San Francisco today to raise
awareness about the possible threat from cyberterrorists and
foreign governments, including China and Russia, who are investing
in electronic warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It illustrates the severity of the problem,'' said Jeffrey
Hunker, a National Security adviser and senior White House adviser.
``Here you have a single individual who disrupted CNN and several
other sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The forum, which will be hosted by ZDNet at their main office,
will be broadcast on the company's Web site ( &LR; www.zdnet.com &LR; )
starting at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; , or Carrie Kirby
at  &LR; ckirby &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
