<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PGE-CLEANUP-SFCHRON &LR;      04-19 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGE-CLEANUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PG&AMP;E'S ECO-FRIENDLY IMAGE FALLS ON ITS FACE  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ PG&AMP;E Corp., parent of San Francisco's Pacific Gas and
Electric Co., worked hard at the company's annual shareholder
meeting Wednesday to depict itself as a champion of environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the energy business, you're in the environment
business,'' Bob Glynn, PG&AMP;E's chief executive, told the two dozen
or so shareholders who turned up for the meeting _ the company's
first to be held outside the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   A firm commitment to safeguarding the environment, he said, ``is
how I sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Local environmentalists weren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he sleeps at night,'' said Lori Ehrlich,
co-founder of Salem Power Plant HealthLink, a grassroots
organization working to clean up two Massachusetts facilities
purchased by PG&AMP;E in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get any unrehearsed answers to our questions,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing was just corporate whitewashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although PG&AMP;E officials insisted that there was no connection
between the decision to move the shareholder meeting outside of San
Francisco and negative publicity surrounding the Julia Roberts
movie ``Erin Brockovich,'' many of those in the crowd were not so
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a shareholder, you don't always know what the company is
doing,'' said John Tierney. ``They tell you words that are soothing
to the ears, but who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is the environment,'' said Melvin Thornhill,
who has held PG&AMP;E stock for 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   He said before the meeting that he was there ``to listen and see
what they have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't much. Taking the podium, Glynn praised PG&AMP;E's
financial performance and service record, and stressed that ``our
environmental commitment and performance were strong in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was optimistic that PG&AMP;E's earnings per share will
rise by as much as 10 percent in the future and emphasized that
``shareholder value is our metric.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnings Results
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E will report its latest quarterly results Thursday. The
company said last month that it lost $611 million ($1.67 per share)
in the final quarter of 1999. That compares with a profit of $196
million (51 cents) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether the metric of shareholder value was
discussed by board members as they dined Tuesday night on sea bass,
salad and a tasty-looking poached-pear dessert in a private dining
room at the luxurious Four Seasons Hotel, site of this year's
shareholder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn did not answer directly when asked during the meeting by
one shareholder, John Cheveddon, a regular attendee at PG&AMP;E's
annual get-togethers, how much it cost to fly the company's top
brass to Boston and put them up for about a week at the Four
Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may have been unintentional, PG&AMP;E clearly had the
deck stacked in its favor yesterday. The number of board members,
executives and company employees in the ballroom far exceeded the
shareholders in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Most seats in the audience were empty until PG&AMP;E staff members
began quickly filling them as the presentation commenced.
</P>
<P>
   The company seemed to be expecting trouble. Police and hotel
security personnel were on guard in the lobby, and a small army of
beefy men wearing earphones roamed the meeting hall.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of East Coast shareholders who braved cold, rainy
weather to attend had to submit to thorough security checks before
entering the ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came from the airport and I didn't have to go through
anything like that,'' said one annoyed shareholder, Nancy Goulart.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came off without a hitch, though, and it was clear
from Glynn's relaxed demeanor during the question-and-answer period
that he had prepared well before arriving in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Arthur Burns took Glynn to task for ``a disconnect
between the environmental subjects you spoke about and what's been
going on in Massachusetts for the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Terming PG&AMP;E's environmental record ``a disaster,'' Burns said
cases of cancer, leukemia and asthma among neighbors of PG&AMP;E's
local plants are higher than in other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn replied: ``We want to have all our facilities to be in
full compliance with all the regulations that apply to them.''
</P>
<P>
   This is something of a mantra among PG&AMP;E officials. Lisa
Franklin, the company's chief spokesman in the Northeast, said
earlier that PG&AMP;E's plants ``operate under a comprehensive system
of authorizations. We operate in complete accordance with those
authorizations.''
</P>
<P>
   And during an interview with The Chronicle after the shareholder
meeting, Glynn declined to elaborate on how his company's
environmental record goes beyond mere compliance with regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compliance is the foundation upon which everything else is
built,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hasn't Seen the Movie
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had not yet seen ``Erin Brockovich,'' which
tells the story of how PG&AMP;E reached a $333 million settlement with
residents of the Southern California town of Hinkley after toxic
chemicals from a PG&AMP;E plant poisoned their water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn said it wasn't high on his list of things to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was, I would have seen it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life Brockovich was forced to cancel plans to attend
the shareholder meeting because of ear troubles that prevented her
from flying from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But her assistant, Chrissy Albice, did show up and asked Glynn
what steps PG&AMP;E is taking to prevent toxic leaks in other towns
where the company has facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn replied that PG&AMP;E has a strong ethics policy in place as
well as regular environmental audits and a toll-free number that
employees can call to report problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ethics policy,'' he said, ``says we must comply with all
laws and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn said he was unable to respond to a lawsuit announced
Tuesday by Boston's Conservation Law Foundation because he had not
yet seen the group's notification letter.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, to be filed in federal court, will demand that PG&AMP;E
take steps to clean up operations at its plants in Salem Harbor and
at Brayton Point in Somerset.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the two oil- and coal-burning plants plants are
responsible for contaminating the groundwater with a variety of
toxic chemicals and exposing surrounding communities to potentially
harmful airborne pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Invitation to Talk
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder Lisa Evans, a former attorney with the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, invited Glynn to sit down with her
and other local residents to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn said he appreciated the offer but pointedly did not say
whether he would accept the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He completely blew us off,'' Evans said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Thornhill, the longtime shareholder who had wanted to
hear what PG&AMP;E would say about its environmental troubles, was
similarly disappointed as the meeting finally adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't answered the questions,'' the retired college
professor said of Glynn. ``I don't feel very good.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 45 years, in fact, Thornhill said he's
thinking about selling his shares in the company.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
